<SLUG> BC-Sports-Running-Holmdel International,0612 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kingdom wins hurdles with his season's best time
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By BERT ROSENTHAL &QC; 
 &UR; AP Track Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HOLMDEL, New Jersey (AP) _ Any notions that two-time Olympic
champion Roger Kingdom's career was at an end were dispelled
Thursday night.
	   The 35-year-old Kingdom, running his fastest race of the year,
won the 110-meter hurdles at the Holmdel International track and
field meet in 13.38 seconds.
	   ``Nobody believes in me anymore,'' the 1984 and 1988 gold
medalist said.
	   Because Kingdom has not won a major international title since
1989, when he was World Cup champion, he has been dismissed as
finished.
	   He had difficulty getting equipment from shoe companies and he
was not invited to many international meets.
	   ``Now I can forget about all those people who think I'm done,''
he said. ``It's been hard to get into meets. I see guys running
13.50s and 13.60s, and they're in. The promoters say they want the
young guys, but they invite Jack Pierce, Courtney Hawkins and Terry
Reese, while I have the credentials and the hardware to get a spot.
	   ``Who blackballed me? Why are they so negative about me? What
did I do?
	   ``I'm bitter, but I'm not going to leave the sport yet. I might
not compete that much longer, but I'm going to stick around in the
sport because I think we need a voice and I want to be that
voice.''
	   Kingdom, the former world record-holder and now co-American
record-holder at 12.92, will chase his sixth national title at New
Orleans next week. He won his last title in 1995, the same year he
was the Pan American Games champion and the bronze medalist at the
World Championships. In 1996, he finished fifth at the U.S. Olympic
trials, and last year he failed to get past the semifinals of the
USA Championships.
	   Pierce, the 1992 Olympic bronze medalist, finished second
Thursday night at 13.54 and Hawkins, the Millrose Games champion,
was fourth at 13.59.
	   Hawkins was impressed by Kingdom.
	   ``He's a competition junkie,'' he said. ``He's the dog you
always like to kick, but he's still got some bite. He bit us
tonight.''
	   Meanwhile, 1996 Olympic high jump champion Charles Austin used
the meet as a tuneup for next week's USA Championships at New
Orleans, where he will be seeking his fourth straight national
title.
	   Bothered by the cold, damp weather, a soft jumping area and the
long wait before competing, Austin, the American record-holder at 7
feet, 10 1/2 inches, cleared only 7-0 1/2 before missing three
times at 7-6 1/2.
	   ``I was a little stiff because of the cold weather,'' Austin
said. ``I should have made it (7-6 1/2). I guess I was just a
little wimp because of the weather.
	   ``I'm in great shape. I was just trying to work the kinks out. I
was pleased with what I did, but I also was not pleased because I
wanted to break the meet record (7-5).''
	   Despite the low winning height, Austin said he would be ready to
extend his winning streak at the national championships.
	   ``I don't want to just win it. I want to win it big,'' he said.
	   Ireland's Marcus O'Sullivan, the three-time world indoor
champion at 1,500 meters, won the ``men's mile'' by about 20 meters
in 4:00.77, just missing breaking the four-minute barrier for the
102nd time in his career.
	   ``I felt sluggish,'' O'Sullivan, 36, said. ``My legs felt dead.
I felt tired.
	   ``Considering how bad I felt, I'm pretty happy with my time. I
know I can run 3:54.''
	   Debbie Marshall was a double winner, taking the women's 800 in
2:05.54 and the 1,500 in 4:18.14.
	   Meredith Raieny Valmon, the 1996 Olympic trials champion at 800
meters, won the 400 in 53.71.
</TEXT>
