r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AsianMarkets     06-12 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Asian Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yen's slide drags down Asian, world stock markets
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By PRISCILLA CHEUNG &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Stock markets in Japan, South Korea and Hong
Kong opened lower once again Friday, as Asia reeled in the face of
more bad news about the yen's weakness, Japan's economy and the
performance of bourses in Europe and the United States.
	   And fears that the weakening yen _ which fell to a nearly
eight-year low against the U.S. dollar Friday morning _ would force
China to devalue its yuan have spilled over to Wall Street and
Europe, raising fears that Asia's protracted financial crisis would
lead to a worldwide slump.
	   A cheaper yuan would also feed Chinese inflation and trigger a
wave of regional devaluations, weakening key economies such as Hong
Kong's and spreading as far as Russia, analysts suggested.
	   ``It's all about the yen,'' said Michael Lim, the head of the
treasury department at Standard &AMP; Chartered Bank in Jakarta.
``Nobody can stand a strong dollar.''
	   The yen tumbled further Friday as traders interpreted comments
by U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin overnight in Washington as
meaning that a coordinated effort by central banks to boost the
falling yen was unlikely.
	   In early trading, the dollar bought 144.21 yen, up 2.53 yen from
late Thursday in Tokyo and also above its late New York rate of
143.79 yen overnight.
	   At one point, the dollar moved as high as 144.75 yen in Tokyo,
matching its most recent previous high on August 30, 1990.
	   Rubin, testifying before the Senate Finance Committee on
Thursday, reiterated that Japan must revive its ailing economy,
warning that ``Japan's economic difficulties and weak currency are
having substantial adverse impact on the East Asian countries.''
	   Rubin also said it will be up to Japan to halt the yen's slide.
	   Tokyo stocks also fell to their lowest levels since Jan. 14. The
benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 148.06 points, or
0.99 percent, to 14,865.98 points at the close of the morning
session, adding to Thursday's 2.12-percent loss.
	   Tokyo and other Asian stocks fell Friday morning on losses on
Wall Street and in European markets.
	   The Dow Jones Industrial Average slumped 1.8 percent to close at
8,811.77 Thursday. Bourses in London, Paris, and Zurich also fell
between 1.6-2.2 percent Thursday.
	   Market participants in Asia were also waiting for the release of
Japan's quarterly gross domestic product data Friday afternoon,
which is expected to show the first annual contraction in the
economy since 1974.
	   In Seoul, the key Korea Composite Stock Price Index was down
17.01 points, or 5.2 percent, to close the morning session at
311.69.
	   Shares in Hong Kong were down by 1.7 percent at the open, but
clawed back slowly later in the morning session as most blue chips
were trading at or near all-time lows.
	   In Kuala Lumpur, the benchmark index opened down 2.3 percent,
while shares in Singapore, Bangkok and Taiwan also opened lower.
	   Shares in New Zealand fell for the 12th consecutive session,
closing 11.5 points lower at 1,997.63.
	   Australian shares also fell for the ninth straight session, with
the key index down 0.8 percent Friday morning.
	   Bucking the trend, Jakarta stocks opened higher on buying in
some state-owned companies, boosted by speculation that the
government may have already found strategic investors for its
divestment plan, dealers said.
	   But the rupiah fell against the U.S. currency early Friday,
trading at 14,250 to the dollar, down from 13,750 late Thursday. 	   
</TEXT>
