r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Japan-Mitsubishi-Hara     06-12 0317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Mitsubishi-Harassment </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mitsubishi Motors welcomes settlement in sexual harassment case
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With US-Mitsubishi-Harassment &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Mitsubishi Motors Corp. said Friday it supports its
U.S. subsidiary's agreement to pay dlrs 34 million to settle the
United States' largest ever sexual harassment lawsuit.
	   ``We think an early resolution was desirable and welcome the two
sides having reached an agreement,'' Katsuhiko Kawasoe, president
of Mitsubishi Motors, said in a statement.
	   Mitsubishi's subsidiary, Mitsubishi Motor Manufacturing of
America Inc., agreed to pay the money to settle charges that it
ignored widespread sexual harassment of female assembly line
workers at its Normal, Illinois plant.
	   The settlement, pending approval by a federal judge, was
announced Thursday by Mitsubishi and the U.S. Equal Employment
Opportunity Commission.
	   ``Our company supports the agreement as a correct business
decision for MMMA to move forward,'' Kawasoe said.
	   Mitsubishi Motors will also back the implementation of various
measures agreed upon between the subsidiary and the commission,
Kawasoe said.
	   In April 1996, the EEOC sued Mitsubishi's North American
division, alleging that the automaker allowed women at the Normal
plant to be groped and subjected to lewd jokes and behavior in a
manner that was ``repeated, routine, generalized, serious,
pervasive and known to and supported by management.''
	   The settlement, however, contained no admission of wrongdoing by
the company.
	   The consent decree requires Mitsubishi to offer mandatory sexual
harassment training to employees, revise its sexual harassment
policy as necessary and investigate allegations of harassment
within three weeks as a ``zero tolerance'' policy.
	   Mitsubishi said some 20 workers were fired in 1997 for sexual
harassment and several others were disciplined.
 &UR; (km)
</TEXT>
