<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 06/12/1998 01:16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w2314 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-India-Greenpeace     06-12 0257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Greenpeace,0256 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Greenpeace floats ``anti-nuclear'' balloon over Indian monument
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With India-Pakistan-Nuclear &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   AGRA, India (AP) _ Greenpeace anti-nuclear campaigners chose
India's most recognizable monument _ the Taj Mahal _ as the site of
a protest Friday.
	   The activists said they floated an Earth-shaped hot-air balloon
draped with banners declaring ``Nuclear Disarmament Now'' about 200
meters (yards) from the 345-year-old tomb known around the world as
a monument to love.
	   Greenpeace, which has campaigned against nuclear weapons since
it was formed in 1971, has sharply criticized last month's
tit-for-tat nuclear testing by India and neighboring Pakistan. The
environmental group is known for having demonstrators spend nearly
two days suspended on ropes from a bridge to protest ``factory''
fishing in Washington state and sailing its Rainbow Warrior into
France's South Pacific nuclear testing sites.
	   The Taj Mahal is in Agra, 200 kilometers (125 miles) south of
New Delhi and 600 kilometers (375 miles) east of India's test site,
but Greenpeace organizers said they wanted to stage their protest
at a place the world would recognize as Indian.
	   ``Becoming a nuclear weapons state should be an embarrassment to
every citizen,'' Simon Carroll, who led the Greenpeace balloon
protest, said in a statement. He also called on the traditional
nuclear powers _ Britain, China, France, Russia and the United
States _ to destroy their stockpiles of nuclear weapons.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-India-Greenpeace; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
