<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Singapore dollar falls, stocks level
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Following the lead of the Japanese yen and most
Asian currencies, the Singapore dollar fell further Friday. The
stock market was slightly up by the midday close.
	   Traders have said the Singapore dollar is easy to sell because
of its liquidity and higher local interest rates, although those
rates have been dropping as the currency loses value against the
U.S. dollar.
	   The Singapore currency hit 1.75 to the U.S. dollar in early
trading, but recovered slightly to 1.743. Its value has been
steadily decreasing over the past few months and is 21.6 percent
lower against the U.S. dollar than last July 1, the day before the
Asian economic crisis began.
	   Singapore's benchmark Straits Times Industrial Index dipped 21
points, or 2 percent, immediately after the market opened. By the
midday closing it had regained the losses and was up 3 points, or
.3 percent.
	   However, the index has lost 891 points, or 45 percent of its
value, since last July 1. 	   
</TEXT>
