<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Baseball-Strawberry Lawsuit,0254 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Darryl Strawberry sued for allegedly failing to pay legal bills
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) _ New York Yankees outfielder Darryl Strawberry
is being sued for allegedly failing to pay dlrs 100,000 in legal
fees in 1994.
	   Attorney Robert Shapiro filed the lawsuit in Los Angeles federal
court, claiming the player had failed to pay him for negotiating a
settlement of Strawberry's contract with the Los Angeles Dodgers.
	   Strawberry, 36, was in Montreal, where the Yankees lost to the
Expos 7-5 Thursday. The Yankees were traveling back to New York on
Thursday night and Strawberry could not be reached for comment.
	   Shapiro claims he had an oral contract with Strawberry, who
allegedly agreed to pay the attorney a flat dlrs 100,000 fee to
represent the player in negotiations to become a free agent.
	   ``No part of said sum has been paid,'' the lawsuit said.
	   Shapiro, who helped represent O.J. Simpson during his criminal
trial, is seeking dlrs 100,000, plus 10 percent interest for each
year since February 1995, and court costs.
	   Strawberry also has played for the San Francisco Giants and the
New York Mets, leading the team to the World Series title in 1986
and an NL East championship in 1988. But his long career has been
marred by a federal conviction on tax charges, a 60-day suspension
following a positive drug test, and more trips to court over
spousal support payments.
	   The Dodgers released him in 1994 because of drug and alcohol
problems.
</TEXT>
