<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Asia-Howard </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Howard: Victory for Hanson will not damage Australia's image
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ALAN THORNHILL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CANBERRA, Australia (AP) _ Prime Minister John Howard said
Friday success for Pauline Hanson's right-wing populist One Nation
party at a weekend state election will not damage Australia's
reputation in Asia.
	   Hanson has been controversial in Australia and Asia for
advocating policies to cut Asian migration and investment and halt
special welfare payments to Aborigines.
	   ``The only thing that would really be detrimental to Australia's
international standing would be if people overseas thought the
government of Australia held views that were hostile to them,''
Howard said in a radio interview in Melbourne.
	   Recent polls have predicted Hanson's forces have weakened the
governing conservatives in Queensland state so much that the
opposition Labor Party will win the majority in Parliament, and
government, at the Saturday poll.
	   If the conservatives lose Queensland, partly because Hanson's
ultra-rightist party has cut into their appeal, it is a bad omen
for Howard. He has to call a federal election by March and faces
the same problems with Hanson on a national scale.
	   Howard said Friday he did not want One Nation to win seats
anywhere in Australia and condemned its policies.
	   ``They are totally unacceptable to me,'' he said on Radio 3AW.
	   Howard played down the potential impact of the Queensland
election result on the timing of the national election, due by
March 1999.
	   Howard has been criticized for not refuting Hanson's policies
earlier and more vigorously than he did.
	   But he insisted Friday that he had not made a mistake on the
issue.
	   ``I feel that if I had gone in much harder and the beginning, it
probably would have given her much more prominence and the results
would not have been much different,'' he said. 	   
</TEXT>
