<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Corruption </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Two former aides to chief minister face graft charge
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Two senior aides of a former chief
minister facing corruption charges were arraigned Friday for
allegedly misusing their office to favor a company in a huge real
estate deal.
	   One of the officials is alleged to have accepted a bribe of 1.2
million ringgit (dlrs 300,000) to facilitate the 20 million ringgit
(dlrs 5.2 million) deal.
	   The former private secretary and press secretary are accused of
asking the then chief minister of Selangor state, Muhammad Taib, in
1989 to clear the application for land by a company in which the
two had interests, the national news agency Bernama reported.
	   Muhammad, 52, a prominent member of Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad's United Malays National Organization party, is himself
facing trail for not declaring his assets that include properties
overseas.
	   On May 29, a court in Brisbane declared him innocent of
violating Australian laws by carrying more than a million dollars
in foreign currency in his hand luggage during a trip to Australia
in December 1996.
	   On Friday, Murad Ibrahim, 46, and Shamsuddin Merin, 54, pleaded
not guilty to charges and were released on bail. But the court
asked them to hand over their travel documents.
	   If convicted, they face a maximum penalty of 14 years
imprisonment or a fine of 20,000 ringgit (dlrs 5,000) or both. 	   
</TEXT>
