<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Falling Yen </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
The yen keeps falling, but Japan may not move to support it
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; TOK101 &QL; 
 &UR; By TODD ZAUN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The yen just keeps plunging against the dollar,
threatening to deepen Asia's economic crisis, deliver a crippling
blow to Japan's ailing banks and force China into a currency
devaluation of its own.
	   But Tokyo's puzzling response _ watch, and wait.
	   The reason, say analysts and traders, is that despite long-term
dangers, the currency's decline has a big short-term benefit: yen
weakness translates directly into higher profits for Japan's export
companies.
	   And with the Japanese public growing increasingly concerned
about the state of their economy, policymakers seem likely to opt
for the quick fix.
	   ``The immediate benefit for the Japanese economy of a falling
yen is actually quite positive,'' said Ken Okamura, a strategist at
Dresdner Kleinwort Benson (Asia) Ltd.
	   ``But there is a fundamental question of whether this going to
spark off a series of problems in other places,'' he said.
	   Japan's currency sank more than two yen-per-dollar Thursday in
U.S. and European markets as traders interpreted comments by U.S.
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin as meaning therre would be no U.S.
support for the sagging yen.
	   It fell further in Tokyo on Friday _ to as low as 144.75 yen to
the dollar _ as traders reasoned that if U.S. officials weren't
worried, Japan was unlikely to do much to stop the fall either.
	   Comments from Japan's policymakers on Friday did little to
change their minds.
	   While Finance Minister Hikaru Matsunaga said he was ready to
take ``decisive action'' to stop the yen from falling too far,
there was no indication such action would come soon.
	   ``When the dollar was at the 130-yen-level, I said I had strong
concern,'' Matsunaga said. ``I am still watching it with strong
concern.''
	   Another influential economic official said he wasn't worried
about yen weakness at all.
	   ``I don't see a negative effect of the weak yen on the Japanese
economy,'' said Koji Omi, Director General of Japan's Economic
Planning Agency, at a regular press conference Friday.
	   Omi suggested that if a weak yen was causing problems elsewhere
that ``leaders of the world economy in Asia, U.S. and Europe should
do whatever is necessary.''
	   The yen's decline has already helped the giant exporters that
power Japan's economy. Honda Motor Co., Canon Inc., and Nintendo
Co. all recently reported double-digit profit growth for the year
ended in March. The profits were due, in large part, to the
dollar's gain against the yen last year.
	   A rising dollar and falling yen helps exporters by making their
products cheaper, and therefore more popular, in overseas markets.
Even if they don't lower prices in foreign markets, profits earned
there become more valuable in terms of the home currency when the
yen falls.
	   But economists say that further yen weakness would make Japan's
exporters so competitive that they'll begin to clobber exporters
from elsewhere in Asia and China, which has so far avoided a
currency devaluation.
	   If yen weakness forces China to lower the value of its yuan,
market watchers worry they'll see a whole new round of devastating
devaluations sweep through Asia as countries knock down the value
of their currencies to keep their exporters competitive.
	   Stocks in South Korea and Hong Kong sank once again Friday as
such concerns spread. The day before, China's Foreign Ministry
spokesman Zhu Bangzao warned that the weakening yen could
destabilize still shaky financial markets around the region.
	   The falling yen also creates dangers closer to home.
	   Japanese banks, already struggling with mountains of bad
real-estate loans at home, are the biggest foreign lenders in Asia
and could be severely hurt if economies there sink further,
analysts said.
 &UR; (tz-et)	   
</TEXT>
