r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Australia-Asia-Tariff     06-12 0222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Asia-Tariffs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Economist: Give up tariff protection to help ride out Asian crisis
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CANBERRA, Australia (AP) _ Warning that Australia is yet to feel
the worst of the Asian financial crisis, a leading economist Friday
urged the government to implement tariff cuts and other domestic
reforms.
	   With more than half of all exports going to Asia, the regional
downturn will have a drastic impact on Australia, Prof. David
Robertson of the Melbourne Business School said.
	   ``The outlook for Australian trade, at this stage, is bleak,''
he told a business seminar. ``It's bleak for goods, for services
and for tourism.''
	   Robertson said the recent fall in the value of the Australian
dollar could make Europe a more attractive market for Australian
goods.
	   ``Europe takes four percent of our exports, so there's plenty of
scope, but it's going to be a monstrous increase if it's going to
counterbalance what's going on in Asia,'' he said.
	   The best way for Australia to ride out the crisis is to urgently
wind back industry assistance such as tariffs and to reform the
domestic economy, he said.
	   The federal government has announced it will freeze at 15
percent tariffs for the car industry for five years from 2000 and
at 10 to 25 percent for the textiles, clothing and footwear
industries. 	   
</TEXT>
