<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Dollar Down, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Australian, New Zealand currencies recover slightly
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS; UPDATEs with Barbara Streisand tour canceled and
interest rates up because of slump, dollar recovering slightly and
stocks falling, edits to conform &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ The Australian dollar's fall in value
to 12-year lows is starting to be felt in Australians' hip-pockets,
as home mortgage lenders raise interest rates and promoters warn of
canceled tours and increased prices.
	   A concert tour by Hollywood star Barbara Streisand is the latest
casualty of the growing gulf between the Australian and the U.S.
dollars, according to a music industry promoter.
	   ``It's common knowledge now that the Streisand tour has been
canceled, and that the dollar fall is the reason,'' the promoter
told Dow Jones Newswires, on condition of anonymity. ``It was a
very low (profit) margin tour anyway before the rot set in.''
	   The value of the Australia dollar has fallen 10 percent to
around 58.8 U.S. cents in 1998, and is down around 24 percent from
75.5 U.S. cents in mid-1997.
	   Until this week, the effect on the man-in-the-street had been
limited largely to consumers of imported commodities and tourists
traveling to regions outside crisis-hit Asia, such as the United
States and Europe.
	   But three banks on Thursday announced they will raise interest
rates on home loans, and other banks said they were reviewing their
rates in the wake of the dollar's fall.
	   Concert promoters say ticket prices for international touring
acts will rise. Depreciation increases the cost in
Australian-dollar terms to stage productions and reduces revenue
from ticket sales in foreign currency terms.
	   The Australian dollar resumed its slide Friday after a rebound
the day before was cut short by a sharply lower yen and gold prices
overnight. It recovered slightly and in local afternoon trading was
worth 58.93 U.S. cents, above its intraday low of 58.32 U.S. cents.
	   Stock prices have joined the dollar in declining on continuing
concerns about the weakness of regional stock markets and
currencies.
	   On Thursday, the Australian bourse closed lower for the eighth
consecutive day, to finish at 2558.7. Traders said they would be
surprised if Friday's close was not down again.
	   At one point Friday, the market's leading indicator, the All
Ordinaries Index, was down 19.8 points, or nearly 8 percent, to
2538.9.
	   The New Zealand dollar also recovered Friday to around 50 U.S.
cents at the close of local trade, up from a low of 49.44 U.S.
cents.
	   The NZSE-40 capital index finished lower, at 1997, but clawed
back from a low of 1955. It is the first time the index has closed
below the 2000 point level since early April 1995.
	   Dealers said the Australian and New Zealand currencies would
continue to be sold as long as the yen and gold prices were under
pressure. 	   
</TEXT>
