r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-Miners     06-12 0268
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Miners </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Deputy prime minister says government making good on coal promises
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Deputy Prime Minister Boris Nemtsov said Friday
that the government was making good on its pledges to support the
coal industry, the ITAR-Tass news agency reported Friday.
	   Nemtsov spoke with reporters on the second day of a miners'
protest outside the seat of government in Moscow, the White House.
	   About 200 coal miners from four mining regions arrived in Moscow
by train on Thursday to protest unpaid wages and call for the
resignation of President Boris Yeltsin _ the man they had supported
wholeheartedly in 1989 and 1991, when he was fighting for his
political survival.
	   ``Answer us, Boris: Why are we dying in the mines for free?''
read the banner they held as they marched 10 kilometers (6 miles)
through the capital to the White House, where they planned to
picket 24 hours a day.
	   Nemtsov said Friday that 205.5 million (dlrs 34.25 million) had
been transferred from the federal budget to the miners of Vorkuta
and Inta, in the Far North, during the first five months of 1998,
ITAR-Tass said. He said that allocation was 80 million rubles (dlrs
13.3 million) more than during the same period in the previous
year.
	   Nemtsov also pointed out the steps the government was taking to
help the industry as a whole, including decreasing rail transport
costs, which should lead to 3 billion rubles (dlrs 600,000) in
savings to coal companies, and ending abuse of office by coal
company managers and middlemen who overcharge for their delivery
services.
	   (ji) 	   
</TEXT>
