<HEADER>
w2360 &Cx1f; wstm-
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Japan-Recession 1stAdd   06-12 0370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Recession, 1st Add </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOKYO: two decades.
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   The agency said Japan's gross domestic product, the sum of all
goods and services produced, shrank 0.7 percent for the fiscal year
ended March 31, 1998.
	   The last time Japan's economy contracted during an entire year
was in 1974.
	   This is the third time the world's second-largest economy slid
into recession since 1992, economists said.
	   Japan's economy is still struggling to overcome the effects of a
collapse in land and stock prices in the early 1990s.
	   The crash left Japan's banking industry burdened with failed
loans that the government now estimates total about 76 trillion yen
(dlrs 531 billion).
	   And just as Japan's economy was finally showing signs of a
fragile recovery early in 1997, the government smothered growth
with an ill-timed tax increase in April of last year.
	   A series of high-profile bankruptcies has also spooked
consumers, who started spending less and saving more.
	   But the final nail in the coffin was the regionwide economic
crisis that started in Thailand last July.
	   Japan has been hit harder by the meltdown than other developed
nations because it lent and exported more to its Asian neighbors. A
recession in Japan bodes ill for the rest of Asia, which had been
counting on the region's economic powerhouse to lift it out of the
crisis.
	   In another sign of Japan's ailing domestic economy, a private
research agency said Friday that corporate bankruptcies in May
soared by more then a third from the previous month.
	   The Teikoku Databank said the number of business failures was up
37.5 percent. The amount of debt left behind by bankruptcies in May
grew to 781 billion yen (dlrs 5.5 billion), the highest since World
War Two.
	   Japan's poor economic outlook drove the yen to an eight-year low
against the U.S. dollar Friday in Tokyo, and the benchmark stock
average briefly dropped below the psychologically important
15,000-point level for the first time since January.
	   The dollar bought 144.04 yen at mid-afternoon, soaring 2.36 yen
above Thursday's close in Tokyo. The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average
dropped to 14,865.98 at midday but closed at 15,022.33, up 8.29.
 &UR; (mef-et)	   
</TEXT>
