</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. dollar surges against yen, Tokyo stocks steady
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with afternoon dollar and bond rates and closing stock
prices

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar rose to near an eight-year high
against the yen Friday after comments from a top U.S. finance
official overnight convinced traders a coordinated international
effort to strengthen the yen was unlikely.
	   A last-minute rally left Tokyo stocks little changed from the
previous day's close.
	   The dollar bought 144.04 yen at midafternoon, up 2.36 yen from
late Thursday in Tokyo and also above its late New York rate of
143.79 yen overnight.
	   At one point, the dollar was quoted as high as 144.75 yen in
Tokyo, matching its most recent previous high on August 30, 1990.
	   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average
gained 8.29 points, or 0.06 percent, to close at 15,022.33. On
Thursday, the average closed down 325.22 points, or 2.12 percent.
	   The yen's decline began overnight following comments by U.S.
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin that were interpreted as signaling
no U.S. effort to support Japan's ailing yen.
	   Rubin, testifying before the Senate Finance Committee on
Thursday, reiterated that Japan must revive its ailing economy,
warning that ``Japan's economic difficulties and weak currency are
having substantial adverse impact on the East Asian countries.''
	   Rubin said it will be up to Japan to halt the yen's slide.
	   In Tokyo, Japanese finance minister Hikaru Matsunaga said Friday
that Japan was ready to take decisive action against an excessive
weakening of the yen.
	   He said Japan's partners from the Group of Seven nations were
also ready to cooperate on such action.
	   ``The G-7 said at their April Washington meeting that they are
ready to communicate and cooperate if there is a sharp change in
foreign exchange,'' he told a regular press conference.
	   Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto said Friday morning he does not
think the dollar at 144 yen reflects Japanese economic
fundamentals.
	   ``The fact that a situation like this continues shows that the
U.S. isn't interested in talking about current account balance
issues,'' Hashimoto told reporters.
	   The yen's decline hurt bank, oil and steel shares but boosted
shares of exporters which enjoy increased earnings as the yen falls
against foreign currencies.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section of the exchange fell 1.56 points, or 0.13 percent, to
1,1177.25 points. The TOPIX closed down 19.79 points, or 1.65
percent, the day before.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese
government bond fell to 1.210 percent from Thursday's finish of
1.245 percent, driving its price up to 111.94 yen from 111.68 yen.
 &UR; (tz-km-dj) 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Japan-Markets, 3rd Ld-Writethru; CT:f; 
(REG:ASIA;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:AFRI;)
