<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-East Timor, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Twelve East Timorese political prisoners released
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS throughout for PMs, ADDS background. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By CHRISTOPHER TORCHIA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   DILI, Indonesia (AP) _ Walking out of a prison in
Indonesian-controlled East Timor on Friday, a dozen political
prisoners raised their fists and vowed to renew the
pro-independence activism that landed them in jail in the first
place.
	   The prisoners, many of them students, were freed under a pardon
granted by President B.J. Habibie, who is seeking a solution to the
bitter conflict that has plagued East Timor since Indonesia invaded
in 1975 and annexed the territory a year later.
	   In Jakarta, the Indonesian capital, more than 1,000 East
Timorese protesters gathered at the Foreign Ministry to press for a
vote on independence in the former Portuguese colony. Some entered
the main building and sat in the lobby.
	   Shouting separatist slogans, the 12 prisoners filed out of
Becora prison in the East Timorese capital of Dili with plastic
bags full of clothes and other belongings. One man clutched a
chicken.
	   ``This freedom is good for our struggle. It's a victory for
us,'' said Tomas Augusto Correia, a 33-year-old municipal worker
who was among the detainees. Most of the prisoners were students
who were arrested for demonstrating against Indonesian authority.
	   However, the conciliatory gesture from Habibie's reform-minded
government failed to satisfy the demonstrators in Jakarta and other
East Timorese who are demanding the release of Xanana Gusmao, a
separatist rebel leader who was arrested in 1992.
	   Habibie is also reluctant to yield to demands for a referendum
on independence in East Timor, instead offering special status that
might include some autonomy.
	   Gusmao, 52, who is serving a 20-year sentence in a Jakarta
prison, is beloved by many East Timorese who see him as a symbol of
their struggle against Indonesian rule. His rebel group, known as
Fretilin, has dwindled over the years and its fighters carry out
only occasional hit-and-run attacks before retreating to remote
mountain refuges.
	   The government has yet to make clear what it plans to do with
Gusmao, whose case has attracted international attention, including
a plea from South African President Nelson Mandela for his release.
	   East Timorese activist and 1996 Nobel Peace Prize co-winner Jose
Ramos-Horta said the prize should have gone to Gusmao. The
charismatic rebel chief has a sharp sense of humor and a fondness
for poetry. His wife and son live in Sydney, where they are active
in the East Timorese separatist movement.
	   Many in the Indonesian military, however, regard Gusmao as a
violent criminal responsible for the deaths of many comrades. Tens
of thousands of East Timorese also died during Indonesia's efforts
to wipe out resistance in the 1970s.
	   On Thursday, the prisoners in Dili refused to leave the jail,
saying they wanted freedom for Gusmao. They agreed to go Friday
after giving wardens a litany of complaints, ranging from the poor
quality of prison food to military repression.
	   Most were serving one- or two-year sentences, and some were due
to leave jail anyway in the coming days.
	   ``Viva East Timor,'' they chanted. Before catching buses to
their homes, some vowed to attend a pro-independence demonstration
planned this weekend in Dili. 	   
</TEXT>
