<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Sick Forests </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tree plagues destroying China's forests
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Infestations of various pests have destroyed
millions of hectares (acres) of Chinese forests, causing at least 5
billion yuan (dlrs 602 million) in losses of timber resources every
year, the state-run China Daily reported Friday.
	   The State Forest Administration reported that forests in China's
northern, northwestern, eastern and southwestern regions face a
``massive bug plague,'' it said.
	   The report said that pine and poplar species were hit especially
hard, with 8 million hectares (19.7 million acres) of forests
damaged each year.
	   China has reforested vast regions of the country that had been
denuded over the centuries in a belated attempt to control erosion
and reestablish its timber resources. But those man-made forests,
often planted in a single species, are more vulnerable to pests
than naturally occurring forests, it said.
	   The report urged local governments to take more active measures
to prevent the spread of insects and disease.
</TEXT>
