w2398 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-Kosovo     06-12 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-Kosovo,0713 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO confers with Russians on Kosovo
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Lead expected after Solana news conference, scheduled for 0800
GMT. &QL; 
 &UR; By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER &QC; 
 &UR; AP Military Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen
and his NATO colleagues are conferring with Russia on the
alliance's efforts to curb Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's
drive against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo province.
	   Cohen and Russian Defense Minister Gen. Igor Sergeyev were
meeting at NATO headquarters Friday, followed by NATO talks with
the Russian minister.
	   Russia opposes military options NATO is considering for the
Serbian province.
	   NATO Secretary General Javier Solana said Thursday that Russia
advised the alliance it would not participate in NATO's plans for
an air exercise over Albania and Macedonia. The alliance hopes the
show of military strength can persuade Milosevic to halt attacks on
ethnic Albanian separatists in Kosovo.
	   ``We would like to have as many partners as possible participate
in the exercise,'' Solana said of his NATO allies.
	   Russia, which has been brought into some NATO consultations, had
been kept informed of plans for potential military exercises in the
Balkans and at one time had ``showed an interest in
participating,'' Solana said. That was before the most recent
outbreak of violence in Kosovo and NATO's announcement of its air
maneuvers.
	   Moscow favors strengthened control over Kosovo's borders with
Albania and Macedonia. Russia could play a pivotal role in the
persuading Milosevic to turn around the crisis in the
independence-minded province of Serbia, Yugoslavia's dominant
republic.
	   On Thursday, NATO ministers approved a package they hope will
persuade Milosevic to pull back his Serb-led army and police forces
in the province.
	   ``President Milosevic would be rash and foolish if he would
ignore the message coming from NATO,'' said British Defense
Secretary George Robertson. ``The message is clear and unambiguous:
`Belgrade, think again.'''
	   Under the measures, NATO will conduct simulated air attacks in
Albania and Macedonia, probably next week, and study options for
further actions ranging from accelerated planning for military
exercises to direct air strikes inside Yugoslavia and use of ground
troops.
	   This is aimed at persuading Milosevic to do three things:
declare a cease-fire in Kosovo; withdraw his forces and end the
repression of the ethnic Albanians; and open serious negotiations
with the opposition.
	   ``We will be holding exercises in the region, including
immediately an air exercise which will demonstrate NATO's
capability to rapidly project power into the region,'' Solana said.
	   German Defense Minister Volker Ruehe said: ``We cannot afford
any longer to focus on hollow solutions of rather symbolic
character like border security missions in Albania or Macedonia.''
	   It was not clear whether the demonstration of NATO power would
be sufficient to persuade Milosevic.
	   ``I don't think anyone can predict what will impress or persuade
Mr. Milosevic,'' said Cohen. But he said a demonstration of
firepower would have ``some educational value.''
	   A senior U.S. defense official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the exercises will be carried out in the next few
days and could include simulated bombing raids by NATO planes and
rocket attacks by helicopters. Details were being worked out.
	   ``This is the threat of force to back up diplomacy,'' said
Robertson. ``Just as it was in the Gulf, so it is in Kosovo.''
	   Added French Defense Minister Alain Richard: ``We can't let the
protagonists believe that we are prepared to stop at a certain
stage.''
	   More than 250 people have died in clashes between government
forces and the Kosovo Liberation Army, armed wing of the Albanian
independence movement. Ethnic Albanians comprise 90 percent of the
province's population.
	   Milosevic is meeting with President Boris Yeltsin during a
two-day visit to Moscow next week, the Russian presidential press
service said Thursday.
	   Yeltsin invited Milosevic to Russia to discuss the Balkan
situation, including the crisis in Kosovo, the ITAR-Tass news
agency said. Milosevic will be in Russian capital Monday and
Tuesday.
</TEXT>
