<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Cyclone,0419 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Death toll in cyclone crosses 700, exodus begins from villages
</HEADLINE>
without water, food &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By RAMOLA TALWAR &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BOMBAY, India (AP) _ For poor villagers in western India, the
disaster of a cyclone that killed at least 727 people was followed
by desperate shortages that forced them Friday on to mud-choked
roads in search of food and drinking water.
	   The death toll Friday stood at 706 in the hardest-hit state of
Gujarat, as workers continued to find bodies flung on power cables
and trees or buried in sludge left behind by a tidal wave three
days after the cyclone hit land.
	   The cyclone weakened Wednesday as it moved north, leaving nine
more dead in Rajasthan state and 12 more in neighboring Pakistan.
	   At least eight entire villages and three camps for salt factory
workers were wiped out near Kandla port, 530 kilometers (330 miles)
northwest of Bombay.
	   The workers earn their living selling salt left behind after sea
water they collect in pans, or shallow pools, evaporates.
	   Soldiers and government officials distributed food and water and
helicopters airdropped packages, but supplies weren't coming
quickly enough.
	   ``The poor are leaving what is left of their homes and walking
to the next village in search of something to eat,'' said survivor
Tejabhai Desai by telephone from Madhabar, a village near Kandla.
	   ``All the water around here is salty. People can't even drink
the rain water that has collected,'' Desai said.
	   Prices have sky rocketed due to scarcity _ bottled water went
from 10 rupees to 50 (about 23 U.S. cents to dlrs 1.25) in a
country where many people get by on the equivalent of dlrs 1 a day.
	   Fifteen villages remained inaccessible. The army was assisting
government workers in clearing roads blocked by fallen trees and
debris whipped up by winds of up to 100 kph (65 mph) when the
cyclone first hit land in Gujarat.
	   Mass cremations of unclaimed bodies continued Friday because
decaying corpses could not be preserved for identification by
relatives.
	   Although 20,000 people from other villages on the Arabian Sea
coast were evacuated by the government, but officials said the
forecast did not indicate the cyclone would touch the Kandla
region.
	   ``The rains came first and people rushed to bar doors and
windows. Then with heavy winds came the wall of water. It was 16
feet (five meters) high and buried everything. Only few of us could
claw out by then,'' said Desai.
</TEXT>
