<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-US Insurance Trade </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US-Japan insurance talks end unresolved
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Talks between Japan and the United States on
opening Japanese insurance markets to foreign competitors ended
Friday without bridging the differences between the two sides, the
Finance Ministry said.
	   Washington and Tokyo disagree over whether Japan is living up to
commitments to deregulate its life and non-life insurance sectors
under a 1996 pact.
	   Under the deal, the United States had sought faster deregulation
of those sectors, but to delay liberalization of medical and
accident sectors because foreign companies already have a strong
presence there.
	   U.S. officials question whether Japan has opened the life and
non-life sectors enough. Japan, however, insists that it has, and
the ministry said it would proceed with the next stage _ opening
medical and accident insurance to more Japanese companies in 2001.
	   A senior Japanese Finance Ministry official said on condition of
anonymity that no specific dates had been set for the next round of
talks. The 1996 pact requires some life and non-life insurance
reforms, such as liberalization of insurance rates, to be made by
July 1, 1998. Japan says it has already carried these out.
	   The Japanese official also said there were no plans to have U.S.
President Bill Clinton and Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto discuss
the issue when Hashimoto visits the United States next month.
	    &UR; (apdj-tz)
</TEXT>
