<HEADLINE>
Floods kill seven people in Bangladesh
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) _ Floods that inundated scores of
villages in northeastern Bangladesh have killed at least seven
people and displaced several thousand others, a lawmaker who toured
the region said Friday.
	   The deaths of three children, a woman and three men were
reported in hardest-hit Zakiganj and Jaintapur areas of Sylhet
district since Tuesday, governing party legislator Imran Ahmed said
in a telephone interview.
	   They drowned in swirling waters that washed away dozens of
mud-and-thatch huts.
	   The flooding in Sylhet, a tea-growing region 190 kilometers (120
miles) northeast of Dhaka, the Bangladeshi capital, were caused by
torrential rains reported in the hills of the neighboring Indian
state of Assam, according to Dhaka's Flood Control Room.
	   The area's Surma and Kushiara rivers overflowed because of
onrushing waters.
	   At least 2,000 villagers, displaced by the flooding, evacuated
to high ground or school buildings, relief officials at Sylhet
contacted by phone said.
	   Bangladesh, a low-lying south Asian delta nation, is buffeted by
floods and cyclones that kill hundreds of people every year.
</TEXT>
