<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Dissidents </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chinese dissidents urge reassessment of Tiananmen movement
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ELAINE KURTENBACH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ China's leaders should openly debate the
Tiananmen Square democracy movement and free a top reformer kept
under house arrest since the military crackdown nine years ago, a
group of veteran dissidents said Friday.
	   Former Communist Party General Secretary Zhao Ziyang, who was
ousted for appearing sympathetic to the protesters' demands in
1989, should be allowed to go free, the dissidents said in a
written appeal addressed to senior party leaders.
	   ``If even a party general secretary cannot enjoy the protection
of the law and party rules, then how can you guarantee democracy
and human rights to the public?'' said the appeal, signed by 12
dissidents and sent by fax to foreign news agencies.
	   ``If China wants to have democracy and law, then it must first
start with the government and the party leadership,'' it said.
	   Meanwhile, a group set up by U.S.-based dissidents including
recently released prisoners Wei Jingsheng and Wang Dan said Friday
their ``Free China'' network will promote democracy in their
homeland.
	   ``We strive to become a significant force in world politics and
intend to successfully challenge the People's Republic of China in
the media and all political and academic forums throughout the
world in a peaceful manner at our best effort,'' the group said in
a statement.
	   Demands for a reassessment of the military suppression of the
student-led protests, in which hundreds and maybe thousands died,
continue to surface despite the insistence by China's top leaders
that they have reached a ``correct verdict'' on the issue.
	   Many Chinese remain resentful of the crackdown and the lack of a
full accounting for the those killed by troops shooting their way
to Tiananmen Square on June 3-4, 1989.
	   The appeal said it was obvious ``even to an elementary school
student'' that Zhao Ziyang was not responsible for the protests
that sprung up in April 1989 following the death of another ousted
liberal leader, Zhao's predecessor Hu Yaobang.
	   By rehabilitating Zhao, who remains a popular figure, the
dissidents suggested the Communist Party might be able to counter
some of the public discontent caused by widespread corruption and
by rising unemployment.
	   ``Water can carry a boat, but it can also capsize it. We appeal
to the central leadership to reverse the verdict on June 4th and
reverse the verdict on Zhao Ziyang,'' it said.
	   Zhao has not made any public appearances since he made an
emotional appeal to the students on May 19, 1989, the day before
martial law was declared in Beijing.
	   Rights groups have reported recently that Zhao has been held
under tighter security since petitioning Chinese leaders in
September to re-examine the 1989 democracy movement.
	   There is no indication the authorities intend to ease their
suppression of public dissent. Last week, Bao Tong, a former aide
to Zhao who spent seven years in prison following the crackdown,
was warned not to speak with foreign reporters after he issued
several interviews openly criticizing the party leadership.
</TEXT>
