r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Thailand-Laos-Dam     06-12 0291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Laos-Dam </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Environment groups ask Thai premier to scrap Laos power deal
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ A band of 14 environmental groups have
asked Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai to cancel an agreement to
buy electricity from neighboring Laos.
	   The groups are opposed to the building of the dlrs 1.2 billion
Nam Theun Two dam in Laos that will supply the power, because they
say it will destroy the environment and displace thousands of
tribal people.
	   In a letter to Chuan, they said Thailand no longer needed the
power because the economic crisis has led to a drop in consumption
of electricity.
	   Among the environmental groups making the appeal were the
Wildlife Fund of Thailand, Foundation for Ecological Recovery, Thai
Rivers Network, Alternative Energy Study Group and the Thai
Volunteers Service Foundation.
	   The Laotian government is building the 681-megawatt dam as a
partner in a consortium that includes Thai, Australian and French
firms.
	   Nearly all the electricity will be purchased by Thailand.
	   The U.S.-based International Rivers Network has said that the
dam, being built on a tributary of the Mekong River, will flood 447
square kilometers (178 square miles) on the Nakai Plateau.
	   The plateau is home to several endangered species such as the
clouded leopard, Asian golden cat, several species of bears along
with elephants, tigers and some primates.
	   The Thai government spokesman was not immediately available for
comment.
	   During the past few months, however, Chuan has been reluctant to
halt other controversial infrastructure projects, such as a gas
pipeline from Myanmar, because he said the contracts, signed by
previous governments, could not be broken.
</TEXT>
