<SLUG> BC-Myanmar-Business Scams </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Myanmar government warning about Western business scams
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   YANGON, Myanmar (AP) _ Myanmar's military government issued a
warning to local businesses in state-run papers Friday about bogus
international groups cheating Myanmar companies out of money by
offering phony prizes.
	   ``There are several fake international organizations which have
been cheating money from inexperienced entrepreneurs from
undeveloped countries,'' a commentary in local papers said Friday.
	   It cited a Madrid-based firm called the Trade Leaders Club as
one of the cheating companies.
	   The company sent a letter to several Myanmar businesses,
including some that were already defunct and another that turned
out to be a minimart, saying they had been selected as the winner
of the ``10th International America Award for Quality,'' the report
said.
	   The recipients were invited to attend a ceremony at the Waldorf
Astoria Hotel in New York City on July 11 _ but the invitees would
have to pay their own way and then also pay the Trade Leaders Club
a dlrs 4,400 fee, the government said.
	   Myanmar, also known as Burma, was subjected to socialist
isolationism from 1962-88 by former Gen. Ne Win. Although the
current military government has slowly been adopting market
policies and opening up the country to investment, economic
problems still abound.
</TEXT>
