<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Netherlands-Belgium,0519 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Low countries meet again at soccer's highest level
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By MIKE CORDER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   VERSAILLES, France (AP) _ The newest chapter in one of soccer's
oldest rivalries will be written Saturday as neighboring low
countries, the Netherlands and Belgium, clash in their first Group
E match.
	   The Netherlands can take confidence from two easy wins over the
Red Devils in qualifying for this World Cup, but the players are
instead looking to a 4-year-old defeat to sharpen their hunger for
victory at Stade de France in Saint-Denis.
	   In their second match in the 1994 World Cup, the Dutch lost 1-0
to Belgium at Orlando's Citrus Bowl, thanks to a string of fine
saves by inspired goalkeeper Michel Preud'homme.
	   ``There is always a struggle between Belgium and Holland,''
Dutch coach Guus Hiddink said. ``We won twice in the qualification
round, but Holland lost in 1994 in the U.S.A. Now they have players
with a lot of experience. They are a tough and smart team.''
	   The teams meet for the 120th time Saturday. The first ``Low
Countries Derby'' was played in 1905.
	   Dutch winger Marc Overmars predicted a gritty Belgian
performance this time.
	   ``Belgium will not let us play our style. They have good players
so I expect a very tough match,'' he said.
	   Belgium will have to be at its best to contain a strong Dutch
attacking side that could be boosted by the return of star striker,
Dennis Bergkamp, at least for one half.
	   The Arsenal star, with 33 goals in 57 internationals, is
recovered from a hamstring injury and might be able to play one
half Saturday.
	   In its last two warm-up matches, the Netherlands shrugged off
Bergkamp's absence and hammered in five goals against both Paraguay
and Nigeria, conceding just one goal in each game.
	   Bergkamp believes the Dutch, World Cup runner-up in 1974 and
1978, have the skills to do well again this time.
	   ``We have enough quality,'' he said. ``If you also have a good
mentality in the team, you can go very far.''
	   Belgium, which placed fourth in the 1986 World Cup in Mexico,
only managed to beat Paraguay 1-0 last Saturday in Brussels.
	   The Belgians will look to PSV Eindhoven striker Luc Nilis and
Fiorentina frontman Luis Oliveira to break through a Dutch back
four that may be missing Frank de Boer, who injured his ankle
Monday in training.
	   Hiddink said he would leave it until as late as possible
Saturday to judge whether De Boer was fit enough before naming his
team.
	   Nilis, who was criticized after a poor performance against
Paraguay, says the real work starts now.
	   ``I admit I didn't play very well. I missed a few chances. But
the most important thing is Saturday's match. I hope I score
then,'' Nilis said.
	   Oliveira, the other striker, believes the Belgians have to
impose themselves, or risk letting the skillful Dutch dictate the
game.
	   ``We have to play to win. Attack aggressively,'' Oliveira said.
``If we don't, and play a waiting game, we will have no chance.''
</TEXT>
