<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Foreign Ministers,0686 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Major powers grapple with nuclear threat, Balkans unrest
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With NATO-Kosovo &QL; 
 &UR; By BARRY SCHWEID &QC; 
 &UR; AP Diplomatic Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ The South Asian nuclear crisis and ethnic
bloodshed in the Balkans held the attention of foreign ministers
from the world's major powers during meetings Friday to confront
the twin challenges.
	   Their immediate goal, in a communique to India and Pakistan, was
a detailed appeal to freeze their nuclear programs and refrain from
deploying nuclear weapons on missiles.
	   By inviting leading countries from all parts of the world, the
United States and its allies were hoping to amplify the appeal and
discourage others from following the lead of India and Pakistan.
	   ``We are taking one step at a time,'' said a senior U.S.
official, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``Nothing dramatic is
likely to happen here. It is a matter of building up world opinion
and protecting arms control agreements.''
	   In the Balkans, Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic is testing
the will of the international community with his suppression of
ethnic Albanians who account for nearly 90 percent of the
population of the Serbian province of Kosovo.
	   Even as the foreign ministers were gathering, Yugoslav troops
appeared readying a major offensive in the Malisevo region. Tony
Lloyd, the European Union's envoy to Kosovo, told the Albanian
leadership the world would not permit a repetition of the bloody
violence in Bosnia.
	   NATO defense ministers in Brussels agreed Thursday on air
exercises over Albania and Macedonia in the next few days to warn
Yugoslavia against further attacks in Kosovo.
	   ``It is not our desire to use force,'' U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said in Washington before flying to London.
``Our desire is to solve this diplomatically.''
	   On the nuclear front, India and Pakistan said after setting off
nuclear devices last month that they had no plans for more tests.
	   But Albright and her foreign minister colleagues want the
longtime foes to forswear future tests and refrain from deploying
nuclear weapons or testing missiles that could deliver the weapons
to their targets.
	   Albright and the foreign ministers of Britain, France, China and
Russia met in Geneva, Switzerland, last week and appealed for all
those goals. In London, they were being joined by Germany, Japan,
Canada and Italy.
	   To add moral pressure, foreign ministers from Argentina, Brazil,
the Philippines, South Africa and Ukraine, all of whom have given
up the nuclear option, were to join the others at a discussion
intended to persuade India and Pakistan to heed world opinion.
	   Heading into the sessions, there was disagreement on economic
sanctions, which the Clinton administration imposed under U.S. law
against the two countries, and no inclination to offer any rewards
to India and Pakistan to agree to a freeze.
	   Japanese Foreign Minister Keizo Obuchi was expected to announce
a comprehensive nuclear nonproliferation proposal aimed at
preventing India and Pakistan from further developing their nuclear
arms capability as well as urging the United States and Russia to
speed up their nonproliferation efforts.
	   The allies, too, were divided on Kosovo.
	   U.S. President Bill Clinton has left open the possibility of
military force to end the violence against ethnic Albanians.
Britain and the United States may ask the U.N. Security Council
next week for authority.
	   The Italian Foreign Ministry indicated that Italy stands ready
to send troops and to lead a multinational force in Kosovo as it
did in neighboring Albania last year.
	   Russian President Boris Yeltsin has pledged to use his influence
with Milosevic to end police and army attacks. Yeltsin remains
opposed to Western military intervention. He has invited Milosevic
to meet with him in Moscow next week.
	   In Beijing, Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao said
the dispute in Kosovo ``is an internal affair of Yugoslavia and
should be properly settled through political means by the parties
concerned in Yugoslavia.''
</TEXT>
