<HEADLINE>
Japan's prime minister survives no-confidence vote against his
</HEADLINE>
Cabinet &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto survived a
no-confidence vote against his Cabinet on Friday, the second time
he has defeated an attempt to topple his government.
	   The 500-member lower house rejected the no-confidence motion by
a 273-207 vote.
	   The motion was submitted Thursday by Japan's biggest opposition
party, which was joined by two other opposition groups _ Liberal
and Communist parties.
	   With Hashimoto's conservative Liberal Democratic Party
dominating Parliament's powerful lower house, the move had little
chance of success. It was mostly seen as a gesture ahead of upper
house elections expected to be held in mid-July.
	   The three opposition parties blamed Hashiomoto and his
government for failing to jump start the moribund economy. The
government announced Japan was officially in recession Friday.
	   Hashimoto earlier survived no-confidence motion in December.
