w2427 &Cx1f; wstm-
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Japan-Recession 2ndLd-Writethru   06-12 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Recession, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japan's economy in severe recession, deepening fears of regional
</HEADLINE>
crisis
 &UR; Eds: PMs. RECASTS throughout with detail and background &QL; 
 &UR; By MARTIN FACKLER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japan announced its first year of negative growth
in two decades Friday, confirming it is in severe recession and
deepening fears its woes will accelerate a regional crisis that has
already taken the roar out of Asia's economic tigers.
	   The Economic Planning Agency said Japan's gross domestic product
for the fiscal year ended March 1998 shrank by 0.7 percent, the
first full year of economic contraction since 1974.
	   Quarterly figures showed the economy to be where many economists
had already feared: in full-blown recession.
	   The agency said gross domestic product, the sum of all goods and
services produced in Japan, fell by a steeper-than-expected 1.3
percent in the January-March quarter. That follows a drop of 0.4
percent _ revised downward Friday from an earlier estimate of 0.2
percent _ in the previous quarter.
	   Two back-to-back quarters of negative growth is generally
accepted as the definition of a recession.
	   Prospects aren't bright for current year, either, although the
EPA is standing by its 1.9 percent growth forecast. While
economists say an upcoming 16.6 trillion yen (dlrs 116 billion)
stimulus package will help, Japan has shown no signs of taking the
painful steps needed to cure its economic woes.
	   ``The package won't be enough to turn things around,'' said
Chris Calderwood, chief economist at the Tokyo branch of Jardine
Fleming Securities. ``This year will be a growth crater''
	   A recession in Japan bodes ill for the rest of Asia, which had
been counting on the region's largest economy to get its house in
order and lead its neighbors out of financial crisis.
	   Instead, Japan has proven unable to wrench itself from a
stubborn eight-year economic downturn that has already driven its
economy into recession twice.
	   Asia's battered financial markets had been showing their first
signs of recovery since the region's economic crisis began last
summer.
	   But now pessimism about Japan's economy has driven the yen to an
eight-year low against the U.S. dollar. That has put renewed
selling pressure on currencies of other Asian countries amid
concern their exports may not be able to stay competitive in key
markets like the United States.
	   It was just such a sell off of the Thai baht last July that
triggered Asia's regional crisis in the first place.
	   In announcing the GDP figures, an official for the Economic
Planning Agency said falling demand for Japanese exports in Asia,
Japan's largest market, was one of the biggest factors behind the
poor showing.
	   Exports dropped by 3.8 percent in the January-March quarter.
Domestic consumption, which had fallen by 1 percent the previous
quarter, edged up 0.1 percent.
	   But economists agree most of Japan's problems are of its own
doing. Unwise lending by Japanese banks a decade ago has left them
burdened with an estimated 76 trillion yen (dlrs 531 billion) in
failed loans still on their books.
	   Writing off those bad loans has absorbed most the excess cash in
the Japanese banking system, instead of letting it be put to more
productive use in new loans to business.
	   To make matters worse, Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto embarked
on a program to raise taxes and balance Japan's federal budget just
as its economy was showing its first sign of recovery since 1990.
The tax increase squelched consumer spending.
	   Japan's economy has been in a stubborn slump ever since its
stock and property markets collapsed starting in 1990. Some
economists say Japan has gone into recession twice since then _ in
1992 and in 1994-1995 _ while other economists say the second
downturn may not have technically been a recession.
	   Under intense pressure at home and abroad to revive growth to
help the rest of Asia, Hashimoto earlier this year reversed his
policy of fiscal tightening and announced the 16.6 trillion yen
stimulus package.
	   But the biggest danger from Friday's figures may be
psychological.
	   They are only the latest in a constant drum beat of bad economic
news that Japanese corporate managers and consumers have heard for
almost a year now.
	   The danger, say economists, is that all this gloom and doom may
become a self-fulfilling prophecy: Worried factory managers could
cut back on production and hiring, and spooked consumers could cut
back even further on spending.
	   That could make the economy go from bad to worse.
	   ``The numbers could put the economy into a vicious cycle by
damaging the confidence,'' said Shun Motani, president of Sphinx
Investment Research.
 &UR; (mef-et)
</TEXT>
