<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Cyprus-Missiles,0344 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Russian missile parts reach Cyprus
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) _ Turkish intelligence say that radar and
control panels for five Russian-made air-defense missile systems
have reached the divided Mediterranean island of Cyprus, a leading
newspaper reported Friday.
	   The Hurriyet said the parts were transferred from ship to ship
in several Mediterranean ports to elude the surveillance of Turkey,
which has threatened to use force to stop their deployment.
	   Turkish foreign ministry officials were not available for
comment.
	   The newspaper also said that three Russian military delegations
had started to train Greek Cypriot army on how to use the
air-defense systems earlier this week in Cyprus. Turkey claims the
missiles could also be used to launch an attack that threatens the
Turkish Cypriot side of the island _ and Turkey itself.
	   Hurriyet confirmed a Russian report that Cyprus had received
parts of the S-300 missile systems, the Russian equivalent of the
U.S. Patriot missiles used in the Gulf War.
	   Russia's Rosvooruzheniye arms trading monopoly, which signed a
contract with Greek Cypriots for the sale, denied the report,
saying the missiles would be sent to Cyprus in mid-August as
planned.
	   Hurriyet said the rest of the missile systems are expected to
reach the divided island by mid-August.
	   On Friday, Hurriyet quoted Deputy Premier Bulent Ecevit as
saying that ``We will increase the Turkish military strength in
Cyprus, if the S-300 missiles are deployed.''
	   Ecevit ordered the Turkish operation in 1974 as premier.
	   Greece has said it will come to the aid of Cyprus if it is
attacked by Turkey, raising fears of a military conflict between
two NATO allies.
	   Turkish Cypriot Leader Rauf Denktash said they would invite
Turkey to permanently settle in the Turkish sector of the island if
the missiles are deployed, Hurriyet said.
	   Turkish intelligence sources also say that Russia could use the
missiles' radar to monitor the Mediterranean from Cyprus.
</TEXT>
