<SLUG> BC-Israel-Palestinians,0491 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Netanyahu meets with opposition leader; talk of unity government
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DINA KRAFT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu met with the
leader of the opposition Friday amid reports that a unity
government might be under consideration as a way to overcome
right-wing objections to a West Bank withdrawal.
	   Right-wing members of Netanyahu's governing coalition have
repeatedly threatened to bring down his government if he goes ahead
with a much-delayed Israeli troop withdrawal from the West Bank.
The United States is pushing for a 13 percent pullback from the
territory which Israel seized from Jordan in the 1967 Mideast war.
	   The U.S. plan, which not been officially announced although many
its details have been disclosed, is an attempt by the Americans to
re-start the peace process that broke down 15 months ago.
	   Netanyahu told a delegation of U.S. Jews on Friday that an
agreement would be signed only after the Palestinian fulfill their
obligations. Israel has repeatedly called on the Palestinian
Authority to do more to crack down on terror groups as a condition
for continuing the peace process.
	   ``When we have an agreement that achieves our security needs and
that the Palestinians comply with, then I will give it to the
government'' for approval, Netanyahu said.
	   Meir Sheetreet of the ruling Likud party said it was time for
the withdrawal to be carried out and said that the formation of a
unity government was an option.
	   ``The prime minister needs to finish up with second
redeployment,'' Sheetreet told Army Radio, ``If the extreme right
threatens to topple the government we will work towards
establishing a unity government.''
	   Netanyahu met Friday morning with Ehud Barak, head of the Labor
Party, but his aides denied that the two discussed formation of a
unity government.
	   In an interview with Israel Radio, Barak did not address the
possibility of a unity government, but stressed the importance of
the decisions currently being made for the future of Israel.
	   ``A decision on the character of an agreement with the
Palestinians will influence lives, in the best case scenario, or
conversely, God forbid, the deaths of people. Extremely fateful
issues are at hand,'' Barak said.
	   Meanwhile, the prospect of holding a national referendum on the
West Bank withdrawal has been gaining momentum in government
circles.
	   A show of public support could be another strategy for Netanyahu
to the weather the political storm that authorizing a withdrawal
would bring.
	   Following Netanyahu's hourlong meeting with Barak, the prime
minister was meeting with Rabbi Avraham Shapira, a spiritual leader
of the National Religious Party, which opposes any West Bank
withdrawal.
	   Jewish settlers continued their campaign against a withdrawal
Friday, taking five flights of Likud members over the West Bank.
</TEXT>
