<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-RugbyU-World Cup Schedule </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Australia looks good for World Cup semis
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ Australia was given a smooth run into
the semifinals of next year's rugby union World Cup when the draw
for the finals was released Friday.
	   The Wallabies are not scheduled to meet fellow southern
hemisphere powers South Africa until the semifinals and would not
face New Zealand unless they make the final.
	   Depending on the results of qualifying tournaments this year,
Australia will probably confront Ireland, the United States and the
sixth European qualifier, likely to be Spain, in its pool based in
Dublin.
	   If the Wallabies top their pool they will have a quarterfinal
match likely to be against host nation Wales in Cardiff on Oct. 23.
	   A win there would pit them against defending champion South
Africa or England in a semifinal on Oct. 30 at Twickenham, with the
final back at Cardiff's new Millennium Stadium on Nov. 6.
	   The Wallabies' opening match of the tournament would be against
the sixth European qualifier on Oct. 3 in Belfast.
	   Only the top three from the 1995 Cup _ South Africa, New Zealand
and France _ and host Wales qualify automatically, with 65 unions
contesting qualifying tournaments for the remaining 16 places.
	   Australia plays Fiji, Tonga and Western Samoa in September, with
three countries qualifying.
	   South Africa is in Scotland's Pool A, Pool B will include New
Zealand and England, Pool C features France and qualifiers from the
Pacific, Africa and the Americas, Wales hosts Pool D, while
Australia and Ireland are in Pool E.
	   The tournament opens on Oct. 1 with the 41 matches played at 18
venues. (djp) 	   
</TEXT>
