<HEADLINE>
Coach takes blame for record loss
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ROTORUA, New Zealand (AP) _ England coach Clive Woodward has
taken the blame for his team's humiliating rugby union defeat
against Australia in Brisbane last Saturday.
	   He said it was wrong to direct the fault at players, and as
coach he took the responsibility for their record 76-0 test loss to
the Wallabies.
	   ``It's my fault _ if you have anyone to blame then it's me,''
Woodward said Friday on the eve of his team's Saturday match
against New Zealand A.
	   Former England and British Lions standoff Stuart Barnes, who is
following the English tour as a television commentator, said
England erred from day one by accepting such a difficult tour
without some of their top players.
	   Apart from four tests against the world's top three nations,
Australia, New Zealand and South Africa, they have three games
against selection teams in New Zealand, starting with the match
against New Zealand A.
	   At least a dozen leading players remained at home to recover
from the club season.
	   Twenty of the 37 players in the squad started the tour without
any international experience, and at least 10 had never played the
game at any significant level though they had been around the
English club scene for some time.
	   Some players are in the third week of their tour without having
played a game.
	   Powerful New Zealand A includes Jonah Lomu, being tried out to
prove he is ready for next Saturday's first test against England in
Dunedin.
	   Teams:
	   ENGLAND: Tom Beim, Matt Moore, Nick Beal, Dominic Chapman, Jos
Baxendell, Josh Lewsey, Matt Dawson (captain), Steve Ojomoh, Pat
Sanderson, Dave Sims, Rob Fidler, Ben Clarke, Will Green, Phil
Greening, Tony Windo. Reserves: Stuart Potter, Alex King, Peter
Richards, Darren Crompton, George Chuter, Danny Grewcock, Lewis
Moody.
	   NEW ZEALAND A: Adrian Cashmore, Glen Osborne, Caleb Ralph, Jonah
	   Lomu, Jason O'Halloran, Lee Stensness, Rhys Duggan, Xavier Rush,
Scott Robertson, Blair Larsen, Norm Maxwell, Andrew Blowers, Kees
Meeuws, Norm Hewitt (captain), Kevin Nepia. Reserves: Jon Preston,
Steve Surridge, Tana Umaga, Eroni Clarke, Mark Hammett, Gordon
Slater, Royce Willis. Referee: Paddy O'Brien (Southland). (djp) 	   
