<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-New Plane </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ukraine presents new passenger plane to potential customers
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) - Ukraine presented its new An-140 plane to
potential customers from Russia, Moldova and Lithuania, and
officials said they already had orders for the first five planes, a
news report said Friday.
	   The turboprop passenger plane is designed to replace the An-24.
The new model is considered a vast improvement over the aging
An-24, which is used for short- and medium-distance runs throughout
the former Soviet Union and its one-time client states.
	   Thursday's presentation in the eastern town of Kharkiv was
attended by aviation officials from Ukraine, Russia, Moldova and
Lithuania, the Interfax news agency said.
	   Serial production of the An-140 is to be jointly carried out by
the Kharkiv aviation plant and Russia's Samara aviation plant. The
director of the plant in Kharkiv, Anatoly Mialitsa, said his plant
already had received orders for the first five aircraft. He did not
elaborate.
	   The new plane made its maiden flight in 1997. Its first serial
model is due to take off this year and clients would start to
receive the aircraft in 1999, Interfax reported.
	   Designers have previously estimated the demand at 89 planes in
Ukraine, 460 in Russia and 170 in other former Soviet republics.
	   They say the An-140, which can carry 52 passengers for 2,300
kilometers (1,400 miles) at a maximum speed of 555 kph (344 mph),
is just as good and half as expensive as foreign competitors.
	   The An-24 was put into service in the early 1960s. An-24s have
been involved in several air crashes in Russia and elsewhere in
recent years.
	   (sms/ji) 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Ukraine-New Plane; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
