<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Hanson </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Woman of the hour poised to redraw Australia's political map
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos BRIS104, BRIS108 &QL; 
 &UR; With BC-Australia-Asia-Howard &QL; 
 &UR; By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   GYMPIE, Australia (AP) _ In less than two years, Pauline Hanson
has risen from being a politically naive fish-and-chips shop owner
disavowed by her own party to become a right-wing populist
kingmaker in Queensland _ and perhaps soon, the nation.
	   After Queensland's election Saturday, her candidates may hold
the balance of power in this state, where the Parliament is evenly
divided between the governing conservatives and the opposition
Labor Party.
	   On the national level, conservative Prime Minister John Howard
is worried about Saturday's outcome. If the Hanson forces can cost
the conservatives Queensland, they may be able to do the same in
the closely divided Senate in the federal election Howard must call
before March 1999.
	   ``Queenslanders will be the first Australians in living memory
to have the chance to elect a real alternative to the multicultural
and politically correct Labor and (conservative) Coalition parties,
whose policy fulfils the agenda of overseas interests, not our
own,'' Hanson proclaimed last week.
	   Hanson's meteoric rise has come back to haunt Howard's Liberal
Party, which, despite its name, is the more conservative of the two
mainstream Australian parties.
	   In 1996, it dumped Hanson as a Liberal candidate for the
national House of Representatives after her anti-Aboriginal
speeches embarrassed the party. But she was elected anyway as an
independent, and last year sold her shop to launch a national
political movement, the One Nation Party.
	   Hanson, 44, stands out among Australian politicians. She is
refreshingly unpolished in speeches and appearances, winning
sympathy when her voice catches or cracks while making
controversial pronouncements. Many Aussies, wether they agree with
her or not, feel she is closer to the people than the caste of
professional politicians roaming Canberra, the national capital.
	   Loathe to alienate Hanson's right-wing partisans, Howard was
reluctant to confront her more unusual policy pronouncements,
instead defending her right to ``free speech.''
	   Among Hanson's views:
	   _Asian immigration should be frozen, or else by 2040 Australia
will be swamped by Asians. In fact, Britons, New Zealanders and the
Irish form the biggest migrant groups. There are about 1 million
Asians and 303,000 Aborigines among Australia's 18 million people.
	   _Welfare programs that benefit Aborigines should be scrapped on
the grounds that they are racially discriminatory. Australia has a
wide variety of welfare, health and relief programs; some are
exclusively for Aborigines, others are targeted at refugees or
drought-stricken farmers.
	   A book Hanson published last year claimed Aborigines were
cannibals who ate their women and children.
	   _Last week Hanson denounced a draft U.N. declaration on the
rights of indigenous peoples as the ``collusion of Aboriginal
separatists, the U.N. and the disloyal and self-seeking globalists
in our midst'' to set up taxpayer-funded separate Aboriginal
states, dismembering Australia.
	   That finally smoked Howard out, who said her speech was not only
``inaccurate and dishonest but it verges on the deranged in various
places.''
	   But Howard's long-delayed salvo against Hanson came hours after
a major poll indicated her One Nation candidates in Queensland were
pulling so much support away from the governing conservatives that
Labor was likely to win power.
	   Even as Howard castigated Hanson, the Queensland branch of his
Liberal Party had formed a tactical alliance with One Nation.
	   In 88 of the state's 89 electoral districts, the Liberals have
agreed to ``exchange preferences'' with One Nation, which means
that if the Liberals come third in the district, their voters are
directed to turn their votes over to One Nation candidates as their
second preference.
	   The alliance disgusted many Liberal Party stalwarts, including
former prime minister Malcolm Fraser and John Hewson, who led the
Liberals' losing national campaign in 1993.
	   ``Not only is she drawing support because of some of her
particularly racist and other views,'' Hewson said, ``But I think
she's become a focal point for general discontent and
disenchantment with the major parties.''
	   Queenslanders cast their votes Saturday, and a poll on election
eve shows One Nation with support as high as 40 percent in a few
rural districts, and at least 15 percent-20 percent in many others.
	   That could sap enough votes from the conservatives to hoist
Labor to victory. Or it could leave Queensland without a majority
party _ and with Hanson's One Nation holding the balance of power.
</TEXT>
