<SLUG> BC-Egypt-Yassin </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yassin wants to stage sit-in at Egyptian-Israeli border
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Sheik Ahmed Yassin, the spiritual leader of
the Islamic group Hamas, will camp out at Egypt's border with the
Gaza Strip if Israel denies him entry, a newspaper said Friday.
	   Yassin would then leave Egypt for another Arab Muslim country,
the London-based Al-Hayat quoted a Hamas official as saying.
	   Yassin, a 61-year-old quadriplegic, has been on a 3 1/2-month
tour of Muslim countries to raise funds and drum up support for
Hamas, which opposes peace with Israel. Israeli leaders have
debated whether to allow the religious leader to return.
	   It was unclear, however, whether the protest could happen in
Egypt. Yassin had planned to return to the Gaza Strip via Cairo,
but Egyptian officials have reportedly refused to let him enter
either. He has stayed in Khartoum, Sudan, pending a final decision.
	   Khartoum-based Egyptian diplomats told the group that barring
his entry was ``postponement and not cancellation,'' said the Hamas
official, who was not named. Yassin would be granted permission to
enter ``within the next few days,'' the official said.
	   If he did enter Egypt and was barred from Gaza, whose borders
are controlled by Israel, Yassin would stage a sit-in ``until the
Israeli position is exposed to the world,'' the official said.
	   He did not say how long Yassin would remain at the border.
	   Egyptian officials could not immediately be reached for comment.
	   Yassin was freed from an Israeli jail last fall in exchange for
the freedom of two Israeli Mossad agents captured in Jordan during
a bungled assassination attempt against another Hamas leader.
