<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. dollar surges against yen, Tokyo stocks steady
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with late afternoon dollar and bond rates &QL; 
 &UR; By TODD ZAUN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar surged to an eight-year high
against the Japanese yen after comments from a top U.S. finance
official convinced traders an international effort to strengthen
the yen was unlikely.
	   The U.S. dollar bought 144.02 yen in late-afternoon trading, up
2.34 yen from late Thursday in Tokyo and also above its late New
York rate of 143.79 yen overnight.
	   Earlier in the day, the dollar was quoted at 144.75, its highest
level against the yen since it reached that same mark on August 30,
1990.
	   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average
gained 8.29 points, or 0.06 percent, to close at 15,022.33. On
Thursday, the average closed down 325.22 points, or 2.12 percent.
	   U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin told a Senate panel
Thursday that official intervention in currency markets ``can be
useful at times, can have effect at times'' but foreign exchange
rates ``will follow fundamentals'' over time.
	   While Rubin didn't rule out U.S. intervention to support the
ailing yen, his comments were interpreted by traders as meaning the
United States doubts government efforts to sell dollars would curb
the yen's fall.
	   Strong U.S. economic growth and a weakening economy in Japan
have been driving the dollar higher against the yen. The threat of
government intervention in support of the yen has been one of the
only things keeping the U.S. currency from rising further.
	   ``Rubin's comment was an unambiguous expression of the U.S.
stance toward the yen's recent fall,'' said Ryuichi Takami, a
senior trader at Sanwa Bank. ``There is no way to buy yen after
such remark.''
	   Comments from finance officials in Japan didn't do much to slow
the yen's decline.
	   Japanese finance minister Hikaru Matsunaga said Friday that
Japan was ready to take ``decisive action'' against an excessive
weakening of the yen but didn't say when such action would occur or
what it would entail.
	   The yen's decline initially drove stocks lower but last-minute
bargain hunting nudged Japan's main stock index marginally higher.
	   Shares of Honda, Toyota and Sony advanced on the stronger dollar
which lets exporters price their products more competitively
overseas.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section of the exchange fell 1.56 points, or 0.13 percent, to
1,1177.25 points. The TOPIX closed down 19.79 points, or 1.65
percent, the day before.
	   Trading on the main section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange
ballooned to an estimated 817 million shares from 418.14 million
shares Thursday.
	   Declines outnumbered advances 653 to 458, while 169 shares were
unchanged.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese
government bond fell to 1.210 percent from Thursday's finish of
1.245 percent, driving its price up to 111.94 yen from 111.68 yen.
 &UR; (tz-km-apdj)
</TEXT>
