<SLUG> BC-Sports-RugbyU-Australia-Scotland </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Australia expects tough battle from Scotland
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ A week after its easiest rugby union
win in history, Australia expects a far different scenario against
Scotland at Sydney Football Stadium on Saturday.
	   Coach Rod Macqueen and captain John Eales know the inaugural
Hopetoun Cup test will be much more of a contest than last week's
76-0 waltz over England in Brisbane.
	   But while Macqueen said the match was not being treated as a
warmup for next month's encounters with New Zealand and South
Africa, he did concede the depleted Scots, missing eight regular
test players who chose to stay at home, represented a stepping
stone toward the tougher tests.
	   ``We are very focused, we know we've got a hard year ahead,'' he
said. ``We know we've got a bit of ground to make up on some of the
other countries and this is all part of the start of it.''
	   While undermanned, Scotland is nowhere near as weak as England
who had five new players last week. The Scots proved earlier this
year they have greater depth when their A team won the Five Nations
A tournament, including a convincing win over England A.
	   With five tour matches so far in Australia following their 51-26
test loss in Fiji last month, they are far better prepared than
England and even in better shape than when Australia beat them 37-8
in Edinburgh last November.
	   Scotland coach Jim Telfer promised an expansive game to match
Australia's attack which scored 11 tries last week, finding room
for his two fullbacks, Glenn Metcalfe and Derrick Lee, their most
attacking players on tour so far.
	   New Zealand-born Metcalfe makes his debut with Lee on the wing.
Another Kiwi-Scot, flanker Gordon Simpson, also makes his
international debut Saturday.
	   Telfer did not like comparisons with England.
	   ``We are separate entities,'' said Telfer. ``We are trying to
focus on our own game and our players have improved since coming
here.
	   ``A Scotsman tends to respond to hard work and adversity quite
often. I would like to think this would be reflected tomorrow in
our display.''
	   Australian flanker David Wilson plays his 50th test Saturday, as
will reserve back Jason Little if he gets a run from the bench,
which Macqueen indicated was likely. The team is unchanged from the
one that beat England last week.
	   AUSTRALIA: Matthew Burke, Ben Tune, Daniel Herbert, Tim Horan,
Joe Roff, Stephen Larkham, George Gregan, Toutai Kefu, David
Wilson, Matt Cockbain, John Eales (captain), Tom Bowman, Andrew
Blades, Phil Kearns, Richard Harry. Reserves: Chris Whitaker,
Nathan Grey, Jason Little, Willie Ofahengaue, Owen Finegan, Dan
Crowley, Jeremy Paul.
	   SCOTLAND: Glenn Metcalfe, Derrick Lee, Cameron Murray, Rowen
Shepherd, Shaun Longstaff, Gregor Townsend, Bryan Redpath, Eric
Peters, Gordon Simpson, Robert Wainwright (captain), Stuart Grimes,
Scott Murray, Matthew Proudfoot, Gordon Bulloch, David Hilton.
Reserves: Craig Joiner, Duncan Hodge, Graeme Burns, Adam Roxburgh,
Stewart Campbell, Gordon McIlwham, Kevin McKenzie. (djp)
</TEXT>
