<HEADER>
w2458 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Japan-USMilitary 1stld-Writethru   06-12 0285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-US Military, 1st ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. government pays compensation to Okinawan rape victim
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with U.S. military confirmation, money paid in April &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The United States has paid compensation to an
Okinawan schoolgirl raped by American servicemen in 1995, a crime
that led to mass protests against the U.S. military in Japan,
officials said Friday.
	   The United States and Japan agreed on a compensation figure in
March, and the Japanese government also paid the girl separate
compensation, said Tadakazu Ukita of the Defense Facilities
Administration Agency.
	   An official with the U.S. military in Japan said on condition of
anonymity that the payment was made in April. Neither he nor Ukita
would say how much the girl was given.
	   The Japanese government paid the girl directly, and was then
reimbursed by the United States in May, Ukita said.
	   Three U.S. servicemen abducted and raped the 12-year-old girl on
Okinawa, Japan's southernmost main prefecture, in September 1995.
The three were convicted in 1996 and given jail terms ranging from
6 1/2 years to 7 years.
	   The rape exacerbated the already bitter sentiments against the
heavy U.S. military presence on the island, which houses more than
half of the 47,000 U.S. troops stationed in Japan.
	   In response to a string of protests, the U.S. government agreed
to close the Futenma Marine Air Station on Okinawa over the next
several years on condition that an alternative heliport be built
elsewhere.
	   Okinawa, one of the bloodiest battlegrounds of World War II, has
become an important strategic location for U.S. bases, close to
China, the Korean Peninsula and Southeast Asia.
 &UR; (km)
</TEXT>
