<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Central Bank </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Foreign central bankers will revamp Thai central bank next month
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ A group of eight current and former
central bank officials from industrialized nations will arrive in
Thailand next month to help restructure the Bank of Thailand,
government officials said Friday.
	   The announcement was made jointly by Bank of Thailand Governor
Chatu Mongkol Sonakul and Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanahaeminda,
and confirmed by central bank officials.
	   Although Tarrin and Chatu Mongkol declined to name which central
bank officials would be part of the team, they will come from the
United States, England, Germany and Japan, said the bank official
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
	   The use of top regulators to give advice on how to supervise
financial institutions was offered to Thailand in January by World
Bank President James Wolfensohn as part of his bank's services.
	   Thailand's central bank was once regarded as one of the best-run
in Asia until scandals began to surface in 1996.
	   Most of them centered around poor supervision of banks and
finance companies, which were allowed to make a high number of
questionable loans to real estate and other companies without being
checked by the Bank of Thailand.
	   Under a dlrs 17.2 billion bailout of the Thai economy supervised
by the International Monetary Fund, 54 of the country's 91 finance
companies have been shut down and their assets are being
liquidated.
	   The central bank was also deeply involved in the failed defense
of Thailand's currency, the baht. Central bankers depleted the
country's foreign reserves, and were eventually forced to float the
baht last July, touching off Asia's financial crisis.
	   The team of Western central bankers will study the Bank of
Thailand and issue a report on restructuring recommendations after
about four months, the bank official said.
</TEXT>
