<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Caucasus </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police station in restive Caucasus attacked
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ A police checkpoint in the Caucasus republic of
North Ossetia was attacked with grenades and gunfire but no one was
hurt, a news agency reported Friday.
	   The Thursday night attack on the mobile police post near the
mountain village of Chmi was the second to target a North Ossetian
police station in two days, the ITAR-Tass news agency said. On
Wednesday night, automatic rifle-fire and grenades hit another
police post set up near a quarry.
	   Citing local police sources, ITAR-Tass said that ``all traces''
of both attacks led to the neighboring republic of Ingushetia.
	   North Ossetia, which is predominantly Orthodox Christian, and
Muslim Ingushetia fought a short but bloody war in 1992. Hundreds
of people were killed and most ethnic Ingush were expelled from
North Ossetia.
	   Both sides have blamed each other for numerous kidnappings.
	   Earlier this week, North Ossetian villagers detained five Ingush
bus passengers in apparent retaliation for the kidnapping of seven
of their neighbors the day before.
	   Both republics are located in the northern Caucasus, a restive
region that also includes breakaway Chechnya.
	   (ji) 	   
</TEXT>
