r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Indonesia-Presidency     06-12 0211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Presidency </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
President says no plans to seek reelection inn 1999
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ President B.J. Habibie says he has no
plans to be a candidate when a special assembly selects a new head
of state in December 1999, a news report said Friday.
	   ``Don't think that I want to be appointed president again,''
Habibie was quoted as saying by the official Antara news agency.
	   Habibie came to power May 21, after his predecessor Suharto, who
led the world's fourth biggest country for more than three decades,
stepped down amid widespread riots and violent protests over his
autocratic rule.
	   The People's Consultative Assembly, the country's highest
constitutional body, is expected to convene a general assembly in
December 1999 to elect a president and vice president.
	   ``When the MPR (Assembly) elects a president and vice president,
it will obviously not be me,'' Habibie said.
	   ``I will consider my task as president completed'' when the
Assembly meets on December 22, 1999, he said.
	   Habibie reportedly made the comments on Thursday to a group of
business leaders.
	   During his brief time in office Habibie has outlined a timetable
for political reform, including parliamentary elections in May
1999.
</TEXT>
