r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Mexico-Chiapas     06-12 0412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Chiapas,0411 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mexican rebels reappear in Chiapas town
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos SCC102-103 &QL; 
 &UR; By JOHN RICE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN CRISTOBAL DE LAS CASAS, Mexico (AP) _ Most villagers had
fled Chavajeval and only Zapatista rebels patrolled the town square
one day after a bloody clash between rebels and the army.
	   The reappearance of Zapatista troops Thursday seemed to indicate
that the rebels are ready to respond to a tougher government line.
	   The scene in the wake of Wednesday's government raid on villages
in a Zapatista stronghold was reminiscent of early 1994, when the
Zapatista National Liberation Army shook Mexico by rising in revolt
in the southernmost state of Chiapas.
	   The increased government pressure on the Zapatistas and last
week's resignation of the conflict's main mediator, Roman Catholic
Bishop Samuel Ruiz, have increased uncertainty over efforts to
negotiate an end to the struggle in the heavily Indian region.
	   On Wednesday, the government sent hundreds of armed state police
and federal troops into three villages in El Bosque, a township
about 25 miles (40 kilometers) north of here. Officials said they
were carrying out arrest warrants for a few local residents.
	   Government grenades and tear-gas apparently were met with armed
resistance. The government says at least nine people, including at
least one policeman, died.
	   Most local residents and all local officials were absent from
Chavajeval on Thursday, 18 hours after government troops departed.
Reporters instead found armed men in Zapatista uniforms, looted
stores and houses, and blood smeared on a clinic floor.
	   The armed men insisted they were civilians, even though they
wore the traditional Zapatista clothing.
	   ``There are no uniforms here,'' said a gun-toting man who
identified himself as Adolfo Lopez Mateos _ the name of a former
Mexican president. He wore a Zapatista-style dark brown shirt,
charcoal pants, boots and a ski mask tucked in his belt.
	   State police with automatic rifles patrolled the town hall of El
Bosque, the township's seat, where the government on Wednesday
arrested officials of the pro-Zapatista shadow government.
	   In recent weeks, the government has raided at least three of the
30-some townships where Zapatistas have set up parallel
governments. The governments were designed to challenge the
authority of officials chosen in elections boycotted by the
Zapatistas and their allies.
</TEXT>
