<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Asia Business Briefs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Some of these stories also moved earlier as separates.
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Contains items from Japan, Thailand, South Korea and Taiwan.

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ NEC Corp. said Friday it has agreed with China's
telecommunications authorities to supply a digital personal
handyphone system to the staff at the Great Hall of the People.
	   Under the agreement it has signed with the Beijing municipal
government, NEC will install the digital cordless system comprised
of 600 PHS phones, a switchboard and 200 radio antennae.
	   The communications equipment and computer maker hopes to supply
PHS networks to other facilities and begin marketing PHS systems in
China for public use.
	   ___
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Total automobile sales in Thailand
dropped 71.8 percent during the first five months of 1998 compared
with the same period the previous year, according to statistics
released Friday by Toyota Motor Corp.
	   Only 59,636 vehicles were sold in Thailand from January to May
1998 compared with 211,682 during the same period last year, a 71.8
percent decline, said Toyota, Japan's top automaker.
	   Sometimes called ``the Detroit of Asia,'' because of its large
automobile manufacturing industry, Thailand's drastic drop in sales
was attributed to the country's crashing economy which spun out of
control almost one year ago.
	   Nearly 2 million Thais are now unemployed, its currency has
fallen by about 40 percent against the dollar, credit is almost
impossible to obtain and many cars and trucks have been
repossessed.
	   Nearly every major Japanese and U.S. automaker has a production
plant in Thailand. Until the crisis, the country was the world's
largest market for pickup trucks after the U.S.
	   ___
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Spurred by Japan's souring economy, corporate
bankruptcies in May surged 37.5 percent from the same month a year
earlier to 1,791 cases, a private credit research agency said
Friday.
	   Debt left behind by the bankruptcies swelled 55.5 percent from a
year earlier to 780.61 billion yen (dlrs 5.42 billion), the largest
bankruptcy debt total recorded for any month of May since World War
II, the Teikoku Databank Ltd. said.
	   The news of mounting bankruptcies came as the government
announced Japan was officially in recession after gross domestic
product shrank for a second consecutive quarter, by 1.3 percent.
	   With May's figures, bankruptcies in all business sectors have
shown double-digit percentage increases for four straight months,
Teikoku said. Among the hardest hit sectors are construction,
manufacturing and wholesale.
	   Because of bad debt problems, financial institutions are holding
off on granting loans to companies in need of funds, while
deflationary pressures on the economy are worsening companies'
inventory levels, the agency said.
	   ___
	   TOKYO (AP) _ New Japan Securities Co., a major securities firm,
said Friday that it will shut down three of its foreign offices to
deal with tougher competition and financial deregulation at home.
	   Scheduled to be closed are: subsidiary New Japan Merchant Bank
(Singapore) Ltd. in Singapore; a representative office in Seoul;
and New Japan Capital Management (Honk Kong) Co., a unit of its
subsidiary in Hong Kong.
	   After the closures, the company will have seven subsidiaries and
representative offices outside Japan.
	   ___
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ South Korea's Jinro Coors Brewing Co.,
the joint venture brewing unit of financially troubled Jinro Group,
said Friday that Adolph Coors Co. of the United States has offered
to take the South Korean company over.
	   ``The U.S. company is in a meeting with our creditor banks to
discuss the deal,'' said a Jinro Coors official. ``Adolph Coors was
said to have offered dlrs 100 million for the purchase of the
venture.''
	   The official refused to reveal further details.
	   But he added that the final decision on the proposed takeover
will be made by its creditor banks.
	   In April, Jinro Group asked Coors Brewing Co., the principal
unit of Adolph Coors, to take over its brewing unit in a bid to
tide over its financial troubles.
	   Jinro Coors is the largest brewer in the country with about 20
percent of South Korea's beer market.
	   ___
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ Taiwanese exporters retained 73 percent of
their total overseas sales in U.S. currency during the January-May
period, which amounted to dlrs 36.26 billion, the central bank
reported Friday.
	   Exporters had a total overseas sales of dlrs 49.54 billion in
the first five months of 1998.
	   Foreign exchange dealers said exporters were expecting the U.S.
currency to appreciate more before exchanging the bulk of their
dollars into New Taiwan dollars.
	   Since the beginning of the year, the New Taiwan dollar has
depreciated 6.9 percent against the U.S. dollar.
</TEXT>
