<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-South Asian Summit,0307 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
South Asian summit to be deferred
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) _ The annual summit of seven South Asian
leaders _ at which Indian and Pakistani prime ministers were to
meet for the first time since their duel of nuclear tests _ is
likely to be postponed from its scheduled dates of July 9-11,
diplomats said Friday.
	   The new dates for the meeting of the South Asian Association for
Regional Cooperation in the Sri Lankan capital of Colombo are
likely to be July 27-29.
	   No reason for the change was immediately given. The dates for
the summit are arranged by mutual consent of the leaders of India,
Pakistan, Bangladesh, Bhutan, Sri Lanka, Nepal and the Maldives.
	   Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee had already agreed to
the July 9-11 schedule proposed by host Sri Lanka. The formal
invitation had not yet been presented to his Pakistani counterpart.
	   SAARC meetings usually focus on multilateral trade and policy
matters, but the upcoming one was expected to be shadowed by
tension in the region created by tests last month that India and
Pakistan said made them nuclear weapons powers. The two countries
have fought three wars in the past 50 years, and continue to clash
over the Kashmir territory split between them which both claim in
its entirety.
	   At last year's summit, Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and
then-Indian Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral agreed to open
negotiations on Kashmir and a number of other disputes. Those
negotiations stalled. The centrist Gujral was replaced two months
ago by Vajpayee who, though considered a moderate, leads the
right-wing Bharatiya Janata Party known for Pakistan-bashing.
	   Both Indian and Pakistani leaders have said they want to resume
talks, but no date for a meeting has been set.
</TEXT>
