<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Austria-Blockade </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Environmentalists block main north-south artery, other freeway
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   VIENNA, Austria (AP) _ Local resident and environmentalists
Friday started a 28-hour blockade of the Brenner Pass on the
Austrian-Italian border, a move feared to cause a traffic chaos in
both countries.
	   Organizers of the blockade, which has been endorsed by the
Tyrolean provincial government, are venting their anger against
what they consider an intolerable increase in heavy-truck traffic.
They are also protesting European Union traffic policy in general.
	   Intermittent blockades were also planned south of Salzburg on
the Tauern freeway, another north-south artery.
	   The Brenner freeway was to be blocked for all traffic between 11
a.m. Friday and 3 p.m. (1300 GMT) Saturday, but police closed it
already an hour earlier.
	   On the Tauern freeway south of Salzburg, traffic was to be
halted for 20 minutes at every hour between 11 a.m. and 6. p.m.
(1600 GMT) on Friday.
	   Huge traffic tie-ups were expected in northern Italy and in
Austria's western Tyrol province, where traffic was being rerouted
from the Brenner freeway to a narrower highway that can no longer
handle present-day auto and truck traffic.
	   The planned blockade drew sharp criticism from Italy and Germany
and from an Austrian road haulage association.
	   But the demonstration was supported by all political parties in
the Tyrolean provincial diet as well as by the most important
parties in Alto Adige, the German-speaking northern Italian
province.
	   Tyrol governor Wendelin Weingartner was planning to take part in
a gathering on the border, personally endorsing the blockade.
	   (rp)
</TEXT>
