<SLUG> BC-SKorea-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
South Korean stock index plunges to 11-year low
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ South Korean shares tumbled to their
lowest level in 11 years Friday, propelled downward by fears that
the falling Japanese yen could derail efforts for the country's
economic recovery.
	   The benchmark Korea Composite Stock Price Index fell by a record
daily margin of 8.1 percent to close at 302.09, the lowest since
January 1987.
	   A falling yen means more competition for South Korean exports _
bad news for the country's key strategy to revive its economy by
selling more goods abroad.
	   Japan and South Korean compete in such key products as cars,
computer chips and home appliances, and the weak yen makes Japanese
goods more competitive in overseas markets.
	   The Japanese yen slipped to an eight-year low of 144.65 against
the dollar Friday. It recovered later in the day, hitting 143.90
yen to the dollar in late afternoon in Tokyo.
	   ``Investors went on a selling spree on signs of instability in
other Asian markets amid the yen's plunge,'' said Park Jun-kyu, an
analyst at Dong-Ah Securities Co.
	   Park said the market sentiment was dampened by concerns that
foreign investors may desert the country, scared by growing
regional instability caused by the falling yen.
	   Earlier this week, the central Bank of Korea estimated that when
the Japanese yen falls by 10 percent, South Korea's annual exports
would decrease by dlrs 1.2 billion.
	   South Korea hoped to use its own weak currency to dramatically
boost exports. But the falling yen all but dashed such hope, the
bank said.
	   South Korean car and other companies are already struggling
under mounds of unsold products as Koreans tightened their belts
and domestic sales plunged.
</TEXT>
