<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-South Korea-Mexico,0506 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Mexico and South Korea hopes hinge on head-to-head
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ERICA BULMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LYON, France (AP) _ Any hopes Mexico and South Korea entertain
of advancing past the first round of the World Cup hinge on the
outcome of their opening match on Saturday.
	   The two less-fancied teams of Group E that includes soccer-power
Netherlands and tough Belgium know that anything less than a
victory in Lyon could bring their stay in France to an early end.
	   Mexico has from the start made it clear its objective is to be
one of two teams from the group to advance to the second round,
while South Korea would be satisfied just to win its first match in
five World Cup finals.
	   ``The match against South Korea is the most important,'' said
Mexico's coach Manuel Lapuente. ``It's our biggest chance of
earning three points, then maybe we can get another with a tie
against Belgium.
	   ``If we don't manage to beat South Korea we'll face a severe
problem against Netherlands and Belgium.''
	   Even before arriving in France, the Koreans pinpointed their
match against Mexico as their best chance for the landmark victory.
They have focused all their attention and effort on the match, as
though it were the World Cup final.
	   ``The match against Mexico is a major preoccupation for us, and
we believe it is a key match for us,'' said Seo Jung-won, who also
played for South Korea in the 1994 World Cup in the United States.
``We think that our level of play has improved drastically since
1994 and we are sure we can win.''
	   Mexico is also anxious to show that a string of poor
performances in warm-up matches ahead of the World Cup are not an
indicator of the team's potential. The team is known as ``El
Tricolor'' for its green, red and white national colors.
	   South Korea knows it's facing a tough opponent.
	   ``Even though Mexico had bad luck in its friendlies before the
World Cup, it is a team with a lot of potential,'' said South
Korean coach Cha Bum-kun, who played for South Korea in the 1986
World Cup finals in Mexico.
	   Mexico is also exercising caution.
	   ``Korea is a hard team, with very fast players,'' said defender
Claudio Suarez. ``They'll be difficult to beat. We'll need to play
well, stay concentrated and beware of breakaways, which they excel
at.
	   ``Technically they have improved in the last 10 years,'' said
Suarez. ``I remember in 1986, the team lost to Italy and Argentina
and had a draw with Bulgaria. This is a very different team from 10
years ago.''
	   In soccer-mad Mexico, where the match will be televised live at
10 a.m. local time, over 55 million people are expected be watch.
	   The South Koreans, meanwhile, are counting on the team to boost
the nation's morale in a time of economic troubles.
</TEXT>
