<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Spain-Nigeria,0514 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Spanish technique, Nigerian spontaneity face off
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By CIARAN GILES &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NANTES, France (AP) _ Flair and technique versus speed and
spontaneity. That's the bill of fare as Spain's most compact team
in years takes on Olympic champion Nigeria Saturday in the World
Cup opener for both teams.
	   The two are favorites to qualify from Group D, generally
recognized as the closest to a ``Group of Death'' here.
	   ``We're playing the toughest team in the most difficult group,''
said Spain coach Javier Clemente, who calls this the best squad
he's ever had.
	   Spain went 8-2-0 in qualifying and has just one loss in its last
34 outings overall.
	   ``We're worried about Spain the same way Spain is worried about
Nigeria,'' said Nigeria coach Bora Milutinovic, leading his fourth
different team at the tournament. ``I put Spain right after the top
five teams: Brazil, Argentina, Germany, Italy and France.''
	   His Super Eagles come with a reputation for scant attention to
strategy, compensated by dazzling skills and blistering speed. They
displayed those traits in their 1994 cup debut, when they made the
second round and nearly knocked off Italy, and again in winning
Olympic gold in Atlanta two years after.
	   But Nigeria has been consistently bad in its string of warmups
ahead of France 98, dropping three games against fellow qualifiers
by a combined score of 9-1.
	   Clemente, however, believes the warmup results will have no
bearing, saying, ``Nigeria is a sensational team and one of the 10
favorites to win the cup.''
	   Milutinovic saw Spain's 4-1 drubbing of Northern Ireland last
week and said that while he admired the team's discipline, he
spotted some weak points he hopes to exploit.
	   With both teams fearing a morale-damaging defeat at the outset,
the coaches might not be scorned for caution.
	   Relying heavily on stars from European club champion Madrid and
domestic league titlist FC Barcelona, Clemente is likely to play a
conservative 4-4-2 combination with Andoni Zubizarreta, 36, in goal
for his fourth World Cup. Fleet-footed Alfonso Perez would be one
striker, with Kiko Narvaez a little behind.
	   Milutinovic has hinted he might be content to seek a draw
against Spain, which would mean a more contained, defense-minded
Nigeria.
	   That would be attributable, at least in part, to the slew of
injuries.
	   While Spain is healthy, Nigeria already has lost defender Jero
Shakpore to a broken collarbone and replaced him Wednesday with
Mobi Oparaku. In addition, first-choice keeper Ike Shorunmu and
veteran striker Emmanuel Amunike were not even brought to France
because of injury.
	   The team got some good news Thursday, though, when Inter Milan
striker Nwankwo Kanu rejoined the squad for full training. He was
the star of the 1996 effort three months before undergoing heart
valve surgery.
	   His comeback has been slowed by various leg injuries, and an
appearance Saturday would certainly boost the team.
</TEXT>
