<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Singapore dollar falls, stocks level
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with market closing, new recession prediction, big
electronics loser; ADDS byline. &QL; 
 &UR; With BC-Asia Recessions, BC-Asian Markets
 &UR; By LAURINDA KEYS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Following the lead of the Japanese yen and most
Asian currencies, the Singapore dollar fell Friday to a 4 1/2-month
low as a fourth investment house forecast recession this year for
the local economy.
	   But after diving to a 9 1/2 year low earlier in the week, the
key stock index recovered somewhat as buyers grabbed blue chip
shares at bargain prices.
	   Vickers Ballas Investment Research predicted Singapore would
fall into a recession this year. Vickers said the economy will
contract 2 percent during the second half of the year, after an
aggregate 3 percent growth in the first half. It predicted a
full-year growth of gross domestic product of .4 percent.
	   The government has said that later this month it will adjust its
currently rosy 2.5 percent to 4.5 percent GDP prediction for the
year, but is awaiting May financial figures.
	   Traders have said the Singapore dollar is easy to sell because
it is more liquid than other regional currencies and local interest
rates are higher. However, those rates have been dropping as the
currency loses value against the U.S. dollar.
	   The Singapore currency hit its lowest level since late January
at 1.756 against the U.S. dollar. But the Singapore currency
recovered slightly to 1.746 by late afternoon.
	   Its value has been steadily decreasing over the past few months
and is 21.6 percent lower against the U.S. dollar than last July 1,
the day before the Asian economic crisis began.
	   Singapore's benchmark Straits Times Industrial Index dipped 21
points, or 2 percent, immediately after the market opened. By
closing it had regained the day's losses and was up 4.66 points, or
.4 percent.
	   However, the index has lost 889 points, or 45 percent of its
value, since last July 1's level of 1981.28.
	   Bank and property stocks continued to be worst hit.
	   But the electronics sector also took a beating on Friday, when
the Stock Exchange of Singapore Electronics Index fell 7.4 percent
to its lowest level since October, 1996.
</TEXT>
