<SLUG> BC_Hong Kong-Stocks </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Share prices close generally higher
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Share prices in Hong Kong closed generally
higher Friday after three straight sessions of sharp losess.
	   The Hang Seng Index, the market's key indicator of blue chips,
rose 29.37 points, or 0.37 percent, to 7,915.44. On Thursday, the
index had slumped 93.30.
	   Turnover amounted to 5.99 billion Hong Kong dollars (U.S. dlrs
767 million), down from Thursday's 6.75 billion Hong Kong dollars
(U.S. million).
	   Brokers attributed the uptrend to selective bargain-hunting
following recent sharp falls because of the fall of the Japanese
yen against the U.S. dollar.
	   They said the index, which fell at the opening in reaction to
overnight falls on Wall Street, appeared to have found some support
at the 7,900-point level.
	   Among gainers, Hang Seng Bank rose 1.60 Hong Kong dollars to
47.00, Hutchison Whampoa rose 30 cents to 33.20, and Cheung Kong
rose 20 cents to 32.90.
	   Going against the trend were HSBC Holdings, which fell 50 cents
to 176.00, and New World Development, which fell 15 cents to 14.40.
</TEXT>
