<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Greenpeace, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0424 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Greenpeace floats ``anti-nuclear'' balloon over Indian monument
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADD scene in last graf. RAISES Greenpeace statement. ADDS
photo numbers. &QL; 
 &UR; With India-Pakistan-Nuclear &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos AGR101-102 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   AGRA, India (AP) _ Greenpeace protesters chose India's most
recognizable monument _ the Taj Mahal _ as the site of a protest
Friday, floating an Earth-shaped hot air balloon draped with
anti-nuclear banners about 200 meters (yards) from the 345-year-old
tomb.
	   Greenpeace spokeswoman Luisa Colasimone said about 30 soldiers
surrounded the balloon when it touched down after the early morning
protest in a field across a river from the Taj Mahal. She said four
protesters were being detained, but it was not clear whether they
would be arrested.
	   Indian authorities can be zealous about protecting the tomb
known worldwide as a monument to love. The Supreme Court recently
ordered nearby factories to close because pollution is blamed for
yellowing the Taj Mahal's white marble walls. Last year, musician
Yanni was required to keep the volume down at an outdoor concert
held nearby for fear noise vibrations would worsen cracks that have
begun to show on the monument.
	   Greenpeace, which has campaigned against nuclear weapons since
it was formed in 1971, has sharply criticized last month's
tit-for-tat nuclear testing by India and neighboring Pakistan.
	   ``Becoming a nuclear weapons state should be an embarrassment to
every citizen,'' Simon Carroll, who led the Greenpeace balloon
protest, said in a statement. He also called on the traditional
nuclear powers _ Britain, China, France, Russia and the United
States _ to destroy their stockpiles of nuclear weapons.
	   The environmental group is known for headline-grabbing protests
in which demonstrators against factory fishing in the United States
spent nearly two days suspended by ropes from a bridge and another
in which their Rainbow Warrior sailed into France's South Pacific
nuclear testing sites.
	   The Taj Mahal is located in Agra, 200 kilometers (125 miles)
south of New Delhi and some 600 kilometers (375 miles) east of
India's nuclear test site. Greenpeace organizers said they wanted
to stage their protest at a place the world would recognize as
Indian.
	   The Greenpeace balloon drew a small crowd of villagers Friday,
while across the river tourists at the Taj Mahal gathered along the
back wall of the complex to watch the balloon take off, hover about
50 feet (16 meters) and land.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-India-Greenpeace, 2nd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
