w2508 &Cx1f; wstm-
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Trade-Environment     06-12 0427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Trade-Environment </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WTO chief: countries must cooperate on free trade and environment,
</HEADLINE>
labor policies &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   GENEVA (AP) _ Freeing-up of trade will continue, despite claims
that it ignores and causes environmental and labor problems, World
Trade Organization chief Renato Ruggiero pledged.
	   But countries must cooperate more to reconcile liberalization
with those concerns, Ruggiero said in a speech to the Hamburg-based
Friedrich Ebert Foundation.
	   ``We must stop viewing the world through a narrow lens and begin
to look at the various challenges we face as pieces of a larger
puzzle demanding broader, more integrated solutions,'' Ruggiero
said in his speech Thursday, a copy of which was released in Geneva
Friday.
	   In the face of protests that the free trade system ignores and
contributes to poverty, unemployment and environmental problems,
ministers last month told the WTO to prepare for talks to further
open up the world economy.
	   But President Bill Clinton and others pledged to try to make the
organization and the global trade system more open and sensitive to
environmental and labor concerns.
	   Ruggiero said the best way to address the worries is through the
system itself. ``If people, especially young people, say
unemployment is too high, they are right. If environmentalists say
growth must be sustainable - and not destroy the planet's essential
equilibrium - they are right.
	   ``But none of these international - and national - problems will
be resolved any easier by restricting trade, closing borders, or
undermining the international rule of law - as embodied in the
WTO.''
	   Ruggiero said the WTO's success was built on a broadening
international consensus. ``We will only reach durable global
solutions to the environment or labor issues ... by constructing
the same kind of international consensus from the bottom up,'' he
said.
	   The WTO committee on trade and the environment needs ``a new
sense of dynamism,'' Ruggiero said. The process to revitalize the
link between the two issues would begin with a ``thorough
preparatory process,'' he added.
	   Much greater technical and policy coordination is needed at the
national as well as international level. National delegations must
bring a ``coherent and consistent message to the negotiating
table.''
	   ``Trade liberalization must be supportive of environmental
objectives; but environmental policies must also be supportive or
growth and development through trade liberalization,'' Ruggiero
concluded by saying.
 &UR; (pw)
</TEXT>
