<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Libya-Gadhafi </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Official Libyan agency calls Gadhafi attack `lies'
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Reports that Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi
was wounded in an assassination attempt last week are ``lies and
cheap allegations,'' the official Libyan news agency said.
	   Libyans arriving in Egypt said the attack took place June 1 on a
coastal road in eastern Libya when Gadhafi was en route to Egypt
for an official visit. The Libyan leader was slightly wounded in
the elbow and one of his female bodyguards was killed, they said.
	   The account could not be confirmed and diplomats in the Libyan
capital, Tripoli, said they had not heard of the incident.
	   The reports amount to ``a flood of lies and cheap allegations,''
the Libyan news agency JANA said late Thursday.
	   It said the reports were circulated by ``a bribed agent,'' but
did not say what country was responsible.
	   Gadhafi was scheduled to visit Egypt for nine days beginning
June 2, but the trip was postponed to June 5. That trip was then
canceled and no explanation was given. President Hosni Mubarak of
Egypt said it was put off because Gadhafi had tonsillitis.
