<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-Crimea </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Foreign investments total dlrs 150 million in Crimea
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) - The volume of foreign investment in the
economy of Ukraine's Crimean Peninsula stood at dlrs 150 million as
of Jan. 1 this year, the autonomous republic's deputy trade
minister said Friday.
	   Foreign investments grew by dlrs 16.7 million since early 1997,
said the official, Alexei Verchenko.
	   Russia accounted for 62 percent of the investments, followed by
the United States, Britain, Germany and Turkey, he said, according
to the Interfax news agency.
	   Foreigners have invested in 120 Crimean enterprises, located
mainly in the south and in the capital Simferopol, which are
producing machinery, fuel, foodstuffs and other goods, Verchenko
added.
	   Crimea, a top resort area during the Soviet days, long has been
awaiting an economic and tourist boom. But the situation in Crimea
is complicated by the peninsula's underdeveloped economy and
political tensions.
	   Populated mostly by ethnic Russians, the Black Sea peninsula was
part of Russia before being transferred to the jurisdiction of
Soviet Ukraine in the 1950s. Many ethnic Russians dream of
returning to Moscow rule.
	   (sms/ji) 	   
</TEXT>
