w2543 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UN-Kosovo-Refugees     06-12 0329
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Kosovo-Refugees </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Refugee flow to Montenegro continues, U.N. says
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   GENEVA (AP) _ The influx of refugees into Albania from Kosovo
has ``abated considerably,'' but a flow into neighboring Montenegro
continues, the U.N. refugee agency said Friday.
	   Refugees are arriving in Montenegro from the troubled Yugoslav
province at a rate of some 350 per day, compared with around 150
new arrivals in Albania Thursday, said Kris Janowski, spokesman for
the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees.
	   Around 9,000 refugees have fled to the Yugoslav republic of
Montenegro since tension between Serbian authorities and the ethnic
Albanian majority in Kosovo flared up earlier this year.
	   ``About 30 percent of those people are ethnic Serbs,'' Janowski
said. In that group, ``there are a lot of young men who apparently
took off since they don't want to be drawn into the conflict or
drafted.''
	   The agency estimates the total number of refugees displaced by
the conflict at around 65,000.
	   UNHCR has expressed concern over the situation of some 13,000
Serbs relocated to Kosovo from Croatia and Bosnia, some of whom
have sought safety in the province's capital, Pristina.
	   Janowski said the agency is also addressing an accommodation
problem in the Montenegro coastal town of Ulcinj, where many ethnic
Albanians have fled.
	   Hotel owners in the resort ``essentially don't want to fill
their facilities with displaced people,'' he said.
	   Meanwhile, the Norwegian air force has agreed to lift emergency
supplies from Sarajevo to Tirana in an operation expected to start
Saturday and last a maximum four days, Janowski said.
	   It is expected to fly between two and four times a day, using
standard C-130 military transport planes.
	   ``We have been in touch with other NATO nations'' with a view to
getting supplies airlifted from Tirana to cope with some 12,000
refugees in northern Albania, Janowski said.
 &UR; (gm)
</TEXT>
