<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-New Trains </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
France, Germany, Japan contract for new Singapore trains
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ French and Japanese train technology will be
used in Singapore's two new Mass Rapid Transit lines, including an
airport connection service and a driverless, underground Northeast
Line.
	   The contracts worth 800 million Singapore dollars (dlrs 460
million) were signed Friday. Communications Minister Mah Bow Tan
also announced a third new line will be completed by 2004.
	   The 13-kilometer (8-mile), 1.75 billion Singapore dollar (dlrs 1
billion) project will connect the developing, downtown Marina
district with the Orchard Road shopping and residential area.
	   When airline travelers board the new Changi Airport Line,
scheduled for completion next century, they'll be riding in 25
Japanese carriages built by a Kawasaki/Nippon/Sharyo joint venture,
Mah announced.
	   On the Northeast Line, now under construction, the automatic,
electric trains _ operated by computer and monitored via two-way
televisions in each passenger compartment _ will be built by
France's GEC Alsthom Transport SA.
	   The signaling system and platform doors that will be
synchronized with the automatic trains will be built by GEC Alsthom
in a joint venture with a Singapore company.
	   Computers will allow the 25 trains on the 20-kilometer (12-mile)
Northeast Line to arrive as fast as every 90 seconds on the route
through Chinatown, along the Singapore River, past the prime
minister's residence and Orchard Road.
	   Maintenance, management, communications and other systems for
the 5 billion Singapore dollar (dlrs 2.86 billion) Northeast Line
project will be built by France's Spie Enertrans and SYSECA; and
Japan's Mitsubishi Corp., Mitsubishi Electric, Itocho Corp., and
Mitsui and Co.
	   Other contracts went to Singapore companies and joint ventures.
Contracts for an automatic fare collection system, and tunnel
ventilation have not yet been awarded.
	   Germany's Schoma Christoph Schottler Maschinenfabrik won a
contract to build locomotives to upgrade existing subway lines,
which will also be getting 16 new cars.
	   Mah said Singapore plans to double its rapid transit network
within the next 10 years and make it comparable to the London
Underground, the Paris Metro or the Tokyo subway.
</TEXT>
