<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-War Crimes Suspect </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
German officials to revoke passport of former Nazi SS officer
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MUNICH, Germany (AP) _ Bavarian officials said Friday they have
begun proceedings to revoke the German passport of a former Nazi SS
officer, which would allow his extradition to the Czech Republic to
face war crimes charges.
	   Czech officials have said they want to retry the 86-year-old
suspect, Anton Malloth, for the murders of inmates at a World War
II concentration camp. They argue that his German citizenship is
invalid and therefore cannot protect him from extradition.
	   Malloth, born in 1912 in Austria, took Italian citizenship after
World War I, then became a German in 1939 _ after Germany had
annexed Austria _ so he could join the SS.
	   He was a guard during World War II at the Theresienstadt
concentration camp, near Prague. In 1948, a Czechoslovak court
convicted him of hundreds of murders at a Gestapo prison in the
camp and sentenced him to death.
	   But he had fled to Italy and reclaimed his Italian citizenship.
Rome revoked it, however, in 1956 after finding he lied about his
SS past.
	   He was deported in 1988, but to Germany because he still had
German papers. He has lived since then on welfare in a retirement
home in Pullach, near Munich.
	   The Bavarian Interior Ministry had asked Italian officials to
help settle Mamlloth's citizenship. In a statement Friday, state
secretary Hermann Regensburger said they had determined that
Malloth has been stateless since 1956.
	   Regensburger said thse process to revoke Malloth's passport
began Wednesday. He said he could not estimate how long it would
take, since Malloth could challenge the decision in court.
	   Asked whether Malloth would be extradited, he said the state had
yet to receive an official request from Prague.
 &UR; (pfg-cb)
</TEXT>
