w2565 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-China-Tibet     06-12 0406
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Tibet </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chinese authorities evict Tibetan nuns, wreck temple, group says
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Chinese authorities have forcibly evicted Tibetan
Buddhist nuns from a cave sanctuary and wrecked nearby temples to
curb a religious resurgence in Tibet, a monitoring group reported
Friday.
	   About 50 nuns, their Buddhist lama and an unspecified number of
other followers were expelled from the temples and meditation caves
at Drag Yerpa in April, the London-based Tibet Information Network
said, citing unidentified Tibetan sources and tourists.
	   Laborers under orders from the local government demolished the
temples so quickly the clerics apparently did not have time to
salvage altars, the group reported. Photographs given to the group
showed parts of shrines lying amid the rubble.
	   Tibet Information Network said it had confirmed that at least
three other monasteries have been closed down in Tibet since China
launched a campaign more than two years ago to purge the clergy of
monks and nuns supporting independence for the Himalayan region.
	   The crusade has banned photographs of the Dalai Lama, the exiled
head of Tibet's theocratic government that China's communist forces
defeated in 1951. Clergy members have been told to denounce the
Dalai Lama or face expulsion.
	   In one case, at Jonang Kumbum monastery in western Tibet,
officials carrying out the campaign in September 1996 pointed
pistols at the heads of monks to force the denunciations, Tibet
Information Network said. The monastery was later closed.
	   At Drag Yerpa, 30 kilometers (20 miles) northeast of the Tibetan
capital, Lhasa, nuns refused to leave their meditation caves,
prompting the authorities to come evict them, the group said.
	   ``They grabbed their hands, dragged them down from the caves and
put them in the vehicles,'' the group quoted a Tibetan source as
saying.
	   Tibetans believe the Drag Yerpa caves were once used by
Padmasambhava, the mystic who brought esoteric tantric Buddhism to
Tibet in the 8th century. Twenty temples and monasteries dotted the
region before China began outlawing Tibetan Buddhism following an
abortive uprising against Chinese rule in 1959.
	   Chinese authorities insisted the Drag Yerpa temples, built since
bans on religion were relaxed in the 1980s, had to be demolished
because they were not located exactly on the site of pre-1959
structures, Tibet Information Network said.
</TEXT>
