<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Cyprus-Missiles, 1st Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Russian missile parts reach Cyprus
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDs: UPDATES with denial, quotes from Greek embassy spokesman; ADDS
background &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) _ Turkish intelligence say that radar and
control panels for five Russian-made air-defense missile systems
have reached the divided Mediterranean island of Cyprus, a leading
newspaper reported Friday.
	   But Greek embassy spokesman Nikos Papaconstantinou said the
Hurriyet report was unfounded.
	   Hurriyet said the parts were transferred from ship to ship in
several Mediterranean ports to elude surveillance by Turkey, which
has threatened to use force to stop their deployment.
	   It also said that three Russian military delegations earlier
this week began training the Greek Cypriot army on how to use the
air-defense systems. Turkey claims the missiles could also be used
to launch an attack that threatens the Turkish Cypriot side of the
island _ and Turkey itself.
	   ``Cyprus has recently decided to bring the missiles to the
island in October or November,'' Papaconstantinou said. ``It adds
more time for discussions to see how to overcome the impasse.''
	   Cyprus has said it is ready to cancel the dlrs 200 million
missile deal if there is substantial progress toward the
reunification of the island and if Turkey accepts its proposal for
demilitarization.
	   Unidentified Turkish foreign ministry officials said the
postponement of the whole missile shipment would not change Turkish
opposition, the Anatolia news agency reported Friday.
	   Papaconstinou also repeated Greek arguments that the missiles
were purely defensive and would pose no threat to anyone.
	   ``But threatening to use force against them is worrisome,'' he
said.
	   Russian embassy officials were not available for comment.
	   Hurriyet confirmed, 5th graf pvs
	   (sh-fd)
</TEXT>
