<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Doctors Cutback </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Malaysia halts new intake of foreign doctors
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ The government has banned the
recruitment of doctors from overseas in public hospitals to stanch
the outflow of foreign exchange from Malaysia's troubled economy,
an official said Friday.
	   Nevertheless, experienced foreign doctors who were willing to
work in rural areas would be allowed to remain, the national news
agency Bernama reported, quoting Health Minister Chua Jui Meng.
	   ``Many of them whose contracts are expiring have expressed the
desire to continue service. I think it is sensible to allow them to
continue service,'' he was quoted as saying.
	   Chua said many foreign doctors were prepared to work in the
sparsely-populated Malaysian states of Sabah and Sarawak on Borneo
island.
	   Out of the 704 positions available, the government has approved
or renewed the contracts of 426 medical officers and specialists
who come mostly from India, Pakistan and Bangladesh.
	   On Monday, the health minister also announced that Malaysia
would no longer recruit nurses from abroad. He said the shortage of
staff in state hospitals could be filled by deploying more than
3,000 local trainee nurses.
	   Many foreign workers repatriate their savings to their home
countries after converting them into dollars or their respective
local currencies, thus tapping into the nation's foreign exchange
reserves.
</TEXT>
