</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-Kosovo, 1st Ld-Writethru, ,0653 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO confers with Russians on Kosovo
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with U.S.-Russian meeting; Lead expected
after Solana news conference, rescheduled to 1435 GMT. &QL; 
 &UR; By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER &QC; 
 &UR; AP Military Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen,
in talks Friday with his Russian counterpart, warned that Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic should ``get the message'' and rein in
his forces in the separatist province of Kosovo, U.S. officials
said.
	   Cohen's meeting with Russian Defense Minister Gen. Igor Sergeyev
came a day after the NATO alliance approved a show-of-force air
exercise over Yugoslav neighbors Albania and Macedonia. NATO also
ordered options be drawn up for possible intervention in Kosovo,
including direct air strikes or the use of ground troops.
	   Russia opposes the military options NATO is considering for the
Serbian province. But a U.S. official present at Friday's 45-minute
meeting at NATO headquarters said it was ``very friendly and frank
throughout.''
	   Cohen and Sergeyev ``agreed ... the violence must stop,'' said
the defense official, speaking on condition of anonymity. Sergeyev
``stressed the importance of the diplomatic approach'' and pointed
to a meeting Monday in Moscow between Milosevic and President Boris
Yeltsin on the Balkan situation.
	   For his part, Cohen stressed NATO's dim view of the violence in
Kosovo and said the alliance's intentions should not be
misunderstood, the official said.
	   ``Milosevic should get the message of our seriousness,'' the
official said, adding that those fighting for independence in
Kosovo also should put down their weapons.
	   On Thursday, NATO Secretary General Javier Solana said that
Russia advised the alliance it would not participate in NATO's
plans for an air exercise over Albania and Macedonia. The alliance
hopes the show of military strength can persuade Milosevic to halt
attacks on ethnic Albanian separatists in Kosovo.
	   ``We would like to have as many partners as possible participate
in the exercise,'' Solana said.
	   Russia, which has been brought into some NATO consultations, had
been kept informed of plans for potential military exercises in the
Balkans and at one time had ``showed an interest in
participating,'' Solana said. That was before the most recent
outbreak of violence in Kosovo and NATO's announcement of its air
maneuvers.
	   Moscow favors strengthened control over Kosovo's borders with
Albania and Macedonia. Russia could play a pivotal role in the
persuading Milosevic to turn around the crisis in the
independence-minded province of Serbia, Yugoslavia's dominant
republic.
	   On Thursday, NATO ministers approved a package they hope will
persuade Milosevic to pull back his Serb-led army and police forces
in the province.
	   ``President Milosevic would be rash and foolish if he would
ignore the message coming from NATO,'' said British Defense
Secretary George Robertson. ``The message is clear and unambiguous:
`Belgrade, think again.'''
	   Under the measures, NATO will conduct simulated air attacks in
Albania and Macedonia, probably next week, and study options for
further actions ranging from accelerated planning for military
exercises to direct air strikes inside Yugoslavia and use of ground
troops.
	   This is aimed at persuading Milosevic to do three things:
declare a cease-fire in Kosovo; withdraw his forces and end the
repression of the ethnic Albanians; and open serious negotiations
with the opposition.
	   German Defense Minister Volker Ruehe said: ``We cannot afford
any longer to focus on hollow solutions of rather symbolic
character like border security missions in Albania or Macedonia.''
	   More than 250 people have died in clashes between government
forces and the Kosovo Liberatie movement. Ethnic Albanians comprise
90 percent of the province's population.
</TEXT>
