<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ethiopia-Eritrea, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ethiopians to bury civilians killed in Eritrean bombing
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Leads throughout to UPDATE with two burials, Ethiopia
reporting no clashes on Friday, expulsion and leave orders for
Eritreans. CHANGES byline &QL; 
 &UR; With AP Photos
 &UR; By DIANNA CAHN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ADIGRAT, Ethiopia (AP) _ Townspeople buried two of the victims
of an Eritrean air attack, but the other two were so disfigured in
the bombing that they could not be identified on Friday.
	   Another 30 people were wounded in the bombing, some of them
needing to have limbs amputated.
	   The Eritrean government said in a statement it bombed the
northeastern border town of Adigrat because the Ethiopians had
turned it into ``the main garrison for reinforcing the invading
Ethiopian army and a center for army logistics.''
	   But Ethiopian government spokeswoman Salome Tadesse, speaking in
the capital Addis Ababa, said the attack was ``an act of
desperation'' following ground fighting on two fronts Thursday.
	   Salome said Eritrean forces were ``heavily defeated'' in both
ground clashes, but Eritrea claimed Ethiopian forces were repulsed.
There had been no new clashes as of Friday morning, Salome said.
	   Ethiopian forces wiped out an entire Eritrean division in the
Thursday fighting at Bure, along the eastern border in the region
of the important Eritrean Red Sea port of Assab, Salome said. She
also laimed that two Eritrean tanks and three anti-aircraft guns
were captured in fighting on the norther Badme-Shiraro front.
	   Eritrean helicopters and warplanes dropped at least eight bombs
on Adigrat on Thursday evening. Two of the bombs hit a combined
industrial-residential area in the town of 40,000, setting grain
warehouses on fire.
	   Four people were killed and more than 30 wounded, said Emmanuel
Gesese, a doctor at the local hospital.
	   Adigrat is about 20 kilometers (12 miles) southwest of Zala
Ambessa, the border town captured by Eritrean forces last week.
Eritreans said it was being used to supply the Ethiopian
counter-offensive on Zala Ambessa.
	   Eritreans working in ``strategic and sensitive'' Ethiopian state
enterprises such as telecommunications and power companies have
been ordered to take a one-month leave but could stay in the
country, Salome said Friday.
	   Several Eritrean businessmen who have allegedly raised money fo
the war effort will be expelled soon, she said.
	   Eritrea accuses Ethiopia of provoking the air attack on Adigrat
by bombing the military-civilian airport at the Eritrean capital of
Asmara on June 5 and 6. A week after those attacks, the Eritrean
Foreign Ministry said for the first time that four civilians had
been killed and 26 wounded in those bombings.
	   Journalists at the airport in the immediate aftermath of the
bombings saw only a handful of wounded, and diplomats reported just
one dead. At the nearest hospital, Halibet, six people, including
one civilian, were being treated for their wounds Thursday.
	   Eritrean rebels fought Ethiopia for 30 years to gain
independence. They succeeded in 1993, two years after helping
Ethiopian rebels under Meles Zenawi _ who is now prime minister _
oust a 17-year military dictatorship. Relations betwen the two
countries deteriorated last year after Eritrea introduced its own
currency, and the clashes began May 6.
	   Rwandan Vice President and Defense Minister Paul Kagame, whose
country along with the United States has authored a peace plan,
returned to Addis Ababa on Thursday. There was no indication
whether the presence of Kagame, Rwanda's de facto leader, indicated
an advance in the plan's prospects.
	   Ethiopia has already voiced support for the plan, which calls
for Eritrea to retreat to the positions it held before fighting
broke out. Eritrea has said the plan needs more work, specifically
that details are needed on how the disputed border would be
demarcated.
	   Regional military sources say the plan calls for Rwanda to
supply peacekeepers to enforce demilitarization of the disputed
border regions.
	   (pvs-aa-dc-jh) 	   
</TEXT>
