<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Norway-Airport Strike </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
South Norway's airports shut down by strike
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   OSLO, Norway (AP) _ An air traffic controllers strike shut down
south Norway's airports on Friday, forcing airlines to bus
passengers to Sweden and grounding helicopters needed to bring
crews and equipment to the country's offshore oil platforms.
	   The Academic Union stepped up a two-week strike by ordering
about 235 civil aviation workers to leave their posts in a dispute
over pay. The strike grounded all flights south of the city of
Trondheim, which is about 500 kilometers (300 miles) north of Oslo.
Airports in the sparsely-ppopulated northern part of the country
were operating normally.
	   Airlines and travel agencies rented more than 100 buses to take
international passengers from the country's main airport, Oslo's
Fornebu, on 4 1/2 hour ride to the Landvetter airport in Goteborg,
Sweden.
	   ``We won't have room in the buses for all the passengers, so
we're asking people to consider whether they really must travel,''
Hanne Bugel, of the SAS airline in Oslo, said by telephone. She
said they were mainly trying to transport passengers with
connecting flights to London, Newark, N.J. and Frankfurt, Germany.
	   The Norwegian airline Braathens said about 20,000 people would
be affected this weekend on its flights alone.
	   Anne Marie Storli, spokeswoman for the striking union, said all
regular flights in southern Norway were grounded by the strike, but
medical, military and rescue flights, as well as those bringing
crews home from North Sea oil platforms, would be allowed.
	   Kai Neilsen, of the Norwegian state oil company Statoil, said
there was no immediate impact on the country's roughly three
million barrel per day oil production. He said it was difficult to
predict how long it would take for the strike to disrupt oil flows.
	   ``In general, probably about a week, because we can't get new
crews out there,'' he said by telephone. He said offshore workers
usually put in two-week shifts, but that contracts allow companies
to extend that stay with one additional week.
	   He said technical problems aboard the platforms could also
disrupt production, if companies cannot fly experts out to the
fields.
	   The Academics Union ordered a strike on May 28 after rejecting
pay raises of about six percent offered to its members employed in
the public sector. It has slowly stepped up the strike to its
current level of about 4,000 people.
	   (dm/mk)
</TEXT>
