<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Vatican-Arafat </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pope receives Arafat, supports peace process
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   VATICAN CITY (AP) _ Pope John Paul II met Friday with Yasser
Arafat and assured the Palestinian leader of the Vatican's support
to get the stalled Middle peace process rolling.
	   A Vatican statement following the 13-minute meeting said Arafat
informed the pope of the ``tragic situation in which the
Palestinian people finds itself, while the peace process is
threatened from all sides.''
	   John Paul told Arafat that the ``peace process must continue
with the good will of all sides, respecting commitments made and
international law,'' the Vatican said.
	   John Paul has spoken out often on the need for Israel and the
Palestinians to push ahead with peace. The troubled situation has
apparently held up a papal trip to the Holy Land.
	   ``Certainly I will pray for you and your nation,'' John Paul
assured Arafat during a photo-session after the formal talks in the
pope's private library.
	   It was the sixth meeting of the two men. In the past, Arafat has
invited the pope to Bethlehem in 2000, when the Roman Catholic
Church marks the start of Christianity's third millennium. Israel
has also invited John Paul.
	   While John Paul has often expressed his hope of visiting the
Holy Land, no firm date for a visit has ever been set.
	   Arafat is also scheduled to meet with Italian political leaders.
He will travel Saturday to Florence to receive an award from the
Tuscan region.
	   (vls) 	   
</TEXT>
