r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Taiwan-China-US     06-12 0403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-China-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Taiwan tells Beijing to note U.S. support
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ China should take note of U.S. popular
support for Taiwan if it wants U.S. President Bill Clinton's
upcoming Beijing visit to be a success, government officials said
Friday.
	   ``The American people wish China to give up the threat of force
and start using peace as a frame of reference for discussion of the
issues between the sides,'' said Sheu Ke-sheng, vice chairman of
the cabinet's Mainland Affairs Council.
	   ``China needs to clearly understand U.S. views on Taiwan,'' he
added.
	   Sheu said recent resolutions in the U.S. Congress and remarks by
Clinton highlight the U.S.'s overwhelming determination to see
China and Taiwan resolve their differences peacefully.
	   Respect for those views is crucial to a successful and
constructive summit with Clinton, Sheu said.
	   Sheu was speaking at a weekly news conference.
	   Foreign Ministry spokesman Roy Wu told reporters Taiwanese
officials have publicly appealed to China to resume talks on 114
separate occasions.
	   ``I think this adequately proves our side's desire to resolve
the issues in a peaceful, rational matter,'' Wu said at a weekly
news conference.
	   Clinton begins the first state visit to China by a U.S.
president since Ronald Reagan on June 25. U.S. committments on
Taiwan are expected to be among the issues that China will raise
during talks.
	   Washington cut diplomatic relations with Taiwan in 1979 in order
to recognize China. But the United States retains strong unofficial
ties with Taiwan, and remains its main weapons supplier.
	   Clinton on Thursday said he wished to encourage China and Taiwan
to restart talks broken off by Beijing in 1995. The House of
Representatives on Tuesday passed a non-binding resolution by a
margin of 411 to 0 calling on Clinton to urge China to drop its
threat of force against Taiwan.
	   Though united with the mainland for just four of the last 100
years, Taiwan is still considered by China as a breakaway province
to eventually be reunited with. Beijing broke off negotiations on
investment protection and other issues in anger over Taiwanese
President Lee Teng-hui's June 1995 visit to the United States.
	   China considered Lee's trip the strongest indication yet that he
was seeking formal independence for Taiwan, a contention Taiwan's
Nationalist Party government denies.
</TEXT>
