w2606 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Indonesia 3rdLd-Writethru   06-12 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
East Timorese protesters invade Indonesian Foreign Ministry
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS foreign minister injury count, other details, grafs 5,9 &QL; 
 &UR; With BC-Indonesia-Rebel Chief; BC-Indonesia-East Timor
 &UR; AP Photos Staffing
 &UR; By IRWAN FIRDAUS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Police and troops beat and kicked
protesters when they broke up a rally by about 1,000 East Timorese
at Indonesia's Foreign Ministry on Friday.
	   Security forces moved in after the group staged a five-hour
noisy demonstration, demanding a referendum on independence for the
disputed territory and the release of an imprisoned rebel leader.
	   It was one of the most audacious protests staged by East
Timorese activists in the capital in years, and appears to have
marked the end of a period of tolerance by security forces after
months of protests by a wide range of anti-government groups.
	   Witnesses said several demonstrators were injured when they
refused to leave. Some tried to escape by jumping over a fence. All
were eventually herded onto buses and driven away under police
escort.
	   The Foreign Ministry said two East Timorese women were
hospitalized. A security guard was also treated at a nearby
hospital after being hit by a rock.
	   ``Why do you beat me?'' shouted a woman who was bleeding from
her mouth.
	   ``We are not criminals,'' screamed others.
	   Police confiscated rebel flags and anti-Indonesian banners. They
even made some protesters take off T-shirts printed with
pro-independence slogans.
	   The buses took many of the protesters to spend the night at a
hostel on the city's western outskirts. Officials said they would
be free to leave after that.
	   The protesters arrived at the Foreign Ministry on Friday
morning. Some entered its main building unchallenged and sat in the
lobby.
	   Later their numbers swelled outside. Hundreds waved outlawed
black, gold, red and white rebel flags. The compound gardens were
cluttered with protest banners.
	   Several senior officials met the group. Indonesian Foreign
Minister Ali Alatas was not in the country.
	   ``Referendum yes. Integration no,'' the demonstrators chanted.
	   The demonstration was the latest in a series of rallies and
marches in the capital.
	   Former President Suharto resigned last month after a wave of
protests and riots. Protests have flared again since his successor
B.J. Habibie promised sweeping reforms, but at a moderate pace.
	   Indonesia invaded the former Portuguese colony in 1975 and
annexed it a year later as its 27th province.
	   Since then, separatists have staged a guerrilla war against
Indonesian troops who have been accused of human rights abuses.
	   The spotlight went back on the future of the disputed territory
when Suharto quit. The former autocrat, who ruled Indonesia for 32
years and who ordered the 1975 invasion, had refused to make
concessions toward East Timor despite calls from the international
community.
	   Earlier this week new head of state Habibie said East Timor must
remain an integral part of Indonesia. However, he was willing to
grant special status to the half-island territory in exchange for
peace.
	   Habibie also announced that the government would release a dozen
East Timorese political prisoners. They left a prison in the
troubled territory's capital Dili on Friday.
	   Habibie has said jailed guerrilla commander Xanana Gusmao must
remain behind bars.
	   Separatists regard Gusmao, who is serving a 20-year sentence in
Jakarta's Cipinang Prison, as a freedom fighter. Indonesia has
branded him a violent criminal.
	   ``Our demand is the release of Xanana and a referendum for East
Timor future,'' said Jervasio Sarmento, 22, an East Timorese who
studies at a university on Indonesia's main island of Java.
	   ``No matter if we have to suffer. the important thing is that we
have to determine our own fate.''
	   On Wednesday several thousand East Timorese staged a rally
rejecting Habibie's peace offering and demanded that a referendum
be held on the question of independence.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Indonesia, 3rd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
