<HEADER>
w2609 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Nigeria 2ndLd-Writethru   06-12 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nigeria, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Crippled during Abacha years, Nigerian opposition keeps fighting
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with report of students clashing with police near
Lagos; youths hand out anti-military leaflets. RESTORES previous
material as full writethru. No pickup. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By TIM SULLIVAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ Police in riot gear and soldiers armed
with assault rifles took up positions throughout Lagos on Friday in
anticipation of protests against Nigeria's ruling military junta.
	   About 15 kilometers (about 10 miles) west of the city, a crowd
of students from the Lagos State College of Education clashed
briefly with police after pouring out into the streets and setting
tires on fire, witnesses said.
	   There were no immediate reports of arrests in that protest,
which authorities broke up using tear gas.
	   In Lagos, the normally cluttered congestion of morning traffic
had fallen off to a trickle of vehicles as many people stayed home
to avoid a confrontation with either the authorities or opposition
activists who were planning to march on the city.
	   Their strength ravaged by years of government harassment, their
leaders in prison or exile, Nigeria's opposition movement is
defiantly pressing ahead with plans for the pro-democracy protests
_ the first major test of the new military regime of Gen.
Abdulsalam Abubakar.
	   Early in the morning, about 60 youths marched through one Lagos
neighborhood, handing out pro-democracy leaflets and heading toward
a major bus terminal.
	   Some carried a large banner reading ``The Struggle Continues.
The Military Must Go. Abiola For President.''
	   Friday's protests were organized months ago to mark the
five-year anniversary of the annulment of the country's last
presidential elections on June 12, 1993, and to call for freedom
for Moshood Abiola, the imprisoned billionaire businessmen who is
believed to have won that vote.
	   But the demonstrations have taken on added significance, coming
just a few days after Abubakar was appointed leader of this
oil-rich but poverty-stricken West African country following the
heart attack death Monday of dictator Gen. Sani Abacha.
	   ``Certainly these demonstrations will go on,'' said Gani
Fawehinmi, a Lagos attorney leading calls for Nigerians to take to
the streets.
	   Fawehinmi expects few changes from the new leader. Abubakar has
already infuriated the opposition by offering only a vague pledge
to move forward with Abacha's flawed democratic reform program.
	   ``Abubakar is becoming the reincarnation of Abacha,'' he said.
	   The protest calls continued despite official insistence that any
gathering would be illegal _ and none-too-subtle threats of
violence.
	   ``The police are ready for anything that threatens the peace of
this country'' said Young Arebamen, a Lagos police spokesman. He
called the rallies unlawful and warned opposition leaders to call
them off.
	   Police sealed off some roads leading to the Lagos district of
Yaba, where opposition groups had hoped to converge for a mass
demonstration rally.
	   Clusters of police and army troops loitered along street corners
and a key intersections in the city as they waited to see if the
demonstrations went ahead.
	   The authorities in the past have shown no reluctance to use
heavy force, including tear gas and machine gun fire to quell
protests in Nigeria.
	   What remained to be seen was just how much support the
opposition could rally.
	   Abacha's regime hobbled Nigeria's opposition movement with
brutal efficiency, arresting, imprisoning and torturing many
opposition leaders _ or driving them into exile.
	   These days, many demonstrations only attract a few hundred
protesters and strike calls are often completely ignored.
	   Trying to head off trouble ahead of Friday's rallies, the
government closed a Lagos technical college and a university and
shut down all primary and secondary schools in Lagos and Kwara
states, both important regions to the opposition movement.
 &UR; (tjs/ids/bk)
</TEXT>
