<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Ticket Scams,0245 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Organizers say two soccer federations, branch of
</HEADLINE>
marketing arm involved in ticket fraud &QL; 
 &UR; By LARRY SIDDONS &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Two national soccer federations and a branch of
FIFA's own marketing company are under investigation for ticket
fraud at the World Cup.
	   Michael Zen-Riffinen, the world soccer federation's acting
general secretary, said Friday that investigations were under way
into the improper sale of World Cup tickets by soccer officials in
Cameroon and an unidentified South American country.
	   The president of the Cameroon soccer federation, Vincent Onana,
was detained as he tried to leave his country with the national
team, FIFA said it was told. Onana was said to have been placed
under investigation this week for embezzlement of public funds,
accused of supplying an English agency with 3,000 tickets worth
dlrs 660,000.
	   Zen-Ruffinen refused to give any details of the South American
case, saying that the federation had not yet been formally advised.
	   In addition, Zen-Ruffian said, FIFA was investigating a case in
which a representative of ISL France, a company with a minority
stake from the ISL marketing giant that handles FIFA's sponsors and
TV contracts, ``apparently sold tickets he did not have to
individuals. It's a rather serious issue.''
	   He said several thousand tickets were involved in the ISL case.
</TEXT>
