<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0577 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   A summary of late news from The Associated Press. Some items
have moved on this circuit in expanded form with ``i'' or ``f''
category codes:
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japan announced its first year of negative growth
in two decades Friday, confirming it is in severe recession and
deepening fears its woes will accelerate a regional crisis that has
already taken the roar out of Asia's economic tigers. The Economic
Planning Agency said Japan's gross domestic product for the fiscal
year ended March 1998 shrank by 0.7 percent, the first full year of
economic contraction since 1974. Quarterly figures showed the
economy to be where many economists had already feared: in
full-blown recession. The agency said gross domestic product, the
sum of all goods and services produced in Japan, fell by a
steeper-than-expected 1.3 percent in the January-March quarter.
That follows a drop of 0.4 percent _ revised downward Friday from
an earlier estimate of 0.2 percent _ in the previous quarter.
(Japan-Recession)
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Police and troops beat and kicked
protesters when they broke up a rally by about 1,000 East Timorese
at Indonesia's Foreign Ministry on Friday. Security forces moved in
after the group staged a five-hour noisy demonstration, demanding a
referendum on independence for the disputed territory and the
release of an imprisoned rebel leader. It was one of the most
audacious protests staged by East Timorese activists in the capital
in years, and appears to have marked the end of a period of
tolerance by security forces after months of protests by a wide
range of anti-government groups. (Indonesia)
	   ADIGRAT, Ethiopia (AP) _ Ethiopians prepared Friday to bury four
people killed in an Eritrean bomb attack, while another 30 writhed
in pain from shrapnel wounds at a hospital. The Eritrean government
said in a statement it bombed the northeastern border town of
Adigrat because the Ethiopians had turned it into ``the main
garrison for reinforcing the invading Ethiopian army and a center
for army logistics.'' Ground fighting also flared on two fronts
Thursday, as Rwandan and U.S. officials returned to Ethiopia to
promote a peace plan. (Ethiopia-Eritrea)
	   BOMBAY, India (AP) _ For poor villagers in western India, the
disaster of a cyclone that killed at least 727 people was followed
by desperate shortages that forced them Friday on to mud-choked
roads in search of food and drinking water. The death toll Friday
stood at 706 in the hardest-hit state of Gujarat, as workers
continued to find bodies flung on power cables and trees or buried
in sludge left behind by a tidal wave three days after the cyclone
hit land. The cyclone weakened Wednesday as it moved north, leaving
nine more dead in Rajasthan state and 12 more in neighboring
Pakistan. (India-Cyclone)
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ Nigeria's opposition movement is defiantly
pressing ahead with plans for pro-democracy protests Friday _ the
first major test of the new military regime of Gen. Abdulsalam
Abubakar. Police in riot gear and soldiers armed with assault
rifles took up positions throughout Lagos in anticipation of
protests against the country's ruling military junta. The normal
flood of morning traffic had tapered off to a trickle of vehicles
as many people stayed home to avoid a confrontation with either the
authorities or opposition activists who were planning to march on
the city. (Nigeria) 	   
