<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Pakistan-Nuclear, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0635 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
India, Pakistan to resume talks
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; URGENT &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: ADDS India says Pakistan agrees to resume peace talks &QL; 
 &UR; By HEMA SHUKLA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ India says Pakistan has agreed to resume
peace talks on June 22, an encouraging sign after nuclear tests by
both countries increased tensions in the region, a foreign ministry
statement said.
	   External Affairs spokesman K.C. Singh said Pakistan had
responded in the affirmative to India's proposals for the talks.
	   ``India is committed to fostering a relationship of trust and
friendship with Pakistan based on mutual respect and regard for
each others concerns,'' the statement said.
	   Weeks ago, India announced a moratorium on nuclear tests after
explosions last month that shocked the world. Pakistan also said it
was finished testing nuclear devices after conducting its own
series of tests.
	   The nuclear issue was not on the day's agenda released by the
Foreign Ministry, but the two sides were to discuss their dispute
over the territory of Kashmir and their missile arsenals.
	   Last month's tit-for-tat tests raised concerns the long-standing
tension between predominately Hindu India and officially Muslim
Pakistan could result in nuclear war. The two nations have they
have fought three wars in the last 50 years.
	   Pakistan announced a unilateral moratorium Thursday on nuclear
testing, and offered fresh talks aimed at easing tensions with
India, particularly over the Kashmiri border region they both
claim. Both sides have repeatedly offered talks in recent weeks,
but there is little evidence they are making real progress toward a
meeting.
	   Pakistan, in a foreign ministry statement, suggested a no-test
pact with India as a ``confidence-building'' measure. But
``moratoriums are not bilateral,'' said Singh.
	   Despite the conciliatory statement from his ministry, Pakistani
Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub expressed deep distrust of India in an
interview with The Associated Press. Several rightist members of
India's main governing party, the Hindu nationalist Bharatiya
Janata Party, followed up the nuclear tests with warnings to
Pakistan to back down on Kashmir.
	   ``Where there is such a threats from the Hindu fundamentalists
you can expect a nuclear launch and a nuclear escalation'' of a
conflict between the two countries, Ayub said.
	   Kashmir has been the flash point of two of the three
Indo-Pakistani wars, and clashes between the two nations' armies
still regularly break out in the region. The two countries fought a
third war in 1971 that resulted in what was then East Pakistan
breaking away from Pakistan to become independent Bangladesh.
	   The U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan welcomed Pakistan's
unilateral moratorium, saying he would like to see both Pakistan
and India sign the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty.
	   The Indian and Pakistani tests prompted worldwide condemnation.
The international environmental group Greenpeace staged a protest
Friday at India's most recognizable monument, floating an
Earth-shaped hot air balloon draped with anti-nuclear slogans near
the Taj Mahal.
	   Kashmir was split between India and Pakistan after the Asian
subcontinent gained independence from Britain in 1947.
	   Pakistan is demanding that Kashmiris on both sides of the
disputed border be allowed to vote on whether a united Kashmir
should go to Pakistan or India. India has rejected such a vote,
saying its sovereignty is nonnegotiable.
	   Jammu-Kashmir is India's only Muslim-dominated state. India has
accused Pakistan of arming and training Muslim militants there who
have been waging a bloody secessionist battle since 1989.
	   Islamabad says it gives only moral support to Kashmiri
militants.
</TEXT>
