<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   A summary of financial and business news from The Associated
Press at 1100 GMT. Stories carry ``f'' or ``i'' category codes and
move on this circuit in expanded form:
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Asian stock markets ended the week mixed
Friday, but the key index in Seoul tumbled 8.1 percent _ its
biggest ever one-day fall _ on fears that the falling Japanese yen
could wreck the South Korean economy. The U.S. dollar was trading
at 144.02 yen in late-afternoon trading, up 2.34 yen from late
Thursday in Tokyo and also above its late New York rate of 143.79
yen overnight. Earlier in the day, the dollar was quoted at 144.75,
its highest level against the yen since it reached that same mark
on August 30, 1990. In Seoul, the key Korea Composite Stock Price
Index slumped 26.61 points to 302.09. (Asian Markets)
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Talks between Japan and the United States on
opening Japanese insurance markets to foreign competitors ended
Friday without bridging the differences between the two sides, the
Finance Ministry said. Washington and Tokyo disagree over whether
Japan is living up to commitments to deregulate its life and
non-life insurance sectors under a 1996 pact. Under the deal, the
United States had sought faster deregulation of those sectors, but
to delay liberalization of medical and accident sectors because
foreign companies already have a strong presence there. U.S.
officials question whether Japan has opened the life and non-life
sectors enough. Japan, however, insists that it has. (Japan-US
Insurance Trade)
	   FLINT, Michigan (AP) _ Striking workers who walked out of a
second General Motors Corp. parts plant, threatening to shut down
the automaker's North American production, said they feared losing
their jobs to overseas workers. ``They want to cut our membership
in half over here,'' said Jill Lee, who makes circuit boards at the
Delphi Flint East plant. ``They're taking away our future from our
families.'' The United Auto Workers stepped up its campaign against
the world's largest automaker Thursday night when it struck the
sprawling Delphi Flint East complex, which supplies parts for
nearly every GM vehicle made in the United States, Canada and
Mexico. About 5,800 workers were affected. (US-GM Strike)
	   CHICAGO (AP) _ Corporate America should thoroughly review its
policies on sexual harassment in case of a flood of lawsuits
similar to the one settled by Mitsubishi Motors for a record dlrs
34 million, legal experts say. If approved by a federal judge, the
automaker will pay the money to settle charges that it ignored
widespread sexual harassment of female assembly line workers at its
Normal, Illinois plant. The settlement was announced Thursday by
Mitsubishi and the U.S. Equal Employment Opportunity Commission.
``What this might do is increase the likelihood of multiparty
sexual harassment claims being brought and this settlement being
used as a bargaining tool to bring more companies to the table,''
said Philip M. Berkowitz, a New York City employment law attorney.
(US-Mitsubishi-Harassment)
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ A strike by about 600 Philippine
Airlines pilots entered its second week Friday as government
officials prepared to rule on whether the financially troubled
company can require pilots to retire early. The pilots' union went
on strike last week to protest a new management policy of ordering
pilots to retire who have reached 20 years of service or flown
20,000 hours, regardless of age. The policy puts 225 pilots in
danger of forced retirement, said Capt. Sotico Lloren, president of
the union. PAL, however, said it was not a unilateral management
policy but a provision in a collective bargaining agreement signed
by airline and union officials. (Philippines-Airline Strike) 	   
</TEXT>
