<HEADLINE>
Major powers grapple with nuclear threat, Balkans unrest
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: TOPS with five grafs of Albright urging denial of loans to
India and Pakistan. &QL; 
 &UR; With NATO-Kosovo &QL; 
 &UR; By BARRY SCHWEID &QC; 
 &UR; AP Diplomatic Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on
Friday urged the world's leading industrial nations to deny loans
to India and Pakistan and to refrain from nuclear cooperation with
the two South Asian countries.
	   ``Our meeting sends the message that the world community is
united not just in outrage and dismay but in action,'' Albright
said, referring to nuclear weapons tests conducted last month by
the two countries.
	   By choosing to test, India and Pakistan have diminished their
security and damaged their prestige, Albright said at a meeting
with the foreign ministers of Britain, Germany, Russia, Italy,
Japan, France and Canada.
	   Calling for unity, Albright said relations with India and
Pakistan ``must not drift back into business as usual.'' One way
she proposed was coordinating votes at world financial institutions
to postpone consideration of loans except for those ``that meet
basic human needs.''
	   The South Asian nuclear crisis competed with the ethnic
bloodshed in the Balkans for the attention of the foreign
ministers.
