</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> Sports-Soccer-Ticket Scams, 1st add,0352 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARIS: ISL case.
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   Officials of FIFA and the French World Cup organizing committee
also sought to distance themselves from the growing number of cases
of fans who thought they had purchased tickets only to find
themselves stranded.
	   The officials placed the blame on unscrupulous tour operators,
especially in Japan, who lured fans with glossy ads and knew they
could never deliver the scarce tickets, which are supposed to be
available only through a limited number of licensed channels.
	   ``They found the ideal way of making money, by deceiving
people,'' said Isabelle Delaye, the organizing committee's ticket
chief.
	   Committee managing director Jacques Lambert said operators who
cheated people on tickets and then flew them to France anyway were
``completely lacking in any morals.''
	   He said the organizers would sue anyone found to have sold
tickets illegally, even licensed agents if evidence pointed to
them.
	   Some 12,000 tickets reportedly failed to materialize in Japan,
prompting five Japanese travel agencies to weigh cancelling World
Cup tours.
	   Bruno Travade, a spokesman for the World Cup organizing
committee, said Thursday he could not explain the missing 12,000
Japanese tickets, but that representatives of the only three
licensed ticket agencies for Asia _ JT Travel, Ken R Tours and
Prime Sports International _ picked up their tickets at the
organizers' Paris headquarters between April 27-29.
	   ``We have the receipts, signed by representatives of the tour
operators, that they collected the number and classification of
tickets they had contracted for,'' Travade said.
	   Worldwide, he said, 138,000 tickets had been distributed to 17
licensed agencies. Other brokers who peddled World Cup tickets face
legal action, the spokesman said.
	   Some Japanese fans were already in France, but without tickets
to the matches they'd paid for in their tour packages. Their travel
agencies were said to be scouring the country trying to locate
tickets to the Japanese matches.
</TEXT>
