w2656 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Australia-Queensland-     06-12 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Queensland-Asians </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Queensland's divisive election unites one group: Asians targeted by
</HEADLINE>
Pauline Hanson &QL; 
 &UR; With BC-Australia-Hanson
 &UR; By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NOOSA HEADS, Australia (AP) _ Pauline Hanson's One Nation Party
has driven a wedge into Queensland's politics and divided the
voters, except for one group _ the Asians who say she has made
racism fashionable.
	   ``The One Nation Party created a crisis mentality among the
Asians, a siege mentality,'' political science professor C.L. Chiou
from Queensland University in Brisbane said Friday.
	   ``My Asian friends are very worried,'' said Chiou, a Taiwanese
immigrant who was educated in California but has lived in
Queensland for 27 years.
	   Hanson, an independent member of Parliament, has called for a
freeze on Asian immigration since her landmark maiden speech in
1996, when she warned Australia was in danger of being ``swamped by
Asians.''
	   She describes Asian neighborhoods as ghettos festering with
crime and corruption, home to Asians who do not want to assimilate
into mainstream Australian society.
	   ``I do not want to go places that I don't understand the
language or street signs,'' Hanson recently said on a radio
interview.
	   In her 1996 speech, Hanson also advocated restoration of the
military draft to raise a standing army to protect Australia from
``invasion'' from the north. She did not need to mention that Asia
is to Australia's north _ no one could miss the point.
	   The undercurrent of fear that One Nation has inspired among
Chinese and other Asian Australians is palpable. While all are
apprehensive about Hanson and her backers, most will not be quoted
by name _ they fear having their names published.
	   ``The policies of Pauline Hanson and One Nation are
anti-Asian,'' said Michael Yau, president of the Chinese Forum, an
umbrella group uniting Queensland Chinese organizations.
	   Explaining the reticence of many Asian Australians to speak out,
he said: ``We Chinese suffer quite a lot; our children are abused
on the school yard and on public transport. We worry about their
safety.''
	   At the Chinese Forum offices, he said, ``We actually get a lot
of feedback, they suffer because of Pauline Hanson and One
Nation.''
	   Many Chinese Australians are professionals or run businesses,
and normally they tend to vote conservative.
	   But since the conservative Liberal Party ruling Queensland has
reached a tactical alliance with One Nation, agreeing to throw its
votes to Hanson's party in districts where the Liberals run in
third place, most Chinese have deserted the conservatives this
time, Chiou said.
	   The Chinese Forum has united with Community Voice, various Hong
Kong associations, several Taiwanese organizations and Chinese
fraternal associations, and ``all have come out against the
coalition government and One Nation,'' he said.
	   There are some 40,000 to 50,000 Asian voters in Queensland,
including about 20,000 to 30,000 Chinese and 10,000 to 15,000
Vietnamese, nearly all of whom will vote for the opposition Labor
Party, he said.
	   With the total number of votes cast in Queensland expected to be
900,000 to 1 million votes, the Asian constituency could be
decisive in some key districts, he said.
	   Beyond Saturday's election, Yau said, if One Nation wins even
one or two seats ``it is scary.'' Opinion polls published Friday
suggested One Nation could win up to eight of the 89 seats in the
state Parliament.
	   Their presence would damages tourism and investment in
Queensland, Yau said.
	   ``We don't want to see any other country look at us as a racist
country,'' he said.
</TEXT>
