<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Cocaine </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
South African arrested for cocaine smuggling
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ A South African man arrested at
Bangkok's international airport has been charged with trying to
smuggle cocaine into the country, police said Friday.
	   A man they identified as Mapulei Moriri, 30, was caught Thursday
with 616 grams (21.6 ounces) of cocaine in 46 small packages, said
police, who could not confirm the spelling of his name.
	   Some of the packages were concealed in his luggage and others he
had swallowed and was carrying in his stomach, said the police.
Police said the street value of the drug would be 1.8 million baht
(dlrs 41,860).
	   The suspect had arrived on a flight from Rio de Janeiro, Brazil,
said police, who added that they had been tipped off. They said a
Namibian man named Rafael Mayumbelo, 31, had been arrested at the
airport on May 31 with 670 grams (23.5 ounces) of cocaine and told
them another courier would arrive this week.
	   Police said Moriri told them the drug was destined for dealers
in the Khao Sarn Road area, which is popular among Western
backpackers.
	   The relatively small market in Thailand for cocaine is generally
limited to foreigners and people in the entertainment world.
</TEXT>
