</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Albanian militants kill Serb policemen near Kosovo capital
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; BY ISMET HAJDARI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Ethnic Albanian militants, boldly
stepping up their attacks, killed two Serb policemen just a few
miles from Kosovo's capital and on Friday promised to come out of
their shadowy underground and show they are a mass organization.
	   Serb sources in the province said two policemen where killed and
one was seriously wounded overnight in an ambush by Albanian
separatists. A Serb police patrol was attacked near Obilic, just 7
kilometers (4.3 miles) northwest of the provincial capital
Pristina.
	   Ethnic Albanian sources claimed that one Albanian was wounded in
the same incident.
	   According to other unofficial information available in Pristina,
the separatists were believed to be in full control of a road
stretch near Suva Reka, 40 kilometers (25 miles) southwest of
Pristina. Suva Reka is located on the vital north-south road
leading from Pristina to Prizren on the Albanian border.
	   The Albanian sources also said Serb forces attacked villages
belonging to the Obilic and Vucitrn municipalities late last night
and that residents were forced to flee and spend most of the night
under open skies.
	   No further details about the attack were available.
	   The ethnic Albanian daily Bujku reported Friday five ethnic
Albanians and seven Serbs were killed in clashes Thursday in Suvo
Grlo near Srbica, a village in the Drenica area 30 kilometers (20
miles) northwest of Pristina.
	   Bujku said the fighting was fierce, with villagers determined to
``resist to the end with the help of the KLA.''
	   The reports on fighting and casualties could not be
independently confirmed.
	   On Thursday, NATO ministers approved a package they hope will
persuade Milosevic to pull back his Serb-led army and police forces
in the province.
	   Under the measures, NATO will conduct simulated air attacks in
Albania and Macedonia, probably next week, and study options for
further actions ranging from accelerated planning for military
exercises to direct air strikes inside Yugoslavia and use of ground
troops.
	   More than 250 people have died in clashes between government
forces and the Kosovo Liberation Army, the armed wing of the
Albanian independence movement. Ethnic Albanians comprise 90
percent of the province's population.
	   Meanwhile, ethnic Albanian media in Kosovo carried Friday an
announcement by the Kosovo Liberation Army, demanding funds raised
in Western countries be re-routed for its own use.
	   The KLA statement instructed Kosovo's government-in-exile based
in Bonn, Germany, to transfer the monthly three-per cent tax on
wages it collects from Kosovo Albanians living and working abroad
directly to the KLA.
	   The money should be transferred to a special fund in the West,
titled ``Homeland calls,'' said the statement. The reaction of the
government-in-exile was not immediately known.
	   In the announcement, the KLA also said its ``general staff will
in future contact the public through its spokesman.''
	   It identified the spokesman as Jakup Krasnici, a teacher from
Negrovce, a village in the Drenica region, the ethnic Albanian
daily Koha Ditore reported.
	   Krasnici was named to ``avoid misinterpretations and the
(release of) statements in the name of the KLA by irresponsible
individuals,'' the announcement said.
	   It said the KLA will continue fighting for ``freedom and
unification of all Albanians,'' adding the KLA had become a mass
organization spread over the entire territory of Kosovo.
	   Also Friday, the leading ethnic Albanian political party termed
the situation ``explosive,'' alleging Kosovo resembles a ``huge
death camp in which Albanians are being massacred'' and where Serb
forces are using ``scorched earth'' tactics.
	   Spokesman Dzemail Mustafa blamed the Serbian regime for what he
called ``ethnocide'' _ a term coined to describe the alleged
systematic killing of ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
	   He said that only the presence of NATO troops could prevent an
escalation of violence and the spreading of the conflict in the
Balkan region.
	   (ih/str/kk/rp) 	   
</TEXT>
