<HEADLINE>
Netanyahu meets with opposition leader; talk of unity government
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with ADDS report of CIA chief meeting with Netanyahu
and Arafat, graf 5. ADDS background on national unity government
graf 2 &QL; 
 &UR; By DINA KRAFT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu met with the
leader of the opposition Friday amid reports that a unity
government might be under consideration as a way to overcome
right-wing objections to a West Bank withdrawal.
	   A unity government would join Israel's two major parties, Labor
and Likud, in a ruling coalition, greatly weakening the power of
Netanyahu's staunchly conservative coalition allies.
	   Right-wing members of Netanyahu's governing coalition have
repeatedly threatened to bring down his government if he goes ahead
with a much-delayed Israeli troop withdrawal from the West Bank.
The United States is pushing for a 13 percent pullback from the
territory which Israel seized from Jordan in the 1967 Mideast war.
	   The U.S. plan, which not been officially announced although many
its details have been disclosed, is an attempt by the Americans to
re-start the peace process that broke down 15 months ago.
	   In another U.S. effort to move the process forward, CIA Director
George Tenet met separately this week with Netanyahu and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and reportedly passed messages
about security coordination between the two leaders.
