<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Day Off </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: fans urged to take day off, avoid strike
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Why fight the expected chaos Monday when London's
underground (subway) is on strike?
	   Soccer fans have a better idea: skip work and watch England's
opening World Cup game against Tunisia.
	   ``Let's Have It Off For England,'' the tabloid Sun newspaper
blared Friday in a front-page headline, starting a campaign to make
Monday afteroon an unofficial holiday.
	   In any case, much of the capital is expected to grind to a halt
as employees stop work to watch the game on TV.
	   The 48-hour underground strike _ expected to begin late Sunday _
might be good news for soccer fans, but it's bad news for business
in the capital.
	   The London Chamber of Commerce said the first day of the strike
Monday could cost British business 35 million pounds (dlrs 57
million) in lost revenue and production.
	   And it could get worse if the British teams in the World Cup _
England and Scotland _ play well and the Rail, Maritime and
Transport union call other strikes during the month-long World Cup
in France.
	   ``If the industrial action continues and either of the British
teams progress to the late stages of the World Cup, it could be an
extremely costly summer for business,'' said Simon Sperryn, chief
executive of the London Chamber of Commerce.
	   (scw) 	   
</TEXT>
