<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-Corrupt Mayors </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Number of mayors suspected of corruption grows in Ukraine
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) - The number of city mayors suspected of
corruption and other offenses appears to be growing rapidly in
Ukraine, according to reports published Friday.
	   In the southeastern town of Zaporizhya, Mayor Olexander Holovko
_ deputy president of the Association of Ukrainian Cities _ is
under investigation for allegedly abusing his authority, the
newspaper Kievskiye Vedomosti reported.
	   Holovko allegedly used municipal money to purchase two cars from
his own father-in-law at inflated prices, the paper quoted Leonid
Kyrylash, an aide to the regional prosecutor, as saying.
	   In addition, Holovko is being investigated for allegedly
transferring 100,000 hryvna (dlrs 50,000) in city money to a
company that then used the funds to purchase shares in a defunct
plant owned by the mayor's wife, the newspaper reported.
	   In the major southern town of Kherson, meanwhile, former mayor
Lyudmyla Kobernyk _ who lost her post last year following demands
from the regional prosecutor's office _ was arrested earlier in the
week, Kievskiye Vedomosti said.
	   It said officials from the prosecutor's office decided to put
Kobernyk behind bars since she had refused to cooperate with
investigators in her case.
	   The reports came a day after Ukrainian media reported the
detention of Olexander Bushko, a prominent businessman and the
mayor of the southern town of Tsiurupynsk, who allegedly maintained
links with organized crime and is suspected of assisting a gang
that specialized in car theft.
	   (sms/ji) 	   
