<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Croatia-Schools </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Croatian teachers strike, forcing early end to school year
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ZAGREB, Croatia (AP) _ The Croatian school year ended a week
early as teachers went on strike Friday, determined to force the
government into granting a 12.5 percent wage increase.
	   The move came after months of fruitless negotiations and a
series of warning protests and walkouts aimed at boosting wages and
winning bonuses for preparational school work done during holidays.
	   ``Our demands are unchanged and the government is simply trying
to buy extra time,'' said Vesna Kanizaj, president of the Union of
Teachers.
	   The government apparently hopes that pressure will die down
during the summer holidays. School is set to resume during the
second week of September.
	   But Kanizaj said the protest would last until the government
caves into teachers' demands.
	   In an effort to downplay the strike, Education Minister Bozidar
Pugelnik called the upheaval a ``circus'' and ended the school year
Friday, a week earlier than scheduled.
	   More than 80 percent of teachers in elementary and high schools
nationwide participated in strikes May 20 and June 4 that paralyzed
the education system.
	   ``The time has come to put an end to the unrealistic union
demands,'' Pugelnik told Zagreb's Radio 101.
	   The early end of the school year left thousands of students in a
dilemma over how to improve their final grades in make-up exams
that usually are given during the last week of classes.
	   The government looks likely to hire substitute teachers.
	   Average monthly teacher salaries are equivalent to dlrs 360 _
below the national average of dlrs 400.
	   The government says it has no money for a wage increase, but
teachers' unions insist education deserves more than 8 percent of
the dlrs 6.4 billion state budget.
	   Discontent is swelling in Croatia as ordinary people struggle to
make do with paltry wages and rising costs, while a new elite grows
richer, its wealth widely rumored to be built on political
connections and corruption.
	   (eb/scl)
</TEXT>
