<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Greece-Teachers Protests </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Violent teacher protests lead to renewed clashes
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ Riot police used tear gas to disperse
striking teachers from outside schools around the country on
Friday, leaving at least four people injured from the ensuing
clashes, local media reported.
	   The strikers were protesting new examinations introduced for
qualified teachers who wish to be appointed to state-run schools.
They say their university degrees should be the only qualification
necessary.
	   Under the previous system, teachers had to wait for years before
they received a state job.
	   Three police officers were injured and at least 25 people were
arrested in clashes around the country between police and
protesters, police said.
	   A protester also suffered serious injures when he was hit by a
tear gas canister, local media reported.
	   Candidates hoping to take the exams on the first day Friday
needed police escorts to enter schools where the tests were being
held after angry protesters threatened them with physical violence.
	   Hundreds of candidates were eventually turned back by angry
colleagues, media said, adding that about 40 percent of those who
had applied to take the exams were unable to make it to the
designated schools.
	   Despite the lower turnout, the examinations did take place,
although they began later than originally scheduled.
	   Teachers were on the second day of a 48-hour strike to protest
the new examinations.
	   Hurling petrol bombs and rocks, about 80 youths attempted to
block the entrance to a central Athens school by constructing
barricades with garbage cans and a car.
	   Clashes between police and protesters reportedly occurred in
most major Greek cities, including the port cities of Salonica and
Patras.
	   The protests came one day after 13 people were injured in
similar incidents around the country.
	   (eb) 	   
</TEXT>
