<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-Estonia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Estonian foreign minister visits Ukraine
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo Planned &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) - Estonia's Foreign Minister Toomas Hendrik
Ilves arrived in Ukraine on Friday for two days of talks on
bilateral cooperation and international issues.
	   Ilves was meeting Friday with President Leonid Kuchma, Prime
Minister Valery Pustovoitenko and other officials.
	   According to Ukrainian officials, the sides were to discuss
plans including a summit of Black Sea and Baltic nations scheduled
for 1999.
	   Cooperation between the 11-member Black Sea Economic Council,
which this month formally proclaimed itself a regional economic
organization, and the Baltic Council also was on the agenda.
	   On Saturday, Ilves was due to travel to the southeastern
Ukrainian town of Zaporizhya to take part in the opening of an
Estonian-funded dairy plant, and to meet later in the day with his
Ukrainian counterpart Borys Tarasiuk.
	   Trade turnover between Estonia and Ukraine currently stands at
dlrs 104.4 million a year, and Estonian companies plan to invest
dlrs 300 million in Ukraine, according to the Interfax news agency.
	   Estonia has expressed willingness to take part in completing the
major Yuzhny oil terminal, which Ukraine is building near the Black
Sea port of Odessa, it said.
	   (sms/ji) 	   
</TEXT>
