<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Corruption </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippine president-elect declares ``revolution'' against
</HEADLINE>
corruption &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ In a message on the centennial of the
Philippines' declaration of independence from Spain,
President-elect Joseph Estrada said Friday his administration will
launch a ``revolution'' against corruption in government.
	   Estrada said the fight would be as tough as the revolution waged
by national hero Andres Bonifacio, who established a secret society
called the Katipunan that fought an armed struggle against Spanish
colonialism.
	   ``It shall be a revolution against graft and corruption and
against those criminals who have been trying to lord it over this
country, so this should be the challenge of my government _ to go
after these grafters in government,'' Estrada said.
	   Curbing corruption, which has been estimated to cost the country
about 20 percent of its national budget, was a campaign promise of
Estrada, a former actor who portrayed underdog heroes.
	   Estrada, who is currently vice president, campaigned on an
anti-poverty platform, promising to narrow the gap between the rich
and the poor.
	   Estrada takes office June 30, when President Fidel Ramos steps
down after six years in office.
	   Revolutionary leader Gen. Emilio Aguinaldo proclaimed
independence on June 12, 1898, from 333 years of Spanish
colonialism.
	   However, later the same year the Philippines was colonized by
the United States, which eventually granted it independence in
1946.
</TEXT>
