</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Irian Jaya-Human Rights </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rights Commission to set up office in Irian Jaya
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ The National Commission on Human
Rights will set up an office in Indonesia's easternmost province of
Irian Jaya, a report said Friday.
	   Clementino dos Reis Amaral, a member of the government-installed
body, said such an office was important because the province was
more prone to rights violations than other Indonesian provinces,
the official Antara news agency said.
	   Therefore, Amaral said the commission had decided to speed up
the opening of the office in spite of the prolonged economic crisis
faced by the country.
	   The crisis has hampered the commission from opening offices in
several provinces, including Aceh, Amaral told a meeting with 500
members of a local rights activists Thursday in the province
capital of Jayapura.
	   Amaral and another Commission member, Asmara Nababan, are
probing allegation by Church leaders that at least 11 villagers
were shot dead and some were missing after a 1996 military
operation to free hostages held by separatists in remote Irian
Jaya.
	   Some churches and houses were also burned down in the villages
of Bella, Alama, and Jila, about 3,452 kilometers (2,157 miles)
northeast of Jakarta.
	   The activists have raised questions about political prisoners in
Irian Jaya and urged the Commission to seek their release as soon
as possible.
	   Indonesia's new President B.J. Habibie has released some
political prisoners, especially those convicted of insulting his
predecessor Suharto, who ruled the country with an iron hand for
three decades.
	   So far, the commission has only a provincial office in Dili, the
capital of the troubled East Timor, a former Portuguese colony
annexed by Indonesia in 1976.
	   East Timor and Irian Jaya, on the western part of New Guinea, as
well as Aceh, on the northern tip of Sumatra, are provinces where
separatists groups are fighting for independence states.
</TEXT>
