<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Peacekeeping-Golan Heights </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Japan to extend peacekeeping mission in Golan Heights
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japan will keep its troops for another six months
in the Israeli-occupied Golan Heights as part of its peacekeeping
mission under the U.N. ceasefire between Israel and Syria.
	   The sixth contingent of Japanese peacekeepers, comprising 45
members of the Ground Self-Defense Force, will leave for the Golan
Heights in August, Kyodo News agency reported, quoting unnamed
government officials.
	   The new team will stay there through the end of February after
replacing the current group working at the U.N. Disengagement
Observer Force, Kyodo said.
	   Foreign Ministry officials were not immediately available for
comment.
	   Since February 1996, Japan has taken part in Syria-based UNDOF
mission, rotating the peacekeepers every six months.
	   Japan has also sent members of its Self-Defense Forces to
Cambodia, Mozambique and Zaire under the 1992 law that permitted
Japanese troops to go abroad for the first time since its defeat in
World War II _ but only for peacekeeping missions and never for
combat.
 &UR; (may)
</TEXT>
