w2719 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Israel-Who'sAJew     06-12 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Who's A Jew </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Netanyahu angers U.S. Reform Jews with talk of `fax' conversions
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo &QL; 
 &UR; By VITA BEKKER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu angered a
delegation of American Reform Jews on Friday, rejecting their plea
for equal rights for non-Orthodox Jewish movements and suggesting
they carry out superficial ``fax'' conversions.
	   The delegation of 170 rabbis and other Reform leaders is in
Israel to take part in the country's 50th anniversary celebrations
and to express opposition to a bill that would formally deny
recognition of conversions carried out by the non-Orthodox Reform
and Conservative movements in Israel.
	   Netanyahu is under pressure from religious parties in his
governing coalition to pass the bill.
	   In his meeting with the delegation on Friday, Netanyahu insisted
that he did not consider any Jews ``second-class Jews.''
	   But ``Israel is not America,'' he told the group.
	   Since Israel grants automatic citizenship to all Jews, he said,
accepting any conversions would have dangerous results.
	   ``How do we prevent 4,000 or 4,000 Romanians _ and millions from
other countries _ from declaring themselves Jews?'' he asked.
``Where's the barrier? ... The question we have here is, how do we
prevent fax-conversions?''
	   Rabbi Eric Yoffie, who is leading the delegation, called
Netanyahu's suggestion that the Reform movement gives ``quickie''
conversions ``outrageous.''
	   ``Our conversions are serious and lengthy and intense,'' he told
The Associated Press.
	   The conversion bill, which has already passed its first reading
in the Knesset, Israel's parliament, would institutionalize the
status quo whereby Israel recognizes only conversions carried out
in the country by the Orthodox chief rabbinate, and not those done
by Reform and Conservative rabbis.
	   Although the bill would have no effect on conversions conducted
outside the country, which are recognized in Israel, it has
outraged Jews in the United States and other western countries,
where the Reform and Conservative movements are far larger than in
Israel.
	   The issue has threatened to strain ties between Israel and U.S.
Jewry, which provides significant financial and political support
for the Jewish state.
	   Netanyahu noted that another obstacle to recognizing Reform and
Conservative conversions was the desire of Israel's Orthodox
rabbinical establishment to maintain its monopoly over issues such
as conversions.
	   ``Rabbis like to maintain their power,'' he said.
	   Netanyahu said he would like the Reform and Conservative
movements to drop a lawsuit in Israel's Supreme Court seeking to
win recognition of their conversions. The conversion bill was
introduced in response to that lawsuit.
	   The solution is not through either legislation or litigation,
Netanyahu said, but through ``incremental changes ... ad hoc
understandings that slowly diffuse a problem and allow it to
evolve.''
	   But Yoffie said Reform Jews are impatient after 50 years of
discrimination.
	   ``We are not willing to accept the situation in which our
converts are not recognized,'' Yoffie said. ``We will not stop our
struggle.''
	   Netanyahu scored some points with the delegation by promising to
visit a Reform synagogue in New York, but did not say when.
	   vb-hla
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Israel-Who's A Jew; CT:i; 
