<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-Chernobyl </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Scientist warns of dangers posed by Chernobyl sarcophagus
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) - Echoing warnings from other Ukrainian
officials, a nuclear scientist said Friday that a concrete and
steel sarcophagus covering Chernobyl's ruined reactor No. 4 was
deteriorating and the fuel inside could be edging close to a chain
reaction.
	   ``The general negative trends are growing,'' said Olexander
Kliuchnykov, whose Interdepartmental Scientific-Technical Center is
in charge of research at the sarcophagus.
	   The sarcophagus was hastily built after Chernobyl's reactor No.
4 exploded during a test in April 1986, spewing a radioactive cloud
across Europe in the world's worst nuclear power plant disaster.
	   Ukrainian officials long have warned of the sarcophagus'
deteriorating state and leaky walls. They are particularly
concerned about radioactive fuel and tons of radioactive dust
inside.
	   Estimates of the amount of leftover fuel vary wildly, from a few
tons to a few hundred.
	   Kliuchnykov said water infiltration into the sarcophagus and a
gradual softening of the fuel-containing components were
potentially dangerous, the Interfax news agency reported.
	   ``There is a significant decrease regarding the barriers that
have stood in the way of a self-sustained chain reaction,'' he
said.
	   Kliuchnykov said an explosion could potentially be triggered
inside the sarcophagus, releasing radioactive particles that would
pose a danger for plant workers and those in the 30-kilometer
(19-mile) ``dead zone'' around it.
	   But ``a nuclear explosion is ruled out,'' he said.
	   The main danger, he said, was a possible release of an estimated
34 tons (37.4 short tons) of radioactive dust or the contamination
of groundwater by radioactive particles. So far, the groundwater
has remained safe, the scientist said.
	   Last month, Ukraine secured a dlrs 120 million grant from the
European Bank for Reconstruction and Development for repairing the
sarcophagus. But there was no announcement as to when the funds
would be released.
	   The total cost of the required repairs to the sarcophagus is
estimated at dlrs 750 million. Western nations have contributed
dlrs 387.5 million so far.
	   Ukraine has pledged to shut Chernobyl by 2000, but wants dlrs
1.2 billion first to complete two new nuclear reactors.
	   (sms/ji) 	   
</TEXT>
