<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Holocaust Lawsuit </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former slave laborers from Hungary say they'll sue VW for back pay
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BERLIN (AP) _ Thirty former slave laborers plan to sue
Volkswagen for back wages after failing to reach a settlement with
the automaker, their German representative said Friday.
	   Klaus von Muenchhausen, a Bremen-based lawyer who is involved in
several similar cases, said the plaintiffs against VW were all
Hungarian Jews now in their 70s.
	   They had been sent from Auschwitz as teen-agers to the VW
factory in Wolfsburg to work in armaments production in 1944-45, he
said.
	   Von Muenchhausen said he decided to take VW to court after
receiving a letter from the company saying the firm had no
intention of making individual wage payments to former slave
laborers.
	   He quoted VW spokesman Klaus Kocks as saying on German
television June 4 that it was impossible to determine what a fair
payment would be, and so VW would instead donate money to east
European countries to fight fascism there.
	   A VW spokesman did not immediately return a call seeking
comment.
	   Some big German industrial firms, including Siemens and
Mercedes-Benz, voluntarily paid reparations to former slave
laborers after the war, but those living behind the Iron Curtain
were unable to apply.
	   Most firms have resisted calls to make new payments to eastern
Europeans, claiming that is the federal government's
responsibility.
	   Bonn has paid more than dlrs 58 billion in reparations to Nazi
victims for such things as health damage and interment in camps.
But it refuses to accept individual wage claims by slave workers,
who were technically working for private companies.
	   A German court last year opened a loophole in the reparations
law to allow East Europeans to apply for imprisonment and health
compensation, even though the deadline expired in 1965.
 &UR; (pfg-cb)
</TEXT>
