<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Foreign Ministers, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0798 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Major powers grapple with nuclear threat, Balkans unrest
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with loans to India, Pakistan to be
denied, ADD background, trim &QL; 
 &UR; By BARRY SCHWEID &QC; 
 &UR; AP Diplomatic Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ The world's leading industrial nations, acting on
a U.S. proposal, decided Friday to deny loans to India and Pakistan
in retaliation for their nuclear tests.
	   Loans for humanitarian purposes would be excluded from the
boycott, the foreign ministers meeting to discuss the nuclear
crisis in South Asia decided.
	   U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright urged the other
nations to refrain from nuclear cooperation with India and
Pakistan.
	   ``Our meeting sends the message that the world community is
united not just in outrage and dismay but in action,'' Albright
said, referring to nuclear weapons tests conducted last month by
the two countries.
	   By choosing to test, India and Pakistan have diminished their
security and damaged their prestige, Albright said at a meeting
with the foreign ministers of Britain, Germany, Russia, Italy,
Japan, France and Canada.
	   Calling for unity, Albright said relations with India and
Pakistan ``must not drift back into business as usual.'' One way
she proposed was coordinating votes at world financial institutions
to postpone consideration of loans except for those ``that meet
basic human needs.''
	   Last week, the World Bank postponed two loans worth more than
dlrs 206 million to India, bringing to more than dlrs 1 billion the
amount delayed because of the South Asian nation's recent nuclear
tests.
	   The crisis competed with ethnic bloodshed in the Balkans for the
attention of the foreign ministers.
	   Their immediate goal, in a communique to India and Pakistan, was
a detailed appeal to freeze their nuclear programs and refrain from
deploying nuclear weapons on missiles.
	   By inviting leading countries from all parts of the world, the
United States and its allies were hoping to amplify the appeal and
discourage others from following the lead of India and Pakistan.
	   In the Balkans, Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic is testing
the will of the international community with his suppression of
ethnic Albanians who account for nearly 90 percent of the
population of the Serbian province of Kosovo.
	   Even as the foreign ministers were gathering, Yugoslav troops
appeared to be readying a major offensive in the Malisevo region.
Tony Lloyd, the European Union's envoy to Kosovo, told the Albanian
leadership that the world would not permit a repetition of the
bloody violence in Bosnia.
	   NATO defense ministers agreed Thursday in Brussels on air
exercises over Albania and Macedonia in the next few days to warn
Yugoslavia against further attacks in Kosovo.
	   ``It is not our desire to use force,'' Albright said in
Washington before flying to London. ``Our desire is to solve this
diplomatically.''
	   On the nuclear front, India and Pakistan said after setting off
nuclear devices last month that they had no plans for more tests.
	   But the foreign ministers want the longtime foes to forswear
future tests and refrain from deploying nuclear weapons or testing
missiles that could deliver the weapons to their targets.
	   Albright and the foreign ministers of Britain, France, China and
Russia met in Geneva, Switzerland, last week and appealed for all
those goals. In London, they were being joined by Germany, Japan,
Canada and Italy.
	   To add moral pressure, foreign ministers from Argentina, Brazil,
South Africa and Ukraine, all of whom have given up the nuclear
option, were joining the others at a luncheon discussion intended
to persuade India and Pakistan to heed world opinion.
	   On hand, too, were ambassadors of the Philippines and China, the
Philippines designated to spread the word to the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations.
	   Heading into the sessions, there was disagreement on economic
sanctions, which the Clinton administration imposed under U.S. law
against the two countries, and no inclination to offer any rewards
to India and Pakistan to agree to a freeze.
	   Japanese Foreign Minister Keizo Obuchi was expected to announce
a comprehensive nuclear nonproliferation proposal aimed at
preventing India and Pakistan from further developing their nuclear
arms capability as well as urging the United States and Russia to
speed up their nonproliferation efforts.
	   The allies, too, were divided on Kosovo.
	   Clinton has left open the possibility of military force to end
the violence against ethnic Albanians. Britain and the United
States may ask the U.N. Security Council for authority next week.
</TEXT>
