r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-France-Libya-Trial     06-12 0335
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-Libya-Trial </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Six to stand trial in absentia for UTA DC-10 bombing
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Six Libyans, including a brother-in-law of Col.
Moammar Gadhafi, are to be tried in absentia for the 1989 bombing
of a French passenger plane that left 170 people dead, judicial
sources said Friday.
	   The date of the trial is yet to be set, said the sources,
speaking on condition they not be identified by name.
	   It came as no surprise that the trial of the six suspects would
go ahead in the absence of the six defendants. Libya has long made
clear it would not turn over its citizens for trial.
	   Evidence gathered by anti-terrorism Judge Jean-Louis Bruguiere,
who traveled to Libya during his eight-year investigation, pointed
to a plot involving the six to bring down the UTA DC-10.
	   The aircraft, en route from Brazzaville, Republic of Congo, to
Paris, exploded over the Niger desert Sept. 19, 1989, killing all
aboard.
	   Investigators who reconstructed the aircraft in a hangar at
Paris' Le Bourget airport concluded that a suitcase loaded with
explosives blew up in the baggage compartment.
	   Bruguiere completed his investigation in January and asked that
the six be tried in absentia. That request was confirmed Friday by
the court responsible for sending criminal suspects to trial.
	   Gadhafi's brother-in-law, Abdallah Senoussi, is among the six to
face trial. The others are: Abdessalam Shibani, director of
Senoussi's office; Abdallah Elazragh, a diplomat posted in
Brazzaville and suspected of giving the booby-trapped suitcase to a
passenger; Ibrahim Naeli and Mustapha Arbas, suspected Libyan
secret service agents; Abdessalam Hamoude, alleged to have procured
a detonator for the bomb in Germany.
	   The U.N. Security Council banned flights from Libya in 1992
after Ghadafi's regime refused to hand over the suspects in the UTA
attack and in the Pan Am bombing a year earlier that killed 270
people over Lockerbie, Scotland.
	   (eg-parf)
</TEXT>
