<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Guinea-Bissau,0466 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thousands flee Guinea-Bissau as government, rebels face off
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LISBON, Portugal _ Tens of thousands of people fled the former
Portuguese colony of Guinea-Bissau on Friday as government troops
prepared to face off against renegade soldiers who launched a coup
attempt, according to media reports.
	   As many as 40,000 people in the West African nation were heading
on foot along the road to the northern border with Senegal, a
Portuguese journalist in the area said, citing local reports.
	   Senegal closed the border on Thursday while medical teams were
dispatched to vaccinate the refugees against yellow fever and
meningitis before being allowed into the country, Pedro Rosa Mendes
told Portuguese state radio Antena 1.
	   Government troops, supported by soldiers from Senegal and the
Republic of Guinea, maintained their siege of a military garrison
in the capital Bissau, where an unknown number of rebels have been
holed up since their attempted powergrab on Sunday.
	   The French embassy was hit by a bazooka shell early Friday as
sporadic gunfire broke out after an overnight lull, the Portuguese
news agency, Lusa, reported, citing diplomatic sources in Dakar.
	   Religious and political leaders offered to mediate between the
two sides, Lusa reported.
	   The president of the National Assembly said representatives from
Muslim and Catholic associations had allied with lawmakers to
propose talks, Lusa said.
	   The two sides had ``demonstrated interest'' in holding talks,
Malan Sanha was quoted as saying by Lusa, but he declined to
provide further details.
	   However, an unidentified western diplomat was quoted by Lusa as
saying that President Joao Bernardo Vieira was reluctant to enter
talks and was confident in his ability to defeat the rebels.
	   More than 2,200 people, mostly foreigners, were evacuated from
Bissau on a Portuguese merchant ship Thursday.
	   Vitor Duque, an official of the shipping company that provided
the vessel told, Antena 1 that the passengers, including children
and old people, were packed on the deck. The huge container ship
was designed to hold only 18 people.
	   The ship was due to arrive in Dakar at about 5 p.m. (1700 GMT),
Duque said.
	   Telephone links with Guinea-Bissau were still jammed Friday. The
Portuguese Defense Ministry said satellite links also were not
working.
	   The rebels are led by former armed forces chief Brig. Ansumane
Mane, who was fired in January amid allegations he was involved in
smuggling arms to rebels in Senegal. He has accused Vieira of
corruption and called on him to step down so that early elections
can be held.
	   Vieira himself came to power in a 1980 coup. He was elected in
the country's first democratic elections for president and
parliament four years ago. 	   
</TEXT>
