<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Islam </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Turkish army steps up pressure on Islamic politics
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) _ Turkey's powerful pro-secular army is
preparing to increase its pressure on the government to step up the
fight against Islamic politics, newspapers said Friday.
	   The country's top generals have scheduled an emergency meeting
on Tuesday shortly before they meet with leading government
officials in a National Security Council, the Turkish Daily News
said.
	   The generals will evaluate the government's progress in its
fight against radical Islam, it said.
	   The generals are unhappy because they feel the government is
moving too slowly. A so-called ``fundamentalism'' law, for example,
has been delayed by the failure of cabinet ministers to attend
parliamentary committee hearings.
	   The military-backed bill would tighten control over Islamic
attire and education and provide heavier punishments for civil
servants involved in pro-Islamic activities.
	   Turkey, overwhelmingly Muslim, has had a secular system for the
last 75 years. It was governed by its first Islamic-led government
until June last year, when the military forced it to resign.
	   (ht-cph)
</TEXT>
