<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Vietnam-Cambodia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Vietnam border experts to go to Cambodia for talks
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HANOI, Vietnam (AP) _ Vietnamese officials are to go to Phnom
Penh for talks with their Cambodian counterparts to resolve land
and maritime border problems, a Cambodian diplomat said Friday.
	   Cambodian ambassador to Vietnam Nuon Sareth said at a news
conference that a four-day meeting will start June 17.
	   It comes on the heels of Cambodian First Prime Minister Ung
Huot's recent visit during which he and Vietnamese Prime Minister
Phan Van Khai agreed that their border disputes should be resolved
before 2000.
	   Vietnam and Cambodia held a first round of border talks in May
1996 which covered only the land border problem. The two countries
share more than 1,000 kilometers (600 miles) of border.
	   A second round which was originally scheduled for last year was
canceled because of the coup d'etat in Cambodia last July.
	   The ambassador said Cambodia expressed its dissatisfaction over
the signing of a maritime border delineation agreement last year
between Vietnam and Thailand without Cambodian participation, but
he did not comment whether Cambodia would honor the pact.
	   He said Khai told Ung Huot that the agreement with Thailand did
not relate to overlapping areas with Cambodia and that all three
countries can negotiate over any overlapping areas. Some disputed
areas are believed to contain valuable oil and gas resources.
	   Nuon Sareth said joint development and production sharing of
such resources would be one way to deal with disputed areas.
</TEXT>
