<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bosnia-Airlift </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNHCR and NATO set up Sarajevo-Tirana humanitarian airlift
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By SRECKO LATAL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) _ The leading U.N. aid agency
and NATO are setting up a humanitarian airlift from the Bosnian
capital to Tirana, Albania to assist thousands of ethnic Albanian
refugees from Kosovo, officials said Friday.
	   The first flight of a Norwegian military transport C-130
Hercules airplane is scheduled for Saturday 10:00 a.m. (0800GMT),
said Ariane Quntier, a spokeswoman for the U.N. High Commissioner
for Refugees, or UNHCR, in Sarajevo.
	   The plan thrilled many in Sarajevo. The city itself survived the
1992-95 Bosnian Serb siege thanks to a UNHCR airlift, which was the
longest in history.
	   Quntier said Sarajevo was picked as the regional UNHCR
headquarters with most of the aid on stock that is not needed
locally any more.
	   ``This will in no way affect our operation in
Bosnia-Herzegovina,'' she told The Associated Press.
	   Only one Norwegian NATO plane will be involved in the airlift
initially planed to last four days _ until next Tuesday.
	   The plane was expected to make two runs to Tirana on the first
day, while in the next three days it would be flying up to three
times daily.
	   Each flight will take some 18 tons of non-food items like tents,
blankets and other sheltering material for an estimated 12,000
refugees who fled fighting in Kosovo and are living in ``very bad
conditions'' in northern Albania, Quntier said.
	   Due to the bad roads in Albania, the aid likely will be going to
be transported by several American NATO helicopters from Tirana to
the north of the country, where the refugees are settled.
	   (sl/rp)
</TEXT>
