<SLUG> BC-Nigeria, 3rd Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Crippled during Abacha years, Nigerian opposition keeps fighting
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS with five grafs to UPDATE with soldiers pouring into the
city; troops fire rifles into the air. Pickup 4th graf pvs, `Their
strength ...' &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By TIM SULLIVAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ Nigeria's ruling military put its might on
display Friday, with soldiers pouring into the city and riot police
positioned at key intersections ready to quash any protests by
opposition activists.
	   Troops packed into transport trucks fired their rifles into the
air as their convoy rumbled through one district of town, prompting
residents to scamper to safety.
	   About 15 kilometers (about 10 miles) west of Lagos, a crowd of
students from the Lagos State College of Education clashed briefly
with police after running into the streets and setting tires on
fire, witnesses said.
	   There were no immediate reports of arrests in that protest,
which authorities broke up using tear gas.
	   Lagos Police Commissioner Abubakar Tsav said in a published
statement that protesters ``will be seriously dealt with.''
