r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Palestinian-Jerusalem     06-12 0364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Palestinian-Jerusalem </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chief Muslim cleric: Homes in Jerusalem should not be left empty
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By SAMAR ASSAD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ The chief Muslim cleric in Jerusalem urged
Palestinians on Friday to move into empty homes in the city to
protect them from being taken over by Jews.
	   ``Either you live in them or rent them to institutions that will
protect them from being taken over by extremists,'' Mufti Ikrema
Sabri said in his weekly sermon at Jerusalem's Al Aqsa Mosque.
``Leaving them empty will put them in danger.''
	   On Thursday night, the Palestinian Cabinet issued a statement
urging Palestinian residents of Jerusalem's Old City to take action
against efforts by Jewish settlers to take over buildings there.
	   ``The Palestinians cannot remain inactive in the face of the
activities of the right wing in the Old City,'' the statement said.
	   In recent weeks, Jewish settler groups have accelerated their
campaign to move Jews into Arab neighborhoods of east Jerusalem,
which the Palestinians claim as a future capital.
	   Sabri warned that Palestinians who sell their homes to Jews will
be considered traitors, and urged Muslims to treat them as social
outcasts and ``have no dealings with them.''
	   According to an old religious ruling, Muslims who sell property,
land or homes to non-believers cannot be buried in a Muslim
cemetery, Sabri said.
	   Five Arab apartments in the Arab neighborhood Silwan were taken
over by Jewish settlers this week, and a Jewish seminary won
approval to build 58 housing units on the Mount of Olives, on land
originally set aside for an Arab girls' school.
	   ``Some believe that the battle for Jerusalem has just begun or
will begin this year,'' Sabri said. ``For us it has begun since the
occupation of Jerusalem in 1967.''
	   Israel captured east Jerusalem in the 1967 Mideast War and later
annexed it. The status of the city is supposed to be determined in
negotiations on a final peace settlement, but Israel says it will
never allow the city to be re-divided.
	   Palestinians say that the settlers' activities are pre-empting
the negotiations on the city's future.
 &UR; sa-hla
</TEXT>
