</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: SUBS 7th graf to fix quote to `4,000 to 5,000 Romanians...' &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo
 &UR; By VITA BEKKER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu angered a
delegation of American Reform Jews on Friday, rejecting their plea
for equal rights for non-Orthodox Jewish movements and suggesting
they carry out superficial ``fax'' conversions.
	   The delegation of 170 rabbis and other Reform leaders is in
Israel to take part in the country's 50th anniversary celebrations
and to express opposition to a bill that would formally deny
recognition of conversions carried out by the non-Orthodox Reform
and Conservative movements in Israel.
	   Netanyahu is under pressure from religious parties in his
governing coalition to pass the bill.
	   In his meeting with the delegation on Friday, Netanyahu insisted
that he did not consider any Jews ``second-class Jews.''
	   But ``Israel is not America,'' he told the group.
	   Since Israel grants automatic citizenship to all Jews, he said,
accepting any conversions would have dangerous results.
	   ``How do we prevent 4,000 or 5,000 Romanians _ and millions from
other countries _ from declaring themselves Jews?'' he asked.
``Where's the barrier? ... The question we have here is, how do we
prevent fax-conversions?''
	   Rabbi Eric, 8th grav pvs
