<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Who's A Jew,0335 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Netanyahu angers U.S. Reform Jews with talk of `fax' conversions
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By VITA BEKKER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu angered a
delegation of American Reform Jews on Friday, rejecting their plea
for equal rights for non-Orthodox Jewish movements and suggesting
they carried out superficial conversions.
	   The delegation of 170 rabbis and other Reform leaders is in
Israel to take part in the country's 50th anniversary celebrations
and to express opposition to a bill that would formally deny
recognition of conversions carried out by the non-Orthodox Reform
and Conservative movements in Israel.
	   Netanyahu is under pressure from religious parties in his
governing coalition to pass the bill.
	   In his meeting with the delegation on Friday, Netanyahu insisted
that he did not consider any Jews ``second-class Jews.''
	   But ``Israel is not America,'' he told the group.
	   Since Israel grants automatic citizenship to all Jews, he said,
accepting all conversions would have dangerous results.
	   ``How do we prevent 4,000 or 5,000 Romanians _ and millions from
other countries _ from declaring themselves Jews?'' he asked.
``Where's the barrier?''
	   Rabbi Eric Yoffie, who is leading the delegation, called
Netanyahu's suggestion that the Reform movement gives ``quickie''
conversions ``outrageous.''
	   ``Our conversions are serious and lengthy and intense,'' he told
The Associated Press.
	   The conversion bill, which has already passed its first reading
in the Knesset, Israel's parliament, would institutionalize the
status quo whereby Israel recognizes only conversions carried out
in the country by the Orthodox chief rabbinate.
	   Although the bill would have no effect on conversions conducted
outside the country, which are recognized in Israel, it has
outraged Jews in the United States and other western countries,
where the Reform and Conservative movements are far larger than in
Israel.
</TEXT>
