<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Caucasus, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian soldiers seized, bomb explodes in Muslim cemetery in
</HEADLINE>
Dagestan &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS, UPDATES with Russian soldiers kidnapped, explosion in
Dagestan cemetery, two more villagers abducted in North Ossetia,
protest against kidnappings in Ingushetia. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Ten Russian soldiers were kidnapped and a powerful
time-bomb exploded in a Muslim cemetery in the Caucasus republic of
Dagestan on Friday, wounding one person, Russian news agencies
reported.
	   The soldiers were seized on Thursday night in a suburb of the
Dagestani capital Makhachkala and their bus was taken in the
direction of neighboring Chechnya, the ITAR-Tass news agency said,
citing the local Interior Ministry.
	   No other details of the abduction were available.
	   The bomb Friday was set at the grave of the father of a top
Dagestani official, the Interfax news agency said.
	   Said Amirov, the mayor of Makhachkala, was not at his father's
grave when the explosion occurred _ even though it went off in the
afternoon hours when people often visit their recently deceased
family members' graves. Amirov has been visiting the grave daily
since his father died last week, Interfax said.
	   In other unrest in the Caucasus region on Friday, two villagers
in North Ossetia were kidnapped, Interfax said. Local police said
that the two had been brought across the republic border into
Ingushetia.
	   The two neighboring republics have been battling through a wave
of kidnappings. Earlier this week, North Ossetian villagers
detained five Ingush bus passengers in apparent retaliation for the
kidnapping of seven of their neighbors the day before.
	   In Nazran, the Ingush capital, thousands of residents took part
in a rally demanding the release of the Ingush hostages, ITAR-Tass
said.
	   North Ossetia, which is predominantly Orthodox Christian, and
Muslim Ingushetia fought a short but bloody war in 1992. Hundreds
of people were killed and most ethnic Ingush were expelled from
North Ossetia.
	   Tensions have continued to simmer. A police checkpoint in North
Ossetia was attacked with grenades and gunfire on Thursday night
but no one was hurt, the ITAR-Tass news agency reported.
	   The attack on the mobile police post near the mountain village
of Chmi was the second to target a North Ossetian police station in
two days, ITAR-Tass said. On Wednesday night, automatic rifle-fire
and grenades hit another police post set up near a quarry.
	   Citing local police sources, ITAR-Tass said that ``all traces''
of both attacks led to Ingushetia.
	   (ji) 	   
</TEXT>
