Arson plot in German village shows xenophobia not just on the
</HEADLINE>
fringes
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with trial recessed until Tuesday &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo FRA103-104 of June 11 &QL; 
 &UR; By PAUL GEITNER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   DOLGENBRODT, Germany (AP) _ When a house for refugees in this
lakeside resort burned to the ground the day before 86 Africans
were to move in, authorities quickly caught and convicted a
teen-age neo-Nazi.
	   Then the arsonist started talking, and prosecutors uncovered a
conspiracy involving not only disaffected youths but otherwise
upstanding citizens who wanted to keep the asylum seekers out.
	   The case, combined with recent electoral successes for a
far-right party, raised new questions about the breadth of
anti-foreigner sentiment in Germany, especially in the formerly
closed and communist east.
	   Five men allegedly involved in the plot went on trial Friday in
Brandenburg state court in Frankfurt an der Oder, four charged with
complicity in the Nov. 1, 1992 crime and the fifth with being an
accessory.
	   Shortly after the start, however, it was recessed until Tuesday
on a defense motion.
	   While the five men and two others awaiting trial on perjury
charges are the only ones charged, prosecutor Petra Marx says she
believes most of Dolgenbrodt's 300 residents share the blame.
	   ``They might not have been actively involved,'' she said in an
interview Thursday. ``But the atmosphere in the village was not the
best at that time, everyone admits.
