<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cycling-Politics-Germany </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former world champion cyclist in German elections as former
</HEADLINE>
communist &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LEIPZIG, Germany (AP) _ Two-time world champion cyclist
Gustav-Adolf Schur of former East Germany is running in German
elections this fall for the former communists, the party said
Friday.
	   The 67-year-old Schur, who won the world championship in 1958
and 1959, is running as a candidate in Leipzig's 310th election
district for the Party of Democratic Socialism, the successors to
the East German communists. The seat is currently held by
conservative Christian Democrat Gerhard Schulz.
	   Schur plans to conduct his campaign by riding a red tandem
bicycle through Leipzig with another PDS candidate, Barbara Hoell,
to talk to potential voters. Hoell is seeking re-election in
another Leipzig district where she won a direct mandate in 1994.
	   With the help of the popular Schur, nicknamed ``Tave'' by his
fans, the PDS hopes to get 25 percent of the city's vote, party
chairman Dietmar Pellmann said.
	   Leipzig has 3,100 PDS members, the most of any German city.
	   Federal elections are on Sept. 27.
