<SLUG> BC-Greece-Bank Strike </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Banks strike to support protests against Ionian's sale
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ State bank employees began a nation-wide
24-hour strike Friday to protest the government's plans to
privatize the country's fourth largest bank.
	   But opposition to the controversial sale appears to be petering
out.
	   Several Ionian Bank branches have opened after a month-long
walkout by its employees was ruled illegal three times by Greek
courts.
	   On all three occasions, workers claimed they would not be
violating the court orders by failing to return to work if they
were covered by strikes called by umbrella trade unions.
	   Ionian's management has filed a fourth law suit, asking for a
fresh ban on the strike.
	   Although workers appear to have accepted that the sale will go
through, they are now negotiating the terms of the privatization in
order to maintain their jobs and long-standing social security
benefits.
	   Ionian's sale is critical for the success of the government's
privatization program and its effort to restructure the banking
sector ahead of Greece's targeted participation in the European
economic and monetary union by 2001.
 &UR; dj-eb
