<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Art Auction </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thai auction of art work from failed finance firms begins
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo BK101

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ About 1,000 people showed up Friday to
witness the first day of an auction of more then 400 paintings and
other pieces of art seized from 56 failed Thai finance companies.
	   The items were seized by the Financial Restructuring Authority,
a government agency set up to liquidate the assets of insolvent
firms shut down by the government last year.
	   The closings were required by the International Monetary Fund as
part of its dlrs 17.2 billion bailout program for the troubled Thai
economy. The proceeds from the auction will go to pay the debts of
the failed companies.
	   The seized items, which are being auctioned at Bangkok's Queen
Sirikit National Convention Center, are expected to generate about
30 million baht (dlrs 697,700), according to Amaret Sila-on, the
chairman of the Restructuring Authority.
	   While the auction serves as testimony of how Thailand fell from
grace, others believe the event is a blessing in disguise.
	   ``I think it is great because collectors can buy. Good paintings
sometimes go into a company collection and never get back out
again,'' said Philip Ng, managing director of Christie's Asia
region, the British auction house handling the event.
	   ``A lot of (finance) companies got into trouble for various
reasons. It is sad for that reason but it is not sad if good
pictures come out to be sold through auctions,'' he said.
	   Suthikiat Chirathivat, vice chairman of the Central Group, a
leading Thai hotel and retail group, said he is looking for
bargains to put in his hotels.
	   ``It's part of our expansion,'' said Suthikiat. ``Our hotels
have been doing well as more Thais tourists are travelling
domestically instead of going abroad.''
</TEXT>
