<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo,0459 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Albanian militants kill Serb policemen near Kosovo capital
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; BY ISMET HAJDARI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Ethnic Albanian militants, boldly
stepping up their attacks against Serb authorities, have killed two
Serb police officers just a few miles (kilometers) from Kosovo's
capital.
	   Serb sources in the province said two police officers where
killed and one was seriously wounded late Thursday in an ambush by
Albanian separatists. A Serb police patrol was attacked near
Obilic, just seven kilometers (four miles) northwest of the
provincial capital Pristina.
	   Ethnic Albanian sources claimed that one Albanian was wounded in
the same incident.
	   Ethnic Albanians, who make up 90 percent of Kosovo's population,
are fighting to gain independence from Serbia, one of the two
republics in the Yugoslav federation.
	   According to other unofficial information available in Pristina,
the separatists were believed to be in control of a road near Suva
Reka, 40 kilometers (25 miles) southwest of Pristina. Suva Reka is
located on the vital north-south road leading from Pristina to
Prizren on the Albanian border.
	   The Albanian sources also said Serb forces attacked villages
belonging to the Obilic and Vucitrn municipalities late Thursday
and residents were forced to flee.
	   No further details about the attack were available.
	   The ethnic Albanian daily Bujku reported Friday that five ethnic
Albanians and seven Serbs were killed in clashes Thursday in Suvo
Grlo near Srbica, a village in the Drenica area 30 kilometers (20
miles) northwest of Pristina.
	   Bujku reported that the fighting was fierce.
	   The reports on fighting and casualties could not be
independently confirmed.
	   On Thursday, NATO ministers approved a package they hope will
persuade Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to pull back his
Serb-led army and police forces in the province.
	   Under the measures, NATO will conduct simulated air attacks in
Albania and Macedonia, probably next week, and study options for
further actions ranging from accelerated planning for military
exercises to direct air strikes inside Yugoslavia and use of ground
troops.
	   More than 250 people have died in clashes between government
forces and the Kosovo Liberation Army, the armed wing of the
Albanian independence movement.
	   Meanwhile, ethnic Albanian media in Kosovo carried Friday an
announcement by the KLA, demanding funds raised in Western
countries be re-routed for its own use.
	   The KLA statement instructed Kosovo's government-in-exile based
in Bonn, Germany, to transfer the monthly 3 percent tax on wages it
collects from Kosovo Albanians living and working abroad directly
to the KLA. 	   
</TEXT>
