<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Match Fixing </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Corrpution agency arrest 30 people for fixing soccer matches
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Thirty people, including six Hong Kong soccer
players and a police officer, have been arrested for allegedly
fixing soccer matches, the territory's chief anti-corruption agency
reported Friday.
	   The Independent Commission against Corruption said the arrests
following raids Wednesday on three gambling establishments operated
by a syndicate.
	   A statement said Singapore authorities have also arrested 14
people, including the main operator of an extensive betting ring,
which had links with the Hong Kong sydnicate.
	   It said the Hong Kong suspects were alleged to have accepted
bribes to fix matches in the territory during the 1996-1998 soccer
seasons.
	   A computer used for logging bets was also seized, the statement
said.
	   A number of preliminary qualifying matches played by the Hong
Kong national team for the 1998 World Cup were also suspected to
have been involved in the match fixing scandal, the Commision said.
	   Hong Kong was eliminated in the early stages of the qualifying
round for the World Cup that is currently taking place in Paris.
	   It said the Hong Kong soccer association is providing full
cooperation to the Commission in its investigation.
</TEXT>
