<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Poland-NATO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. defense secretary to visit Poland next week
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen makes
his first trip to Warsaw on Monday to discuss assistance that
America and NATO can offer Poland on its path to integrate with the
military alliance.
	   During a two-day visit, Cohen is to meet with President
Aleksander Kwasniewski, Prime Minister Jerzy Buzek and Defense
Minister Janusz Onyszkiewicz.
	   Following a NATO defense ministers' meeting in Brussels on
Thursday, Cohen said he hopes to discuss ways of assisting Polish
authorities in reforms necessary for the country to meet NATO
standards, including reducing the size of the Polish army.
	   Poland has been invited along with Hungary and the Czech
Republic to join NATO next April, and Cohen said he was satisfied
with the three nations' progress so far.
	   Cohen comes at a time when the president and the Cabinet are
competing for control over the army, after the new constitution
last year abolished the National Defense Committee.
	   The government, responsible for the defense policy, wants to
take over the committee's power to decide the army's shape and on
state defense policy. The president, who is the army's supreme
commander, objects and says it would limit his powers.
	   Onyszkiewicz says the government should decide on the defense
policy since it is in charge of spending public money and is
accountable before the parliament. He agrees the president should
be consulted.
	   A government draft bill should be ready in June.
 &UR; (ms-pfg)
</TEXT>
