<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-Lords-Cameras </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Lords hones in on technology
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Lord's will set a cricket precedent by installing
cameras dedicated to assisting the third umpires make close run-out
decisions, starting with the second Test between England and South
Africa next Thursday.
	   The home of cricket will be the first cricket venue in Britain
to install broadcast quality cameras designed to give the third
umpire an unprecedented view of the crease when calling close
decisions.
	   The cameras will be trialed early next week and are expected to
be ready for the second England-South Africa Test.
	   The third umpire, the off-field adjudicator developed for
limited overs cricket, currently uses television replays to decide
on close run-out decisions.
	   But officials at Lords have decided to reduce the element of
doubt from decisions by instaling the cameras in line with each
crease.
	   The project was funded by the MCC and the English Cricket Board.
It was based on a similar system used at test venues in South
Africa.
	   The cameras will mean third umpires can now be used at Lord's
matches not covered by television networks.
	   (jp/sw)	   
</TEXT>
