<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Vatican-Cuba </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cuban bishops say they expert religious gains to stay
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By FRANCES D'EMILIO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   VATICAN CITY (AP) _ Cuba's bishops said Friday they expected to
hold on to religious freedoms gained thanks to Pope John Paul II's
visit but declined to predict if political opening would follow.
	   The 13 Roman Catholic bishops from the Communist-run island
capped a week of meetings with the pope and other top Vatican
officials to review the consequences of the pontiff's landmark
visit Jan. 21-25.
	   ``It's not our task to make predictions about Cuba's political
future, and it's also difficult for political analysts,'' said
Havana's archbishop, Cardinal Jaime Lucas Ortega told a news
conference.
	   But, the cardinal added, the Catholic church was determined to
``reinforce our role and work for our people.''
	   Much of the church's new gains have come in the field of social
services. For example, on the parish level, the church can now
carry out such services as helping single mothers, alcoholics and
the disabled.
	   In the weeks before the pope came, the government of Fidel
Castro declared Christmas an official holiday for the first time in
nearly three decades.
	   Santiago's archbishop, Pedro Meurice Estiu, chatting with some
reporters after the news conference, said there was no doubt
Christmas 1998 would also be a public holiday.
	   ``Smoking the first cigar makes you dizzy,'' said the
archbishop, meaning there would be no going back on the religious
gains. In April, Easter was ``celebrated not only in the church but
also in the streets.''
	   The church has greater access to the media, the bishops said.
And priests can visit political prisoners once or twice a month if
the inmate requests them.
	   The pope, addressing the bishop's earlier in the week, said he
welcomed the gestures made so far by the government but made clear
the Vatican expected greater progress in opening up society.
	   John Paul has made appeals for church-run schools and greater
access to the media.
	   Castro's government, in response to a papal appeal, did release
several hundred prisoners, including some charged with political
offenses.
	   The pope has also called for the repeal of the 37-year U.S.
embargo on Cuba.
	   Asked if he thought the United States was moving toward lifting
the embargo, Santiago's archbishop told reporters: ``You have to be
patient. Things don't change overnight.''
	   On Thursday, direct humanitarian aid from the United States
resumed for the first time in two years when a plane chartered by
Catholic Relief Services arrived in Havana with medicine and
medical supplies.
	   (fd)
</TEXT>
