<SLUG> BC-Bosnia-Airlift,0205 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNHCR and NATO set up Sarajevo-Tirana humanitarian airlift
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By SRECKO LATAL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) _ The leading U.N. aid agency
and NATO are setting up a humanitarian airlift from the Bosnian
capital to Tirana, Albania to assist thousands of ethnic Albanian
refugees, officials said Friday.
	   The first flight of a Norwegian military transport C-130
Hercules airplane is scheduled for Saturday 10:00 a.m. (0800 GMT),
said Ariane Quntier, a spokeswoman for the U.N. High Commissioner
for Refugees in Sarajevo.
	   The plan thrilled many in Sarajevo. The city itself survived the
1992-95 Bosnian Serb siege thanks to a UNHCR airlift, which was the
longest in history.
	   Serbian authorities are conducting a harsh crackdown on ethnic
Albanians in the separatist province of Kosovo.
	   Only one Norwegian NATO plane will be involved in the airlift
initially planned to last four days _ until next Tuesday.
	   Each flight will take some 18 tons of non-food items like tents,
blankets and other sheltering material for an estimated 12,000
refugees who fled fighting in Kosovo and are living in ``very bad
conditions'' in northern Albania, Quntier said. 	   
</TEXT>
