<BODY>
<SLUG> HERO'S-ONE-WAY-PERMIT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hero's son granted one-way permit, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Hero's son granted one-way permit, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   HERO Lee Ying-kwong's son has been granted a one-way permit in a
surprise mainland move amid wide public sympathy over the family's
plight.
	   The good news came as Lee's body was found yesterday morning in
the harbour, about 200 metres from the Ocean Terminal in Tsim Sha
Tsui _ two days after he disappeared while trying to rescue two
boys who fell into a flooded nullah in Quarry Bay at the height of
Tuesday's record rainstorm.
	   Lee Kwok-hung, 19, will be arriving at noon from Xinhui in time
for the funeral of his 51-year-old father, said Kwok-hung's uncle
He Beihai.
	   The one-way permit was granted yesterday.
	   The youth will pick up his travel document in Jiangmen city in
western Guangdong this morning before proceeding to Hong Kong.
	   His mother Yip Po-heung, 41, had said she hoped Kwok-hung could
come to Hong Kong to help her.
	   Ms Yip, accompanied by Mr Lee's brother Lee Chung-kwong, broke
down in tears after the body was certified to be that of her
husband.
	   ``Why did you do that? Why did you leave us?'' Ms Yip screamed
in grief when she saw her husband's body.
	   She later thanked the public for their support and assistance.
	   Lee Chung-kwong said everyone would do the same as his brother
had but advised children not to play in dangerous locations.
	   The two boys Mr Lee saved were still in Pamela Youde Nethersole
Eastern Hospital.
	   Sze Kin-man, 12, remained in critical condition. His brother
Kin-keung, 9, was in stable condition last night.
	   Meanwhile, the government said it was considering awarding Mr
Lee the Order of the Medal for Bravery, the first person to be so
honoured, in this year's SAR honours.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
