w2847 &Cx1f; wstm-
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Germany-ExportingTrai     06-12 0432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Exporting Trains </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Germany continues train export efforts in wake of high-speed crash
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By IAN MADER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ Despite its reputation for technological
prowess, Germany has had a hard time catching up with French rivals
in marketing high-speed trains abroad.
	   Last week's disastrous crash of an InterCity Express that killed
100 people isn't expected to help.
	   One major potential customer, Taiwan, said this week it will
wait to see the final accident report before signing a dlrs 1.7
billion deal with Siemens to supply fast locomotives for a
330-kilometer (200-mile) connection on the island.
	   Siemens spokesman Ernest Thompson said the contract originally
was to be signed in July.
	   But the investigation into the June 3 crash in northern Germany
is expected to take months.
	   Investigators so far have focused on a possible wheel failure on
one of the ICE's passenger cars.
	   Mike Knutton, editor of International Railways Journal, said
there could be a psychological impact on other potential buyers _
at least initially _ if investigators fault the train design for
the crash.
	   ``It's a small market for high-speed trains, but it's a glamour
market,'' he said. ``The trains that are sold are, of course, very
prestigious for the home country.''
	   The Taiwan deal involves only ICE locomotives, which have
different wheels than on passenger cars. French companies are to
supply the passenger wagons for the Taiwanese project.
	   A spokeswoman for the Taiwan consortium, Corinna Fu, said they
still expect the deal to go forward before year's end.
	   Siemens and partner Adtranz, a Daimler-Benz subsidiary, also are
pressing ahead with their latest generation of ICEs, with a new
wheel system.
	   The third-generation ICEs are the first to be sold abroad.
Holland has agreed to buy four of the trains, which are to cruise
at top speeds of 300 kilometers (185 miles) an hour _ 100 kph (62.5
mph) faster than the train that crashed was going.
	   France, though, already has exported its high-speed trains to
Spain and Korea and is involved in a joint-venture to produce fast
trains for the northeast U.S. corridor.
	   The French success abroad may have more to do with aggressive
marketing and low bids than anything else, Knutton said. Japan has
run high-speed trains since the 1960s with no fatal accidents and
hasn't sold any abroad, he noted.
	   Australia also wants a high-speed link, between Sydney and
Canberra. German companies are also contenders for that deal.
 &UR; (im-cb-pfg)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Germany-Exporting Trains; CT:f; 
