<SLUG> BC-India-Cyclone, 1st Ld-Writethru,0463 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Death toll in cyclone crosses 700, exodus begins from villages
</HEADLINE>
without water, food &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES the death toll to 735, ADDS quotes from a relief
worker in 11th to 14th grafs &QL; 
 &UR; By RAMOLA TALWAR &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BOMBAY, India (AP) _ For poor villagers in western India, the
disaster of a cyclone that killed at least 735 people was followed
by desperate shortages that forced them on to mud-choked roads
Friday in search of food and drinking water.
	   The death toll stood at 714 Friday in the hardest-hit state of
Gujarat, as workers continued to find bodies flung on power cables
and trees or buried in sludge left behind by a tidal wave three
days after the cyclone hit land.
	   The cyclone weakened Wednesday as it moved north, leaving nine
more dead in Rajasthan state and 12 more in neighboring Pakistan.
	   At least eight entire villages and three salt factory worker
camps were wiped out near Kandla port, 530 kilometers (330 miles)
northwest of Bombay.
	   The workers earn their living selling salt left behind after sea
water they collect in pans, or shallow pools, evaporates.
	   Soldiers and government officials distributed food and water,
and helicopters airdropped packages, but supplies weren't coming
quickly enough.
	   ``The poor are leaving what is left of their homes and walking
to the next village in search of something to eat,'' said survivor
Tejabhai Desai by telephone from Madhabar, a village near Kandla.
	   ``All the water around here is salty. People can't even drink
the rain water that has collected,'' Desai said.
	   Prices have skyrocketed due to scarcity _ bottled water went
from 10 rupees to 50 (about 23 U.S. cents to dlrs 1.25) in a
country where many people get by on the equivalent of dlrs 1 a day.
	   Fifteen villages remained inaccessible. The army was assisting
government workers in clearing roads blocked by fallen trees and
debris whipped up by winds of up to 100 kph (65 mph) when the
cyclone first hit land in Gujarat on Tuesday.
	   Aid workers were worried that the exodus would create fresh
problems the government would be unable to handle.
	   ``Hundreds of laborers are on the move in search of work. If
they don't find work and can't pay for their next meal, there will
be trouble,'' said Meher Bhatt, head of the Disaster Mitigation
Institute in Ahmedabad, the capital of Gujarat state.
	   Bhatt said the death toll would likely exceed 1,000 in Gujarat
state, a claim Indian officials disputed.
	   ``Those working along the coast as salt workers or construction
workers were migrant labor and, therefore, local people don't know
how many are missing. There will definitely be more than 1,000
dead,'' Bhatt said.
	    &UR; Mass cremations, 11th graf 	   
</TEXT>
