<HEADLINE>
Dire warnings as yen dives, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Dire warnings as yen dives, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE tumbling yen sent new shockwaves through the world's
financial markets yesterday as fears were expressed of a global
recession and the SAR was urged to brace itself for a devalued
yuan.
	   The yen was hammered again yesterday and broke through 143 to
the US dollar in London last night to trade at 143.54. It had
traded at 141.61 to the greenback in London trading late on
Wednesday and broke through 142 in Asian trading earlier yesterday.
	   The yen, hit by growing signs of recession in Japan, took
another blow last night when US Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin
seemed to rule out international intervention to support it.
	   Mr Rubin said that Washington was ``greatly concerned with the
weakness of the yen'', but that the ``ultimate answer'' to the
currency's weakness lay in Japan.
	   He also said that intervention was ``not a fundamental
solution''.
	   Premier Zhu Rongji had words of comfort for the SAR.
	   He reiterated Beijing's support, saying he was ``confident in
the ability'' of the SAR government to run the economy, according
to television reports.
	   Earlier in Hong Kong, Thai Deputy Prime Minister Supachai
Panitchpakdi warned that Asia could enter a new crisis and lead the
global economy into a ``black hole'' of depression.
	   And the architect of Hong Kong's dollar-peg system, John
Greenwood, speaking at the conference on the region's economic
woes, said that it would be foolish for Hong Kong to count on a
fixed or stable yuan.
	   He urged Hong Kong ``to be ready for changes in China's currency
strategy''. Despite his call for wariness he said he did not expect
the yuan to be devalued.
	   The gloomy forecasts came during another day of losses on the
stock exchange. The Hang Seng index fell 93 points or 1.2 per cent
to close at 7886.07.
	   Compounding yesterday's misery, benchmark three-month interbank
interest rates shot up again to end at 12.09821 per cent, up from
9.57143 per cent.
	   ``The increase in Hibor (Hong Kong Interbank Offered Rates) is
caused by the negative sentiment from people panicking about Japan
and the yen-dollar rate,'' an analyst said.
	   Some analysts viewed the market as over-reacting to the
depreciating yen and talk of a yuan devaluation.
	   ``This is a little misguided,'' said Phillip Chan, research
director at Shenyin Wanguo Securities. ``We don't believe the
renminbi (yuan) will be devalued and there is no reason why it
should,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
