<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ethiopia-Eritrea, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ethiopians to bury civilians killed in Eritrean bombing
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: leads throughout to add quotes, color, details from Zala
Ambessa front, U.S. team arriving in Eritrean capital, CORRECT
Ethiopian spokeswoman's name to Selome sted Salome, CORRECT
Ethiopian claim to wiping out brigade sted division &QL; 
 &UR; With AP Photos
 &UR; By DIANNA CAHN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ADIGRAT, Ethiopia (AP) _ In the safety of pre-dawn quiet,
townspeople buried two of the victims of an Eritrean air attack,
but the other two were so disfigured in the bombing that they could
not be identified on Friday, a local official said.
	   ``Two were buried early because people wanted to get out of
town,'' said local government spokeswoman Netsanet Asfaw. ``The
other two bodies were unrecognizable and have not been claimed.''
	   Another 30 people were wounded in the bombing, some of them
needing to have limbs amputated. Shops were closed to mourn the
dead and dozens fled to outlying villages for fear of additional
bomb raids.
	   The Eritrean government said in a statement it bombed the
northeastern border town of Adigrat because the Ethiopians had
turned it into ``the main garrison for reinforcing the invading
Ethiopian army and a center for army logistics.''
	   But Ethiopian government spokeswoman Selome Tadesse, speaking in
the capital Addis Ababa, said the attack was ``an act of
desperation'' following ground fighting on two fronts Thursday.
	   Selome said Eritrean forces were ``heavily defeated'' in both
ground clashes, but Eritrea claimed Ethiopian forces were repulsed.
There had been no new clashes reported as of Friday afternoon.
	   Also Friday, a U.S. negotiating team arrived in the Eritrean
capital of Asmara and Rwandan vice president Paul Kagame was
expected to follow. The two countries have authored a proposal for
ending the conflict, which began May 6.
	   The U.S. officials declined comment. The plan, which calls for a
pullback of forces to pre-conflict positions, has been received
favorably by Ethiopia but Eritrea says it needs more work,
specifically on how the disputed border would be demarcated.
	   Regional military sources say the plan calls for Rwanda to
supply peacekeepers to enforce demilitarization of the disputed
border regions.
	   On the Badme-Shiraro front, in the Yirga triangle where the
conflict first erupted, Ethiopian forces captured three tanks and
two anti-aircraft guns and destroyed another of each, Selome said.
	   The Ethiopian military said Friday it also wiped out an entire
Eritrean brigade Thursday in fighting at Bure, along the eastern
border in the region of the Eritrean Red Sea port of Assab.
	   ``A whole commando brigade of the Eritrean People's Liberation
Front has been destroyed,'' said Col. Ephrem Bangee, commander of
Ethiopian troops at a third front just south of the border town of
Zala Ambessa captured by Eritrean forces last week.
	   Bangee said his front, about 20 kilometers (12 miles) northeast
of Adigrat, remained quiet after Ethiopian forces beat back
Eritrean troops earlier in the week, but expected further Eritrean
offensives.
	   Soldiers on the rocky slopes of the Zala Ambessa front hung a
bullseye on a rock for target practice and set up
rocket-propelled-grenade launchers in drills they conducted to pass
the time.
	   Eritrean helicopters and warplanes dropped at least eight bombs
on Adigrat on Thursday evening. Two of the bombs hit a combined
industrial-residential area in the town of 40,000, setting grain
warehouses on fire.
	   Tension in the town eased Friday as the day passed without
incident. But residents repeatedly pointed to the sky saying they
were afraid more bombs were going to fall.
	   Bangee said his army would not ``follow the beacon of the
enemy,'' with immediate retaliation.
	   Asfaw, the Adigrat spokeswoman, said some of the hundreds of
civil militiamen who have taken up posts in Adigrat since fighting
began arrested an Eritrean man Friday who was suspected of spying
for the Eritreans. Asfaw said several alleged Eritrean spies have
been arrested in recent weeks and that security forces have found
bombs in peoples homes.
	   No terrorist incidents have been reported, however.
	   Meanwhile, Eritreans working in ``strategic and sensitive''
Ethiopian state enterprises such as telecommunications and power
companies have been ordered to take a one-month leave but could
stay in the country, Selome said Friday.
	   Several Eritrean businessmen who have allegedly raised money fo
the war effort will be expelled soon, she said.
	   Eritrea accuses Ethiopia of provoking the air attack on Adigrat
by bombing the military-civilian airport at the Eritrean capital of
Asmara on June 5 and 6. A week after those attacks, the Eritrean
Foreign Ministry said for the first time that four civilians had
been killed and 26 wounded in those bombings.
	   Journalists at the airport in the immediate aftermath of the
bombings saw only a handful of wounded, and diplomats reported just
one dead.
	   Eritrean rebels fought Ethiopia for 30 years to gain
independence. They succeeded in 1993, two years after helping
Ethiopian rebels under Meles Zenawi _ who is now prime minister _
oust a 17-year military dictatorship. Relations between the two
countries deteriorated last year after Eritrea introduced its own
currency.
	   (pvs-kjd-dc-jh)
</TEXT>
