<SLUG> RETHINK-HOS-WAGE-LIMIT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Critics scorn plan to rethink HOS wage limit, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Critics scorn plan to rethink HOS wage limit, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Susan Lannin and Michael WongASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   HOUSING advocates have slammed suggestions that the income limit
for Home Ownership and Sandwich Class housing schemes be lowered.
	   They say it would force many of the HOS-entitled homebuyers to
look for property on the more expensive private market.
	   Executive Councillor, Leung Chun-ying, yesterday reportedly said
the government needed to lower the maximum income levels on both
schemes as some families could now afford to buy private flats in
the wake of the property slump.
	   The income limits for HOS subsidies is $33,000 per month and
$33,000$60,000 for Sandwich Class Scheme entitlement.
	   Mr Leung, who is Chief Executive Tung Chee-hwa's adviser on
housing, is also a member of the Housing Authority, which manages
the schemes.
	   Housing Authority member and Democratic Party spokesman on
housing Lee Wing-tat said Mr Leung was ``testing the waters'' in an
attempt to benefit property developers by forcing more people to
buy private flats.
	   ``Leung is a very important person. I don't believe it's his
personal opinion . . . there is common thinking between him and Mr
Tung.'' Mr Lee said families earning $33,000 a month would not be
able to save enough money to buy a private flat.
	   Democratic Party vice-chairman, Dr Anthony Cheung Bing-leung,
also a member of the authority, said the party would continue to
push for a higher income limit so more middle-income earners would
have the chance to own homes.
	   A Housing Department spokesman said there had been no official
suggestion to lower the income limits of the schemes.
	   Secretary for Housing Dominic Wong Shing-wah said the government
would be flexible in its demands for private developers to build
35,000 flats a year, in order to meet Mr Tung's target of 85,000
flats annually.
	   Some of the 16,000 HOS flats will go on sale later in the year.
	   Meanwhile, Bank of East Asia chairman David Li yesterday urged
the government to do more to ease the shortage of credit in the
property market in order to alleviate the negative impact of the
economic crisis.
	   Mr Li also urged his fellow bankers not to shut down their
lending programs for the property market.
	   Hong Kong's biggest property developers and banks met to discuss
ways to improve the liquidity in the money markets.
	   The meeting included top officials of Cheung Kong Holdings, Sun
Hung Kai Properties, New World Development Henderson Land
Development, Swire Pacific, Wheelock &AMP; Co, Sino Land, Great Eagle
Holdings and senior executives of HongkongBank, Bank of China,
Standard Chartered Bank and Bank of East Asia.
	   
</TEXT>
