<HEADLINE>
Fewer companies sending their staff for training, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Fewer companies sending their staff for training, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Kang Siew LiASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   NATIONAL Productivity Corp (NPC) is concerned over a drop in the
number of companies sending their staff for training, with demand
for its public training programmes falling by nearly 50 per cent.
	   NPC director-general Ismail Adam said many companies seem to be
placing less emphasis on training of staff due to the economic
slowdown.
	   ``This is the period to send their staff for training because
they can spare the time to complete a full programme and it also
prepares them for the time when the economy recovers,'' he told
reporters in Petaling Jaya yesterday.
	   Ismail likened staff training during these times to the field of
football where ``players have to continue training to keep in shape
during non-playing seasons''.
	   Before the start of the economic problems, NPC was organising an
average of 15 public training programmes a month, which range from
two to five days.
	   ``However, in-house training programmes conducted by NPC for
companies which provide internal training for their staff are not
affected by the economic turmoil,'' Ismail said. NPC still
organises an average of 20 in- house training programmes a month.
	   He said companies which send their staff to participate in NPC's
training programmes can later claim the expenses incurred from the
Human Resources Development Fund (HRDF) Nonetheless, he added,
recognising that some companies are experiencing financial
difficulties due to the economic situtation, NPC is repackaging and
offering discounts on its programmes.
	   Ismail was speaking after International Trade and Industry
Ministry parliamentary secretary Ahmad Kamaruzaman Mohamed Baria
launched the Malaysian Technical Cooperation Programme 1998. The
programme runs from June 1 to July 25.
	   In his speech, Ahmad Kamaruzaman said that as at the end of last
year, 1.7 million employees had been trained under the HRDF scheme
which disbursed some RM500 million to industries for the purpose.
	   ``In Malaysia, small- and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs)
constitute some 84 per cent of total manufacturing establishments.
	   ``However, their contributions to the country's manufacturing
output, value-added and employment are only 12.3 per cent, 17.5 per
cent and 19.1 per cent, respectively,'' he said.
	   Ahmad Kamaruzaman attributed this to the lower level of
technology and innovations due to lack of capital equipment,
inadequate skilled manpower and overdependence on the domestic
market.
	   He said the Malaysian Technical Cooperation Programme 1998 has
been extended to 97 developing countries in the world since it was
introduced 17 years ago.
	   ``This fact alone speaks a great deal about the effectiveness
and relevance of the programme and the courses conducted by NPC,''
he said. NPC is one of the implementing agencies under the
programme.
	   This year, a total of 20 participants representing 14 developing
countries are involved in the programme. The countries are Egypt,
Cambodia, Fiji, Indonesia, the Maldives, Mongolia, Morocco,
Myanmar, Nepal, the Philippines, Sri Lanka, Sudan, Tonga and
Uganda.
	   Allocations for the annual programme have been affected by the
economic turmoil. From a total of RM670,000 a year, it has been
slashed to RM400,000 this year. The programme comprises two
courses: productivity improvement programme and systems development
for SMEs.
	   
</TEXT>
