<SLUG> BC-Hungary-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Party that wavers on economic reform to have 4 ministries
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BUDAPEST, Hungary, (AP) _ A party that questions some of
Hungary's most vaunted economic reforms will have four portfolios
in the new center-right government, it was announced Friday.
	   The key defense portfolio, and the agricultural and
environmental ministries will go to the Independent Smallholders'
Party, and a fourth ministry is subject to negotiation, Janos Ader,
deputy head of the biggest parliamentary party, the Young
Democrats, told the state news agency MTI.
	   His announcement means that five ministries will go to coalition
partners of the Young Democrats, who won 147 seats in the
386-member parliament in general elections last month.
	   The Democratic Forum, which got 18 seats, will head the Justice
Ministry.
	   The populist, right-wing Smallholders' Party won 48 seats and
were the only coalition partners available for the Young Democrats
after they ruled out a ``grand coalition'' with the previously
ruling Socialists, who finished second with 134 seats.
	   Smallholders leader Jozsef Torgyan is regarded as a loose
cannon, and his election promises of cutting taxes and scrapping
the crawling-peg devaluation of the Hungarian currency and fees for
highway use and higher education are seen as fiscally
irresponsible.
	   The new parliament will convene June 18, when President Arpad
Goencz will officially ask Young Democrat leader Viktor Orban to
form a government.
	   (ek/as)
</TEXT>
