<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Romania-Gypsy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Poor diet, lack of education affect Roma children
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) _ Roma children throughout Europe
continue to struggle with a poor diet and lack of education, but
also must battle stereotypes, an activist said Friday.
	   ``Roma are dangerous and teach their children to steal _ these
are the main stereotypes you find in relations between the majority
of the population and Gypsies,'' said Viorica Stefanescu of Save
the Children.
	   The international non-governmental organization, with branches
in 27 countries, organized a two-day conference that began Friday
on Roma children in Europe.
	   Discussions, attended by representatives from 18 countries,
focused on the health, education and identity of Roma children,
also known as Gypsies.
	   Poor diet causes health problems such as malnutrition, anemia,
dystrophy and rickets in Romania, according to a Save the Children
report.
	   A lack of sanitation, identity papers and health records
sometimes make it difficult for doctors to work among the Roma
population.
	   Most of Europe's Roma live in Eastern Europe and the Balkans,
where they enjoyed a measure of enforced equality during more than
four decades of communism.
	   The end of communist rule, accompanied by growing economic
hardships, led to mass poverty, along with increased threats and
violence.
	   There are officially 400,000 Roma in Romania, but the actual
total is thought to exceed 1 million. Many hide their ethnicity
because of discrimination.
	   (ma/scl) 	   
</TEXT>
