	   THESE were some of the claims made by Rajasegaran in a
statement, entitled, ``Anti-Union Actitivies by Certain
Employers'', released at a press conference on June 3 1998.
	   Kian Joo Can Factory: Company refused to recognise the
industrial union but actively sponsored and recognised the in-house
union months before it was registered.
	   U-Hoe Industries Sdn Bhd: Company refused to recognise the
industrial union claiming it recognised an in-house union and also
had concluded a collective agreement. On investigation it was found
that the so called in- house union was in fact a sports club. The
club's chairman was the company's personnel officer.
	   Recognition claim to TH Loy Industries: Since November 14 1994
the company changed its name three times from TH Loy Industries to
Crest Petroleum to Pacific Hall: a new claim had to be submitted
each time it changed its name. The Director-General of Industrial
Relations is unable to carry out a membership certification because
of the company's refusal to cooperate.
	   George Kent (M) Bhd: Terminated a female employee on October 31
1996.
	   The matter was reported to the Industrial Relations Department
and is now pending a decision of the minister. The Human Resources
Minister has not made a decision on the union's request to refer
the dispute to the Industrial Court.
	   
