<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Air Safety,0291 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bureaucratic red tape hamper's air safety, say air traffic
</HEADLINE>
controllers &QL; 
 &UR; By HEMA SHUKLA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ The lives of millions of passengers in
Indian airspace are threatened because safety recommendations are
not implemented, worker morale is low and procedures are sloppy,
industry experts said Friday.
	   Brijesh Shekhar, general secretary of India's Air Traffic
Controller's Guild said at a seminar in the Indian capital that
passenger safety is dependent on coordination between pilots and
controllers. Any break in the link can lead to a disaster like the
1996 midair collision between a Saudi jetliner and a Kazak cargo
plane that killed all 349 people aboard the two planes.
	   A government commission that investigated the crash recommended,
among other things, that standards for controllers be tightened.
None of the recommendations have been implemented, said Shekhar,
who blamed bureaucratic delays.
	   This, coupled with dated equipment, long hours, fatigue and poor
pay has dampened morale, resulting in frequent strikes and work
slowdowns, Shekhar said. Shekhar represents 800 controllers at 120
airports.
	   Other panelists at the seminar organized by private industry
complained that India's airline industry was careless.
	   People have an ``everything goes,'' kind of an attitude, said
Meera Juneja, a regional director of the Dutch airline KLM.
	   Objects could frequently be found lying runways, posing a hazard
for arriving and departing planes, panelists complained.
	   This week, a plane being loaded collapsed on its tail after
cargo slid to the back of the aircraft, damaging it. Freight
experts said standard procedure were not followed.
</TEXT>
