<HEADLINE>
Three universities make `Asia's best', HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Three universities make `Asia's best', HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Ceri WilliamsASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THREE Hong Kong universities have come out high on a list of the
best universities in Asia for 1998, according to a new survey.
	   Researchers ranked the University of Hong Kong fourth out of 65
Asian universities which offer courses from arts and humanities to
business degrees.
	   The Chinese University of Hong Kong was ranked eighth and the
Hong Kong University of Science and Technology twelth.
	   The Hong Kong Polytechnic University was 34th on the list.
	   The University of Tokyo was given first place and the
International Islamic University in Malaysia was placed 65th _ the
bottom of the list _ by the researchers.
	   Cesar Bacani, senior editor at Asiaweek, which conducted the
survey, said the results this year were similar to those last year
when they first launched the survey. ``As a rule the more well-off
the country the higher the universities were rated as they have
more resources.'' The survey classified the universities according
to factors such as their academic reputation, student selectivity
and faculty resources.
	   They were also ranked according to research output, average
annual teaching pay and benefits.
	   Students per teacher and articles in international journals per
teacher were other factors taken into account.
	   Asiaweek reported that some universities did not take part in
the survey _ among them the City University of Hong Kong _ either
because they refused to or did not send in enough information.
	   
</TEXT>
