	   DOMESTIC Trade and Consumer Affairs Minister Datuk Seri Megat
Junid Megat Ayub yesterday chided some wholesalers and retailers
for raising the price of local rice at a much higher price than
necessary.
	   ``They get their rice from the same farmers as Padiberas
Nasional Bhd (Bernas). As they (wholesalers and retailers) bid a
higher price for the rice, the farmers will go to them eventually.
	   ``That is why they (wholesalers and retailers) sell the rice at
a higher price to consumers.
	   ``I can understand if the price of rice sold to consumers is a
slightly higher by RM1 or RM2 for them (wholesalers and retailers)
to make a little profit but if the difference in price is RM7, it
would be impossible for the consumers to accept,'' he told
reporters in Kuala Lumpur yesterday after attending the weekly
Cabinet meeting.
	   Megat Junid, who is scheduled to meet rice wholesalers and
retailers today to discuss the price issue, had met Bernas on
Tuesday. Bernas had explained to the minister the situation in the
rice industry especially issues relating to the price rise.
	   ``I want them (wholesalers and retailers) to explain why the
local rice, which is 80 per cent consumed by the public, is much
higher than what it is supposed to be. There may be some elements
of profiteering,'' he said.
	   Bernas had on Monday dismissed allegations that it is the cause
of the increase in the price of rice in the recent weeks.
	   Its managing director, Mohd Ibrahim Mohd Nor, had said that
Bernas supplies only 18 per cent of the rice in the domestic market
and ``as such, I do not believe we are able to shake the market.''
	   Ibrahim said he believed that rice wholesalers and retailers are
taking advantage of the situation to jack up prices.
	   Meanwhile, Megat Junid said the ministry has identified the
prices of three items - rice, chicken and red chillies - as have
experiencing sudden increases.
	   ``If this continuously happens, it can lead to the increase in
the Consumer Price Index,'' he added.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
