<HEADLINE>
Pope John Paul II to visit 12 Polish cities next year
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ Polish-born Pope John Paul II will make
stops in 12 cities when he visits his homeland next year, a
newspaper said Friday.
	   Gazeta Wyborcza said it learned unofficially that the pope will
stay in Warsaw during his June 5-13, 1999, trip.
	   From there, it said, he will travel to the Baltic port city of
Gdansk, Bydgoszcz, Torun and Elk in northern Poland; Lichen,
Lowicz, Siedlce and Drohiczyn in central and eastern Poland; and to
Sandomierz, Zamosc and Krakow in southern Poland.
	   A spokesman for Poland's bishops, the Rev. Adam Schultz, refused
to confirm the information but said a draft itinerary had been sent
to the Vatican for approval.
	   The trip would be John Paul's eighth to Poland since becoming
pope in 1978. During his stay, he is expected to beatify more than
100 Poles killed during the Nazi occupation.
