<BODY>
<SLUG> 44-NABBED-FOR-ILLEGAL sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
44 nabbed for illegal World Cup betting, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
44 nabbed for illegal World Cup betting, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Valerie Bolcina and Michael WongASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   FORTY-FOUR World Cup fans were arrested in a Wan Chai bar early
yesterday morning after an undercover police operation exposed an
illegal bookmaking ring.
	   The group, which included 36 men and eight women, was released
on bail last night after they were detained after Wednesday's
inaugural tournament match between Scotland and Brazil.
	   Police seized $6,700 betting money in cash and a betting slip
with a face value of $30,000.
	   A 29-year-old man took a bet from a police officer who posed as
a customer at a bar at 491-499 Lockhart Road during a week-long
operation in local pubs.
	   Police made the arrests after the match at about 1.30 am when
the man settled the bet with the officer. Others in the bar were
also taken in for questioning by the Organised Crime and Triad
Bureau.
	   Five of the men, suspected to be bookmakers aged between 25 and
37, were released later on bail ranging from $5,000 to $10,000 in
cash.
	   The others were bailed out at $1,000 in self-recognisance.
	   All of them will report back to police on 25 June.
	   The law permits gambling only at controlled outlets.
	   Even placing a bet with an overseas bookmaker by phone or via
the Internet on unlicensed Hong Kong premises could be illegal.
	   A spokesman for the Home Affairs Bureau said: ``If people place
bets overseas from Hong Kong they will possibly infringe the
Gambling Ordinance.'' The difficulty in proving an offence lies in
the gathering of evidence for such cases.
	   District operation officer Lee Yick-leung said many people did
not realise the seriousness of the offence.
	   ``Many have a misconception that betting on football matches is
not the same as betting on horses.
	   ``We are trying to drive home the message,'' he said.
	   Like betting on horse racing, betting on football was a ``game
of chance'' and was banned under conditions three and seven of the
liquor licence.
	   Leung Wing-ling, owner of Soccer Pub and Karaoke on Morrison
Hill Road, said no gambling was allowed in his premise.
	   ``Customers here are frequent visitors. They know better not to
gamble,'' he said.
	   Although many of his visitors were first-time customers who came
to watch World Cup matches on the 100-inch big-screen television,
Mr Leung said he made sure no one would bet on matches.
	   ``I would kick them out if I see anyone accepting bet on matches
here.'' Mr Lee said anyone found guilty of illegal gambling could
face a maximum fine of $5 million and two years' imprisonment.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
