<BODY>
<SLUG> AXE-COUNCILS-SAY-UNIONS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Axe councils, say unions, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Axe councils, say unions, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   May TamASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   AT LEAST five civil service unions involved in municipal
services want the municipal councils to be dissolved.
	   The unions said the move would not bring about a threat to their
job security.
	   They said this move would help to get rid of ``troubles'' made
by some ``unprofessional'' councillors who ``make decisions based
on their own interests rather than the public interest''.
	   It would also remove the confusion of different policies from
the two councils.
	   The five unions include more than 7,000 civil servants, or about
one-quarter of the 27,000-strong Urban and Regional Services
department.
	   Jim Chang Hok-yan, chairman of the Government Librarian Grade
Staff Association, said his members would enjoy greater job
security if the two councils were dissolved.
	   ``We want to maintain our civil servant status and the benefits
we enjoy now, whatever changes are made to the district
organisations,'' he said.
	   The same line was echoed by Cheng Chiu-kit, chairman of the
Federation of Urban Services Department Trade Unions, which
comprises four unions including hygiene inspection, abattoirs,
cleansing and hawker control.
	   The government is consulting the public on proposals to dissolve
the councils and transfer their work to government departments and
relevant statutory bodies.
	   Other proposals include merging the two councils, merging the
councils with district boards to form several regional bodies and
maintaining the status quo.
	   Michael Suen Ming-yeung, Secretary for Constitutional Affairs,
has said the number of civil servants employed ``would not be
affected'' by any future changes.
	   He said the final decision on the future of district
organisations would be based on ``needs''.
	   Provisional Urban Council member Fred Li Wah-ming of the
Democratic Party, said in response to the criticism that some
councillors are ``unprofessional'', that the head of the civil
service, Lam Woon-kwong had admitted there were staff in the
municipal services who were ``loafing''.
	   He said the unions' response reflected the need for an elected
council to supervise municipal work.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
