<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Uganda-Student-Killings </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Student survivor of rebel killings tells of human ``roasted meat''
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) _ A survivor of a rebel massacre at a
technical institute in western Uganda said Friday his colleagues
were reduced to ``a heap of roasted meat'' in burned dormitory.
	   ``I managed to count the bodies of our burned colleagues,''
Milton Aguzu said in a speech at a demonstration against the
attackin which 80 people were killed. ``I used to eat meat, but I
no longer can because of what I saw.''
	   Aguzu said he survived last Monday's massacre at the Kichwamba
Technical Institute near Kabarole, 316 kilometers (195 miles) miles
west of Kampala by hiding in the bushes.
	   The government said the attack was carried out by the Allied
Democratic Forces group, whose goal is to oust President Yoweri
Museveni.
	   Initial reports said the insurgents planned to abduct the
students, but when the students barricaded themselves inside one of
the college buildings, the rebels set fire to it.
	   About 40 government soldiers camped near the institute were
outnumbered four to one by the insurgents, the government said.
	   Students from Makerere University and technical institutes in
Kampala demonstrated Friday against the attack, singing traditional
funeral songs and waving placards saying, ``Why kill innocent
students?'' and ``Fight soldiers not students.''
	   The insurgents have bases in the foothills of the Rwanzori
Mountains that form the border between Uganda and the Democratic
Republic of the Congo. They stage frequent attacks on Uganda's
western districts along the border. Some of the rebels are members
of former armies or groups defeated by Museveni's National
Resistance Movement in 1986.
	   The government is also fighting rebels from the West Nile Bank
Front in the northwest and from the Lord's Resistance Army in the
north.
	   (HW-cm-jh) 	   
</TEXT>
