	   SINGAPORE'S benchmark stock index closed 4.5 per cent lower
yesterday amid fresh currency weakness in the region and
increasingly gloomy corporate prospects.
	   ``Most stocks have fallen to attractive levels but there is not
much interest given the present economic situation and currency
concerns,'' a dealer with a European brokerage said.
	   The Straits Times Industrials index ended 49.40 points down at
1,067.81.
	   The broader All-Singapore index fell 6.78 points to 307.55.
	   Turnover rose to 117.88 million shares valued at S$210.44
million, from 113.58 million shares worth S$253.48 million on
Tuesday.
	   Falling stock led those rising 290 to 44 with 256 others
unchanged.
	   DBS Land Ltd was among the most heavily traded stocks, with 7.7
million shares changing hands before closing six cents down at
US$1.48.
	   Top gainer was the foreign tranche of United Overseas Bank Ltd
which rose 25 cents to US$6.10.
	   
