<SLUG> SHARES-CLOSE-BROADLY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Shares close broadly lower, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Shares close broadly lower, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SHARES on the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE) closed broadly
lower yesterday as the regional currencies woes took centre stage,
dragging the key KL Composite Index (KLCI) to close 15.78 points
lower or 3.12 per cent down to 489.86.
	   Selling activities were rampant across the board yesterday due
to the declining ringgit against the US dollar, said analysts.
	   ``It was like a selling spree because of nervousness ...,'' said
one.
	   Continued selling on heavyweight stocks such as Maybank, Tenaga,
Telekom, Genting and Sime Darby weighed local sentiment.
	   One analyst said, ``Everywhere we turn now, we see problems and
uncertainties. It is difficult for the stock market.''
	   The declining yen, he said is expected to continue to be the
main factor that contributes to the bearish sentiment.
	   At the close, the broader Emas Index lost 3.26 points to 126.27
while the Second Board Index was down by 1.30 points to 107.57.
	   The scoreboard showed 455 losers, with 114 gainers and 152
counters remaining unchanged.
	   The broad-based BT Ordinaries eased 3.35 points to 119.25 while
the 30- share New Straits Industrial Index slipped 45.37 points to
end at 2,929.25.
	   On the KLSE, total turnover was higher with 111.432 million
shares valued at RM281.706 million compared with 84.244 million
shares worth RM179.801 million on Tuesday.
	   Turnover on the main board totalled 96.650 million shares valued
at RM269.347 million while trade on the Second Board was 7.206
million shares worth RM10.023 million.
	   Maybank was the most avtive counter yesterday with 7.529 million
shares traded followed by Tenaga with 6.953 million shares. Telekom
was the third active with 6.360 million shares changing hands.
	   
</TEXT>
