<SLUG> MID-LEVELS-LANDSLIP sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Evacuation after Mid-Levels landslip, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Evacuation after Mid-Levels landslip, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THIRTEEN people were evacuated from a luxury Mid-Levels
apartment building after a landslip scarred an unregistered slope.
	   Emergency repair work was being hurriedly carried out on the
hill, which separates Bowen Road and Magazine Gap Road.
	   The 50-metre landslip damaged Bowen Mansion at the foot of the
hill.
	   Five flats facing the scarred slope were evacuated by police as
the Highways Department worked to clear the debris.
	   Falling rocks and soil damaged air-conditioning units and
windows up to the third floor of the building.
	   ``The rocks and soil gained a lot of momentum from falling so
high, so they caused quite some damage,'' said Senior Geotechnical
Engineer Jerry Ho Leung-ping.
	   He said the landslip created a pile of debris measuring five by
six cubic metres near Bowen Mansion.
	   ``The Highways Department workers are spraying the erosion scar
with concrete and removing the debris from the building.'' Mr Ho
anticipated the possible use of soil nails and installation of
horizontal drains to make the slope stable.
	   Experts from the Landslip Investigation Division (LID) were
trying to determine whether the recent heavy downpour caused the
erosion of the slope.
	   The landslip was reported around 10 am by a woman who was
awakened by rocks smashing into her window.
	   Residents of the five flats will not be permitted to return
until the LID has determined if the slope is stable.
	   The Geotechnical Engineering Office does not maintain natural
hills because they will have to remove grass and trees in the
process.
	   ``These natural hills have been around for thousands of years,
so we don't want to disturb them unless there are signs of risk,''
Mr Ho said.
	   He said the best preventive measure was to avoid erecting
buildings near risky slopes.
	   ``Builders need to make sure that they have a good buffer zone
if they build near a risky hill.''
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
