<SLUG> EX-BANKER-WINS-COSTS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ex-banker wins costs in laundering case, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Ex-banker wins costs in laundering case, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Julie ChuASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A FORMER top banker once charged with laundering $7.08 million
was yesterday awarded a ``substantial'' amount of costs against the
government.
	   Kevin Wallace, an ex-private banker of Merrill Lynch, did not
appear in Eastern Magistracy for the award.
	   His lawyer, Alexander King, refused to disclose the whereabouts
of Mr Wallace, 46, who was once stranded in Hong Kong.
	   ``Mr Wallace was forced to stay in Hong Kong for nine months,
unable to work and meet his family,'' Mr King said outside court.
	   The American was originally charged with dealing with $7.08
million known or believed to represent proceeds of an indictable
offence.
	   He appeared in court for the first time last July but the case
was adjourned three times pending inquiries.
	   Prosecutors decided to drop the case in March as they could not
secure overseas witnesses to attend.
	   Magistrate Garry Tallentine granted the costs to Mr Wallace.
	   Mr Wallace worked for Merrill Lynch International Bank in
Singapore from April 1990 to April 1997.
	   
</TEXT>
