<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-2-Pound Coin </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Britons getting new 2-pound coins in their change
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Britons can fill their pockets with a little more
spending power next week as a new 2-pound coin goes into
circulation.
	   The 2-pound piece, worth about U.S. dlrs 3.25 at current
exchange rates, is the nation's first multicolored coin. With a
white center and yellow ring around the outside, it resembles some
of the change circulating in continental Europe, such as France's
10-franc piece.
	   The launch of the new coins has vending machine operators, the
telephone company and parking meter suppliers scurrying to make
sure customers can use them.
	   Many prepared for the change last year, when Britain introduced
a slightly smaller version of its 50-pence coin, worth about 82
U.S. cents.
	   Like all British money and postage stamps, the coins bear a
likeness of Queen Elizabeth II.
	   Roger Holmes, the deputy master of the Royal Mint, called the
coin ``a new and worthy addition to Britain's coins.''
	   The coin also demonstrates ``how the coinage can be updated to
meet changing needs and demands,'' he said, politely declining to
point out that means higher prices.
	   (db-kg)
</TEXT>
