<BODY>
<SLUG> MUHAMMED-PLEADS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Muhammad pleads not guilty to failing to declare all assets, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Muhammad pleads not guilty to failing to declare all assets, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Kamarul YunusASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   FORMER Selangor Menteri Besar Tan Sri Muhammad Muhammad Taib
pleaded not guilty at the Sessions Court in Kuala Lumpur yesterday
to a charge of failing to declare all his and his family's assets
last year.
	   His case was then transferred to the High Court in Kuala Lumpur
after the Sessions Court allowed the prosecution's request. The
High Court fixed trial for December 7 to 18 this year.
	   Earlier, Sessions Court Judge Mohamad K. Abdul Rahman allowed
Muhammad a bond of RM10,000 without surety to ensure the former
Menteri Besar's presence at the High Court.
	   Muhammad, 53, is charged with committing the offence under the
Prevention of Corruption Act or Akta Pencegah Rasuah (APR) 1961 on
May 26 last year.
	   He is charged with knowingly ignoring conditions in a statutory
declaration dated May 23 1997 by declaring assets worth, at the
time of acquisition, only RM10.82 million and A$3.46 million (A$1  &QC; 
RM2.41 at current exchange rates).
	   The Public Prosecutor had required Muhammad to declare, under
Section 25 (1)(a) APR 1961 (Act 57) in a notice dated April 10
1997, all movable and immovable assets belonging to him or owned by
his agents or trustees, wife and children.
	   He is alleged to have committed the offence at the office of the
Deputy Public Prosecutor in the Anti-Corruption Agency's
headquarters in Pesiaran Duta, Kuala Lumpur, on May 26 last year.
	   Under Section 25(2) of the Act, Muhammad faces a maximum
sentence of one year's imprisonment or a fine of RM2,000, or both,
upon conviction.
	   Senior Deputy Public Prosecutors Datuk Abdul Gani Patail and
Azahar Mohamed prosecuted, while Muhammad was represented by
counsel Muhammad Shafee Abdullah and Burhanudeen Abdul Wahid.
	   On May 29 this year, Muhammad was acquitted by the Brisbane
District Court of two charges of making a false declaration
pertaining to the amount of money he was bringing into Australia on
December 16 1996, and failure to declare an equivalent of A$1.26
million when he was leaving for New Zealand six days later.
	   During the trial, Muhammad said he had purchased properties
valued at more than RM10.4 million in Australia and New Zealand
under the name of his wife, Puan Sri Asbi Rohani Asnan.
	   The properties are a piece of land valued at A$460,000 and a
bungalow valued at A$460,000 in Sovereign Islands, Gold Coast, a
farm in Currajong, also in Australia, valued at A$3.7 million, and
two pieces of land and a house in New Zealand valued at NZ$4
million (NZ$1  &QC;  RM2.05).
	   Muhammad resigned as Selangor Menteri Besar on April 14 1997,
following the Australian court case, and last Monday the Umno
Supreme Council extended his leave as party vice-president until
the court has made a decision on his case.
	   
</TEXT>
