<HEADLINE>
Investors agree to smaller refunds, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Investors agree to smaller refunds, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Martin WongASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   INVESTORS in failed brokerage CA Pacific are willing to accept
smaller refunds so that all can benefit from the $325 million
compensation package announced on Wednesday.
	   Some 20 representatives of the investors put forward the
counter-proposal in a meeting with Stock Exchange officials
yesterday. They also urged the government to inject money into the
collapsed company instead of giving them cash in advance.
	   The stock exchange had announced a scheme in which the
government would pay $325 million in advance to enable 70 to 80 per
cent of the investors to claim up to $150,000 from the compensation
fund.
	   But investors said instead of making some of them receive
nothing under the package, they would each prefer to get less.
Democrat Dr John Tse Wing-ling accused the government of not doing
enough. ``The money ($325 million) that the government is giving
out is only cash in advance. They will take the money back later.''
	   
</TEXT>
