<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thai shares and currency continue fall
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Thailand's benchmark stock index fell
for a sixth consecutive day Friday, deepening worries among
investors that the country's economic crisis is worsening.
	   The Stock Exchange of Thailand index closed at 279.37 points,
4.55 points, or 1.6 percent off Thursday's close.
	   At Friday's closing level, the SET index was down 25 percent
from its closing level on the last trading day of 1997, and at its
lowest point since Dec. 16, 1987.
	   Dealers attributed the slump to gloom among investors about
medium-term prospects for Thailand's financial markets.
	   Moody's Investors Service predicted Thursday that Thai banks may
not be able to recover up to dlrs 30 billion in bad loans, a figure
equal to a quarter of the country's gross domestic product.
	   At the same time, some major Thai companies have started to
suspend repayments of foreign debt, citing an inability to pay.
	   ``The reason the market is going down is more of the same:
people have fears about the Thai economy,'' said Stuart Matthews,
head of research at Deutsche Morgan Grenfell Securities.
	   He said investors are dumping stocks because they see little
value in them given the amount of capital Thai companies will have
to raise in the next few years.
	   The Thai baht, meanwhile, ended lower in Asian spot trading
Friday, amid a regional currency sell-off sparked by the fall of
the yen to an eight-year low against the U.S. dollar.
	   Dealers said profit-taking on dollars managed to pull the baht
up from the day's low by the close of trade.
	   At Friday's close, the baht has dropped 40.4 percent since the
Thai government abandoned its fixed foreign exchange system last
July 2.
	   Dealers attributed the baht's decline to worries that the yen's
slump was putting increasing pressure on China to devalue its own
currency to keep its exports competitive. A devaluation by China,
analysts said, would hurt most other Asian currencies.
	   The yen fell Friday to an eight-year low of around Y144 to the
dollar.
	   Thai central bank governor Chatu Mongol Sonakul said Friday
speculators on the Thai currency had ``lost in the millions'' of
dollars after the Bank of Thailand intervened to stop their
activities.
	   ``They know we are serious. They know we have the power. And
they had lost in the millions,'' he told reporters.
	   Chatu Mongol had said last week that the central bank had
intervened in the trade of Thai baht, but he didn't specify when
the intervention took place.
	   He said the intervention had warded off speculation and helped
stabilize the baht.
</TEXT>
