<SLUG> SKILLS-SCHOOL-OPENS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Skills opportunity school opens in September, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Skills opportunity school opens in September, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE fifth skills opportunity school will be opened in September
to aid the growing number of students who have trouble adapting to
normal class studies.
	   The Chi Lin Nunnery, which has been devoted to community
services, built the Buddhist Secondary School with the help of
private donors.
	   The already-opened skills opportunity schools cater for
Secondary 1 and Secondary 3 students aged between 12 and 14 who
need intensive remedial support.
	   Principal of the Chi Lin Buddhist Secondary School K L Chansaid:
``Chi Lin Nunnery in providing educational services has a primary
school and is now also running a kindergarten. They are well
received by pupils and parents alike and also well supported by the
community.'' Mr Chan said the skills opportunity school is a new
concept that is being quickly developed.
	   ``Despite our lack of experience, we will do our best.
	   ``We will act with love, patience and innovation.'' The
curriculum will emphasise the diverse needs of the pupils and
courses will be tailor-made to their aptitude.
	   Flexible and interest-oriented teaching methods will be used to
help pupils establish confidence and independence and to help
develop their potential.
	   
</TEXT>
