<BODY>
<SLUG> AMBITIONS-KRU-AIMS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ambitious KRU aims to soar higher, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Ambitious KRU aims to soar higher, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Fauziah IsmailASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ENCIK Norman Abdul Halim is ambitious. The managing director of
KRU Bhd wants to turn his company into a giant media and
entertainment group like Disney or Warner.
	   In the short span of seven years since the rap group KRU burst
into the Malaysian entertainment scene, Norman and his two brothers
- Yusry and Edry - have succeeded in turning KRU Bhd into one of
Malaysia's top corporate players in the entertainment world.
	   They have successfully amassed RM10 million in assets for the
company and are handling businesses worth much more.
	   The economic slowdown has not dampened their spirits to achieve
much more for the company. Instead, it has spurred them to work
harder to consolidate the company's position.
	   While Norman is in the forefront of KRU Bhd, his brothers are
more inclined towards the production and technical aspects of the
music business.
	   Under the KRU Bhd flagship is KRU Productions (music and artiste
management), KRU Publishing (music copyright protection), KRU
Records (artiste and repertoire), DB Lumens (sound and lighting
company), Bizzare Events (event management) and the newly-created
KRU Motion Pictures (telemovies and production of music and
corporate videos).
	   There is also a joint-venture company called KRU Beverages,
which manufactures and distributes Kruze Cola.
	   This and more from a company which started with a RM2,000
advance from EMI to buy a keyboard.
	   ``Music is a hobby, doing business is my interest,'' Norman told
Business Times when asked why he decided to venture into business
instead of concentrating on being the a ``pop icon''.
	   ``KRU Bhd is a blend of the two ... it is doing business, which
is very much linked to the music world.''
	   But Norman wants to diversify the company's business into
something he described as more ``corporate.''
	   ``We have been doing music videos but we can also do corporate
videos ...
	   which not many people know about. We are convinced enough that
we are able to do it and offer them high quality product at a
competitive price.
	   ``We are doing a corporate video of our own company now so that
we will be able to show other companies what we can offer,'' he
added.
	   Not many know that KRU Bhd's subsidiaries are already doing jobs
for the Malaysian Industry-Government Group for High Technology
(MIGHT). MIGHT had engaged DB Lumens for the Langkawi International
Dialogues.
	   KRU Bhd has also organised events for several projects such as
Le Tour de Langkawi.
	   ``Our focus is on media and entertainment because we know our
capabilities in these areas. We have proven that we can organise
events through our own concert tour, the KRUmania Mega Tour, and
the Le Tour de Langkawi concert.
	   ``We built this company on our own merits and credibility ...
heavily using information technology applications in our work.''
	   Norman said while the ``pop icon'' hype has not helped that much
in terms of promoting what the company is doing or can do for the
corporate community, it is a brand name which he is using to sell
the company.
	   ``We, KRU, is a business in itself. We are our product. Yes, we
bopped and bounced on stage during performances but when dealing
with the corporate sector, we are as serious as any businessman.
	   ``People see us differently. We know where to draw the line
where image is concerned ... I cannot expect people to be convinced
of my ability to do business if I were to dress the way I did when
I perform on stage,'' he said.
	   The name, KRU, has opened some doors of opportunities for the
company.
	   ``First, we give them the group. Then we tell them these are the
things that we are capable of doing ... our products are our
credentials. It has worked well for us,'' he added.
	   KRU Bhd has, on its payroll, 40 professionals handling among
others the human resources, legal, finance and corporate affairs of
the company.
	   He said the ban on the KRUmania Mega Tour last year, which
prompted the intervention of Deputy Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar
Ibrahim, was actually a blessing in disguise for the group.
	   ``People opened their eyes as to what KRU, as a group, can do.
We handled the tour ourselves, using our own expertise and
equipment. People realised that although we are young, but we have
the commitment to see through what we aim to do.''
	   Does he thinks KRU Bhd is growing too big, too fast? ``I don't
think so.
	   We gave ourselves 10 years to establish our name in the industry
... it just so happens that we did this in a shorter period of
time,'' he said.
	   Norman said KRU Bhd decided to go ahead with the setting up of
KRU Motion Pictures at a time when some 2,000 production houses
have closed because ``we were in too deep already.
	   ``We made our commitments for some of the equipment early last
year. Then the crisis set in. We believed, however, it could be
used to our advantage. At our own facility and using our own
equipment, we can actually produce music videos and corporate
videos at a competitive price.''
	   He is also looking at opportunities abroad. In Singapore, KRU
Motion Pictures has formed a tie-up with Fandi Ahmad International,
a company owned by Singapore's ex-soccer star Fandi Ahmad. The
joint venture company will tap the huge business opportunities
available in the republic.
	   Norman has also set his sights on business opportunities in
Brunei and the US where it is looking for an agent to market its
services such as those in the music production aspects of the
business.
	   ``We are spreading our risks instead of putting all the eggs in
one basket. We want to be a diversified group,'' he said.
	   While the effects of the economic crisis may have some impact on
the company, Norman said the company is adjusting accordingly.
	   Citing an example, he said, KRU Beverages has slowed down due to
the present situation.
	   While the product, Kruze Cola, is marketable, it does need a
good distribution network. ``It is a volume game but it is not a
good time to give credit sales. We are keeping the product in the
market at minimum quantity,'' he added.
	   Reporting good returns for the 1996 and 1997, he said, these
were the progressive years for the company. ``We were looking at 80
per cent to 120 per cent returns then.''
	   ``Now, while we cannot control what is happening externally, we
can adjust to the situation.
	   ``It is a crawling period for some of the companies in the
stable but we have contingency plans. As an owner, you take all the
precautions. We make do with what we have and get the job done ...
without compromising on quality of the work,'' he said.
	   Besides managing the KRU Bhd and the other companies under the
flagship, Norman still pens and produces songs on top of performing
at shows and concerts with his brothers.
	   ``No grey hair yet but I would probably get a heart attack
first,'' he quipped, when asked if he is finding it stressful being
a ``pop icon'' while at the same time handling businesses worth
millions of ringgit.
	   ``No, I'm not tired yet ... I enjoy doing the things I do but I
find that the stress gets back to me. KRU as a group has a long way
to go and in business, we aim to sustain,'' he said.
	   True to the lyrics of the song he is writing for the
Commonwealth Games 1998 titled ``Never Let the Spirit Die'', Norman
is letting his spirits soar to greater heights.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
