<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Yeltsin </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
On national holiday, Yeltsin admits reforms taking longer than
</HEADLINE>
expected &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos MOSB102-5 &QL; 
 &UR; By MITCHELL LANDSBERG &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ President Boris Yeltsin conceded Friday that
Russia's reforms are taking longer than expected and warned
Russians that it will take more time for the country to become
prosperous and stable.
	   Speaking on Russia Day, which commemorates Russia's declaration
of sovereignty from the Soviet Union in 1990, Yeltsin tried to put
the best face on his achievements in the past eight years.
	   However, in a nationally televised address, he admitted that
Russians had good reason to be disappointed by the slow pace of
reform.
	   While there have been successes, Yeltsin said, ``They have not
resulted in a noticeable improvement in living conditions. Russia's
economy has not become prosperous and stable, nor are its citizens
well provided for or confident of their future.''
	   None of that comes as news to Russians, who are well aware that
their country is stuck in a particularly difficult passage between
a command economy and one driven by the market.
	   In fact, what was bigger news to most Russians was that Friday
was Russia Day, which the government was promoting as the main
holiday of the year. It was a day off for most people, and roads
out of Moscow were clogged with people headed to the country for a
long weekend.
	   According to a nationwide poll earlier in the week, virtually
nobody in the country was aware of the holiday's name. Forty-seven
percent of those questioned said they thought Friday was
Independence Day _ not a bad answer, but technically incorrect.
	   Others thought the day commemorated Yeltsin's election as
president. Twelve percent said they didn't know it was a holiday at
all, and 25 percent were ``undecided,'' according to the pollsters,
the All Russian Center for Public Opinion Research. They did not
give the poll's margin of error.
	   In his speech, Yeltsin said the past eight years had ``not been
an easy test for any of us. It was difficult, but we withstood, we
didn't give up, we didn't turn back.''
	   While it's true that prosperity has so far eluded most Russians,
Yeltsin reminded them of the one ``tangible achievement'' of
post-Soviet Russia: freedom.
	   ``The freedom to speak one's mind. The freedom to pursue one's
religion. The freedom to elect the mayor, member of parliament,
governor, president,'' Yeltsin said.
	   ``However, freedom ... can only be won, sometimes by sacrificing
your calm, your convenience and well-being. Both the state and its
citizens need this freedom. It will help to reveal the huge
potential of our people and will help to make a sharp
breakthrough.''
	   (ml/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
