<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Centennial, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippines marks centennial of declaration of independence
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with hundreds of thousands of people turning up to
watch the parade and fireworks, day-long festivities ending in
street dancing, concert beamed live nationwide in new grafs 7-8 &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos Available
 &UR; By JIM GOMEZ &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ As brass bands played in town squares
throughout the nation, President Fidel Ramos jubilantly waved a
large Philippine flag Friday in a re-enactment of the country's
declaration of independence from Spain 100 years ago.
	   Church bells pealed and government offices offered free food as
Filipinos commemorated Asia's first revolution against Western
colonial rule.
	   Ramos urged the nation to use its hard-won independence as an
inspiration in dealing with the current Asian financial crisis.
	   ``Our heroes claimed our people's right to be free,'' said
Ramos, whose term ends June 30. ``Whenever our resolve should
falter, let us look back to how our story as a nation began.''
	   Ramos waved the flag from the balcony of a refurbished house in
Kawit town in Cavite province, south of Manila, where revolutionary
leader Gen. Emilio Aguinaldo proclaimed independence on June 12,
1898, from 333 years of Spanish colonialism.
	   More than 30 countries sent representatives to join Friday's
celebration in Kawit and at Manila's Rizal Park, named after
national hero Jose Rizal, who was shot by the Spanish for
advocating equality.
	   Hundreds of thousands gathered to watch a parade depicting the
country's struggle against Spanish colonialism and a massive
fireworks display over Manila Bay.
	   The festivities, which ended with street dancing and a
government-sponsored musical concert at a Manila track and field
stadium, were beamed live by television in cities nationwide, where
day-long celebrations were also held.
	   Leftist groups under the New Patriotic Alliance, however, burned
an American flag at an ``alternative'' celebration to highlight the
United States' subsequent takeover of the Philippines, which they
said was downplayed in the government-sponsored festivities.
	   Ramos, elected in 1992, dismantled monopolies and deregulated
many industries, allowing Filipinos to enjoy economic progress
after years of stagnancy. The reforms helped shield the Philippines
from the worst effects of the regional currency crisis.
	   ``It may take some more years for us to realize the full
benefits of freedom,'' Ramos said. ``But we have learned ... that
freedom without growth, without development and without justice is
largely meaningless.''
	   In 1892, Filipino nationalists established a secret society
called the Katipunan, which prepared for armed rebellion against
Spain.
	   The revolt erupted four years later and spread rapidly through
much of the country.
	   A month before the declaration of independence, U.S. naval
forces destroyed a Spanish armada in Manila Bay, in fighting that
followed the outbreak of the Spanish-American war.
	   Spain, still unwilling to hand over power to the Filipino
revolutionaries, ceded the country to the United States for dlrs 20
million in December 1898.
	   The following year, hostilities broke out between Filipino
revolutionaries and American forces sent to occupy the new U.S.
colony. The brief but brutal Philippine-American war is considered
by some historians as the ``first Vietnam'' of the United States.
	   The United States formally granted the Philippines independence
in 1946, but American influence remains strong.
</TEXT>
