<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Germany-Kohl Visit,0450 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Campaigning chancellor pays quick visit to team
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By NESHA STARCEVIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NICE, France (AP) _ Two years ago, after winning the European
title, the German players broke out into a song when two prominent
guests came to the locker room to congratulate them.
	   ``Helmut, sink the tax rate, Egidius open the purse,'' the song
went.
	   Chancellor Helmut Kohl and Egidius Braun, chairman of the German
Soccer Federation, would love to hear the song again _ in Paris
after the World Cup on July 12.
	   A jovial Kohl came Friday to the Cote d'Azure to give the German
national team a morale boost before its opening World Cup game and
perhaps earn a few points from voters back home.
	   Kohl, who claimed his visit had nothing to do with politics,
flew into Nice aboard a special Luftwaffe plane, faced the press
and then went off to have coffee with the team.
	   The Germans are staying at the four-star Mas d'Artigny, a
walled, wooded compound outside Saint-Paul-de-Vence in the hills
above Nice.
	   At the start of his four-hour visit, Kohl met with Braun, coach
Berti Vogts and four senior players before facing reporters at a
press center set up by the Germans outside their training ground at
Charles Ehrmann stadium.
	   Braun reminded Kohl of the song the players sang after winning
the European title in 1996 at Wembley with a 2-1 win over the Czech
Republic, as the two of them went into the locker room.
	   ``It would be wonderful to hear the song again,'' Kohl said.
	   Kohl has a habit of visiting the German soccer team abroad and
is a proclaimed lover of the game. Although he said his visit had
nothing to do with him being chancellor, some populist exposure
won't hurt in his uphill battle to win re-erection in September.
His challenger, Social Democrat Gerhard Schroeder, is also thinking
of flying in.
	   The chancellor predicted Germany would beat all its three group
opponents _ the United States 3-1, Yugoslavia 2-1 and Iran 2-0.
	   ``Then we'll probably play one of our neighbors and one is
definitely more uncomfortable than the other,'' Kohl said about a
possible second-round clash with traditional rival the Netherlands.
	   Kohl said he won't be able to attend Germany's opening game
Monday in Paris against the United States because of a EU summit _
``I have to fight my own hard battles in Cardiff'' _ but that he's
left July 12, the date of the final, open in his diary.
	   ``We have a very good chance of achieving a big success,'' Kohl
said.
	   Captain Juergen Klinsmann then gave Kohl a soccer ball signed by
all players.
</TEXT>
