<HEADER>
w2911 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  MINISTRY-AGENCIESsked     06-12 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> MINISTRY-AGENCIES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ministry, agencies to monitor La Nina, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Ministry, agencies to monitor La Nina, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Sreerema BanooASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Science, Technology and the Environment Ministry will work
closely with various meteorological agencies to monitor La Nina,
the next likely potentially destructive weather phenomenon.
	   Its minister Datuk Law Hieng Ding said at present, there is no
available information if El Nino, the weather phenomenon which was
the cause of prolonged drought, will be followed by La Nina.
	   ``There is a sign that the El Nino is nearing its end, but
whether or not it will be followed by La Nina, we cannot forecast
yet,'' he said in Kuala Lumpur yesterday after attending the weekly
Cabinet meeting.
	   He added that the World Meteorological Organisation, in a
report, had said El Nino will be followed by La Nina, which is
expected to bring heavy rain and storms.
	   Law assured that various government agencies are prepared to
deal with ``La Nina''. The National Security Division, he said is
on standby and is prepared to tackle not only haze and forest fires
but also floods.
	   On Monday, Deputy Agriculture Minister Datuk Tengku Mahmud
Mansor was reported to have said that agencies like the Drainage
and Irrigation Department have been put on alert to undertake the
necessary preparations in anticipation of La Nina.
	   On the current weather situation, Law said, it is improving and
generally the whole region is free of haze and no hot spots or
smoke haze areas have been detected.
	   The ministry, he added, will continue to monitor the situation
and enforcement of the anti-open burning campaign is on-going.
	   In the two months since the launch of the campaign on April 8,
Law said, 345 cases have been detected and in 69, prosecution is
being undertaken.
	   ``Two cases in Pahang are up for mention on June 17, six cases
in Kelantan are up for mention on June 23 while one case in Malacca
is up for mention on June 15,'' he said.
	   Meanwhile, he said, an indoor air purifier has been installed at
the Puduraya bus terminal. ``It was installed 10 days ago, however,
we have yet to determine its effects. We are in the process of
monitoring how effective it is,'' he said, adding that there may be
some room for modification and improvement.
	   The air purifier was built by a team comprising the Chemistry
Department, Malaysia Electric Corp, Sirim Bhd and the Sunway Group.
The cost to build two units is RM50,000.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
