<HEADLINE>
Filipinos to mark freedom centenary, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Filipinos to mark freedom centenary, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Lucia Palpal-latocASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   HUNDREDS of Filipinos in Hong Kong will be missing today's
celebration of their motherland's 100 years of freedom because of
the deadlock in the labour dispute at Philippine Airlines.
	   The celebration in Manila will begin with a nationwide pealing
of church bells at 6am, and a re-enactment of the independence
declaration in Kawit town in Cavite province, outside the capital,
at 4.30pm.
	   Filipino communities all over the world, including Hong Kong,
will raise the national flag and re-enact the declaration of
independence from 333 years of Spanish colonial rule a century ago.
	   As part of the celebration in Hong Kong, a temporary marker will
be unveiled at the site where the first Philippine flag was sewn at
Morrison Hill Road, Wan Chai.
	   Philippine Vice-Consul Raul Hernandez said the strike by the
620-strong PAL pilots' union has affected the celebrations.
	   ``I personally know some people who had to cancel their plans
because all the flights are fully booked,'' he said.
	   He appealed to his countrymen in Hong Kong who missed their
flights to attend the day-long celebrations here.
	   Mr Hernandez also hoped the celebration would encourage
Filipinos working overseas to ``help project a positive image of
the Philippines by being the best Filipinos that they can be''.
	   In a message to the 160,000-strong Filipino community in Hong
Kong, President-elect Joseph Estrada said leading his country to
the 21st century was an ``awesome task''.
	   ``But we are invigorated by the knowledge that the greater
masses of our people are behind us,'' said the ex-movie actor who
beat his closest rival by a wide margin.
	   He said he was hopeful the country would overcome the regional
economic difficulties.
	   Chief Executive Tung Chee-hwa will join about 500 other senior
government officials and diplomats in giving a toast during a
reception organised by the Philippine Consulate at Conrad Hotel.
	   A giant Centennial Swatch specially designed by Filipino artist
Fernando Zobel de Ayala will be unveiled at the Bayanihan Kennedy
Town Centre this morning. A Centennial fiesta dinner-dance will cap
the celebrations.
	   Political analysts in Manila say the Philippine's real
independence should be 4 July 1946 when the United States after 50
years of rule gave back freedom to the Filipinos.
	   Mr Hernandez defended the nationwide consensus that the birth of
the nation was on 12 June 1898.
	   ``We did not have full freedom at that time but it was the
beginning of the country's birth as a nation.''
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
