<HEADLINE>
Bail blow a timely reminder, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Bail blow a timely reminder, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A WOMAN'S taste for expensive watches may make her Hong Kong's
first e-mail thief, the District Court heard yesterday.
	   Florence Cheung Siu-ming, 22, a former employee of Wharf Cable,
allegedly used credit card numbers stolen from various people to
order Rolex and Omega watches via her e-mail account.
	   Cheung is accused of committing the offences between April 1996
and around the same time last year. She was arrested last June,
after police raided her Tin Siu Wai flat.
	   Cheung had been granted bail but yesterday District Court Judge
Richard Hawkes remanded her in custody until the start of the trial
to ensure it began on schedule.
	   Prosecutor Eric Kwok said the trial should begin on time because
the first prosecution witness would be flown from England.
	   Cheung faces four counts of theft and seven of obtaining
property by deception. No pleas were taken.
	   The trial will open on 27 July at the District Court.
	   
</TEXT>
