<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-Queens, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sampras loses in straight sets to Woodforde
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Updates with details, Woodford quotes, other results

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Pete Sampras suffered a setback in his Wimbledon
preparations Friday when he was beaten in straight sets by
Australia's Mark Woodforde at the Queen's Club grass-court
tournament.
	   The top-seeded Sampras, who had a bye in the first round and
beat Wayne Black in the second round, looked flat as he slumped to
a 6-3, 6-2 defeat on his favorite surface.
	   It was the latest surprising loss for Sampras, who was ousted in
the second round of the French Open by little-known Ramon Delgado
of Paraguay.
	   Sampras had beaten the 66th-ranked Woodforde, known primarily as
a doubles specialist, in all of their previous 10 matches and
dropped only two sets in the process.
	   Sampras entered Queens as a tuneup for Wimbledon, a tournament
he has won four times and where he is the defending champion.
	   Sampras declined to speak to the media until after his doubles
match later in the day.
	   Woodforde said players have noticed that Sampras is lacking
motivation this year.
	   ``Everyone is aware that, motivation-wise, he's not there,''
Woodforde said. ``I played a pretty good tight match against him,
and he just wasn't able to pick it up where in the past he was able
to take it up a notch or two. That's where he is found wanting.''
	   Woodforde mixed up his shots, returning well and often catching
Sampras with lobs whenever the American ventured to the net. But
his most effective tactic was to hit a succession of drop volleys
which fell just over the net and left Sampras stranded.
	   The Australian also served far better than Sampras, hitting
three aces in the opening game to set the tone of the match.
	   In contrast, Sampras produced four double-faults, the last of
which gave Woodforde a break for 3-2 in the second set. A netted
backhand voley then gave Woodforde a second break for 5-2.
	   After so many defeats to Sampras, Woodforde was surprised he
finally made his breakthrough on grass.
	   ``I don't know if I 100 percent believed that I could beat
Sampras, especially on grass,'' he said. ``I maybe would have given
myself more of a chance on a different surface. Hard court,
perhaps.''
	   In other matches, fourth-seeded Jonas Bjorkman of Sweden was
surprised 6-3, 4-6, 6-3 by No. 14 Byron Black of Zimbabwe. Another
Swede, No. 8 Thomas Enqvist, advanced with a 6-1, 3-6, 6-2 win over
Jordi Burillo of Spain.
	   American Brian MacPhie, who only got into the tournament as a
lucky loser when Mikael Tillstrom withdrew, reached the
quarterfinals with a 6-3, 6-3 victory over Ivo Heuberger of
Switzerland.
	   In order to clear up a backlog of matches caused by rain delays,
players faced the prospect of playing two matches to get the
tournament back on track.
	   (str-sw)
</TEXT>
