<BODY>
<SLUG> CRIPPLED-TAXI-DRIVER sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Crippled taxi driver accepts out-of-court settlement, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Crippled taxi driver accepts out-of-court settlement, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Neil WesternASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A CRIPPLED taxi driver whose life was ruined because of a
speeding barrister's ``gross negligence'' accepted millions of
dollars in damages yesterday.
	   Justice Conrad Seagroatt said lawyer David Ma Wai-kwan's
reckless driving was to blame for the crash seven years ago that
condemned father-of-two Yau Wai-kan to a wheelchair.
	   After the accident Mr Ma pleaded guilty to careless driving and
was fined $500, although the prosecution facts did not mention Mr
Yau had been hurt at all.
	   ``In my view Mr Ma was extremely fortunate not to have been
arrested for reckless driving.
	   Everything indicates it was a bad case of reckless driving,''
the judge said.
	   Mr Yau, who was seeking $18 million, reached an undisclosed
out-of-court settlement with Mr Ma two days into a trial at the
Court of First Instance.
	   Mr Ma claimed in court the taxi driver was partly to blame for
the crash, alleging both vehicles were switching lanes when the
collision occurred. Mr Yau, and a passenger, told the court Mr Ma
hit him straight from behind while travelling at up to 100kph along
Gloucester Road, Wan Chai.
	   Although the deal meant Mr Justice Seagroatt did not have to
enter judgement, the judge said he wanted to assure Mr Yau that he
accepted his version of events.
	   ``This was a serious motor accident which has ruined a man's
life.
	   ``Mr Yau should not in any way consider he was to blame for this
accident to the slightest extent.
	   ``It was clear . . . that there was gross negligence on the part
of Mr Ma and that was apparent from the outset.'' During the
hearing Mr Justice Seagroatt stopped Mr Yau's lawyer, Nicholas
Pirie, cross-examining Mr Ma over whether he had been drinking
before the accident.
	   Such questioning was irrelevant, he said.
	   ``The negligence was so clear-cut that any explanation for it
did not matter.'' The crash happened in the early hours of 15
November 1991 as Mr Ma was returning from an evening out.
	   The lawyer's BMW struck the back of the taxi, which spun around
twice and ended up facing the opposite direction.
	   Mr Yau, 47, suffered a severed spinal cord and was left
tetraplegic. Confined to a wheelchair he suffers frequent tremors
in his legs and is unable to control his bowels.
	   His condition was made worse because of the cramped
350-square-foot flat he shared with his wife and two children.
	   He later contracted tuberculosis, and consequently, moved to a
new flat with a balcony.
	   Earlier this year Mr Ma was acquitted of conspiracy to pervert
the course of justice after a judge ordered the jury to return not
guilty verdicts because of insufficient evidence.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
