<HEADLINE>
Costs of most goods stable, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Costs of most goods stable, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Thurs. - Prices of most essential items surveyed
in the Klang Valley remained stable.
	   Ikan merah was most expensive at Carrefour hypermarket and Giant
Subang Jaya where it was sold at RM13.90 per kg.
	   Green chillies were most expensive at the Lucky Garden wet
market where they were sold at RM18 per kg.
	   In Ipoh, the short supply of ikan merah pushed up prices by RM2
to RM3.
	   It was going for RM18 per kg at the Central market compared to
RM15 last week and RM16 per kg at the Buntong market (RM14 per kg
last week). At the Canning Garden market, the price remained at
RM18 per kg. Most of the supermarkets surveyed did not sell the
fish today.
	   The prices of ikan selar varied at between RM4.50 and RM10 per
kg.
	   The prices of green chillies also remained high at between RM9
and 11 per kg.
	   In Penang, prices of ikan merah varied from RM4.50 to RM8 per
kg. It was not available at Looking Good supermarket.
	   The best bargain for ikan selar was RM4.50 at the Sui Wah
supermarket in Sunshine Square. Elsewhere it was selling for
between RM5 and RM7.50.
	   Prices of green chillies remained unchanged, selling at between
RM7 and RM10 per kg at most of the outlets.
	   In Johor Baru, ikan merah and ikan selar were sold at an average
of RM10 and RM7.90 per kg respectively at wet markets, while
supermarkets priced them at an average of RM14.40 and RM8.40 per kg
respectively.
	   
</TEXT>
