MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Malaysian Islamic Chamber of Commerce (DPIM), which has
already formed a tie-up with its counterpart in Sudan, is now
looking at establishing some form of cooperation with chambers in
Iran and Turkey.
	   The chamber plans to set up cooperation with their counterparts
in Iran and Turkey before the end of the year and move on to Europe
and China next year, its council member and Entrepreneur
Development Bureau chairman Zainuddin Mohd Tahir said yesterday.
	   The tie-ups will provide its members with opportunities for
joint- ventures and investments in these countries, he told a press
conference in Kuala Lumpur yesterday.
	   The Chamber had signed a memorandum of understanding with the
Sudan Businessmen and Employers Federation during Prime Minister
Datuk Seri Dr Mahathir Mohamad's official visit to the North
African country last month.
	   Zainuddin said Sudan was chosen because it was not only an
Islamic country but also its political stability does not pose as a
hindrance to foreign investments.
	   The Chamber's members have expressed interested in the Sudanese
telecommunications, transportation, power generation, food
production, livestock and tourism industries.
	   
</TEXT>
