<HEADLINE>
End to smouldering saga, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
End to smouldering saga, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   JERRY Lui Kin-hong's conviction was the latest twist in a saga
of death and intrigue that was unravelled after graftbusters began
probing an alleged multi-billion dollar cigarette smuggling
syndicate in the early 1990s.
	   Most of the developments surrounded a series of statements made
by Tommy Chui To-yan, a former shareholder of Giant Island, to whom
Lui ensured cigarettes was supplied in return for bribes.
	   Chui confessed to smuggling and made detailed allegations
against associates at Giant Island and named Lui as a corrupt
partner in crime.
	   But Chui, who was to be a witness for the Independent Commission
Against Corruption, was found dead in Singapore in April 1995,
allegedly killed by a triad hit squad.
	   His statements could no longer be used as evidence, but
investigations continued.
	   Henfrey Tin Sau-kwong, a former customs officer turned Giant
Island director, was later jailed for six-and-a-half years for
conspiracy to pervert the course of justice by ``preventing'' Chui
being a witness in the case.
	   Lui was convicted of conspiring with Chui and three other former
or current Giant Island shareholders _ Chen Ying-jen, Hung Wing-wah
and Chong Tsoi-jun.
	   Chong, who had cigarette smuggling charges against him dropped
after Chui's death, was later charged with Hong Kong's biggest
alleged tax evasion, involving more than $50 million. But, confined
to a wheelchair, Chong leaped to his death before the trial began.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
