</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> LIM-REFUTES-UNION sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Lim refutes union leader's allegations, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Lim refutes union leader's allegations, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Hamisah HamidASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   HUMAN Resources Minister Datuk Lim Ah Lek yesterday refuted all
the allegations made by Malaysian Trades Union Congress (MTUC)
secretary- general G. Rajasegaran at a press conference at the MTUC
headquarters last week.
	   Rajasegaran had alleged that Lim had taken the leaders of the
Metal Industry Employees Union (MIEU) to task for not taking up the
Carnaud Metal Box Sdn Bhd workers' cause. Lim said this is a
serious allegation and that he was not involved in the negotiations
on the compensation for workers who had accepted the voluntary
retrenchment scheme by Carnaud Metal Box.
	   ``This is very serious and he (Rajasegaran) has accused me of
negotiating on behalf of the workers,'' he said, adding, ``I've
never done that''.
	   ``The issue is that the workers were being discriminated against
(in the Carnaud Metal Box case) as their leader, Mr Jacob
Engkatesoo, received more compensation compared with the rest of
the workers who had accepted the retrenchment scheme,'' Lim told a
news conference before the ministry's post-Cabinet meeting in Kuala
Lumpur yesterday.
	   In 1996, 69 workers of Carnaud Metal Box accepted the voluntary
retrenchment scheme from their employer, after they were
represented by Rajasegaran, who was MIEU executive secretary and
Engkatesoo, the secretary-general, in negotiations with the
employer.
	   These retrenched workers then took up the matter with the
minister after they discovered that Engkatesoo had received an
ex-gratia payment of RM425,000 in addition to the compensation.
	   Lim said that after he had met with the employer and was
convinced that the workers were being discriminated against, he had
referred the matter to the Industrial Court, which had directed
Carnaud Metal Box to pay RM1.4 million to the workers.
	   Lim also responded to other allegations by Rajasegaran in a
statement that the MTUC secretary-general had released to the media
at last week's news conference.
	   Among the allegations were that the then Labour Minister's
failure to make a recognition order of the Penang Textile Workers'
Union in 1987 although a majority of 65.9 per cent of workers were
in favour of it.
	   The company, Terry Prai Sdn Bhd had instead supported an
in-house union with the production manager as the president,
claimed Rajasegaran.
	   Lim said the ministry's records showed that the Labour Minister
at that time had given a directive to the company to recognise the
union starting August 5 1987 and as such, it was a non-issue.
	   On Terry Prai's in-house union, Lim said records at the
ministry's Trade Unions Department showed that the department had
not received any application to form the in-house union at Terry
Prai.
	   Rajasegaran also alleged that Lim had accused a particular MTUC
leader of being responsible for the picketing of Thomson Audio
employees in September 1996.
	   Lim said in his discussions with the union representing Thomson
Audio workers, he was informed that the union had been advised by
an MTUC leader to picket.
	   Rajasegaran had also claimed that the minister had not replied
to his letter on September 3 1996 where he had asked Lim to point
out the information in the MTUC reports to the International Labour
Organisation (ILO) that the minister had described as lies.
	   In response to this, Lim said he had called the MTUC and the
Malaysian Employers' Federation (MEF) for a meeting on October 11
and 22 1996.
	   He said the Human Resources Ministry had found that some of the
MTUC's responses to the ILO's questionnaires did not reflect the
true picture of the labour scenario in the country and there was
distortion of facts.
	   ``During the meeting, MTUC representatives did not refute or
question the Government's and employers' views on MTUC's response
to the ILO questionnaires.
	   ``The tripartite meeting had agreed that all replies to
international questionaires will not be submitted separately and
will be discussed by the three parties first.
	   ``It had also agreed that all statements given to outsiders
should not smear the country's image and all doubts on laws and
government policies should be referred to the Human Resources
Minister,'' the minister said.
	   In the news conference which lasted about one -and a half-hours,
reporters were also shown the video of Rajasegaran making
statements on the country's labour relations and tripartite system
at a seminar in Washington DC on May 14 and 16, 1996.
	   Lim said the Government is not stopping Rajasegaran from
speaking on the workers' welfare but that the union leader has to
make sure his facts are right.
	   
</TEXT>
