<HEADLINE>
French couple want their partly built boat, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
French couple want their partly built boat, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Thurs. - A French couple waited more than 13 years
for their boat to be built, and tired of waiting any longer, sued
the builder for the return of the partly-built vessel.
	   The Kuala Terregganu High Court, on Dec 14, 1994, dismissed
their suit, ruling that it could not order specific performance
against the builder, who had died in 1996.
	   It held that the couple, Claude Besnard and Annie Beulin, could,
if they wanted, sue for damages.
	   Unhappy with the decision, they appealed and their matter was
fixed for hearing before the Court of Appeal today.
	   The couple's counsel Abdul Rahman Abdullah said his clients were
not asking for specific performance, but only wanted the boat,
``which is lying there'', to be returned to them.
	   Judge Datuk N.H. Chan said this was not in the couple's
affidavit and moreover the respondent, Ali Ngah, had since died.
	   He fixed the case for mention on July 27.
	   The couple's affidavit stated that they commissioned Ali to
built the boat in 1980 and gave him RM43,500 worth of materials.
Ali promised delivery within eight months.
	   Ali's son Abdul Manan was in the court today.
	   
</TEXT>
