<SLUG> EASE-LIQUIDITY-WOES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Move to ease liquidity woes, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Move to ease liquidity woes, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Bayani CruzASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA) yesterday increased
transparency in its foreign exchange transactions in a bid to
minimise sharp rises in interest rates arising from tight liquidity
in the financial markets as well as future speculative attacks on
the Hong Kong dollar.
	   Effective immediately, the monetary authority will disclose its
two-day forecast for the level of change in the aggregate balance
attributable to the HKMA's foreign exchange transactions involving
the Hong Kong dollar.
	   The information on HKMA's two-day forecast on its aggregate
balance will be displayed on a new electronic page of the
widely-used Reuters financial service.
	   The forecast will enable banks to anticipate the changes in the
liquidity conditions in the interbank market, enhance the
transparency of Hong Kong's linked exchange rate system, and
facilitate a more efficient adjustment in the interbank interest
rates, HKMA chief executive Joseph Yam said yesterday.
	   ``More information can improve the efficiency of the market and
make it more effective. It will also make it more difficult for
currency speculators to attack the Hong Kong dollar,'' Mr Yam said.
	   He said there had been no speculative attack on the Hong Kong
dollar in recent days.
	   ``I do not feel that there was any speculative element and it
seems like (US dollar) demand was genuine,'' Mr Yam said.
	   Standard Chartered Bank regional treasurer Stanley Y F Wong
yesterday said the financial markets, particularly banks, will have
more time to prepare for possible shortages in liquidity with the
two-day forecast in the level of change in the aggregate balance of
the HKMA's forex transactions involving Hong Kong dollars.
	   ``This will minimise sudden sharp rises in interest rates in the
interbank market arising from unexpected shortages in liquidity on
a particular day,'' Mr Wong said.
	   Yesterday's forecast, for example, indicates that the aggregate
balance will stand at a negative level of $0.4 billion in two days.
This will give banks more time to shore up their positions in view
of the expected balance, the HKMA said.
	   Bank treasurers and analysts said the HKMA's new disclosure is
intended to bolster the strength of the Hong Kong dollar by
increasing transparency in the financial system.
	   The Hong Kong dollar, which is pegged to the US dollar at the
rate of 7.8, is currently being buffeted by intense pressure
arising from the continuing depreciation of the yen and rampant
rumours about the possible devaluation of the yuan.
	   Mr Yam also said the HKMA may consider using its US$96.2 billion
(HK$750 billion) in forex reserves to bolster the slumping yen.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
