<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-Albania </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Albanians happy with NATO decision on show of force
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With NATO-Kosovo &QL; 
 &UR; By JEFFREY ULBRICH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) - Albanian Defense Minister Luan
Hajdaraga said Friday he was delighted with NATO's decision to make
a show of force in the Balkans because it is clear Yugoslavia wants
to dominate Kosovo militarily.
	   The minister, here for a meeting between NATO and 27 partner
countries in the Euro-Atlantic Partnership Council, spoke a day
after the alliance decided to conduct immediate air exercises over
Albania and Macedonia as a way of pressuring Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic.
	   That show of power, expected sometime next week, was one of
several steps taken by the 16-nation North Atlantic Treaty
Organization to persuade Milosevic to stop his offensive against
ethnic Albanians in the the southern province of Kosovo, where they
are in a large majority.
	   ``We are very pleased about the decision taken by the NATO
Council yesterday,'' Hajdaraga said in an interview.
	   ``The stand of Milosevic in the Kosovo crisis is very clear, it
is to dominate the situation by military means.'' The danger is, he
said, that ``those means can spread to Albania.''
	   Under the measures taken by defense ministers Thursday, NATO
will conduct simulated air attacks over Albania and Macedonia and
study options for further action ranging from accelerated planning
for military exercises to direct air strikes inside Yugoslavia and
use of ground troops.
	   This is aimed at persuading Milosevic to declare a cease-fire in
Kosovo, withdraw his forces and end the repression of the ethnic
Albanians and open serious negotiations with the opposition.
	   Hajdaraga said Albania understood the gravity of the situation
and noted with pleasure that all of the countries here agreed with
the decision.
	   Like his colleagues in NATO, Hajdaraga hoped a diplomatic
solution could be found to the crisis in Kosovo, where many among
the majority ethnic Albanians support independence.
	   ``In case the political solution and diplomatic means will fail,
maybe the military solution will be the right means.''
	   Two major problems face Albania, he said.
	   ``The first is the fighting raging near our borders and the
second is the refugees coming to Albania. The number of the
refugees settling in northern Albania is about 15,000. There is a
problem for us to support them, to house them, and to fulfill their
needs.''
	   (ju-ss)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-NATO-Albania; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:ENGL;)
