	   KUALA LUMPUR, Thurs. - A housewife told the Sessions Court today
that she had to seek the assistance of a motorist to send her niece
to hospital after the girl had been knocked down by another
motorist.
	   Koo May Chan, 33, said she stopped a car that was leaving the
Taman Maluri Jaya Jusco carpark for help to send Chiew Yuen Kee,
two, to hospital.
	   She said her own daughter Chin Sim Yee, who was also knocked
down was sent to a clinic by her sister-in-law's friend.
	   May Chan was giving evidence at the trial of businessman Teh
Chuan Ann, 40, who is charged with attempting to commit culpable
homicide not amounting to murder of Koo Mei Fong, Chiew and Chin.
	   Teh, of Taman Tenaga, Cheras, is alleged to have committed the
offence about 7.30pm on Jan 25 at the Jaya Jusco supermarket
carpark.
	   He also claimed trial to two charges of committing mischief by
causing damage of more than RM25 to the vehicles owned by Lau Kiat
Kean and Liong Mun Kong at the same place and time.
	   Teh is represented by S.T. Ravindran and Alvin Loo while Deputy
Public Prosecutor Noor Ruwena Mohd Nurdin is prosecuting.
	   She said when Chin returned from the clinic she saw that she
(Chin) had injuries on both her legs and was complaining of pain.
	   May Chan said during an argument between Teh and her sister Mei
Fong over a parking lot, she saw a woman and two children sitting
in his car.
	   She said after the argument, Teh got into his car and after the
occupants got out, he drove the car into Mei Fong and the children.
Two other cars in the parking lot were also damaged.
	   Hearing before judge Lim Yee Lan was adjourned to Aug 20.
	   
</TEXT>
