<SLUG> ONE-MONTH-HIBOR-HITS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
One-month Hibor hits 15pc in the morning, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
One-month Hibor hits 15pc in the morning, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Hong Kong Interbank Offered Rate (Hibor) soared again
yesterday to its highest level since January as the yen dived for a
fourth straight day.
	   Dealers said the one-month interbank rate reached a peak of 15
per cent in the morning.
	   The surge was partly driven by the sustained weakness in the
yen.
	   But there were rumours that the Hong Kong Monetary Authority
(HKMA) had pumped two-month and three-month funds into the market,
sending the one-month interbank rate down to 8 per cent in the
morning session, dealers said.
	   The benchmark three-month Hibor shot up to 12.09821 per cent
yesterday from 9.57143 per cent on Wednesday.
	   The one-month Hibor ended at 12.94643 per cent against 9.38839
per cent on Wednesday.
	   There were also rumours that some major players were lending
Hong Kong dollars in the interbank market given the attractive
Hibor rates.
	   ``Those major market players may be speculators,'' said Carlos
Cheung, spot market head at Bank of East Asia.
	   Mr Cheung said regional currencies were unlikely to recover by
the end of the year, which would exert pressure on the Hong Kong
dollar.
	   Traders expect interbank rates will trend further upwards today
with continuing tight liquidity in the market.
	   But one money market analyst at an US bank said tight liquidity
would make banks utilise their funds more efficiently.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
