<BODY>
<SLUG> SHIPPING-TRADE-NEEDS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`Shipping trade needs new tankers to boost tonnage', BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
`Shipping trade needs new tankers to boost tonnage', BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   WHILE demand for crude and clean oil product is rising, the
tonnage availability is expected to shrink due to the age profile
of existing tanker fleet.
	   GMV Ship Management Sdn Bhd general manager Captain Johari Mohd
Noh said the forecast development of tanker demand and supply
suggests that the balance between the two will narrow and that
there will be a marked tightening in the availability of tonnage
given the age profile of existing fleet and the existing order book
and yard availability.
	   ``Over 35 per cent of the existing fleet is over 20 years old
while 13 per cent is over 15 years, whereas order book for
deliveries up to the year 2000 amounts to only 15.5 per cent of the
fleet,'' he said in his paper entitled ``Liquid Bulk Trade:
Opportunities and Challenges'', which was presented at the Fourth
Biennial International Conference in Subang Jaya yesterday.
	   ``In theory, with many vessels having reached the age of 20 and
assuming that the vessels age shall not exceed 25, there will be a
need for replacement of a large number of vessels in the near
future,'' he said.
	   Johari also said the consumption of world major oils is set to
increase from 76.85 million tonnes in 1997 to 161.12 million tonnes
in 2020, an increase of about 100 per cent.
	   ``Palm oil is expected to have the largest increase by 27.88
million tonnes or about 100 per cent, followed by rapeseed oil by
21.12 million tonnes.
	   ``For this reason, Malaysia and its Asean neighbours are set to
be a major source of vegetable oil exports within the next
decade,'' he said.
	   However, he added, the El Nino phenomenon that has affected our
area lately (haze, drought and water shortage) is expected to
affect negatively on the production, and hence, the trade growth.
	   ``Nonetheless, this shortfall is expected to be offset by the
expanding export based production within Latin America and
South-East Asia over the medium- and long-term. Overall, shipping
demand is set to rise,'' he said.
	   On the Very Large Crude Carrier (VLCC) market, Johari said it
has improved tremendously over the last one year based on
increasing time charter earnings.
	   ``The Aframax size market has also stabilised over the years,
but is currently being adversely affected by the Asian economic
turmoil.
	   ``The clean petroleum market also has strong fundamentals, but
similar to Aframax, current earning is poor due to the Asian
economic problem. Demand has substantially reduced, at least for
the time being,'' he said.
	   Johari said Asian refiners, however, are expected to boost
production and export in order to generate additional revenue, but
this will be at the expense of lowering the import from Arabian
Gulf.
	   He added that the parcel tanker trade is also being adversely
affected, partly by over tonnage and partly by the lower demand due
to the Asian economic crisis.
	   ``Owners who have placed substantial orders for new vessels for
deliveries in 1996 and 1997 have found difficulties in employing
the vessels in the spot market,'' he said.
	   At the same time, chemicals production have slacken while the
number of production plants planned in South-East Asia has been
shelved, thus multiplying the effect of excess tonnage over demand.
	   Shipowners' problems, however, are not limited to the falling
demand and the excess tonnage only, but they are also exposed to
the increasing ship operating cost, including increase regulations.
This has an adverse effect on the earnings of tankers.
	   Nonetheless, Johari said the outlook of the tanker market in the
long run is still good. ``In my opinion, the current Asian economic
crisis is just an economic correction given its past continuous
high growth over a long period.
	   ``Once recovered, the economy will become more matured and
stronger. The tanker owners who are currently suffering from
depressed tanker market condition, would then be able to breathe
again,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
