<HEADLINE>
Fomca disappointed by Abu Hassan's allegations against it, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Fomca disappointed by Abu Hassan's allegations against it, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PETALING JAYA, Thurs. - The Federation of Malaysian Consumers'
Associations today expressed surprise and disappointment over the
statement by Datuk Abu Hassan Omar yesterday alleging that Fomca
and the Selangor Consumers' Association had politicised the water
crisis to confuse the people and to gain popularity.
	   Fomca president Prof Mohd Hamdan Adnan was speaking at a Press
conference at the Fomca building.
	   The Selangor Menteri Besar had accused Fomca and the SCA of
being more interested in politicising the water crisis rather than
working with the authorities to help consumers.
	   He had urged the Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs Ministry
and the Registrar of Societies to review the status of both
associations as he felt their recent actions were similar to that
of political parties.
	   The basis for his accusations stemmed from a report quoting the
SCA legal advisor A. Jayaseelan as saying that the association
planned to sue the Selangor State Government and the Menteri Besar
for allegedly being negligent in managing water resources.
	   ``Fomca has no political agenda behind its actions. We are
merely voicing the grievances of the people affected by the water
crisis,'' Hamdan said.
	   ``As a responsible consumer association, it is our duty to act
as a conduit between the public and the parties involved in the
water management. Therefore we are dumbfounded that the Government
is questioning our motives when it should be working alongside us
to help the public. Instead it seems to be hindering our efforts.''
	   Hamdan said that Fomca received hundreds of complaints each day.
	   ``It is obvious to us that the actions of the State Goverment
and the Selangor Water Authority lack transparency,'' he said.
	   Also present at the Press conference was Fomca
director-cum-legal advisor T. Indrani who confirmed reports
yesterday that two suits were being filed, one against the State
Government and the Menteri Besar, and another against Kuala Lumpur
City Hall and the police for withdrawing Fomca's permit to hold a
forum on the water crisis at Bandar Tun Razak Sports Complex.
	   Indrani also clarified that the suit against KL City Hall and
the police is being filed by the SCA.
	   ``It will be filed at the end of the month seeking about RM5,000
compensation. This was the amount spent on venue rental and the
printing of 50,000 announcement flyers among other expenses.''
	   She said the second suit, against the State Government and the
Menteri Besar for negligence would be filed by individuals because
under Malaysian law ``there is no provision for class action by a
group of people under one name against an institution or
individual.''
	   
</TEXT>
