</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> COMPETITIVE-ENVIRON sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Competitive environ for ship managers and seafarers, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Competitive environ for ship managers and seafarers, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE commercial environment in which today's ship managers and
seafarers operate has changed, becoming highly competitive,
extremely cost-conscious and completely international in nature.
	   This has affected the relativities between quantity, quality and
costs of seafarers as ship managers engage in a delicate balancing
act to remain commercially competitive.
	   Mr Barrie Lewarn, a director at the Faculty of Maritime
Transport and Engineering, Australian Maritime College, said this
in his paper entitled ``Training and Manpower Planning for the
Maritime Industry''.
	   The paper was presented at the IKMAL 4th Biennial International
Maritime Conference in Subang Jaya.
	   ``With the internationalisation of shipping it is considerably
harder for ship managers to consistently match supply and demand,''
he said.
	   A global marketplace for seafarers has provided an environment
where job mobility is both easy and becoming the norm. As such,
many ship managers have established their own training schemes to
engender loyalty among seafarer employees.
	   ``A greater commitment by ship management organisations to
quality training is one way which will assist them to maintain the
quantity of seafarers required by their organisations.''
	   On the quality of seafaring personnel, Lewarn said the
internationalisation of shipping has caused the quality, reputation
and confidence in the certificates of competency issued by some
countries to become highly questionable.
	   ``Internationalisation has allowed the less ethical operator to
exploit the world market for seafarers with little regard to the
quality of those seafarers... as a result, the first response of
concerned governments was to develop the International Convention
on Standards of Training, Certification and Watchkeeping for
Seafarers, 1978 (STCW 78) through the auspices of the International
Maritime Consultative Organisation (IMCO).''
	   However, because further concerted international action was
needed, STCW 95 was set up to raise the level of competence of
seafarers and those responsible for training.
	   ``STCW is the international community's approach to improving
the quality and professionalism of seafarers, employers, trainers
and marine administrators and has great potential to enhance the
safe and efficient operation of ships.''
	   As for costs, he said, the main challenge faced by employers in
the international market is finding the correct balance between
costs and competency.
	   ``The lift in standards projected by STCW 95 will almost
inevitably increase the costs of employing seafarers. If this also
drives less reputable certificates of competency from the seas,
then the cost will be offset by the benefits,'' he said.
	   He added that while costs are important, quality and competence
are also important, and it is the balance between these two issues
that provides a challenge for the reputable ship-operating
employer.
	   On the certificate of competency, Lewarn said because the skills
are not uniform around the world, the certificate is not a uniform
measure of competence.
	   He also said from the point of view of maritime education and
training institutions, the STCW 95 and ISM Code are global issues
of regional relevance.
	   Maritime Education and Training (MET) institutions have a role
to play in promoting quality and safety, he added.
	   ``In simple terms, MET must seek to achieve quality staff,
quality equipment, facilities, programmes and graduates.
	   ``STCW 95 and the ISM Code are not a panacea for some of the
current problems. In the final analysis, managers must not, and in
many countries, cannot abrogate their responsibilities. It is in
the interest of everyone to act professionally and strive for
quality,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:COMPETITIVE-ENVIRON sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
