</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> PEREGRINE-LOW-REPAYMENTS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Peregrine unit liquidator warns of low repayments, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Peregrine unit liquidator warns of low repayments, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ESTIMATES by Price Waterhouse, the provisional liquidator for
Peregrine Fixed Income, suggest creditors of the unit of the failed
investment bank could be repaid as little as 19 per cent of their
money.
	   In a worst-case scenario, it was possible the sale of assets
would realise no more than US$2.41 billion (HK$18.80 billion),
Price Waterhouse said.
	   It estimated that between 19 per cent and 52 per cent of the
Peregrine unit's debts could be recovered, depending on how much
could be raised by selling the bonds and derivatives still in the
unit's hands.
	   Peregrine Fixed Income was one of the world's biggest junk bond
trading houses before the Peregrine group collapsed when Indonesian
firms defaulted on loan repayments. Not surprisingly, US$1.091
billion in Peregrine Fixed Income's bond and derivative assets, or
52.4 per cent of US$2.079 billion total assets before provisions,
is in Indonesia.
	   Price Waterhouse partner Ted Osborn told a creditors meeting
yesterday that the portfolio was being divided into a ``good book''
and a ``bad book''.
	   The bad book is for debt that is unlikely to be repaid.
	   ``Roughly three-quarters is in the bad book,'' he said. ``And a
substantial portion is in Indonesia.'' Simon Copley, another Price
Waterhouse partner, said an independent consultant was called in
when the provisional liquidator couldn't decide what to do with
Peregrine Fixed Income's portfolio.
	   ``Independent advice confirmed that we couldn't sell or manage
the portfolio because of its very high credit risk and a lack of
liquidity, we couldn't even hedge,'' he said.
	   ``We couldn't sell and we couldn't manage, it was a traders'
worst nightmare.'' Mr Osborn said the ``majority'' of the bonds _
and almost all the derivatives _ were in default.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:PEREGRINE-LOW-REPAYMENTS sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
