	   KUALA LUMPUR, Thurs. - The four companies given the concession
to manage solid waste disposal in the country have until December
to take over from the local authorities.
	   Housing and Local Government Minister Datuk Dr Ting Chew Peh
said today it was imperative for the four to speed up the signing
of the interim agreement with over 90 local authorities for the
takeover.
	   Ting said the interim agreement would be in force until the
Government finalised the concession deal with the four companies,
and the proposed Solid Waste Management and Cleansing Bill was
tabled.
	   ``I don't want to speculate ... By December, the concessionaires
will sign the interim agreement with the local authorities,'' he
said when asked what action would likely be imposed on the
concessionaires which failed to comply with the directive.
	   Ting spoke to reporters after witnessing the signing of a
distributorship agreement between Acetai Corporation Sdn Bhd and
Japan's Meiji Milk Products Co Ltd.
	   The four concessionaires are DRB-Hicom Group's subsidiary Alam
Flora Sdn Bhd, Northern Waste Industries, Southern Waste Management
Sdn Bhd and MMC Engineering.
	   Southern Waste Management is to manage solid waste disposal in
Malacca, Negri Sembilan and Johor, while Alam Flora is responsible
for the central region comprising Kelantan, Trengganu, Pahang,
Selangor and Kuala Lumpur.
	   The northern region comprising Penang, Perak, Perlis and Kedah
would be managed by Northern Waste Industries and MMC Engineering
would manage the task in Sabah, Sarawak and Labuan.
	   ``Besides the takeover process, the Housing and Local Government
Ministry will also monitor the quality of services provided by the
concessionaires.''
	   On the number of local authorities who have signed the interim
agreement with the concessionaires, he said so far Alam Flora had
taken over solid waste management from Kuala Lumpur City Hall while
Southern Waste was now managing solid waste for the Johor Baru City
Council and Johor Baru Central District Council.
	   ``Alam Flora is now in the midst of taking over solid waste
management from the local authorities of Petaling Jaya and Kajang
while Northern Waste is discussing with Ipoh Municipal Council,''
he said.
	   
</TEXT>
