<HEADLINE>
PSA takes steps to combat Millennium Bug effect, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
PSA takes steps to combat Millennium Bug effect, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Port of Singapore Authority (PSA) has taken a number of
steps to combat the possible adverse effects of the Millennium Bug
problem.
	   Dr Robert Chin, head of the IT Infrastructure department at PSA
Corporation, said the port's 14 million TEUs (twenty-foot
equivalent units) handled in 1997 were highly dependent on
extensive use of sophisticated IT, and therefore vulnerable.
	   The port's operations and customer links are highly computerised
and supported by sophisticated equipment control systems.
	   However, he said, the PSA had to be concerned about systems
outside its control, including those of customers, suppliers,
public utilities, government and trade agencies, other port's and
ship's navigation.
	   Accordingly, PSA had set up a high level committee, supported by
task forces and technical testing procedures. On the IT front, they
had been downsizing systems since 1984 and were phasing out legacy
systems.
	   Despite resource problems and the readiness of others, Dr Chin
said the PSA was on track to verify all engineering systems by
mid-1999, had all IT systems fully tested within the same period
and instal comprehensive corporate wide contingency planning.
	   Dr Chin was speaking at a ``Year 2000: Challenges in the
Shipping and Transport Industry'' conference in Singapore on June
9.
	   Speaking at the same conference, its chairman Robin Guenier said
the inability of most current computing systems and microprocessor
chips to cope with the transition from 1999-2000 could threaten
business survival and the provision of basic services, with
incalculable social and political consequences.
	   Guenier, one of the world's leading experts in the century date
change, warned business and political leaders that only they could
determine priorities, provide resources and get things done.
	   ``Yet a recent survey in the UK indicated that only about 28 per
cent of the anticipated cost of a comprehensive solution had been
incurred, although most major systems had to be fixed before the
end of 1998.
	   ``The survey also suggested that the position was generally
worse in the world as a whole,'' he said.
	   Geunier felt that many found the whole phenomenon almost
impossible to believe. Businesses were very wary of the huge costs
involved while some in the computer industry found the subject
rather dull and were reluctant to become involved in implementing
solutions.
	   In tackling on board operations, Captain Phil Davies of Chevron
Shipping stressed the importance of a structured approach and
demonstrated the way his company had gone about the work.
	   In striving for compliance, he said Chevron emphasised the vital
importance of close liaison with manufacturers and those in the
supply chain, particularly customers and port authorities.
	   A worldwide airfreight and seafreight business, operating from
270 sites in 60 countries, had to pay particular attention to the
supply chain, according to Markus Heyer, a director of Panalpina.
	   Presenting the forwarders' perspective, Heyer said his company's
activities were conditioned by suppliers, third party logistics,
manufacturers, carriers, warehouses and Customs authorities.
	   This meant that awareness, dialogue and cooperation were vital
if forwarding businesses were to survive and prosper.
	   The legal aspects of the millennium problem were covered by
Steven Hazelwood, of Ince &AMP; Co in Singapore, who said that failure
to achieve compliance rendered operators of ships and shore
installations and manufacturers more vulnerable to claims and
attempts to exclude or limit liability.
	   ``It is essential to exercise due diligence under the Hague and
Hague- Visby Rules,'' he said. He noted there were implications for
contractual rights and tortious liability, limitation of liability
and the effects on insurance, ship finance, sale and purchase and
new buildings.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
