<HEADLINE>
ROC: Allow auditors to do their jobs, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
ROC: Allow auditors to do their jobs, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Roziana HamsawiASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Registry of Companies (ROC) will be conducting on-going
checks on both private and public companies which have terminated
the services of their auditors before their appointment periods
expire and hire new ones to replace them.
	   The checks, said registrar Datuk Ramly Ali, is to ensure that
these terminations were carried out sincerely to protect the
companies' interests and in accordance with the law.
	   If this is violated by any company, legal action such as taking
the company or its directors to court will be carried out, he said
in a press statement released yesterday.
	   It has been known, said Ramly, that some companies have
terminated the services of their auditors before the expiry of
their appointment periods when the auditors have questioned the
validity of their accounts and given ``qualified opinions'' on the
accounts.
	   The ROC has advised all companies that they must let their
auditors do their jobs in a professional manner to ensure that the
public and investors' confidence in their companies are maintained.
	   This is in line with the concept of transparency and good
corporate governance, Ramly said.
	   He said that in difficult times like this, most companies are
facing financial liquidity problems, and in such a scenerio, some
auditors have questioned the validity of some financial
transactions and asset assessments undertaken by the companies.
	   There are cases where the auditors could not validate some
suspicious transactions worth millions of ringgit.
	   ``These auditors then make a report to the ROC based on Section
174 (8) of the Companies Act 1965, and consequently the directors
of the company concerned may have not been pleased with the report,
thus they fire the auditors,'' he said.
	   Ramly said such termination can only be done in accordance with
the procedure stipulated under Section 172 (4)-(12) of the
Companies Act 1965.
	   Under this section, an auditor can only be fired or terminated
through a resolution passed by not less than a three-quarter
majority vote by the shareholders at the company's annual general
meeting or extraordinary general meeting.
	   The notice for the termination must also be forwarded to the
auditors concerned and to the ROC.
	   The concerned auditors also have the right to be heard and make
a written representation to be distributed to all shareholders and
be tabled at the meeting.
	   Failure to do this will result in the termination of the
auditors to be regarded as not lawfully valid, and the directors
responsible can be fined up to RM5,000.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
