Consultation paper ready in September, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Consultation paper ready in September, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE consultation paper on the compensation scheme for clients of
collapsed brokerages will be issued this September, Securities and
Futures Commission (SFC) executive director David White says.
	   ``We are now studying different compensation- insurance schemes
to see how we can come up with a better one in Hong Kong,'' Mr
White said yesterday.
	   The recent failure of various brokerages, including C A Pacific
Securities, had prompted the commission to develop a long-term
scheme to compensate clients of collapsed brokerages.
	   ``We are aiming at a compensation scheme that is much better
than the current one,'' Mr White said.
	   He said the problem of whether margin account clients should be
included in the compensation scheme would be tackled after the
consultation period.
	   Mr White also dismissed suggestions that a ``super regulator''
should be formed in Hong Kong over the next five years. There have
been recent suggestions that the two existing industry watchdogs,
the SFC and the Stock Exchange of Hong Kong, should be merged to
oversee all regulatory matters.
	   But despite the success of establishing super regulators in
other countries, Mr White said the situation in Hong Kong was
different from those prevailing in other countries.
	   He added the SFC had made substantial progress in its work in
previous years.
	   ``We have increased the number of cases that we've handled.'' He
also raised concerns about the various risks facing Asia this year,
such as the political atmosphere in Indonesia, prospects of a yuan
devaluation and the slump of the yen and its corresponding impact
on the region.
	   
</TEXT>
