<BODY>
<SLUG> NIP-THE-RICE-PROBLEM sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nip the rice problem in the bud, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Nip the rice problem in the bud, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE increase in the price of rice has caused many angry words to
be spoken recently. Having learnt, perhaps, from the recent sugar
and water problems, the authorities have done fairly well in coming
out quickly to cool rising tempers and make a few things clear.
Firstly, it does seem as if the Federation of the Malaysia Consumer
Associations (Fomca) owes Padiberas Nasional Bhd (Bernas) an
apology for accusing Bernas of being the cause of the price
increase. Secondly, price increases can come about as a result of
profiteering and not necessarily as a result of the economic
problems facing the nation. And thirdly, the country needs a more
permanent solution to the rice problem.
	   Bernas managing-director Mohd Ibrahim Mohd Nor on Monday
dismissed Fomca's allegations than the company was to be blamed for
rice that has become dearer in recent weeks. As a ``small
supplier'' - Bernas supplies about 18 per cent of the rice in the
domestic market - it's role in the price structure is minimal. In
Ibrahim's own words, ``We can't shake the market''. Wagging a
finger at Fomca, Bernas at the same time pointed its finger at rice
wholesalers and retailers, who might have taken advantage of the
situation to push prices. Poor harvests worldwide due to the
current weather phenomenon has also been identified as the case for
the price increase. Since early last month, prices of home-grown
rice has gone up by 21 per cent while that of imported varieties
are now 52 per cent more expensive.
	   The Agriculture Ministry came out quickly to announce that an
investigation into these allegations will be conducted. Its
minister, Datuk Amar Dr Sulaiman Daud, seems to share Bernas' view
that profiteering could be the main factor behind the rice price
rise. He said when Deputy Prime Minister and Finance Minister Datuk
Seri Anwar Ibrahim announced last December the price increase for
padi, Anwar specifically stated that it would not result in an
increase in the retail price of rice. These are very reassuring
points, indeed, and millions of rice-eaters in this country would
want to know who has been trying to make money out of their misery
and their already diminishing purchasing power. Punishing the
culprits would seem to be quite important, as the Government would
certainly not want a repeat of the sugar issue to depress consumer
sentiment further.
	   Getting to the bottom of the issue, however, will require the
authorities to go well beyond finding and punishing the profiteers.
The ministry, together with Bernas and other industry players,
needs to look at the long-term issues facing the rice industry.
This is a good time to debate once more the merits of
self-sufficiency. Currently, Malaysia imports 65 per cent of its
rice requirements from Thailand, Vietnam, India, Pakistan and
Taiwan, valued at RM700 million a year. This includes 2,000 tonnes
of Japanese rice from the US. Such figures could easily surpass RM1
billion by the year 2000 if steps are not taken to improve local
rice production.
	   If self-sufficiency is not possible or critical, the options
available must be studied carefully and implemented as soon as
possible. One is to encourage Bernas to start massive rice
cultivation projects abroad and import the rice into the country.
The immediate disadvantage of this is that while the imported rice
from Bernas' own fields overseas would be cheaper than other
imports, the nation will be moving even farther away from
self-sufficiency. Production and supply would also be vulnerable to
external factors that Malaysia would have very little control over.
	   Another option is to make rice an item of barter trade that
could also help reduce the overall import bill for food.
	   The most basic of the actions that the authorities must take is,
of course, to ensure that the enforcement division carries out its
tasks without fail. Certain rice grades, for example, are
controlled items. With very efficient enforcement, a problem can be
addressed before it becomes an issue.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
