	   CLEAR ENOUGH? ... With the opening of the RM9 billion Kuala
Lumpur International Airport in Sepang less than three weeks away,
improvement works are being undertaken on the airport's signages to
ensure that they are clear enough for passengers.
	   At several strategic locations within the airport, signages have
been enlarged so passengers will not `feel lost'.
	   Malaysia Airport (Sepang) Sdn Bhd general manager Muhammad Adnan
Yahya said the changes were made after several ``advance
passengers'' complained during trials that they got ``lost''
because there was not enough signages or the signages were too
small.
	   ``Most of the changes were made at important locations such as
at the Contact Pier, Satellite A and the arrival hall building,''
he told the New Straits Times yesterday.
	   Malaysia Airports Berhad managing director Datuk Khairuddin
Ibrahim said, however, that ``too many signages would make this
airport too similar to the Sultan Abdul Aziz Shah International
airport in Subang''.
	   Yet, one visitor noted: ``There needs to be more signages. I
feel lost just entering the airport.''
	   Temporary paper signages such as the ones shown here have also
been put up at KLIA before permanent signages are put up.
	   Apart from enlarging the signages, they have also been colour
coded to differentiate between domestic and international travel.
	   
</TEXT>
