<SLUG> BANKS-HEALTHY-AGENCY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Banks healthy: rating agency, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Banks healthy: rating agency, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   NON performing loans (NPLs) would have to jump to 10 per cent of
the total before the profitability of banks in Hong Kong were
undermined, international ratings agency Fitch IBCA said yesterday.
	   But the gloomy outlook for property values and the rising levels
of unemployment could result in the individual ratings of some
banks having to be reviewed, the agency said.
	   In an analysis of the financial health of banks in Hong Kong,
Fitch IBCA calculates that 2 per cent of total loans are currently
non-performing and that banks have set aside reserves to cover
approximately 20 per cent of these non performing loans (NPLs).
	   In a clear reflection of the strength of banks' balance sheets,
the agency said that assuming a loss rate of 30 per cent, NPLs
would have to rise to 10 per cent of total loans for the banks to
report a negative return on their equity.
	   ``This reflects the remarkably strong and liquid balance sheets
of banks in Hong Kong and their good profitability. If Japanese
banks were faced with a similar charge, 40 per cent of their
capital would disappear,'' the report says.
	   Fitch IBCA's analysis of banks assumes a ratio of loans to
assets of 50 per cent, an equity to assets ratio of 10 per cent,
average interest rates of 11 per cent and a tax rate of 12 per
cent.
	   A recent Hong Kong Monetary Authority survey showed banks had a
loan to valuation (LTV) ratio of just over 50 per cent. This
suggests that even if property prices were to fall by half from
their peak, most loans would still be fully secured.
	   Defaults on residential mortgages have also been very low: 0.04
per cent of loans overdue by three months for the period to the end
of last September.
	   ``As our analyses show, the sound condition of banks in Hong
Kong means that they are well able to absorb a rise in NPLs to as
much as 10 per cent without too much damage. These strengths have
been factored into our credit ratings. However, even if banks can
absorb the losses, their performance may be significantly
affected,'' Fitch IBCA says.
	   
</TEXT>
