<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Power will stay on for England-Tunisia game
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MILFORD, England (AP) _ Residents of two small villages in
central England will get to watch Monday's England-Tunisia World
Cup opener after an electricity company decided against going ahead
with power cuts.
	   An East Midlands Electricity official said Friday blackouts in
the villages of Milford and Lea would be rescheduled following
angry protests.
	   ``In the light of comments received from customers over the last
few days we have now arranged for the work to be carried out at
another time,'' said EME manager Keith Stanyard.
	   ``We will also be doing our utmost to ensure that further
planned interruptions do not coincide with World Cup matches.''
	   Jeanette Fallon, who lives in Milford, breathed easier.
	   ``We couldn't believe they would be that daft,'' she said. ``But
we are glad they have seen sense.''
	   (scw)	   
</TEXT>
