<HEADLINE>
Jobs lifeline for mainland, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Jobs lifeline for mainland, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   TERTIARY industries will provide much needed employment for the
large number of workers who are expected to lose their jobs as a
result of the economic restructuring on the mainland, said Stanley
Ko, chairman of the Hong Kong Coalition of Service Industries
(HKCSI).
	   The HKCSI is a highly autonomous body established within the
Hong Kong General Chamber of Commerce.
	   Mr Ko was leading a delegation on a visit to Beijing hosted by
the State Development and Planning Commission.
	   The 10-member delegation was received by Mr Bao Xuding,
vice-chairman of the State Planning and Development Commission
(SDPC). Before the government reshuffle Mr Bao was minister for
machinery.
	   ``It is clear that the Chinese leadership is committed to
carrying through the changes currently going on, both within the
government and in the wider economy in general, although that is
not without pains,'' said Mr Ko.
	   Apart from Mr Bao, the delegation also met and held discussion
with Mr Lan Shiliang, director of the Office of the Tertiary
Industry of the SDPC, as well as other government officials from
the State Economic and Trade Commission, the Bureau of Internal
Trade and the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Relations.
	   ``We have been encouraged by the positive message that China is
pressing ahead with measures to liberalise its service sector. This
will provide more opportunities for foreign investors. Being one of
the leading service economies in the world Hong Kong would have
much to gain from further market opening in China,'' said Mr Ko.
	   The Office of Tertiary Industry and the HKCSI also agreed to
continue fostering exchange and co-operation.
	   
</TEXT>
