<BODY>
<SLUG> A-BUDGET-FOR-WIDE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A budget for wide tax reforms, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
A budget for wide tax reforms, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   New taxes to yield Tk 350 crore: Tk 9320 crore deficit:
Incentives to investors: Computers, parts exempted from VAT: Cash
incentives for garments exports: Air-conditioners, refrigerators,
ceramic tiles, perfumes, toiletries to cost more: Import duty on
double-decker buses goes: Motor vehicle tax up
	   A four-tier tax rate structure, against the existing five-tier
tax rates for personal income tax, a series of incentives for
capital market and additional levies on a number of items consumed
by the affluent section are some of the highlights of the 1998-99
budget presented in the Jatiya Sangsad by Finance Minister SAMS
Kibria on Thursday in the absence of BNP members.
	   As a result of the fresh levies, air-conditioners,
refrigerators, ceramic tiles, perfumes, cigarettes, foreign toilet
soaps and toiletries as also imported furniture will be costlier.
	   Travel by taxis and three-wheelers may also cost more, because
of a hike in motor vehicle tax and fees as also a doubling of
supplementary duty on three-wheelers.
	   The budget by and large seeks to spare the common and poorer
section of the people from fresh tax burden.
	   The estimate for the National Board of Revenue
(NBR)-administered taxes has been placed at Tk 15,700 crore for
1998-99 as against the 1997-98 revised estimate of Tk 14,100 crore.
	   The net tax efforts will yield Tk 350 crore. The Finance
Minister, however, was optimistic that another Tk 385 crore of
additional revenue would accrue to the exchequer because of
intensive monitoring, supervision and procedural improvements. The
total revenue would grow by an additional Tk 865 crore owing to
natural revenue expansion, resulting from higher GDP growth.
	   The budget estimates the government's total expenditure for
1998-99 at Tk 30096 crore, as against 27070 crore in the revised
budget for the year 1997-98. The overall deficit for 1998-99 has
been placed at Tk 9320 crore of which Tk 5907 crore will be
financed by foreign aid and grants and the rest by domestic market
borrowings.
	   In his budget speech, the Finance Minister reiterated his faith
in market economy. To promote higher private investment, he sought
to give a boost to the capital market by providing a wide range of
incentives to investors, investing in stocks and shares.
	   With regard to the incentive for the capital market, the source
of income invested in purchase of shares in the primary and
secondary market will not be questioned provided the investor
retains the share for at least one year and pays tax at the rate of
seven and a half per cent on his investment.
	   Second, the Finance Minister proposed to exempt from tax income
from mutual fund accruing to the issuing companies, a benefit now
enjoyed by the Investment Corporation of Bangladesh (ICB). This
benefit has now been extended to all mutual funds.
	   Third, the discrimination in tax rates between publicly traded
financial institutions and non-financial business or industrial
enterprises has been removed.
	   All companies, including banks, insurance companies and other
financial institutions, which are listed with the stock exchange
will be subjected to a uniform tax rate of 35 percent. Finance
Minister Kibria hoped that a large number of banks and financial
institutions would be encouraged to list themselves with the stock
exchange as a result of this step.
	   Other incentives include a modification in the statutory
obligation of industries enjoying tax holidays to invest 30 per
cent of tax exempted income in government securities.
	   Kibria proposed that the dividends declared by such tax holiday
enjoying companies would count towards a statutory requirement of
investment. As for dividend income derived by individual tax
payers, the budget proposed that tax be deducted at source at the
rate of 10 per cent on the amount of dividend. This would be
treated as the final settlement of tax liability.
	   The Finance Minister hoped that more companies would be
encouraged to declare dividends which in turn would have a positive
impact on the share market.
	   The Finance Minister also proposed to exempt investment of
untaxed income in shares from primary and secondary market and for
expansion of existing units and repayment of industrial loan,
provided that tax be paid at the rate of seven and a half per cent.
	   The Finance Minister also proposed to simplify the provision for
filing returns under self-assessment scheme for private limited
companies by limiting the number of conditions to and extending the
provision beyond the financial year 1998-99.
	   The two conditions are that the income declared must be higher
by 10 per cent over the assessed income last year and the minimum
tax must be at least Tk 25,000.
	   Other measures on the direct tax front include a provision of
random selection of 10 per cent of the returns certified by
chartered accountants for auditing by taxmen and a revision of the
existing rates for withholding taxes.
	   The thrust of the budget proposal is to simplify the income tax
structure and widen the tax base through an increase in tax
compliance.
	   On the indirect tax front, the budget proposes to reduce the
highest rate of custom duty from 42.5 per cent to 40 per cent. This
reduction in duty involving a revenue loss of Tk 121 crore would
cover a wide range of consumption items, including processed
fruits, used clothes etc.
	   The budget also proposed a few steps in line with the government
policy to ensure speedy and hassle free clearance of imported and
exported cargo by reducing the discretionary powers of customs
officials.
	   The number of duty rates has been brought down to five from the
existing six rates. The new rates will be 7.5 per cent, 15 per
cent, 25 per cent, 30 per cent and 40 per cent.
	   The duty rates on a large number of raw materials and
intermediate products covering 852 H.S code are also proposed to be
reduced.
	   The items enjoying a reduction in duty rates include, food
flavour, tin can, crown cork and lug cap. A wide range of raw
materials and intermediate goods used for shrimp cultivation,
poultry and bakery will also attract lower rates of duty. The items
include active yeast (from 30 to 7.5 per cent), Vitamin B and its
derivatives (22.5 to 7.5 per cent) and animal and vegetable fats
and oil used as fish feed (42.5 to 30 per cent). The Finance
Minister said that although the reduction in duty rates would
result in substantial revenue loss, the government must make such
sacrifices to stimulate industrialisation, promote exports and
provide assistance to the agricultural sector.
	   In order to generate employment opportunities the budget
proposed to exempt computer and parts from the value added tax as
also from the existing customs duty of 2.5 per cent and 15 per cent
respectively. This duty concession will also extend to
uninterrupted power supply (UPS) imported along with a computer.
	   To help small, medium and large industries producing plastic
articles of everyday use, customs duty rates on primary polymer
have been brought down from 30 to 25 per cent. For expansion of
solar energy, photovoltaic generator has been exempted from customs
duty and value added tax in line with wind generators. A few
measures designed to support the leather industry include reduction
in duty rates on various pigments used in the industry from the
existing 15 per cent, 22.5 per cent and 30 per cent to a uniform
rate of 15 per cent. Duty on synthetic fibre is proposed to be
brought down from 2.5 to 0 per cent. Vat dyes from 15 to 7.5 per
cent, pigment from 15, 22.5 and 30 to 15 per cent and some spares
and components of the textile industry from 30 to 25 per cent.
	   To boost exports of readymade garments, cash incentives upto 25
per cent has been proposed.
	   The budget proposed to allow newspapers and periodicals to
import newsprint free of duty equal to the quantity of indigenously
produced newsprint purchased by them. To compensate the newspaper
industry for increased cost, the rate of government advertisement
is proposed to be raised by 30 per cent.
	   In order to reduce the cost of public transport, imports of
double-decker bus and taxi cabs will be free of duty. The duty of
on other types of buses and trucks is proposed to be slashed from
22.5 per cent to 15 per cent. Dumper and tipper trucks used in the
construction industry will invite only 7.5 per cent duty as against
the existing 22.5 and 15 per cent respectively. For the benefit of
the common man duty structure on various types of pulses has been
rationalised at a uniform rate of 7.5 per cent.
	   The VAT has been streamlined by introducing a participatory
system for determining annual sales volume for small traders and
retailers. The step is intended to facilitate voluntary compliance
by tax payers and collection of taxes without harassment at the
retail level. Nine more items have been included in the VAT net at
the retail level ranging from firearms, carpets, watches to ceramic
pieces, silver, brass, bronze and crystal glass c.i sheet and foam.
The system of tax collection procedure has also been simplified.
	   A number of new service sectors have also been brought under the
VAT network to widen the tax base. The services include, security
service, pathological laboratory, automatic or mechanised saw mill,
airconditioned garment shop and trade service, i.e wholesale deals
by importers and other domestic traders. Travel agency which had
been exempted from VAT has been brought into the network to bring
it on a par with entities rendering similar service.
	   Cigarettes will attract higher rates of supplementary duty. The
revised rates are 32 per cent, 49 per cent, 50 per cent and 51 per
cent. The Finance Minister justified the higher rates of duty on
the ground that smoking is injurious to health.
	   Other items on which the supplementary duty rates have been
hiked substantially include airconditioners (10 per cent to 40 per
cent), Refrigerators (15 per cent to 20 per cent), ceramic tiles
(10 per cent to 20 per cent) Cigarette papers (35 per cent to 45
per cent) , imported furniture (40 per cent), toilet soap and
toiletries (from 10 - 20 per cent to 40 per cent).
	   In part I of his speech, the Finance Minister took credit for
the healthy growth of the economy and expressed the government's
determination to implement reforms without delay to enable the
country to face fierce competition unleashed by the forces of free
market economy.
	   The actual growth rate achieved in 1997-98, he said, was 5.9 per
cent, which was preceded by a growth rate of 5.7 per cent in
1996-97. Such high growth rates, he asserted, were never achieved
for two consecutive years by any previous government.
	   The growth rates for the last two years indicated the success of
the government's economic policies, he claimed.
	   The Finance Minister also referred to the introduction of a new
index to measure the rate of inflation. According to the new index
in April, 1998, the inflation rate was 6.63 per cent as against
2.51 per cent in June 1997 and 6.65 per cent in June, 1996. The
increase in the inflation rate compared to last year, he said
quoting experts, was due to the unexpected shortfall in Aman
production.
	   However, he expressed the government's determination to curb any
long-term inflationary pressure and gave the assurance that
monetary and fiscal policies would be so geared so as not to allow
inflationary pressure to destabilise the macro-stability of the
economy.
	   The Finance Minister maintained that the performance of
Bangladesh economy was better than that of other developed
countries. In 1997-98 (July to April), exports accelerated by 15.75
per cent, 200 per cent higher than other developing countries. Taka
depreciated by about 5.7 per cent which was very modest compared to
the currency in India, Pakistan, South Korea , Thailand, Indonesia,
Malaysia, Nepal and Sri Lanka. Remittances by Bangladesh citizens
also increased by 7.5 per cent during the first eight months of the
current fiscal year.
	   The Finance Minister announced that arrangements for
privatisation of nine private sector enterprises in the current
year had been finalised. He also announced a proposal to issue
bonds worth Tk 60 crore in 1998-99 to compensate the losses of
banks for implementation of rehabilitation measures for sick public
sector industries.
	   He indicated that remision of interest of enlisted sick
industries which had borrowed upto Taka 50 lakh from the state
owned banks would be considered by a special committee headed by a
retired judge. The government would reimburse 50 per cent of such
remitted interest to banks.
	   Of the total proposed government spending of Tk 30,096 crore in
1998-99, the highest outlay of Tk 4596.14 crore would be on
education, while health and family welfare would account for Tk
2224.54 crore. Implementation of the second phase of the pay
commission recommendations would cost Tk 495.14 crore, including
development expenditure in the fiscal year 1998-99 and Tk 691.32
crore in 1999-2000. In total, a sum of Tk 2074.87 crore would be
spent for pay hike in three stages including pay increases in
development projects.
	   The allocation for defence is proposed to be raised to Tk
2786.43 crore in 1998-99 from Tk 2600.8 crore last year.
	   The Finance Minister justified the hike in defence expenditure
on grounds of national interests. He said that despite the increase
the total expenditure on defence constituted only about 1.8 per
cent of the GDP, which was much lower than defence spending in
other developing countries.
	   
</TEXT>
