<HEADLINE>
Mirvac tempts HK investors, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Mirvac tempts HK investors, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   AUSTRALIAN property developer Mirvac Group plans to offer at
least four residential projects in its home country to investors in
Hong Kong during the next few months.
	   The company is keen to take advantage of the low exchange rate
of the Australian dollar with the Hong Kong currency, as well as
the level of inflation and interest rates.
	   Wayfoong Property, a wholly-owned subsidiary of HSBC group, was
appointed sole agent in Hong Kong for Australia-listed Mirvac Group
last November.
	   Alice Lee, deputy manager of overseas marketing for Wayfoong,
said the mortgage rate for Australian property stands at 5.95 per
cent _ the lowest level for 20 years, while the currency remains at
a low level of A$1 to HK$4.6.
	   This was a good opportunity for Hong Kong investors to tap into
the Australian property market.
	   She said that after the Asian currency turmoil and the prolonged
slump in the local property market, Hong Kong investors were
expected to diversify their investment portfolios.
	   According to First Pacific Davies, Australian property owners
have never had it so good, and the omens look promising for the
immediate future.
	   Sydney property values rose by nearly half for the properties
traded there in 1997.
	   Despite the previous growth, Ms Lee said it was not too late to
enter the Australian property market as the country's economy was
surging strongly.
	   David Mann, corporate relations manager for Mirvac Group, said
the first project to be launched in Hong Kong would be the
Shoremark development in Sydney.
	   Mr Mann said rental yield for residential property in Australia
is around 5 to 6 per cent.
	   There are 95 Shoremark units available for sale during a sales
exhibition in Hong Kong from 12 to 15 June.
	   Prices range from A$310,000 for a one-bedroom apartment to
A$495,000 for a three-bedroom apartment.
	   
</TEXT>
