<HEADLINE>
AL hails budget: BNP protest procession baton charged, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
AL hails budget: BNP protest procession baton charged, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The new proposed national budget for the year 1998-99 presented
by Finance Minister SAMS Kibria in Parliament yesterday drew mixed
public reaction.
	   Different political parties including the ruling Awami League
and student organisations brought out processions in the city last
evening to welcome the budget while the opposition including the
BNP rejected it terming it an anti-people one.
	   Police arrested three BNP activists from a sit-in-demonstration
in between Ananda Community Centre and the BNP office. The BNP
activists started the sit-in-demonstration as police had
intercepted their procession brought out to protest the budget.
	   Dhaka city AL and Bangladesh Awami Jubo League (BAJL), the youth
wing of the ruling party brought-out a procession preceded by a
rally in front of its Bangabandhu Avenue office.
	   AL leaders Muzaffar Hossain Paltu, Nurul Fazal Bulbul, Fazlur
Rahman Fantomus and BAJL General Secretary Advocate Kazi Iqbal
addressed the rally.
	   Expressing their total support to the new budget, they
congratulated Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina and Finance Minister
SAMS Kibria for what they termed a ``development-oriented and
pro-people budget.''
	   Muzaffar Hossain Paltu also termed the budget a ``document of
success'' of the government, totally committed to leading the
nation towards prosperity.
	   Bangladesh Chhatra League ( S-P), the student front of the AL
brought out a procession welcoming the budget from the TSC of the
Dhaka University. BCL President Enamul Haq Shamim and General
Secretary Ishaq Ali Khan Panna led the procession which paraded
some parts of the campus last evening.
	   In a brief rally before the procession, the BCL leaders
expressed support to the budget on behalf of the student community.
	   Meanwhile, police dispersed a BNP procession, taken out against
the budget, by resorting to a mild baton charge and picked up three
supporters near the BNP's central office in the city last evening.
	   The police action left at least two activists slightly injured.
One of the injured was identified as Ashraf.
	   According to eyewitnesses, the BNP procession, led by the Dhaka
city BNP Convener Sadek Hossain Khoka, MP was stopped by police
about 100 yards from the BNP central office at Nayapalton at 7.05
pm.
	   At one stage, the BNP activists, chanting slogans against the
budget, pushed the police back about 10 yards. After the police
intervention, BNP leaders Amanullah Aman, MP, Najimuddin Alam, MP
and Salahuddin Ahmed started addressing the processionists to
condemn the police intervention.
	   After the speech of Salahuddin Ahmed, police resorted to a mild
lathi charge and dispersed the processionists. Later, Sadek Hossain
Khoka also addressed a handful of workers present there. Following
the police action, the processionists ran helter skelter for
safety.
	   Two of the three teenage boys, picked up by police from the
spot, were identified as Bachchu and Nizam. Police also tried to
pick up Sharif Hossain, a personal security staff of the Leader of
the Opposition in Parliament Begum Khaleda Zia from the spot, but
Sadek Hossain Khoka managed to avert it.
	   Leaders of the Ganotantrik Chhatra Oikyo (GCO), an alliance of
eight student organisations, at a rally at TSC last evening
criticised the government for what they called a budget that had
betrayed the student community. The GCO activists also took out a
procession which ended in front of the National Press Club.
	   
</TEXT>
