<HEADLINE>
Small drop in KMB passenger load amid downturn, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Small drop in KMB passenger load amid downturn, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KOWLOON Motor Bus Holdings (KMB) said yesterday average
passenger loading only dropped slightly in the first six months of
this year despite the Asian financial crisis.
	   ``The average passenger loading dropped slightly by 1 per cent
compared with the corresponding period in the previous year,'' said
John C C Chan, managing director of KMB.
	   Mr Chan said as the economic condition of Hong Kong weakens,
people tend to use a cheaper means of transportation such as a bus.
``Therefore, KMB could maintain the level of passenger loading at
last year's level.'' But he said the bus industry was not totally
immune from the effects of the regional turmoil. ``It is because
some people may be spending a longer time at home because of the
poor economic situation.'' Mr Chan said the average passenger
loading may further drop in the coming weeks as people were staying
home to watch the World Cup.
	   ``We are confident that the overall passenger loading of 1998
could be maintained at last year's level because of the addition of
a series of routes after Chek Lap Kok airport commences service.''
He said the company would continue to seek opportunities on the
mainland. ``We are looking at development opportunities in the
mainland as the mainland is a large and potential market for the
company.''
	   
</TEXT>
