<HEADLINE>
High Court grants CA Pacific wind-up order, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
High Court grants CA Pacific wind-up order, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   David EvansASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE High Court of the First Instance has granted the Official
Receiver a Regulating Order for both CA Pacific Securities and CA
Pacific Finance with respect to the winding up of both companies.
	   The order is for the first meeting of creditors and
contributories to be held in order to appoint a liquidator and a
committee of inspection.
	   Coopers and Lybrand are the current provisional liquidators.
	   The winding-up of CA Pacific Finance Limited and CA Pacific
Securities Limited will also be regulated by the court under the
Companies Ordinance.
	   This week it was announced CA Pacific Securities' clients would
get an initial payment of $150,000 from the compensation fund _ a
record.
	   The Government, Securities and Futures Commission and the Stock
Exchange of Hong Kong agreed in January to relax both the
compensation rules and the limt on the amount in relation to the
default of CA Pacific Securities. They had determined that if the
usual $8 million limit were observed, the compensation that each
client might receive was likely to be very limited.
	   ``Under the current compensation rules,'' said a government
statement yesterday, ``the maximum compensation payable to
claimants against any single registered broker was $8 million. Even
with a flexible approach, claimant compensation would be limited,''
the statement added.
	   In January, due to the recent spate of brokerage collapses, it
was decided to increase the level of compensation fund resources.
	   ``In order to put investors hearts at ease,'' Secretary for
Financial Services Rafael Hui said at the time, ``we will increase
the compensation fund as well as making flexible arrangements. The
SEHK and the SFC will inject $150 million immediately and a further
$150 million each if necessary.''
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
