<HEADLINE>
Consumers may enjoy cheaper Super Grade rice, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Consumers may enjoy cheaper Super Grade rice, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Thurs. - Consumers stand to enjoy a lower price
for Super Grade rice once wholesalers nationwide come up with a new
recommended retail price equivalent to the price sold at Bernas
outlets and subsidiaries.
	   Although no time-frame was given, Domestic Trade and Consumer
Affairs Minister Datuk Seri Megat Junid Megat Ayob said the
industry players had agreed to come out with a revised price list
as soon as possible.
	   He said although there were no specifics on how much lower the
price would be, wholesalers had promised it would be lower than the
present price.
	   ``If they still increase the price, the Government is likely to
decide on whether to control the price of Super Grade rice. In
addition, the Government can take `administrative' action against
the wholesalers.''
	   He said at the moment, the Government would let market forces
determine the price instead of making it a controlled item.
	   Megat Junid said this after meeting Padiberas Nasional Bhd,
wholesalers, millers and retailers to discuss the cause of the
price increase in Super Grade rice, which is not
Government-regulated.
	   Bernas is selling a 10kg packet of super grade rice with five
per cent broken content for RM14, with 10 per cent broken content
for RM13.80, and the same packet with 15 per cent broken content
for RM13.
	   He said Bernas represented between 25 and 30 per cent of the
supply of local rice or 16.7 per cent of the total market in
Malaysia at the pre- wholesaling level.
	   He did not deny some millers might have taken advantage of the
situation by pushing up prices to between RM1.30 and RM1.60 per kg;
and some wholesalers have been selling at RM1.80 per kg.
	   These factors, among others, could be due to supply and demand,
transportation and labour costs.
	   The ministry would continue to monitor rice price movements, and
the Padi and Rice Price Control and Monitoring Division has been
told to prepare a report on local and imported super grade rice.
	   The only control on Super Grade rice is on its quality. It
should contain not more than 15, 10 and five per cent of
low-quality rice (beras hancur).
	   Standard Grade is a local produce which contains broken rice,
rice from unripened padi and permissible foreign bodies while
Premium Grade is local rice of moderate quality.
	   
</TEXT>
