<HEADLINE>
Exports during last two years highly encouraging: Kibria, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Exports during last two years highly encouraging: Kibria, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Exports from Bangladesh during the last two years is highly
encouraging compared to the average performance of the developing
countries, Finance Minister Shah AMS Kibria told the Parliament
yesterday. Presenting the budget for the fiscal 1998-99 in the
Jatiya Sangsad, Kibria said exports from Bangladesh in 1996-97 in
dollar terms increased by 13.8 per cent while it further
accelerated to 16.75 per cent in the July-April period of 1997-98
fiscal. 'The rate of growth of exports from Bangladesh is more than
200 per cent higher than that of the developing countries,'' he
said in his budget speech. Speaking about the import performance,
the finance minister said imports during the first six months of
the current fiscal year rose 2.21 per cent, however, he said,
imports of industrial raw materials during this period registered
an increase by 17.7 per cent. He said the deficit in the current
account balance during the period July-December of the fiscal
1997-98 decreased by 24.9 per cent compared to the corresponding
period last year.
	   Despite a sudden increase in food imports in the later half of
the current fiscal, Kibria said, there has been no deterioration in
the reserve situation of the country thanks to rapid increases in
exports. The finance minister said Bangladesh Bank was pursuing a
flexible exchange rate policy with a view to encouraging exports.
The exchange rate is being determined on the basis of daily index
of real effective exchange rate (REER), he said. Kibria referred to
the turbulent international economic climate decelerating growth of
world export in 1998 and said the growth rate of exports from
developing countries would drop to 7.4 per cent this year. Quoting
the IMF projections, he said exports from developing countries
increased by 10.8 per cent in 1997. According to the Bangladesh
Economic Survey, 1998, along with the budget, the total import bill
was US dollar 7,162 million during the 1996-97 fiscal year while
the same during the July-December period of the current fiscal was
US dollar 3,612 million.
	   During the July-March period of the current fiscal year, the
survey said, the total exports from Bangladesh rose to 3,764.71
million US dollar representing 15.89 per cent increase over the
same period of the previous year. The exports during this period
registered an increase by 31.2 per cent in the ready-made garments
sector, 28.11 per cent in the tea sector and 11.9 per cent in the
knitwear sector. According to the survey report, ready-made
garments and knitwear represented 73 per cent of the total exports
from Bangladesh during the period July-March in the current fiscal.
The survey report also said that raw jute, frozen food and chemical
products suffered decrease in exports by 18.36 per cent, 9.82 per
cent and 24.65 per cent respectively during the period.The survey
report indicated a positive development in the export trend of
leather which suffered decrease by 7.6 per cent during the 1996-97
fiscal. It came down to only 0.28 per cent during the first nine
months of the current fiscal.
	   However, the survey said, the growth rate of exports of
ready-made garments, especially the knitwear, saw a downtrend
during the current fiscal year due to withholding of GSP facility
by the European Union since January, 1997. Bilateral discussion and
a strong trade diplomacy pursued by the present government helped
extension of flexible GSP facilities up to December 31, 1998, under
the scope of derogation, the survey report also said. It also said
the total trade deficit during the first six months of the current
fiscal stood at US dollar 1,007 million while it was 1,341 million
during the same period in the previous year. This proves that trade
balance registered an improvement by 24.9 per cent, the report said
adding this improvement was the result of 18.8 per cent export
increase and 2.2 per cent import increase during the period.
	   Finance Minister Shah A M S Kibria, in his budget speech, said
the expatriate Bangladesh nationals remitted US dollar 1,475
million during the 1996-97 fiscal which registered an increase by
7.85 per cent during the first eight months of the current fiscal
year. 'The remittances from abroad are largely influenced by
international economic environment,'' he said adding that the
remittances by the Bangladesh nationals increased at a satisfactory
rate despite the slump in Southeast Asia.
	   
</TEXT>
