<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Ticket Scams, 1st Ld-Writethru,0768 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ticket troubles escalate at World Cup
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with organizers disclaiming responsibility, other
details and background &QL; 
 &UR; By LARRY SIDDONS &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ A growing international scandal over World Cup
tickets erupted on two new fronts Friday, with the tournament
organizers saying they were investigating two soccer federations
and a branch of their own marketing arm for possible roles in the
scams.
	   Michel Zen-Ruffinen, FIFA's acting general secretary, said
investigations were under way into the improper sale of tickets by
soccer officials in Cameroon and an unidentified South American
country.
	   The president of the Cameroon soccer federation, Vincent Onana,
was detained as he tried to leave his country with the national
team, the world soccer body said. He was placed under investigation
this week for embezzlement of public funds, accused of supplying an
English agency with 3,000 tickets worth dlrs 660,000.
	   Zen-Ruffinen refused to give details of the South American case,
saying that the federation had not yet been formally advised.
	   FIFA also was investigating a case in which a representative of
the marketing company ISL France ``apparently sold tickets he did
not have to individuals.'' ISL, the giant Swiss-based marketing
company which handles FIFA's sponsors and television negotiations,
owns a small part of ISL France, Zen-Riffinen said.
	   ``It's a rather serious issue'' involving several thousand
tickets, he said.
	   With some 12,000 Japanese fans still without tickets they had
been promised and other victims reported in Europe and South
America, leaders of FIFA and the French World Cup organizing
committee said they were ready to sue agents who sold tickets
illegally, or sold tickets they never had.
	   They said they had heard complaints from fans missing tickets in
the Netherlands, Belgium, Germany, England and Brazil, as well as
Japan.
	   ``I know we shall discover more situations in other countries,''
Zen-Ruffinen said.
	   At the same time, FIFA and the French organizers tried to
distance themselves from the scandal, repeatedly saying they had
followed the rules in distributing tickets and that the problem lay
with unscrupulous businesses and naive fans desperate for tickets.
	   ``There's some confusion here, and that is creating excuses for
the operators,'' said Isabelle Delaye, the organizing committee's
ticket chief. ``We should criticize them. They found the ideal way
of making money, by deceiving people.''
	   Jacques Lambert, the committee's managing director, said his
group had repeatedly warned fans not to deal with anyone but
licensed brokers and to beware of schemes that promised too much.
	   ``Any other agency, company, body, whatever, pretending they had
tickets, had no tickets whatsoever,'' Lambert said. ``We had a lot
of reminders about them, for people to be very careful. Clearly,
those warnings have not been heeded.''
	   FIFA defended the French committee, but confirmed there were
enough problems to force the federation to make drastic changes in
ticket policies before the next Cup in 2002, which is being
co-hosted by Japan and South Korea.
	   It also said some of the problems fans were encountering could
have started right in international soccer's backyard.
	   World Cup tickets are legally available through just three
sources _ FIFA and the organizing committee, national soccer
federations and 17 licensed ticket brokers around the world.
	   Those brokers have 150-200 licensed re-sellers, but officials
said at a 90-minute news conference that they did not known if the
agents dealing in phantom tickets were officially approved or from
outside the group.
	   While there were some ticket problems in 1990 in Italy and
supply rarely meets demand for World Cup tickets, there never have
been such widespread complaints.
	   The organizing committee printed almost 2.7 million tickets,
about 800,000 less than the record number sold for the 1994 World
Cup in the United States. Even though there are eight more teams
and 12 more games, the French stadiums are much smaller than the
big U.S. arenas.
	   With the Cup is back in the middle of soccer-mad Europe, there
has been increased pressure for the tickets available. The European
Union said the organizer's ticket-distribution plans were weighted
too heavily for French fans and sponsors, and ordered changes, but
the tickets remain the hottest thing on the market with all the
stadiums full.
</TEXT>
