<SLUG> YUAN-DEVALUATION-PEG sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yuan devaluation possible warns architect of peg, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Yuan devaluation possible warns architect of peg, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Teresa LeeASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ECONOMIST John Greenwood, the architect of the Hong Kong dollar
to the US dollar peg, says Hong Kong should be ready for a possible
devaluation of the yuan.
	   In the face of a slackening of the mainland's export and
domestic economy, the yuan may be devalued in the end, said Mr
Greenwood, chief economist of LGT Asset Management.
	   Mr Greenwood, however, said he expects the peg to remain stable
in face of a yuan devaluation despite statements from other
economists that the Hong Kong dollar will come under strong
pressure if Beijing devalues its currency.
	   ``The devaluation of the renminbi might mean a temporary
speculative attack on the Hong Kong dollar. I think it's much more
likely that such effects would be spread out over time,'' Mr
Greenwood said.
	   ``Over the last 15 years, the Hong Kong dollar has survived a 70
per cent depreciation of the renminbi. There is no reason why a
further adjustment of the renminbi should cause an adjustment of
the Hong Kong dollar in future,'' he said.
	   Mr Greenwood believes the yuan is likely to come under strong
pressure in 1999.
	   ``Gradually, I think we will see the mainland's trade surplus
diminish. And given the rather deflationary conditions in China at
the moment, the capital inflows to China may also be reduced, and
the overall balance of payments would be subject to pressure in
1999,'' he said.
	   He said Hong Kong should be well-prepared for a possible
devaluation of the yuan.
	   
</TEXT>
