<BODY>
<SLUG> UNITED-BINTANG-CONFIDENT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
United Bintang confident of 15pc increase in its exports, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
United Bintang confident of 15pc increase in its exports, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   IN times when most companies are struggling to keep their heads
above the water, United Bintang Bhd is confident of maintaining its
performance this year based on its bullish export business.
	   The reconditioned and used heavy equipment trader's export sales
nearly doubled to RM31 million for the year ended Dec 31, 1997,
from RM16 million in the previous year.
	   Executive director Gary Loh yesterday said: ``We are confident
our exports will increase by more than 15 per cent and account for
80 per cent of the turnover for the year ending Dec 31, 1998.''
	   In line with this, United Bintang is planning to open a sales
office in Dubai, United Arab Emirates.
	   ``The office in Dubai will cater for the company's export
business in Iraq, Iran, Africa and India.
	   ``We will be tapping into those countries as soon as the office
is set up,'' he added.
	   At present, United Bintang exports its reconditioned and used
heavy equipment - bought in Malaysia and Japan - to United States
and Canada.
	   ``We will be sourcing heavy equipment from Indonesia and
Thailand soon as prices of equipment have declined in these
countries due to the regional economic woes,'' he said.
	   Last year, United Bintang announced that it was going to export
equipment to Japan. However, due to the economic problems, the
company has decided to focus on expanding to the US and Canada.
	   ``In future, we will be concentrating on making the US our main
export market. But there is much to learn about the heavy equipment
market in the country.''
	   Loh was speaking after United Bintang's annual meeting in Kuala
Lumpur.
	   Currently, United Bintang exports reconditioned and used
equipment valued between RM70,000 and RM400,000.
	   In Malaysia, he said, the domestic reconditioned and used heavy
equipment market has shrunk at an alarming rate.
	   ``Due to the economic problems faced by the country, many
construction projects have been deferred or cancelled. As such, the
demand for heavy equipment has declined more than 70 per cent in
Malaysia.
	   ``Therefore, we have decided to increase exports to compensate
for the decline in business in Malaysia.''
	   United Bintang is the sole distributor of the Terex brand of
articulated trucks in Malaysia.
	   The trucks are manufactured by a Scottish company, Terex
Equipment Limited, which is the third largest manufacturer of
articulated trucks in the world.
	   To date, United Bintang has secured 20 per cent of the used
heavy machinery market in the domestic market.
	   On the company's plans to venture into property development in
Malaysia, Loh said United Bintang had put the diversification plan
on hold due to the economic downturn in the country.
	   United Bintang registered a group pre-tax profit of RM3.81
million for the year ended Dec 31, 1997 from RM7.57 million
achieved in 1996.
	   Its turnover fell 31 per cent to RM89.91 million from RM129.6
million previously while earnings per share fell to 13 sen from 29
sen.
	   
</TEXT>
