<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-Sri Lanka-New Zealand, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New Zealand needs 296 runs for victory
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with details at the end of the third day's play. No
pickup. &QL; 
 &UR; By CALLISTUS DAVY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) _ In a crucial third and final test, New
Zealand Friday faced a daunting target of 296 runs for victory
against host Sri Lanka.
	   After bowling Sri Lanka out for 282 runs in its second innings,
Sri Lanka batted cautiously and scored 10 without loss at close of
play on the third day.
	   New Zealand won the first cricket test and Sri Lanka leveled the
three-test series in the second test.
	   The home team, batting a second time with a 13 run lead on first
innings, got out half an hour before the day's scheduled close at
the Sinhalese Sports Club stadium.
	   Sri Lanka's total was boosted mainly through two half centuries
by Arjuna Ranatunga (64) and Romesh Kaluwitharana (88).
Kaluwitharana struck 8 fours in 146 balls, and defied the New
Zealanders in a last wicket stand of 71 runs with Muttiah
Muralitheran, who was unbeaten on 26.
	   Ranatunga in his role as skipper sustained the Sri Lankan
innings in the face of a collapse, taking the total from 36 for 4
and leaving the crease after a 102 run alliance for the fifth
wicket with Hashan Tillekeratne (40).
	   Ranatunga had nine fours in his knock which came in 96
deliveries. The Sri Lankan skipper was particularly harsh on the
spinners but in a lapse of concentration stepped out to hit Mark
Priest, only to drive the ball into the hands of Chris Cairns at
mid off.
	   Left arm spinner Daniel Vettori took a career best 6 for 64 to
dismiss Sri Lanka for 282. Sharing the new ball with Chris Cairns,
Vettori stepped into action as early as his second over when he
claimed the wicket of Marvan Atapattu who was trapped leg before
for 5.
	   The 19 year old Vettori then got rid of Mahela Jayawardena for
11 and Aravinda de Silva for 3, making Sri Lanka face trouble at 36
for 4. Cairns earlier put New Zealand in front by making Sanath
Jayasuriya touch a moving delivery only to be caught behind by a
diving Adam Parore in front of first slip. Jayasuriya made just 8
runs.
	   Vettori improved on a previous best of 5 for 84, also against
Sri Lanka at Hamilton, New Zealand in 1996-1997. Vettori also
accounted for middle order batsman Hashan Tillekeratne who was
bowled by a full length ball for 40.
	   His last two wickets were that of tail enders Pramodya
Wickremasinghe for a duck, and Niroshan Bandaratilleke for 7.
	   (cd-of-aks)
</TEXT>
