<HEADLINE>
Prime Success has expansion in mind, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Prime Success has expansion in mind, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Patricia LeeASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SHOEMAKER and coffee shop operator Prime Success International
Group will continue to expand its retail business on the mainland
this year by opening up to 220 more outlets.
	   Prime Success will be able to post satisfactory profit growth in
the first four months of this year, managing director Keeper H M
Chen said yesterday.
	   However, he admitted total orders of OEM (original equipment
manufacturing) footwear from Japan would fall 2 per cent this year
as the economy slowed.
	   To reach a 70 per cent sales growth target in retail business
this year, Prime Success plans to open 220 more outlets this year
throughout the mainland.
	   The new shops will be comprise of directly owned outlets,
associates, franchises and agents. The firm already has 580
mainland outlets.
	   The footwear retail and wholesale business made up 50 per cent
of the company's sales last year.
	   ``Compared to the wholesale business, the retail business can
provide a better profit margin for the company,'' said Mr Chen.
	   He added that the margin for footwear was on average 27 per
cent.
	   The company is also considering joining a footwear production
project in Shanghai.
	   ``We are still in a discussion but we hope to finalise a deal
this year,'' said Mr Chen.
	   The company plans to open 15 coffee shops this year, bringing
the total to 200 by the year 2005.
	   Mr Chen expects the turnover in each coffee shop to reach US$5
million (HK$39 million).
	   Under the company's expansion plan, a total of 600 coffee shops
will be opened in Japan and 82 in Taiwan.
	   Mr Chen said negotiations are underway for the opening of
outlets in Beijing, Tianjin and Nanjing.
	   
</TEXT>
