<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup-Japan-Tickets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Shortfall of 6,200 tickets for World Cup reported in Japan
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japanese travel agents say they are short 6,200
tickets for the national team's World Cup match against Argentina
on Sunday, a news report said Friday.
	   The Kyodo News agency report, citing the Japan Association of
Travel Agents, said that 14,700 soccer fans had reserved and paid
for tours to France for Japan's opening match.
	   Several of the tours were canceled Thursday because thousands of
tickets had not been delivered before fans were to leave for the
games, meaning that the number of fans needing tickets had dropped
to 9,500.
	   JATA said Friday that travel agents reported they had received a
total of 3,300 tickets to the match _ leaving another 6,200
Japanese without the tickets they had paid for.
	   For Japan's second match against Croatia on June 20 in Nantes,
the association said travel agents had received an additional 120
tickets, but added that they do not expect that number to increase
much.
	   Ticket shortages are also being reported in a number of
countries other than Japan and some have reportedly blamed the
World Cup organizers for not providing enough tickets to the
official agents.
	   The organizers, however, have denied they were responsible for
Japan's ticket trouble, suggesting that Japanese travel agents
which had ordered tickets from unauthorized agents might have been
tricked.
	   Also Friday, the Football Association of Japan was quoted by
Kyodo as saying it will sell tickets for Japan's matches if the
team advances beyond the first round-robin.
	   The association will offer the tickets, which will be allocated
by the World Cup organizing committee, as part of a tour package
for Japan's first match in the final round.
	   The shortage of tickets has outraged people in Japan. Incensed
fans at Tokyo's Narita International Airport on Thursday shouted at
tour company representatives and demanded an explanation for the
missing tickets.
	   (may-jc)
</TEXT>
