<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Elections </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cambodian commission certifies 39 parties to run in election
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ Cambodia's National Election
Committee announced Friday that all 39 registered political parties
have officially qualified to contest the elections scheduled for
July 26.
	   Kassie Nou, vice chairman of the committee, said the official
approval was granted after all the parties fulfilled all
requirements stated in electoral law.
	   Those approved include the FUNCINPEC party of deposed Co-Premier
Prince Norodom Ranariddh, the main rival to the country's
strongman, Hun Sen, and his Cambodian People's Party.
	   Hun Sen has tried to place as many obstacles as possible in the
path of his rival, and the election committee is widely considered
to have been handpicked to favor Hun Sen's party.
	   One threat that has been hanging over Ranariddh's head is that
he would be barred from running under a statute of the political
party law that prohibits any party from fielding its own
independent army and controlling an autonomous piece of territory.
	   When Ranariddh was deposed by Hun Sen in a coup d'etat last
July, some of the prince's loyalists formed a resistance force and
settled into an enclave on Cambodia's northern border.
	   Government troops failed to dislodge them, and negotiations to
have them rejoin the national army have so far not been successful.
	   ``All 39 parties have met the requirement, so did the FUNCINPEC
party,'' Kassie Nou said. ``What we decided was based on electoral
law, we don't deal with the political party law.''
	   He also said that the period during which objections could be
lodged with the committee had expired, so any future complaints
about political parties should be forwarded to the government, not
the committee.
	   A committee official said Thursday that the number of eligible
Cambodians who have registered to vote in July's election has
surpassed the 80 percent mark and is expected to top 90 percent
when the registration process ends next week.
	   In three weeks of registration, nearly 4 million people, or
80.45 percent of the 5.6 million people eligible to vote, had
already received voting cards, said Prum Nhean Vichet.
</TEXT>
