	   TAIPING, Thurs. - In a bid to get rid of transvestites who mar
the town's image because of their indecent behaviour at the scenic
Taiping Lake Gardens, the Taiping Municipal Council will install
brighter lights at their popular haunts.
	   Larut Matang and Selama assistant district officer Mohd Sabri
Yusoff, who is also the deputy chairman of the LMS committee to
tackle social problems, said certain irresponsible elements had
used catapults to smash the streetlights.
	   ``The new bright lights hopefully will deter vice activities,''
he said, adding that the indecently dressed transvestites harassed
visitors to the gardens.
	   Mohd Sabri said 10 transvestites had so far been picked up in
three raids conducted recently at the gardens.
	   Meanwhile, Mohd Sabri said 75 people, including 22 students,
were also picked up during the raids to clean up the town's sleazy
image.
	   He said the raids were conducted yesterday and on May 23 and May
30 by 35 officers from the various government departments and
agencies in the district.
	   They included the police, Perak Islamic Religious Department,
Taiping Municipal Council, LMS Education Department, Youth and
Sports Department and the LMS district office.
	   Mohd Sabri said the raids were also conducted at the Taiping bus
terminal, mini-cinemas, pubs and karaoke centres.
	   Some of the couples detained for khalwat were handed over to the
Perak Islamic Religious Department to be charged under the
Enactment for Indecent Behaviour in Public Places.
	   Mohd Sabri said if found guilty under the enactment, the couples
could be fined RM1,000 or face six months' jail.
	   
</TEXT>
