<SLUG> BC-Kosovo-War Crimes </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. war crimes tribunal to send investigators to Kosovo
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JENIFER CHAO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) _ The Yugoslav war crimes tribunal
said Friday it is sending investigators to the troubled Serbian
province of Kosovo to check out reports of possible atrocities.
	   Details of the visit, to take place in the coming weeks, were
not disclosed. Tribunal chief prosecutor Louise Arbour said the
U.N. court's investigation aimed to ``send an appropriate signal to
both belligerents the necessity that they obey by the laws and
customs of war.''
	   The investigation has been backed by the United States, said
David Scheffer, the roving U.S. ambassador for war crimes issues.
	   ``We've been extremely focused on the role the tribunal can and
might be able to play in investigating what appears to be very
serious criminal activities taking place in Kosovo,'' he said.
	   Ethnic Albanians, who comprise 90 percent of the southern
province's population, are demanding independence from Serbia.
	   More than 250 people have died during clashes between government
forces and the Kosovo Liberation Army, the armed wing of the
Albanian independence movement.
	   Scheffer added it is ``imperative'' that Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic provides all the necessary authorization to
allow investigators into the province.
	   ``It has been delayed for too long and it is indicative of his
(Milosevic) entire approach to the issue,'' said Scheffer, who was
attending the inauguration ceremony of the tribunal's third
courtroom.
	   Arbour said there are clear indications that an armed conflict
is in progress in Kosovo, and the tribunal has jurisdiction to
prosecute perpetrators of possible war crimes.
	   The tribunal was established by the U.N. Security Council in
1993, and its jurisdiction covers all serious violations of
international humanitarian law committed in the former Yugoslavia
since 1991.
	   Work at the tribunal has intensified as the number of suspects
in custody increased almost threefold in the last seven months,
said Judge Gabrielle Kirk McDonald in her speech during the
inauguration ceremony.
	   The third court, funded by the U.S. and Dutch governments, aims
to ease the ``judicial congestion'' at the court.
	   The U.N. court has issued some 20 public indictments against 59
people, plus a number of sealed indictments. There are 27 suspects
in custody.
	   Its top suspects are former Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic
and his wartime military chief, Gen. Ratko Mladic, indicted but
both still at large.
	   ``We strive to establish as judicial fact the full details of
the madness that transpired in the former Yugoslavia,'' said
McDonald.
	   ``By recording the capacity for evil in all of us, we hope that
in the future we will recognize the warning signs and act with
sufficient speed and determination to prevent such bloodshed,'' she
added.
	   Meanwhile, a four-member Bosnian Serb delegation headed by two
deputy prime ministers left Banja Luka on Friday to visit Bosnian
Serb suspects being held in the tribunal's cell block here.
	   (jc)
</TEXT>
