<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Iran-Foreign Invasion,0612 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Iranian team has big impact on quiet French town
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ANWAR FARUQI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   YSSINGEAUX, France (AP) - In this quiet little town in the heart
of France where the church bell tolls the hours and Paris is as far
as most residents have ever traveled, the arrival of Iran's World
Cup team has been something of a foreign invasion.
	   None of the residents have seen the players since they arrived
Sunday in this town of 7,000. They are holed up under tight
security in a 19th century chateau that is now a famous pastry
school.
	   But in town, posters of the team and paper Iranian flags are
plastered on every shop window, at the bookstore one can buy a
video of ``Iran's remarkable women'' and boarding houses are full
of journalists and drivers for the Iranians. At the local
laundromat the red-white and green uniforms of the players are
going through the spin cycle.
	   At the town hall, a bus load of curious senior citizens inspect
the month-long exhibition of precious Persian carpets and
handicrafts. Some buy the poems of Omar Khayyam translated into
French, or leaf through books by other Iranian poets and writers.
	   The show kicked off with an Iranian movie and a discussion by
Shahla Sherkat, an Iranian woman journalist, and will close June 17
with an Iranian dinner, a concert and poetry recitation.
	   The Iranians wanted a quiet place where their players could be
protected from Western influences. Local women, such as media
coordinators, were asked to dress modestly in the presence of
players.
	   ``We wanted to put Yssingeaux on the map, and having a World Cup
team stay here was the best way of doing it,'' said the town's
deputy mayor, Jacques Barrot.
	   Yssingeaux is not the only small town in France with an Iranian
connection. Nearly 20 years ago the small town of Neauphle le
Chateau near Paris was the last home of the late Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini before he returned to Iran to lead the Islamic revolution
that overthrow the U.S.-supported shah.
	   ``Some people like the Iranians here, and others don't. That's
just the way the French are,'' said Jean-Claude Rerole, proprietor
of the Cactus Sports shop in Yssingeaux. ``I, for one, think it's
very, very good for the town.''
	   The Iranians have brought business, but some residents don't
like the foreigners with their strange customs, and the media
invasion.
	   When Sherkat, the Iranian woman journalist, walked into town in
the Islamic head-dress that all women in Iran must wear by law,
heads turned and tongues wagged.
	   Iran's bad name in the West hasn't exactly helped.
	   Several Iranian dissidents have been assassinated in France
since the Iranian revolution, with the Tehran government thought to
have been behind the killings. As recently as 1996, Reza Mazlouman,
deputy education minister under the shah, was shot dead under
mysterious circumstances in Paris.
	   Even the woman on the cover of the video selling in Yssingeaux,
Iranian Vice President Massoumeh Ebtekar, was the strident
interpreter and spokeswoman for the militants who stormed the U.S.
Embassy in Tehran in 1979 and held 52 Americans hostage for 444
days.
	   Ever since Iran's moderate president, Mohammad Khatami, took
over as president last August, Iran has been trying to change its
international image. Iran's drive in Yssingeaux is part of that
effort.
	   ``We wanted to sow the seeds of Iranian goodwill in the heart of
France, in a virgin place like this town where it would grow,''
said Mohammad Navah, organizer of the exhibition in Yssingeaux.
</TEXT>
