<BODY>
<SLUG> NEW-MEASURES-TO-HELP sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New measures to help sick industries, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
New measures to help sick industries, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Finance Minister SAMS Kibria has proposed new measures in the
budget to resolve problems of sick industries.
	   He has proposed to issue bonds worth Tk 60 crore to compensate
the government-owned banks which will sustain losses arising out of
settlement of loans cases of sick industries.
	   The Finance Minister told Parliament yesterday that the problems
of the sick industries previously identified and listed by the
government would come under the purview of the new initiative.
	   Under it a borrower's case having up to Tk 50 lakh loans from
any government-owned bank would be considered by a special
committee to be set up. It would be headed by a retired judge.
	   The Finance Minister said the committee taking into
consideration the condition of a sick industry, previous relief, if
any, financial capacity, honesty and reputation of the concerned
borrowers would recommend a solution. It would have the power to
give remission of interest and penal interest of up to 100 per
cent.
	   The government would reimburse 50 per cent of the losses of
banks in such cases. The amount of money that the committee would
determine and the borrower would be asked to pay would be payable
in three years in not more than 36 monthly instalments.
	   In cases having loans of more than Tk 50 lakh, the compromise
would be arrived at based on the bank-client relationship in the
light of some broad guidelines.
	   Sponsors of those sick industries could also submit proposals
for rehabilitation of sick industries if there were prospects of
turning those sick industries into profitable ones.
	   The Finance Minister said that all government committees
relating to sick industries would be abolished once all decisions
relating to this initiative were implemented.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
