<HEADLINE>
Highest allocation for education sector, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Highest allocation for education sector, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The education sector is the highest recipient of the new budget
for fiscal 1998-99 with proposed increase of 9.4 per cent over the
revised allocation of the outgoing year.
	   In the new budget, allocation for the education sector has been
proposed to be raised to Tk 4596.14 crore against Tk 4199.98 crore
of the revised budget for 1997-98.
	   ``We are already receiving dividends of highest allocation in
the education sector,'' said Finance Minister SAMS Kibria,
presenting the national budget in Parliament yesterday.
	   He said the literacy rate has increased from 47 per cent to 51
per cent during the last two years.
	   ``For the first time in the history of Bangladesh, the majority
of the people are literate,'' he said amidst cheers from treasury
benches.
	   Kibria said the subvention for the salaries of the registered
and aided school teachers was revised for the first time along with
the revision of pay scale of the government employees.
	   The rate of subventions of teachers in the registered private
primary schools will be revised upward next fiscal year.
	   The Finance Minister proposed to raise the allocation for
libraries from Tk 2 crore to Tk 3 crore and for the scientific
laboratories equipment from Tk 3 crore to Tk 5 crore.
	   
</TEXT>
