<BODY>
<SLUG> 13.38-PC-RISE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
13.38 pc rise in defence spending, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
13.38 pc rise in defence spending, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The proposed defence allocation in the national budget for
1998-99 is about 13.38 per cent more than the outgoing fiscal year.
	   The net allocation for defence was Tk 2457.53 crore in 1997-98
while in the new budget for 1998-99, Tk 2786.43 crore has been
proposed for the sector, an increase of 13.38 per cent.
	   In the revised budget for FY 1997-98, the allocation was
increased to Tk 2600.8 crore.
	   However, the total budget for the Defence Ministry stands at Tk
2902.27 crore, including the allocations for Department of
Meteorology, Survey Department, SPARRSO, Freedom Fighters' Welfare
Trust, Cadet Colleges and Defence Division.
	   Total defence expenditure constitutes about 1.8 per cent of GDP
in 1998-99 fiscal.
	   To justify the increase, the Finance Minister in his budget
speech quoted the Human Development Report, 1997 as showing that
the average defence spending in all developing countries in 1995
stood at 3.1 per cent of GDP.
	   The defence expenditure as share of GDP in Bangladesh is less
than that of India (2.5 per cent), Pakistan (6.5 per cent) and Sri
Lanka (4.9 per cent).
	   Underscoring the point of internal security, Kibria proposed an
allocation of Tk 675.46 crore for the police force in 1998-99. It
was Tk 646.11 crore in the revised budget for 1997-98.
	   The annual budget for police has been raised by 30 per cent
compared to the allocation in the revised budget of FY 1995-96.
	   
</TEXT>
