<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nigeria, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Crippled during Abacha years, Nigerian opposition keeps fighting
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with police breaking up pockets of protesters with
tear gas; Edits throughout to conform and delete outdated
material. &QL; 
 &UR; By TIM SULLIVAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ Firing canisters of tear gas into the air,
riot police dispersed groups of protesters in Nigeria's commercial
capital Friday before the activists could converge for a mass
demonstration.
	   In the Yaba district on the city's north side, several vehicles
filled with riot police roared into position to block about 300
protesters from marching toward the area's main bus terminal.
	   Firing bullets into the air and tear gas at the crowd, the
police sent the demonstrators scurrying for cover.
	   Another group of between 500 and 600 anti-military activists
were dispersed with tear gas, witnesses said.
	   Their strength ravaged by years of government harassment, their
leaders in prison or exile, Nigeria's opposition movement defiantly
tried to pressed ahead Friday with plans a pro-democracy rally _
the first major test of the new military regime of Gen. Abdulsalam
Abubakar.
	   Elsewhere in Lagos, troops packed into transport trucks fired
their rifles into the air as their convoy rumbled through one
district of town, prompting residents to run to safety.
	   About 15 kilometers (10 miles) west of Lagos, a crowd of
students from the Lagos State College of Education clashed briefly
with police after running into the streets and setting tires on
fire, witnesses said.
	   Lagos Police Commissioner Abubakar Tsav said in a published
statement that protesters ``will be seriously dealt with.''
	   Fearing violence, the normally cluttered congestion of morning
traffic had fallen off to a trickle of vehicles as many people
stayed home to avoid a confrontation.
	   Early in the morning, about 60 youths marched through one Lagos
neighborhood, handing out pro-democracy leaflets and heading toward
a major bus terminal.
	   Some carried a large banner reading ``The Struggle Continues.
The Military Must Go. Abiola For President.''
	   Friday's protests were organized months ago to mark the
five-year anniversary of the annulment of the country's last
presidential elections on June 12, 1993, and to call for freedom
for Moshood Abiola, the imprisoned billionaire businessmen who is
believed to have won that vote.
	   But the demonstrations have taken on added significance, coming
just a few days after Abubakar was appointed leader of this
oil-rich but poverty-stricken West African country following the
heart attack death Monday of dictator Gen. Sani Abacha.
	   Key opposition leaders say with Abacha's death, now the entire
military leadership must relinquish its hold on the country.
	   ``Abubakar is becoming the reincarnation of Abacha,'' said Gani
Fawehinmi, a Lagos lawyer and anti-military activist leading the
call for protests.
	   He said expected few changes from Abubakar, who has already
infuriated the opposition by offering only a vague pledge to move
forward with Abacha's flawed democratic reform program.
	   Police sealed off some roads leading to the Lagos district of
Yaba, where opposition groups had hoped to converge for a mass
demonstration rally.
	   Clusters of police and army troops loitered along street corners
and key intersections in the city as they waited to see if the
demonstrations went ahead.
	   The authorities in the past have shown no reluctance to use
heavy force, including tear gas and machine gun fire to quell
protests in Nigeria.
	   Abacha's regime hobbled Nigeria's opposition movement with
brutal efficiency, arresting, imprisoning and torturing many
opposition leaders _ or driving them into exile.
	   These days, many demonstrations only attract a few hundred
protesters and strike calls are often completely ignored.
	   Trying to head off trouble ahead of Friday's rallies, the
government closed a Lagos technical college and a university and
shut down all primary and secondary schools in Lagos and Kwara
states, both important regions to the opposition movement.
 &UR; (tjs/ids/bk)
</TEXT>
