<BODY>
<SLUG> TAX-PROPOSALS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tax proposals basically sound: Muhit, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Tax proposals basically sound: Muhit, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Former Finance Minister AMA Muhit termed the proposed budget for
the 1998-99 fiscal a good one but he said that one would need to
scrutinise the budget documents in detail in order to make specific
comments on the proposed budget.
	   ``As I listened to the budget, it appeared to be a good one,''
Muhit told The Independent immediately after the budget speech of
the Finance Minister yesterday evening.
	   ``The taxation proposals are basically sound. It aims at
simplification of direct tax, reduction and rationalisation of
import tax, expansion of VAT coverage and higher realisation of
supplementary duties,'' the former Finance Minister said.
	   ``I am particularly happy for the attention paid to information
technology and energy development,'' Muhit said in his instant
reaction on the proposed budget, adding: ``We have at least a
status report on energy sector although the outlook is not very
comfortable.''
	   ``The budget has been cleverly presented. There is no specific
statement on supplementary budget of last year (1997-98). There is
also very little on banking and money matters,'' he said.
	   ``The emphasis placed by the Finance Minister on the troubles of
the nationalised industries is interesting,'' Muhit remarked and
said: ``We do not, however, have a clear target of privatisation,
nor is there any special emphasis on activating the domestic
demand.
	   ``Estimates of public expenditure for the last year (1997-98) is
not consistent with shortfall in revenue generation and aid
spending,'' he said.
	   Asked what the impact of the new budget on the country's
investment scenario would be, the former Finance Minister said:
``Taxation policies will obviously have some impact on investment.
But I would have expected a more elaborate treatment of the subject
of domestic investment.''
	   The efforts to bring out untaxed money for investment are also
not too bold or robust, Muhit added.
	   
</TEXT>
