<SLUG> FOREX-RESERVES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Forex reserves up by $ .073b, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Forex reserves up by $ .073b, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Country's foreign exchange reserve has risen by a meagre margin
of .073 billion to 1.680 billion US dollars in one year to June 1.
	   Finance Minister Shah AMS Kibria disclosed this in his 1998-99
annual budget speech in the Jatiya Sangsad yesterday.
	   On June 1, 1998, total forex reserves in Bangladesh Bank stood
at 1.680 billion dollar from 1.607 billion on the day in 1997.
	   ``This improvement was attained in the reserve position of
Bangladesh despite highly unfavourable international climate,'' the
Minister told the Parliament.
	   He said before the assumption of office by the present
government, there had been a sudden fall in the foreign exchange
reserves in 1995-96 fiscal year.
	   From June 30, 1995 to June 30, 1996, total reserve had plummeted
from 3.07 billion to 2.03 billion dollars, Kibria said, pointing to
the massive slide amid a political turmoil at the fag-end of the
previous regime.
	   But, he said, the present government had to ``endeavour very
hard in last two years to arrest this fast depletion of reserves''.
	   
</TEXT>
