<BODY>
<SLUG> BLACK-MONEY-TO-BUY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Black money to buy shares: no question will be asked, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Black money to buy shares: no question will be asked, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The Finance Minister, Shah AMS Kibria, presenting the budget for
1998-99 in Parliament yesterday proposed that investment of
undisclosed money (black money) in buying primary and secondary
shares in the capital market would be allowed without asking any
question about its source.
	   But the investors would be required to pay 7.5 per cent tax and
the investors would have to retain these shares at least for one
year.
	   The budget proposed exemption of tax on income from mutual
funds. It would be applicable to all mutual funds established and
operated in the private sector. At present such exemption is
enjoyed only by the Investment Corporation of Bangladesh (ICB).
	   The budget sought to remove discrimination in regard to the
corporate income tax. At present income of the publicly traded
companies is taxed at 35 per cent and non-publicly traded companies
at 40 per cent.
	   But there are some banks, insurance companies, financial
institutions and non-resident companies which do public trading and
yet are taxed at 40 per cent. The budget proposed 35 per cent tax
on this category of companies.
	   The budget also proposed that companies enjoying tax holiday
which declare dividends would be required to invest 30 per cent of
such exempted income in government securities or in the same
industry.
	   It said the mandatory investment of the dividend might be made
during the tax holiday period or within one year from the expiry of
the tax holiday period.
	   The budget proposed 10 per cent deduction of tax at source on
the dividend earned by individual tax payers from investment in
corporate bodies. This would be treated as the final settlement of
the tax liability.
	   
</TEXT>
