<HEADLINE>
Inflation stands at 6.63 per cent, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Inflation stands at 6.63 per cent, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Inflation has shot up to 6.63 per cent from last year's rate of
2.51 per cent, according to the reckoning presented by the Finance
Minister in Parliament yesterday, reports APB.
	   The rate was calculated in the new index as in April 1998. The
old index, however, shows the inflation rate at 6.28 per cent.
	   In June 1997, the rate was 2.51 per cents. In June 1996,
however, the rate was much higher, 6.65 per cent, Finance Minister
Shah AMS Kibria said in his budget speech.
	   ``According to experts, the current inflationary pressure is due
to unexpected shortfall in Aman production,'' the Minister told the
House, assigning the reasons for the growing inflation, which
causes rise in prices.
	   The Finance Minister hoped that after boro and wheat harvest the
inflation rate would decline.
	   
</TEXT>
