<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EU-Money Dispute </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Santer tells Kohl not to turn EU budget reform into election issue
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ROBERT WIELAARD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ European Commission President Jacques
Santer urged German Chancellor Helmut Kohl Friday not to make
European Union budget reform an election issue in the Sept. 27
German elections.
	   ``We must have an objective debate'' about new funding for the
EU to enable it to absorb 11 newcomers, he said.
	   ``We must not bring electioneering arguments into this debate.''
	   At a press conference, Santer did not name Germany but his
target was evident. Germany wants to close the gap between what it
pays into the EU and what it gets back. German officials insist
their net payment be cut from 22 billion marks (dlrs 12.2 billion)
to 7 billion marks (dlrs 3.9 billion) annually.
	   Others say such demands are unreasonable at a time when the EU
plans to take in Cyprus and 10 East European nations, all of them
than current EU members and expecting help to catch up.
	   The money dispute will figure on the agenda of an EU summit next
Monday and Tuesday in Cardiff, Wales, along with foreign issues
such as Kosovo and the deteriorating Russian economy and the
recession in Japan. The summit ends after a lunch with South
African Nelson Mandela as a farewell to a leader who is to step
down next year.
	   EU budget reform has been a topic of debate in the union since
last July.
	   However, talks have gone nowhere with Germany and the
Netherlands _ another net payer _ insisting on austerity while
poorer countries such as Spain, Portugal and Greece demand
``solidarity'' from their partners.
	   The issue is crucial to Kohl whose Christian Democrat-Liberal
alliance faces an uphill struggle to get reelected. It is keen to
show voters it wants an EU that is affordable and more
people-friendly.
	   In a joint letter to British Prime Minister, and summit host,
Tony Blair he and French President Jacques Chirac termed the EU an
ivory tower that issues edicts affecting the lives of 370 million
Europeans but is accountable to none.
	   They want to correct the ``tendency of some institutions to
distance themselves from citizens,'' a stab at the European
Commission, long the whipping boy of EU-bashers.
	   Blair has pledged to have ``an informal discussion of the future
development of the European Union, addressing in particular how we
can better meet the challenges we face while responding to citizens
concerns.''
	   Santer said the summit must reaffirm that EU budget reform is
wrapped up by next Spring. In a pre-summit letter to the EU
leaders, Blair agreed, saying they must give ``direction and
momentum to the negotiations.''
	   There is broad agreement the budget _ some dlrs 100 billion this
year, half of it devoted to subsidies for the EU's 10 million
farmers _ must be revamped.
 &UR; (rw-pa)
</TEXT>
