AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The government has set an Annual Development Programme (ADP)
outlay of Taka 13,600 crore for the fiscal 1998-99 with 46 per cent
or Taka 6,256 crore coming from the domestic resources.
	   The proposed size of ADP is 11.5 per cent higher than that of
the revised ADP of Taka 12,200 crore for the fiscal year 1997-98,
Finance Minister Shah AMS Kibria said while announcing the national
budget for the fiscal 1998-99 at the Jatiya Sangsad yesterday.
	   According to the proposed ADP outlay, 54 per cent of the
resources is expected to come from the external resources. This is
8.9 per cent higher than that of the external assistance of 1997-98
revised budget.
	   The highest-allocation in the proposed ADP went to transport
sector. A sum of Taka 1162.66 crore has been allocated for 87
projects of Roads and Highways directorate. Total allocation in ADP
for the Bangladesh Railway has been proposed at Taka 426.59 crore
while a sum of Taka 113 crore has been proposed for Inland Water
Transport sector. The ADP allocation for Bangabandhu Bridge project
is Taka 465 crore.
	   Education sector is the highest recipient of the combined
allocations of the revenue budget and the ADP. In the revised
budget of the fiscal 1997-98, total allocation stood at Taka
4199.98 crore. In fiscal 1998-99 it is proposed to raise to Taka
4596.14 crore. Total allocation for 1998-99 is 9.4 per cent higher
than that of the revised allocation for the fiscal 1997-98.
	   The proposed ADP for the next fiscal has allocated Taka 1373
crore in the fiscal 1998-99 in the health and family welfare sector
against Taka 1111.62 crore in the fiscal 1997-98.
	   In the proposed ADP an allocation of Taka 718.88 crore will go
to the crop subsector while the allocation of Taka 85.6 crore and
Taka 80 crore respectively will go to fisheries and livestock
sectors.
	   In the proposed ADP the total allocation for power sector stands
at Taka 1390 crore in the fiscal 1998-99 against the revised ADP
for 1997-98 at Taka 1252.50 crore.
	   Apart from power generation, this allocation will be available
for investment in transmission and distribution. About 32 per cent
of the total allocation for power sector will be spent for rural
electrification.
	   The external assistance to Bangladesh has been increased despite
the availability of concessional loan and grant worldwide is
decreasing.
	   It is expected that the range of World Bank's minimum annual
assistance to Bangladesh would be increased to US dollar 600 to 650
million US dollars as against US dollars 400 to 450 million in the
current fiscal.
	   
</TEXT>
