<HEADLINE>
Highlights, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Highlights, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Following are highlights of the proposed budget for 1998-99,
reports UNB.
	   No fresh tax has been proposed.
	   Duties on raw materials and intermediary products reduced to
give support to local industries.
	   Special duty and other facilities proposed to encourage some
industries, specially export-based industries.
	   Systematic reforms proposed to check harassment and corruption
in revenue collection and also to curtail the discretion of the
customs and tax officials.
	   The budgetary proposals in detail:
	   To support the local industries, duties on following raw
materials and intermediary products have been reduced:
	   - Raw materials under 190 HS codes.
	   - Raw materials and intermediary products under 852 HS.
	   - 2,591 products (HS Code).
	   Considering export possibilities, setting up of backward
linkage, national priority, environmental cooperation and
employment opportunity special incentives have been given in the
following sectors:
	   - Agro-based industries (food flavour, tin can, crown cork and
lag cap, glass made bottle and jars).
	   - Withdrawal of duties and VAT from computer and computer spares
and reduction of duties on UPS.
	   - Reduction of existing duty of 30 per cent to 25 per cent on
polymer, basic raw materials for plastic industry.
	   - To increase the use of solar energy withdrawal of duty and VAT
from photovoltaic generator.
	   - Instead of 15, 25 and 30 per cent duties on different types of
pigment used in leather industry 15 per cent duty has been proposed
amalgamating all other three duties.
	   - Reducing duty to zero from 2.5 per cent on synthetic fibre, to
7.5 per cent from 15 per cent on colour or vat dyes and to 25 per
cent from 30 per cent on some spares of textile industry have been
proposed.
	   - To continue ``alternative facilities'' for one more year for
readymade garments.
	   - Reduction of duties on buses and trucks to 15 per cent from
22.5 per cent.
	   Initiative has been taken to expedite the economic development
by reducing overall excise and duties:
	   a) Proposed to introduce four tier tax rate structure for
personal income tax and revised tax will be zero, 10, 18 and 25 per
cent instead of the existing five tier tax rate structure of zero,
10, 15, 20 and 25 to make tax system more realistic, rational and
modern.
	   b) To encourage tax payers to make investments, proposal has
been made to enhance the upper limit of investment from Tk 100,000
to Tk 150,000.
	   c) To reduce the highest rate of customs duty of 42.5 per cent
to 40 per cent to give support to local industries.
	   Systematic reforms have been proposed to check harassment and
corruption in revenue collection and also to curtail the discretion
of the customs and tax officials:
	   a) In case of contractors, suppliers and biri producers it has
been proposed that the tax is deducted at source will be treated as
final settlement of their tax liability.
	   b) To discourage mis-declaration of goods or its value, wide gap
in and difference of duty for similar items have been proposed.
	   To encourage and expedite the capital market special facilities
have been proposed:
	   a) In purchase of shares from primary and secondary market,
subject to the condition that the investor pays tax at the rate of
seven and a half per cent has been proposed.
	   b) To exempt tax income from all mutual funds accruing to the
issuing companies.
	   c) To reduce to 35 per cent from 40 per cent tax from banks,
insurance companies and other financial institutions.
	   Measures were proposed for protection of environment:
	   To discourage the three-wheelers increase in supplementary duty
and maximum depreciation on assessment of old reconditioned cars
have been proposed.
	   To increase revenue expansion of tax base systematic reforms
have been proposed.
	   a) Income and wealth tax from the government employees will be
strengthened.
	   b) The existing income tax rules provide for tax on perquisites
received by a salaried persons the rules have been made more
rational and simple.
	   c) To include nine more items in VAT net at retail level. The
items are: firearms, carpet, watch, cement and MS products, ceramic
crockery, glass, crystal, pyrex and melamine, household decoration
pieces made of ceramic, brass, silver, copper and crystal glass, CI
sheet and foam.
	   d) To collect VAT on retail price at production stage of
cosmetics, toiletries, detergent, disinfectant, soft drink, tissue
paper, paint, varnish, aerosol and air-freshners.
	   e) Five new services are proposed to be brought under the
purview of VAT: security service, pathological laboratory,
automatic or mechanised saw mill, air-conditioned garments shop and
trade service.
	   
</TEXT>
