<SLUG> BC-Foreign Ministers, 4th Ld,0274 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Major powers grapple with nuclear threat, Balkans unrest
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 5th graf pvs to ADD communique quotes.
PICKUP 6th graf pvs. &QL; 
 &UR; By BARRY SCHWEID &QC; 
 &UR; AP Diplomatic Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ The world's leading industrial nations, acting on
a U.S. proposal, decided Friday to deny loans to India and Pakistan
in retaliation for their nuclear tests.
	   Loans for humanitarian purposes would be excluded from the
boycott, the foreign ministers meeting to discuss the nuclear
crisis in South Asia decided.
	   A communique approved by the eight countries _ the United
States, Britain, France, Germany, Japan, Canada, Italy and Russia _
also urged India and Pakistan to halt their testing programs and
not to deploy nuclear weapons on their missiles.
	   Additionally, they were urged to deal with the ``root causes''
of tensions between them, especially over Kashmir, the mostly
Muslim enclave that straddles their border.
	   The joint steps were taken as India and Pakistan moved to hold
negotiations later in the month, a step welcomed by the U.S.
officials.
	   ``The recent nuclear tests have created an atmosphere of
regional instability which will undermine the region's
attractiveness to both foreign and domestic investment, damaging
business confidence and the prospect for economic growth,'' the
communique said.
	   The eight foreign ministers, as a group, said all countries
``should act as they see fit to demonstrate their displeasure and
address their concerns to India and Pakistan.''
	    &UR; U.S. Secretary ... PICKUP 6th graf pvs.
</TEXT>
