<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Sir Hurst, HFR, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: England hero Geoff Hurst to get knighthood
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: For release at 2300 GMT; adds quotes from Hurst &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Call him Sir Geoff.
	   Geoff Hurst, whose three goals earned England the 1966 World Cup
in the final against West Germany, receives a knightood Saturday
from Queen Elizabeth II.
	   The honor for the former West Ham star comes on the eve of
Monday's World Cup opener for England against Tunisia, 32 years
after Hurst brought England its one and only World Cup trophy.
	   Hurst, 56, is the only player to have scored a hat trick in the
championship game of the World Cup, although some believe that one
of his three goals in the 4-2 victory didn't cross the goal line.
	   British Prime Minister Tony Blair urged current England players
to match Hurst's feat.
	   ``The prime minister, who has since met Mr. Hurst, remembers him
as one of his heroes when he watched the World Cup final in 1966,''
a Blair spokesman said. ``Perhaps this will spur on (Alan) Shearer,
(Michael) Owen and (Teddy) Sheringham to get hat tricks, too.''
	   Hurst described getting the news.
	   ``My wife opened the letter and then just passed it to me,'' he
said. ``It was a very tearful moment in the Hurst household.''
	   ``When you are my age, this comes as quite a shock,'' he added.
``When I was younger it seemed easier to absorb.''
	   Hurst is just one of many British sports figures on the queen's
Honors List.
	   Michael Bonallack, secretary of the Royal and Ancient Golf Club
of St. Andrews, also receives a knighthood.
	   The Order of the British Empire (OBE) goes to 1992 Olympic
hurdles champion Sally Gunnell, former Olympic and world 100-meter
champion Linford Christie, and Ian Peacock, chief executive of the
Lawn Tennis Association.
	   Among those receiving the Member of the British Empire (MBE) are
WBC heavyweight boxing champion Lennox Lewis, England cricket
captain Alec Stewart, former England soccer star John Barnes,
Scottish golfer Colin Montgomerie, golfer Alison Nicholas and
middle-distance runner Kelly Holmes
	   (scw) 	   
</TEXT>
