AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A Division Bench of the High Court Division, of the Supreme
Court comprising Mr Justice K M Hasan and Mr Justice M Mohammad
Latifur Rahman on Thursday issued a rule challenging the legalities
of the practice of 'Safe Custody' whereby the innocent girls/women
are put in prison thereby violating their inalienable fundamental
rights as citizens in the name of their welfare, according to a
press release issued on Thursday by the Law Associates.
	   In the present case Mrs. Rokeya Kabir, Executive Director,
Bangladesh Nari Progati Sangstha filed a write petition on behalf
of Mosammet Ayesha Akhter (alias Dipali Pal Chowdhury), who is
detained in the Dhaka Central Jail in the guise of 'Safe Custody'
although she committed no crime nor is there any allegation of any
offence committed by her. Besides, she has not been charged with
any crime or offence whatsoever under the Penal Code or violation
or breach of any law in Bangladesh.
	   Dipali Pal, as claimed by her, being a mature person at her own
will embraced Islam, took the name Mosammet Ayesha Akhter and
married a Muslim boy. The angry father of Dipali, alias Ayesha
Akhter lodged a false FIR against the Muslim boy and his family.
Consequently, Ayesha's father-in-law, an old man of 70 was arrested
in connection with Sutrapur PS Case No. 36(3) 98. Thereafter, in
order to secure the release of her father-law-law, Ayesha
voluntarily surrendered to the Sutrapur Police on 11-5-98 and she
was produced before the Metropolitan Magistrate Court. However,
without being an accused or a witness in the FIR, she was sent to
Dhaka Central Jail in the guise of 'Safe Custody' where she is
experiencing immense misery.
	   Tania Amer, Barrister-at-law, the learned Advocate of The Law
Associates moved writ of Habeas Corpus in the High Court Division
for the Enforcement of Fundamental Rights.
	   Upon hearing Barrister Tania Amer, Advocate for the petitioner
and upon consideration of the said petition the Court issued a Rule
Nisi calling upon the respondents to show cause on or before 15th
June, 1998 as to why the direction should not be given upon the
respondents to produce Ayesha Akhter before the Court so that the
Court may satisfy itself that the said Ayesha Akhter (previously
Dipali Pal Chowdhury) is not held in custody without any lawful
authority and why a declaration should not be given that there is
no law in Bangladesh whereby any person, whether a major or a minor
or a female who is neither an alleged criminal nor a witness in the
FIR can be detained in jail by any Magistrate or any authority
under the guise of 'Judicial Safe Custody' or otherwise; and that
the practice of Safe Custody is violative of the jail code and no
one in jail shall be denied access to a lawyer of her own choice
and that there is no law in Bangladesh empowering any investigation
officer, or any other person to pray before any court to put a
victim girl in jail in the guise of Safe Custody, and that such
prayer is ultra vires and or such other or further order or orders
passed as to this court may seem fit and proper.
	   
</TEXT>
