<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Islam, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Turkish army steps up pressure on Islamic politics
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDs: UPDATES with police arresting dozens in headscarf ban protest &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) _ Police arrested scores of Islamic students
Friday during a clash Friday, and newspapers reported that Turkey's
army is preparing to again pressure the government to step up the
fight against Islamic politics.
	   The country's top generals scheduled an emergency session for
Tuesday shortly before they meet with leading government officials
in the National Security Council, the Turkish Daily News said.
	   The generals will evaluate the government's progress in its
fight against radical Islam, it said.
	   The generals are unhappy because they feel the government is
moving too slowly.
	   A so-called military-backed ``fundamentalism'' law, for example,
has been delayed by the failure of cabinet ministers to attend
parliamentary committee hearings. The bill would tighten control
over Islamic attire and education and provide heavier punishments
for civil servants involved in pro-Islamic activities.
	   The students arrested Friday in Istanbul were protesting the
suspension of 11 university friends for wearing Islamic-style
headscarves and beards, the Anatolia news agency said.
	   Private NTV television showed students being injured by police
truncheons. No injury toll was immediately available.
	   The university has banned headscarves and beards, which are seen
as a sign of loyalty, in compliance with the military's crackdown
on displays of Islamic traditionalism.
	   Turkey, overwhelmingly Muslim, has had a secular system for the
last 75 years. Last year the military forced the first Islamic-led
government her to resign.
	   (ht-sh-fd)
</TEXT>
