w1083 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-India-Pakistan-Nuclea 5thLd-Writethru   06-12 0486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Pakistan-Nuclear, 5th Ld-Writethru,0485 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Top-level meeting could break the ice between India and Pakistan
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDs: RECASTS: ADDS comments from senior US official. CHANGES
byline, overline &QL; 
 &UR; By ARTHUR MAX &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ Pushed by the urgency of a nuclear
threat, India and Pakistan agreed Friday to resume top-level talks
in hopes of reversing an escalation of tension and distrust.
	   India announced that the foreign secretaries of the two
countries will meet in New Delhi June 22 to resume discussions
broken off last September. The meeting is likely to prepare some
groundwork for a brief meeting between the prime ministers during a
regional summit next month.
	   It is the first concrete step to halt the tailspin in South
Asian tensions that began May 11 when India conducted a series of
nuclear tests and proclaimed itself a nuclear weapons state.
Pakistan followed suit two weeks later, resisting international
pressure for restraint. Both later declared a moratorium on further
tests.
	   The meeting in 10 days will be the first direct contact between
senior diplomats since a Hindu nationalist government took power in
New Delhi in March, adopting a harsher tone toward India's
traditional rival, Pakistan.
	   The announcement came as the foreign ministers of eight leading
industrial nations stepped up sanctions against India and Pakistan,
deciding at a meeting in London to deny all loans except those
earmarked for humanitarian projects.
	   For weeks after the nuclear tests, Indian Prime Minister Atal
Bihari Vajpayee and Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif
proclaimed their readiness for talks, but without indicating any
concession that might make them more successful than earlier
disappointing rounds.
	   ``India is committed to fostering a relationship of trust and
friendship with Pakistan based on mutual respect,'' said the
Foreign Ministry. Pakistan, observing the Muslim sabbath, had no
immediate comment.
	   The statement said the agenda will be the same formulated in
June 1997: the territorial dispute over Kashmir; ``peace and
security, including confidence building measures;'' a disengagement
of forces on the 19,000-foot-high (5,800-meter-high) Siachin
glacier; economic cooperation, drug trafficking.
	   Disarmament was not an agenda item. Both sides have pledged to
continue developing missile systems mounted with nuclear warheads
capable of reaching each other's largest cities, despite
international calls for a freeze on missile tests.
	   In September, the foreign secretaries' talks collapsed over how
to continue discussions on Kashmir, the Himalayan territory was the
catalyst for two wars between India and Pakistan in the last 50
years.
	   Pakistan says all efforts to resolve Kashmir are doomed without
international mediation. India says Kashmir is a problem for the
two countries to sort out alone. 	   
</TEXT>
