<BODY>
<SLUG> JAMUNA-BRIDGE-GAS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Jamuna Bridge Gas pipeline collapses, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Jamuna Bridge Gas pipeline collapses, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The 30-inch-diametre gas pipeline, worth Tk 40 crore along the
Jamuna Bridge, collapsed on Thursday during a hydraulic test-run
for the supply of gas to the western part of the country.
	   The pipeline was installed by the Hyundai company, which also
constructed the main component of the Bridge. The design of the
pipeline was not submitted to the Petrobangla Board and not
approved by it, according to a Petrobangla source.
	   A source in the Bangladesh Consultant Ltd, working along with
RPT, NEDECO as consultant on the Bridge said that earlier it had
also raised objection about the engineering of the pipeline set up
along the southern side of the bridge.
	   Originally, Petrobangla had suggested that the gas pipeline be
designed along with the design of the spans of the bridge. Besides,
it also suggested that the pipeline be installed at the same time
as the spans.
	   After the collapse of the gas pipeline, Communications Minister
Anwar Hossain Manju and Secretary Jamuna Bridge, Abdul Muyeed
Chowdhury visited the site.
	   Earlier it was decided that the supply of gas to the western
part of the country would begin from day one of the inauguration of
the Bridge. But with the collapse of the gas pipeline the supply of
gas to the western part would not take place as planned, sources
apprehended.
	   UNB adds: Sources said that low standard of work in setting up
of the pipeline was the reason behind the accident.
	   They said that the iron angles with which the pipeline was hung
had been fixed 12 feet apart from each other instead of four feet.
	   APB adds: ``The 4.8 km pipeline, installed a few days ago,
smashed into river Jamuna when hydraulic fluid (water) was moved
through the pipe under pressure,'' an official said.
	   Jamuna Multipurpose Bridge Division in a press release in Dhaka
said: The contractor suffered a serious setback in his efforts to
complete all works on the bridge prior to the opening ceremony on
June 23.
	   From a preliminary inspection it would appear that the bridge
itself was not damaged, the Division clarified.
	   ``In a combined statement from the JMBA, Construction
Supervising Consultant and the Contractor, it is understood that
the bridge-opening ceremony will go ahead as planned,'' it said.
	   Salvage the broken pipeline has already started, but engineers
said the repairs of the gas-pipe might take about two months.
	   Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina is scheduled to open the bridge on
June 23.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
