<HEADLINE>
Four cockle-hunters scour the peninsula's rivers, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Four cockle-hunters scour the peninsula's rivers, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   FOR THE LOVE OF IT ... The cockle business has taken four men
from Tumpat in Kelantan to many rivers in Peninsular Malaysia to
earn an income for themselves and their families.
	   After almost 25 years of travelling in Malacca, Kedah, Perak and
Kelantan, the team comprising (from left) Salim Mohamad, 50, Lokman
Long Omar, 37, Mohd Ali Mamat, 48, and Mustafa Mamat, 40 (not in
picture), are now based at the Pahang River in Pekan, Pahang, in
their quest for cockles.
	   Team leader Mohd Ali said cockles were a craze in Kelantan.
	   ``This is our main source of income.''
	   Asked about the difficulties they had to overcome in collecting
cockles, Mohd Ali said the water level had to be low.
	   ``The low water level makes the task of collecting easier.
	   ``We use a basket, like the one on a bicycle, joined to a piece
of bamboo that enables us to scoop the cockles from the riverbed.''
	   The team had so far caught about 200kg of cockles from the
Pahang River which would be sold in Kelantan.
	   
</TEXT>
