<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bosnia-Mass Graves </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Foensic experts complete exhumations on second mass grave
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) _ International forensic
experts have completed exhumations at the second mass-grave site in
eastern Bosnia, a U.N. news release said Friday.
	   Bodies and parts of bodies of some 200 people were found at two
sites called ``secondary mass graves'' as the bodies were initially
buried in other mass graves, removed and then reburied into these
two and another 10 estimated sites in the region in an apparent
attempt to destroy evidence.
	   The international experts began exhumations last month to find
evidence of crimes committed during the 1995 Bosnian Serb offensive
against the eastern Muslim enclave of Srebrenica and to support
investigations and trials by the U.N. war crimes tribunal in The
Hague, Netherlands.
	   Up to 7,000 people, mainly men, are still missing and are
presumed to have been massacred by Bosnian Serbs overrunning the
enclave in July 1995.
	   The U.N. press release said some of the bodies had ``hands bound
behind their backs'' and were blindfolded.
	   The evidence appeared to corroborate survivors' reports that
after Srebrenica fell to the Serbs, many Muslims were summoned,
executed and buried in numerous mass graves in the region.
	   (sl/rp) 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Bosnia-Mass Graves; CT:i; 
