<HEADLINE>
Opposition leaders oppose expansion of VAT net, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Opposition leaders oppose expansion of VAT net, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Jatiya Party chief Hussain Muhammad Ershad said on Thursday the
government had failed to prepare a budget for the welfare of the
commonman.
	   BNP member and former State Minister for Planning Dr. Moin Khan
said that due to the budgetary measures the economy would further
collapse and the people would continue to lose their purchasing
power.
	   M. Morshed Khan MP of the BNP said the budget lacked
transparency and contained no incentives for the use of heavy
machinery.
	   Moulana Delwar Hossain Sayeedi of Jamaat-e-Islami said the new
budget contained nothing more than customary rhetoric.
	   They made these observations as instant reactions to the new
budget soon after Finance Minister Shah AMS Kibria placed it in
Parliament.
	   H.M. Ershad said the commonman of Bangladesh did not expect such
a budget from the Awami League government. The people would be hit
by price hike as the coverage of the Value Added Tax (VAT) had been
expanded.
	   The former President said that so long the VAT used to be
collected at the whole sale stage, now it had been expanded to the
retail stage.
	   He said the Finance Minister had even increased the price of CI
sheets and other building materials that were used by commonman.
	   The JP Chief said the people could not accept the budget because
it was not prepared for their welfare. The budget, therefore, was
also not acceptable to JP, he said.
	   Dr. Moin Khan said the budget reflected the government's
failures of the past one year. During the year, the prices
spiralled by 61 per cent and the Taka was devalued by five per
cent. The Finance Minister's budget speech was a proof of the
downward trend of the economy, he said.
	   He said the GDP growth rate had fallen from 5.9 per cent to 5.6
per cent even though foodgrain production had been higher. This did
not prove the efficiency of the government. If agricultural output
had not been higher, the GDP growth rate would have fallen further,
he said.
	   He said the Taka 13,600 crore Annual Development Programme did
not reflect the real situation. As in current year, the government
might not have adequate revenue surplus to finance the ADP if the
mistakes committed so long are not been corrected.
	   Moin Khan said the government was hoodwinking the people by
talking about giving incentives to jute growers. The AL had in its
manifesto promised Taka 500 per maund of jute, but growers were
getting only Taka 150 per maund. The Government's deeds did not
tally with its words, he said.
	   He said that the government would once again fail to implement
new pay scales for government employees, because Taka 150 crore
earmarked for this was only one-tenth of the actual requirement.
The pressure of VAT would come on the average citizen. There was no
initiative to reverse the downward trend of the economy, he added.
	   M. Morshed Khan said the budget was not transparent because the
Finance Minister did not explain the HS Code on which new taxation
proposals had been made. The people thus remained in the dark about
the steps the Finance Minister had promised to take in this
respect.
	   The budget was also not friendly to new industries, he said.
	   Moulana Delwar Hossain Sayeedi, leader of the three Jamaat MPs
in Parliament said that the during the last two years the
government had failed to implement its high-sounding promises like
serving the people, improving the lot of the poor and protecting
the peasants and workers.
	   He said the budget did not contain realistic steps to end the
frustration and anger of the people arising out of the power crisis
and the collapse of the share market. There was also no direction
to overcome the economic stagnation and disaster, he said.
	   Moulana Sayeedi said it was not proper to impose so many taxes
on the fragile economy.
	   The promise made by the Finance Minister not to tolerate
repression of women and children was hollow because during the last
two years no realistic steps had been taken in this regards. The
government had miserably failed to improve the law and order, he
alleged.
	   The government had also failed to implement the three promises
it had made last year. Introduction of old-age allowance started
only in the eleventh month of the fiscal year. The Employment
Generation Bank was yet to be established and the shelterless
people were yet to get housing facilities, he added.
	   Dilip Barua, General Secretary of Bangladesher Samyabadi Dal in
a press statement last night said the budget was not
welfare-oriented. The budget would increase the inequality among
the people because its main objective was to make the rich richer,
he alleged
	   
</TEXT>
