<HEADLINE>
Robbers who took papers instead of RM200,000, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Robbers who took papers instead of RM200,000, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   R. SittamparamASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   JOHOR BARU, Thurs. - It was a case of picking the wrong
suitcase, when two robbers, in making their escape after robbing a
businessman at a shopping complex, mistakenly dropped one
containing RM200,000 worth of jewellery and took off with the other
containing sales documents.
	   It seems luck was not on the robbers' side that day as an hour
later one of the armed duo, a 19-year-old youth, was caught by
police after a short car chase at Jalan Pingat.
	   Police investigations are under way to ascertain if an armed
man, who was shot during a scuffle with a police patrol team at the
Plaza Leisure Mall car park at 10.50pm yesterday, was the second
robbery suspect.
	   State Criminal Investigation Department chief Senior Assistant
Commissioner II Mohd Mokhtar Hassan said two men committed the
robbery at Plaza Pelangi shopping complex at Jalan Pelangi at
5.45pm.
	   The two, armed with a pistol and a knife, had forced the
jewellery supplier's two workers to carry the briefcases into a car
and one of the workers to drive them away.
	   On reaching the Pelangi Leisure Mall nearby, the robbers
alighted with the two bags and tried to hail a taxi when the
workers shouted for help.
	   An alert security guard managed to overpower the robber armed
with the knife but released him, when the other fired two warning
shots. In their getaway, the robbers dropped the bag containing the
jewellery.
	   The robbers then hijacked a car nearby in making their escape.
	   Alerted police chased the robbers' car and cornered it. They
arrested one while the other escaped.
	   After questioning him, a police launched an operation and
another police team spotted a suspicious looking man at the Plaza
Leisure Mall car park.
	   Mohd Mokhtar said the man drew out a pistol and fired at the
police team who identified themselves.
	   Police shot dead the man and found another pistol in the man's
car.
	   ``The dead man, Ong Seng Kiat, 31, had been just released from
prison and believed to have been involved in five robberies.''
	   
</TEXT>
