<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Austria-Food Flap,0374 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Spartan diet has Austrian team dreaming of home cooking
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By GEORGE JAHN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MARGAUX, France (AP) _ Home cooking should be some of the best
for soccer players from Austria, which is known for its schnitzels,
goulash, strudel and other delectables.
	   With the World Cup team based in the Bordeaux region, the team
would seem to be reveling in local French specialties like meat,
fish, desserts and wine.
	   So why are the players eating pasta and rice almost every day?
	   ``Doctor's orders,'' explained Romeo Auer, the team cook. ``I
make what the squad's doctor tells me, and he's been telling me to
go easy on the meat.''
	   Auer said the idea is to serve a diet low on protein but rich in
vitamins, carbohydrates and fiber. Dr. Ernst Schopp, the squad
physician, feels that's the ideal combination to keep the squad fit
for World Cup competition.
	   So their diet is spartan by Austrian standards, which feature
meat on the table in most households every day, including a big
schnitzel each Sunday.
	   At the training camp table, a typical breakfast consists of
juice, coffee, tea and muesli cereal. Lunch is most often a rice or
pasta dish, perhaps with a tiny chunk of lamb or fish. And dinner
is also light, so that the squad gets a good night's sleep when
lights go out a 10:30 p.m.
	   ``I understand the need for healthy food, but three weeks of
rice is too much,'' groused midfielder Hannes Reinmayr.
	   Although Coach Herbert Prohaska says a player is allowed up to a
half-liter a wine a day, that, too, is too little for some players.
After all, Austria serves up pretty good wines of its own, and its
per capita beer consumption is among the highest in Europe.
	   ``At home, I drink up to two liters of wine a day,'' claimed
goalkeeper Franz Wohlfahrt.
	   ``We're here to play soccer and not to drink,'' Prohaska said,
when asked whether he has sampled some of the local vintages.
	   Despite players' complaints, the team cook says no to a big
serving of meat _ at least not until the team posts a victory.
	   ``Then they get schnitzel,'' he says, smiling. ``If the doctor
says it's OK.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Soccer-Austria-Food Flap; CT:s; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
