<BODY>
<SLUG> SACRIFICED-FOR-DEVELOPME sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`Environment can't be sacrificed for development', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
`Environment can't be sacrificed for development', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MALACCA, Thurs. - Chief Minister Datuk Seri Abu Zahar Isnin said
it would be meaningless if the country was developed but had the
quality of its environment at its worst levels.
	   ``We experienced the haze last year and this problem badly
affected our tourism industry. Therefore, the relevant authorities
and industrialists should not compromise with wrongdoing which can
affect the quality of our environment.''
	   Abu Zahar said this today in his keynote address when opening
the Melaka Industrial Excellence campaign here.
	   He said in order to achieve their goals and remain competitive
in the global market, they must seriously emphasise environmental
issues.
	   Abu Zahar added that workers' health and their welfare should
also be high on the agenda.
	   ``The International Labour Organisation reported that 90 per
cent of industrial accidents were related to unsafe acts with the
remaining 10 per cent, to unsafe conditions.
	   ``A study by the Human Resource Ministry showed that the country
is losing as much as RM4 billion a year due to industrial
accidents. Last year, a total of 128,621 cases were reported while
some 88,127 have been compiled in the first quarter of this year.
	   ``I would urge local and foreign investors to ensure that the
technology they use at their workplaces is accompanied by high
health and safety standards.''
	   Abu Zahar also said companies must strive towards having a
risk-free or accident-free working environment.
	   In order for Malaysia to become a developed country by 2020, Abu
Zahar said it was imperative for investors to effectively apply
managerial skills and concepts to all levels.
	   ``The country needs to upgrade her corporate managerial skills
in order to maintain high achievement in industrial activities,''
Abu Zahar said.
	   He added the process of upgrading the skills of workers in
Malacca was far from satisfactory.
	   He said the industrial and skills development centre, set up by
the State Government and private companies, had yet to be fully
utilised by manufacturers.
	   
</TEXT>
