<SLUG> BC-Africa-Briefs,1046 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Zimbabwe, Central African Republic
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Contains items on Burundi, South Africa, Namibia, Angola,
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ------
	   BUJUMBURA, Burundi (AP) _ President Pierre Buyoya appointed two
vice presidents just three days before talks resume on ending
Burundi's civil war, the state radio said.
	   Radio Burundi said Vice President Frederic Bavugimyumvira will
be in charge of political affairs and administration. Vice
President Marcias Sinamenya will handle economic and social
affairs.
	   Buyoya, a retired army major who seized power from a civilian
president in 1996, took his first oath of office on Thursday. Last
week, a transitional constitution took effect to provide for a
government of transition.
	   Bavugimyumvira, a Hutu, is a leader in the FRODEBU party that
won the country's first democratic elections in 1993. Three months
later, Tutsi paratroopers ousted the civilian government and
assassinated President Melchior Ndadaye.
	   Sinamenya, also a Hutu, is a former governor of the Central
Bank.
	   Burundi's East African neighbors imposed economic sanctions
after Buyoya's coup to force a return to democratic rule.
	   At least 200,000 people, most of them civilians, have been
killed in the fighting that began after Ndadaye's slaying.
	   ---
	   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) _ Two right-wing Afrikaner
Weerstandsbeweging (AWB) members received amnesty Friday for the
1991 bombings of a school and union offices in Pretoria.
	   No one was injured in the night-time bombing of Hillview High
School, where whites were angry over admission of black students;
or in the bombing of the offices of the Congress of South African
Trade Unions (COSATU), the Truth and Reconciliation Commission
said.
	   The bombings took place after the 1990 release from prison of
anti-apartheid activist Nelson Mandela, who became the country's
president in 1994's first all-race elections.
	   The commission was established in 1995 to investigate human
rights violations by both sides of the apartheid struggle, and can
grant amnesty if applicants tell the truth and prove political
motivation.
	   Petrus Judeel and Andries Kriel, who also admitted to bombing
post offices and stealing explosives, received amnesty without
appearing at a public hearing because they did not kill, injure,
torture or abduct anyone.
	   ----
	   WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) _ Namibia's wildlife police unit on
Thursday charged four Namibians and a Zambian with possessing 21
elephant tusks, one of the country's largest illegal ivory hauls in
the past three years.
	   Police said the five were arrested just north of Windhoek when
they tried to sell the ivory for 150,000 Namibian Dollars (dlrs
30,000).
	   The tusks, including eight especially large specimens, appeared
to have been buried for some time before the attempted transaction.
	   Elephants are protected under the Convention on International
Trade in Endangered Species (CITES),
	   -----
	   BANGUI, Central African Republic (AP) _ An influx of foreign
rebels and bandits have turned the Central African Republic into a
hotbed of unrest ahead of presidential elections expected later
this year, a United Nations body reported here.
	   Armed attacks by guerrillas and robbers known as ``zaraguinas''
have proliferated in the northern countryside of this volatile
country, which has experienced several coups and military uprisings
in recent years, the U.N. humanitarian information unit said in a
statement.
	   ``The situation remains precarious ahead of the elections which,
in this region, often go hand in hand with trouble,'' the U.N.
agency known as IRIN said.
	   Although the capital, where the country's 1,350 U.N.
peacekeepers are based, is calm, insecurity prevails elsewhere in
the country, the U.N. agency said.
	   The three-month mandate of the U.N. soldiers _ which succeeds a
multinational African force _ will be reviewed in July. President
Ange-Felix Patasse has not announced a date for the elections..
	   Attacks have hampered relief agencies from delivering aid to
some of the country's 38,600 refugees, most of whom are from
neighboring Sudan.
	   Rebel groups in the country hail from Sudan, Chad and Congo,
IRIN said.
	   The Congolese rebels include members of the late dictator Mobutu
Sese Seko's now-disbanded military who fled what was then Zaire
during the takeover by President Laurent Kabila's rebel forces last
year.
	   -----
	   WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) _ Angolan human rights activist Manuel
Neto has been reunited with his family in the Angolan town of
Lubango, the National Society of Human Rights in Namibia said on
Thursday.
	   Neto was deported overland to Angola last month, the government
said. The London-based human rights group Amnesty International
denounced his expulsion, saying he faced certain detention and
torture.
	   Angolan intelligence officials took Neto to the town of Ondjiva,
where he was briefly questioned and then reunited with his family,
the Media Institute of Southern Africa in Windhoek said.
	   Neto had apparently upset the Angolan government by founding an
organization, the Angolan Human Rights League, in Windhoek last
month.
	   ----
	   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) _ A World Bank affiliate has approved a
dlrs 27.8 million investment in the Commercial Bank of Zimbabwe,
the largest state-owned bank.
	   The investment by the International Finance Corporation will
complete a privatization process that also involves Amalgamated
Bank of South Africa (ABSA), a statement by IFC said Thursday.
	   ABSA is purchasing 26 percent interest with a dlrs 10 million
investment. IFC will receive 15 percent interest for its dlrs 27.8
million investment, an ABSA statement said Thursday.
	   The Zimbabwe government will retain 20 percent of the shares.
Remaining shares will be held by individuals.
	   It is expected that CBZ will list on the Zimbabwe Stock Exchange
within the next year.
	   The privatization will enable the bank to link up with other
financial institutions in the region.
	   The country's volatile economy saw the Zimbabwe dollar plunge by
nearly 60 percent in value against the U.S. currency last year.
Inflation has exceeded 30 percent and unemployment is estimated at
around 50 percent. 	   
</TEXT>
