<HEADLINE>
Retrench only as last resort, employers told, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Retrench only as last resort, employers told, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Thurs. - Employers should regard retrenchment only
as a last-resort measure to cut cost to cope with the economic
slowdown.
	   This was emphasised at the Federation of Malaysian
Manufacturers' briefing on Effective Human Resource Management on
Compensation Packages and Industrial Relations today.
	   ``Retrenchment makes a person lose part of his personal identity
when he least expects it,'' said Lt Col (R) D. Pillai, human
resources manager of Metrod (M) Bhd, when speaking on the
procedures and pitfalls of retrenchment.
	   ``More importantly, it affects the morale of those still
employed. They would be constantly worrying if they would be
next.''
	   Employers should abide by the Code of Conduct for Industrial
Harmony of 1975 which required them to adopt positive measures to
avert reducing their workforce, he said.
	   Among the steps were temporarily freezing recruitment,
restricting overtime claims and reducing shifts.
	   Other measures included retraining of staff, and restrictions on
working on weekly rest days.
	   The briefing was attended by some 80 human resource personnel
from various companies.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
