<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-Tainted Blood </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Prosecutor recommends charges be dropped against former ministers
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By PIERRE-ANTOINE SUCHARD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ The chief prosecutor at a special court recommended
on Friday that an appeals court drop charges against three former
Cabinet ministers in the 1985 contamination of 1,300 people with
AIDS-tainted blood.
	   Jean-Francois Burgelin said the actions of former Socialist
Prime Minister Laurent Fabius, former Social Affairs Minister
Georgina Dufoix and former deputy Health Minister Edmond Herve were
``involuntary and stemmmed from negligence rather than malicious
intention.''
	   The three had been placed under investigation for ``complicity
in poisoning,'' in part for opting not to purchase U.S.-made AIDS
tests that would have prevented the tragedy. France's Pasteur
Institute was preparing its own AIDS test at the time.
	   They also opted against importing expensive blood products
treated with heat to de-activate the AIDS virus.
	   All three have said they never knowingly approved the use of
tainted blood.
	   Four former health officials, including the doctor who headed
the National Center for Blood Transfusion in 1985, were convicted
on charges related to the case and jailed.
	   Burgelin submitted a 100-page report defending his suggestion
the charges be dropped to the Court of Justice, a special court
empowered to prosecute officials for crimes committed while in
office.
	   The daily newspaper Le Monde quoted the report as saying that
French health officials acted more quickly than counterparts in
other countries to set up screening programs for blood donors.
	   The newspaper quoted the report as citing documents showing
that, at the time, the U.S. pharmaceutical company Abbott, which
manufactured the AIDS test, wasn't able to fully satisfy the needs
of the French market.
	   The court, composed of 12 members of parliament and three French
magistrates, now must decide whether to accept the prosecutor's
suggestion to drop the charges, which carry a maximum 30-year
prison sentence.
	   Burgelin reiterated opinions expressed last year when he urged a
lower court to dismiss the case. He had described the deaths as
resulting from the ``inextricable overlapping of responsibilities
that modern technology engenders.''
	   But a lower court went on to rule to pursue the charges.
	   About 1,300 hemophiliacs were infected with the AIDS virus in
the mid-80s when government medical authorities distributed blood
products they knew could be contaminated with HIV. More than 500 of
the victims have since died.
	   After the scandal broke in 1990, victims' families successfully
argued that the ministers be prosecuted.
	   Fabius was prime minister from 1984-86.
	   (ma-parf-eg)
</TEXT>
