<HEADLINE>
Ground water alternative for Wangsa Maju plant, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Ground water alternative for Wangsa Maju plant, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PETALING JAYA, Thurs. - The Wangsa Maju water treatment plant
which will begin operations next month, will obtain its raw water
from the Klang Gates dam and also groundwater tapped from areas
near it.
	   Puncak Niaga (M) Sdn Bhd executive chairman Datuk Rozali Ismail
said the ground water would be an alternative source if Klang Gates
could not supply sufficient water to the plant.
	   The company is implementing the project funded by the Federal
Government. The new plant would be capable of producing 45 million
litres per day.
	   The water level at the Klang Gates dam has recently dropped as a
result of the dry spell, causing the Bukit Nanas water treatment
plant to operate at 80 per cent capacity.
	   At present, Bukit Nanas is the only water treatment plant
supplied by Klang Gates dam.
	   Rozali said work to construct the pipe had already begun and
would be ready before the plant started operations next month.
	   He assured residents near the water treatment plant that they
need not worry about the tapping of ground water as it would be
carried out far from residential areas.
	   
</TEXT>
