<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Germany-US,0355 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Klinsmann says Germans respect the United States a lot
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By NESHA STARCEVIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NICE, France (AP) _ Captain Juergen Klinsmann said Friday the
German team had a lot of respect for the United States, whom the
Germans play Monday in Paris.
	   ``They have several experienced players who play in Europe and
they've achieved some good results recently,'' Klinsmann said.
These include a victory over Brazil.
	   He said the reigning European champion and three-time World Cup
champion would not underestimate the Americans.
	   ``They've grown as a team. They've made progress since the 1994
World Cup, they are self-confident, which is typical of their
mentality and we have a lot of respect for them,'' Klinsmann said.
	   ``We expect a physical, strong team,'' said Klinsmann, who
according to some reports may be heading to the MLS after the World
Cup.
	   Klinsmann said the Germans were gearing to win three points.
	   ``It's very important to win the opening game,'' he said. ``We
are approaching the game with optimism and in a good spirit.''
	   Coach Berti Vogts, who has been reluctant to discuss the
American team, also said he expected a physical game.
	   ``They had great problems against Belgium'' (in a friendly
match), Vogts said, adding that Germany was the favorite.
	   ``But we can't talk about small teams anymore. There are no
small teams. The world of soccer is growing closer,'' he said.
	   ``It's very important to get a good start,'' Vogts said of
Monday's game at the Parc des Princes stadium. ``We can see how
hectic it can get if you don't have a good start,'' he said,
referring to Italy's 2-2 draw against Chile.
	   Vogts, as usual, declined to discuss his starting lineup.
	   ``It's not important who plays, it's important that they play
well,'' Vogts said.
	   The Germans practiced Friday morning by playing a combination of
tennis and soccer in small groups.
	   On Thursday evening, the team visited nearby Monte Carlo for
sight-seeing and dinner.
	   (ns-sl)
</TEXT>
