<HEADLINE>
CGE buys 17.8pc stake in Intan Utilities, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
CGE buys 17.8pc stake in Intan Utilities, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   INTAN Utilities Bhd yesterday said its substantial shareholders
Vista Meranti Sdn Bhd and its wholly-owned subsidiary IMD Sdn Bhd,
have collectively sold 17.84 per cent or 9.551 million shares in
Intan to Compagnie Generale Des Eaux Asia Pacific Pte Ltd.
	   There was no mention of the sale price and method of payment.
	   CGE Asia Pacific, a company incorporated in Singapore, is a
wholly-owned subsidiary of the Paris Stock Exchange-listed Vivendi
Group.
	   The Vivendi Group is the world's largest water distributor. It
serves more than 170 million consumers worldwide.
	   In Malaysia, the Vivendi Group has had a presence since 1986
through associate, the Taliworks group of companies.
	   Through CGE Utilities (M) Sdn Bhd, it is involved in operating
27 water treatment plants in Selangor.
	   Intan Utilities is an investment holding company with one
wholly-owned subsidiary, Metropolitan Utilities Corp Sdn Bhd (MUC).
	   MUC is involved in the sourcing, treatment and supplying of
treated water to the Perak Water Supply Board for distribution to
consumers.
	   It has been granted a 20-year build-operate-transfer concession
for this operation by the Perak State Government in 1989 under the
Greater Ipoh Water Supply phase II privatisation project.
	   In a statement yesterday, Intan Utilities said Tan Sri Vincent
Tan Chee Yioun, who is the ultimate controlling shareholder of both
Vista and IMD, is deemed an interested party in Intan.
	   This is due to his 10.8 per cent stake via his interests in
Berjaya Group Bhd.
	   Following the sale by Vista and IMD and the deemed interest, he
now has a 31.81 per cent equity interest in Intan Utilities.
	   CGE Asia Pacific has contracted to purchase up to 30 per cent
equity interest in Intan Utilities from Vista, IMD and several
other third parties.
	   As part of the agreement, a new company Kristal Utama Sdn Bhd,
which will become a 75 per cent subsidiary of CGE Asia Pacific will
assume the responsibilities of Vista and IMD.
	   
</TEXT>
