<SLUG> EMPLOYMENT-SCENARIO sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Employment scenario, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Employment scenario, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   When an organisation like the Bangladesh Public Service
Commission (PSC) comments that the increasing rate of unemployment
among the educated youth, and lack of new job opportunities are
combining together to create conditions for socio-economic
instability in the country, one ought to give more than a casual
glance at it and try to decipher the intrinsic meaning of the words
in order to find new directions for solving the problems. The
remarks are well documented in the PSC's 1997 annual report which
was prepared after compiling data on the employment situation of
the last one decade.
	   The report was reportedly distributed in the Jatiya Sangsad on
Thursday last.It is only a harsh reality that the rate of
unemployment of the educated youths in Bangladesh is one of the
highest in the world. The job market is not growing in proportion
to the number of educated youths being added every year to the
already existing large body of the unemployed. Not many jobs are
created in the country, for which a slow-moving economy is held
responsible by the experts. A backward and impractical education
system is equally to be blamed for the situation. The world has
undergone radical changes, and the present time demands a pragmatic
and need-based education, keeping both eyes on the job market at
home and abroad.
	   There is demand for Bangladeshi workers in many foreign
countries but as our youths lack the required technical skills and
working English, these jobs are going away to other countries. When
the rest of the world is progressing at a rapid pace with timely
and intensive application of modern technology, we still tend to
cling to obsolete ideas and methods, and the worst sufferer of this
is the vast community of students in various institutes. We
strongly feel that our education system needs overhauling with the
induction of technology oriented curricula at all levels. Unless we
do that - the unemployment problem of the educated youths will be
difficult to solve.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
