<SLUG> ROAD-SAFETY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Road safety, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Road safety, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The increasingly high volume of road traffic in Bangladesh is
bringing into sharp focus the serious need for reduction of road
accidents. At a seminar on Road Safety Publication' last Tuesday,
the discussion centred around creation of a mass awareness of the
various traffic hazards and problems. In this context extensive use
of both the electronic and the print media could be recommended.
Safety hazards in Bangladesh are practically double that of
Pakistan and India in the South Asian region, and 20 times more
compared to countries like USA and UK, according to the seminar
report.Public awareness to ensure road safety is very much present
as far as private users of vehicles are concerned.
	   It is educating the drivers of the public transport system which
needs to be given due emphasis. Again, it would be most proper if
the licensing office, namely, the Bangladesh Road Transport
Authority took up the task of making sure that defective vehicles
do not get their licences renewed. The police also need to increase
their vigilance on a routine basis so as to detect vehicles
operating under a false license as well as weed out defective
vehicles which pollute the air and are accident-prone. A start has
been made with the identification and tagging of vehicles emitting
noxious fumes at a checkpoint near the Sangshad. The number of such
checkpoints could be increased so that gradually the vehicles on
all our roads are covered.
	   Road dividers which have proved to be effective in minimising
accidents can be introduced to bisect the inter-city highways,
bringing down head-on collisions. The removal is also recommended
of impromptu bazaars by the sides of the highways and widening both
sides with earth-fill, if necessary. This would reduce the plunging
of vehicles into ditches causing fatalities and injuries. Traffic
security is not limited to awareness of the dos and don'ts of
travelling, but also a need for the relevant infrastructure to be
in place, ensuring road safety for all.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
