<HEADLINE>
Beware the return of socialism, Klaus says
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PRAGUE, Czech Republic (AP) _ Former Premier Vaclav Klaus called
on Czechs to vote for his party in early elections next week,
warning Friday against the return of socialism.
	   By voting for the Civic Democratic Party, ``only then you can be
certain that your vote will stop the coming of the left,'' the
state news agency CTK quoted Klaus as saying.
	   He said his party is worried by the possible ``waste of votes,''
should other center-right parties fail to meet the 5 percent
threshold necessary to get into parliament following elections June
19-20.
	   According to polls conducted by the independent Sofres-Factum
agency and published Friday by the daily Mlada Fronta Dnes, support
for the Christian Democrats and the Freedom Union sank to 6 percent
and 5.4 percent, respectively.
	   The opposition Social Democrats lead with 26.7 percent, followed
by Klaus' party, with 19.5 percent.
	   Pollsters queried 1,554 people Wednesday. No margin of error was
given.
	   Freedom Union leader Jan Ruml angrily dismissed Klaus' appeals,
saying votes for his party would be in double digits.
	   While the poll showed 47 percent Czechs would support a grand
coalition of the Social Democrats, Civic Democratic Party and
Freedom Union, all three parties have repeatedly said no such
coalition is possible.
	   Regular parliamentary elections had been scheduled for 2000. But
Klaus' government collapsed in November over a party financing
scandal, and a caretaker government with a limited mandate was
installed.
	   (nr/scl) 	   
</TEXT>
