<BODY>
<SLUG> MENEM-IN-TROUBLE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Menem in trouble, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Menem in trouble, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   President Carlos Menem's prophecy that Argentina will win the
World Cup has been greeted with a sense of foreboding, and not
elation, by his countrymen, who seem to believe that the President
and good results in soccer do not go together. They are still
haunted by the rankling memories of Argentina's 0-5 drubbing at the
hands of the Colombians in 1993, when Menem was among the
spectators. That was enough to seal the President's fate, as the
soccer-crazy people of his country decided to unofficially ban him
from watching Argentina's matches!
	   It is not known why they turned their ire on a man who could not
have wished anything ominous for the team . Perhaps, the fans were
stunned by the way Argentina lost to a neighbour, and were looking
for a scapegoat! Finally, none other than the President had to take
the blame !The whole thing might appear to be a case of a sport
being blown out of proportions. But then one has to go beyond the
bounds of logic to discover why the Argentines took the defeat so
seriously. Soccer is their life. So winning in this game means a
lot more than scoring a valuable point. This is perhaps true not
only of the Argentines but the South Americans in general. When
their players failed miserably, the soccer fans could not believe
their eyes, but were still not ready to blame them.
	   The cult heroes do enjoy a great degree of impunity. Even a poor
performance on their part was attributed to a phenomenon not very
easy to explain or elaborate.The Argentine players, however, had
proved their worth many times in the past to become heroes in the
eyes of their fans. So one mishap' did not shatter their
reputation.President Menem has tried to clear his name of a stigma'
by saying that his team will come out victorious in France. If he
can prove himself right, the Argentine fans will have to look for
alternative sources of trouble' when things go wrong in future.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:MENEM-IN-TROUBLE sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
