<HEADER>
w1140 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  NUCLEAR-CONFLAGRATIONske     06-12 1740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> NUCLEAR-CONFLAGRATION sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nuclear conflagration in South Asia: What the G-8 nations can do, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Nuclear conflagration in South Asia: What the G-8 nations can do, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Barrister Harun ur RashidASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   India and Pakistan exploded nuclear devices last month to the
dismay of the international community. The Security Council and the
major powers expressed their disappointment and unanimously
deplored the actions of both India and Pakistan. The US and Japan
imposed immediate economic sanctions on new loans and fresh
financial non-humanitarian aid. The major powers, otherwise known
as G-8 countries (USA, UK, France, Germany, Canada, Italy, Russia
and Japan), are meeting today, 12th of June for further discussions
on taking coordinated action to defuse the highly tense and
volatile situation in the sub-continent. If the G-8 countries
(which represent 60% of the GDP of the world) want to put a halt to
th7up for the Comprehensive Test
Ban Treaty (CTBT) or the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT)
will continue to fall on deaf ears.
	   It is wrong to assume that mere condemnation or limited
sanctions by the major powers will deter them from the path of a
potentially armed conflict. The region in perspective: It is an
admitted fact that the situation is much more dangerous than it was
a few weeks ago. Though India and Pakistan are not as yet on the
brink of hostilities, all the elements of an armed conflict are
there. It may be noted that on the ground, it has been reported
that there has recently been ``routine firing'' in the 80 km
Siachen Glacier where Indian and Pakistan troops face each other
across a line of control in divided Kashmir territory. Any
misunderstanding or misjudgment could even start a disastrous
border war. The volatile nature of the relationship between India
and Pakistan is rooted in the dispute on Kashmir ( a
Muslim-majority territory). Kashmir is divided between India and
Pakistan, with both sides claiming territorial rights over it.
India and Pakistan fought their first war over disputed Kashmir in
1948.
	   After India's defeat by China over disputed frontiers in the
Himalayas in 1962, the second war was fought on Kashmir in 1965.
The third war in 1971 ended with erstwhile East Pakistan becoming
an independent and sovereign Bangladesh in a parallel War of
Liberation. Since the BJP-led government came into political power
in mid-March of this year, the situation has been further
exacerbated as it threatens to implement one of the BJP
manifestoes' to reclaim the whole territory of Kashmir. The
statement of the Indian Home Minister LK Advani, (former President
of BJP ) to the effect that India's nuclear tests have ``brought
about a qualitatively new stage in Indo-Pakistani relations ......
it signifies India's resolve to deal firmly and strongly with
Pakistan's hostile designs and activities in Kashmir. `` How would
you read this statement if you were a Pakistani ?It appears that
when the BJP-led government became much more belligerent after the
explosion of nuclear devices, Pakistan reacted strongly to the
threat by India and declared its own nuclear strength to withstand
India's ``aggression''.
	   This was a tit-for-tat response to correct the strategic
imbalance in the sub-continent and also a signal to India to
refrain from any misadventure on Pakistan's side of Kashmir.
Sanctions counter-productive? Unless comprehensive and collective
sanctions including trade are imposed on a country, experience
shows that sanctions do not bite. Many examples can be cited as to
the ineffectual effects of haphazard sanctions (at present Cuba,
Libya, Iran and earlier Southern Rhodesia and South Africa.) In the
present scenario Russia, Germany and France do not approve of
sanctions for either India or for Pakistan. So far, only the US and
Japan have imposed sanctions. One may note, however, that the
sanctions apply only on fresh loans or new non-humanitarian
financial aid. There is a view that both India and Pakistan will
rough it out as they appear to be safe for at least one year as
sanctions will not affect the loans or aid already approved or in
the pipeline. Under the guise of ``nuclear nationalism'', both the
countries have justified their actions.
	   (In Pakistan especially there was popular pressure on the
government to retaliate Indian action as a matter of national
pride.) An overwhelming majority of the public of both countries
appear to be jubilant and proud of the actions taken by their
respective governments. Both governments have warned their citizens
to brace for economic hardships, with the Pakistan Prime Minister
promising that Pakistani children would take only one meal a day if
that was the price to pay for nuclear tests. With such emotional
patriotic rhetoric, sanctions will in effect unify the people
further and strengthen the hands of the government. Regrettably,
sanctions will not make the reality of the nuclear tests go away,
instead it will only make the poor nations poorer. As a result, the
governments may be tempted not to repay any debts till the
sanctions remain and in that case the foreign banks and
international or regional financial institutions will be affected
adversely. If India and Pakistan become financially desperate, one
cannot rule out the possibility that they be at liberty to make
money by selling its nuclear capabilities to other nuclear'
aspirant nations.
	   What's more, sanctions could isolate this region that perceives
itself already under siege. What can the G-8 countries do? The G-8
countries should realise that this is not a region where nuclear
deterrence may work so easily, because this area has a history of
hostility, territorial disputes and animosity rooted in religion.
Intense distrust, suspicion and contiguous borders constitute a
combustible situation. Furthermore, poor detection capabilities on
each other's actions and absence of zero warning time may tempt
them to make a preemptive strike against each other. It is in this
that the real danger lies of a war between the two countries. All
the G-8 countries are aware of the immense and enduring tensions in
the sub-continent between India and Pakistan on the unresolved
dispute of Kashmir. The present status quo in Kashmir is contrary
to the UN resolution which states that the status of Kashmir is to
be decided by the Kashmiri people on the basis of a free and fair
plebiscite. The 1972 Simla Agreement between India and Pakistan
speaks of the resolution of the dispute through bilateral
negotiations. Pakistan wants to sit down with India on all matters
including the Kashmir issue.
	   But, India considers Kashmir as part of its territory and
perceives Pakistan to have occupied one- third of it illegally and
does not wish to discuss Kashmir issue as it undermines its
sovereignty. The present irreconcilable position on the Kashmir
dispute is an important issue that needs to be addressed earnestly
and immediately. Although after the nuclear tests both countries
expressed their desire to open a dialogue with each other to
establish a cooperative relationship, India appears to be reluctant
to include Kashmir as an agenda for talks with Pakistan. Here lies
the bottleneck. If the G-8 countries are serious about ending this
threatening armed conflict, the first step to is to evolve a
mechanism in association with the UN through which the Kashmir
dispute may be resolved through peaceful negotiations. I would
argue that it is the only avenue to defuse the tension permanently
in the sub-continent. The major powers reacted quickly and at the
rhetorical level strongly at the detonation of nuclear devices by
both India and Pakistan. It is not merely the conduct of nuclear
tests that is at issue here.
	   The holding of nuclear explosions is only a symptom of deep
suspicion and distrust on each other's design on the disputed
territory of Kashmir. In fact, what has happened in the region is a
result of the failure of major powers to appreciate the underlying
cause of the tension in the region because of the pending Kashmir
dispute. The G-8 countries must focus on a strategy to prevent an
armed conflict from occurring between India and Pakistan. The
crucial issue is: how to settle peacefully the vexed question of
the Kashmir dispute? Until and unless the major powers are strong
enough to put pressure on India and Pakistan to resolve this
territorial issue, durable peace in the region is a far cry.
Neither sanctions nor rhetorical statements would be enough to
contain the unstable situation in the sub-continent. If the major
powers miss the opportunity to bring India and Pakistan to the
negotiating table on the Kashmir dispute, the de facto nuclear
moratorium will be finally over.
	   Soon we may witness a few other countries conducting nuclear
tests and late President Kennedy could become right when he
predicted that by 2000 there could be 32 countries which would have
nuclear weapons capability. The five official nuclear countries
(US, UK, France, Russia and China) have no credible standing to
preach to other countries unless they decide a time-table to
destroy their own nuclear weapons, otherwise it will reflect an
attitude of double standard The five nuclear countries have to get
their act together to agree on a schedule to end their nuclear
status and it would have a decisive influence on other countries.
The world has a great stake in halting the nuclear proliferation
and we will watch with great interest what course of action the
major powers (G-8 countries) would take at the meeting. The writer
is a former Bangladesh Ambassador to the UN in Geneva.
	   
</TEXT>
