<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Slain Journalist </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Lawmakers plan own investigation into reporter's killing
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ A group of lawmakers said Friday they will conduct
their own investigation into the killing of a newspaper editor who
was also a regional co-chairman of their Yabloko party.
	   Larisa Yudina, editor of the Soviet Kalmykia Today newspaper,
disappeared Sunday after leaving her home in Elista, capital of the
Kalmyk Republic in southern Russia. She was found dead Monday, with
multiple knife wounds and a fractured skull.
	   Lawmaker Sergei Ivanenko said Yabloko members in the State Duma,
the lower house of parliament, would conduct an investigation
separate from the police ``to put pressure on the government'' to
find the killer.
	   Soviet Kalmykia Today is the only opposition newspaper in
Kalmykia and Yudina frequently wrote stories critical of President
Kirsan Yulimzhinov.
	   Russian media have reported that Yudina left her home to meet
someone who promised to give her documents about a misappropriation
of funds.
	   Interior Minister Sergei Stepashin has said Yudina's killing was
a ``contract and political'' one.
	   ``One cannot be absolutely sure that there will be no attempts
to halt the investigation of this crime,'' Ivanenko told the
Interfax news agency.
	   Three people, including a former official in Yulimzhinov's
administration, have been detained in connection with the killing.
	   (ls) 	   
</TEXT>
