<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Train Crash </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Train traffic nearly back to normal 10 days after Germany's worst
</HEADLINE>
train crash &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   HANOVER, Germany (AP) _ Train traffic was nearly back to normal
in Germany Friday, 10 days after the nation's worst postwar train
crash that officials say killed 100 people.
	   Twenty-four of the 59 first generation InterCity Express trains
that were pulled out of service for special ultrasonic tests of the
wheels have been inspected, a railway spokesman in Hamburg said. No
defects have been found.
	   Authorities have said they are nearly certain a broken wheel on
a first generation ICE train caused the June 3 derailment and
devastating crash at Eschede, 60 kilometers (35 miles) north of
Hanover.
	   Inspection for wheel defects on the high-speed ICEs has been
taking about 12 hours for each train, the spokesman said.
	   The trains pulled out of service for inspection were replaced by
slower inter-regional trains, with some additional coaches borrowed
from Austria and Switzerland to help fill the gap.
	   After days of uncertainty about how many people had died in the
crash because bodies were so badly mutilated, police in Celle said
that the figure of 100 released on Thursday still stands.
Previously the number of dead was put as high as 102 and as low as
95.
 &UR; (gb-pfg)
</TEXT>
