<HEADLINE>
Rafidah: Submit status report on centre, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Rafidah: Submit status report on centre, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MALACCA, Thurs. - The State Government has been directed to
submit a status report on its industrial composite centre in Taboh
Naning, Alor Gajah, as its progress was not satisfactory.
	   The development of the area, supposed to be the country's main
composite industrial centre, has not reached expectations.
	   International Trade and Industry Minister Datuk Seri Rafidah
Aziz said there was a lot more to be done to expand the project.
	   Speaking after chairing the state-level industrial development
and co- ordination meeting, she said the matter which was one of
the subjects discussed needed to be given emphasis by the State
Government.
	   ``We have reviewed the overall development...it is still
concentrated on Phase One, that is production of light Eagle
aircraft components.
	   ``It is the hope of the Government that this area could also
become the venue for other projects that require composite
materials in its productions or for its research and development
activity.''
	   She said the State Government had been asked to submit a status
report on the project to enable her ministry to line up future
programmes for the area.
	   ``The Government has earmarked Malacca as the country's
composite industrial development centre. It looks like a lot needs
to be done. With the report, the Federal Government, through my
ministry, will be able to assist to expand the project.'' ``
	   Rafidah also revealed that the State Government had identified
134 hectares in Serkam for `halal food' activities.
	   She said export-oriented `halal food' productions would be
carried out by both local and foreign investors to penetrate the
global market.
	   A joint committee comprising representatives from the State
Government and Federal Government had been formed to identify
viable produce.
	   She added the Economic Planning Unit in the Prime Minister's
Department had approved the project and its allocations.
	   Rafidah also said a technical committee had been formed to
oversee the development of the inland port in Taboh Naning.
	   
</TEXT>
