<SLUG> COST-DETECTION-UNITS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEDCs told to set up cost detection units, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
SEDCs told to set up cost detection units, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Hamidah AtanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MALACCA, Thurs. - All States, through their respective State
Economic Development Corporations, have been asked to set up a
`cost detection unit' so that Malaysia can continue to remain
cost-competitive in the global market.
	   This is also to enhance efficiency in the industrial and trade
sectors.
	   International Trade and Industry Minister Datuk Seri Rafidah
Aziz said today the formation of the unit was inevitable for
industries and businesses to expand.
	   ``This unit must be set up so that we will be able to determine
the norms and standards of the costs.
	   ``These standards will become the benchmark for comparison. If
the cost goes up, we will know how to react by taking the necessary
measures,'' she said after chairing the state-level industrial
development and co- ordination meeting today.
	   Also present were Chief Minister Datuk Seri Abu Zahar Isnin, who
is also State Development Corporation chairman, his deputy Datuk
Ibrahim Durum, other Executive Council members and industrialists
operating in Malacca.
	   Rafidah said local and foreign investors and businessmen should
strive to ensure the country remained an ideal cost-competitive
location.
	   ``There is a need for us to determine the actual costs. If there
is no proper monitoring, we will lose our competitiveness,'' she
said.
	   She also said the Federal Government and agencies including her
ministry would assist SEDCs to determine the cost price for
industries and trade.
	   She said benchmark marking was important to enable Malaysia to
compete with other countries.
	   ``Once this becomes an exercise, it will become our business
culture. We will know how to react when costs go up. We will become
more efficient and conscious to save costs.''
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
