<SLUG> BINATIONAL-CONFERENCE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BINATIONAL CONFERENCE CLOSES OPERATION CASABLANCA STILL A SORE SPOT, THE NEWS
</HEADLINE>
Binational Conference Closes Operation Casablanca Still A Sore Spot, The News &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   THE NEWS
   MEXICO
   ENGLISH
LATIN AMERICA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E.,

<TEXT>
2nd Floor WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax:
202-546-4194 COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE
OF FDCH, INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS
CONTAINED HEREIN MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO
WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Foreign Relations Secretary Rosario Green joined U.S. Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright at a press conference on Operation
Casablanca Thursday, Associated Press reported.
	   Green noted that both governments were taking steps to improve
cooperation and communication on drug enforcement, including the
installation of direct telephone lines between the two foreign
relations offices.
	   As for Operation Casablanca, Green said, ''The investigation has
to be pursued according to law.'' But Albright put limits Thursday
on American cooperation with a Mexican investigation into alleged
violations of Mexican law by the U.S. undercover agents who carried
out the anti-narcotics sting operation in Mexico.
	   Saying that the United States will cooperate ''as possible,''
she added that prosecution and extradition of American agents would
be counterproductive. She spoke after Cabinet-level discussions on
a range of cross-border issues.
	   Her comments raised the possibility of a conflict with Mexican
authorities, who are preparing to accuse the U.S. agents of a
series of violations while in Mexico carrying out Operation
Casablanca.
	   In a move that would obstruct any attempt to extradite the
agents, Alabama Republican Representative Spencer Bachus introduced
a proposal to Congress that would protect the agents, Notimex
reported.
	   U.S. House Resolution 288 states ``the United States should
reject the extraditions solicited by Mexico of the agents involved
in Operation Casablanca due to the actions they took in benefit of
the operation.''
	   Albright's statements and the accompanying legislative
maneuvering come on the same day the New York Times published an
article reporting that Albright and U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert
Rubin disagreed on whether or not to inform Mexican officials of
Operation Casablanca.
	   According to the article, Albright was willing to inform Mexican
authorities of the investigation, but Rubin decided to maintain its
secrecy.
	   The Secretary of State sent a letter to Rubin insisting that
``we need to do a better job of coordination,'' with Mexico.
	   During meetings held in November and December on the
investigation, U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno said the secrecy of
the investigation could have ``collateral'' effects on relations
with Mexico such as a negative reaction by financial markets in
addition to the expected diplomatic troubles.
	   However, Rubin decided to continue the secrecy of the operation
because of the Treasury Department's ``skepticism'' about
corruption in Mexico, the article reported.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE NEWS all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
