<HEADLINE>
FOLLOWING CLASH, COCOPA ASKED TO TAKE CHARGE, THE NEWS
</HEADLINE>
Following Clash, Cocopa Asked To Take Charge, The News &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   THE NEWS
   MEXICO
   ENGLISH
LATIN AMERICA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E.,

<TEXT>
2nd Floor WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax:
202-546-4194 COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE
OF FDCH, INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS
CONTAINED HEREIN MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO
WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   One day after clashes in Chiapas left nine people dead, a
prominent federal deputy called on the congressional mediation body
Thursday to find persons of ``moral quality'' to help re-establish
peace talks, Notimex reported.
	   National Action Party (PAN) Deputy Santiago Creel Miranda said
the Conciliation and Pacification Commission (Cocopa) must appoint
negotiators with ``moral authority'' or that represent institutions
which have proven to be capable of contributing to peace in the
southeastern state.
	   ``Certainly Congress can not remain removed from the situation
when we have a commission like Cocopa, which must reinforce its
activities in order to facilitate the road to peace,'' said Creel.
	   Creel also disagreed with calls for the rebel Zapatista Army of
National Liberation (EZLN) and the government to meet face-to-face.
	   Members of Cocopa were not silent on Thursday either, Agence
France-Presse reported.
	   The legislative negotiating body made a ``desperate'' call to
the government to stop hostilities in Chiapas, which this week has
witnessed the most intense violence since the EZLN rebelled on Jan.
	   1, 1994.
	   Outside Mexico City, meanwhile, the 53 people arrested during
the skirmish between EZLN supporters and the Army in El Bosque
provided their declarations before the local Public Ministry,
Notimex reported.
	   
</TEXT>
