<HEADLINE>
OAXACA POLICE ON LOOKOUT FOR POSSIBLE EPR COUNTERATTACK, THE NEWS
</HEADLINE>
Oaxaca Police On Lookout For Possible Epr Counterattack, The News &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   THE NEWS
   MEXICO
   ENGLISH
LATIN AMERICA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E.,

<TEXT>
2nd Floor WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax:
202-546-4194 COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE
OF FDCH, INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS
CONTAINED HEREIN MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO
WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   OAXACA, Oax. -- Police in Oaxaca say they are on the look-out
for a reprisal attack by the People's Revolutionary Army, which
lost 12 comrades in a bloody gunfight with police Sunday, Spanish
news agency EFE reported.
	   This state's Attorney General's Office said fears were piqued
Thursday by the detention of a presumed rebel who was arrested with
possession of weapons and ammunition.
	   The arrest was made in Oaxaca's Loxicha region known as a hotbed
of EPR activity. Eighty area Indians have been arrested with having
EPR ties.
	   Adalberto Pacheco Santiago was found in possession of three
high-powered guns, including one Israeli model commonly used by the
Guatemalan and El Salvador governments, and portable radio
communication gear.
	   Pacheco's mother told the local press Thursday that her
20-year-old son has been missing since January and pleaded to
judicial authorities not to make unfounded accusations.
	   The EPR first appeared in Guerrero on June 28, 1996, and carried
out a deadly three-town attack in Mexico on Aug. 29 that ended with
at least 10 dead.
	   Authorities have cracked down on the group, which operates
mainly in Pacific Coast states Guerrero and Oaxaca.
	   A Sunday shoot-out with a military patrol in the town of El
Charco in Guerrero ended with 12 killed and 26 detained. Theories
have swirled as to what sparked the shoot-out or what the EPR was
doing at El Charco. One theory suggested EPR members were attending
a meeting at a local schoolhouse with another indigenous guerrilla
group, the EPRI, when soldiers discovered them.
	   Yet another theory says members of the EPR have admitted they
were trying to recruit local residents in the mountainous El Charco
region when they were discovered by soldiers.
	   The Associated Press reported, though, that no local townspeople
were among the dead at El Charco. All 11 were alleged active EPR
members, officials said. Only the three men who ran into the school
building were actually armed. The clash at the schoolhouse in El
Charco, was among the bloodiest clashes since the EPR emerged in
June 1996.
	   Among the 27 people arrested after the clash, two have admitted
being active members of the EPR and have given authorities
information about the group's operations, the statement said.
	   It said two EPR members, identified as Ericka Zamora Pardo and
Efren Cortez Chavez, told authorities they were holding a
recruitment meeting in the schoolhouse and planned to spend the
night there.
	   
</TEXT>
