<HEADLINE>
Malcon V to be disbanded in July at Kota Baru camp, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Malcon V to be disbanded in July at Kota Baru camp, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PETALING JAYA, Thurs. - The Malaysian Contingent V, which has
served under the North Atlantic Treaty Organisation's Stabilisation
Force in Bosnia- Herzegovina, will be disbanded at the Desa
Pahlawan Camp in Kota Baru on July 18.
	   Armed Forces chief Jen Tan Sri Ismail Omar said today that
Defence Minister Datuk Seri Syed Hamid Albar would officiate the
ceremony, marking the end of Malaysia's large-scale peacekeeping
involvement in Bosnia- Herzegovina.
	   Ismail said that the members of Malcon V and their equipment
would then be absorbed and redeployed into the mainstream of the
various army, navy and air force units.
	   Ismail said this after receiving the advanced group of 300
Malcon V soldiers, led by Mejar Zulkafli Abdul Aziz, who returned
home tonight on board a chartered Malaysia Airlines DC-10 aircraft
at the Royal Malaysian Air Force base in Subang.
	   The aircraft, which was delayed due to technical hitches,
arrived from Split, Croatia at 7.30pm.
	   Also present to greet the Malcon V members were Army chief Jen
Datuk Seri Mohd Zahidi Zainuddin, RMAF chief Lt Jen Datuk Seri
Ahmad Saruji Che Rose and senior Armed Forces' officers.
	   Ismail said that Malcon V's main group of 278 soldiers would
arrive on June 24 with the final group of 211 soldiers on July 10.
	   The 789-strong Malcon V, which began its tour of duty on Dec 25
last year under the command of Kol Syed Khalid Syed Mahmood,
comprised 80 officers, 704 other ranks and five civillians.
	   Malcon V, Ismail said, would be replaced by the combined
Belgium- Luxembourg force.
	   ``A handing-over ceremony, to be officiated by the Malaysian
ambassador to Bosnia-Herzegovina, will be held on June 22 at
Livno.''
	   With the withdrawal of Malcon V following the end of Nato's
mandate, Malaysia's stint in Bosnia-Herzegovina will not end as the
Government had approved up to 50 soldiers to be deployed there.
	   ``The 50, who will be part of Nato's Deterrent Force assigned to
remove landmines and bring war criminals to justice, will be sent
as early as next month.''
	   
</TEXT>
