	   Public Safety Secretary Rodolofo Debernardi Debernardi is
revamping his department, getting rid of the subsecretariat and
reorganizing lower offices, reported Federal District Legislative
Assembly Dep. Armando Salinas Torre.
	   After conducting a work meeting with Debernardi, Salinas Torre,
of the pro-business National Action Party (PAN) who serves as the
president of the Committee on Public Safety, said that the
secretariat is lacking a sound crime prevention program and that
until now only emergency plans have been drawn up.
	   Salinas Torre said the only plans implemented have been
``reaction cells'' and new special security efforts now being
provided in 14 neighborhoods -- plans Debernardi presented about
two weeks ago to the local legislative assembly, known as the ALDF.
	   But Salinas Torre said Debernardi did not give sufficient
answers, failing to respond to how officers are selected for the
police corps and how they are picked to be placed in the
neighborhood anti-crime program. ``It is seen a 'programmed
diarrhea' now that the government has not been capable of including
a total program of Public Safety, nor of structuring new
programs,'' Salinas Torre said.
	   The local legislator described as serious the fact that 28
separate departments within the Public Safety Secretariat have no
department heads.
	   Salinas Torre said during Debernardi's meeting with legislators
the minimum salary for police officers is 3,507 pesos a month.
Nevertheless, Debernardi said, fewer police are following paths
into corruption.
	   Salinas Torre said ``instead of a secretary, we have a chief of
a sectorship who can tell us how many units are in bad shape or the
number of police that there are, but not the foundations of his
crime-fighting operation.'' 
