<HEADLINE>
Board reverses earlier decision requiring students to pass CLP, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Board reverses earlier decision requiring students to pass CLP, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Thurs. - Law students in Australian and New
Zealand universities who enrolled on or before April 30, and who
have commenced studies will be exempted from sitting the
Certificate in Legal Practice to qualify as a lawyer in Malaysia.
	   Legal Profession Qualifying Board chairman Tan Sri Mohtar
Abdullah announced this decision, made on June 3, in a statement
today.
	   The announcement reverses the board's earlier decision requiring
students who graduate after May 1 next year to pass the CLP, which
means that only final-year students are exempted.
	   Mohtar said the decision to exempt current students was made
after the board considered appeals from students, parents and deans
of Australian law schools.
	   The exemption will only apply to students in full-time study who
have commenced their first year or first semester in a law course,
and who will complete the course in Australia or New Zealand. This
includes students within recognised twinning programmes.
	   However, students who transfer courses from a university outside
Australia and New Zealand into one in these two countries are not
exempted.
	   Students enrolling on or after May 1, are also bound by the
guidelines.
	   Exempted students will be required to obtain a certificate from
the board.
	   ``The decision and the process of its implementation have been
conveyed to all recognised universities in Australia and New
Zealand,'' Mohtar said.
	   Besides the new CLP requirement, the guidelines which came into
force on April 30 also set criteria for the recognition of degrees
from the two countries.
	   The criteria will also apply only to those who enrolled on or
after April 30.
	   The issuance of the guidelines is a move to standardise the
entry requirements to the Malaysian Bar.
	   They are similar to those issued in 1995 for universities in the
United Kingdom.
	   The 14 recognised Australian universities are Monash University,
University of Melbourne, Australian National University, University
of Sydney, University of Adelaide, University of Western Australia,
Macquarie University, University of New South Wales, University of
Queensland, University of Tasmania, University of Technology in
Sydney, Bond University in Queensland, Murdoch University and
Queensland University of Technology.
	   The five recognised universities in New Zealand are University
of Auckland, University of Canterbury, Victoria University of
Wellington, University of Otago and University of Waikato.
	   
</TEXT>
