<SLUG> CRITICS-DECRY-DELAY-CITY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICS DECRY DELAY OF CITY CAR INSURANCE PROGRAM, THE NEWS
</HEADLINE>
Critics Decry Delay Of City Car Insurance Program, The News &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   THE NEWS
   MEXICO
   ENGLISH
LATIN AMERICA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E.,

<TEXT>
2nd Floor WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax:
202-546-4194 COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE
OF FDCH, INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS
CONTAINED HEREIN MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO
WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Mayor Cuauhtemoc Cardenas not only encourages a culture of
irresponsibility, but also breaks the law, said local PAN and PT
deputies, who say they are angry that a mandatory car-insurance
program has been shelved for a year.
	   ``The PAN demands that Cardenas rectifies that error,'' said
Pablo Jaime Jimenez, of the pro-business National Action Party
(PAN).
	   Jimenez said Cardenas needs to let the local legislative
assembly, known as the ALDF, debate the postponement of the SUVA
insurance program.
	   His comments also seemed targeted at Federal District officials
who said they were suspending the SUVA plan to foster ``a culture
of responsibility'' among Mexico City citizens. The plan was to go
into effect July 1, 1998 and requires Mexico City's more than 3
million cars to have third-party car insurance.
	   Cardenas on Wednesday declared that implementation of the SUVA
plan be delayed until July 1, 1999, provoking a backlash only a few
days before it was to go into effect. Moreover, mix-ups this week
between Cardenas and staff members confused the time of
postponement to between six months and one year. In his statements
Thursday Jimenez called Cardenas a lawbreaker because the mayor did
not go through proper legislative channels to validate postponement
of SUVA.
	   ``If they admit these arbitrary rulings, there will be a
negative feeling against the government and society because if the
government violates the law and it is allowed, afterward it will
have no moral authority to demand that the people follow the law,''
Jimenez said.
	   Shortly after Cardenas took office Dec. 5, 1997, Federal
District transportation officials heralded the SUVA plan as part of
an improved and revamped Federal District traffic code, which
included beefed-up transit laws. Besides SUVA, fines were increased
and the city passed an ordinance requiring all drivers to buckle
up.
	   Mix-ups this week have confused the situation. Wednesday
Cardenas said the insurance system would be postponed one year, but
Tuesday he said the plan was being suspended for only six months.
	   On Tuesday Federal District Transportation Director Raymundo
Artis Espriu and Federal District spokesman Javier Gonzalez Garza
offered a news conference in which they made pains to assert it was
unknown when the SUVA program would enter into full force.
	   Contrary to Cardenas' statements, Gonzalez Garza said the exact
start date would not be known until this coming Monday. Gonzalez
Garza also said officials were delaying the plan in order to foster
``a culture of responsibility.''
	   Cardenas explained that one of the reasons to postpone the full
entry of the insurance system is that authorities still have not
yet determined how cars from other federal or state entities will
be handled if they are found in violation of the SUVA law.
	   But despite the apparently mixed signals between Cardenas and
lower Federal District officials, one thing seems certain: the city
may lose the insurance program simply from disinterest by citizens.
	   Of the little more than 3 million cars that are driven in the
Federal District, only 850,000 -- not even a third -- have
insurance.
	   People do not seem very interested in complying with the
program, citing a lack of money, although the fine for not
complying with the SUVA will be 25 minimum daily salaries -- more
than 300 pesos.
	   More than 20,000 people have been injured in automobile
accidents in 1998, according to figures offered by the city
prosecutor's office (PGJDF).
	   Monterrey company Aba/Seguros said that it has already begun to
offer the SUVA to the public at the cost of 299 pesos annually,
including IVA. Another company was quoted as selling the SUVA at an
annual cost of about 450 pesos.
	   Some ALDF deputies and many city officials said they were happy
with the decision to postpone the entrance of the SUVA system.
	   ``It would be very difficult that in July the sanction program
would enter in vigor, now that there are many things to clarify,
such as who will be responsible for not verifying what had been
completed and where and how violators would be prosecuted,'' said
the president of the ALDF's Transportation and Ways Committee,
Elvira Albarran.
	   Authorities say drivers who have already bought insurance do not
need to worry because coverage will start beginning July 1, 1999.
	   A Monterrey insurance company said that it has already begun to
offer the SUVA to the public at the cost of 299 pesos annually,
including IVA. Another company was quoted as selling the SUVA at an
annual cost of about 450 pesos.
	   
</TEXT>
