	   KULIM, Thurs. - Despite the economic slowdown, the Education
Ministry will proceed with its proposed conversion scheme for
certificate holders among teachers to enable them to enjoy the same
starting salary as their diploma-holder counterparts.
	   Minister Datuk Seri Najib Tun Razak said the teachers would not
be required to enrol in teacher training colleges again to enjoy
the same starting pay.
	   ``We are working on a conversion programme based on their
experience.
	   ``There is a scheme that we are working on and I will announce
it later,''
	   he said after launching the Sekolah Menengah Kebangsaan Sultan
Badlishah's golden anniversary celebrations here today. The school
was established in 1948.
	   Also present were State Assemblymen for Kulim and Lunas Datuk
Yong Pau Chak and Dr Joe Fernandez respectively and school
principal Abdul Rahim Mohd Said. He stressed the conversion
exercise would be carried out progressively, possibly next year.
	   Najib was asked if the Government was still considering allowing
certificate holders among teachers to enjoy the same starting
salary as diploma-holder teachers.
	   Yesterday, he announced the promotion of 3,000 graduate and
non-graduate teachers under an exercise, involving RM18.9 million,
to reward long- serving teachers.
	   When the diploma course programme was introduced at all teacher
training colleges in 1996, the ministry had also announced that
certificate holders among teachers should attend special courses
for up to eight weeks at the colleges to enjoy the starting salary
of their diploma-holder counterparts.
	   Earlier, Najib said that the Ministry had allocated RM5 million
to train 1,780 information technology trainees and to conduct IT
courses for 30,000 primary and secondary school teachers.
	   
</TEXT>
