<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bosnia-Serbs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Moderate Bosnian Serbs and hard-liners form coalitions each
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By IRENA GAJIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BANJA LUKA, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) _ Hard-liners and
reformists, two main power blocs in the Bosnian Serb republic,
Friday formed coalitions, teaming up for September elections in
Bosnia.
	   In Banja Luka, in northwestern Bosnia, moderate Bosnian Serb
leaders, triumphant and cheering, joined hands to seal their fresh
alliance in a move aimed at winning key points ahead of the ballot.
	   The three reformist Bosnian Serb parties united forces by
signing an accord to run as a coalition titled ``Harmony.''
	   The three parties, with Western support, already dominate the
government of the Serb-controlled half of Bosnia.
	   Their new alliance is intended to secure them three top
positions: the republic's presidency and two posts reserved for
Serbs in Bosnia's joint presidency and government.
	   The Serb National Alliance, Socialist Party and the Independent
Social Democrats are expected to agree on a joint slate of three
candidates for the posts, with each party contributing one. The
leader of the Serb National Alliance, Biljana Plavsic, is thought
likely to be the consensus choice for Serb Republic president, a
post she already holds.
	   Meanwhile, Bosnian Serb hard-liners, comprising loyalists of
war-time leader Radovan Karadzic, and the ultranationalist Radical
Party formed their own coalition Friday in the eastern Bosnian town
of Bijeljina, the Bosnian Serb news agency Srna reported.
	   The hard-liners announced that their joint candidate to run
against Plavsic for the Bosnian Serb presidency would be Nikola
Poplasen from the ranks of ultranationalists.
	   Poplasen and Aleksa Buha, from Karadzic's party, signed the
coalition agreement and said they would later come up with the
names of their joint candidates for the other two top posts.
	   If successful, the reformists' alliance could unseat two key
Bosnian Serb hardliners: Momcilo Krajisnik, who holds the Serb seat
in the three-man Bosnian presidency, and Boro Bosic, who is a
co-chairman in Bosnia's joint government.
	   (ig/kk/rp) 	   
</TEXT>
