<HEADLINE>
CARDENAS TOURS LA MERCED, THE NEWS
</HEADLINE>
Cardenas Tours La Merced, The News &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   THE NEWS
   MEXICO
   ENGLISH
LATIN AMERICA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E.,

<TEXT>
2nd Floor WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax:
202-546-4194 COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE
OF FDCH, INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS
CONTAINED HEREIN MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO
WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The mayor of the Federal District, Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, handed
over credits to 64 stall owners of the La Merced market who were
affected by the fire that occurred in that place in May, forcing
many retailers out of business.
	   Accompanied by Venustiano Carranza borough delegate, Ramon
Sosamontes, Cardenas passed out loans ranging between 4,000 and
10,000 pesos for the purpose of helping to jump-start businesses in
the market affected by the fire.
	   During the handing over of the loans, Sosamontes reaffirmed his
commitment ``for the market to recover its capacity.''Sosamontes
told stall owners that the government mission's is to support small
business owners and, in particular the merchants of La Merced, so
that they can acquire merchandise until the market is repaired and
is in better condition than it was before the fire.
	   In an interview after the tour, Cardenas said that police
operations will continue to attempt to control the numbers of
street merchants, who are known as ambulantes.
	   He also remade his invitation to the political parties and to
the ambulantes' organizations to establish a dialogue that
contributes to finding alternatives to solve the problem.
	   
</TEXT>
