<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Safe Passage </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Human rights group condemns Israeli travel restrictions on
</HEADLINE>
Palestinians &QL; 
 &UR; By JACK KATZENELL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Israel's failure to open a ``safe passage'' to
allow Palestinians to travel between the West Bank and the Gaza
Strip constitutes collective punishment and is causing unacceptable
hardship, an Israeli human rights group charged Friday.
	   In the Israel-Palestinian agreements, Israel recognized that the
West Bank and the Gaza Strip constitute ``a single territorial
unit'' and promised to open the ``safe passage'' permitting freedom
of movement between them.
	   But two years have passed and Israel has not carried out this
commitment, citing security reasons. A limited number of
Palestinians cross between the two areas each week in convoys
guarded by Israeli border police.
	   In a report entitled ``Divide and Rule,'' the Betselem human
rights group says the Israeli policy constitutes collective
punishment.
	   ``The severance between the Gaza Strip and the West Bank
precludes development of communal, social, economic and political
life of the residents of the two areas,'' and ``creates two
Palestinian societies with weak ties between them,'' the report
says.
	   The report says Israel makes it easier for a Palestinian to get
a permit to work in Israel than to cross between the two areas.
About 72,000 Palestinian workers and businessmen have permits to
work in Israel, while only 600 permits are issued each week for
passage between the two areas.
	   To obtain a work permit, a Palestinian must be over 23, married
and with no record of crime or security offenses. To make the
crossing men must be over 45 and women over 35 and with a clean
record.
	   These discrepancies cast doubt on the claim that the
restrictions are purely for security reasons, the report argues.
	   The division has particularly devastating effects on families,
the report says. It cites the case of Hanan Sheikh Ahmed, a married
woman from the Gaza Strip who traveled to the West Bank to be with
her dying father while he underwent surgery, and was then refused a
permit to return on the grounds that she was under 35. Only after a
year, when a human rights group intervened, was she allowed to
return.
	   The restrictions also affect students living in the Gaza Strip
but studying in the West Bank, who are sometimes unable to get to
the university.
	   An Israeli official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Friday the ``safe passage'' could have been opened a long time ago
were it not for Palestinian intransigence. ``They insist on an
extra-territorial corridor, with no Israeli security checks
whatsoever,'' he told The Associated Press.
	   ``If they had accepted our proposals, a much larger number of
Palestinians would be making the crossing today and they would find
it much more convenient than the present situation,'' the official
said.
	   The restrictions were tightened in the wake of a series of
suicide bombings by Islamic militants in Israeli cities, he said.
	   Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's policy adviser David
Bar-Illan said the delay in the opening of the ``safe passage'' was
``due entirely to security considerations based on the constant and
very real threat of terrorism.''
 &UR; jk-hla
</TEXT>
