<SLUG> BC-NATO-Albania,0213 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Albanians happy with NATO decision on show of force
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With NATO-Kosovo &QL; 
 &UR; By JEFFREY ULBRICH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ Albania's defense minister said Friday
he was delighted with NATO's decision to make a show of force in
the Balkans because it is clear Yugoslavia wants to dominate the
separatist province of Kosovo militarily.
	   Luan Hajdaraga, in Brussels for a meeting between NATO and 27
partner countries in the Euro-Atlantic Partnership Council, spoke a
day after the alliance decided to conduct air exercises over
Albania and Macedonia to put pressure on Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic.
	   That show of power, expected sometime next week, was one of
several steps taken by the 16-nation North Atlantic Treaty
Organization to persuade Milosevic to stop his offensive against
ethnic Albanians in the southern Serbian province of Kosovo, where
they make up the vast majority of the population.
	   ``We are very pleased about the decision taken by the NATO
Council yesterday,'' Hajdaraga said in an interview.
	   ``The stand of Milosevic in the Kosovo crisis is very clear, it
is to dominate the situation by military means.'' The danger is, he
said, that ``those means can spread to Albania.''
</TEXT>
