<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Foreign Ministers-Protests </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Anti-nuclear demonstrators urge Group of Eight nations to disarm
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JENNY E. HELLER
 &UR; Associated Press Writer

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Demonstrators shouted ''Stop the nuclear
hyprocrisy!'' and ''Bin the bomb!'' Friday outside St. James's
Palace, directing their messages at foreign ministers meeting
nearby to discuss the crisis over India and Pakistan.
	   Three-dozen representatives from the London-based Campaign for
Nuclear Disarmament urged the foreign ministers of the Group of
Eight industrial powers to take specific steps toward a complete
ban of nuclear weapons.
	   ''We are here to make sure they can't ignore the issue,'' said
William Peden, the group's parliamentary officer. ''It's given them
a bit of a sore ear, and all the people driving past are getting
the message even if the G-8 don't.''
	   India and Pakistan exploded their first nuclear bombs last
month, but have said they had no plans for further tests.
	   After a Friday morning session, the foreign ministers from
Britain, Canada, France, Germany, Italy, Japan, Russia and the
United States decided to stop all non-humanitarian aid to the two
countries and to urge them to halt nuclear tests and deployment of
any nuclear weapons.
	   But the anti-nuclear demonstrators sought stronger action.
	   They demanded the establishment of an ad-hoc committee in Geneva
to discuss disarmament, and for the G-8 leaders to sign on to
Ireland's initiative proposed Tuesday, which would urge nuclear
powers to disarm within a few years.
	   The anti-nuclear protestors had to compete with a larger group
from the Serbian province of Kosovo, members of the Albanian
minority in the region seeking asylum in Britain.
	   They, too, were using shouts and signs to try to influence the
foreign ministers, who spent the afternoon discussing a reponse to
the Serbs' agression against ethnic Albanians.
	   ''We want NATO to go into Kosovo,'' protestor Burim Trishtina
said. ''First, we must secure all the people, and then make a
dialogue. There is no dialogue if someone holds arms to your
head.''
	   (jh-kg)
</TEXT>
