<SLUG> MARKETS-DOWN-GOVTS-CUTS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETS DOWN, GOV'T CUTS POSSIBLE, THE NEWS
</HEADLINE>
Markets Down, Gov'T Cuts Possible, The News &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   THE NEWS
   MEXICO
   ENGLISH
   JENNIFER BARSKYLATIN AMERICA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E.,

<TEXT>
2nd Floor WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax:
202-546-4194 COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE
OF FDCH, INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS
CONTAINED HEREIN MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO
WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A global market bloodbath dragged the peso and stock market down
further Thursday, increasing prospects of further budget cuts and
monetary tightening.
	   ``It was bloodshed all over - equities in emerging markets,
global bonds, currencies, commodities,''
	   said Santander Currency Trader Hector Kalb.''Everyone suffered,
it was a big flight to quality.''
	   The peso closed at 9.04 against the dollar versus Wednesday's
close of 8.90, its lowest since the new peso's introduction in
1993.
	   The market's IPC index lost 2.44 percent to close at a
seven-month low of 4289.31 points.
	   Analysts said there is little question the peso is suffering
from external shocks, not Mexico's fundamentals.
	   Asia's markets tumbled overnight as the Yen's exchange value
fell to almost an eight-year low of 143.50.
	   ``This has nothing to do with Mexico's fundamentals at all,''
said Kalb.
	   ``This is just a shift in portfolios.''
	   So unless the world situation makes a quick turn around --
unlikely in light of Russia's failed attempt to raise 7 billion
dollars in debt and the continued worsening of Asian economies --
the situation is not likely to improve in the short term.
	   Indeed it will probably worsen. ``The international situation is
being reflected in the Mexican market, said Felipe Garcia, Latin
American Economist with IDA.
	   And the only way that will change is if lenders of last resort
replenish the flows that usually keep the market steady, he said.
But they aren't there any more. ``They've taken their money and
run,'' Garcia said.
	   This trend is also reflected in foreign ownership of Mexican
treasury certificates (cetes), which has been hovering at about
10-12 percent. If the government perceives the peso's decline is
driving prices up and increasing inflation rates it may decide to
intervene.
	   ``Another budget cut seems inevitable and another monetary
tightening not far from happening,'' said Jorge de Gotari,
Santander's Latin American fixed-income analyst. A tightening of
monetary policy would mean higher interest rates and presumably
more interest in cetes and a stronger peso.
	   Gotari sees the potential government move as positive despite
the negative effects higher interest rates would have on bank
lending and outstanding debt.
	   ``Right now there are too many external factors that are out of
the government's hands,'' he said.
	   The most important of these are commodity prices, particularly
oil. Crude oil prices fell 5.4 percent to 12.75 dollars per barrel.
	   With about 38 percent of the government's revenues derived from
oil revenues, Finance Secretary Jose Angel Gurria, has already
implied that without a boost in prices, another budget cut will be
unavoidable.
	   The government has already cut the budget 2.85 billion dollars
this year.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE NEWS all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
