<BODY>
<SLUG> PAY-FAIR-EQUITABLE-WAGES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pay fair, equitable wages to estate workers, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Pay fair, equitable wages to estate workers, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Ganesh RasagamASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   JAWATANKUASA Sokongan Masyarakat Ladang welcomes the recent
statements in the media by various ministers on the plight of
thousands of estate workers who do not receive a monthly wage.
These workers are still bound by a colonial wage structure despite
the colonialists having left 40 years ago! While the plantation
companies have made fabulous profits over the years the estate
workers' wages are about 60 per cent of the average wage of
manufacturing workers and they have remained stagnant in real terms
for 25 years.
	   The plantation sector has been the backbone of the economy and
has continually been a major source of foreign revenue in good as
well as bad times. However, the plantation worker has always been
mired in poverty and still trapped in poor living conditions in
many estates.
	   It is quite incredible that there are 60,000 vacancies in
plantations which need to be filled and the Government is planning
to recruit foreign workers. It is obvious that the plantation
sector is unable to attract or retain a viable workforce based on
the existing wage structure and living conditions.
	   In fact, Deputy Home Minister Datuk Tajol Rosli Ghazali had said
in January that even laid-off foreign workers from other sectors
are reluctant to work in the plantations due to the tough working
conditions and low pay.
	   It is in the long-term interest of plantation companies and the
Government to make the plantation sector more attractive by
dismantling the outdated wage structure and giving the workers
monthly wages. An attractive wage structure and decent housing will
ensure the sector has an adequate workforce. This and soaring palm
oil prices will help plantation companies increase their
productivity and profits.
	   For far too long the issue of plantation workers' wages has been
left to the plantation companies and workers' representatives to
decide through negotiations without much success. It is now time
for the Government to intervene in this process in the interest of
the country's economic recovery.
	   The committee has been campaigning for a minimum monthly wage,
annual increments and bonus payments similar to the other sectors
as well as better retirement benefits. It is time to correct the
historical injustices of the past and give fair and equitable wages
to estate workers.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
