<SLUG> PHASING-OUT-OF-LEADED sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Phasing out of leaded petrol unjustified, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Phasing out of leaded petrol unjustified, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   N. BalaASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   I REFER to the report on the phasing out of leaded petrol (New
Sunday Times, May 31).
	   I use leaded petrol for my car and I believe there are several
thousand other consumers or more owning and using vehicles that can
only take in leaded petrol, and who cannot afford to buy a new car.
	   We keep our old cars in running condition and do not mind paying
a little bit more per litre for leaded petrol.
	   Unless there is a cheap way to convert such vehicles for the use
of unleaded petrol and there are motor workshops willing to do so,
the move to phase it out can only be described as unwarranted and
unjustified.
	   As far as atmospheric pollution is concerned I feel there are
other bigger culprits to go after.
	   We have no other choice but to keep on using our old vehicles as
the cost of a new vehicle or even a second-hand one is prohibitive
in these trying times.
	   I appeal to the authorities to rethink their decision and allow
us to carry on using our vehicles instead of creating piles of junk
overnight.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
