<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Kosovo-War Crimes,0238 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. war crimes tribunal to send investigators to Kosovo
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JENIFER CHAO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) _ The Yugoslav war crimes tribunal
said Friday it is sending investigators to the troubled Serbian
province of Kosovo to check out reports of possible atrocities.
	   Details of the visit, to take place in the coming weeks, were
not disclosed. Tribunal chief prosecutor Louise Arbour said the
U.N. court's investigation aimed to send a signal to both sides to
follow the rules of war.
	   The investigation has been backed by the United States, said
David Scheffer, the U.S. ambassador for war crimes issues.
	   ``We've been extremely focused on the role the tribunal can and
might be able to play in investigating what appears to be very
serious criminal activities taking place in Kosovo,'' he said.
	   Ethnic Albanians, who comprise 90 percent of the southern
province's population, are demanding independence from Serbia,
which is one of two republics in the Yugoslav federation.
	   More than 250 people have died during clashes between government
forces and the Kosovo Liberation Army, the armed wing of the
Albanian independence movement.
	   The tribunal was established by the U.N. Security Council in
1993, and its jurisdiction covers all serious violations of
international humanitarian law committed in the former Yugoslavia
since 1991. 	   
</TEXT>
