<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Croatia,0386 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Injury-plagued Croatia may have to revamp for opener
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By TONY CZUCZKA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   VITTEL, France (AP) _ Injuries may force Croatia to revamp its
team for Sunday's opener against fellow debutant Jamaica.
	   Defender Slaven Bilic remains in doubt with a muscle injury
suffered in a tuneup against Slovakia two weeks ago, coach Miroslav
Blazevic said Friday. With striker Alen Boksic already out with a
knee injury before the championship, Croatia's entire right side
could be in for a facelift.
	   And the team's top scorer, Davor Suker, was often benched at
European club champion Real Madrid this season because other
players were first choice ahead of him.
	   ``We have some problems because some players haven't had enough
competitive exposure,'' Blazevic said Friday. ``But overall, I'm
more than satisfied with the condition of the team after
practice.''
	   Despite Croatia's troubles with the health of some of its
veterans, anything other than a win in the night match at Lens
would be a major upset. A quarterfinalist in the 1996 European
Championship, its first major international tournament, Croatia is
expected to advance out of the World Cup's Group H along with
two-time champion Argentina.
	   Blazevic's lineup may yet contain a surprise or two, though.
	   Mario Stanic of Italy's Parma, a former Belgian league top
scorer, could move up from midfield to take Boksic's spot. But if
Bilic drops out _ or Blazevic rests him for the tougher next match
against Japan _ the coach would likely look for another solution.
	   True to his secretive style, Blazevic won't announce his lineup
until the day of the game.
	   The Croatians, two of whom played in the 1990 World Cup for
Yugoslavia, were preparing for their clash with the much-hyped
Jamaicans by reviewing videos of the ``Reggae Boyz'' in action.
	   In addition, defender Igor Stimac of Derby County was giving his
teammates tips on how to take on the Jamaicans, whose top players
are also with English clubs.
	   The Jamaican team angered the Croatians earlier this week by
ejecting two assistant coaches who had come to watch an open
practice. Croatia protested to soccer's governing body FIFA about
the incident.
	   (tc-sl)
</TEXT>
