<HEADLINE>
Sampras loses in straight sets to Woodforde
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Updates with Rusedski injured in grafs

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Pete Sampras suffered a setback in his Wimbledon
preparations Friday when he was beaten in straight sets by
Australia's Mark Woodforde at the Queen's Club grass-court
tournament.
	   The top-seeded Sampras, who had a bye in the first round and
beat Wayne Black in the second round, looked flat as he slumped to
a 6-3, 6-2 defeat on his favorite surface.
	   It was the latest surprising loss for Sampras, who was ousted in
the second round of the French Open by little-known Ramon Delgado
of Paraguay.
	   Sampras had beaten the 66th-ranked Woodforde, known primarily as
a doubles specialist, in all of their previous 10 matches and
dropped only two sets in the process.
	   Sampras entered Queen's as a tuneup for Wimbledon, a tournament
he has won four times and where he is the defending champion.
	   Queen's also lost its No. 2 seed when Greg Rusedski of Britain
suffered an ankle injury during his third-round match against
Italian qualifier Laurence Tieleman.
	   With the score at 2-2 in the first set, Rusedski slipped while
stretching for a backhand volley and fell awkwardly with his left
leg buckling underneath him.
	   Rusedski screamed in pain and writhed on the grass before being
carried off the court and taken to a hospital for X-rays.
	   Tournament doctor Johnnie Gaynor said it appeared to be just a
sprain. It wasn't immediately clear whether the injury would force
Rusedski to miss Wimbledon, where he reached the quarterfinals last
year.
