<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Kuwait-Parliament </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Emir deciding whether to disband Parliament
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo Available &QC; 
 &UR; By DIANA ELIAS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KUWAIT (AP) _ Kuwaitis are waiting to see if the only elected
parliament in the Gulf will be dissolved Saturday after their prime
minister said he could no longer work with the legislature.
	   The prime minister, Sheik Saad al-Abdullah al-Sabah, has
reportedly accused the 50-seat legislature of blocking economic
reforms and showing disrespect for his Cabinet.
	   Lawmakers say they are insisting on the right to question
misappropriations of government money and expensive weapons deals.
	   The emir, Sheik Jaber al-Ahmed al-Sabah, meets with the Cabinet
Saturday and is expected to decide whether to dissolve parliament
and call for elections, which should be held within two months.
	   Lawmaker Nasser al-Saneh said the emir is likely to shut down
the legislature.
	   Although Parliament has a large pro-government bloc, ``it turned
out to be a different creature'' that questions ministers and
scrutinizes weapons deals, he said.
	   Political analysts say that if elections are held, the new
legislature is likely to resemble the present one's composition.
	   Lawmakers have also been critical of laws proposed by the
government that would impose fees for services and taxes to make up
for budget shortfalls due to declining oil prices.
	   ``If there were no red lines (the Parliament) would be asked not
to cross - such as theft of public money, weapons deals and
misappropriation of government land - the other issues in the
government's complaint could be worked out,'' Abdullah al-Nibari,
an opposition lawmaker wrote in the independent Al-Qabas daily.
	   Tension between the government and legislature surfaced earlier
this month when a lawmaker said he was going to grill the interior
minister, Sheik Mohammed al-Khaled al-Sabah, over what he termed
inefficiency in fighting corruption, drugs and crime.
	   Sheik Mohammed is a member of the ruling family.
	   ``The (interior minister's) grilling was the drop that made the
glass overflow,'' al-Saneh said.
	   The parliament was elected in 1996 in the second polls since the
1991 Gulf War that ended a seven-month Iraqi occupation of the
country.
	   It has been widely criticized for wasting time in idle
discussions and for taking little action.
	   Although Kuwait has the only parliament in the region, the
country does not allow political parties and the emir has the right
to dissolve the legislature.
	   Emirs have twice dissolved parliaments that were severely
critical of government policies. Each time the dissolution lasted
years _ from 1976 to 1981 and from 1986 to 1992.
 &UR; de-lm/jbm
</TEXT>
