<SLUG> BC-Slovakia-Bilingual Protest, 1st Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Frustrated Hungarians yank their kids from schools in Slovakia
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS protest in another district in 6th graf, adds comments in
7th graf, CORRECTS name to Gyurovszki in 4th graf. &QL; 
 &UR; By JANA DOROTKOVA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRATISLAVA, Slovakia (AP) _ Tensions that have their roots in
the Austro-Hungarian Empire have erupted in a wave of school
protests by Hungarians living in Slovakia.
	   Accusing the government of blatant disregard of the nation's
largest minority, ethnic Hungarian parents have pulled their
children from school in one-day protests in several regions _ the
latest on Friday.
	   The boycott was prompted by an education bill in parliament
that, if approved as expected, would require Hungarian children to
drop Hungarian-language history classes and learn history and
geography in Slovak language instead. But the overriding issue,
according to the parents, is the government's consistently unfair
treatment of Hungarians.
	   ``We want our children to learn the Slovak language properly,
but we want them to remain Hungarian,'' said Ladislav Gyurovszki, a
leader of the Association of Hungarian Parents in Slovakia.
	   ``The state wants them to lose their national identity,'' he
said.
	   Friday's protests by Hungarians in the Galanta, Moldava and Sala
districts followed a similar one last week in Komarno.
	   Other districts were expected to join the protest next week,
said Rudolf Meszes, the chairman of the parents' association.
 &UR; While relations, 7th graf. 	   
