<SLUG> BC-Switzerland-Dalai Lama </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dalai Lama joins celebrations at Swiss Tibetan monastery
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   RIKON, Switzerland (AP) _ The exiled Tibetan spiritual leader
joined in a Swiss monastery's anniversary celebrations Friday,
consecrating 10 new prayer wheels.
	   The Tibet Institute in Rikon, near Zurich, which is celebrating
its 30th anniversary this year, becomes the first monastery in the
West to be blessed by the current Dalai Lama.
	   Since fleeing Tibet to lead his nation from exile, the Dalai
Lama has been the sole voice and face of his people. His policy of
compromise and negotiation won world support and the 1989 Nobel
Peace prize.
	   Beijing, which says Tibet has always been part of China, sent
its army to the area in 1950. The Dalai Lama fled to India nine
years later during an abortive uprising against the Chinese, and
was followed by about 100,000 refugees.
	   In Tibetan Buddhism, turning the prayer wheel, a metal cylinder
containing a sacred verse, or mantra, is equivalent to reciting a
mantra.
	   The Rikon monastery has an abbot and seven monks, all of them
Tibetan. Consecrated in November 1968, it was named the Tibet
Institute to get around a Swiss law forbidding the founding of
monasteries.
	   Some 2,500 Tibetans live in Switzerland.
 &UR; (gm)
</TEXT>
