w1234 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-France-People-Kennedy     06-12 0358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-People-Kennedy Photos </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RFK Jr. unveils family photos at UNESCO
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos PAR108,109

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Robert F. Kennedy, Jr. remembers the photographer
being there when he had breakfast in the morning and said his
prayers at night.
	   Now the pictures Jacques Lowe shot are on public display, a
record of America's premier political family and an apparent sign
that the Kennedys knew early on of their dynasty's place in
history.
	   Part of a week-long UNESCO tribute entitled ``The Kennedy
Dream,'' the 150 black-and-white photographs taken between 1956 and
1968 reveal the many sides of the Kennedy clan.
	   There's Jackie in a bathing suit and fringed cap trying to
capsize Jack rowing a small boat; JFK and Jackie on the campaign
trail, having an early-morning breakfast in an Oregon diner; Bobby
and Ethel praying with the kids at bedtime.
	   ``The show means a lot to me because Jacques captured the
happiest times, the best moments of our life,'' Kennedy told The
Associated Press at the exhibit Friday.
	   ``He was always there. He was there when we said our prayers and
our parents put us to bed, and he was there when we woke up in the
morning,'' Kennedy said.
	   Lowe said the Kennedy family shots were rarely posed, even those
with the kids.
	   ``It happened very naturally,'' according to Lowe. ``No one ever
said `Let's do this.'''
	   Trust was a central factor in the German-born photographer's
access to the family.
	   Lowe said he first shot family pictures of then-Sen. John F.
Kennedy, Jackie and their toddler Caroline on a day that Kennedy
was in a bad mood after nonstop campaigning.
	   When the pictures came out well anyway, Kennedy began to trust
him and ultimately made him the official White House photographer.
	   After JFK's assassination in November 1963, Lowe continued to
profile the family of his brother, Robert.
	   But after the then-presidential candidate was in turn
assassinated 30 years ago this month, Lowe says he was so
traumatized that he put away his cameras and moved to an isolated
house in the French Alps where he lived for 18 years.
	   (ma-ip)
</TEXT>
