<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Trade-Environment, 1st Ld-Writethru,0287 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WTO chief: Countries must cooperate on free trade and environment
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to DELETE extraneous reference to Ruggiero &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   GENEVA (AP) _ Efforts to promote free trade will continue,
despite environmental and labor problems, the World Trade
Organization chief said.
	   WTO chief Renato Ruggiero insisted, however, that countries must
cooperate more to reconcile free trade with those concerns. He made
the comments in a speech to the Hamburg-based Friedrich Ebert
Foundation, a research group.
	   ``We must stop viewing the world through a narrow lens and begin
to look at the various challenges we face as pieces of a larger
puzzle demanding broader, more integrated solutions,'' Ruggiero
said in his speech Thursday. A copy of the speech was released in
Geneva on Friday.
	   Despite protests that the free trade system contributes to
poverty, unemployment and environmental problems, ministers last
month told the WTO to prepare for talks to further open the world
economy.
	   U.S. President Bill Clinton and others, however, pledged to try
to make the organization and the global trade system more sensitive
to environmental and labor concerns.
	   Ruggiero said the best way to address the worries is through the
system itself. ``If people, especially young people, say
unemployment is too high, they are right. If environmentalists say
growth must be sustainable _ and not destroy the planet's essential
equilibrium _ they are right.
	   ``But none of these international _ and national _ problems will
be resolved any easier by restricting trade, closing borders, or
undermining the international rule of law _ as embodied in the
WTO.''
</TEXT>
