w1240 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sudan-Fighting-Oil     06-12 0424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sudan-Fighting-Oil </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sudan rebels claim capture of strategic town; warns oil companies
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By CHEGE MBITIRU &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) _ Southern Sudan rebels said Friday they
have captured a strategic town in the Blue Nile province and warned
foreign oil companies it will not honor their exploration
concessions there.
	   If true, the capture of Mabaan near the Ethiopian border by the
Sudan People's Liberation Army would open the way to Melut and
Renk, putting the rebels on eastern banks of the White Nile river
and threatening the government's barge traffic.
	   ``Our forces captured Mabaan on Thursday,'' said Michael George
Garang, an SPLA spokesman in Kenya. ``We are telling the foreign
oil companies to get out, because we will not honor their
agreements with Khartoum.''
	   It was impossible to independently verify the rebel claims and
government officials in Khartoum, the capital of Sudan, were
unavailable for comment.
	   Mabaan is about 600 kilometers (370 miles) south of Khartoum.
The road from Ethiopia branches there to Melut and Renk.
	   Garang could not identify the oil companies in the area. The
U.S. oil company Chevron worked in southern Sudan until the early
1990s when it abandoned its concessions because of the insurgency.
	   Since launching the current offensive a year ago, the rebels
have captured a series of towns and only once have they made a
hasty, and eventually, false claim.
	   Garang, who is not related to SPLA leader Col. John Garang, said
he had no casualty figure for either side in the battle for Mabaan.
	   Since 1983, the rebels have been fighting for increased autonomy
and development for the predominantly animist, Christian and
African south, which traditionally has been dominated by the Muslim
and Arabized north.
	   At least 1.5 million people have died in the fighting and
accompanying famine.
	   Sudan _ Africa's geographically largest country and one of its
poorest _ currently produces between 18,000 and 20,000 barrels of
oil a day and imports up to 40,000 barrels a day to meet domestic
needs. Sudan currently imports dlrs 400 million worth of oil a
year.
	   On Wednesday, the rebels announced the capture the day before of
Ulu, about 455 kilometers (280 miles) southeast of Khartoum.
	   The town is 150 kilometers (90 miles) south of the city of
Damazin and the Roseires dam, which provides 80 percent of
Khartoum's electricity.
	   The dam is about 500 kilometers (315 miles) southeast of
Khartoum.
	   (VAR-cm-jh)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sudan-Fighting-Oil; CT:i; 
