<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Pakistan-Budget,0372 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pakistan increases defense spending in dlrs 13.7 billion budget
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By KATHY GANNON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) _ Pakistan introduced a dlrs 13.7
billion budget Friday that increases defense spending and sharply
raises its debt payments.
	   The dlrs 249 million raise in defense spending to dlrs 3.2
billion, is a 9 percent increase over last year. However after
inflation _ officially 8.5 percent, but unofficially closer to 13
percent _ the actual spending increase was either tiny or
nonexistent.
	   The budget comes just two weeks after Pakistan tested six
nuclear devices generating global condemnation and threats of
economic sanctions.
	   The United States and Japan have both come out in favor of
sanctions, but several European nations, including Russia, have
rejected them as counterproductive.
	   ``We are prepared to make any sacrifice for the security and
solidarity of our homeland,'' Finance Minister Sartaj Aziz Aziz
said in his budget speech.
	   Defense and debt servicing are Pakistan's two biggest
expenditures.
	   Debt servicing will cost Pakistan dlrs 9 billion or two-thirds
of its budget. This is almost twice the interest Pakistan paid last
year.
	   This year Pakistan's deficit was 5.4 percent of gross domestic
product, the lowest since this poor country of 140 million people
became indebted to international lending institutions some 17 years
ago, Aziz said.
	   Aziz said the deficit target for next year is 4.6 percent,
slightly higher than the 4 percent target set by the International
Monetary Fund, which has negotiated a dlrs 1.6 billion loan
package.
	   It's still not known whether international sanctions will effect
the IMF loan or multilateral aid.
	   Pakistan spends less than 5 percent of its gross national
product on education and health care. And on social security
benefits for its elderly, Pakistan spends only .2 percent, this
compares to 11 percent in the United States and 38 percent in
Sweden.
	   In a country of 140 million people, 60 million people do not
have access to health facilities and and 67 million people are
without safe drinking water. And 89 million people do not have
basic sanitation facilities. 	   
</TEXT>
