w1249 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BEWARE-OF-MANYsked     06-12 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BEWARE-OF-MANY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`If many fear you, beware of many', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
`If many fear you, beware of many', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Mazlan NordinASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SOME foreign words are learnt the hard way because of their
relevance in more ways than one to contemporary situations. One
such is the Latin expression annus horribilis, meaning awful year,
once used by Queen Elizabeth to describe the misfortunes of the
British royal family members in 1992.
	   It is now also used by others, including political analysts, to
describe the economic turmoil in some Asian countries.
	   For Indonesia though there is the consequent political upheaval
leading to the resignation of President Suharto after 32 years in
power, and thus another Latin expression multis terribilis, caveto
multos. It means: If many fear you, beware of many. The advice is
one which leaders past and present would take to heart.
	   Once published in the Jakarta Post (on May 8, 1995) was a
commentary on ``Jaman Edan'', a Javanese expression meaning the age
of madness. It was coined by Ranggawarsite (1802-1873), the great
court poet of Surakarta, who also wrote essays on social issues,
education, economics and law.
	   Noted was his experience in what was described as one of the
darkest periods of Javanese history, from 1820 to 1860. During the
four decades entire villages were pauperised due to ``exploitative
practices conducted by the Dutch colonial Government and aided by
the bureaucracies of the Javanese kings''.
	   And so it was that the Javanese under Prince Dipanegara
revolted. Quote: ``It is not difficult to imagine that the Javanese
became demoralised during this time of political disintegration,
and that various forms of deceit and hypocrisy emerged within the
courts. In those courts political intrigue thrived, and violations
of norms became common.
	   ``People skilful in winning the trust of those in power have
always won, no matter how wicked such a person may have been ... to
later generations of Javanese people, Jaman Edan has come to mean
any time or period during which villains who violated ethical norms
not only get away unpunished, but are actually rewarded''.
	   Remembered too is a poem by Ranggawarsita from his book Serat
Kala Tida (The Age of Social Upheavals): The lustre of the realm is
now vanished to the eye, In ruins the teachings of good ways for
there is no example left.
	   Other than rebellion another form of protest was a custom
inherited from the old days of the Majapahit empire. An unjust king
was warned of being ``left and evaded'' by his people. It meant
that they would migrate into the hinterland and the king could not
then count on them to man his army or provide labour for
agriculture and other activities.
	   In the present circumstances, however, no such form of protest
can be effected.
	   Among pressing problems facing the administration of President
B.J.
	   Habibie is the rise in the number of the unemployed due to the
steep depreciation of the rupiah and economic turbulence. According
to latest reports the number of jobless will rise to 15 million.
	   Mentioned in the Indonesian journal Forum Keadilan is the
increase in the number of those living below the poverty level. In
1970 some 70 million people or 60 per cent of the population were
considered poor.
	   Since then the percentage had consistently gone down and in 1996
the number of those below the poverty level was 22.5 million or
just 11.2 per cent of the total population.
	   The economic turmoil has demolished the gains, according to an
Indonesian economist. The number of those considered dirt poor has
now risen to 118.5 million or 60.6 per cent of the populace. It is
no longer an estimate but a fact of life, he said, and thus worse
than the situation in 1970.
	   There was then the warning: ``Without waiting for the students
and intellectuals to make their moves they themselves will march
forth to seek that little pot of rice in order to just survive ...
We would be committing a grave sin if we simply wait for anarchy to
smother us.'' Meanwhile warnings about the danger of Indonesia
becoming ``another Yugoslavia'' have been voiced by Amien Rais, the
militant opposition leader during Suharto's rule, and by
Christianto Wibisono, director of the Indonesian Business Date
Centre and also a political analyst in Jakarta.
	   Both are nonetheless not of the same hue as Tengku Hassan Tiro,
leader of the secessionist National Liberation Front of Aceh. He
had once described Indonesian nationalism as a ``Western invention
to contain Islam''
	   in the former Dutch East Indies.
	   The idea was said to been formulated by a Dutch administrator,
Christian Snouck Hurgronje, who once visited Mecca disguised as a
Muslim. The objective was to destroy Islam as a politico-religious
faith slowly and subtly so that Indonesia could be secularised and
westernised.
	   As things are, however, Indonesian unity remains firm.
``Helping'' to bolster it are calls by such as Jose Ramos-Horta to
change the status of East Timor, former Portuguese colony and
presently the 27th province of the Indonesian republic.
	   Both Habibie and former opposition leader Megawati Sukarnoputri,
and others have rejected such notions. In the present context there
are no separatist leaders such as Imam Kartosuwiro of West Java and
Abdul Kahar Muzakar of Sulawesi to fan separatist tendencies.
	   The patriotic slogan ``From Sabang to Meruke'' is firmly in the
hearts and minds of the people whatever their ethnic origins -
Minangkabau, Batak, Ambonese, Sundanese, Makasarese or Javanese.
They are many facing Habibie, a non-Javanese, and for him thus is
the reminder from the second part of the Latin expression ``beware
of many''.
	   As things are some students are still demonstrating, trade
unionists picketing their work places and political parties
proliferating.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BEWARE-OF-MANY sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
