<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Belarus-Prices </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Lukashenko objects to price increases
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MINSK, Belarus (AP) _ President Alexander Lukashenko said Friday
that higher prices are not the way to curb demand in Minsk for meat
and dairy products.
	   Instead, he ordered city authorities to increase production of
sausages and cottage cheese.
	   ``The important thing is to saturate the market and do away with
this high demand,'' Lukashenko said.
	   During a visit to a dairy plant, he reminded authorities that he
has ordered price increases not to exceed two or three percent.
	   He said that by the end of June he wants to see eight to 10
different kinds of sausages being sold in Minsk and five or six
kinds of cottage cheese.
	   Belarus has made fewer free-market reforms than probably any
other former Soviet republic, with most businesses remaining in
state hands and the government setting prices.
	   The national currency, the Belarusian ruble, has suffered
another dramatic slump recently, leading to a surge in prices for
what meager goods are available in the stores.
	   Lukashenko said the food shortages are confined to the capital,
Minsk.
	   ``There is no panic-buying of these foodstuffs in regional
centers,'' he said. ``Even with the existing prices, not everybody
can afford them.''
	   (str/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
