<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Finland-Earns-Finnair </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Finnair profit up by 47 percent
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HELSINKI, Finland (AP) _ Citing growth in all sectors, Finland's
national carrier, Finnair, increased its 12-month pretax profit by
47 percent, to 630 million markkaa (dlrs 116 million), the company
said Friday.
	   Net sales during the 12 months ending March 31 also grew, to 8
billion markkaa (dlrs 1.5 billion) from 7.4 billion markkaa a year
earlier.
	   The number of passengers flying Finnair grew by 12.5 percent
during the period, and cargo traffic increased by 15 percent, the
airline said.
	   Finnair said growth will continue except in the Far East.
	   ``The Finnish economy is expected to grow favorably ... and the
demand for airline services is directly linked to economic
growth,'' the company said. ``The new financial year has begun well
and conditions favor a good result for this year.''
	   Finnair said it will lose about 80 million markkaa (dlrs 15
million) once European Union regulations banning duty free sales in
the region come into force, as scheduled in July 1999.
	   Finnair, founded in 1923, is one of the world's oldest airlines.
It flies to 70 destinations, including 40 in Europe, with a fleet
of 56 aircraft. It employs 11,000 people worldwide.
	   (mhh-jd)
</TEXT>
