w1255 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  THE-LESSONS-THAT-HANSONs     06-12 1366
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> THE-LESSONS-THAT-HANSON sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
The lessons that Hanson's rise holds, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
The lessons that Hanson's rise holds, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Rose IsmailASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PAS and Pauline Hanson uttered in the same breath may seem
strange, incongruous even. But for Australian sociologist Professor
Clive Kessler, the parallel is startlingly apparent.
	   He says support for Hanson, whose One Nation party is likely to
win up to four seats in tomorrow's elections in Queensland, comes
from people who have been geographically and culturally isolated
and who see themselves embodying the true personality of the
nation.
	   Because of their insularity, he says the many changes Australia
has experienced have bypassed them. ``These changes have not been
part of their experience.''
	   Similarly, Malaysia in the 1960s was quite plural and diverse
but there was a rural-populist movement based in Kelantan which saw
the State through a Malay image.
	   Kessler who spent months studying the movement said the people
living in Kelantan then felt they were the only real Malays.
	   They had a we-local-people-know-best attitude. Through the
party, the Kelantanese sought ways to affirm their identity.
	   In both cases, Kessler says, there were narrow, conformist,
exclusive notions of the individual in the nation-state. Anything
different would have been a mistake, an aberration which had to be
treated with suspicion.
	   Today, in Australia, this provincial worldview - variously
labelled as the Old Australia, the Middle Australia or the
Anglo-Celtic outlook - is creeping into the mainstream, threatening
to shake the foundation of national politics.
	   It is also alarming people far beyond the borders of the
northern ``Sunshine State''.
	   As Kessler points out, everyone will be looking out for the
contagion effects of tomorrow's elections.
	   For Malaysians with relatives and friends from down under, the
Hanson factor is undoubtedly worrying.
	   ``It's harder for Asians to get in now,'' says an
Australian-Chinese lecturer living in Sydney. ``There is definitely
a bias towards White Australians. This won't make life harder for
us on a day-to-day basis but in the long-run, who knows?''
	   One person presumably perspiring under the collar as One Nation
gains ground in Queensland is Prime Minister John Howard.
	   Even if his National-Liberal coalition gets the vote in the
elections, critics say One Nation will end up holding the balance
of power in the State Parliament.
	   Australian newspaper reports have also indicated that a good
performance by One Nation in Queensland will translate into the
national election (which Howard is likely to call for before March,
next year), leaving his government to contend with
ultra-conservative policies such as a cut in Asian immigration,
softer gun laws and tariffs.
	   The probability of this happening, up to Press time, is pretty
high.
	   Polls over the past week have shown One Nation enjoying as much
as 18.5 per cent support State-wide and more than 20 per cent
support in disaffected rural areas. Polls have also given the
Labour party as much as a 55-45 per cent lead over the
Liberal-National coalition after the distribution of preference
votes.
	   (This is a complicated voting system which allows for ranking of
candidates in order of preference and where the votes of minor
candidates are distributed to remaining candidates until a majority
is determined.) The Liberals have seen support crumble in key urban
seats in Brisbane while the Nationals, traditionally the farmers'
friend, have seen supporters desert them for One Nation.
	   Hanson, whose influence has been grossly underestimated by
Howard, knows the extent of voter angst in her backyard.
	   Basing her career on a constituency of allegedly ``forgotten
people'', she has attracted rural and semi-urban dwellers tired of
being seen as vapid and colourless, alarmed by the effects of
globalisation and two decades of multiculturalism and uncertain
about their economic future.
	   To entice them into her fold, she claims she is ``an Australian
fighting for Australia''.
	   She says she represents ``ordinary Australians, mainstream
Australians, underprivileged White Australians'' who want
monoculturalism, discriminatory immigration, tariff protection for
Australian industries and the pulling back of all privileges given
to the indigenous folk of Australia.
	   The alleged links that One Nation has with the lunatic fringe -
the Freedom Scouts (which is threatening Asia with two alarming
alternatives: the atom bomb or germ warfare) and the Ku Klux Klan -
is also frightening many people, both within and outside Australia.
	   So, if the proponents of multiculturalism had hoped to place
Australia on the world map as a country comfortable with ethnic
diversity, they are now seeing a biting backlash in the bigotry
that comes with Hanson's party.
	   If we are to learn anything from all this, it would be in the
following points: first, major political parties which are far
removed from people at the grassroots will have a huge price to pay
at election time.
	   A second lesson would be in the way leaders handle simmering
resentment, distrust and anger towards government.
	   Says Kessler: ``He (Howard) could have provided a more
constructive alternative, he could have said: `I understand your
suffering. I know what you are going through. We will find ways to
deal with the problems but her way is not the right way'.''
	   Instead, because of his hidden agenda, Howard from the very
start showed reluctance to criticise her. His rationale: if you
attack her, it would only build her up.
	   When he decided late last week to label her as `deranged', it
seemed a little too late.
	   Universiti Kebangsaan Malaysia sociologist Norani Othman, who is
watching the Queensland elections from Sydney, says people in power
often don't realise they can be indirectly responsible for
unleashing negative forces in society.
	   They usually ignore it until the strength of emotions cannot be
contained, she says.
	   ``We have seen this happening in many countries where religious
militancy or cultural fundamentalism have been allowed to fester
without check or control.''
	   Such trends have led to the downfall of governments.
	   A possible third lesson and one which Norani says she finds most
heartening was in the way Australians make use of democratic
structures to openly declare their frustrations with the political
system.
	   She says Malaysia can learn a great deal from this. ``We tend to
sweep things under the carpet and grumble in private. We become
cynical because we assume we are powerless.
	   ``We have democratic structures but they remain untested,
unchallenged because we're not in the habit of operating within
such a framework in our daily lives.
	   ``Over here (in Australia), I have a keen sense of these
structures and how political tensions are kept in check within the
democratic framework.
	   She says many Australians are dismayed by Hanson's influence and
embarrassed that pockets of bigotry still exist in the country.
	   They are also wondering why incipient racism still clings in
dark corners of the country when the White Australia Policy was
abandoned in the 70s.
	   ``Many of us don't realise that social engineering takes time,''
says Norani. ``I am confident that things will improve. The
Australians have a sense of what they can do and this is important
because extreme views and positions will be kept in check when
issues are allowed out into the open.''
	   
</TEXT>
