<SLUG> BC-Israel-Safe Passage,0335 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Human rights group condemns Israeli travel restrictions on
</HEADLINE>
Palestinians &QL; 
 &UR; By JACK KATZENELL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Israel's failure to open a ``safe passage'' to
allow Palestinians to travel between the West Bank and the Gaza
Strip constitutes collective punishment and is causing unacceptable
hardship, an Israeli human rights group charged Friday.
	   In the Israel-Palestinian agreements, Israel recognized that the
West Bank and the Gaza Strip constitute ``a single territorial
unit'' and promised to open a ``safe passage'' between them.
	   But two years have passed and Israel has not carried out this
commitment, citing security reasons. A limited number of
Palestinians cross between the two areas each week in convoys
guarded by Israeli border police.
	   In a report entitled ``Divide and Rule,'' the Betselem human
rights group says the Israeli policy constitutes collective
punishment.
	   ``The severance between the Gaza Strip and the West Bank
precludes development of communal, social, economic and political
life of the residents of the two areas,'' the report says. It
``creates two Palestinian societies with weak ties between them.''
	   The restrictions have separated families and made it difficult
for students living in the Gaza Strip to study in the West Bank.
	   An Israeli official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Friday the ``safe passage'' could have been opened a long time ago
were Palestinian's willing to allow security checks on the
corridor.
	   ``If they had accepted our proposals, a much larger number of
Palestinians would be making the crossing today and they would find
it much more convenient than the present situation,'' the official
told The Associated Press.
	   Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's policy adviser David
Bar-Illan said the delay in the opening of the ``safe passage'' was
``due entirely to security considerations based on the constant and
very real threat of terrorism.'' 	   
</TEXT>
