<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Montenegro-UPDATE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Parliamentary election results in Montenegro final
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PODGORICA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Final results cementing the victory
of reformist President Milo Djukanovic's supporters in May 31
elections were announced Friday by Montenegro's election
commission.
	   With 170,000 ballots cast in its favor, Djukanovic's pro-Western
coalition ``For a Better Life'' won 42 seats in the 78-seat
parliament.
	   The party of Djukanovic's opponent Momir Bulatovic, protege of
hard-line Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, gained 29 seats
with 123,957 votes.
	   Five seats went to the Liberal Alliance party and one each to
two ethnic Albanian political parties in Montenegro.
	   Results were delayed because the vote had to be repeated at two
polling stations because of ``irregularities.'' Both polling places
had only a few hundred registered voters, and could not have
influenced final results.
	   A number of minor complaints also had to be addressed.
	   The new parliament is scheduled to convene Monday.
	   The commission gave the elections a clean bill of health, saying
they were ``free and democratic'' and expressed the will of the
people in this mountainous republic of just 630,000 residents.
	   Montenegro, together with Serbia, with 10 million inhabitants,
forms the present-day Yugoslav federation. Both republics provide
an equal number of deputies to the upper chamber of the federal
parliament.
	   (kk/scl) 	   
</TEXT>
