w1270 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  RICE-PRICE-IN-PERSPECTIV     06-12 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> RICE-PRICE-IN-PERSPECTIV sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rice price in perspective, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Rice price in perspective, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   IN the current confusion over the price of rice, it is perhaps
timely to put things in perspective. The Malaysian rice situation
should be viewed from two windows - that of Peninsular Malaysia and
Sabah and Sarawak, for they are totally separate.
	   The authorities' concern is over the rise of prices in the local
grades in Peninsular Malaysia, a phenomenon seen from the start of
the new year.
	   To them, there is no justification for the steep hike when 80
per cent of the 1.45 million tonnes required for the peninsula is
produced locally.
	   They have said a price difference of about a ringgit or two for
10 kg may be acceptable but certainly not between RM7 and RM8 as is
the case today.
	   At issue is the local Super grade which is floated. The Premium
and Standard grade rice are under price control.
	   The authorities have also made it clear that they are not overly
concerned about the prices of imported rice as, at the end of the
day, it is for the consumers to choose the type they want.
Moreover, it is unrealistic to expect price control of the imported
varieties for these are subject to world price fluctuations. It is
understandable that the authorities are closely monitoring the
price movements and anxious to check a further hike and reduce the
existing levels. Rice is the nation's staple and in these difficult
times, a big price rise will no doubt burden the people,
particularly the lower income group.
	   In the furore over the sharp price hike, it is convenient to
make Padiberas Nasional Bhd, the country's sole rice importer, the
scapegoat.
	   Facts do not lie and they clearly tell us that Bernas should not
be blamed. The Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs Ministry has
attested to this after a full explanation from Bernas. Indeed, it
is impossible for Bernas which controls a mere 20 per cent of the
supply to cause the spiralling prices.
	   Those conversant with the rice trade in fact point out that
Bernas did not increase prices for some eight months since the
onset of the region's economic problems up to April. It even had to
bear losses because of the ringgit's depreciation. Yet the local
price has seen a steady rise since January. The Ministry, lamenting
that the Super grade rice is priced too high, said even though
Bernas sells it at RM10 for a 10kg bag, there are groups pricing it
between RM15 and RM20 under different brand names. The Ministry in
blaming millers, wholesalers and retailers has ominously warned
that a refusal to bring down prices will force it to find a
solution. While the Agriculture Ministry has delivered a similar
warning, it rightly points out that price control could have an
adverse impact on the industry.
	   The local rice trade is a complex one given its large number of
players and layers. In a free economy like Malaysia's, it would be
naive to assume that there is no multiplier effect in the wake of
last December's padi price increase despite the assurance by
millers that they will absorb the additional costs. However, the
important question is whether the increase is a fair quantum.
Instead of pointing fingers, the best course is to try and reduce
this multiplier effect. This is however a well nigh impossible task
as effective supervision in terms of manpower is too costly.
	   Perhaps, the solution lies in using Bernas' prices at its retail
outlets as a benchmark for determining a fair margin of profit for
dealers.
	   Ultimately, it will be in the interest of the trade to be
reasonable.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
