<HEADLINE>
New York: Down, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
New York: Down, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   BLUE-CHIP share prices bounced up and down Wednesday before
closing down 0.86 per cent on profit-taking in the high-tech
sector.
	   The Dow Jones index of 30 blue chips shed 78.22 points to close
at 8,971.70. Some 612 million shares changed hands with 976
advancers, 2,012 decliners and 507 issues unchanged.
	   On the bond market, average yields fell to their lowest levels
in 30 years after Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan said that
higher interest rates may be needed if demand does not slow.
	   Greenspan said that while the Asian crisis drove down the value
of US exports in first quarter 1998, the slowdown was not ``likely
to threaten the expansion of this country's economy''.
	   
</TEXT>
