<SLUG> TOKYO-LOWER sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tokyo: Lower, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Tokyo: Lower, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SHARE prices closed 2.1 per cent lower yesterday on selling due
to the yen's plunge against the dollar and worries about falling
Asian stock markets, brokers said.
	   Bargain hunters after the previous day's fall retreated as the
yen came closer to the 142-yen barrier, brokers said.
	   The key Nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues on the Tokyo
Stock Exchange fell 325.22 points at 15,014.04, narrowly managing
to stay above the psychologically-important 15,000.
	   The broader Topix index of all first-section issues dropped
19.79 points to 1,178.81. An estimated 400 million shares changed
hands on the major board, up from 353.2 million shares the previous
day.
	   Shortly after 3pm, the currency was trading at a new seven-year
low of 142.10 yen.
	   The Nikkei 225 index fell to as low as 15,002.55, but public
fund buying, along with modest position covering, blocked further
declines, brokers said.
	   Share prices were under pressure from the outset in the wake of
the declines of Asian markets on the previous day, with sentiment
unnerved by the further falls seen again yesterday.
	   Investors remained active sellers of banks in particular, in the
wake of the fall of the Hang Seng index in Hong Kong, brokers said.
	   Selling spread due to worries over the sizeable exposure of
local banks to Hong Kong borrowers, they said.
	   But selling eased somewhat amid cautiousness ahead of the
setting of the special quotation to settle June futures contracts.
	   ``Sellers retreated ahead of the SQ Friday, because even they
did not want to continue to push share prices sharply lower,'' a
Meiko Securities Co Ltd broker said.
	   ``Futures-led selling pushed the market to the lows, but there
was talk of public funds buying which helped to pull prices off
their lows. Also, the fact that Hong Kong stabilised after falling
to its lows helped revive sentiment.
	   ``From here, the point of concern is that if we see further
falls of the major markets overnight - London and in the United
States - this will feed through to further falls of the local
market again tomorrow (today),'' the Meiko broker said.
	   
</TEXT>
