<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-Guerlain Attacked, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Famed perfumer wounded in attack by armed gang
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs. UPDATES thruout with four wounded in shootout, art works
also stolen, other new info; shows photo available &QL; 
 &UR; APPhoto PAR101 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   VERSAILLES, France (AP) _ Up to a dozen heavily armed masked men
attacked the home of world-renowned perfumer Jean-Paul Guerlain
early Friday, shooting him and a guardian after plundering the
mansion of art works and other valuables, police and judicial
sources said.
	   Two other people, one of whom was hit in the face by the
attackers, suffered minor injuries, said the sources, speaking on
condition of customary anonymity. The other jumped out a second
story window, suffering arm injuries.
	   Guerlain, 63, was operated on Friday morning for a wound to the
thigh inflicted by a 9 mm bullet, and was ``doing well,'' according
to the prestigious perfume and cosmetics house that bears his name.
	   The guardian was reported in critical condition in a Paris
hospital with two bullet wounds to the chest.
	   Police mounted a search for the gang, none of whom had been
caught more than 12 hours after the attack which lasted from about
midnight until 3 p.m.
	   Police sources said the attackers, highly organized and
apparently lying in wait, took the Guerlain household hostage upon
his return around midnight from a gala celebration of the
perfumery's 170 years in business.
	   It was not known how they penetrated the walled estate in the
Yvelines region west of Paris where Versailles is located.
	   Guerlain was held until about 3 a.m. while the various buildings
of the estate were pillaged of jewels, art works and other
valuables, said the police sources.
	   ``The commando carried out a break-in that we could qualify as
savage,'' said one inspector from the Criminal Brigade.
	   Gunfire broke out as the gang was leaving, said the police and
judicial sources, indicating that Guerlain may have tried to grab a
pistol at the time.
	   Guerlain President Thibault Ponroy said the perfumer, one of
France's top ``noses,'' had spoken with him on the telephone after
surgery Friday morning.
	   Guerlain ``is out of danger,'' Ponroy said. ``He was
complaining. When Jean-Paul complains, he's doing well,'' he told
LCI television station.
	   On Thursday night, Guerlain presented his new perfume,
``Guerlinade,'' at a gala at his boutique on Paris' famed
Champs-Elysees.
	   Guerlain is the great grandson of the founder of the prestigious
perfume and cosmetics house created in 1828, creator of the
well-known fragrance ``Shalimar.''
	   Guerlain has been run by the world's No. 1 luxury group LMVH --
Louis Vuitton Moet-Henessy -- since 1994.
	   (eg-parf)
</TEXT>
