w1281 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Guinea-Bissau 1stLd-Writethru   06-12 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Guinea-Bissau, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thousands flee Guinea-Bissau as government, rebels exchange fire
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with fighting in Bissau, Portuguese Navy warship en
route, situation reported calm in second-largest city,
international phone lines apparently cut &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) _ Tens of thousands of people fled the
former Portuguese colony of Guinea-Bissau on Friday as government
troops fought renegade soldiers who launched a coup attempt,
according to reports.
	   As many as 40,000 people in the West African nation were heading
on foot along the road to the northern border with Senegal, a
Portuguese journalist in the area said, citing local reports.
	   Senegal closed the border on Thursday while medical teams were
dispatched to vaccinate the refugees against yellow fever and
meningitis before they were allowed into the country, Pedro Rosa
Mendes told Portuguese state radio Antena 1.
	   Government troops, supported by soldiers from neighboring
Senegal and the Republic of Guinea, meanwhile maintained their
siege of a military garrison in a northern suburb of the capital
Bissau, where an unknown number of rebels have been holed up since
their attempted powergrab on Sunday.
	   A spokesman for the Portuguese Prime Minister's office, who was
in contact with the Portuguese embassy in Bissau, said sporadic
shelling and automatic weapon fire could be heard in the capital
throughout the day.
	   ``It's a very unstable situation. We're not sure who's
winning,'' the spokesman said on customary condition of anonymity,
adding that the embassy had been hit by several stray shells.
	   The French embassy was hit by a bazooka shell but no one was
injured, the Portuguese news agency Lusa reported, citing
diplomatic sources in Dakar in Senegal.
	   Portuguese residents in Bafata, the country's second-largest
city, 140 kilometers (87 miles) to the east of Bissau, told Lusa
there was no military activity in the area.
	   The president of the National Assembly Malan Sanha said
representatives from Muslim and Catholic associations had allied
with lawmakers to propose talks, Lusa reported.
	   The two sides had ``demonstrated interest'' in holding talks,
Sanha was quoted as saying by Lusa, although he declined to provide
further details.
	   However, an unidentified western diplomat quoted by Lusa said
President Joao Bernardo Vieira was reluctant to enter talks and was
confident in his ability to defeat the rebels militarily.
	   More than 2,200 people, mostly foreigners, were evacuated from
Bissau on a Portuguese merchant ship Thursday.
	   Vitor Duque, an official of the shipping company that provided
the vessel told, Antena 1 that the passengers, including children
and old people, were packed on the deck. The huge container ship
was designed to hold only 18 people.
	   The ship was due to arrive in Dakar at about 5 p.m. (1700 GMT),
Duque said.
	   A Portuguese frigate was expected to arrive in Guinea-Bissau on
Sunday to oversee the evacuation of other foreigners, diplomats
said.
	   Portuguese phone company Marconi said international phone lines
apparently had been cut in Bissau, making contact impossible.
	   The rebels are led by former armed forces chief Brig. Ansumane
Mane, who was fired in January amid allegations he was involved in
smuggling arms to rebels in Senegal. He has accused Vieira of
corruption and called on him to step down so that early elections
can be held.
	   Vieira himself came to power in a 1980 coup. He was elected in
the country's first democratic elections for president and
parliament four years ago.
	   (bh/jt)
</TEXT>
