<SLUG> BC-Jamaica-Angry Depositors,0306 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Depositors in failed investment firm storm meeting
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By CAROLL ORR &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) _ Angry depositors stormed a meeting and
forced the retreat of the chief executive officer of one of
Jamaica's failed financial institutions, with some climbing on top
of his car as he sped off.
	   Henry Fullerton, CEO of Caldon Financial Group, came
face-to-face with angry investors Thursday night at a meeting
scheduled to liquidate another company. The hotel management called
police as the protesters forced their way into the meeting and
confronted Fullerton, waving placards and shouting ``We want our
money!''
	   ``You're a damned thief. You're a disgrace to society. If you go
to Timbuktu we are coming there for you,'' one person shouted at
Fullerton.
	   Fullerton agreed in February to voluntarily liquidate the Caldon
Financial Group after months of financial difficulties. The
government spent dlrs 700 million last year to take over numerous
banks and financial institutions in Jamaica to try to avoid a
financial crisis.
	   After bodyguards ushered Fullerton outside to his car, some
protesters climbed on the vehicle to try to stop him from leaving.
	   ``My husband was on top of the car and he was almost run over,''
said Lorna Karjohn, one of the depositors.
	   Fullerton was also questioned for two hours Thursday by
investigators.
	   ``Mr. Fullerton has not been charged with fraud but our
investigations could lead to him being brought in for questioning
once again,'' said Fitz Bailey, superintendent of the crime
commission.
	   Liquidators from the international firm Peat Marwick, assigned
to the case after the government took over Caldon, said there may
not be funds or assets to repay depositors.
</TEXT>
