<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup Briefs, 1st Ld Writethru,0741 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
France, Romario's comments, Mandela's letter, strike called off in
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: includes new items on Nigerian mourning, cool weather in
Nantes, boy expelled from school &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS _ Flags will be flown at half staff at Saturday's
Nigeria-Spain game in memory of the late Nigerian leader Sani
Abacha.
	   FIFA spokesman Keith Cooper said Friday that there would be no
moment of silence and that it was up to each team whether they
wanted to wear black armbands in mourning at their Group D opener
in Nantes.
	   Abacha, a military strongman whose regime had been the focus of
human-rights protests, died Monday in Nigeria of a heart attack.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   YSSINGEAUX, France (AP) _ One reason the Iranians chose
Yssingeaux for their World Cup base was because its mild June
temperatures and sunny clime were like home.
	   But judging by the cold, wet weather that has welcomed them
since they arrived in this small town in the heart of France
Sunday, the players may be wondering if they took a wrong turn
somewhere.
	   The mercury plunged to a freezing 0 degrees centigrade (32 f.)
Friday, about 15 degrees less than the norm for this time of year,
following a hail storm the previous day.
	   So far, every one of the team's practice sessions has been under
heavy rain.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   PARIS (AP) _ Romario says he's in top form despite being dropped
by the Brazilian World Cup team with a leg injury. He's also
critical of the team's performance against Scotland.
	   ``Yesterday, I played a game of soccer with my friends. I train
everyday with my Flamengo team. I'm in top form,'' Romario was
quoted in an interview published Friday by the sports daily
L'Equip.
	   The paper also asked his opinion of Brazil's performance against
Scotland.
	   ``Brazil played very badly,'' Romario said. ``Certain players
were very nervous. I could sense the enormous tension coming from
them.''
	   ___ &QC; 
	   PARIS (AP) _ South African president Nelson Mandela sent a
personal letter to every player on the World Cup team urging them
to make their countrymen proud at France 98, Le Parisien newspaper
reported Friday.
	   ``I am counting on you to bring glory to your country and your
people,'' Mandela told South Africa captain Lucas Radebe. For star
striker Benedict McCarthy, the president had these encouraging
words: ``You are the pride of your parents and your country.
Continue to score goals.''
	   Mandela sent the letters to encourage his team before they faced
France in Marseille Friday night. ``He wanted every one to have the
impression that he was on their side. He wrote the letters himself
last week,'' Le Parisien quoted the presidents spokesperson Parks
Mankahlana as saying. The paper also printed some extracts of the
letters.
	   The letters were sent to the South African embassy in Paris and
brought to the players early this week by South African ambassador
Barbara Masekela.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   NANTES, France (AP) _ Tram conductors called off a strike
planned for Saturday, the day of the Spain-Nigeria match in this
city in northwest France, after getting a bonus.
	   The conductors received a bonus of 1,800 francs (dlrs 300)
because of the extra work during the World Cup. Tram personnel
agreed to wait for the end of the World Cup before starting
contract negotiations on their wages for the tram line servicing
Beaujoire stadium.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   NORFOLK, England (AP) _ An 11-year-old boy was sent home by his
teachers after arriving at school with a design of the English flag
_ the cross of St. George _ dyed into his hair as a tribute to
England's World Cup team.
	   West Lynn primary school officials told Alec Wilkinson's mother
to take him home.
	   ``Everyone at the school is keen for England to do well, but
this is just going too far,'' said the local education authority,
Norfolk County Council.
	   ``The school has been very tolerant of some of this boy's
unusual hairstyles in the past, but this one was particularly
striking and went too far,'' a spokesman said.
	   ``There have to be acceptable standards of appearance. What sort
of impression would people get if every pupil had something like
this dyed into their hair?
	   Mrs. Wilkinson told her local newspaper, The Eastern Daily
Press: ``He's had green streaks, a chessboard and a spider's web
before now and they haven't said anything about it.''
</TEXT>
