<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Romania-Sentence, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Court sentences controversial miners' leader
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with prosecution appealing sentence.
 &UR; By MIHAELA ARMASELU &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) _ The leader of a group of coal miners
whose rampage through Bucharest in 1991 caused Romania's first
post-Communist prime minister to resign was sentenced Friday to 18
months in prison.
	   But the prosecution appealed the decision Friday afternoon,
calling the sentence ``illegal.''
	   The Bucharest appeals court sentenced Miron Cozma for illegally
possessing firearms and carrying an unlicensed pistol, but
acquitted him of undermining state authority and jeopardizing
railway traffic, national radio reported.
	   ``The sentence demonstrates there was no judicial evidence to
show that Cozma urged the miners to come in to the capital and
force the premier to resign,'' judicial analyst Mihai Valentin
Neagu told The Associated Press.
	   Neagu said if any miner had testified that Cozma had asked him
to come to the capital, the miner would have incriminated himself
as being involved in the rampage. Instead, all the miners have
remained silent about the incident.
	   In 1990, then-President Ion Iliescu called on miners under
Cozma's leadership to come to Bucharest to defend him during
anti-Communist protests. They rioted in the city center.
	   On Sept. 24, 1991, about 5,000 coal miners from Romania's Jiu
Valley mining area, headed by Cozma, commandeered trains and
traveled again to the capital. En route, miners destroyed some
railroad cars.
	   Armed with clubs, iron bars and tree branches, the miners,
protesting falling living standards, stormed government
headquarters and battled with security forces.
	   The clashes left three people dead and nearly 300 injured.
Miners demanded the resignation of Prime Minister Petre Roman, who
stepped down several days later.
	   Rampages in 1990 left six dead. But Cozma was not charged in
those clashes.
	   Cozma has been in custody since January 1997. If the prosecution
had not appealed, the months Cozma had spent in prison would have
been deducted from the court's sentence, and he could have been
released in 25 days.
	   (ma/scl)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
