w1300 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-India-Pakistan-Nuclea 6thLd-Writethru   06-12 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Pakistan-Nuclear, 6th Ld-Writethru,0572 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Conflicting statements over resumption of talks highlights
</HEADLINE>
difficulties &QL; 
 &UR; EDs: UPDATES throughout with Pakistan denying it had agreed to
Indian proposal. CHANGES overline &QL; 
 &UR; By ARTHUR MAX &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ India said Friday that Pakistan had
agreed to resume top-level talks later this month, but Pakistan's
foreign minister denied it and said India was ``trying to pull a
fast one.''
	   The conflicting statements appeared to dash hopes of an imminent
reversal in the escalating tension that followed nuclear tests by
both countries last month. Instead, it highlighted the distrust
that separates them and the difficulties in finding a common
language.
	   The countries apparently differed over the meeting's agenda and
venue.
	   An Indian government statement said New Delhi had received
Pakistan's response on Thursday to proposals submitted five months
ago to resume suspended negotiations.
	   ``We note that our view that the bilateral dialogue process
should proceed ahead for mutual benefit is finding acceptance in
Pakistan,'' it said.
	   The statement said India invited Pakistan's foreign minister to
New Delhi for talks later this month.
	   But Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan said his country
had not accepted the invitation. The Indians had made the
announcement ``unilaterally, on their own,'' he said.
	   If talks were held, they would be in the Pakistani capital of
Islamabad, not India's capital, he told The Associated Press.
	   In an interview with the British Broadcasting Corp., Khan
accused India of ``trying to pull a fast one'' by making an
announcement without Pakistan's agreement.
	   A statement released in Islamabad invited India's foreign
secretary to the Pakistani capital on June 20, and said the Indian
proposal was ``totally unrealistic.''
	   Khan told the AP that Pakistan's message to India on Thursday
was a proposal for a two-item agenda comprising confidence-building
measures and talks on the territorial dispute over the disputed
region of Kashmir. The Himalayan territory was the catalyst for two
wars between India and Pakistan in the last 50 years.
	   The Indian statement cited a broader agenda, including all the
items discussed in a series of meetings last year.
	   The Indian and Pakistani prime ministers are scheduled to attend
a regional summit next month, and a round of preliminary talks
would be expected to prepare the ground work for the first direct
meeting between the two men since the India's Hindu nationalist
government took office in March.
	   Tensions between the countries have been rising since May 11
when India conducted a series of nuclear tests and proclaimed
itself a nuclear weapons state. Pakistan followed suit two weeks
later, resisting international pressure for restraint. Both later
declared a moratorium on further tests.
	   The latest dispute came as the foreign ministers of eight
leading industrial nations stepped up sanctions against India and
Pakistan, deciding at a meeting in London to deny all loans except
those earmarked for humanitarian projects.
	   For weeks after the nuclear tests, Indian Prime Minister Atal
Bihari Vajpayee and Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif
proclaimed their readiness for talks, but without indicating any
concession that might make them more successful than earlier
disappointing rounds.
</TEXT>
