<SLUG> BC-UN-Bosnia,0305 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Annan recommends extension of U.N. Mission in Bosnia until June
</HEADLINE>
1999 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Citing the continuing challenge of
rebuilding Bosnia-Herzegovina, Secretary-General Kofi Annan
recommended Friday that the U.N. mission remain in the Balkan
country until at least June 21, 1999.
	   U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said the Security Council was
expected to approve the recommendation Monday.
	   In his report to the council, Annan said his recommendation was
based on the assumption that NATO-led troops would remain there
during that period to provide security for the U.N. operation.
	   The U.N. Mission in Bosnia-Herzegovina, whose current mandate
expires at the end of the month, includes about 2,000 civilian
police sent there to train and advise the newly reconstituted
police forces in parts of the country ruled by Bosnia Serbs and the
Muslim-Croat Federation.
	   About 200 of the U.N. police are Americans.
	   In the report, Annan outlined some of the problems facing the
United Nations in rebuilding Bosnia-Herzegovina following the 1995
Dayton Peace Accord, which ended the 3 1-2 year ethnic war.
	   ``Very regrettably, the last three months have seen an increase
in violent incidents aimed at returning refugees and displaced
persons, in particular those belonging to minority groups,'' he
said.
	   He said U.N. police were doing everything possible to facilitate
the return of all refugees but added ``it would be overly
optimistic to expect a decisive change before the nationwide
elections'' set for Sept. 13.
	   U.N. officials say they fear the three groups _ Muslims, Croats
and Serbs _ will try to prevent wholesale return of minorities
before the election to keep minority participation in the balloting
as low as possible.
</TEXT>
