<SLUG> METACORP'S-PROPOSAL sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Metacorp's proposal to ease traffic flow in KL, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Metacorp's proposal to ease traffic flow in KL, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Kasmiah MustaphaASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   METACORP Bhd has submitted a proposal to the Government to
upgrade three stretches of road leading into the city in a move to
ease traffic congestion, said chief executive officer Yusli Mohamed
Yusoff.
	   He said the roads are Jalan Loke Yew heading towards Bank
Negara, Jalan Melawati to Jalan Genting Kelang as well as Jalan
Pahang to Jalan Ipoh.
	   ``These stretches of road are not included in the concession
given to us earlier. That is why we cannot do anything when
consumers complain about traffic congestion along the roads.
	   However, Yusli did not disclose the amount needed to upgrade the
roads.
	   He added Metacorp will not impose toll on these roads. It has
however proposed a price increase on the current toll charges, a
longer concession period or both.
	   The company is the concession holder for Jalan Pahang, Sungei
Besi Expressway and East-West Link Expressway. The concessions will
end by year 2018.
	   Speaking after the company's annual meeting in Kuala Lumpur
yesterday, Yusli said Metacorp's tolling operations, which is the
core business, generated revenue of RM65 million per year.
	   Urban toll roads roads are generally less affected by the
economic slowdown although traffic flow has dropped slightly for
this year especially for commercial vehicles, he added.
	   On the company's property projects, Yusli said launching of new
phases at Taman Tasik Utama in Ayer Keroh, Malacca, would be
carefully planned.
	   ``We are considering more of low and medium cost housing
projects and probably will launch them by next year.''
	   Yusli said the company's investment in Spitalfields Holdings Ltd
and Spitalfields Development Group for the development of
residential and office space in London has also provided a good
return.
	   He said Metacorp invested about STG23 million (about RM151
million) for the project, adding that the company is expected to
make about 25 per cent return on the investment within the next few
years.
	   In April, a major part of the Spitalfields site was sold to
London International Financial Futures and Options Exchange.
	   Yusli said part of the proceeds from the sale was used to reduce
Metacorp's borrowings by STG10 million. The company had borrowed
STG21.5 million to finance the project.
	   At the three-hour meeting shareholders took on a ballot vote to
re-elect Datuk Mohamed Ishak Mohamed Ariff, David William Berry and
Marzuki Rafie to the board of directors. Mohamed Ishak was also
re-elected chairman of Metacorp.
	   
</TEXT>
