<SLUG> RESIDENT-AT-WITS'-END sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Residents at wits' end over monkey mischief, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Residents at wits' end over monkey mischief, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Bhavani Krishna IyerASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MONKEYS from secondary jungle near Overseas Union Garden, Kuala
Lumpur, are driving residents up the wall with their mischief.
	   The residents of Jalan Hujan Abu and Jalan Hujan Rahmat are at
their wits' end over the destruction to household items and theft
of food over the past three weeks.
	   A.T. Pani of Jalan Hujan Abu 3 said residents feared the monkeys
would eventually attack them as they are aggresive.
	   He said a group of four monkeys usually come to the area between
3pm and 5pm.
	   Pani and his sister, who are both visually handicapped, cannot
do much if they are attacked.
	   ``To make matters, I have a two-month-old daughter who is
defenceless against the creatures,'' he said, adding that the
monkeys moved very fast.
	   Pani said the monkeys even took a dip in large containers
containing water stored because of the rationing exercise.
	   ``We have to keep all doors and windows closed all the time as
we fear they will come into the house and create mischief.''
	   According to Pani, the monkeys were not the least afraid of
residents who tried to chase them away with sticks.
	   ``Instead, they advanced and tried attacking us,'' he added.
	   Chandra Tilaka said a neighbour had his house ransacked by the
monkeys who had found their way in through an unlatched bedroom
window.
	   ``They opened biscuit tins and eat other food in the kitchen.
They also soiled the settee and bed,'' she said.
	   Tilaka said it was possible that the monkeys had come from an
area around the nearby Kesas Highway after losing their natural
habitat.
	   ``They are obviously moving from place to place. We are not even
able to put our clothes out to dry in the porch because of the
menace,'' she said.
	   She said a friend told her the monkeys had previously created
havoc in Jalan Hujan Emas and Jalan Hujan Gerimis.
	   ``We called Kuala Lumpur City Hall for help but were told that
the matter was under the jurisdiction of the Parks and Wildlife
Department.''
	   Tilaka said an officer from the department came to the area on
Wednesday after being alerted to the problem and laid traps in the
nearby jungle.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
