<SLUG> BC-Britain-Nigeria Protest </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Daughter of jailed Nigerian politician calls for his release
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By CAROLINE BYRNE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Demonstrators outside the Nigerian embassy Friday
demanded the release of Moshood Abiola, who apparently won the 1993
presidential elections but was jailed after the vote was annulled.
	   Among the two dozen protesters was Abiola's daughter, Wura
Abiola, who said demands were mounting for the release of the
millionaire after Nigerian dictator General Sani Abacha died of a
heart attack Monday.
	   ``Those whispers are that people will not accept anything but a
complete change and a change in the way our leaders are being
treated, a change in the way our country is being run and that
means free the detained politicians,'' said Wura Abiola, who has
not seen her father for a year.
	   ``The people feel a groundswell of hope and nothing but real
change will make them happy,'' she said.
	   The protest marked the annulment of the June 12, 1993,
presidential elections in which, according to his supporters, her
father won an estimated 85 percent of the popular vote.
	   Abiola, who is being held in solitary confinement, is a
southerner who would have broken the traditional northern hold on
power if he'd become president.
	   Nigeria's new ruler, Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar, has said he plans
to steer the nation toward an elected civilian government, but has
not announced the release of Abiola or other political prisoners.
	   The demonstrators chanted and surrounded an effigy of Abubakar
crucified on a makeshift cross. Around the crucifix, a sign read
``Abacha is dead. Abubakar Must Go Now.''
	   ``The process of change has started and its like a rock rolling
down a hill. It will crush as many people as that stand in its
way,'' said Oche Onyeagucha, the secretary for external affairs of
the Democratic Alternative Party, another emigre Nigerian group.
	   (beb/cb-kg)
</TEXT>
