<SLUG> PEDESTRIAN-WALKWAYS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pedestrian walkways free of hawkers, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Pedestrian walkways free of hawkers, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PEDESTRIAN walkways along Jalan Tan Cheng Lock, Jalan Silang and
Leboh Pudu are finally free of the 92 licensed hawkers and traders
with the exception of several itinerant ones playing hide and seek
with City Hall enforcement officers.
	   Kuala Lumpur City Hall Press officer Rozielawatie Rahmat said
hawkers and traders have been relocated to backlanes, including
Lorong Bandar and Lorong Panggung, as well as behind the Kota Raya
shopping complex.
	   She said the traders were relocated in stages from April in
preparation for the Commonwealth Games. A check by the New Straits
Times revealed pavements to be free of hawkers.
	   The illegal hawkers were, however, trading along the pavements
despite signboards stating that it was an offence to do so.
	   It is understood that the hawkers move their stalls when
enforcement officers make their rounds. Pedestrians were often
forced onto the roads as customers at the stalls monopolised the
pavements.
	   Meanwhile, City Hall Director-General (II) Datuk Ghani Rais said
the relocation was an on-going exercise with efforts concentrated
initially at the city centre. This was part of the local
authority's preparation for the Commonwealth Games, he added.
	   He said by 2000, roadside hawking would be a thing of the past
as all traders and hawkers would be relocated into designated
hawker centres or shopping complexes.
	   
</TEXT>
