w1321 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  MALAYSIA-DADAH-FREEsked     06-12 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> MALAYSIA-DADAH-FREE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Plan to make Malaysia dadah-free, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Plan to make Malaysia dadah-free, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Zainul ArifinASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   EFFORTS to make Malaysia a nation of drugs within 25 years are
on, starting with a programme to turn the children born today into
a dadah- free generation.
	   The target is to be achieved through a series of educational
programmes addressing the problem of dadah abuse in the family
unit, at schools, at work and country wide.
	   Preventive programmes need to begin early in a child's life,
starting at the pre-school level and implemented gradually at all
levels of primary, secondary and tertiary education.
	   ``A time span of 25 years or roughly one generation is our
target in realising the vision ... By the year 2023, we envisage
the emergence of a whole drug-free generation nationwide,'' Deputy
Home Minister Datuk Mohamad Tajol Rosli said in New York on
Wednesday.
	   Speaking at the United Nations General Assembly Special Session
on the World Drug Problem, he said the task was daunting but the
process had already begun in the last few months.
	   ``Admittedly, this is an ambitious vision. However, it is not
just a rhetorical proposal. We aim for it to be a serious,
comprehensive and workable long-term strategy.
	   ``We are convinced that it is achievable and we are determined
to achieve it.''
	   In an interview later, Tajol said a crucial step in eradicating
the dadah problem was to curtail demand, and that could be done by
educating the people, especially parents and youths on the dadah
scourge.
	   For example, two weeks ago the National Narcotics Council, which
co- ordinated efforts to combat dadah abuse, started a programme
called ``A Day With the Community'' aimed at educating parents as
well as youths on the dangers of dadah abuse.
	   The event held at Kampung Kerinchi in Kuala Lumpur brought home
the horrors of dadah menace.
	   ``We showed the residents what is dadah, the punishment for
trafficking as well as the effects of dadah.
	   Tajol said there was a demonstration on how a convicted
trafficker is whipped, to strike fear among those present,
especially the youths. Former addicts were also brought in to talk
to the residents.
	   Parents were counselled on ways to keep narcotics out of their
homes as well as how to detect tell-tale signs that their children
are using dadah.
	   There were also discreet consultations for dadah users and their
families.
	   The anti-dadah message targeted at youths will also employ the
``reverse role model'' technique.
	   In urban areas where young people frequented clubs and discos,
there is a tendency for some of them to indulge in psychotropic
drugs like Ecstasy.
	   In some youth circles such indulgence was considered hip and
trendy.
	   ``We will ask the boys or girls whether they want to spend the
rest of their lives with peers that take dadah,'' Tajol said,
adding that if they could see the final consequence of dadah abuse
many would naturally be turned off.
	   He said so far, about 300 pupils had been tested positive for
dadah abuse.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
