<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Morocco,0383 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Hadji slightly bruised but ready for Brazil
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By TAREK EL-TABLAWY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   AIX-EN-PROVENCE, France (AP) _ A toe injury, which doctors say
needs about three weeks to heal, will not prevent Morocco's star
midfielder from donning the team jersey in the match against
Brazil.
	   Deportive La Coruna's El-Moustafa Hadji, who fractured his toe
recently, resumed his training Friday along with the rest of the
team. He did not, however, practice with a ball due to slight
swelling on the right foot.
	   ``I'll be ready to play against the Brazilians,'' said Hadji,
adding that the Norway match Wednesday left him feeling mild
discomfort after a run in with another player.
	   Even for those who weren't injured, however, the first day of
preparation for the June 16 match against Brazil in Nantes was more
laid back than other training sessions.
	   ``They are still recovering from the last match (against
Norway),'' said team coach Henri Michel after the Atlas Lions
finished their two-hour drills and stretching session Friday.
	   But there is nothing laid back about how much emphasis Michel
and the players are putting on this match.
	   ``We are giving this (match) all the importance it deserves,''
said Michel. ``Brazil ... have the ability to find a goal when
necessary.''
	   The much-awaited match, the team's second Group A competition,
is not the first time they have faced the defending champions on
the field. The two met in Brazil in October for a showdown which
the hosts won 2-0, again partly because of Morocco's habit of
making costly defense mistakes at crucial times. It is a
shortcoming that gave them a 2-2 draw against Norway Wednesday,
instead of a win.
	   ``We were afraid of them that time,'' goalie Driss Benzekri told
the AP. ``We saw, however, that the only problem was the mistakes
we made.''
	   Michel has voiced similar fears, but is confident that ``Brazil
will not have an easy time getting past strong tactical players
like (defender Noureddine) Naybet and Hadji.''
	   Team captain Naybet, who also plays for Deportive La Coruna, was
equally confident.
	   ``It will be a difficult match, but we are up to the
challenge,'' he said.
	   (tt-sl)
</TEXT>
