<BODY>
<SLUG> SOME-LAND-OFFICERS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Some land officers can't even read a plan, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Some land officers can't even read a plan, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Abdullah Sani IsmailASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   IN the early 1970s a civil servant from the top echelon suddenly
got the inspiration that subdivision of land should be carried out
by private companies.
	   Whether the inspiration was divine or trading, the transfer of
responsibility has gradually eliminated the experience land
officers have acquired over generations.
	   Today's land officers have been deprived of a tremendous wealth
of experience; the chief among them can hardly indicate in a plan
where the sun rises.
	   By virtue of being land officers, the law continues to authorise
them to determine the nature of each subdivision, and empowers them
to approve, reject or amend the application accordingly. However,
they are not in a position anymore to decide, much less understand
the nature of the operation, because for more than 30 years others
have been preparing the application for them.
	   Due to this, their performance in other land matters
deteriorate, causing complaints and criticisms.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
