</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Chechnya </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chechnya vows to crack down on kidnappings
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Chechnya will redouble efforts to crackdown on
kidnappings and may start detaining relatives of hostage-takers
until they surrender, a news agency reported Friday.
	   Hundreds of people have been kidnapped in Chechnya and
surrounding regions, usually for ransom, since the region's
two-year war for independence from Russia ended in 1996.
	   Acting Prime Minister Shamil Basayev told Interfax that one
possible solution was ``detaining the close relatives of the
kidnappers until they release the hostages and come to law
enforcement agencies.''
	   ``A kidnapper's family is normally perfectly aware of his
illegal actions and sometimes helps (him) instead of calling him to
order,'' Basayev said. He noted that relatives also benefit from
any ransom received.
	   Basayev said he was also considering setting up a special force
to fight groups that law enforcement agencies can't handle.
	   ``It would make sense to vest such a unit with the right to
carry out operations without performing legal formalities,'' he
said, noting that obtaining warrants and coming up with plans takes
time and can lead to leaks.
	   Chechnya considers itself independent and has run its own
affairs since Russian troops pulled out in the fall of 1996. Moscow
says the Muslim republic remains a part of Russia.
	   (ls) 	   
</TEXT>
