<BODY>
<SLUG> ENDANGERED-WILDLIFE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Concerted efforts needed to protect endangered wildlife, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Concerted efforts needed to protect endangered wildlife, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   S.M. Mohd IdrisASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SAHABAT Alam Malaysia supports and commends Science, Technology
and Environment Minister Datuk Law Hieng Ding for a proposed
mandatory jail sentence for exotic meat sellers.
	   However, good laws will prove ineffective if there is inadequacy
in the enforcement mechanism due to the Ministry's lack of
manpower.
	   Villagers could play a vigorous role by assisting the
authorities in detecting those responsible for the decimation of
our wildlife.
	   School environmental clubs and non-governmental organisations
could be enlisted to police a designated area.
	   The sale and use of traps for catching mammals or birds should
be banned while the commercial sale of wild animals should be
prohibited.
	   There is also a need to restrict the import and export of
animals.
	   State Government and district councils which have always
neglected the wildlife aspects in development projects should play
a more responsible role by cancelling projects which would endanger
the well-being of wildlife and their habitats.
	   By incorporating wildlife habitats and forest reserves into
structure plans, our wildlife will be ensured of a future.
	   State Governments should be committed to the establishment of
national parks and reserves which are vital for the preservation of
our flora and fauna.
	   
</TEXT>
