<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Elections </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Regional vote in Italy a test for reborn Christian Democrats
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ Politicians from a centrist movement formed to
replace the defunct Christian Democrats were wrapping up their
campaign Friday in a regional election seen as a major test of
their ambitions.
	   The Christian Democrats were Italy's dominant party after World
War II, but corruption scandals in the early '90s brought the
party's demise.
	   Its politicians went on to form a half-dozen minor parties.
	   For the first time, the small parties are running together
Sunday in a coalition called the Popular Reformer Center. The
election is the latest in a series of staggered local voting over
the last few weeks. Sunday's will be held in Fruili Venezia Giulia,
a northeastern region where nearly 1.1 million people are eligible
to vote.
	   ``It's a dress rehearsal for a big Catholic and lay movement,''
said former Italian president Francesco Cossiga, who has been
spearheading the resurrection of a big centrist party.
	   Results are expected on Monday.
	   In local elections elsewhere in Italy a week ago, the
center-right coaltion led by Silvio Berlusconi, the media tycoon
and former premier, defeated most of the mayoral candidates backed
by Premier Romano Prodi's center-left.
	   (ar-fd)
</TEXT>
