<SLUG> ROAD-CLOSURE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Road closure brings hardship to residents, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Road closure brings hardship to residents, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   L.H. LimASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE closure of the only access road between Taman Sri Melor and
Taman Sri Intan, Kajang, and Sungai Chua by the Selangor State
Development Corporation's on Tuesday has left some 387 families in
the lurch.
	   They now have to use an old wooden bridge to get to the main
road in Bangi and on to Sungai Chua.
	   The residents claimed the bridge was too narrow, allowed only
one-way traffic flow, and was not suitable for heavy vehicles.
	   They fear that fire engines would not be able to use the bridge
to across in the event of a fire at the other side.
	   Even water tankers will not be able to use the bridge, a
resident said.
	   The closure of the access road has also caused massive traffic
congestion along Persiaran Bangi, Jalan Reko and Jalan Sungai Chua
as motorists used these roads as shortcuts from Bandar Baru Bangi
to Sungai Chua.
	   Taman Sri Melor Residents Association secretary Abdul Aziz Abdul
Rahman said residents were upset as the PKNS had not provided an
alternative route.
	   ``PKNS should have asked for views from residents associations
before taking such a drastic step,'' Abdul Aziz said.
	   He said at an earlier meeting between residents associations,
PKNS officials and the developers of Taman Sri Melor and Taman Sri
Intan, the corporation had agreed to build a billet bridge from
Taman Sri Intan to Persiaran Bangi as an alternative route.
	   He said the steel-cabled bridge would provide temporary access
until PKNS fully developed Section 7 and Bandar Baru Bangi.
	   He urged the Kajang Municipal Council (MPKJ) to identify the
access road approved by the council when the former Hulu Langat
District Council approved the housing projects.
	   ``Nothing has been done over the last two years even after the
council had issued the certificate of fitness,'' he said
``Developers and PKNS should not compromise on the basic
infrastructure,''
	   he added.
	   Meanwhile, Taman Sri Intan Residents Association chairman
Mustafa Sulaiman regretted that the wooden bridge had been offered
as an alternative temporary measure.
	   Council president Mohd Yusup Badul said the council will again
hold talks with PKNS to discuss the road closure and the
alternative roads.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
