u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-Kosovo 3rdLd-Writethru   06-12 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-Kosovo, 3rd Ld-Writethru ,0926 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO confers with Russians on Kosovo
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Cohen, Sergeyev quotes &QL; 
 &UR; By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER &QC; 
 &UR; AP Military Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen
said Friday that NATO's planned air power demonstration and
consideration of armed intervention is sending a message to
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic that he should halt the
slaughter of innocent people in Kosovo.
	   ``We are looking at a very short time frame ... to solve this
peacefully,'' Cohen told a news conference at the end of a two-day
defense ministers' meeting at NATO headquarters.
	   Cohen had a private meeting with Russian Defense Minister Igor
Sergeyev in the morning, then again in the afternoon with the other
15 NATO defense ministers as part of the NATO-Russia Permanent
Joint Council.
	   The talks came a day after the Western alliance approved a
show-of-force air exercise over Yugoslav neighbors Albania and
Macedonia and also ordered options be drawn up for possible
intervention in Kosovo, including direct air strikes and the use of
ground troops.
	   Russia opposes the military options NATO is considering for the
Serbian province.
	   ``NATO, all the ministers, and Russia have a unanimous attitude
toward events in Kosovo,'' Sergeyev said at another news
conference. ``Currently, we have to focus on political measures.''
	   More than 250 people have died in clashes between government
forces and the Kosovo Liberation movement. Ethnic Albanians
comprise 90 percent of the province's population.
	   Cohen said he hoped Sergeyev would carry a message back to
President Boris Yeltsin that there is ``undivided consensus by the
NATO countries,'' on the attitude to take toward Yugoslavia.
	   ``That will have an impression, I hope, on President Yeltsin,''
he said.
	   In an interview with ABC television, Cohen warned that NATO's
dim view of the crackdown in Kosovo not be taken too lightly.
	   The NATO alliance agrees ``the bloodshed has to stop; that very
strong message has to be sent to Mr. Milosevic that he has to cease
and desist the slaughter, the shelling of villages and killing of
innocent people and to resolve this peacefully,'' Cohen said.
	   ``We're sending a signal that ... an air exercise will
demonstrate that we have the capacity to mobilize very quickly and
demonstrate rapidly deployable power. But secondly, it also
demonstrates there is solidarity of support and consensus
throughout NATO and beyond NATO itself,'' Cohen said.
	   Cohen met for 45 minutes with the Russian at NATO headquarters
here. Gen. Hugh Shelton, the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,
also attended.
	   Cohen's meeting with Sergeyev was ``very friendly and frank
throughout,'' said a U.S. defense official who spoke on condition
of anonymity.
	   It came a day after the NATO alliance approved a show-of-force
air exercise over Yugoslav neighbors Albania and Macedonia. NATO
also ordered options be drawn up for possible intervention in
Kosovo, including direct air strikes or the use of ground troops.
	   NATO Secretary General Javier Solana said Thursday that Russia
advised the alliance it would not participate in NATO's plans for
an air exercise over Albania and Macedonia. The alliance hopes the
show of military strength can persuade Milosevic to halt attacks on
ethnic Albanian separatists in Kosovo.
	   ``We would like to have as many partners as possible participate
in the exercise,'' Solana said.
	   Russia, which has been brought into some NATO consultations, had
been kept informed of plans for potential military exercises in the
Balkans and at one time had ``showed an interest in
participating,'' Solana said. That was before the most recent
outbreak of violence in Kosovo and NATO's announcement of its air
maneuvers.
	   Moscow favors strengthened control over Kosovo's borders with
Albania and Macedonia. Russia could play a pivotal role in the
persuading Milosevic to turn around the crisis in the
independence-minded province of Serbia, Yugoslavia's dominant
republic.
	   On Thursday, NATO ministers approved a package they hope will
persuade Milosevic to pull back his Serb-led army and police forces
in the province.
	   ``President Milosevic would be rash and foolish if he would
ignore the message coming from NATO,'' said British Defense
Secretary George Robertson. ``The message is clear and unambiguous:
`Belgrade, think again.'''
	   Under the measures, NATO will conduct simulated air attacks in
Albania and Macedonia, probably next week, and study options for
further actions ranging from accelerated planning for military
exercises to direct air strikes inside Yugoslavia and use of ground
troops.
	   This is aimed at persuading Milosevic to do three things:
declare a cease-fire in Kosovo; withdraw his forces and end the
repression of the ethnic Albanians; and open serious negotiations
with the opposition.
	   ``We will be holding exercises in the region, including
immediately an air exercise which will demonstrate NATO's
capability to rapidly project power into the region,'' Solana said.
	   German Defense Minister Volker Ruehe said: ``We cannot afford
any longer to focus on hollow solutions of rather symbolic
character like border security missions in Albania or Macedonia.''
	   Added French Defense Minister Alain Richard: ``We can't let the
protagonists believe that we are prepared to stop at a certain
stage.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-NATO-Kosovo, 3rd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
