<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Fans set aside differences in soccer's melting pot
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos XWCMA-101,102,103 &QL; 
 &UR; By MORT ROSENBLUM &QC; 
 &UR; AP Special Correspondent &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MARSEILLE, France (AP) _ The people shouting ``Go France''
included Algerians just off the boat, kids of Senegalese descent,
and right-wing whites who in normal times say Arabs and blacks
should go home.
	   And South African fans, throwing their arms around the shoulders
of French foes and sharing their beer, were of as many colors as
the new South African flag.
	   This is Marseille, a tough town at the heart of southern France,
where racial politics can get ugly. But when World Cup football is
concerned, all else falls away.
	   ``Football is a religion here, pure and simple,'' said Jean-Luc
Bailly, a local fruit and vegetable king. That is said about a lot
of places, but in Marseille it is no figure of speech.
	   At the ancient port, a happy band of South Africans chanted
Xhosa war cries and hailed their team, ``Bafana Bafana.'' Laughing
Frenchmen fought back with, ``La Marseillaise.''
	   The musical combat recalled that scene out of ``Casablanca,''
but this was more serious than a mere world war. France was about
play its opening match. South Africa would play its first World Cup
match ever.
	   ``We'll win, of course, against all odds,'' Greg Judge
pronounced, with a dubious chuckle. Normally clad in a somber
banker's suit, he wore a huge floppy jester's hat in South African
colors.
	   ``And if we don't, we're still having so much fun it's
unbelievable,'' he said. ``This is the best ever laugh. The French
are cool dudes, and we're loving it.''
	   Judge was among two dozen countrymen, who were leading French
passersby in gyrating African dance. ``We are maybe 4,000 at
most,'' he said. ``We'll have to shout loud to outdo 60,000
Frenchmen.''
	   The French would be shouting loudest for Zinedine Zidane, their
beloved ``Zizou,'' the son of an Algerian night watchman who grew
up in the hardscrabble immigrant suburbs north of Marseille.
	   Another handful of French players spent time with Olympique de
Marseille, ``OM,'' the first division team that is a deity to the
city's massive football congregation.
	   The national team, ``Les Bleus,'' includes black Frenchmen from
Africa, the South Pacific, the Caribbean and South America.
	   Far more than intolerance, the hosts and visitors worried about
the wind, a dreaded ``mistral'' blow that gusted to 120 kilometers
per hour (75 miles an hour) and threatened to give the match the
air of a basketball game.
	   Marseille is nuts about soccer even during the off season. Now
that France is playing its first World Cup game since 1986, the
city talks of nothing else.
	   At Bailly's shop, Le Jardin d'Etienne, housewives poking the
plums and hefting the lettuce argue over the possible score.
	   The McDonalds at the old port offers a World Cup special for 59
francs, about 10 dollars: a Big Mac, fries, a drink, and an ``OM''
scarf.
	   Local radio stations drone on about teams and their chances. If
South Africa does well, one notes, it would be no surprise. The
coach is Philippe Troussier, a Frenchman.
	   Fans that they are, the Marseillais seemed to appreciate the
joyous zeal South Africans brought to their streets.
	   Sam Tsatsi spent dlrs 3,000 he could not easily afford to fly up
for the Cup. As he sang, ``Bafana, Bafana,'' a Frenchman painted up
in blue, red and white chimed in with, ``Allez la France.''
	   ``My team will win,'' Tsatsi informed the man. ``Non,'' the man
replied. They smiled widely and separated, each certain he was
right.
	   Nearby, four South Africans ate a late lunch and discussed their
chances.
	   ``This our first World Cup since we rejoined the world,'' said
Clifford Collings, who works in the Paris embassy of what many call
the new South Africa. ``We'll be doing our best.''
	   Yusuf Randera-Rees, 15, added, ``We'd better.'' He used his
mother's frequent flyer miles to come up from Johannesburg.
	   But this was still Marseille.
	   ``We'll kill them, the poor guys,'' said Rene Raynaud, a
salesman, who had scored rare match tickets for two Caribbean
friends from the French island of Guadaloupe.
	   Raynaud threw an arm around Dominique Capanel and added. ``I
haven't seen my old pals in years. What better occasion can you
imagine?''
</TEXT>
