<HEADLINE>
Abu Hassan urges Ministry to review Fomca, SCA status, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Abu Hassan urges Ministry to review Fomca, SCA status, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Sa'odah EliasASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SHAH ALAM, Wed. - Menteri Besar Datuk Abu Hassan Omar today
urged the Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs Ministry and the
Registrar of Societies to review the status of the Federation of
Malaysian Consumers Associations and the Selangor Consumers
Association.
	   He said their status should be reviewed as their recent actions
were similar to that of political parties rather than consumers
bodies.
	   ``The associations, it seems, are more interested in
politicising the water crisis rather than working with the
authorities to find ways to help consumers.
	   ``This is proven when they work hand in glove with the
opposition parties,'' he told reporters after chairing the weekly
Exco meeting.
	   Abu Hassan was responding to a report quoting the Selangor
Consumers Association's legal advisor A. Jayaseelan as saying at a
Press conference that the association planned to sue the Selangor
State Government and the Menteri Besar for allegedly being
negligent in managing water resources and denying the people a
steady supply of water.
	   Fomca secretary-general N. Marimuthu, DAP secretary-general Lim
Kit Siang, Pas MP for Kubang Kerian Mohamad Sabu, Parti Rakyat
Malaysia secretary-general G. Rajasekaran and representatives of 29
NGOs were also at the Press conference.
	   Today, Abu Hassan said he had directed State Legal Adviser
Ahmadi Asnawi to study the matter and advised the association not
to proceed with its signature drive as it would only confuse the
public.
	   The Menteri Besar said he was shocked when he read the report on
the planned suit as Fomca, being the umbrella body for consumer
associations, had indicated it was satisfied with the explanation
on water resource management given by the Selangor Waterworks
Department at a meeting on June 2.
	   Besides that, he said, the State Government had announced its
plan to hold a briefing on the matter for all State assemblymen,
party leaders and representatives of non-governmental organisations
on June 25.
	   He said the State Government had so far spent RM14 million to
rent tankers and to finance various programmes to ensure enough
water supply for consumers.
	   Abu Hassan said he would also announce during the briefing,
other investments to improve water supply for Selangor and the
Federal Territory.
	   
</TEXT>
