<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Will Norway's British style help against Scotland?
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By STEPHAN NASSTROM &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LA BAULE, France (AP) _ Eleven of Norway's 22 World Cup players
compete in England. The first coach that had an influence on
Norway's manager Egil ``Drillo'' Olsen's was British.
	   No wonder many people say Norway plays British-style soccer.
	   ``My influence very early was George Curtis, who came to Norway
and coached,'' Olsen recalled. ``I started to think more
systematically after seeing him. Then we didn't know about zone
defense at all.''
	   Another British friend is Richard Pollard, who now coaches
college soccer in the United States. He scouted for Olsen when
Scotland _ Norway's next opponent in Group A _ drew 0-0 in an
exhibition against the United States May 30 at RFK Stadium in
Washington D.C.
	   ``I got a report from him,'' Olsen said.
	   Soccer may be an art and not science ``but science will also
influence football,'' said Olsen, who spends hours studying his own
players and opponents on video.
	   He probably is right. Since taking over as head coach in 1990,
Olsen's style has helped the Norwegians to 42 wins, 23 draws and 15
losses in 80 matches. They're unbeaten in their last 15 games,
including a 2-2 draw against Morocco in their World Cup opener
Wednesday.
	   So how does Olsen explain the success of a team that went
unbeaten through its qualifying campaign and beat fellow World Cup
sides Denmark, Mexico and Saudi Arabia by a combined 13-2 in its
last three exhibitions before the World Cup?
	   ``We have fighting spirit ... we've worked hard with the young
talents for years and in my opinion our (long-ball) style is the
most effective,'' Olsen said.
	   ``That's why I believe in it. I was criticized because I said
that if I coached Brazil they would be even better. Of course I
believe in the style. I think our style is also better for others.
It's not only suitable for Norway.''
	   Brazil will be looking for revenge in the last Group A match
June 23 against Norway in Marseille.
	   Ronaldo and company lost a friendly 4-2 a year ago in Oslo with
Tore Andre Flo scoring twice. That's when the tall Chelsea striker
earned his nickname ``Flonaldo''.
	   Olsen liked what he saw in the last 35 minutes of the opener in
Montpellier against Morocco.
	   ``We played very well ... in fact, we had the last five goal
chances in the match,'' he said.
	   Stig Inge Bjornebye, one of Norway's key defenders who set up
Dan Eggen's equalizer with a free kick, was optimistic going into
Tuesday's match with Scotland in Bordeaux.
	   ``I think we have a pretty good chance of making the second
round,'' the Liverpool star said. ``The atmosphere in the squad was
very good after the draw.
	   (sn-sl)
</TEXT>
