<HEADLINE>
Dutch prints on display, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Dutch prints on display, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Ooi Kok ChuenASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A WIDE selection of Dutch printmaking techniques is on display
until tomorrow at the National Art Gallery.
	   Dubbed Graphic Art Now, the more than 200 works through various
processes are taken mainly from last year's seventh edition of the
Graphic Art Now exhibition at the Singer Museum in Laren, Holland,
initiated by two art galleries in Amsterdam, Petit and
Clement/Printshop.
	   Versatile though they are, prints are very much a technique
thing, which could be decisive in the creation of the intended
lines (depth, intensity, pattern, form), images (configuration and
abstract or in-between), tone, colour and texture.
	   Because the employed technique tends to have a homogenising
effect on the end image, the cult of nationality is often a futile
exercise here.
	   Exceptions there are, of course; in Japanese woodcuts and
ukiyo-e prints, for example, and in the stark imagery of German
Expressionism.
	   Printmaking has evolved over several hundred years to allow
greater flexibility, innovation and a multiplicity of subject
matters.
	   Prints are narrative elements or drawings, or even studies or
``reproductions'' of paintings, or mere diversions. They can be
done by printmaking exponents and have been done by famous artists
from Delacroix to Lautrec to Picasso.
	   Themes range from the detailed mythical dramas of Albrecht Durer
to the political satires of Daumier.
	   In Dutch graphics, Rembrandt van Rijn (1609-1669) has few peers.
His etchings are believed by some to have as overpowering an effect
as the play of light and shadow in his oils.
	   The Dutch printmaking tradition dates from the Renaissance, with
engravers like Lucas van Leyden (1494-1533) with his landscapes and
interiors. Other well-known Dutch printmakers include Ferdinand Bol
(1616- 1680), Adriaen van Ostade (1610-1685) and Anthony Waterloo
(1609-1676).
	   This exhibition of contemporary Dutch creations encompasses both
the serious and the frivolous.
	   For simplicity, few can match the Minimalist, frail, coloured
frames of Eric de Nie's etching, Jan Baas's lithography with its
dominant mass of green, the precarious stack of Petra Dolleman's
silkscreen, the broken calligraphic lines of Adri Grigge's etching,
or the configurations in Leo Huijg's woodcut.
	   For fidelity to more complex prints, the landscape etchings of
Hans van Hagen, Reiner Homan, Wim van der Meijetching and Philip
Wiesman contrast sharply with Nicholaas Wijnberg's delicate
still-life and the Mother and Child theme in Lies van Vlijmen's
Portrait.
	   The artists have cast their eyes further afield - to Asia, with
Jacomijn den Engelson's depiction of Buddha's hands and feet in
woodcut, and Ton Diekstra's ``crumbling'' effect in his etching,
Thai Ruins; Ton de Laat strikes a more sombre, almost reverential,
tone in his etching of the Prambahan temple palace in Java.
	   For sheer magnificent panorama, achieved in a small print, Hans
Dolieslager's silkscreen, Summer Field, is a visual delight. And
Diana van Hal's woodcut landscape presents an interesting
topographical flatness.
	   For composition and perspective, there's Laetitia de Haas'
etching of an entrance facing the sea.
	   Strong colour contrast is also evident in Dianne Bakker's
longish woodcut, with the red, dotted dress of her subject set
against a vast brown curtain which blends with her auburn hair.
	   Marli Turion works in digital prints, reminiscent of the
collages of the late Ismail Zain.
	   This is the second time an exhibition of Dutch graphics, culled
from the biennial show, is at the NAG, the previous one having been
in October and November 1995.
	   The exhibition will be in Penang at the Universiti Sains
Malaysia's Museum and Art Gallery from June 25 to July 11.
	   It has toured Singapore, Bangkok, Jakarta, Ho Chi Minh City and
New Delhi, and the next stop is South Africa.
	   Two Malaysian printmakers will conduct a workshop on different
graphic techniques at the centre on Saturday (9am - noon).
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:DUTCH-PRINTS sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
