<DOCNO> APW19980612.1040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 06/12/1998 12:45:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1351 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  ISLAMIC-ART-AND-SOULsked     06-12 2121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> ISLAMIC-ART-AND-SOUL sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Islamic art and soul, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Islamic art and soul, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Mohd Adnan KaderASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   IN a Muslim society, the mosque is the hub of the ``Downtown''
community around which all the hustle and bustle of activities
takes place. There is a certain aura about it which makes it stand
out from among the rest of the buildings.
	   Sheikh Abdul Aziz Kamel, an eminent architect and researcher of
Islamic arts and architecture, explains that the sight of a mosque,
built in reverence and love for God, ``the Creator, the Cherisher
and Sustainer of the worlds, gives comfort to the eyes and the
spirit, because it speaks the language of the soul''. Only
traditional artists and craftsmen are able to build such buildings.
Kamel says that the Islamic world is a treasure throve of
magnificent mosques and palaces symbolishing a rich and humane
civilisation.
	   He commented that the skills of the traditional Muslim artists
and craftsmen that go into building them are still out there but
unfortunately most are now wasting away their lives making
souvenirs for tourists.
	   These traditional artists and craftsmen have the potential and
capabilities not only to design and build mosques and palaces but
also towns, streets, open spaces for gardens, market places and
farms.
	   He says that for too long Muslims have neglected their
inheritance and if they persist they will lose it forever.
	   The testimony to their unique skills are still preserved
throughout the world from Bosnia right across to the vast expanse
of China.
	   In Turkey, Egypt, Iran, Morocco, Pakistan, Uzbekistan, Spain,
Indonesia and Saudi Arabia, we can still see the proud heritage
standing as evidence of the creative genius of the people inspired
by their faith.
	   The examples are abundant, says Kamel, and to name a few, they
are the Alhambra Palace in Andalucia, the buildings of old Cairo,
the mosques of Istanbul, the Niuje mosque in Beijing and, as
acknowledged the most beautiful architectural piece of monument
ever built, the Taj Mahal. The list goes on.
	   Kamel is the only architect at present who has taken it upon
himself to promote and develop the use of traditional Muslim arts
and crafts in the building and the handicraft industry.
	   He says that the process of development of the tradition ceased
with the arrival of the colonialists but now since we are no longer
subjected to their alien rule, Muslims should be encouraged to
revitalise the traditional handicraft industries and modernise them
to suit the present times.
	   Islam is a progressive religion. It does not reject everything
that is foreign but it teaches man ``to enjoin all that is right
and good and forbid all that is wrong and evil.''
	   Though there is no denying that the Muslim nations have
benefited to some extent from the colonialists they have lost much
more in return.
	   For one thing, the sense of humanitarianism has been very much
impaired by the modern demands of consumerism. Consumerism, by its
very nature, is wasteful especially since it has now taken a step
further in promoting the use of disposable consumer products that
are non-biodegradable. This has far reaching implications on the
environment.
	   Middle-aged people and above can still remember the days when
the water was pure, the air clean and the food fresh. The people
were caring and they had more character and individuality. This is
what happiness is all about - to be able to enjoy one's company and
surroundings and feel contented.
	   Kamel is championing the cause of bringing back the Muslim
architectural and handicraft industry to the fore in order to
protect and preserve the environment from the cruel infliction
suffered at the hands of misused technology.
	   He emphasised that the handicraft industry will change the whole
cultural landscape of the towns and instill in people an awareness
of their heritage and tradition.
	   People will cherish the things they own that are handcrafted and
this attitude will be a strong factor in restraining man and help
him to preserve and maintain the delicate balance in the ecosystem.
	   Wouldn't you like to own a beautiful hand-crafted piece of
furniture which you can pass on to your children as a family
heirloom and they to theirs knowing that it is one of its kind?
	   Or do you want a factory-made ``mahogany'', and when the time
comes, you throw it away and buy yet another piece of ``mahogany''
from the so-called ``latest collections''?
	   It may be called ``mahogany'' but it is only a veneer, a
delusion like everything else in the modern world of mass
production. Think about it.
	   When we buy the mass-produced furniture, we are an accomplice to
a crime - the crime of deforestation, the crime of destroying
thousands of animal and plant species, and the crime of persistent
pollution of the environment.
	   During the Caliphate, the artists and craftsmen had a great deal
of influence on the growth and development of the traditional urban
society of the Muslim world.
	   The seed of the concept of Muslim downtown was first planted
when Prophet Mohammed identified a spot for a market place and a
mosque when he went to Al-Madinah Al-Munawarah to establish the
first Muslim community, says Kamel, during his lecture at the
conference on ``Art and Architecture in the Muslim World'', held in
Shah Alam last year.
	   This set the blueprint for the future shape of development of
the Muslim towns to serve the spiritual and material need of the
people.
	   Commerce and spiritual life go hand in hand in the Islamic way
of life.
	   Islam reached Malaysia and Indonesia by way of commerce.
	   Kamel observed that during the Golden Ages of Islamic
civilisation, the just and pious rule of the caliphs provided the
ideal conditions for the people to achieve the greatest
accomplishment in the arts, architecture, the sciences,
philosophies and mathematics.
	   Furthermore, they were the premier patrons of the arts and
sciences. The successive Caliphs governed with varying degrees of
understanding of the relationship between the spiritual world and
the material world and the importance of continued economic
prosperity.
	   Everybody benefited from this including non-Muslims who lived in
peace and harmony with the Muslims and enjoyed a life of freedom
and equal opportunities.
	   Kamel strongly feels that mimicking the West and its lifestyle
is unnatural and it is causing chaos to both society and the
environment.
	   According to him, the western concepts of town planning divides
the town into zones.
	   There is the industrial zone, commercial zone, residential zone
and recreational zone. This is the main contributing factor to the
stress people are faced with now.
	   In a modern metropolis, people spend a great deal of time to
travel to and from work everyday. The lifestyle is the direct cause
of increasing demands for cars and the subsequent massive traffic
jams choking up the highways.
	   ``Modern cities,'' says Kamel, ``are constructed from glass,
concrete and steel structures with their main consideration only
for cars and other fast transportation to move man. Humans are
secondary. The structures are cold and sterile, a good breeding
ground for all the social ills.
	   ``In these surroundings, Man is made to feel insignificant and
he is perpetually on edge. He is psychologically restless and
impatient without understanding why. In the evening most of the
downtown is dead, because people want to get away as quickly as
they can to the comfort of their home. Modern cities are not
people-friendly.''
	   Kamel feels that the effects can be softened with a little human
touch.
	   The human touch can be applied with various natural elements,
like wood, wrought iron, copper, brass, natural floral tiles and
stucco-coloured glass.
	   All it takes is the skill of the traditional Muslim artists and
craftsmen.
	   Kamel says that the buildings that man build asserts an
imperceptible influence on the spirit of the people.
	   Man may build buildings but it is the buildings that build the
soul of the children and the children's children, he says.
	   Traditional Muslim artists and craftsmen considered the effect
of sight on the human soul. They believed that the quickest way to
remove stress is through what the eyes perceive. People feel
comfortable with arches, domes and pillars decorated with human
elements as they can relate it to the elements of nature that they
represent.
	   In Islam, art is functional. Everything man uses in his daily
life is art, says Kamel.
	   Utensils, vases, carpets, the copper lamp, even the design of
the Quran is a work of art. These designs in turn have a great
influence on the artists and architects who used them on the
ornaments on the ceilings, walls and other areas.
	   One of the most important features of a traditional Muslim home
is the privacy of the family. The home must be airy and comfortable
and the women's modesty protected.
	   The concept of courtyard grew out of this and to keep the home
cool in the daytime, the wind direction and the movement of the sun
are taken into consideration before the house is designed.
	   The art of Mashrabiah, the wooden lattices, was developed to
serve as a protection of woman's modesty. It is like a veil: people
can't see the face but they can be seen clearly.
	   Mashrabiah is used for the windows or partition indoors. It is
designed in such a way that it keeps the home airy. It is one of
the most advanced art forms; in fact, it is a philosophy.
	   Central in the tradition of the Muslim arts and architecture is
the institution of the Mu'almeen, the master craftsman. The
tradition goes back more than a thousand years.
	   In a traditional Muslim society, says Kamel, art is everything
that is made by the sensitive hands of the craftsmen who are very
much respected.
	   As the Islamic influences spread so did the creative influence
of the artists and craftsmen.
	   The towns grew according to the dictates of the Islamic way of
life. The origin of the Muslim architecture may have its roots in
Arabia but the style varies from country to country, says Kamel.
	   This tradition was perpetuated by the highly refined institution
of Mu'almeen. The Mu'almeen are the equivalent of the modern-day
architects.
	   The Mu'almeen also followed a strict scientific building code
which reflected the Islamic social values and its obligatory
duties, says Kamel.
	   This resulted in the existence of an urban fabric which
preserved the psychological well-being of the town dwellers. It
also holds true for the preservation of the environment.
	   The Mu'almeen had many apprentices. The greatest accomplishments
in Muslim architecture today bears testimony of the superior skills
of the Mu'almeen.
	   The Mu'almeen used the local craftsmen and local building
materials. For this reason, the mosques and other buildings were
constructed with the same principles and methods but they had a
flavour of its own.
	   The mosques in Tunisia and Turkey, for instance, have their own
unique identities, says Kamel.
	   In China, though the Chinese philosophy and culture may appear
worlds apart from Islam yet Islamic belief took root there by
merging gently and harmoniously with the Chinese philosophy and
culture.
	   It is a clear evidence of the universal appeal of Islam and it
can be seen in the shape of the mosques which are a beautiful blend
of Chinese and Muslim architectural elements.
	   Islamic art and architecture are not only confined to building
mosques and palaces but also homes, markets, streets, open spaces
for gardens and farms. The concept of township in Islam is based on
man's unity with his environment.
	   Town centres in traditional Muslim cities are made for
pedestrians. In England, more and more city centres are restricted
only for pedestrians.
	   The pedestrian malls are spruced with trees and plants and
benches for people to sit. This new concept is coming close to the
Muslim concept except it is devoid of spirituality which the mosque
provides.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
