<HEADLINE>
Casino drops plans to sue Sarawak MP, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Casino drops plans to sue Sarawak MP, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Wed. - The Australian-based Asean Protective
Services agency will not proceed with legal action against a
Sarawakian MP who owed the Burswood International Resort casino in
Perth RM4.8 million.
	   This agreement was reached after the politician had promised to
pay the debt in instalments.
	   Agency director Christopher White said, however, it will proceed
with legal action against six other Malaysians who owed the casino
some RM2.4 million.
	   ``We have decided not to proceed with legal action against the
Sarawakian MP as we have reached a commercial settlement,'' he said
when contacted.
	   The MP is a senior member of the Parti Bangsa Dayak Sarawak.
	   Yesterday, the MP made a RM50,000 first payment to the agency,
which was engaged by the casino to recover debts, and pledged to
settle the remaining sum by the end of the year.
	   The payment was made by telegraphic transfer through a bank in
Perth.
	   The agency has received the money.
	   ``We have got no further interest in the MP's case as he has
promised to pay the amount in due course,'' he said.
	   White said a Klang-based lawyer who owed the casino RM500,000
has also worked out a repayment scheme to settle his debts.
	   The MP and the lawyer were among eight Malaysians who had been
threatened with legal action by Burswood to recover gambling debts
totalling some RM8 million.
	   However, White said the agency will serve writs to the six
others who owed the casino RM2.4 million.
	   ``We will serve the writs to the six within this month.
	   ``We have no other choice as they have not come forward to seek
a compromise,'' he said.
	   He said three were from Selangor and the others from Johor.
	   He said the six had debts with the casino dating back one to
three years.
	   
</TEXT>
