<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Football-World Bowl </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
German love affair with football helps NFL Europe's World Bowl
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ROY KAMMERER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ No one symbolizes the Germans' love
affair with American football like 48-year-old Rhein Fire place
kicker Manny Burgsmueller.
	   Burgsmueller, a former German soccer great, passed the legendary
George Blanda this season as the oldest man ever to play pro
football.
	   ``The game is fascinating _ like a chess match,'' said
Burgsmueller, a few months older than Blanda when he retired.
	   Burgsmueller leads the Duesseldorf Rhein Fire against German
rival Frankfurt Galaxy in Sunday's World Bowl _ the championship
game of the NFL Europe league.
	   League officials predict a sellout of 50,000, quite an
accomplishment during the middle of soccer's World Cup.
	   The two clubs' regular season meetings both topped 40,000 in
attendance. They are also 1-2 in league attendance, with Frankfurt
averaging 34,202 and Duesseldorf 25,448.
	   ``Football is booming in Germany,'' said Rhein Fire spokesman
Gerald Meier. ``There's millions of Germans that like the American
way of life and football is a part of that.''
	   But if the NFL and Fox, joint owners of NFL Europe, can
celebrate their success in Germany, a look elsewhere around the
league brings a hard reality check.
	   The England Monarchs drew a dismal 5,944 fans per game, while
neither the Barcelona Dragons or Scottish Claymores could crack
10,000.
	   That's one reason why NFL owners and Fox officials will meet in
Frankfurt this week to determine the future of the league.
	   One thing is clear: Either Barcelona, Scotland or the English
franchise will be scrapped and replaced next season in the six-team
league by a new club in Berlin.
	   ``We're having incredible success in Germany,'' said NFL Europe
president Oliver Luck, a former Houston Oilers quarterback. ``And
we have to ask ourselves, can we continue to support a franchise
that tops out at 10,000, if that's all the market will give us?''
	   Soccer is so dominant in Europe that in most countries there
really isn't a No. 2 sport. Many people believe that's one reason
football has caught on in Germany.
	   ``The most popular sports are soccer, soccer, followed by indoor
soccer. But after that, in team sports, there is a huge gap,'' Luck
said.
	   The lone exception is the British Isles, where football has
failed to compete with a variety of sports as well as soccer.
	   ``A typical statement from the Brits is we have our rugby, our
cricket, our snooker _ there are very few disengaged fans,'' Luck
said.
	   NFL Europe also admits to mistakes in Barcelona, England and
Scotland, with too many management switches and a failure to build
local identification with the clubs.
	   The two German teams, on the other hand, have a reputation for
saavy promotion. Rhein Fire, for example, drew media attention
across the country by advertising on manhole covers.
	   But the team's most successful PR move was signing up the then
46-year-old Burgsmueller three years ago, giving the fledgling club
and the sport some badly needed name recognition.
	   Burgsmueller is German soccer's fourth all-time leading scorer
with 213 goals. He's also loved by the country's working-class fans
for his hard-nosed style.
	   But the ex-forward has surprised everyone by becoming a vital
weapon in the team's offense.
	   Burgsmueller was the league's leading scorer this season with 57
points, making all 21 PATs and going 12 for 13 in field goal
attempts.
	   He admits that, three years ago, he didn't know the first thing
about the American game.
	   ``I said from the start I would need to perform well for this to
work,'' Burgsmueller said. ``But this just proves that even at an
advanced age, if you set your mind to it, you can succeed at a new
sport.''
	   (rk/sw) 	   
</TEXT>
