<SLUG> BC-Sports-Auto Racing-Tyrell </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tyrell boss gets fitting retirement present
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   GOODWOOD, England (AP) _ Tyrell Grand Prix boss Ken Tyrell
received a fitting retirement present Friday, when his
grandchildren re-acquired the Formula One car Jackie Stewart drove
to the 1970 championship.
	   Two of Tyrell's grandchildren paid 73,000 pounds (dlrs 119,720)
at auction for the first Tyrell-Cosworth Formula One car produced
for the Scottish driver.
	   Adrian Tyrell, 28, and his cousin, Claire, said they had paid a
reasonable price for the car which launched Stewart on a string of
wins in the early 1970s.
	   ``In fact it was not as much as we expected and I have got
something I really wanted,'' Adrian said.
	   Ken Tyrell said: ``I'm delighted the car is staying in the
family. I think it would be sad if it had gone abroad.''
	   (jp) 	   
