<BODY>
<SLUG> COUNTERFIT-CARD-RACKET sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Counterfeit card racket crippled, 10 arrested, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Counterfeit card racket crippled, 10 arrested, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   R.V. VeeraASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Wed. - Police have crippled an international
syndicate believed to have used counterfeit credit cards to rake in
about RM15 million in cash and goods, with the arrest of 10 people
in the Klang Valley, early this week.
	   Initial investigations revealed that the gang members had been
operating for about five years with established ``links'' in Hong
Kong, Thailand, Australia, Japan and European countries.
	   Among those detained in a series of raids on Monday were the
syndicate's suspected mastermind, a woman, and at least two men
believed to have been picked up by police earlier, for similar
offences.
	   Police have obtained remand orders to detain the 10 - who were
arrested in Wangsa Maju, Ampang and Old Klang Road - to facilitate
their probe.
	   Also seized were several hundred counterfeit credit cards, an
assortment of equipment and related paraphernalia used to produce
plastic cards and emboss the relevant particulars and data on them.
	   The arrests followed weeks of intensive surveillance by a team
of officers from the Commercial Crime branch of the Federal police
headquarters in Bukit Aman.
	   The New Straits Times understands that most victims of the
fraudulant transactions were merchants of outlets which had
unknowingly accepted the counterfeit credit cards in Japan, apart
from those in Hong Kong, Australia and some countries in Europe.
	   A source said: ``Members of the gang do not stay at one place to
operate their counterfeit trade. They are known to use several
make-shift operations centres in the Klang Valley to avoid police
detection.
	   ``It is at these centres that the gang is known to have used an
assortment of equipment to produce blank cards before embossing and
encoding the names and relevant data of genuine card holders.
	   ``The data which the gang had obtained is believed to have been
duplicated at high-risk outlets where owners lose sight of their
credit cards during transactions for payment of goods or for other
services.''
	   The source said that apart from the purchase of goods, the gang
members had also made cash withdrawals through automated teller
machines in Malaysia and overseas.
	   In Monday's operation, the police team which had split into
groups raided several areas in the Klang Valley to make the
arrests.
	   In one of the raids, police arrested six people after a search
of a flat in Taman Wangsa Maju - believed to have been the gang's
most recent operation centre.
	   Fax machines, embossing machines and several hundred counterfeit
credit cards were also seized from the flat.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
