<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turks and Caicos-Haitian Refugees,0247 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report says Haitians who died in capsized boat were not shot
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   COCKBURN TOWN, Turks and Caicos (AP) _ Examinations of the
bodies of six Haitian refugees who drowned Monday when their sloop
capsized off the Turks and Caicos islands did not have gunshot
wounds, police said Friday.
	   Some of the survivors of the shipwreck said marine police had
fired at the boat. But police said warning shots were fired in the
air, but not at the overcrowded boat, said Deputy Police
Commissioner Bryan Davies.
	   The sunken boat has been raised and will be examined, Davies
said Friday.
	   The 70 Haitians who survived the sinking are being interviewed
with the help of interpreters and also spent more than an hour
Thursday talking with a representative from the Haitian consulate
in the Bahamas.
	   The ship sank Monday just 15 miles off Providenciales, the
largest island in the British archipelago 600 miles southeast of
Florida.
	   Survivors said as many as 113 people were on the boat, but
police said there were about 70 survivors and six bodies recovered.
	   Davies said police also want to interview the occupants of two
sailing yachts that may have been near the incident. The names of
the vessels are unknown, but some survivors said they were flying
U.S. flags.
	   Thousands of Haitian refugees fleeing their impoverished country
have ended up in the Turks and Caicos islands in recent years.
</TEXT>
