<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Ingushetia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ingush leader appeals to Yeltsin to help get hostages released
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The leader of southern Russia's Ingush region
appealed Friday to President Boris Yeltsin to help obtain the
release of two Ingush held hostage in neighboring North Ossetia.
	   The two were among more than a dozen bus passengers taken
hostage Monday in the North Ossetian village of Batako. The rest
were released.
	   The hostage-taking was an apparent retaliation for the abduction
of seven residents from Batako, which was blamed on Ingush.
	   Ingush leader Ruslan Aushev appealed to Yeltsin to help and to
restore order in the region, the ITAR-Tass news agency reported.
	   Both North Ossetia and Ingushetia are located in the North
Caucasus, a restive region that also includes breakaway Chechnya.
	   Predominantly Orthodox Christian North Ossetia and Muslim
Ingushetia fought a short but bloody war in 1992. Hundreds of
people were killed and most ethnic Ingush were expelled from North
Ossetia.
	   Aushev said Ingush homes have been burned in North Ossetia and
some people trying to return to their former homes face resistance.
	   (ls) 	   
</TEXT>
