<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-England ,0432 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: England's Tony Adams set for ``good day at the office''
</HEADLINE>
against Tunisia &QL; 
 &UR; By MORLEY MYERS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LA BAULE, France (AP) _ With their opening match just three days
away, England's World Cup players relaxed with a round of golf
Friday, seemingly ignoring Monday's crucial Group G clash with
Tunisia in Marseilles.
	   But behind the lighthearted humor, manager Glen Hoddle's
22-strong squad was focussed on the task ahead.
	   ``They are really looking forward to going into action and there
is an extra bounce in their step as it gets closer,'' said Hoddle.
	   No one is more eager to get into the fray than Tony Adams, the
iron man at the heart of the England defense.
	   Like the rest of the England players, 31-year-old Adams has
never figured in a World Cup finals tournament, despite playing in
51 internationals.
	   ``I am very excited and very grateful to get the opportunity to
play at the highest level. This is a very exciting period of my
life,'' said Adams, a recovering alcoholic who has conquered his
personal demons.
	   Adams' joy at captaining Arsenal to the League and FA Cup
battle, was marred by an end-of-season injury, but there are no
question marks about his fitness now.
	   ``I feel very fit, at my strongest. The rest I had after the FA
Cup was good for me,'' he said.
	   Adams was impressed with the way Brazil opened its title defense
with a 2-1 victory over Scotland, saying the champions had good
players in addition to the star-rated Ronaldo.
	   ``Brazil is an excellent team. You stop one player and another
one gets through. It is not just about Ronaldo, although he is a
marvelous player. I relish the chance of to play against this sort
of opponent.''
	   But Adams is now concentrating on Tunisia, determined to enjoy a
good day at the office _ which is how he describes his match
performances.
	   ``Our first game is Tunisia and I expect to have hell of a good
day at the office, as simple as that,'' he said. ``I am focused
bang on Tunisia ... I will know the strengths and weakness of every
player they have on the team by then.''
	   Adams felt disappointed at the axing of Paul Gascoigne, but
believed the story of Gazza's downfall should be laid to rest.
	   ``There is an element of sadness. I would have liked a fit
talented Paul Gascoigne playing in the World Cup, but it is not to
be and to keep talking about it is to do a disservice to the other
players ... you have got to go out there and seize the day.''
	   (mm-sl)
</TEXT>
