<SLUG> BETTER-CARE-FOR-IPOH'S sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Better care for Ipoh's expectant mothers, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Better care for Ipoh's expectant mothers, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Khairun NazirahASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   EXPECTANT mothers can expect special treatment at the Ipoh
Hospital's Obstetric and Gynaecology (O&AMP;G) unit with the launch of
an aggressive programme to ensure that pregnancies are risk-free.
	   The unit has been revamped; some of the facilities have been
upgraded and new ones installed. It occupies a RM3 million complex
which sits on the site of the old hospital which was built 10 years
ago.
	   Its comfortable waiting area and well-equipped labour suites
will help calm the jitters of new expectant mothers, especially.
	   The complex has a fully operational modern birthing centre, an
operation theatre, a sterilisation unit, eight maternity suites and
a seminar hall.
	   It is equipped with the facilities to cope with high-risk
pregnancies.
	   A brainchild of the hospital's O&AMP;G unit chief Datuk Dr N.
Sivalingam, the centre is the result of years of research and
planning. This has paid off as the centre is now not only the the
pride of the Ipoh Hospital, but the northern region as well. It
also serves as a teaching and referral centre for the region.
	   Pregnancy and childbirth may be natural processes but they are
by no means risk-free. However, with modern research, there are
ways of cutting down the risks and reducing the number of maternal
deaths.
	   Health Ministry director-general Tan Sri Dr Abu Bakar Suleiman
said recently that there are plans to set up ultra-modern birthing
centres at obstetric and gynaecology units by the year 2000 in
Malaysia's hospitals to cope with high-risk pregnancies.
	   He said the centres would have an atmosphere close to the home
environment.
	   Although such centres have been set up in some hospitals, they
were merely equipped with maternity units unlike at the Ipoh
Hospital where it is a new, independent complex.
	   Dr Abu Bakar said the Ipoh O&AMP;G complex was one of the ministry's
earlier budgeted projects that was carried out despite the economic
downturn.
	   According to Dr Sivalingam, the Ipoh unit also adopts the
ministry's shared care concept for all pregnancies. This involves
the use of outside health centres and the private sector, including
general practitioners, for normal pregnancies.
	   ``Here, we use the Risk Coding System which allows staff of
public health centres to identify the mothers through colour
codes,'' he explained.
	   The colour coding identification method is a strategy to reduce
maternal morbidity and mortality as high-risk mothers or pregnant
moms who require special care are managed more intensively.
	   New mothers' visiting cards are tagged with one of four colours
- white, green, yellow and red.
	   The new moms visiting any of the primary healthcare centres will
first be screened by a doctor and given a tag according to their
health status.
	   A mother with pre-existing conditions such as high blood
pressure, diabetes, heart problems or severe anaemia is considered
high-risk mothers because her chance of developing complications
are higher, and will be given a red tag which means she must
deliver her baby in hospital.
	   A yellow tag indicates that her pregnancy must be monitored by a
doctor while green- and white-tagged moms are considered low-risk
cases and receive care at clinic-level.
	   The code system is reviewed with each ante-natal and post-natal
visit.
	   The four major causes of maternal death in Malaysia are post
partum haemorrhage (uncontrolled bleeding after delivery);
hypertensive-related pregnancies; pulmonary embolism and associated
medical conditions such as rheumatic heart diseases; and diabetes.
	   Mothers found to be anaemic are given iron, folic acid and
vitamin B complex supplements while underweight moms are put on the
supplementation feeding programme and will receive full cream milk
and hematinics.
	   Perak's network of primary healthcare facilities comprising
consisting of health centres and community clinics have trained
nurses and midwives with experience in outpatient treatment or
first aid.
	   At the community clinics, cooking demonstrations and talks on
nutrition are conducted by community nurses for the new mothers in
the vicinity.
	   Like other disciplines, the O&AMP;G unit also has its own High
Dependency Unit (HDU) to monitor the critically ill obstetric
patients who do not meet the criteria for admission to an intensive
care unit.
	   The HDU is also to reduce the morbidity and mortality of
critically ill obstetric patients and like a caring body, the unit
also ensures that the patients and their relatives are given moral
support during the critical phase of the illness.
	   All admission to the HDU, which has six beds, is determined
through consultation with the specialist. Those likely to be
admitted are patients with cardiopulmonary disorders, complicated
heart diseases, acute bronchial asthma, severe lung disease, severe
hypertension, obstetric haemorrhaging and other severe medical or
surgical conditions.
	   In addition, those with post-delivery complications like
postpartum haemorrhaging, sepsis and deep vein thrombosis may also
be admitted.
	   Despite its purpose, the HDU room is far from a morbid area. The
bright and clean environment, and the friendly staff are
therapeutic.
	   Other programmes run by the O&AMP;G unit include the weekly
ante-natal classes involving both husband and wives. During these
classes, the couples are taught normal preparatory exercises,
physiology, lactation, contraception and delivery.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BETTER-CARE-FOR-IPOH'S sked; CT:w; 
