<HEADLINE>
Closure of radio channels confirmed, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Closure of radio channels confirmed, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Wed. - Airtime Management &AMP; Programming (AMP)
today confirmed the closure of its two radio channels, TalkRadio
and Classic Rock.
	   Two new Astro's 24-hour non-FM channels - Era and Chuan Zhen Xin
Qu Tai (both under AMP management) - which were previously aired
from Astro's digital satellite radio, have since been broadcast
over the two vacant frequencies.
	   At present, Era (the Bahasa Malaysia network) can be heard at
these frequencies; 103.3FM Klang Valley, 103.6FM Seremban, 103.6FM
Penang, 103.7FM Ipoh, 90.3FM Malacca and 104.5FM Johor Baru, while
Chuan Zhen Xin Qu Tai's frequencies are as follows; 101.8FM Klang
Valley, 100.6FM Seremban, 99.7FM Penang, 100.6FM Ipoh, 106.4FM
Malacca and 95.4FM Johor Baru.
	   It is learnt that while the closure of the Classic Rock channel
was a hot speculation for almost a month, TalkRadio's came as a
surprise. The closure took effect last Monday.
	   The former was given a two-and-a-half-week advance notice of its
closure while the decision on the latter was taken only a few days
before the shut down.
	   Prior to the closure, Classic Rock tunes were aired on Astro's
satellite radio on Channel 307, while TalkRadio was on Dawn Radio
channel on Astro's 308.
	   According to AMP general manager Ruslan Abdul Rahman, although
both Classic Rock and TalkRadio had attracted a group of dedicated,
loyal listeners, based on market research, the company concluded
that the size of the audience did not justify dedicated networks.
	   ``That is why we decided to introduce the Bahasa Malaysia and
Chinese language networks to provide new opportunities for the
promotion of local music and artistes.''
	   
</TEXT>
