<HEADLINE>
Singer Na Ying has no regrets about relationship, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Singer Na Ying has no regrets about relationship, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Ricky YapASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   HER romance with a Chinese soccer player forced her out of the
recording studios for three years, but it was a blessing in
disguise for singer Na Ying.
	   At that time, the Chinese soccer team was trying to make the
1996 Atlanta Olympics, followed by the 1998 World Cup qualifiers,
and public opinion was that Na Ying's relationship with Kao Fong, a
striker, would distract him.
	   ``There was pressure on us to break the relationship as the fans
were afraid Kao Fong would not be at his best.
	   ``However, they gradually accepted us when they realised we were
really in love,'' said Na Ying.
	   ``We met during a function in 1995 where I was one of the
performers and Kao Fong and his teammates were guests. He
introduced himself and we started talking. The next day, he called
me and we soon became a couple.''
	   Na Ying added that not many people could accept the relationship
and some even chided her. ``I did a lot of soul-searching during
those three years and told myself that once the public furore died,
I needed a fresh start in my singing career. I set my sights on the
regional music market and changed management companies.'' She
joined K's Productions Ltd, which manages Taiwanese singer Jeff
Chang. It clinched a three-year recording deal for Na Ying with EMI
Asia last June.
	   Na Ying then released a Mandarin album, Conquer, apparently
referring to her desire to break into Chinese-speaking markets.
	   Na Ying's friend, Faye Wong, sings backup vocals on Dream Is
Over. Na Ying also composed her first song, No Matter How Bitter.
	   Na Ying started singing at 10 and joined the Sheng Yang Music
Academy in 1983. She graduated two years later and joined a
song-and-dance troupe in her hometown. In 1988, she won the gold in
the ``Yang Guang'' nationwide singing competition. Since then, she
has released more than 15 albums. Na Ying was voted Best Female
Artiste of China from 1991 to 1995.
	   Na Ying does not have any regrets about missed opportunities as
she loves Kao Fong. They have not set a wedding date as both are
busy with their careers.
	   Na Ying was in Kuala Lumpur and Penang recently for meet-the-fan
sessions. During a Press conference, she received a souvenir plaque
from an EMI Asia representative.
	   
</TEXT>
