<HEADLINE>
DOE to submit report on noise pollution, vibration from plant, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
DOE to submit report on noise pollution, vibration from plant, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SEREMBAN, Wed. - The State Department of Environment has been
asked to submit a detailed report on the alleged noise pollution
and vibration from a power plant which is affecting residents of
Taman NLFCS in Tanjong Gemuk, Port Dickson.
	   Menteri Besar Tan Sri Mohamad Isa Abdul Samad said today the
report was necessary in the wake of cracks appearing on roads in
the housing estate which the residents claim are caused by the
vibrations.
	   He said the State Public Works Department has also been directed
to conduct tests on the affected roads to ascertain the cause of
the problem.
	   The New Straits Times reported today that 60 families living
near the plant of the independent power producer were worried about
the problem which they claimed was turning from bad to worse.
	   Taman NLFCS Residents' Association committee chairman S. Gabriel
claimed that despite numerous appeals to the authorities no
effective measures had been taken to solve the problem.
	   He said the residents moved into their homes in 1992 while the
plant was set up in 1994.
	   The problems faced by the residents ere first highlighted by the
NST in October 1996.
	   Mohaned Isa said the matter was raised during the recent State
Development Committee meeting following complaints received from
the Taman NLFCS Residents' Association committee members. ``They
also met me to explain their problem,'' he said after chairing the
State Executive Council meeting at Wisma Negri here.
	   He said the DOE in its preliminary report during the meeting
stated that the vibration was within the permissible level.
	   However, Mohamad Isa said, the department was asked to look into
the complaint again and to come up with an in-depth report.
	   Meanwhile, a spokesman of Port Dickson Power Sdn Bhd, when
contacted, said the company was arranging a meeting with the
affected residents.
	   He said they were willing to meet the residents' committee and
iron out whatever grievances they face.
	   ``We will listen to all their problems and do our best to settle
the matter soon,'' he added.
	   Gabriel confirmed that the company had contacted him to arrange
a meeting to discuss the matter.
	   However, Gabriel said what the residents really wanted was for
their homes to be relocated and not mere compensation.
	   According to him, residents there had been suffering for the
past five years and being compensated would not put an end to the
problem.
	   ``Compensation would not mean an end to the problem,'' he said,
adding that what they wanted was to be compensated for their losses
during the five years and to be relocated to avoid any further
hardship.
	   He said that they were now unable to sell their houses as
everyone was aware of their plight and there would be no takers.
	   ``Therefore, we have no choice but ask that we be relocated and
compensated for whatever losses and sufferings experienced,'' he
said.
	   
</TEXT>
