<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Bergkamp's fear of flying may eliminate him from 2002
</HEADLINE>
World Cup &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   VERSAILLES, France (AP) - Injury deprives some superstars of
ever playing in the World Cup.
	   Others have the misfortune to be born in countries too weak to
ever qualify for the showpiece event.
	   Dutchman Dennis Bergkamp is set to bow out of soccer's most
important event in 1998 for a more unusual reason: a profound fear
of flying.
	   On the eve of the Netherlands' World Cup opener Saturday,
Bergkamp conceded that his refusal to fly makes any thought of
appearing at the 2002 tournament in Japan and South Korea
impractical.
	   ``I am 29 and it's is difficult to know what will happen in the
future. But I don't think the situation will change when it comes
to me flying,'' Bergkamp said.
	   Bergkamp won't specify the exact reason for his fear of flying,
but he hasn't set foot in a plane since returning from the 1994
World Cup.
	   During the championship, a Dutch journalist flying with the team
between Orlando to Dallas caused a bomb hoax as the aircraft was
delayed on the runway.
	   Known as an introspective and thoughtful player, Bergkamp had
already been disturbed by a plane crash that killed 176 people _
including Surinamese youth players - in 1989.
	   Counseling, arranged by both by the Netherlands and his club
Arsenal, has failed to ease Bergkamp's anxiety, and the striker
will travel separately from his teammates between World Cup venues.
	   Bergkamp, unlikely to start against Belgium because of injury,
has been in spectacular form for Arsenal, guiding the club to the
English Premiership and F.A. Cup double last year.
	   Voted the third best player in the world by FIFA in 1997,
Bergkamp has scored 33 goals for the Netherlands, putting him just
two short of the Dutch record held by Faas Wilkes.
	   (ae-sl)
</TEXT>
