<SLUG> AUSTRALIA-KEEN-ON-JOINT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Australia keen on joint ventures in MSC project, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Australia keen on joint ventures in MSC project, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Shyla SangaranASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Australian Government has expressed strong interest to
collaborate with its Malaysian counterpart in the Multimedia Super
Corridor (MSC) project, particularly with regards to the electronic
commerce (e-commerce) flagship application.
	   Its Minister for Communications, Information Economy and the
Arts Senator Richard Alston said both countries stand to benefit
from such a collaboration especially when e-commerce promises huge
business opportunities.
	   He added that Australia views the MSC not only from a business
viewpoint, but also in terms of the prospects of enhancing further
its ties with Malaysia. ``The MSC facilitates the exchange of ideas
and knowledge. On top of that, we are very keen in touching base
and maintaining the good relationship with the Malaysian
Government,'' Alston said, adding that more Australian companies
are expected to set up operations in Malaysia in the future. He was
speaking to reporters after visiting the office of MSC-status
company and home-grown software developer Datek Sdn Bhd in Petaling
Jaya on Monday.
	   Other than the MSC partnership, Alston said Australia will
assist Malaysia in its efforts to put in place the new Multimedia
and Communication Act. He explained that this followed his recent
meeting with of Energy, Telecommunications and Posts Minister Datuk
Leo Moggie.
	   The Act is designed to improve the efficiency of the existing
telecommunications industry and to facilitate the development of
new information technology (IT) and multimedia services in
Malaysia.
	   At the same Press conference, Datek's chairman and chief
executive officer Darryl Carlton announced that the company will
launch its new accounting business software solution next month,
followed by another product, Arumba, which is targeted for
telecommunications companies, in September.
	   
</TEXT>
