<HEADLINE>
Russian soldiers seized, bomb explodes in Muslim cemetery in
</HEADLINE>
Dagestan &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: INCORPORATES BC-Russia-Ingushetia, minor editing. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Ten Russian soldiers were kidnapped and a powerful
time-bomb exploded in a Muslim cemetery in the Caucasus republic of
Dagestan on Friday, wounding one person, Russian news agencies
reported.
	   The soldiers were seized Thursday night in a suburb of the
Dagestani capital Makhachkala and their bus was taken in the
direction of neighboring Chechnya, the ITAR-Tass news agency said,
citing the local Interior Ministry.
	   No other details of the abduction were available.
	   The bomb Friday exploded at the grave of the father of
Makhachkala's mayor, the Interfax news agency said.
	   Mayor Said Amirov was not at the grave when the explosion
occurred _ even though it went off in the afternoon hours when
people often visit their recently deceased relatives' graves.
Amirov has been visiting the grave daily since his father died last
week, Interfax said.
	   In other unrest in the Caucasus region on Friday, the leader of
Ingushetia appealed to Russian President Boris Yeltsin to help
obtain the release of two Ingush held hostage in neighboring North
Ossetia.
	   The two were among more than a dozen bus passengers taken
hostage Monday in the North Ossetian village of Batako. The rest
were released.
	   The hostage-taking was an apparent retaliation for the abduction
of seven residents from Batako, which was blamed on Ingush.
	   Predominantly Orthodox Christian North Ossetia and Muslim
Ingushetia fought a short but bloody war in 1992. Hundreds of
people were killed and most ethnic Ingush were expelled from North
Ossetia.
	   Aushev said Ingush homes have been burned in North Ossetia and
some people trying to return to their former homes face resistance.
	   A police checkpoint in North Ossetia was attacked with grenades
and gunfire on Thursday night but no one was hurt, ITAR-Tass said.
	   The attack on the mobile post near the mountain village of Chmi
was the second to target a North Ossetian police station in two
days, ITAR-Tass said. On Wednesday night, automatic rifle-fire and
grenades hit another police post set up near a quarry.
	   Citing local police, ITAR-Tass said that ``all traces'' of both
attacks led to Ingushetia.
	   (ji/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
