<SLUG> BC-Austria-Blockade, 1st Ld Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Environmentalists block main north-south artery, other freeway
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs. RECASTS and UPDATES with no major traffic snarls, only
about 1,000 attending rally at Schoenberg on Brenner pass,
comments; ADDS byline. &QL; 
 &UR; By ROLAND PRINZ &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer

<TEXT>
	   VIENNA, Austria (AP) _ Local residents and environmentalists
Friday started a 28-hour blockade of the Brenner Pass on the
Austrian-Italian border, but bad weather and advance warning
prevented any of the predicted major traffic snarls.
	   Blockade organizers, endorsed by the government of Austria's
Tyrol province, are venting their anger against what they call an
intolerable increase in heavy-truck traffic, and protesting
European Union traffic policy in general.
	   Intermittent blockades also took place south of Salzburg on the
Tauern freeway, another north-south artery.
	   The Brenner freeway was blocked for all traffic between 11 a.m.
Friday and 3 p.m. (1300 GMT) Saturday, but police closed it already
an hour earlier.
	   On the Tauern freeway, traffic was halted for 20 minutes at
every hour between 11 a.m. and 4. p.m. (1400 GMT) on Friday, two
hours less than planned because of lack of interest due to cold and
rainy weather.
	   Only about 1,000 protesters _ including Tyrol governor Wendelin
Weingartner _ attended a rally at Schoenberg on the Brenner pass.
The weather kept the crowd far below organizers' expectations.
	   Weingartner criticized attempts to abolish night-time road tolls
on the Brenner pass, considered excessive by the EU.
	   Only a shift from roads to railways can solve the transit
problem, he said.
	   ``Tyrol stands united against the (European Union's) traffic
policy, which disregards human beings,'' claimed Fritz Gurgiser,
the chairman of Transit Forum Tirol Austria, protest organizers.
	   He claimed a study drafted at the EU's behest shows transit
traffic across the Brenner pass will increase from the present 1.2
million to two million trucks per year.
	   The local automobile club reported that traffic chaos did not
materialize _ probably because the protest had been well publicized
in advance and many drivers took alternative routes to and from
Italy. The cold weather also probably kept many at home who
otherwise would have gone away for a holiday weekend.
	   In Tyrol province south of Innsbruck, traffic was being rerouted
from the Brenner freeway to a narrower highway that can no longer
handle present-day peak auto and truck traffic.
	   The blockade drew sharp criticism from Italy and Germany and
from Austrian and Bavarian road haulage associations.
	   But the demonstration was supported by all political parties in
the Tyrolean provincial diet, as well as by the most important
parties in Alto Adige, the German-speaking northern Italian
province.
	   (rp/as)
</TEXT>
