<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-Queens, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Umotivated Sampras goes out in Wimbledon warmup
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMS; RECASTS, trims; will be updated with final three
quarterfinals

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ What's troubling Pete Sampras just 10 days before
Wimbledon begins?
	   Mark Woodforde, who defeated the four-time Wimbledon champion in
straight sets Friday at the Queen's Club tournament, thinks he
knows the answer.
	   ``Everyone is aware that, motivation-wise, he's not there,''
said the Australian, a 6-3, 6-2 third-round winner on Sampras'
favorite surface.
	   ``I played a pretty good tight match against him, and he just
wasn't able to pick it up where in the past he was able to take it
up a notch or two,'' said Woodforde, known primarly as a doubles
specialist.
	   ``That's where he is found wanting.''
	   Friday's defeat was the latest surprising loss for defending
Wimbledon champion Sampras. He has struggled most of the year and
was ousted in the second round of the French Open by little-known
Ramon Delgado of Paraguay.
	   Sampras, who had beaten the 66th-ranked Woodforde in all of
their previous 10 matches, put off interviews until after a doubles
match later Friday.
	   Woodforde mixed up his shots, returning well and often catching
Sampras with lobs whenever the American ventured to the net. But
his most effective tactic was to hit a succession of drop volleys
which fell just over the net and left Sampras stranded.
	   The Australian also served far better than Sampras, hitting
three aces in the opening game to set the tone of the match.
	   In contrast, Sampras produced four double-faults, the last of
which gave Woodforde a break for 3-2 in the second set. A netted
backhand voley then gave Woodforde a second break for 5-2.
	   In addition to its top seed, Queen's also lost No. 2 Greg
Rusedski of Britain, who suffered an ankle injury Friday during his
third-round match against Italian qualifier Laurence Tieleman.
	   With the score at 2-2 in the first set, Rusedski slipped while
stretching for a backhand volley and fell awkwardly with his left
leg buckling beneath him.
	   Rusedski screamed in pain and writhed on the grass before being
carried off the court and taken to a hospital for X-rays.
	   Tournament doctor Johnnie Gaynor said it appeared to be just a
sprain. It wasn't immediately clear whether the injury would force
Rusedski to miss Wimbledon, where he reached the quarterfinals last
year.
	   In order to clear up a backlog of matches caused by rain delays,
players Friday faced the prospect of playing two matches _ third
round and quarterinals _ to get the tournament back on track.
	   Seventh-seeded Tim Henman of Britain became the highest ranked
played to reach the quarterfinals with a 6-1, 6-7 (7-5), 6-4
victory over 1997 champion and 10th-seeded Goran Ivanisevic.
	   In the first quarterfinal match, 14th-seeded Byron Black of
Zimbabwe defeated Brian MacPhie, United States, 7-5, 6-1.
	   (scw) 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Tennis-Queens, 4th Ld-Writethru; CT:s; 
