<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ethiopia-Eritrea, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ethiopians and Eritreans blame each other for clashes
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: for AMs. RECASTS and UPDATES with details from Badme, troop
reinforcements at Zala Ambessa, Kagame. &QL; 
 &UR; With AP Photos ADI101-104
 &UR; By DIANNA CAHN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ADIGRAT, Ethiopia (AP) _ The guns were quiet in the
Ethiopia-Eritrea conflict Friday, but the two countries'
governments continued their salvos of blame for the escalating
clashes threatening to spiral into war.
	   Residents fled the northern town of Adigrat after Eritrean
helicopters and planes bombed the town Thursday killing four
civilians and wounding 30.
	   U.S. and Rwandan diplomats were shuttling between the Ethiopian
capital Addis Ababa and the Eritrean capital Asmara to try to help
resolve the conflict.
	   In Adigrat, about 20 kilometers (12 miles) from the embattled
Ethiopian border town of Zala Ambessa, residents hastily buried two
victims of Thursday's bombing raid before dawn so they could leave
town. The other two were so disfigured they could not be
identified, according to Netsanet Asfaw, a local government
spokeswoman.
	   Wounded still filled beds lining the corridors of Adigrat's
hospital, where over 100 wounded soldiers are also being treated.
	   Dozens of residents fled to outlying villages Friday fearing
further shelling, and all businesses were closed in a sign of
mourning.
	   Neither side reported new clashes on Friday.
	   The Ethiopian army poured reinforcements into the front lines
south of Zala Ambessa Friday, ten days after Eritreans captured the
town. Col. Ephrem Bengee, a commander in the area said he expected
a fresh Eritrean offensive there after a lull of several days.
	   Soldiers packed into six trucks, numbering over 300, sang and
cheered as they passed through Adigrat heading north.
	   The Eritrean government said in a statement it bombed the
northeastern border town of Adigrat because the Ethiopians had
turned it into ``the main garrison for reinforcing the invading
Ethiopian army and a center for army logistics.''
	   But Ethiopian government spokeswoman Selome Tadesse, said in
Addis Ababa the attack was ``an act of desperation'' after Eritrean
forces were ``heavily defeated'' in ground fighting on two fronts
Thursday. Eritrea claimed Ethiopian forces were rdriven back.
	   Eritrean rebels fought Ethiopia for 30 years to gain
independence. They succeeded in 1993, two years after helping
Ethiopian rebels under Meles Zenawi _ who is now Ethiopia's prime
minister _ oust a 17-year military dictatorship. Relations between
the two countries deteriorated last year after Eritrea introduced
its own currency.
	   A planeload of 125 foreigners evacuated from Asmara Friday,
apparently fearing Ethiopian retaliation for Thursday's attack on
Adigrat: 78 of them were Filipinos, the rest Britons, South
Africans, Australians and Croatians.
	   A U.S. negotiating team declined comment upon their arrival in
Asmara Friday. Rwandan Vice President Paul Kagame followed and left
early in the evening, according to Eritrean presidential spokesman
Yemane Gebremeskel. He declined comment on Kagame's quick visit.
	   The two countries have authored a proposal for ending the
conflict which calls for a pullback of forces to pre-conflict
positions. Ethiopia accepted the plan, but Eritrea says it lacks
detail, specifically on how the disputed border would be
demarcated.
	   Regional military sources say the plan calls for Rwanda to
supply peacekeepers to enforce demilitarization of the disputed
border regions.
	   On the western Badme-Shiraro front, in the Yirga triangle where
the conflict first erupted, Ethiopian forces captured three tanks
and two anti-aircraft guns, Selome said. They also destroyed a tank
and a gun.
	   Selome said Thursday the Eritreans had suffered heavy losses at
a battle that began Wednesday at Erde Mattios in the Yirga region.
But Eritrean military sources at the site said Ethiopian troops
penetrated as deep as 16 kilometers (10 miles) into Eritrean
territory before being pushed back.
	   Ethiopians suffered heavy human and material losses, the sources
said. They had no comment on Eritrean casualties.
	   Eritrean government spokesman Negash Ashafa said 600 Ethiopian
soldiers were taken prisoner, while the Ethiopians said they had
captured a large number of Eritrean troops.
	   The Ethiopian military said Friday it also wiped out an entire
Eritrean brigade Thursday in fighting at Bure, along the eastern
border in the region of the Eritrean Red Sea port of Assab.
	   ``A whole commando brigade of the Eritrean People's Liberation
Front has been destroyed,'' Bangee said. But Eritrea said the
Ethiopian forces were repelled.
	   Meanwhile, Eritreans working in ``strategic and sensitive''
Ethiopian state enterprises such as telecommunications and power
companies have been ordered to take a one-month leave but could
stay in the country, Selome said Friday.
	   Several Eritrean business leaders who have allegedly raised
money for the war effort will be expelled soon, she said.
	   Eritrea accuses Ethiopia of provoking the attack by bombing the
military-civilian airport at the Eritrean capital of Asmara on June
5 and 6. A week after those attacks, the Eritrean Foreign Ministry
said for the first time that four civilians had been killed and 26
wounded in those bombings.
	   (pvs/str/jh)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Ethiopia-Eritrea, 3rd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
