<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-US-Jones,0424 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Jones: I'm not just MTV
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos XLF101-107 &QL; 
 &UR; By RONALD BLUM &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAINT-JEAN D'ARDIERES, France (AP) _ He is the poster boy for
U.S. soccer, a rock 'n' roll guy with flying dreadlocks and his own
show on MTV.
	   That's how you become known for playing soccer in America. Now
Cobi Jones is trying to show the world he can play at the top
level, too.
	   ``I'm a lot more experienced, a lot more well-versed in the
game, a lot more confident,'' he said Friday. ``I respect the
big-time players, but I'm not overawed by these players.''
	   Four years ago, he started one game in the World Cup and came
into three as a sub, making little impact. This time, it appears
he'll be starting as an outside midfielder when the United States
opens against Germany on Monday.
	   ``A young 24-year-old out on the field against Romario and
Bebeto is kind of overawed,'' he said, looking back at the
second-round loss to Brazil that eliminated the U.S. team from the
last World Cup. ``I think we have that confidence now. I think this
team is very confident we can go out and play.''
	   Confidence is a key word for American players these days. In
Jones' case, U.S. coach Steve Sampson was more concerned about
fitness.
	   ``In the last year,'' Sampson said, ``he's really tried to
concentrate on the finer elements of his game, working on his ball
control, his technique and his finishing, his diet, spending
additional time in the weight room, making sure he is extremely
fit, not just fit for his club side but for the international
game.''
	   Jones, who has eight goals in eight games for the MLS's Los
Angeles Galaxy, was clearly annoyed be the fitness remark.
	   ``I've always been the same way,'' he said. ``I fluctuate
between 145 and 150. I never go over it. I sometimes get under it
when I get caught up in nonstop training.''
	   His image is part of the problem. He looks oh so cool, with the
dreadlocks and shades.
	   Jones has hosted ``MTV Mega-Dose,'' a show on health and
fitness. The next taping is scheduled for September.
	   Jones, who turns 28 a day after the Germany game, has been
wearing his hair in dreadlocks for about eight years, since his
second year at UCLA. He said he did it because it's ``no
maintenance.''
	   ``I've thought about cutting them every once in a while,'' he
said. ``I did cut them shorter. That's so they won't be in my
eyes.''
	   That's one short cut to stardom he's willing to take.
</TEXT>
