<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EU-Mad Cow,0277 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU veterinary experts split on beef ban end; delay vote
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ European Union veterinary experts were
divided Friday over a proposal to lift a global ban on British beef
exports, delaying a vote until next week.
	   Sources said Britain, Ireland and Sweden favored ending the ban,
imposed in March, 1996 because of ``mad cow'' disease. Germany and
others, however, questioned the wisdom of such a move.
	   If there is no majority among the veterinary experts from the 15
EU nations, the proposal to lift the export ban goes to the EU
agriculture ministers.
	   The veterinary experts said they need more time to consider the
European Commission's recommendation to resume exports of British
beef from cattle born after August 1 1996.
	   The ban was imposed in March 1996 after Britain acknowledged a
link between cattle with bovine spongiform encephalopathy, or BSE,
and the fatal human brain ailment Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease.
	   Even if the political go-ahead for a resumption of British beef
sales is given soon, it will take months before British beef is
exported again. The resumption of trade would have to wait until
final EU checks have been carried out on anti-BSE health and safety
measures in Britain.
	   Under the proposal, beef must be deboned, come from animals aged
between six and 30 months that have been killed in approved
slaughterhouses and come from herds guaranteed to be BSE-free.
	   Germany, in particular, is wary about resuming British beef
sales, fearing a consumer backlash. Chancellor Helmut may not be in
the mood for concessions in the runup to September elections.
</TEXT>
