<BODY>
<SLUG> WHERE-MANY-ARE-CALLED sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Where many are called but few are chosen, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Where many are called but few are chosen, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Harun HashimASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MANY are called but few are chosen. This adage is used in
several situations.
	   Its most popular usage is in relation to job interviews where a
large number of people are interviewed in response to newspaper
advertisements of job opportunities but only a few will be
successful.
	   In the legal profession the adage has a different conotation.
	   When a lawyer first enters the profession he is said to have
been called to the Bar. It is the ambition of every young lawyer to
one day become a judge.
	   However, very few are elevated to that position. There are about
70 superior court judges in the country and more than 7,000
practising lawyers which makes the chances of becoming a judge
about one for every 100 lawyers.
	   The number of young people entering the legal profession each
year has increased from a hundred 30 years ago to over 1,000 now.
	   This increase is attributable to the increase in the number of
law schools at local universities, the large number of students
studying law overseas and the twinning programmes for law degrees
between local private colleges and universities in the United
Kingdom.
	   With the current economic slowdown, young lawyers are finding it
difficult to join law firms.
	   Indeed, several law firms have recently retrenched lawyers.
	   Worse still, quite a number of law firms have closed down
because of the economic slowdown.
	   The question arises whether we are producing too many lawyers,
the economic slowdown notwithstanding.
	   Generally, every law graduate wants to be a lawyer because that
is the reason why he or she chose a law course in the first place.
	   Added to this, the law course itself creates a lasting
impression of justice surrounded in an aura of wise judges and
eminent counsel thus instilling in the minds of young lawyers that
the pursuit of justice is a lifetime occupation.
	   A legal education is a very useful discipline. Basically it
trains a person to identify problems and find solutions.
	   Thus a law degree is also a useful qualification in the civil
service, foreign service, police, banking, finance, insurance,
management positions in the corporate world and politics. Not all
law graduates need to become lawyers.
	   There are 93 law schools in Japan producing 38,000 law graduates
each year.
	   To enter the legal profession a law graduate has to sit for and
pass a public examination to gain entry to the Institute of
Judicial and Legal Training.
	   Only the top 600 successful candidates will be accepted each
year to join the institute and undergo two years of professional
training with examinations.
	   Of these, the top 50 will join the judiciary, the next 50 the
government legal service and the remaining 500 will qualify to
become lawyers in private practice.
	   Japan has a population of more than 121 million. We have just
exceeded 20 million! Perhaps the time has come for the Legal
Profession Qualifying Board of which the Attorney-General is the
chairman to seriously consider establishing a regime to limit the
number of lawyers entering the profession each year.
	   An oversupply of lawyers will lead to unethical practices.
	   What the country needs is well-trained lawyers with high ethical
standards.
	   With this is in view, the Qualifying Board recently issued
guidelines in the recognition of United Kingdom, Australian and New
Zealand law degrees for purposes of admission to the Certificate in
Legal Practice examinations.
	   But such recognition can only be transitionary.
	   In most countries the basic qualification to practice law is a
first degree in law from a local university.
	   This requirement makes sense because the lawyer must be fully
trained in local law in order to practice law in his own country.
	   Foreign law degrees are based on the domestic law of the country
the university is located.
	   The UK law degree, for example, is a mixture of the English
common law, British Acts of Parliament and the civil law of Europe,
all largely irrelevant to present day Malaysia.
	   Islamic law applicable in Malaysia is ignored by all foreign
universities.
	   The high failure rate of UK law graduates in the CLP
examinations is partly due to the lack of knowledge and
understanding of Malaysian laws.
	   The recognition of foreign first law degrees is a legacy of the
past when we did not have our own law schools.
	   We cannot stop people from acquiring law degrees overseas but if
they want to practice law in Malaysia they should posses a first
degree in law from a Malaysian university.
	   At present Malaysian universities produce about 500 law
graduates a year.
	   If there is justification for more law graduates, then local
private colleges should have twinning programmes with Malaysian
universities.
	   The Legal Profession Act should therefore be amended to the
effect that only persons with a Malaysian first degree in law will
be admitted to the Bar in Malaysia after the year 2000. Even so,
the adage that many are called but few are chosen will continue to
apply.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
