<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0602 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Albanian militants kill Serb policemen near Kosovo capital
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Contact Group members weighing JAT flight ban;
Kosovo Albanians welcoming NATO moves, Serbs alternately gloomy and
critical. &QL; 
 &UR; By ISMET HAJDARI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Ethnic Albanian militants, boldly
stepping up their attacks against Serb authorities, have killed two
Serb police officers just a few miles (kilometers) from Kosovo's
capital.
	   Fighting between Serbian forces and the KLA erupted again Friday
in the Decani region in western Kosovo, close to the border with
Albania. It was a Serbian offensive there last week that prompted
NATO to announce Thursday a show of air power to persuade Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic to halt such assault.
	   Ethnic Albanians outnumber Serbs nine-to-one in Kosovo. Most
seek independence from Serbia, the Yugoslavian republic which
stripped the province of broad autonomy in 1989 and has ruled
repressively since. More than 250 people have been killed since
Serbian police started a crackdown against Albanian militants in
March.
	   Ethnic Albanian sources claimed that six villages in the Decani
area were attacked Friday, some with grenade launchers normally
issued to the Yugoslav army.
	   There was no independent confirmation of their report. The
state-run Tanjug news agency in Belgrade reported that a Serb
police officer was seriously hurt in what it called an attack by
``armed Albanian terrorists'' near one of the villages, Prilep.
	   Serb sources in the province said two policemen where killed and
one was seriously wounded in an overnight ambush by separatists
near Obilic, just seven kilometers (four miles) northwest of the
provincial capital Pristina. Ethnic Albanian sources claimed one
Albanian was wounded in the same incident.
	   Albanian sources further reported Serb attacks on villages in
the Obilic and adjacent Vucitrn regions, saying residents fled and
spent the night under open skies.
	   The ethnic Albanian daily Bujku reported Friday five ethnic
Albanians and seven Serbs were killed in clashes Thursday in Suvo
Grlo in the Drenica area 30 kilometers (20 miles) west of Pristina.
	   On Friday, Western foreign ministers met in London with their
Russian counterpart to step up pressure. Britain, which is weighing
a United Nations' move to back use of NATO force in Kosovo, called
on Milosevic to pull back his troops immediately.
	   The United States, Canada, Britain, France, Italy and Germany
also said they would ``take steps to ban'' flights by Yugoslav
Airlines to underline their concern at the Kosovo violence, British
Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said.
	   Kosovo Albanians welcomed the international moves. It's ``high
time'' that someone strikes against Milosevic, said Eroll Haxhiu,
46, a jewelry salesman in Pristina. ``America can and should do
it.''
	   Members of Kosovo's Serb minority _ whom Milosevic promised to
protect when taking power in Serbia in 1987 _ were alternately
gloomy and defiant.
	   Serbian pensioner Vasilje Stefanovic said Yugoslavian leaders
were responsible for the current problems.
	   ``We are to blame for everything that is happening. We deserve
it,'' he said.
	   Ethnic Albanian media in Kosovo on Friday carried a statement
from the KLA _ the main militant group _ demanding that it be given
a new war tax to be levied on Kosovo Albanians working abroad to
fund the fight against the Serbs.
	   The KLA, a shadowy group which first emerged in 1996 said it now
had about 15,000 fighters in the province. 	   
</TEXT>
