<SLUG> BC-Albania-Macedonia-NATO-Kosovo </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Albania will offer space for NATO drills, Macedonia not yet
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By MERITA DHIMGJOKA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TIRANA, Albania (AP) _ Albania said Friday it will offer NATO
airspace and airports for maneuvers in the country aimed at
deterring further violence in Serbia's adjoining secessionist
province of Kosovo.
	   But neighboring Macedonia, whose prime minister visits Albania
this weekend, said it had not yet received an official request from
NATO for exercises and would not allow its territory to be used for
military activity against any neighboring country.
	   Macedonia's Foreign Minister Blagoj Handziski made the comments
when asked by reporters about NATO plans _ announced Thursday _ for
simulated air raids in Albania and Macedonia to deter further
violence in Kosovo.
	   Yugoslavia _ consisting of Serbia and Montenegro _ adjoins
Macedonia.
	   Albania's Prime Minister Fatos Nano, who has lobbied for weeks
for NATO intervention to stop Kosovo violence spiraling out of
control and engulfing the region, announced after a Cabinet meeting
that Albania would offer NATO air space and airfields.
	   ``We are convinced that the crisis in Kosovo is not only a
problem for Albania,'' Nano said. Macedonia ``is also interested in
regional stability ... and I hope that they will not try to keep
their country artificially out of the crisis when the crisis is at
its door.''
	   Macedonia's dominant Slavs have strong ties to the Serbs, but it
also has a sizeable ethnic Albanian majority in its western
territory adjoining Kosovo and Albania proper.
	   (md/kt/as)
</TEXT>
