<HEADLINE>
Ticket troubles escalate at World Cup
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Colombian denial &QL; 
 &UR; By LARRY SIDDONS &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ A growing international scandal over World Cup
tickets erupted on two new fronts Friday, with the tournament
organizers saying they were investigating two soccer federations
and a branch of their own marketing arm for possible roles in the
scams.
	   Michel Zen-Ruffinen, FIFA's acting general secretary, said
investigations were under way into the improper sale of tickets by
soccer officials in Cameroon and an unnamed South American country.
French news reports said it was Colombia, but Alvaro Fina, head of
the Colombian federation, said FIFA had assured him his country was
not involved.
