</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> MORE-WAYS-TO-RECOVER sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
More ways to recover loans, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
More ways to recover loans, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   BEGINNING last year the Public Services Department has been
collecting an average of RM1 million a month from those who had
taken study loans, revealed its deputy director-general II, Datuk
Khalil Hussain on Tuesday.
	   This is a tenfold increase over the department's average monthly
recovery figure of RM100,000 before 1997. An improvement, it cannot
be denied. But it is still insignificant, far, far insignificant
given the fact that the PSD has been giving out huge sums of money,
running into hundreds of million ringgit annually in loans to
students pursuing higher education since 1986. As Khalil, who heads
an internal PSD committee on loan recovery, said, each year the
department gives out more than RM500 million in loans and
scholarships.
	   Once only providing scholarships, the PSD began disbursing study
loans, repayable over a 25-year period after the students'
graduation, in the mid-1980s, during the last recession. But the
amount recovered monthly had been paltry. Contributing factors were
the hefty discounts given to high achievers and long loan repayment
tenure. The primary obstacle was, and still is, most students could
not be traced after they graduated. Since the department stepped up
its efforts like roping in the help of the Malaysian Student
Departments overseas and universities and chasing guarantors, it
had been able to track more of its student debtors, as reflected in
the increased monthly recollections. Still the PSD has to redouble
its efforts. For one, how long will, or rather can, the Government
continue to make annual provisions to fund student loans? For
another, the annual collections, if effectively, efficiently and
diligently carried out, would replenish a substantial portion of
the total annual loans, relieving partially the Government's
financial burden of annual allocations.
	   Perhaps the PSD should study and implement one strategy of
Mara's student loan recovery plan. That agency had a long history
of carrying in its books unrecovered loans similar to the more
recent experience of PSD.
	   But for the last few years, it has published names of borrowers
in the daily newspapers. Although it has yet to reveal the details
of the response to the publication of the names of defaulters,
reports indicate the recovery rate has increased substantially.
Embarrassment, it appears, can impose sufficient pressure on the
recalcitrant borrowers to own up and repay their debts. The PSD
could take the same road.
	   Khalil is on record as having said that the department, after
five reminders, would refer defaulters to the Attorney-General's
Chambers. The question is: how many of these people have been
charged in court? If tracing the defaulters is the problem, why not
go after the guarantors?
	   The department could give an incentive for the borrowers to come
forward.
	   It could offer discounts, as much as, say, 50 per cent, to those
who express intent to repay. The objective of the entire loan
recollection exercise should be to extract as much repayment as
possible from these graduates. Their higher education and
subsequent degrees were made possible by the taxpayer's money. They
should not be allowed to go scot- free, if only because present and
future loan seekers might be equally disinclined to discharge their
obligation when their turn comes. Clearly then, the PSD has the
moral and legal duty to devise a more effective way to recover such
loans, however difficult the task might be.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
