<HEADLINE>
Ollerenshaw the first to go as FA clean house, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Ollerenshaw the first to go as FA clean house, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Vijesh RaiASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   NEGRI Sembilan are cleaning house and the first to go is
Australian Scott Ollerenshaw.
	   It is learnt the Negri FA management committee have instructed
coach M.
	   Karathu to stop fielding Ollerenshaw who has earned their
dissatisfaction for only scoring once in the 13 League and two FA
Cup matches Negri have played so far.
	   Ollerenshaw did not make the trip to Malacca for Tuesday's FA
Cup second round return leg match and given the current scenario,
is unlikely to play for Negri again.
	   Although Negri cannot sign a replacement if they terminate
Ollerenshaw's contract, this is a risk they are willing to take.
	   The general feeling is that even without Ollerenshaw, Negri
can't do any worse and NSFA feel it would be better to rely on
local players for the remaining seven matches in Premier One.
	   But Ollerenshaw is not the only player who has faced action as
it is learnt that three local players - Faizal Zainal, Khairil
Zainal and Othman Katmon have been ordered to take a ``rest''.
	   According to a Bernama report, Negri FA Secretary Abdullah Sani
Abdul Hamid said the decision was taken during the management
committee meeting last Monday. ``Our only hope now is to at least
qualify for the Malaysia Cup competition,'' he said.
	   Karathu declined to comment about the status of the three local
players but confirmed the management have asked him not to use
Ollerenshaw.
	   ``I will abide by their decision and use local players for our
remaining matches.
	   ``Now that we have been eliminated from the FA Cup, we have to
concentrate on making the Malaysia Cup,'' said Karathu.
	   To do so, Negri have to finish in the top six of Premier One but
given the points separating the teams, the race for Malaysia Cup
berths could well go to the wire.
	   
</TEXT>
