<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Apartheid Plot, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0684 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S., Britain asked apartheid government to keep chemical weapons
</HEADLINE>
from blacks &QL; 
 &UR; EDS: RECASTS with info that U.S. and Britain asked apartheid
government to withhold technology; New overline &QL; 
 &UR; By PAUL HARRIS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) _ The United States and Britain
asked the apartheid government to withhold its biological warfare
technology from the majority black government that was expected to
succeed it, a former government official said Friday.
	   Former Surgeon-General Niel Knobel confirmed under questioning
that the two countries made a joint diplomatic overture to the
apartheid government shortly before the first all-race vote in 1994
that elected President Nelson Mandela's African National Congress,
said an official of the Truth and Reconciliation Commission, which
is investigating apartheid-era human rights abuses.
	   Knobel said the Americans and British did not want the
technology to go to the ANC government and asked the apartheid
government to destroy its stockpiles, media reports on Friday said.
	   Knobel said that apartheid's last president. F.W. DeKlerk, met
with Mandela who agreed to kill the program.
	   It was not clear how much the U.S. and Britain knew about the
program that was publicly described for the first time in detail
this week before the commission.
	   Mind-boggling projects aimed at preserving white rule were
hatched and nurtured in secret laboratories, according to the
apartheid-era army scientists who testified.
	   They described plans to make poisoned chocolates, to find a
germ-warfare agent that would kill only blacks and to give Mandela
brain damage.
	   Poisons were made and passed on to apartheid assassins, referred
to in secret documents only by their code names ``Chris'' and
``Koos.''
	   One scientist, Schalk van Rensburg, testified that a shirt laced
with poison had been given to an ANC activist. The target, who was
not identified, unknowingly gave the deadly garment to a friend who
then died.
	   Retired Archbishop Desmond Tutu said this week's testimony was
the most shocking he has heard as chairman of the Truth Commission,
set up in 1995 to heal racial divisions.
	   ``Here are people of high intelligence, coldly and clinically in
white laboratory coats, working on things they know were meant to
be instruments of destroying people,'' Tutu told The Associated
Press on Thursday.
	   The scientists explained that they were virtually brainwashed by
government propaganda in the 1980s that South Africa was on the
brink of falling to communism and black rule.
	   ``That was the psychosis that prevailed,'' Daan Goosen, who
headed a covert biological research laboratory, recalled Thursday.
	   ``I was not thinking rationally at the time,'' he said. ``Today,
I know I was wrong. You can't do that to people, it is just not
justifiable.''
	   Scientists who had any doubts about their work could have been
killed for breaking ranks, van Rensburg claimed.
	   ``We had been told in no uncertain terms, if you let the side
down you are dead,'' van Rensburg said.
	   Goosen said the biological and chemical weapons program was
controlled by Dr. Wouter Basson, who will be forced to testify,
according to a ruling on Friday by the Truth Commission.
	   Dressed in a pinstriped white shirt, Basson sat grim-faced while
the panel rejected his lawyer's appeal to postpone his appearance
because it could prejudice a possible criminal case against him.
	   Basson allegedly produced and sold ecstasy and other drugs,
officials have said.
	   The Truth Commission, established to help promote
reconciliation, can grant amnesty to those who fully confess to
politically motivated apartheid-era human rights abuses.
	   The hearings were adjourned until next Thursday, when Knobel is
expected to finish testimony he began Friday. Knobel said he
thought Basson's program was developing conventional biological and
chemical weapons, and he claimed to know nothing about the poison
projects.
	   Basson is likely to be called next week. 	   
</TEXT>
