w1449 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Britain-PrisonerClear     06-12 0421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Prisoner Cleared </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Man cleared of murder after 23 years in prison
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With AP Photo LON118, LON120 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ A 69-year-old man who spent 23 years in prison for
a murder he always denied committing was cleared Friday when the
Court of Appeals ruled that the victim might have died a natural
death.
	   The judges expressed regret that Patrick Nicholls, who served
the longest prison term ever in a British case of miscarried
justice, had spent ``such a very long time in jail.''
	   Nicholls was imprisoned in 1975 for the murder of Gladys Heath,
a 74-year-old family friend found dead at her home in Worthing,
southern England.
	   Nicholls, who insisted he found Mrs. Heath at the foot of her
stairs, has been free on bail since March, when new evidence
indicated she could have died naturally.
	   He broke down in tears at the Law Courts as Lord Justice Roch
read out the ruling of the three appeals judges.
	   ``We allow this appeal because the pathological evidence that
this was an unlawful killing and that natural causes could be
excluded has now been shown to be unreliable,'' Roch said.
	   ``In allowing this appeal, we would wish to express this court's
great regret that as a result of what has now been shown to be
flawed pathological evidence the appellant was wrongly convicted
and has spent such a very long time in jail.''
	   Roch made the announcement after hearing from the prosecution's
lawyer, Bruce Houlder, who said, ``Nobody now could be sure that
Mr. Nicholls was responsible for the murder.''
	   At the time of the trial, two pathologists concluded Mrs. Heath
died of a heart attack after being suffocated and severely beaten
in the face.
	   But a new review of the case found that the facial injuries were
trivial and probably caused by the fall, which likely was prompted
by the heart attack.
	   Nicholls, seated in a wheelchair when he spoke to reporters
later, broke down again as he said: ``I would like to thank my
mother, Ida, for the help she gave me in these past 23 years. She
died a year ago.''
	   Nicholls' common-law wife also died while he was in prison.
	   ``I always thought I would get out sometime,'' he said.
``Always. Somehow or other, I still retained a little faith in the
system. I have lost it many, many times, of course. But lurking at
the back of my mind was always the belief I would get out some
time.''
	   ``It has been a long time. I think I will have a few pints and
think things over,'' he said.
	   (acw-kg)
</TEXT>
