<SLUG> BC-Swiss Banks-Nazis </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Swiss Jewish newspapers denounce U.S.-based report for absurdity
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   GENEVA (AP) _ A Swiss Jewish newspaper Friday labeled as absurd
a report asserting wartime Switzerland was ``saturated'' with
pro-Nazi groups.
	   Author Alan Morris Schom ``deliberately suppressed the strong
anti-Nazi movement in Switzerland,'' said the Israelitisches
Wochenblatt.
	   The paper joined the country's other Jewish weekly in attacking
the report issued Wednesday in New York by the Simon Wiesenthal
Center. The Basel-based Juedische Rundschau on Thursday described
the study as full of ``exaggerations and falsifications.''
	   The Israelitisches Wochenblatt, published in Zurich, said the
report made it easy for nationalist Swiss to reject efforts to make
good on any wrongs committed during World War II.
	   It is true that the Nazis had a well-organized network of
largely secret organizations in neutral Switzerland preparing to
include the country in the Third Reich, said the newspaper. But the
movement had to be put in proportion.
	   ``The Swiss Nazis were weak in numbers,'' said the weekly. ``In
the parliament in Bern they had exactly one seat for four years.''
	   ``If Swiss society were really so saturated with Nazis, that
would have had to be reflected in parliamentary elections,'' it
added.
	   The distortions undermined legitimate efforts to root out
anti-Semitism in Switzerland, the newspaper said.
	   For example, it said, it would be worthwhile examining more
closely Schom's repetition of the long-standing allegation that the
Swiss government during World War II had an anti-Jewish policy.
	   ``Because of the absurdity of the other allegations, however,
this will certainly not happen,'' the weekly said.
	   The Juedische Rundschau said Schom's report starts with errors
in the first paragraph, which incorrectly states that the Swiss
cantons (states) in World War II numbered 21, when there were
actually 22.
	   ``So many details are presented painfully wrong,'' said the
Juedische Rundschau, which earlier this year led Swiss Jewish
criticism of a report by Schom asserting Switzerland put Jewish
refugees in slave labor camps.
	   A number of Jews who lived in refugee camps said that for the
most part they suffered no more than the Swiss themselves and that
the country was a safe haven for many on a hostile continent.
	   On Wednesday, the U.S. State Department disputed the charges in
Schom's report, noting that Switzerland provided shelter for 50,000
Jewish refugees.
 &UR; (agh-gm)
</TEXT>
