<HEADLINE>
Board to study Negri's problems, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Board to study Negri's problems, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Kamarulzaman SallehASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Negri Sembilan FA established an independent three-man board
of inquiry to investigate problems affecting their team's poor run
in the Premier One League.
	   FA secretary Abdullah Sani Abdul Hamid said the board, headed by
FA vice-president Ahmad Ali, who is Negri Sembilan State
Development Corporation deputy general manager, will interview all
players and team officials for inputs.
	   Two other members of the board are Port Dickson District Officer
Hassan Nawawi Abdul Rahman and lawyer Tan Foong Luen.
	   ``The inquiry will start immediately and we expect them to
submit their report to the FA management committee by next week to
enable us to initiate measures to check the slide,'' he said in
Seremban yesterday.
	   Abdullah Sani said he did not discount the possibility of the FA
revamping the whole team if the board felt it would be good for the
team.
	   The Deers are currently lying in sixth position in the league
with 18 points after 13 matches. To make matters worse, they were
shown the exit in the FA Cup by second division outfit Malacca on
5-2 aggregate on Tuesday.
	   The problem started when banners criticising Perak coach M.
Karathu first surfaced during the team's away match in Kuantan
which Perak lost 1- 2 and the banner appeared again during their
home match against Pahang last week.
	   It was also reported last week that some players had petitioned
for Karathu's removal prompting the FA to issue a stern warning to
the players and officials to refrain from indulging in such ploys.
	   ``We would rather have a bunch of young and dedicated players
who are committed towards ensuring the team's success instead of
fielding primadonas who are out to destroy the team,'' he said.
	   He said although the team had ``grounded'' several first team
players who lacked commitment, the FA was not afraid to sack
others, including its imports, who did not live up to expectation.
	   
