<SLUG> BC-Foreign Ministers, 6th Ld,0687 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Major powers deny loans to India, Pakistan
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: SUBS penultimate graf to CLARIFY Russia did not go along with
airline ban. &QL; 
 &UR; With BC-Kosovo-Allies
 &UR; By BARRY SCHWEID &QC; 
 &UR; AP Diplomatic Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ The world's leading industrial nations, acting on
a U.S. proposal, decided Friday to deny nonhumanitarian loans to
India and Pakistan in retaliation for their nuclear tests.
	   The action came at a meeting of U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright and seven foreign ministers on the nuclear
crisis in South Asia and ethnic turmoil in Kosovo.
	   A communique approved by the eight countries _ the United
States, Britain, France, Germany, Japan, Canada, Italy and Russia _
also urged India and Pakistan to halt their testing programs and
not to deploy nuclear weapons on their missiles.
	   Additionally, they were urged to deal with the ``root causes''
of tensions between them, especially over Kashmir, the mostly
Muslim enclave that straddles their border.
	   Albright also urged the other nations to refrain from nuclear
cooperation with India and Pakistan. The senior U.S. officials,
speaking on condition of anonymity, said the two countries would be
denied such help.
	   The joint steps were taken as India and Pakistan faltered in
moves to hold negotiations later in the month. Senior British and
American officials said the effort had collapsed in disagreements
over how to proceed.
	   ``The recent nuclear tests have created an atmosphere of
regional instability which will undermine the region's
attractiveness to both foreign and domestic investment, damaging
business confidence and the prospect for economic growth,'' the
communique said.
	   The United States has imposed economic sanctions, under U.S.
law, against both countries. The eight foreign ministers, as a
group, said all countries ``should act as they see fit to
demonstrate their displeasure and address their concerns to India
and Pakistan.''
	   ``Our meeting sends the message that the world community is
united not just in outrage and dismay but in action,'' Albright
said, referring to nuclear weapons tests conducted last month by
the two countries.
	   The eight nations, four of whom are nuclear powers, pledged
themselves to ``systematic and progressive efforts to reduce
nuclear weapons globally with the ultimate goal of eliminating
those weapons.'' A Japanese foreign ministry official said the
pledge was the result of pressure by his government.
	   ``We all, nuclear weapons states and non-nuclear weapon states
alike,'' the communique said, ``reiterate our determination to
fulfill the commitments relating to nuclear disarmament.''
	   By choosing to test, India and Pakistan have diminished their
security and damaged their prestige, Albright said at a meeting
with the foreign ministers.
	   Calling for unity, Albright said relations with India and
Pakistan ``must not drift back into business as usual.'' One way
she proposed was coordinating votes at world financial institutions
to postpone consideration of loans except for those ``that meet
basic human needs.''
	   Last week, the World Bank postponed two loans worth more than
dlrs 206 million to India, bringing to more than dlrs 1 billion the
amount delayed because of the South Asian nation's nuclear tests
last month.
	   The South Asian nuclear crisis competed with the ethnic
bloodshed in the Balkans for the attention of the foreign
ministers.
	   They called on Yugoslavia to let up its military pressure on
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo and ``make rapid progress'' in talks
with their leaders.
	   The United States, Britain, Canada, France, Germany and Italy
said they would move to ban flights of commercial Yugoslav airlines
to and from their countries and Yugoslavia. Japan said it would
consider going along but Russia said it did not agree to such a
move. European Union approval would be required for implementation
of such a move by its members, British officials said.
