<SLUG> BC-Switzerland-Dalai Lama,0233 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dalai Lama joins celebrations at Swiss Tibetan monastery
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   RIKON, Switzerland (AP) _ The Dalai Lama joined in a Swiss
monastery's anniversary celebrations Friday, consecrating 10 new
prayer wheels.
	   The Tibet Institute in Rikon, near Zurich, which is celebrating
its 30th anniversary this year, becomes the first monastery in the
West to be blessed by the current Dalai Lama.
	   Speaking to reporters later, the exiled Tibetan spiritual leader
said he is convinced that U.S. President Bill Clinton ``will raise
the Tibetan issue'' during his visit to China later this month.
	   His return to Tibet would be ``possible in a few years, maybe
more,'' he added. ``The day of political changing will come.''
	   The Dalai Lama pointed to ``very positive changes'' in China,
especially in freedom of expression. Newspapers had hinted at a
readiness to ``open the door'' to him, he said.
	   Since fleeing Tibet to lead his nation from exile, the Dalai
Lama has been the sole voice and face of his people. His policy of
compromise and negotiation won him world support and the 1989 Nobel
Peace prize.
	   The Rikon monastery has an abbot and seven monks, all of them
Tibetan. Consecrated in November 1968, it was named the Tibet
Institute to get around a Swiss law forbidding the founding of
monasteries.
	   Some 2,500 Tibetans live in Switzerland. 	   
</TEXT>
