<HEADLINE>
Acid '98 discusses challenges of electronic commerce, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Acid '98 discusses challenges of electronic commerce, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Wendy LeeASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ELECTRONIC commerce (e-commerce) is increasingly being
recognised as the medium that will revolutionise global trade and
its facilitation system.
	   The power of e-commerce enables a global electronic marketplace
that will increase efficiency, reduce the need for capital and
reduce costs for all sectors including governments, businesses and
consumers, said United Parcel Service (UPS)'s Asia-Pacific regional
director for global facilitation and Customs operations James Goh.
	   ``Creating an environment that allows e-commerce to flourish
will make it a major force for economic growth among Asia-Pacific
Economic Cooperation (Apec) economies in the 21st century,'' Goh
told a Press briefing in Kuala Lumpur last Friday. E-commerce
applications in global trade, security and barrier issues were some
of the main issues discussed at the Apec Customs- Industry Dialogue
(Acid '98).
	   Acid '98, which carried the theme Meeting the Challenges of the
Next Millennium, was held in Kuala Lumpur. The two-day event ended
on Tuesday.
	   It served to present a common position of the Customs industry
to important international organisations that play a significant
role in global trade. Proposals and recommendations that are in
line with the goals and ideals of Apec were also aligned to bodies
such as the World Customs Organisation, the World Trade
Organisation, the United Nations Conference for Trade and
Development, International Chambers of Commerce and the Asean Free
Trade Area (AFTA) for consideration.
	   Acid is an annual meeting of customs and global trade experts
held under the auspices of the Apec Sub-committee on Customs
Procedures (Apec-SSCP).
	   During the briefing, a cheque worth US$60,000 (RM234,000) from
UPS was presented to the National Chamber of Commerce and Industry
of Malaysia (NCCIM) in conjunction with Acid '98.
	   
</TEXT>
