<SLUG> FIGHT-VIRUSES-WITH sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fight viruses with echinacea, thuja, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Fight viruses with echinacea, thuja, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Q: I AM 20 years old and have these tiny warts that look like
pimples growing under my armpits all the time. It has a somewhat
medium-hard pinkish surface with milky yellowish contents and is
growing in clusters.
	   This causes my armpit to be dark brown in colour and it looks
filthy. I am worried because these warts can hurt. I have burst
them regularly but this only causes even more to grow and leaves
scars.
	   I also have yellowish discharge on my panties everyday which
changes to light-green. Sometimes it becomes even darker. I have
oral sex with my boyfriend. I have read that these symptoms might
lead to sexually- transmitted diseases. Is this true?
	   A: IT sounds as if you are suffering from an infection caused by
a virus known as Molluscum contagiosum. This virus spreads through
direct contact and can even spread through clothes. You must be
very careful to not pass it on to those you come into close contact
with.
	   The medical treatment is to freeze-dry the little eruptions and
thereby kill the virus. This process is known as cryotherapy.
Sometimes, the tops are surgically removed.
	   You can boost your immune system's ability to fight viruses with
echinacea. Anti-viral herbs such as thuja can be consumed or
painted directly onto the eruption. Thuja can be combined with
calendula extract and tea tree oil for an antiseptic and healing
wash.
	   You may be suffering from a sexually-transmitted disease. Both
you and your boyfriend must see a doctor for a proper diagnosis.
Echinacea and other immune-enhancing herbs may be of benefit, but
if the discharge is due to gonorrhoea (a type of STD) you both need
a course of antibiotic treatment.
	   Your discharge may however be due to an infection in your
vagina, in which case herbal medicine may be of benefit. You need
to discuss this with a health professional.
	   
</TEXT>
