<SLUG> BREEDING-AEDES-10 sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Breeding aedes: 10 schools compounded, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Breeding aedes: 10 schools compounded, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Carolyn HongASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Wed. - Ten schools were among the 5,133 premises
issued with compounds for breeding the aedes mosquito in the first
five months of this year, Housing and Local Government Minister
Datuk Dr Ting Chew Peh said today.
	   He said most of the compounds were issued to construction sites,
households, factories, commercial premises and squatters. The
Government collected RM369,000 in fines. A total of 826,695
premises were inspected.
	   ``We also took firm action by issuing 44 stop-work orders to
construction sites, mainly in Selangor and Federal Territory,'' he
told reporters before his Ministry's post-Cabinet meeting.
	   He said there were 6,344 dengue cases from January to May,
compared to 6,523 in the corresponding period last year, a drop of
2.7 per cent. Five people died compared to 18 last year.
	   States which showed a significant drop in cases were Selangor
(62 per cent drop from 1,911 last year to 717 this year), Penang
(58.8 per cent down from 373 to 156), Perak (40 per cent decline
from 482 to 269) and Federal Territory (6.1 per cent fall from
2,294 to 2,153).
	   States which showed a marked increase were Sarawak (393 per cent
up from 115 last year to 588 this year), Terengganu (322 per cent
rise from 81 to 342), Kedah (201 per cent hike from 75 to 226) and
Malacca (133 per cent climb from 93 to 217).
	   Ting said the overall drop of 2.7 per cent was ``not
satisfactory'' and urged the States to step up fogging, education
and cleanliness campaigns.
	   They are to submit reports to the Ministry every two weeks.
	   
</TEXT>
