<SLUG> BC-Northern Ireland </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Patten says police reform `central' to Northern Ireland agreement
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By SHAWN POGATCHNIK &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) _ Reform of Northern Ireland's
predominantly Protestant police force will be central to making the
peace agreement work, the politician charged with the task said
Friday.
	   Chris Patten, Britain's last governor of Hong Kong, said his
eight-member Independent Commission on Policing for Northern
Ireland was confident of meeting its mid-1999 deadline.
	   The government-appointed commission is supposed to recommend
ways of making the 13,000-strong Royal Ulster Constabulary more
acceptable to the north's minority Catholics, many of whom view it
with suspicion or outright contempt.
	   Plans for police reform formed a particularly emotive part of
the Belfast agreement, which was struck April 10 among eight
parties and the British and Irish governments.
	   While many pro-British Protestants want the police force
retained as is, militant Catholic supporters of the IRA-allied Sinn
Fein party demand its abolition.
	   ``All of us on the commission believe that the Good Friday
agreement represents a wonderful opportunity for Northern Ireland.
We want to see the promise of that agreement fulfilled,'' Patten,
an English Catholic who was a minister in Britain's Northern
Ireland Office in the early 1980s, said at a press conference.
	   ``We all want to see a Northern Ireland that is both peaceful
and prosperous. We see the future policing arrangements as a
central issue, as the agreement itself makes clear. And we're
profoundly aware of the responsibility that's been placed upon
us.''
	   Patten was accompanied by all seven of his colleagues, among
them two law-enforcement experts from the United States _ Gerald
Lynch, president of John Jay College in New York, and Kathleen
O'Toole, secretary for public safety in Massachusetts.
	   But they all declined to answer questions on specific
contentious policing issues, such as whether the ``Royal'' in the
force's name should be retained and whether its members should
operate unarmed.
	   Patten said it would be ``criminally irresponsible'' for the
commission to talk in specific terms before its report is
published.
	   (sp-kg)
</TEXT>
