<BODY>
<SLUG> HELPING-AN-UNWED sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Helping an unwed mom turn her life around, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Helping an unwed mom turn her life around, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Hadjee DeanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   AY back in the 70s, when I was a young Social Welfare Officer in
a northern State, a pretty Malay girl came to see me. She said that
she was from Kuala Lumpur and came from a respectable family.
	   She was studying in one of the colleges and was six months
pregnant.
	   After being jilted by her boyfriend, she had tried abortion but
it had been unsuccessful.
	   She felt that a Social Welfare Office away from her home was the
right place to seek help. She asked me to place her with a family
just to have the baby delivered and given away, after which, she
would go back and continue her studies.
	   She pleaded with me not to ask her more information, especially
about her family. She told me to just call her ``Ana''.
	   Although I had dealt with juvenile delinquents, underaged
prostitutes, wayward children, marital problems, etc, this was the
first case of its kind that I had encountered.
	   I rang up an official at my headquarters in Kuala Lumpur for
advice. The reply was ``Please try your best to assist the girl''.
	   After several enquiries, I placed her with my friend's family.
As luck would have it, a Government official who had been married
for 10 years but not yet blessed with a child was looking for a
baby to adopt.
	   A doctor who examined his wife and him confirmed that there was
nothing wrong with them.
	   Like some men who need to prove their virility, the husband
started to court a young girl with the view of marrying her
secretly in Thailand.
	   However, after our counselling, he was prepared to adopt the
girl's baby. He still loved his wife who was caring and faithful.
	   His wife was very happy as the husband had abandoned temporarily
his plan to take a second wife.
	   Actually, he was not keen to take a second wife because of the
accompanying responsibilities.
	   So the couple found a new common interest to occupy their time.
After getting a written consent from the girl to give her baby up
for adoption, they took great care of her, giving her the best
medical treatment and showering her with nourishing food and
vitamins.
	   Three months later a healthy baby boy was delivered and they
looked after him as if the child was their own.
	   As for the girl, they nursed her with traditional and modern
medicine during her confinement period.
	   After her confinement, she was as beautiful as when she came to
see me.
	   Before leaving for home in Kuala Lumpur, the couple gave her
RM700 as a token of their gratitude.
	   When the boy was two years old, the adoptive mother became
pregnant thus bringing more joy to the couple. A pretty girl was
born to them a year later, and before I was transferred to another
State, another boy and a girl were added to their family.
	   They treated the adopted boy and their other natural children
equally and showered them with love, care and affection.
	   The children are doing very well in their respective posts in
Kuala Lumpur and every now and then I would receive postcards or
presents from the parents.
	   The adopted boy got married last year and is going to be a
father soon.
	   This phenomenon of getting children after adopting one is known
to some people as berjangkit. I, myself, do not know if it is true,
but in this particular case, it had worked out very well.
	   Looking back on what I had done, I feel happy that I had helped
a young girl in trouble. As she did not want to divulge her
identity, my friends and I respected her wish to the last.
	   The girl later on married someone in high position and has had
several children. She keeps in touch with me through postcards in
which she tells me how happy and grateful she was for all the help
that had been extended to her.
	   She said that Allah had sent her to some selfless and caring
people and she has been praying hard that Allah would give guidance
to such kind people and forgive the sinners because as the Malay
proverb goes Bumi mana yang tidak di timpa hujan, laut mana yang
tidak berombak.
	   
</TEXT>
