<HEADLINE>
Clear confusion over place-names, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Clear confusion over place-names, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Noor Azlina YunusASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   WRITE in support of Muhammad Safian Mohamed Omar's letter,
``Place-names still misspelt despite reform, standardisation''
(NST, May 29).
	   My colleagues and I are currently preparing a 15-volume
Encyclopedia of Malaysia and we are concerned about the spelling of
place-names to ensure that it is not only correct but consistent
throughout all volumes.
	   However, it seems that determining the correct spelling is no
simple matter as we have been informed by both the Dewan Bahasa dan
Pustaka and the Department of Survey and Mapping that State
Governments are responsible for the place-names in their respective
States and no consolidated list of place-names for the whole
country is available.
	   This makes it very difficult for publishers of reference works
and maps, and is very confusing for travellers.
	   It is high time that a national system of spelling is adopted.
	   As Muhammad Safian said, ``re-spelling might cause some
confusion but we did it 26 years ago and can surely do it again''.
	   
</TEXT>
