<SLUG> WHEN-ALTERNATE-DAY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
When alternate day water supply plan is a farce, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
When alternate day water supply plan is a farce, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   yckASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   HE current water crisis faced by some areas in the Klang Valley
shows without doubt the gross inefficiency of the water
authorities.
	   The hardship faced by the people does not befit a nation which
aims to be a developed country.
	   If similar problems were to occur in a developed nation, the
repercussions would have been great for those in charge.
	   I stay in Happy Garden, Old Klang Road, in a zone A area under
the water rationing exercise. The alternate day water supply plan
is a big farce.
	   There were occasions when my area had been without water supply
for eight continuous days.
	   Enquiries to the water authorities proved to be a sheer waste of
time as the standard answer given was that there was simply no
water! Sending the water tanker was as good as not supplying water
at all as only those folks ``lucky'' enough to stay near where the
tankers stopped would benefit from it.
	   If the water authorities could not supply water on alternate
days, why did they include Happy Garden in zone A?
	   It would have been better if they created a new zone for such
areas - zone C - whereby water supply is irregular and can be
stopped indefinitely till an act of God reverses the El Nino
phenomenon.
	   Then, at least, those staying in such a zone can prepare
themselves by digging wells or moving to other places rather than
relying on the mercy of the authorities.
	   I have no doubt that we will be able to achieve Vision 2020 as a
nation but when we do, please make sure that water is available for
all Malaysians in this tropical country.
	   
</TEXT>
