<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Grenada-Used Car Flood,0368 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Used cars find second home in Caribbean, change vehicle market
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By RICHARD SIMON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ST. GEORGE'S, Grenada (AP) _ When some people on this island
want to buy a car, instead of going to the local new car dealer
they go to their computers.
	   Buying a used car through the Internet or through an agent has
made owning a vehicle affordable for many residents of the
Caribbean, where import taxes on new cars often double the purchase
price.
	   ``Many of the people who purchase these cars for Eastern
Caribbean dlrs 40,000 and dlrs 50,000 (dlrs 15,000-18,500) would
have never been able to afford a brand new car, which can range
from 80,000 to 120,000 (dlrs 30,000 to 44,500),'' said Neil Nedd, a
30-year-old used car dealer on Grenada, one of the Windward
Islands.
	   Nedd has a contact in Japan who helps him screen and purchase
used vehicles, but he said many people now buy directly through the
Internet.
	   In some Caribbean countries, the rising flood of less expensive
used cars has hurt new car dealers. In Antigua, the government last
year banned used car imports.
	   Michael McIntyre, a new car dealer on Grenada, said the 110
percent tax on new cars is a deterrent for most residents. He
advocates lowering the tax to 65 percent. Other new car dealers,
such as Royston Lahee, say buyers should beware because
unscrupulous vendors could lie about the age or conditions of the
cars being shipped in from abroad.
	   Lahee said he would like to see more government regulation, but
the Grenadian government does not seem likely to ban the used car
imports.
	   ``This is an open market and everyone has the right to carry on
legitimate business,'' said junior Finance Minister Patrick Bubb.
	   Used cars have become more plentiful as the popularity of
leasing has grown in countries such as Japan and the United States.
Cars that are 2 or 3 years old are being turned in as leases
expire.
	   ``That has definitely flooded the used car market with
better-than-usual-quality used cars,'' said Scott D. Upham,
president of Providata Inc., an automotive consulting firm in
Michigan.
</TEXT>
