<SLUG> PAHANG-FANS-FEEL sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pahang fans feel `cheated', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Pahang fans feel `cheated', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Pritam SinghASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   O far this season Pahang have enjoyed tremendous fan support but
the 5000 odd fans who witnessed the home team dished out a poor
performance against Penang in the FA Cup second leg at the
Darulmakmur Stadium on Tuesday, felt `cheated'.
	   It would seem, according to the fans, the League leaders did not
try hard enough to win the match. If anything, Pahang did not mind
going out of the FA Cup competition.
	   It was, therefore, not surprising to hear the cat calls from the
crowd who have been very supportive of the home team this season.
	   According to Hanif Wan Cik, a regular fan, if Pahang's strategy
is to concentrate on winning the League title, yesterday's showing
did not do their cause any good.
	   ``Penang are also title contenders and having beaten Pahang
twice in the FA Cup, they now have the psychological edge when the
two teams meet in Penang for the return leg of the league,'' said
Hanif.
	   ``And Pahng will only have themselves to blame should they
falter.''
	   Another fan, N.T. Rajah, said winning the FA Cup may not be as
glamorous as being crowned the league champions but the home team
should have given their best.
	   ``It was obvious they did not give their best and that is why we
felt cheated.''
	   Kim Fook, who runs a coffee shop, was most vocal. ``Pahang tipu
(cheated),'' he shouted after the match.
	   Others, among them Mohamed Ridzuan Abdullah, cautioned the team
not to be carried away by their eight-point lead.
	   ``Look at what happened to Sabah last year and Negri Sembilan
the year before.
	   ``Both led the table standings but fell at the last hurdle. And
I hope history does not repeat itself this year.''
	   And so Pahang may be well-advised not to take their fans for
granted.
	   What's happening to Selangor and Perak should be a grim reminder
that fans will not hesitate to desert the team should it keep
losing matches.
	   
</TEXT>
