<SLUG> BC-Italy-Big Dig </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Italy announces five-year dig of tantalizing ancient hill
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ After unearthing a stunning fresco and a fascinating
mosaic from the bowels of a hill, archaeologists have won a
five-year commitment from the government for a big dig.
	   Culture Minister Walter Veltroni promised Friday that they will
have 400 billion lire (dlrs 220 million) in funding for work on the
Oppian Hill, one of the seven hills of ancient Rome, as well as
other digging.
	   The other sites include the Circus Maximus, the ancient sports
arena where recent testing has located the central spine of the
stadium. The funding will also cover work at the ancient Baths of
Trajan and Titus and several Roman forum areas.
	   Experts from the national and city offices of archaeology as
well as colleagues from abroad will work together on the project,
said Veltroni, who is also deputy premier.
	   The fresco discovered recently in an ancient passageway gives a
a bird's eye view of an ancient city experts are still trying to
identify.
	   The mosaic, which appears to be 1,800 years old, was later
discovered on a nearby wall and depicts a man leaning on a column.
Another fresco, found behind the wall in a hidden room, represents
grape harvesting.
	   In the past, many ancient sites in Rome turned up accidentally
during sewer and utility line work, but now Italy wants a more
active exploration of what still lies underneath the surface.
	   (fd)
</TEXT>
