<HEADLINE>
Public administrators must co-operate with academics, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Public administrators must co-operate with academics, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   S. Zubaidah AljunidASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   HE late Tun Abdul Razak once said: ``... our intellectuals by
and large have a deep concern for the problems of our people and
particularly the urgent need to transform our society to reach the
higher living standards and industrial wealth of the advanced
countries ... they are welcome to put forth their views for the
consideration of the Government.''
	   (He said this in a message to participants at the International
Conference of Universities in Kuala Lumpur in August 1970.) In the
spirit of this quotation, I would like to highlight a predicament
faced as an academic researcher.
	   If the Government is sincere in welcoming academics to put forth
their views for the progress of the nation, this must be shown by
those in the first line of contact, namely, public administrators.
	   As a lecturer and postgraduate student who is trying very hard
to write a thesis, I often find myself making appointments to meet
government officials to clarify certain points in my research.
	   I have been fortunate to meet a handful who have been willing to
sacrifice their time but the majority however, have been
disappointments.
	   Some do not even bother to answer my letters or faxes requesting
an appointment.
	   The majority would instead ask me to meet a subordinate or pass
me to other departments. There seems to be a tendency to shy away
from meeting academic researchers, especially amongst those holding
high profile posts.
	   This, despite the fact that they are the ones making policy
decisions which have a direct bearing on problems addressed in such
academic research.
	   I do not see how academic researchers can help in the progress
of the nation if this type of attitude persists amongst public
administrators.
	   
</TEXT>
