<SLUG> CISCO-TO-OPEN-CENTRE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cisco to open centre for networking skills, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Cisco to open centre for networking skills, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Sharifah KasimASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   NETWORKING company Cisco Systems Inc will announce this year the
opening of an educational centre called the Network Academy. The
centre is dedicated to training and developing networking expertise
in the country.
	   Working with a local partner, Cisco is expected to introduce the
centre in the third quarter of this year. The company, said
managing director of South Asia Cisco Systems (USA) Pte Ltd Todd A.
Abbott, is currently working on an implementation plan for the
Network Academy.
	   ``One of the critical issues in market acceptance for new
networking technologies is skilled resources, and so the concept of
the Network Academy is to partner with a local organisation to roll
out an educational facility to meet this need,'' Abbott told a
Press conference in Singapore last week.
	   Cisco has selected a partner from the education sector but
Abbott declined to reveal the name of the partner.
	   Both parties, he added, will develop a set of curriculum,
laboratory equipment and necessary infrastructure to roll out
educational and training services in networking either in the
graduate or undergraduate level.
	   According to Abbott, the setting up of the Network Academy in
Malaysia is part of Cisco's investments strategy, which includes a
plan to set up a similar centre in each country in Southeast Asia.
	   He said the company looks at the region as an opportunity to
invest despite its difficult economic conditions.
	   ``We are making investments in the infrastructure and people to
prepare ourselves for the region's economic turnaround, so that
when the economy turns around, we can grow faster than what we have
experienced,'' he added.
	   Abbott said Asia, including Japan, historically contributes
between 16 and 17 per cent of Cisco's worldwide revenues.
	   This is expected to decrease to 12 to 13 per cent in this
financial year ending July, mainly due to the decline in the
company's business in Japan.
	   He said the company is also experiencing a business downturn in
Malaysia, but it is still optimistic about the local market.
	   In order to protect customers from currency fluctuation, Cisco
offers currency protection and financing programmes for long-term
projects.
	   Prior to the Press conference, Cisco introduced a set of
solutions which enables the integration of data and voice networks.
They include four products designed to enable the next generation
of carrier-class, Internet protocol-based or IP-based services
through seamless integration of IP and Asynchronous Transfer Mode
(ATM) technologies.
	   The four products are Cisco BPX 8650 IP+ATM switch, Cisco MGX
8800 wide area edge switch, Cisco BPX 8680 universal service node,
and the Cisco TGX 8750 optical core switch.
	   Service providers will be able to deploy IP and ATM services
using these products which feature Cisco IOS software and service
management tools.
	   Cisco integrated its IP and ATM technologies through Tag
Switching, which is said to be the industry's first end-to-end
implementation of the emerging Multi-protocol Label Switching
(MPLS) standard.
	   Tag Switching is intended to integrate IP and ATM technologies,
giving service providers advantages of the ATM technology, namely
privacy and quality of service, while providing the universal
connectivity of IP.
	   
</TEXT>
