<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Train Accident </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
German regional trains collide injuring 42 people, six seriously
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KARLSRUHE, Germany (AP) _ Two regional trains collided Friday in
southern Germany injuring 42 people, six seriously, police said.
	   The accident comes just 10 days after a high-speed ICE passenger
train derailed 50 kilometers (35 miles) north of Hanover,
collapsing an overpass and killing 100 people in Germany's worst
post-war railway accident.
	   Karlsruhe police said the two engines of the trains collided on
a single track about 4:25 p.m. (1525 GMT) between Ubstadt-Weiher
and Oestringen-Odenheim about 35 kilometers (20 miles) northeast of
Karlsruhe.
	   ``We don't know yet exactly how it happened, but it's clear this
accident should not have occurred,'' a police spokesman said.
	   He said it was possible a signal was falsely set or someone
didn't pay attention to it.
	   Both engineers were injured, one seriously, and were not in a
position to be immediately questioned, the spokesman said.
	   The injured were taken to hospitals by ambulance and helicopters
for treatment.
	   While both engines appeared to be demolished, an overall damage
estimate would not be available until further investigation, police
said.
	   (gb)
</TEXT>
