<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bulgaria-IMF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bulgaria, IMF to sign three-year agreement
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) _ Bulgaria and the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) have agreed in principle to a three-year financial
agreement, an IMF official announced Friday.
	   But according to IMF mission leader Anne McGuirk, negotiations
in areas such as investment programs, social service reforms,
health care and agriculture could not be completed because of a
time crunch.
	   ``The details of the agreement and the concrete figures will be
agreed on in July and it will be signed in September,'' Finance
Minister Radev explained.
	   According to McGuirk, the main challenge facing Bulgaria in the
next three years is continuing the transition to a market economy.
The agreement stresses structural reforms.
	   ``There are numerous symptoms of economic growth in Bulgaria.
Internal market demand and export is constantly growing,'' McGuirk
said.
	   Bulgaria may exceed the 4 percent growth projected for this
year, she said. In the medium term the IMF projects annual growth
of 4 percent to 5 percent.
	   Tax rates will be reduced in next year's budget, Radev said.
This will be accompanied by a broadening of the tax base. The
budget is set to be completed by the end of October.
	   (vt/scl)
</TEXT>
