<BODY>
<SLUG> LOAN-RECIPIENTS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Loan recipients who cannot repay urged to discuss with PSD, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Loan recipients who cannot repay urged to discuss with PSD, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUANTAN, Wed. - Recipients of Public Service Department's study
loans who are having difficulties with repayments, are advised to
contact the department to work out a solution.
	   Deputy Minister in the Prime Minister's Department Datuk Fauzi
Abdul Rahman said by doing so, they could avoid court action.
	   Commenting on a statement by Federation of Malaysian Consumer
Associations that it was unfair for the Government to take action
under the present economic situation, Fauzi said court action was
the last resort.
	   ``We studied various aspects, including the economic situation
and financial difficulties before taking action,'' he said.
	   Fauzi had announced last week that the PSD was filing bankruptcy
notice against 89 loan defaulters.
	   He said they made up only 0.03 per cent of the 10,325 PSD
scholarship holders and 33,110 recipients of study loans.
	   ``There is still room for discussion,'' he said.
	   In another development, Fauzi said the Government's proposal to
mobilise civil servants from one department to assist another to
cope with the manpower needs was more an ``optimum sizing''
exercise.
	   He said the move was aimed at making civil servants more
productive, efficient and at cutting down expenses.
	   Chief Secretary to the Government Tan Sri Abdul Halim Ali said
last Saturday that the redeployment programme was to avoid new
recruitment.
	   Fauzi said there should not be a problem for those affected to
adapt to the new job and work environment.
	   
</TEXT>
