<SLUG> BC-Sudan-Opposition </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sudanese rebels warn people not to use major highway to Red Sea
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Sudanese guerrillas warned civilians Friday
not to use the highway between Khartoum and Port Sudan, saying it
was a military area.
	   The highway is a strategic link between the capital and the
country's only outlet to the Red Sea.
	   A statement from the National Democratic Alliance, the umbrella
grouping of Sudanese opposition parties and guerrilla factions,
said a unit of the Umma Liberation Army ambushed a patrol of the
government's National Islamic Front on Thursday, inflicting heavy
casualties.
	   The guerrillas attacked the patrol on the Khartoum-Port Sudan
highway, eastern Sudan, and captured several members of the NIF,
the alliance said in a fax to The Associated Press in Cairo from
Asmara, Eritrea.
	   ``The National Democratic Alliance calls on citizens to avoid
the Port Sudan-Khartoum highway, which has become a military
area,'' the fax said.
	   The Umma Liberation Army is the military wing of the Umma Party,
the party of former Prime Minister Sadiq el-Mahdi.
	   The National Islamic Front is the movement of the Sudanese
parliament's speaker, Hassan Turabi, widely regarded as the
ideologue of the government of President Omar el-Bashir, who
overthrew el-Mahdi in a military coup in 1989.
	   The alliance is waging a two-front insurrection. Guerrillas
allied to Umma are active in eastern Sudan while the country's
biggest rebel group, the Sudan People's Liberation Army, is
fighting in the south. The SPLA, which draws its support from the
south's mainly Christian and animist population, seeks autonomy
from the Islamic north.
	   More 1.3 million people have died in the fighting and consequent
famines since the war began in 1983.
 &UR; bm-jbm
</TEXT>
