<SLUG> COURT-DISMISSES-BANKS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Court dismisses bank's application, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Court dismisses bank's application, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MULTI-PURPOSE Bank Bhd's application to wind up SCK Furnishing
Sdn Bhd over its failure to settle debts amounting to RM495,612.44
was dismissed by the High Court yesterday on a technicality.
	   Judge Datuk K.L. Rekhraj, in dismissing the application with
costs, ruled that the petition was flawed as the statutory notice
served on the company did not have the date of the service.
	   ``There is no evidence of the service date on the notice. It is
very important as it is the proof that the notice has been
served,'' he said.
	   The petition was filed after SCK Furnishing, a subsidiary of
construction-based SCK Group Bhd, had failed to settle its debts
arising from an overdraft facility provided by the bank.
	   The bank was represented by Sri Dev Nair while Andrew Chin and
Raymond Tan appeared for SCK Furnishing.
	   The bank has also filed winding up petitions against SCK Group
and its two other subsidiaries - Shanghai Chong Kee Construction
Sdn Bhd and SCK Cerabrics Sdn Bhd - over the failure of the
subsidiaries to settle their debts to the bank.
	   SCK Group, listed on the Second Board of the Kuala Lumpur Stock
Exhange, had stood guarantee for the payment of overdraft
facilities taken by the subsidiaries from the bank.
	   The petition against SCK Group will be heard on June 26 before
judge Datuk T.S. Nathan.
	   
</TEXT>
