WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PUBLIC Bank Bhd, the nation's third largest bank in terms of
assets, seems to be well-insulated against the economic downturn
with higher profits, more shareholder funds, better risk-to-capital
ratio and a healthy non- performing loans situation, according to
its latest quarterly results.
	   Its group pre-tax profit surged 370.3 per cent for the first
quarter ended March 31, 1998 to RM118.2 million compared to the
previous quarter ended Dec 31, 1997.
	   At the bank level, pre-tax profit jumped 62.8 per cent to RM94.9
million when compared to the previous quarter.
	   For the financial quarter under review, the bank's net
non-performing ratio was at 1.07 per cent compared to 1.06 per cent
previously.
	   As at March 31, 1998, the banking system's average
non-performing ratio was seven per cent.
	   In a statement released after the bank's annual meeting in Kuala
Lumpur yesterday, it said Public Bank's risk weighted capital ratio
improved to 13.19 per cent from 10.74 per cent the previous
quarter.
	   The bank's shareholders funds grew by 18.4 per cent to RM2.61
billion from RM2.21 billion while the group's shareholders funds
increased by 12.2 per cent to RM3.23 billion from RM2.87 billion.
	   The bank's total assets for the first quarter of this year stood
at RM28.24 billion from RM29.44 billion while for the group it was
at RM41.78 billion compared to RM41.90 billion.
	   Deposit from customers at the bank's level during the period
under review was recorded at RM20.63 billion against RM21.04
billion in the previous quarter. For the group, deposits from
customers stood at RM30.39 billion from RM32.02 billion.
	   The bank's total loans and advances stood at RM10.87 billion
from RM11.11 billion the previous quarter while at the group level,
it was at RM19.56 billion from RM20.46 billion.
	   President and chief executive officer Tan Sri Teh Hong Piow said
in the statement that Public Bank would continue to manage its
operations prudently to meet the challenges of the current
difficult economic and banking environment.
	   He added the group would remain sound and stable, with its
proven track record in prudence and asset quality.
	   On the bank's operations, it is expected to offer two life
insurance products under the concept of Bankassurance. Initially
the products will be sold at selected branches.
	   The first is a critical illness plan to protect customers
against 36 critical illnesses, death and total and permanent
disability due to natural or accidental causes.
	   The second will be a convertible term plan covering death and
total and permanent disability.
	   The bank's new computer system, which was installed recently,
has enabled it to offer cross company services to customers, it
said adding that the computer system would be fully Year 2000
compliant by the end of this year.
	   For the year ended Dec 31, 1997, Public Bank's group pre-tax
profit was RM634.7 million while net profit decreased by 28.1 per
cent to RM400.1 million.
	   Earnings per share for last year was 16.6 sen compared to 24.7
sen in the previous year.
	   Public Bank shares closed at RM1.39 on Tuesday. They opened
trading at the same price yesterday but was suspended at 2.30pm at
RM1.38 with 130,000 shares done.
	   
</TEXT>
