<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-Gerry Weber Open </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kafelnikov last remaining seed at Gerry Weber Open
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HALLE, Germany (AP) _ Russia's Yevgeny Kafelnikov, the defending
champion, was the only seeded player left at the Gerry Weber Open
Friday after he ousted Magnus Norman in straight sets.
	   Kafelnikov, the second seed, reached the semifinals by beating
the eighth-seeded Swede, 7-6 (7-1), 6-2 in just over an hour as
unusual cold continued to plague the dlrs 875,000 grass court
event.
	   Richard Krajicek of The Netherlands, the third seed, struggled
with his returns and fell to Sweden's Magnus Larsson, 6-4, 6-2 in
an earlier match.
	   Krajicek, the 1996 Wimbledon champion, became the latest victim
after upsets had already claimed this year's Australian Open
champion, Petr Korda, and the recent winner of the French Open,
Spain's Carlos Moya.
	   Larsson took control of the match by whipping in a high
percentage of first serves after he gained a break against Krajicek
to take a 5-4 first set lead.
	   Krajicek, along with problems returning the Swede's serve, also
complained about the slippery center court. Despite the artificial
roof, moisture from ongoing rain has caused players to slip and
slide.
	   The hard-serving Dutchman, who reached Wimbledon's fourth round
last year, plans to play Rosmalen in The Netherlands next week.
	   ``It was very slippery out there,'' said Krajicek. ``I'm hoping
I can get some more practice at Rosmalen and that it will be
warmer.''
	   Kafelnikovk, who also reached the final two years ago, faces
Thomas Johansson in Saturday's semifinal after the Swede ended the
upset run of Germany's Hendrik Dreekmann.
	   Johansson struggled to a 6-3, 1-6, 6-4 victory over Dreekmann,
who had ousted Moya and Boris Becker.
	   Larsson faces the winner of a later match between Italy's
Gianluca Pozzi and Paul Haarhuis of The Netherlands.
	    &UR; (rk)	   
</TEXT>
