<HEADLINE>
Dikir barat performance allowed at expo, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Dikir barat performance allowed at expo, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KOTA BARU, Wed. - Despite the ban on dikir barat performances,
the State Government today announced that it was issuing a special
permit to the organisers of the ``Buy Malaysian Goods'' exposition
beginning Friday to hold a performance at the venue.
	   The six-day exposition, to be held at Padang Perdana, is jointly
organised by the Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs Ministry's
State enforcement division and the Kelantan Consumer Affairs
Council.
	   State Culture, Tourism, Youth and Sports Committee chairman
Abdullah Yaakub said the decision to allow a dikir barat
performance during the exposition was reached at today's weekly
State Executive Council meeting chaired by Menteri Besar Datuk Nik
Abdul Aziz Nik Mat.
	   ``The approval was given after the ministry, in its application,
gave the assurance that the performance would not contravene the
State Government's guidelines on entertainment,'' he told reporters
after the meeting at Kota Darulnaim.
	   Abdullah also said discussions would be held with the organisers
of the exposition on the conditions to be observed when holding the
dikir barat performance.
	   He added that enforcement officers from the local authority
would be monitoring the performance.
	   Asked whether the State Government had lifted its ban on dikir
barat performance, he said approval to hold the performance during
the exposition was given on the basis that the case was a special
one.
	   ``The dikir barat performance to be held during the exposition
will determine the State Government's decision whether to continue
with the ban,'' he said.
	   The State Government had banned all dikir barat performances
when some organisers were found to have contravened conditions in
their permits by including other forms of entertainment
unacceptable to Islam.
	   
</TEXT>
