<BODY>
<SLUG> FIRMS-GIVEN-TWO-YEARS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Firms given two years to finish Tasek Kenyir tasks, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Firms given two years to finish Tasek Kenyir tasks, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Rosli ZakariaASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA TERENGGANU, Wed. - The State Government has given five
companies a two-year extension to complete their projects at Tasik
Kenyir.
	   Menteri Besar Tan Sri Wan Mokhtar Ahmad said the decision was
taken after considering their explanation that they could not
proceed with the projects due to the lack of basic infrastructure.
	   ``We are now trying to speed up infrastructure development,
including constructing feeder roads to previously inaccessible
areas and a building for the waterworks department.
	   ``Once they are in place, hopefully by next year, the five
companies have to honour their pledge to proceed with their
projects.''
	   Wan Mokhtar was asked to comment on the delay in the projects
proposed as far back as 1993 by SPPT Development Sdn Bhd, ASM
Development Sdn Bhd, Atasan Holdings Sdn Bhd, Kenyir Lake Tourist
Sdn Bhd and Rumpun Indera Sdn Bhd.
	   He said despite the encouragement by the Government for the
private sector to take the lead in the development projects in the
the State, the Government still had to play a leading role.
	   He said because of this, the private sector had missed several
golden opportunities.
	   ``In view of this, the State Government had to divert its funds
to provide the infrastructure to encourage the private sector to
invest.
	   These funds could have been used for other social development
programmes,''
	   he told reporters after a two-day visit to Tasik Kenyir.
	   Wan Mokhtar was taken on a tour of the areas at Tasik Kenyir
which have been identified for development, namely Sungai Petang,
Pulau Petang, Sungai Belembing, Sungai Tembat and Sungai Petuang.
	   He also visited the site for the highway project that will link
Sungai Gawi in Tasik Kenyir and Ipoh as well as a feeder road that
leads to a 400-hectare land for the development of an education and
training centre.
	   He was also taken to the aquaculture project near Sungai Gawi
and briefed on the success of the project undertaken by the
Fisheries Department.
	   As for the highway project, Wan Mokhtar said it was slightly
behind schedule but it would be completed by 2000.
	   ``This highway is an important link. It will reduce travelling
time to Terengganu from Ipoh by about two hours,'' he said.
	   He added that at present, it would take about eight hours to
travel from Ipoh to the East Coast using the Grik Highway.
	   
</TEXT>
