Death toll in cyclone crosses 800, exodus begins from villages
</HEADLINE>
without water, food &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES the death toll to 835 with a government spokesman
saying that 95 more bodies were located &QL; 
 &UR; By RAMOLA TALWAR &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BOMBAY, India (AP) _ For poor villagers in western India, the
disaster of a cyclone that killed at least 835 people was followed
by desperate shortages that forced them on to mud-choked roads
Friday in search of food and drinking water.
	   The death toll stood at 814 Friday in the hardest-hit state of
Gujarat, as workers continued to find bodies flung on power cables
and trees or buried in sludge left behind by a tidal wave three
days after the cyclone hit land.
	   The toll crossed 800 after two government helicopters located 95
more bodies in the worst-hit Kandla port area later Friday, which
were picked up by rescue workers, said a government spokesman in
Ahmedabad, the capital of Gujarat state.
