<SLUG> BC-France-World Cup-Scottish Fan </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Scottish fan under formal investigation for World Cup violence
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ A Scottish soccer fan accused of injuring a French
policeman has been banned from attending World Cup matches, and is
under formal investigation, judicial sources said Friday.
	   Stephen Stapley, 30, is accused of throwing a beer bottle at a
policeman during violent street clashes Tuesday night. The
policeman suffered cuts.
	   Tuesday's street festivities _ marking the start of the World
Cup _ were marred by fights between drunken fans and police. Thirty
four policemen were injured.
	   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Stapley
was placed under formal investigation _ one step short of being
charged.
	   He requires judicial authorisation to leave France during the
probe. He is currently being held in custody.
	   French authorities have vowed to crack down on violence during
the World Cup, and are warning hooligans they face jail terms,
deportation, or stiff fines.
	   A French court Thursday sentenced a Scottish soccer fan to a
two-month suspended sentence for throwing beer cans at a policeman
during Tuesday's violence.
