<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Czar's Burial </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Deputy prime minister to attend czar's burial
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Deputy Prime Minister Boris Nemtsov and his family
will attend the burial of Russia's last czar, his aide said Friday.
	   Nemtsov headed the Russian government commission that was in
charge of determining the identity of nine sets of bones recovered
in 1991 near where Nicholas II was executed by the Bolsheviks.
	   Repeated DNA testing has confirmed their identities as Nicholas,
his wife, three of their children children and four servants.
	   Most members of the commission will attend the July 17 service
in St. Petersburg, Nemtsov's aide, Viktor Aksyuchin told Echo
Moscow radio station.
	   The patriarch of the Russian Orthodox Church said earlier in the
week that he would not officiate at the service. President Boris
Yeltsin has not said whether he would attend, but Russian media
have said he would not if Patriarch Alexy II did not.
	   The funeral service will be held in the Peter and Paul
Cathedral, the traditional burial site of the Romanovs, who ruled
Russia for 300 years. Hundreds of foreign representatives have been
invited to attend.
	   (ls) 	   
</TEXT>
