<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bosnia-Croats </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Split among Bosnian Croats to create new party
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By AIDA CERKEZ &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) _ Bosnian Croat politicians
who recently split with the ruling Croat Democratic Union said
Friday they would form a new party supporting an integrated Bosnia.
	   The initial meeting of the yet-to-be-named party was held Friday
in Sarajevo. The group is currently calling itself the New Croat
Initiative.
	   Its basic principles will include an integrated Bosnia, a goal
contrary to that of the Croat Democratic Union, loyal to Croatian
President Franjo Tudjman. The party has had almost no competition
in Bosnia.
	   ``The main principal is that Bosnia-Herzegovina is our
homeland,'' Kresimir Zubak said in a statement carried by the local
news agency ONASA. Zubak is the Croat member of the Bosnian joint
presidency.
	   Zubak explained last week he was fed up with the Croat
Democratic Union's policy of dividing Bosnia, and with party
leaders who used the war to get rich.
	   Zubak said he will send his resignation Saturday to the Croat
Democratic Union.
	   The new party ``is a Croat national, but not nationalistic
party, and will not be closed for other nations in Bosnia,'' Zubak
said.
	   International officials have been sympathetic toward the new
party because Croat Democratic Union hard-liners have been
uncooperative with efforts to integrate Bosnia and implement the
Dayton peace agreement.
	   ``We want to offer an alternative to Croat people in Bosnia,''
ONASA quoted Zubak as saying.
	   The leader of Bosnia's Muslims and the chairman of the
collective presidency, Alija Izetbegovic, welcomed the move as
``positive progress.''
	   (ac/scl) 	   
</TEXT>
