<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iraq-Diplomacy Reshuffle,0248 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iraq is replacing some 30 ambassadors
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By LEON BARKHO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Iraq is replacing most of its foreign
ambassadors in a drive to improve its image, which has been
severely tarnished since its 1990 invasion of Kuwait, an official
said Friday.
	   The senior Iraqi official said the government plans to replace
some 30 of its 35 foreign ambassadors. The official spoke on
customary condition of anonymity.
	   Iraq's most influential newspaper, Babil, reported this week
that a number of Iraqi foreign diplomats have been recalled to
Baghdad, but it gave no details.
	   It is time that Iraqi embassies were ``injected with new blood
to destroy the wall of isolation the enemies have constructed
around Iraq,'' the newspaper said.
	   Iraq has been under sweeping U.N. economic sanctions since the
invasion.
	   Saddam's half brother, Barzan al-Tikriti, is one of the
ambassadors who has been recalled, the official said. He was Iraq's
representative to the U.N. offices in Geneva.
	   Iraqi ambassadors to Yemen, Algeria, India, Tunisia, Pakistan,
Jordan, Russia, Malaysia were also among those recalled, the
official said.
	   The envoy to the Arab League, Nabil Najim, a close associate to
Saddam and a member of his Tikriti clan, has been appointed senior
undersecretary at the Foreign Ministry, the official said.
	   Iraq's ambassador to the United Nations, Nizar Hamdoun, may also
be replaced.
</TEXT>
