<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Swiss Banks-Nazis,0419 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Swiss Jewish newspapers denounce U.S.-based report for absurdity
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   GENEVA (AP) _ A Jewish newspaper in Switzerland disputed a new
report that the Swiss were heavily pro-Nazi during World War II,
charging Friday that the study distorted the strength of a movement
supporting the Third Reich.
	   The newspaper, the Israelitisches Wochenblatt, alleged the study
issued in New York by the Simon Wiesenthal Center, ``deliberately
suppressed the strong anti-Nazi movement in Switzerland.''
	   The center's report alleged Switzerland's 4 million people were
``thoroughly saturated'' with right-wing groups claiming tens of
thousands of members during the war.
	   The paper joined the country's other Jewish weekly in attacking
the study. The Basel-based Juedische Rundschau on Thursday
described the study as full of ``exaggerations and
falsifications.''
	   The Israelitisches Wochenblatt, published in Zurich, said the
report made it easy for nationalist Swiss to reject efforts to make
good on any wrongs committed during World War II.
	   The newspaper said that while the Nazis had a well-organized
network of largely secret organizations in neutral Switzerland
preparing to include the country in the Third Reich, the movement
had to be put in proportion.
	   ``The Swiss Nazis were weak in numbers,'' said the weekly. ``In
the parliament in Bern they had exactly one seat for four years.''
	   ``If Swiss society were really so saturated with Nazis, that
would have had to be reflected in parliamentary elections,'' it
added.
	   The Zurich newspaper said the distortions will make it difficult
to examine the repetition of allegations it described as being more
worthy of study, such as the long-standing charge that the Swiss
government had an anti-Jewish policy during World War II.
	   The Juedische Rundschau said author Alan Morris Schom's report
starts with errors in the first paragraph, which incorrectly states
that the Swiss cantons (states) in World War II numbered 21, when
there were actually 22.
	   ``So many details are presented painfully wrong,'' said the
Juedische Rundschau, which earlier this year led Swiss Jewish
criticism of a report by Schom asserting Switzerland put Jewish
refugees in slave labor camps.
	   On Wednesday, the U.S. State Department also disputed the
charges in Schom's new report, noting that Switzerland provided
shelter for 50,000 Jewish refugees.
</TEXT>
