<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Egypt-Ethiopia, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ethiopian minister rules out direct negotiations with Eritrea
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Ethiopian quotes after meeting Mubarak

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Ethiopia will not negotiate directly with
Eritrea because it is occupying Ethiopian land, the country's
foreign minister said Friday.
	   Ethiopian Foreign Minister Seyoum Mesfin arrived in Cairo and
held talks with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and Foreign
Minister Amr Moussa.
	   Earlier this week, Eritrea asked Egypt to mediate the border war
with Ethiopia that broke out last month.
	   ``Direct negotiations are impossible because it is unacceptable
for someone to come and occupy your territory and tell you: `come
and negotiate with me','' Mesfin told reporters at Cairo airport.
	   ``It is against international law.''
	   After meeting Mubarak, Mesfin said: ``This war is an imposed
(war) from Eritrea.''
	   ``I strongly believe, as (does) my government, that borders
can't be changed by wars, but by peacefull means and
negotiations,'' Mesfin said.
	   The foreign minister said his government supported the
U.S.-Rawandan initiative on solving the conflict, and he called on
African states to back it.
	   Eritrea has rejected the initiative.
	   Moussa told reporters that President Mubarak had urged Mesfin to
avoid confrontation and negotiate to reach a solution.
	   Mesfin's visit comes a day after Abdullah Mahmoud Jaber, an
adviser to Eritrean President Isaias Afwerki, left Cairo after
asking Egypt to mediate in the dispute.
	   Border skirmishes broke out on May 6 when Ethiopia accused
Eritrea of occupying a swath of land along their border. The two
sides differ over where Italy, the former colonial power, drew the
border.
	   Eritrean forces fought a secessionist rebellion against Ethiopia
for 30 years. They realized their aims in 1993, two years after
helping Ethiopian rebels under Meles Zenawi, the current president,
overthrow the Addis Ababa government.
 &UR; str-bm-jbm
</TEXT>
