<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Liberia-Peacekeepers </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
West African peacekeepers turn police in Liberia
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MONROVIA, Liberia (AP) _ Liberia on Friday granted police powers
to Nigerian-led West African peacekeepers who have been without a
clear mandate since former rebel leader Charles Taylor was elected
president last July.
	   In an agreement signed in Liberia's capital, Foreign Minister
Monie Captan gave the ECOMOG peacekeeping force a mandate to
``assist the government in providing security and the maintenance
of law and order.''
	   Lansana Kouyate, executive secretary of the Economic Community
of Western States, also signed the deal. ECOWAS, a regional
political and economic body, originally deployed the force under
Nigerian leadership.
	   The troops are, however, forbidden from intervening in civil
disputes or engaging in commercial activities in Liberia, Captan
said.
	   The new deal also extends the force's original military
peacekeeping role. ECOMOG troops were first deployed to Liberia to
oversee the implementation of a peace accord and elections last
year.
	   Some of the troops have since been redeployed to Sierra Leone,
where they overthrew junta forces in February. But others have
stayed behind.
	   President Taylor has had cool relations with the peacekeepers,
accusing them of interfering in his bid to create a national
military from remnants of his former rebel group.
	   (jpl-gam-bk)
</TEXT>
