<SLUG> BC-Turks and Caicos-Haitian Refugees,0239 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report says Haitians who died in capsized boat were not shot
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   COCKBURN TOWN, Turks and Caicos (AP) _ Examinations of the
bodies of six Haitian refugees who drowned Monday when their sloop
capsized off the Turks and Caicos islands did not have gunshot
wounds, police said Friday.
	   Some of the survivors of the shipwreck said marine police had
fired at the overcrowded boat. But police said they only fired
warning shots in the air, Deputy Police Commissioner Bryan Davies
said.
	   The boat has been raised and will be examined, Davies said
Friday.
	   The 70 Haitians who survived the sinking were being interviewed.
They spent more than an hour Thursday talking with a representative
from the Haitian consulate in the Bahamas.
	   The ship sank Monday just 15 miles (25 kilometers) off
Providenciales, the largest island in the British archipelago 600
miles (1,000 kilometers) southeast of Florida.
	   Survivors said as many as 113 people were on the boat. Police
said there were about 70 survivors and only six bodies were
recovered.
	   Davies said police also want to interview the occupants of two
sailing yachts that may have been near the incident. The names of
the vessels are unknown, but some survivors said they were flying
U.S. flags.
	   Thousands of Haitian refugees fleeing their impoverished country
have ended up in the Turks and Caicos islands in recent years. 	   
</TEXT>
