<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Train Accident, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
German regional trains collide injuring 37 people
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES reducing number of injured to 37, describes injuries
in grafs 2-3, other details, trims pvs &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   KARLSRUHE, Germany (AP) _ Two regional trains collided Friday in
southern Germany injuring 37 people, police said.
	   Two people were hospitalized with head and spinal injuries, and
12 were treated for broken bones, a Karlsruhe police spokesman
said. The others suffered lesser injuries.
	   Earlier reports had 42 people injured, six seriously, but police
later corrected that.
	   The accident comes just 10 days after a high-speed ICE passenger
train derailed 50 kilometers (35 miles) north of Hanover,
collapsing an overpass and killing 100 people in Germany's worst
post-war railway accident.
	   In the latest accident, police said the two diesel-powered
engines of the trains collided on a single track about 4:25 p.m.
(1525 GMT) between Ubstadt-Weiher and Oestringen-Odenheim about 35
kilometers (20 miles) northeast of Karlsruhe.
	   It was not immediately clear how many passengers were on the
trains or at what speed they were traveling.
	   ``We don't know yet exactly how it happened, but it's clear this
accident should not have occurred,'' a police spokesman said.
	   He said it was possible a signal was falsely set or someone
didn't pay attention to it.
	   Both engineers were injured, one seriously, and were not
immediately capable of being questioned, the spokesman said.
	   While both engines appeared to be demolished, an overall damage
estimate would not be available until further investigation, police
said.
	   (gb)
</TEXT>
