<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Auto Racing-Tyrrell, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tyrrell boss gets fitting retirement present
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Tyrrell throughout &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   GOODWOOD, England (AP) _ Long-time Formula One owner Ken Tyrrell
received a fitting retirement present Friday when his grandchildren
re-acquired the Formula One car Jackie Stewart drove to the 1970
championship.
	   Two of Tyrrell's grandchildren paid 73,000 pounds (dlrs 119,720)
at auction for the first Tyrrell-Cosworth Formula One car produced
for the Scottish driver.
	   Adrian Tyrrell, 28, and his cousin, Claire, said they had paid a
reasonable price for the car which launched Stewart on a string of
wins in the early 1970s.
	   ``In fact it was not as much as we expected and I have got
something I really wanted,'' Adrian said.
	   ``I'm delighted the car is staying in the family. I think it
would be sad if it had gone abroad,'' Ken Tyrrell said.
	   Ken Tyrrell and his son, Bob, stepped down in February from
management of the Tyrrell Racing team after failing to come to
terms with the team's new owners.
	   Tyrrell Racing was bought out last year by British American
Racing. Tyrrell announced last year he was retiring, although he
had planned to do it at the end of the 1998 season before the
falling out with British American Racing.
	   (scw)	   
</TEXT>
