<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Netherlands-International Court </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. official calls for pragmatism in talks on international court
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) _ The U.S. ambassador on war crimes
Friday called for a pragmatic approach to next week's international
conference to discuss the establishment of a permanent
international criminal court.
	   Ambassador David Scheffer said debates over the structure of the
court have continued for three years and ``this is crunch time.''
	   ``We cannot seek in Rome to create a dream factory of
international criminal law, a theoretically pure institution,'' he
told reporters during a one-day visit.
	   ``What emerges from Rome will be an international court that
satisfies the needs of international criminal justice in our time
and for the next century,'' he added.
	   During the Rome conference, envoys from more than 180 countries
will try to hammer out, among other things, the court's structure
and jurisdiction.
	   Scheffer stressed that it is vital that the court has enough
backing by a broad section of countries worldwide and it has the
clout to do its job.
	   Scheffer was in The Hague for the inauguration ceremony of the
third courtroom at the Yugoslav war crimes tribunal.
	   That U.N. tribunal was established by the Security Council in
1993, and it is prosecuting serious violations of international
humanitarian law committed in the former Yugoslavia since 1991.
	   Scheffer said the permanent international criminal court will
deal with ``the most serious commissions'' of crimes.
	   ``You can boil it down to almost mass killings. That's where the
focus of this court needs to be,'' he added.
	   ``You cannot create a court where we are creating a human rights
ombudsman that will have at least the temptation to take any and
all violations of human rights,'' he added.
	   (jc)
</TEXT>
