<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Netherlands,0443 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Dutch look to patch up old wounds
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With Sports-Soccer-Netherlands-Belgium &QL; 
 &UR; By ANDREAS EVAGORA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   VERSAILLES, France (AP) _ For two decades, the progress of
talented Dutch teams has been wrecked by clashes between players
and management. This time, players pledged things will be
different.
	   Disputes over tactics, money and simmering race problems have
undermined the Netherlands in major tournaments ever since Johan
Cruyff walked out on the team before the 1978 World Cup.
	   During the 1996 European Championships, Edgar Davids was sent
home for criticizing coach Guus Hiddink.
	   Two years earlier, Ruud Gullit walked out on training before the
World Cup.
	   Gullit was also one of the players at the center of conflicts
before the 1990 World Cup.
	   ``There have been disputes in the past, but this time there are
no divisions,'' Hiddink said Friday in Versailles, where the team
was completing preparations for its World Cup opener against
Belgium.
	   ``We are very determined. The individuals know that in their
careers they will not play in many World Cups with the kind of
squad that we have here,'' he said.
	   Captain Frank de Boer noted that the absence of experienced
superstars like Gullit and Marco van Basten could ease tensions
within the camp.
	   ``In the past, players like Gullit and van Basten could have had
a say in the tactics,'' de Boer said. ``But that is not the case
this time. We are a younger team.''
	   The Netherlands is better prepared for success than in the 1996
European Championships, he said, when the team failed to show top
form and lost in the quarterfinals.
	   ``We are more experienced than in 1996,'' de Boer said. ``And
this time we don't have anything to interfere with our preparations
as we did then.''
	   Davids' inclusion in the squad is seen as a sign of more cordial
relations within the Dutch camp.
	   ``This time, we are really a team,'' striker Jimmy Hasselbaink
said.
	   The Netherlands also approaches the World Cup with revamped
tactics, having abandoned its conventional 4-3-3 in favor of a more
cautious 4-4-2.
	   ``It's a little bit more defensive, but most of us play 4-4-2
for our clubs,'' de Boer said.
	   Striker Dennis Bergkamp was also in confident mood.
	   ``We have a chance to get to the final,'' Bergkamp said.
	   ``If you look at the clubs that our players play for, and their
roles for their teams, the quality of the squad is clear,''
Bergkamp said. ``It is different from two years ago. We are a lot
more experienced. We are wiser now.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Soccer-Netherlands; CT:s; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:INDI;)
(REG:ENGL;)
