<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Rand Drops Again,0270 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Second day of perilous drop for Rand
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) _ The South African Reserve Bank
signaled its intent Friday to stop propping up the rand, triggering
another plunge in its value against the dollar.
	   Late Friday, the dollar was quoted at a record high of 5.30
rand, up from 5.25 late Thursday.
	   Since June 3, the rand has lost nearly 4 percent of its value to
the dollar, and a full 8.3 percent since the beginning of the year,
AP-Dow Jones newservices reported.
	   The latest fall was attributed in part to the reserve bank's
decision on Friday to drop its interest rate by half a point to 17
percent, a signal of retreat from its strategy over past weeks of
selling dollars and hiking interest rates to boost the rand's
value.
	   But the global strength of the dollar also played a role.
	   The Reserve Bank's actions raised the specter ``that the rand
will fall to 5.70 (rand to the dollar) in the near term,'' Larry
Hatheway, an analyst at SBC Warburg Dillon Read in London, told Dow
Jones.
	   He said Friday's rate cut was puzzling because the central bank
had just tightened monetary policy late in May to curb pressure on
the rand.
	   This flip-flop will ``do little to restore confidence in the
currency,'' he added.
	   The interest rate drop came amid growing pressure from
economists, market participants and politicians who have questioned
the cost of the bank's policies.
	   Earlier this month, the bank reported it had spent over dlrs 6
billion defending the rand from what it saw as foreign speculation
for profit.
</TEXT>
