<HEADLINE>
Ajinomoto may further raise prices if situation worsens, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Ajinomoto may further raise prices if situation worsens, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   AJINOMOTO (Malaysia) Bhd is contemplating to further increase
the prices of its food seasoning products if the current economic
situation worsens.
	   Managing director and general manager Yasushi Akasaka said
yesterday the company had raised the prices of its main product
line - Aji-No-Moto - by two to three per cent since early this
year.
	   The increase was due to the escalating cost of raw materials
especially tapioca starch which was mainly imported from Thailand,
he said.
	   The company's other core raw materials are sago starch and sugar
cane which are sourced from Sarawak.
	   Akasaka said the price of imported tapioca starch had risen by
50 per cent and that Ajinomoto sourced about 40 per cent of the raw
materials from overseas.
	   Akasaka, who spoke after Ajinomoto's annual meeting in Petaling
Jaya, Selangor, said the company expected its group pre-tax profit
to decline slightly this year from the RM7.94 million recorded in
the year ended Dec 31, 1997.
	   Apart from the rise in cost of raw materials, the expected lower
profit could also be attributed to the drought.
	   ``The lower profit is expected to be further aggravated by the
uncertainties in the market which will likely result in a slowdown
in the retail and food services industries.''
	   He said Ajinomoto was counteracting these shortcomings through
cost saving programmes and increase in export market.
	   Despite these shortcomings, Akasaka said the company had
targeted a 10 per cent increase in sales turnover to RM135 million
this year from RM124.5 million last year.
	   The higher sales revenue was expected in view of the growing
demand for its products including two new products within the
Seri-Aji and Aji-Shio lines.
	   He said the Aji-No-Moto product line had posted an 11 per cent
growth in sales last year, and Tencho - a naturally derived food
seasoning - was also performing well.
	   Ajinomoto exported about 20 per cent of its products last year
to Oman, Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, Sri Lanka, Singapore and China,
among others. It plans to increase export sales by another five per
cent this year. Akasaka said the company would be spending about
RM8.5 million to expand its operations.
	   
</TEXT>
