<HEADLINE>
Hot dishes for Thai food lovers, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Hot dishes for Thai food lovers, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A TEAM of chefs from Central Sukhontha Hotel in Haadyai,
Thailand, brings you the spiciest of Thai dishes at Wenworth Hotel
Kuala Lumpur until June 18.
	   Headed by sous chef Veerasak Pidthongkha, the team comprises
cooks Srisawat Bunsang and Ladda Woraward, hostess Nipa Keawrath
and sales manager Wipanun Suwannetra.
	   Veerasak, who is in Malaysia for the first time, said Malaysian
cooking was similar to that of the Thai.
	   ``Malaysian food is tasty and spicy but not as hot as Thai food.
	   ``Thai food is rich in coconut milk and we use a lot of lemon or
the sour taste,'' said Veerasak, who learned to cook at the age of
17.
	   Spice for the dishes were flown in from Thailand for the
promotion which is available for buffet lunch and dinner at
Wenworth Court.
	   Among the dishes are seafood souffle in banana leaf, chicken in
green curry sauce, fish with sweet and sour sauce, grilled fresh
water prawn with savoury sauce, roast beef tenderloin with basil,
fried clams with chilli oil paste, fried noodle Thai-style and rice
cooked with chicken.
	   The chefs will also hold cooking demonstrations for such dishes
as Kanom Krok (baked coconut milk pudding), Sakoo Sai Gai (steamed
sago balls stuffed with chicken) and Kao Mok Kai (steamed rice
pancake stuffed with chicken).
	   Wenworth Hotel Kuala Lumpur food and beverage manager Denis Ong
said: ``People seem to like Thai food and most restaurants offer
Thai food especially tom yam which is loved by everyone.''
	   Ong said that during the promotion, lucky draws are held for
patrons to its Palms Cafe.
	   The grand prize is a trip to Haadyai, comprising an air ticket
and accommodation at Central Sukhontha Hotel, and American buffet
breakfast for two persons.
	   Other prizes include free stays at Wenworth Hotel.
	   The buffet lunch or dinner is priced at RM30 for adults and
RM16.50 for children aged four to 12.
	   Buffet high tea is priced at RM18 for adults and RM13 for
children aged four to 12.
	   For more details, call 03-9833888 ext 143.
	   
