<SLUG> SIMPLIFY-CUSTOMS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Simplify Customs procedures, Apec panel urged, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Simplify Customs procedures, Apec panel urged, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Tan Chin SiangASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Apec Sub-committee on Customs Procedures needs to work more
closely with the business sector in order to facilitate trade flow
among member countries.
	   Sarawak's Finance and Public Utilities Minister Datuk Dr George
Chan Hong Nam said he was surprised to learn recently that to
effect clearance from Customs was ``no easy task and existing
procedures were somewhat cumbersome.''
	   Information and statistics available showed that to effect
clearance from Customs involved, on the average, 27 to 30 parties,
40 documents, 200 data elements (some of which were overlapping)
and between 60 to 70 per cent of re-keying of data at least once.
	   ``There is an urgent need for us to get our act together and to
spare those dealing with Customs and authorities in the clearance
of imported goods, the painful and sometimes frustrating
experience.
	   ``What is needed is a partnership between the parties involved
so that we can work towards a win-win situation,'' he said.
	   Dr Chan, who is also Deputy Chief Minister and Minister for
Social Development, said this when opening the second session of
the Apec Sub- committee on Customs Procedures in Kuching yesterday.
	   Among those present at the three-day function were the deputy
director- general of Customs Malaysia Madehi Koleh, Sarawak's state
director of Customs Frankie Nyamboi, and about 80 officers from the
18 Apec member countries.
	   On the economic problems in Asia, Dr Chan said in today's
increasingly borderless economy, economic problems in one nation
could spread to its neighbours as well.
	   He said what followed ever since the Thai baht nosedived in July
last year was a clear manifestation of the need for the region to
strengthen and enhance its economic co-operation.
	   ``There is an urgent need for countries in the region to
seriously work out new economic strategies and work together to
combat the economic attacks staged by giant economic syndicates.''
	   Dr Chan said the more advanced economies should also co-operate
and perovide assistance to ensure an early economic recovery of the
affected countries because the economic turmoil would eventually
affect them as well.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
