<SLUG> TIMBER-PRODUCTS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Timber products likely to net RM13.2b, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Timber products likely to net RM13.2b, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   EARNINGS from the export of timber products are anticipated to
decrease slightly in the first quarter of this year, judging from
the industry's sluggish performance since July last year.
	   ``We forecast the total earnings to fall to RM13.2 billion for
the first three or four months (of this year),'' Primary Industries
Minister Datuk Seri Dr Lim Keng Yaik said in Kuala Lumpur
yesterday.
	   Last year, earnings from timber products totalled RM14.7
billion, up six per cent from RM13.89 billion in 1996.
	   Conversely, palm oil exports are expected to bring in RM18.6
billion.
	   Last year earnings from the commodity totalled RM12.7 billion.
	   Dr Lim said this after chairing a dialogue with representatives
from the Malaysian Panel Products Manufacturers Association, Panel
Products of Sarawak Timber Association and Sabah Timber Industries
Association.
	   In the two-hour meeting, several issues were raised by the
associations, including the effect of the region's economic
slowdown and weak ringgit on the plywood market.
	   The price of a three-millimetre plywood, for instance, has
dropped to US$240 per cubic metre from US$420 per cubic metre last
year.
	   ``Some of the millers are facing difficulties in exporting
plywood because they cannot export at that price. (Due to the
problems) I was informed that most of the `big' millers are losing
some RM1 million a month.''
	   Besides the plunge in plywood prices, Dr Lim said exporters also
had to contend with high freight charges.
	   He cited the rates at Ston Port, in the United Kingdom, which
had increased to US$1,100 (about RM3,900) per TEUs (twenty-foot
equivalent units) from US$950 per TEUs.
	   The associations had also asked that the interest rate of the
Export Credit Refinancing scheme be reduced to the 1984 level of
4.5 per cent.
	   ``They found the current rate of 10.8 per cent too high,'' said
Dr Lim, adding that the associations would submit a proposal to the
Finance Ministry on this.
	   Dr Lim said the associations were confident of increasing the
volume of plywood orders by 30 per cent, if the interest rate was
reduced.
	   Deputy Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim had last month
announced that the Government had increased the allocation for
credit facilities to RM4 billion from less than RM2 billion
previously.
	   Of this, RM3 billion would be channelled through the ECR scheme,
which was managed by Exim Bank and made available through all
banks.
	   Some RM1 billion more would be in the form of Exim Bank
supplier, buyer and overseas investment credit facilities.
	   Modelled after South Korea's trade financing facilities, the ECR
scheme was introduced in 1977. Exim Bank took over its management
from Bank Negara in January, last year.
	   
</TEXT>
