<HEADLINE>
Acetai set for 20pc sales growth this year, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Acetai set for 20pc sales growth this year, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ACETAI Corporation Sdn Bhd, the manufacturing and marketing arm
of biscuits manufacturer Hwa Tai Industries Bhd, is confident of
achieving a 20 per cent growth in sales this year in view of the
continued good demand in the local food-based industry.
	   Last year, Acetai recorded a RM60 million sales.
	   Managing director Denny Teh Chin Chye yesterday said the
company's confidence of meeting the target was reflected in the
recent expansion of its manufacturing facilities in Batu Pahat,
Johor.
	   ``We spent about RM10 million to install the latest equipment
and machinery at the plant which will make it more efficient and
cost- effective,'' he said, without disclosing further details of
the plant.
	   Teh was speaking to reporters after the signing of a
distributorship agreement between Acetai and Japan-based Meiji Milk
Products Co. Ltd in Kuala Lumpur.
	   The signing ceremony was witnessed by Housing and Local
Government Minister Datuk Dr Ting Chew Peh.
	   Acetai has been appointed the sole distributor of Meiji Milk's
range of milk products in the country.
	   Meiji Milk is one of the largest companies in the dairy-based
manufacturing industry in Japan. It posted sales turnover of more
than RM16 billion last year and 10 per cent of this came from its
milk products business.
	   Acetai will be distributing the latter's infant formula milk
powder at its extensive sales network of 12,000 nationwide. It is
considering manufacturing the products locally.
	   ``But this will only happen in the long term,'' Teh said.
	   He said Acetai hopes to capture a five per cent share in the
infant milk market in the country, estimated to be around RM6
million annually, in the first 12 months.
	   
