<SLUG> BC-UN-Angola,0469 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Security Council moves toward new, tough sanctions against UNITA,
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ROBERT H. REID &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Urged by the U.N. special representative
in Angola, the Security Council moved Friday to impose new
sanctions against UNITA to punish the former rebel movement for
failing to meet its obligations under a peace plan.
	   The three nations overseeing the Angolan peace process _ the
United States, Russia and Portugal _ reached agreement late
Thursday on a draft resolution which would freeze UNITA's foreign
bank accounts, ban the purchase of diamonds mined in UNITA areas
and prohibit most contacts with officials in regions where the
central government is not in control.
	   UNITA is believed to earn up to a half a billion dollars a year
from diamond sales. Subject to Security Council approval, those
measures would take effect June 25 unless UNITA relinquishes
control of certain key areas, including Bailundo, Andulo, Mungo and
Nharea.
	   At the council's morning session, however, council President
Antonio Monteiro of Portugal announced that several members had put
forward ``considerable'' amendments and supplementary proposals.
	   The council was to resume meeting Friday afternoon to see
whether all 15 members could agree on a final text. It was unclear
when a vote could be taken.
	   Under the 1994 peace agreement, signed in Lusaka, Zambia, UNITA
_ a Portuguese acronym for the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola _ agreed to hand back to the government the
entire 50 percent of the country it seized during the civil war.
	   UNITA also agreed to demobilize its fighters and integrate them
into the national army in return for a role in the government. But
implementation has been slow, and the United Nations blames UNITA
for most of the delays.
	   Last October, the Security Council imposed air and travel
sanctions against UNITA, in addition to an oil and weapons embargo
in effect since 1993.
	   The U.N. special representative to Angola, Alioune Blondin Beye,
asked the council last Friday to crack down on UNITA. Diplomatic
sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said he threatened to
resign if the council failed to take strong action.
	   Beye said earlier this month that UNITA was hiding armed men in
remote areas of the vast southwest African nation, despite the
movement's pledge that it demobilized its 70,000-strong guerrilla
army. UNITA has denied the allegation.
	   UNITA fought a civil war for nearly two decades against the
government following Angola's 1975 independence from Portugal. An
estimated 500,000 people died in the continent's longest civil war
before the government and UNITA signed the 1994 peace accord.
</TEXT>
