<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Japan,0292 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Japan subdued in Toulouse ahead of opening match
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By YURI KAGEYAMA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TOULOUSE, France (AP) _ World Cup excitement has yet to hit the
Japanese team, who arrived Friday in Toulouse for their first game
in their first World Cup.
	   ``My players are great. They aren't nervous, but their
concentration isn't down either,'' coach Takeshi Okada said after
practice in a suburban stadium, held behind closed doors as has
been standard recently.
	   ``There's no change from when we were in Aix-Les-Bains,'' said
defender Akira Narahashi, 26, referring to the resort-town training
camp that the team left earlier in the day.
	   ``When the game approaches closer, then maybe my excitement will
grow,'' 26-year-old midfielder Hiroaki Morishima said. ``If I came
this far, I'd sure like to stand on the pitch.''
	   Okada is not announcing the lineup to his players until right
before the game against Argentina Sunday because ``they already
know,'' he said.
	   Reporters were allowed to catch the last 15 minutes of practice,
when the forwards and midfielders were shooting and a couple of
defenders were going over heading.
	   In the closed session, the team went over their strategies for
the last time, Okada said.
	   Okada has said Japan plans to play a more defensive game, using
a tight one-on-one defense, and going for a counterattack when the
opportunity arises.
	   ``Now, I have nothing to do,'' Okada said. ``I did everything I
can do.''
	   The team will practice right at the World Cup stadium Saturday.
But it will be a light routine to prepare for the match, which is
sure to be a historic one for Japan, win or lose.
</TEXT>
