<BODY>
<SLUG> USE-PROPER-SITE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`Use proper site management', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
`Use proper site management', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE contractor carrying out work to upgrade Jalan Gasing from
four lanes to six will be asked to implement proper project site
management to ensure better traffic flow in the area.
	   Petaling Jaya Municipal Council engineering department head
Abdul Haq Abdul Hamid said the contractor did not carry out the
project in phases but excavated the entire stretch from the Jalan
Changgai junction to near Jalan Templer roundabout in one go.
	   This resulted in earth spilling onto the road, large pipes
placed in front of homes and traffic congestion which has irked
residents in the area.
	   He was speaking at a Press conference after meeting with
residents, headed by David Boler and Petaling Jaya Selatan MP
Donald Lim over the issue at the engineering department at Menara
PJ in Petaling Jaya yesterday.
	   Abdul Haq said the contractor had numerous problems with service
utility companies which took too long to remove or realign their
cables, resultingin unnecessary delay.
	   The council is in the process of widening Jalan Gasing from
Jalan Changgai to the Jalan Templer roundabout to a three-lane dual
carriageway.
	   The council also plans to cover drains along the road to prevent
water from overflowing.
	   The residents had earlier brought up three major points for
discussion, one of which was to expedite the project which started
in January and is expected to be completed before the Commonwealth
Games.
	   Abdul Haq said residents had also asked the council to
reconsider using all six lanes as this would limit movement in and
out of their homes.
	   They have asked the council to reserve a lane on each side of
the road as an emergency lane.
	   He said the council would open only two lanes for traffic and
leave one lane for local traffic such as residents reversing out of
their homes and for school buses to wait for students.
	   Residents also asked that a tonnage limit be set for heavy
vehicles such as lorries.
	   Abdul Haq said the residents' suggestions would be taken into
consideration and discussed at the next Traffic Committee meeting.
	   
</TEXT>
