<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Albanian militants kill Serb policemen near Kosovo capital
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES in graf 3 with one ethnic Albanian reported killed,
seven villages said under attack; changes sourcing on 15,000
fighters. TRIMS. &QL; 
 &UR; By ISMET HAJDARI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Ethnic Albanian militants, boldly
stepping up their attacks, killed two Serb policemen just a few
miles from Kosovo's capital and on Friday said they command 15,000
fighters across the secessionist province.
	   Fighting between Serbian forces and the militants erupted again
in the Decani region in western Kosovo, close to the border with
Albania. It was a Serbian offensive there last week that prompted
NATO Thursday to announce a show of air power to persuade Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic to halt such assault.
	   Ethnic Albanian sources claimed that seven villages in the
Decani area were under attack Friday, including from grenade
launchers normally issued to the Yugoslav army. They said one
Albanian, named as Rexhep Mazrekaj, 38, was killed.
	   There was no independent confirmation of their report, but the
state-run Tanjug news agency in Belgrade reported that a Serb
policeman was seriously hurt in what it called an attack by ``armed
Albanian terrorists'' near one of the villages, Prilep.
	   Ethnic Albanians outnumber Serbs nine-to-one in Kosovo. Most
seek independence from Serbia, which in 1989 stripped the province
of broad autonomy and has ruled repressively since. More than 250
people have been killed since Serbian police started a crackdown
against Albanian militants in March.
	   Serb sources in the province said two policemen where killed and
one was seriously wounded in an overnight ambush by separatists
near Obilic, just 7 kilometers (4.3 miles) northwest of the
provincial capital Pristina. Ethnic Albanian sources claimed one
Albanian was wounded in the same incident.
	   According to other information reaching Pristina, separatists
control a stretch of road near Suva Reka, 40 kilometers (25 miles)
southwest of the capital, severing its link to the key trading town
of Prizren near the Albanian border.
	   Albanian sources further reported Serb attacks on villages in
the Obilic and adjacent Vucitrn regions, saying residents fled and
spent the night under open skies.
	   The ethnic Albanian daily Bujku reported Friday five ethnic
Albanians and seven Serbs were killed in clashes Thursday in Suvo
Grlo in the Drenica area 30 kilometers (20 miles) west of Pristina.
	   Bujku said the fighting was fierce, with villagers determined to
``resist to the end with the help of the KLA.''
	   NATO is planning simulated air attacks in Albania and Macedonia,
adjoining Kosovo, to try and persuade Milosevic to halt military
action.
	   On Friday, Western foreign ministers met in London with their
Russian counterpart to step up pressure. Britain, which is weighing
a United Nations' move to back use of NATO force in Kosovo, called
on Milosevic to pull back his troops immediately.
	   The United States, Canada, Britain, France, Italy and Germany
said they would ``take steps to ban'' flights by Yugoslav Airlines,
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said.
	   Kosovo Albanians welcomed the NATO moves. Nobody in former
Yugoslavia proved able to strike Milosevic, said Eroll Haxhiu, 46,
selling jewelry in Pristina market. ``America can and should do
it.''
	   Members of Kosovo's Serb minority _ whom Milosevic promised to
protect when taking power in Serbia in 1987 _ were alternately
gloomy and defiant.
	   Leaders ``ruined the good country we had (old Yugoslavia), and
they will ruin this one too,'' said Vasilje Stefanovic, a pensioner
from Prizren. ``We are to blame for everything that is happening.
We deserve it.''
	   ``If they attack us, they'll be attacking a sovereign country,''
said Jovan Banjanin, 40, who declined to state his occupation. ``We
will have to defend ourselves, and this has nothing to do with the
Albanian issue.''
	   Ethnic Albanian media in Kosovo on Friday carried a statement
from the Kosovo Liberation Army _ the main militant group _
demanding it get a new war tax to be levied on Kosovo Albanians
working abroad to fund the fight against the Serbs.
	   The KLA, a shadowy group which first emerged in 1996, named
Jakup Krasniqi, 47, a teacher from the Drenica region, as its
spokesman. According to the Albanian state news agency ATA, it said
it commands 15,000 fighters Kosovo-wide.
	   (ih/str/kk/as)
</TEXT>
