<SLUG> PERAK-HOPES-FOR-NO-HITCH sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Perak hopes for no hitch in Manjung power plant, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Perak hopes for no hitch in Manjung power plant, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Zubaidah Abu BakarASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PERAK hopes the proposed ``take-over'' of Tenaga Nasional
Berhad's wholly- owned subsidiary TNB Janamanjung Sdn Bhd by
Malakoff Bhd will not slow down work on the coal-fired independent
power plant in Manjung, Perak.
	   Menteri Besar Tan Sri Ramli Ngah Talib said the State Government
is not questioning the deal but, ``our utmost concern is to ensure
proposed development programmes for the area proceeded as planned.
	   ``They (Janamanjung) had committed to build a 2001MW power plant
in Manjung. We hope the plan will be carried out smoothly,'' he
said in Ipoh yesterday.
	   Speaking after launching the State-level Bank Simpanan Nasional
Employees Savings Scheme, Ramli said although the State Government
believed that work on the IPP would not be affected, it would
monitor the development.
	   ``We are monitoring and would extend our help, in terms of
facilitating construction of buildings, land reclamation works and
other arising problems.''
	   The State Government, Ramli said, would co-ordinate work to
ensure its success as the project costing close to RM7 billion is
one single biggest investment in Perak in several years and would
become a catalyst for social and economic growth in and around the
area.
	   In a Memorandum of Understanding signed on Tuesday and which is
expected to be concluded within two months, Tenaga proposed to
inject its entire stake in TNB Janamanjung to Malakoff.
	   The power plant, the first coal-fired power plant project using
the pulverised fuel-firing technology, is said to be the biggest
such plant which has an IPP structure.
	   It will be built on 254ha of the 320ha reclaimed land in Teluk
Penchalang. Of the 254ha, 70ha is for the power plant and 175ha for
the ash pond. The remainder will be used as port facilities, coal
stockpiles and common access road.
	   The first stage of the project which will generate 700MW is
expected to begin commercial operation on June 1, 2001, with
subsequent units of 700MW to be generated in November 2001 and June
2002.
	   Construction is scheduled to commence in September.
	   The project will be conducted on a turnkey basis with
participation of up to 40 per cent local contractors.
	   
</TEXT>
