<SLUG> WEEDING-OUT-BACKYARD sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Weeding out backyard food makers, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Weeding out backyard food makers, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   IN the light of the recent cholera alert, the Petaling Jaya
Municipal Council is going all out to close down backyard food
manufacturers.
	   Kampung Tunku State Assemblyman Khoo Ooi Seng said the council's
Health Department would be carrying out a door-to-door operation
soon to nab offenders.
	   ``They are producing food under unhygienic conditions near
toilets and drains.
	   ``We want to avoid the outbreak of diseases, especially with the
Commonwealth Games around the corner,'' he said after attending the
council's Health Committee meeting yesterday.
	   Khoo said the manufacturers were involved in supplying food such
as cendol, pau, ice-cream and pickled fruits.
	   He said they would be moved to a hawker centre which was not
popular with the public.
	   ``They have to be relocated to a more suitable place. We can
allow them to operate in unpopular hawker centres like the one in
Damansara Kim,''
	   Khoo said.
	   He said by centralising the food producers, the council would be
able to monitor the level of hygiene at their businesses.
	   He said the council would concentrate on homes in Old Town which
have been identified by the Health Department as being premises for
backyard manufacturers.
	   On the supply of water to hawker centres, Khoo said the council
would be providing metered water supply soon to the Jalan Othman
centre and another in Seri Setia.
	   He said the service would be extended to at least 200 hawkers
who would have to pay individual water bills.
	   Khoo said the council had approved 64 new business applications
for various trades such as restaurants, offices and workshops.
	   
</TEXT>
