<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Honors, HFR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Stage sirs: Knighthoods for Ian Holm and David Hare
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: EMBARGOED for release at 2301 GMT Friday, time set by source &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Actor Ian Holm and playwright David Hare are the
latest knights of the English stage. Both received knighthoods in
the queen's birthday honors list announced Saturday.
	   Nobel Peace Prize-winner Joseph Rotblat, a nuclear scientist who
became an anti-nuclear activist, also was made a knight, as were
John Mortimer, creator of ``Rumpole of the Bailey,'' and conductor
John Eliot Gardiner, a maverick whose prodigious output includes
more than 150 recordings and the founding of several musical
bodies.
	   Stage director Peter Brook was made a Companion of Honor, an
exclusive order for people who have done ``conspicuous national
service.'' In more than a half-century of stage work, Brook has won
praise for classics, as well as experimental theater. His films
include ``Lord of the Flies'' in 1963 and ``Meetings With
Remarkable Men'' in 1978.
	   In the business world, a knighthood went to British Broadcasting
Corp. director-general John Birt and Sir Colin Marshall, chairman
of British Airways, was made a life peer.
	   Newly knighted actor Ian Holm, 66, received a 1981 Oscar
nomination for his role as an athletics coach in ``Chariots of
Fire,'' played ``King Lear'' this year on stage and television to
critical acclaim.
	   Sir David Hare, the 51-year-old anti-establishment playwright,
has achieved great success in London and on Broadway with a string
of acclaimed plays, including ``Skylight,'' ``Amy's View,'' ``The
Secret Rapture'' and ``Racing Demon.''
	   Wtiter John Mortimer, a lawyer, used his inside view of the
legal profession to create the irascible ``Rumpole,'' whose
popularity in novel form spread internationally with a successful
television version.
	   It was a very good year for honors in all areas of the arts.
	   In addition to the knights, Peter Cattaneo, director of
Britain's hit movie ``The Full Monty,'' received an MBE, or Member
of the Order of British Empire honor, as did jazz singer Carol Kidd
and Northern Ireland poet and playwright Damian Gorman.
	   Christopher Bruce, artistic director of the Rambert Dance
Company, got a CBE, or Commander of the Order of British Empire,
and so did cellist Steven Isserlis and biographer Victoria
Glendinning.
	   Writer Terry Pratchett, author of a series of comic fantasies,
received an OBE, or Officer of the Order of British Empire.
	   The government, which chooses the awards _ which numbered almost
1,000 this year _ included 175 people connected with health and
associated voluntary organizations to mark the 50th anniversary of
Britain's free National Health Service.
	   The honors are announced on the monarch's ``official'' birthday,
always a Saturday in June when military parades are held. The
queen's own birthday is April 21.
	   In descending order, the honors are life peerage, knighthoods,
CBE, MBE and OBE. The Companion of Honor is an exclusive and highly
prized award limited to 65 people at any one time.
	   (rb-acw-kg)
</TEXT>
