w1635 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  Y2K-SOLUTIONS-FIRMsked     06-12 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> Y2K-SOLUTIONS-FIRM sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Y2K solutions firm sees turnover going up 30pc, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Y2K solutions firm sees turnover going up 30pc, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   GROWING awareness among Malaysian companies of the Millennium
Bug or the Y2K problem will benefit the information
technology-based Jen Group of companies which has already secured
RM10 million worth of work in this area.
	   The Jen group is an IT resource provider with capabilities in
systems integration, project management, software services,
recruitment of IT professionals as well as Y2K solutions.
	   It expects its turnover to go up by more than 30 per cent this
year to RM20 million from RM15 million last year.
	   The Petaling Jaya-based group is 100 per cent Malaysian-owned
and is made up of Jen Software Professional (JSP) Sdn Bhd, Jen
Consulting Services (JCS) Sdn Bhd and JSP Consulting Sdn Bhd.
	   The RM10 million worth of Y2K-related projects will be carried
out by JCS which also projected turnover from similar projects to
rise to RM30 million in the near future.
	   According to managing director Ang Kim Jhew, many Malaysian
companies have yet to address the Y2K problem effectively although
there are just as many which are addressing the problem, either
through in-house solutions or external expertise.
	   Y2K refers to the inability of earlier computer programmes to
recognise the Year 2000 as they use two digits to denote the year.
Calculations and time-sensitive functions will be in disarray if
the problem is not corrected.
	   JCS, a member of Pikom, licensed the Y2K methodology from Data
Dimensions, an American company which developed the methodology in
1991 and has used it to help 30 Fortune 500 companies seek
solutions to the Y2K problem.
	   ``Our staff at JCS are fully trained and well versed in the
methodology.
	   ``While we do not sell the methodology to companies seeking
assistance for the Y2K problem, we offer the services of our
trained staff.
	   ``Besides that, we conduct Y2K `Health Checks' where we carry
out complete reviews of all activities of a company and identify
areas where they are lacking in reaching Y2K compliance,'' said
Ang.
	   Philip Teh of JCS added that the company also examines the
``supply chain integrity'' of a company seeking Y2K compliance.
	   For instance, a large manufacturing concern depends on smaller
companies or vendors to supply parts.
	   So while the large company is Y2K compliant, its suppliers or
vendors may not be and that will cause a lot of problems.
	   The group, with clients ranging from the financial, oil and gas,
insurance, telcos and manufacturing sectors noted that since early
this year, the momentum has been picking up steadily with more
companies seeking Y2K compliance.
	   ``We attribute it to increasing awareness of the problem through
increasing publicity and government efforts, especially in the
financial sector.
	   ``For instance, Bank of Commerce Bhd, which is our client, has
been very proactive in seeking compliance.
	   ``Publicly-listed companies are also very proactive,'' said Ang.
	   In anticipation of more Y2K-related projects, Jen Group will be
hiring an extra 40 staff by the end of this year, bringing the
total staff strength to 250, from the modest 10 it started with in
1991.
	   Ang said small conversion projects to reach compliance may take
between three and four months while larger conversion projects may
take up to nine months. ``Health checks'' take one month to
complete.
	   Jen Software Professional, which adopted the System,
Applications and Products (SAP), a German business application
software, is the only SAP company in Malaysia to have operations in
Penang.
	   On the outlook of its IT recruitment business, Ang said the
economic slowdown had affected it by 40 per cent but this has been
off-set by clients seeking to outsource work since they do not have
the staff strength to carry out the work internally.
	   Ang was quick to point out that there were still a lot of
IT-related jobs in the country and refuted claims that there was a
surplus of IT professionals in Malaysia.
	   He added that the country needs more such people and there was a
general shortage being experienced overseas.
	   The group is looking into the possibility of either being listed
on the Second Board of the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange or on the
Malaysian Exchange of Securities Dealing and Automated Quotation
(Mesdaq) in a year's time.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:Y2K-SOLUTIONS-FIRM sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
