<HEADLINE>
Guthrie puts investment in real estate on hold, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Guthrie puts investment in real estate on hold, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Long Hui ChingASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUMPULAN Guthrie Bhd has successfully raised US$500 million
(about RM2 billion) for the Guthrie-Koll Fund, for the purpose of
investing in real estate in Malaysia.
	   However, due to the current economic slump, it will wait for the
right time to enter the market. The fund was intially expected to
be launched at the end of this year.
	   The Guthrie-Koll fund was jointly created and is managed by
Guthrie in collaboration with the Nasdaq-listed Koll Real Estate
Group of the United States.
	   Investors in the fund are medium-sized companies from the US.
Monies from the fund will be used to invest in properties here for
the medium- term, which will then be leased to American companies
operating in Malaysia.
	   These properties are expected to be those in need of financial
assistance.
	   Speaking after Guthrie Ropel Bhd's annual meeting in Kuala
Lumpur yesterday, chairman Tan Sri Abdul Khalid Ibrahim said the
fund will wait for the currency and property prices to stabilise
before investing.
	   As for Guthrie Ropel, based on its performance in the first
three months of this year, and the current high prices of palm oil,
Abdul Khalid expressed optimism of improved results for this year.
	   It has not embarked on plans to go into property development
although last year, the group voiced intentions to do so and went
to authorities in Johor for approval.
	   However, the process of planning and getting approvals will
continue.
	   ``It is unlikely that this year, we will embark on property
development, but will concentrate on rubber and palm oil
production,'' he said.
	   Commenting on the current low price of natural rubber in the
market, Abdul Khalid said it was time for the Government to review
the supply and demand for natural rubber since there is currently
an opportunity to improve its prices.
	   One way to do this is to either reduce the stock pile of rubber,
or remove the control over prices in the international market.
	   He added that Malaysia, a member of the International Natural
Rubber Organisation, should think about its independence in
controlling rubber prices.
	   Inro, which groups natural rubber producers and consumers,
attempts to stabilise prices within a band primarily through the
operation of a buffer stock. It buys natural rubber from the market
to support prices when they are too low and sells from the
stockpile to contain high prices.
	   Thailand, Indonesia and Malaysia are the top three natural
rubber producing countries while Inro's major importing members are
the United States, China and the European Union.
	   Last month, Primary Industries Minister Datuk Seri Dr Lim Keng
Yaik said he and his Thai and Indonesian counterparts hoped to look
into the stand of the consuming countries within Inro, which had
been less than accommodating to producers' request for better
natural rubber prices.
	   Dr Lim said although the three major natural rubber producing
countries had faced significant currency depreciation, natural
rubber prices were in fact cheaper in terms of US dollars and
European currencies now than a year ago.
	   Dr Lim also expressed Malaysia's disappointment at Inro over its
inability to support natural rubber prices at fair and equitable
levels.
	   Abdul Khalid said if the price of natural rubber is allowed to
reflect supply and demand, it will also reflect the currency
fluctuation.
	   Asserting that Malaysia should have independence in controlling
its rubber price, he said Malaysia was not only a producer of
natural rubber but also a consumer.
	   ``The idea of Inro is to protect the manufacturers of
non-producing nations. Since Malaysia is both producer and
consumer, it is not necessary for it to protect only the
manufacturers of rubber products.
	   ``It is in the best interest of Malaysia to allow rubber prices
to find its own level,'' he said.
	   Guthrie is in favour of the free float of rubber prices as this
will indicate the real demand for rubber. Producers will also be
able to decide whether to continue producing rubber or not.
	   On edible oil, Abdul Khalid said the demand is expected to
continue to increase.
	   He said the situation in Pakistan and India may result in both
countries being unable to buy soybean oil from the US, in which
case, it may be good news for palm oil producers.
	   
</TEXT>
