<HEADLINE>
Domestic tourism `catalyst to industry's recovery', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Domestic tourism `catalyst to industry's recovery', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   GENTING HIGHLANDS, Thurs. - Domestic tourism should act as the
catalyst for the overall recovery of the tourism industry in the
country, Culture, Arts and Tourism Minister Datuk Sabbaruddin Chik
said today.
	   He said the domestic tourism was a ``natural'' and readily
available market which would boost job opportunities in the
industry.
	   ``While more effort and money is needed to promote tourism at
the international level, promotion of domestic tourism can be done
rather easily,'' Sabbaruddin said when opening the Seri Malaysia
Hotel Genting at Goh Tong Jaya near here.
	   The minister also launched the Seri Malaysia Hotels website that
provides information on the chain's 16 hotels.
	   He urged local tour operators and hotels to help promote
domestic tourism by offering attractive packages and discounts in a
bid to stem the outflow of the ringgit by Malaysians going on
foreign tours.
	   Later at a Press conference, Sabbaruddin said the accommodation
sector of the tourism trade was an important component and last
year accounted for 35 per cent of the industry's RM10.5 billion
foreign exchange earnings.
	   ``In this regard it is important that those providing
accommodation give their best and get co-operation from others to
better this achievement,''
	   he said.
	   The Culture, Arts and Tourism Ministry's secretary-general Datuk
Ismail Adam, who is also chairman of Rangkaian Hotel Seri Malaysia
Sdn Bhd which owns the chain said last year, it registered an
average occupancy of 59.83 per cent.
	   ``Of this 88 per cent were Malaysians which is very good and in
line with our objective to provide quality and well-priced products
for domestic tourists,'' Ismail said.
	   
</TEXT>
