<HEADLINE>
S. Korean outlook `negative', BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
S. Korean outlook `negative', BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Francis FernandezASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THOMSON BankWatch has altered the outlook for South Korea's BBB
rating to ``negative'' from ``stable''.
	   Its director of sovereign risk analysis, Ms Betty J. Starkey,
said the economic outlook for South Korea appears to be worsening
and the timetable for a turnaround is likely to be further delayed.
	   She said the recently released figures for first quarter 1998
gross domestic product (GDP) growth revealed that the economy
contracted by 3.8 per cent, more sharply than most forecasts, and
the downturn is made worse by the occurrence of stagflation as
inflation looks set to over take previous estimates of 6.7 per
cent, reaching levels of 10 per cent or higher by the year-end.
	   Export growth slowed down for the first time in five months in
May, as exporters started to feel the effects of the steadily
weakening yen and a domestic credit crunch.
	   The declining yen poses a serious threat since nearly half of
all South Korean exports, namely in the car, shipbuilding, steel
and semiconductor sectors, compete against Japanese goods.
	   Starkey pointed out that high interest rates to defend the
external value of the won has hampered the ability of local firms
to repay their obligations, and the problem is exacerbated by the
very high debt-to- equity of South Korean firms.
	   With an estimate of 20 trillion won worth of bonds maturing this
month alone and the country's short-term domestic obligations being
rolled over, she said banks are unlikely to put up with this
situation for long given their own precarious situation.
	   The worsening short-term economic outlook appears to have
prompted the Government to ease its previous tough stance on
reforms, with banks being allowed to give loans to struggling firms
while some prominent chaebols have been propped up despite their
massive bad debts.
	   Reflecting the worsening outlook, the Kospi stock market index
fell to an 11-year low in the last week of May while spreads on
South Korean sovereign bonds issued in early April are trading
recently at around 415 basis point above the US Treasury notes.
	   Accordingly, foreigners are still reluctant to enter South
Korean markets and the economic downturn will likely continue
through the second and third quarters of 1998, Starkey said.
	   However in the midst of the generally depressed economic
picture, foreign currency reserves have risen steadily, quadrupling
from US$8.9 billion (US$1  &QC;  RM4) at end-1997 to US$38.76 billion at
end-May, while the current account surplus looks set to meet the
target of US$21 billion to US$23 billion, or around 6 per cent of
GDP required by the International Monetary Fund programme.
	   
</TEXT>
