<HEADLINE>
Penang to run course on emergency planning, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Penang to run course on emergency planning, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PENANG, Thurs. - Penang is set to be the second State in the
country after Selangor to train emergency planning and response
experts when it offers a postgraduate degree in the field at the
end of the year.
	   Chief Minister Tan Sri Dr Koh Tsu Koon today said the one-year
masters programme in Emergency Planning and Response jointly
offered by Universiti Putra Malaysia and the Fire and Rescue
Services Department would commence in November.
	   ``This intake can accommodate up to 230 people whose jobs deal
with ocupational health and safety,'' he told reporters after
launching an exhibition in conjunction with the State-level Health
and Industrial Safety Week at the Caring Society Complex.
	   ``We hope this programme will see Penang producing a pool of
emergency response professionals at factories and offices dealing
with the health and safety of workers.''
	   Also present were Fire and Rescue Services Department
director-general Datuk Dr Soh Chai Hock, State Human Resources
Committee chairman Datuk Dr Kang Chin Seng and Universiti Putra
Malaysia's director of technology Dr Mohamed Daud.
	   Soh said the masters course would be held at the Fire and Rescue
Services Department at Seberang Prai for three days every two
weeks.
	   ``A pioneer batch of 21 who are now studying in Kuala Lumpur are
expected to graduate in October,'' he said.
	   Soh, who is also the Malaysian president of the United
Kingdom-based Institute of Fire Engineers, said graduates of the
programme would automatically be made associates of the institute.
	   ``After two years of practice, they will be accorded the status
of a chartered fire engineer in Europe,'' he added.
	   Meanwhile, Mohamed said the course fees were RM7,000, and that
factory managements could sponsor their employees for it.
	   He said entry requirements included: a bachelor's degree in
science, management or engineering and five year's working
experience, or an accredited diploma or completion of other
professional courses and 10 years' working experience.
	   
</TEXT>
