<HEADLINE>
Some 47,000 workers retrenched between July '97 and June '98, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Some 47,000 workers retrenched between July '97 and June '98, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Hamisah HamidASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A TOTAL OF 46,643 workers was retrenched between July last year
and June 6 this year, about 10 months after the financial crisis
hit the region.
	   Of this figure, 11,793 workers were laid off between July and
December 1997 while another 34,850 were laid off between January
and June 6 this year.
	   Local workers made up 86.7 per cent and the rest were foreign
workers, a statement released by the Human Resources Ministry said
yesterday.
	   The majority of the workers retrenched was from the
manufacturing sector, representing 60.5 per cent or 28,223 workers.
	   The Ministry also reported that the number of applications
submitted to the Home Ministry to import foreign workers or
re-deploy them in the manufacturing and plantation sectors
indicates that there are many job opportunities available in the
local labour market.
	   Between February 17 and June 4 this year, the technical
committee at the Home Ministry had approved applications to import
21,763 foreign workers and re-deploy 603 workers for the
manufacturing sector.
	   During the period, the committee received 325 applications for
77,431 foreign workers for the manufacturing and plantation
sectors.
	   For the plantation sector, the committee approved applications
to import 18,088 foreign workers and redeploy 329 workers.
	   According to the statement, the number of active job-seekers
registered with the ministry's Manpower Department between January
and May this year showed a rising trend.
	   The number of vacancies, however, has fluctuated, with a
significant increase between January and March but a decrease in
April, and an increase again in May. Placements for job-seekers
average 1,900 a month.
	   Meanwhile, the weekly retrenchment trend since February this
year showed that the number of workers laid off has decreased since
the third week of March.
	   The weekly average of workers being retrenched is about 1,600
per week.
	   
</TEXT>
