WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   I REFER to the letters by P. Chen and S.V. Vijaythevan (NST, May
21) and to the news report entitled ``Pensioners plead for
continuation of free medication'' (NST, May 25).
	   One of the functions of trade unions is to look after the
welfare of their members regarding fair terms of employment,
equitable wages, and housing and medical benefits.
	   The two umbrella organisations for workers, Cuepacs and the
Malaysian Trades Union Congress, recently made so much fuss over
chicken prices and called for a consumer boycott of the bird. They
are not tired of blowing their own trumpets about the ``success''
of what they ``masterminded''.
	   Now chicken prices are something the workers themselves can take
care of. If the prices are high, and workers don't buy chicken for
a week or two, prices would come down.
	   In the US, for example, housewives have been instrumental in
getting meat prices down - without the need for trade unionists to
``shout''.
	   Comparatively, the issue of medical benefits and medicine prices
is a cause of much concern to workers, particularly pensioners. Yet
the two organisations have not been seen to champion this issue.
	   Cuepacs and MTUC should redeem their ``chicken-feed'' image by
studying the reasons for deteriorating medical benefits coupled
with escalating costs and make appropriate representations to the
Government.
	   The organisations are in the best position to do so as they
represent that large section of the population that keeps the
wheels of the country's economy turning. Not to take good care of
the health of these people is like neglecting proper maintenance of
aircraft - and we know what happens then.
	   
</TEXT>
