<HEADLINE>
United Bintang expects exports to rise, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
United Bintang expects exports to rise, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   RECONDITIONED equipment supplier United Bintang Bhd expects a
further 15 per cent increase in its exports to help offset the
decline in local sales.
	   According to executive director Gary Loh, 15 per cent is a
conservative estimate and the number should actually be higher.
	   ``Before the turmoil started, we had taken steps to go overseas
to do business and we managed to send a lot of stocks to the US,
Canada and Europe,'' Loh said.
	   Loh was speaking to reporters after the group's annual general
meeting in Kuala Lumpur yesterday.
	   He added that the group managed to clear a very substantial
amount of stocks thus far. Existing stock in hand is currently
valued at RM40 million.
	   ``Seventy-five per cent of the existing stocks can be cleared
within this year. After we are finished with selling all of this,
we will embark on further purchases,'' he said.
	   United Bintang already has sales offices in the US and Canada.
It is intending to open another office in Dubai as soon as sales
are recorded.
	   Dubai is hoped to be its gateway to supplying reconditioned
equipments to Iran, Iraq and South Africa.
	   ``We hope the volume of business will increase tremendously with
our export ventures. We are at a starting point and after adapting
ourselves to the business environment, volume will increase in a
few years,'' Loh said.
	   The group is eyeing the US as its main export market as the
weakened ringgit will provide currency gains to United Bintang.
	   For the 1997 financial year, total value of exports was RM31
million.
	   Exports contribute some 80 per cent to United Bintang's sales.
	   Meanwhile, local sales dropped by some 70 per cent. However, Loh
is confident that the group can at least maintain the current level
of profitability.
	   United Bintang registered a pre-tax profit of RM3.81 million for
the financial year ended December 31 1997 compared with RM7.57
million in 1996.
	   Its turnover fell 31 per cent to RM89.91 million from RM129.6
million previously. After-tax profit dropped 54 per cent to RM2.38
million from RM5.15 million in 1996.
	   
</TEXT>
