<BODY>
<SLUG> PEOPLE-WANT-CHANCE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
People want chance to voice their grievances, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
People want chance to voice their grievances, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Martin JallehASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PEOPLE in the Klang Valley are suffering. They have no water.
Some have no more strength to wait in line and to carry water into
lifts or up flights of steps.
	   They do not have enough water to bathe and to flush their
toilets. The whole thing really stinks (literally too). Not only
are they short of water, but much-needed answers, too.
	   The only thing that the public is not short of, and which they
do not need at all, is the growing realisation of the many
shortcomings of those in charge - bureaucrats whose many
explanations have often held no water.
	   Instead of regular buckets of water, the public has to contend
with the buck-passing of officials, who, very often, water down the
sufferings of the people with their many misplaced assurances.
	   Unbelievably, not only have the people been deprived of constant
water supply, they have also been denied of an opportunity to voice
their frustrations and to demand accountability from the powers
that be. A public forum (which was very much a people's initiative)
to discuss the water crisis had to be called off.
	   The organisers had made it very clear that they had no political
agenda.
	   The relevant authorities had been invited to present their views
and to provide much needed clarification. There was really nothing
to hide.
	   In fact, the Press had reported on June 1 that the Selangor
Waterworks Department had asked for help from non-governmental
organisations to disseminate information on the water crisis and to
provide feedback - the forum, could, therefore, have been an
excellent opportunity.
	   The response of Selangor Menteri Besar Datuk Abu Hassan Omar
was, to say the least, very disappointing. A letter from his office
was sent to the organisers of the public forum requesting them to
cancel the forum.
	   If Abu Hassan was really convinced that the forum ``would
confuse the public'' he could have seized the opportunity to send
his men there to ensure that clarity be the order of the day.
	   Sad to say, once again the public has been made to appear the
fool and portrayed as being incapable of engaging in an intelligent
discussion over an issue which has drastically affected their daily
lives.
	   Public participation, feedback and criticism should be given a
place in society. The right to dissent is very much a part of the
democratic process.
	   People are more educated now. They are more aware of their
rights.
	   Surely they deserve more respect from the very people they have
elected.
	   Representatives of the rakyat should encourage public discussion
and debate rather than shy away from, or stop, them.
	   Surely after 40 years of independence our politicians should
expect and allow a greater level of fair comment and a demand for
greater accountability and transparency.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:PEOPLE-WANT-CHANCE sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
