<SLUG> TAKE-OVER-BY-YEAR-END sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
4 outfits to take over by year-end, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
4 outfits to take over by year-end, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Ariff AwangASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   FOUR private companies will take over solid waste management
from 90 local authorities by the end of this year, said Housing and
Local Government Minister Datuk Dr Ting Chew Peh said.
	   The Government had urged the concerned local authorities, Ting
said, to expedite the signing of interim agreements with these
firms and enable the takeover to be carried out in stages.
	   The minister was speaking after witnessing the signing of a
distributorship pact between Meiji Milk Products Co Ltd and Acetai
Corp Sdn Bhd in Kuala Lumpur yesterday.
	   The four companies which will manage solid waste disposal are
Alam Flora Sdn Bhd (a subsidiary of DRB-Hicom Group), Northern
Waste Industries, Southern Waste Management Sdn Bhd and MMC
Engineering.
	   Ting said, ``The interim period (before the takeover is
completed) is good for the companies involved as it gives them the
chance to prove their waste management capabilities.'' The interim
agreements between the local authorities and these companies will
be in effect until the Solid Waste Management and Cleansing Bill
and several other related Bills are passed by Parliament, he added.
	   So far, he said, only three local authorities have signed
interim agreements and these are Kuala Lumpur City Hall (with Alam
Flora in January last year), Johor Baru Tengah District Council and
the Pasir Gudang local authorities (with Southern Waste
Management).
	   Ting said in Sabah and Sarawak, the process of transferring
waste management to MMC Engineering may be slower as the company
has to seek the approval of the state government.
	   
</TEXT>
