w1664 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Tennis-Queens 6thLd-Writethru   06-12 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-Queens, 6th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sampras goes out in Wimbledon warmup
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMS; UPDATES with Sampras quotes; Add last quarterfinal
results

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Just 10 days before Wimbledon begins, Mark
Woodforde detects a lack of motivation in Pete Sampras' game.
	   But Sampras, beaten by the Australian 6-3, 6-2 in a third-round
match Friday on grass at the Queen's Club, begs to differ.
	   ``This tournament has always been a bit of a wake-up call for
me,'' Sampras said. ``I'm disappointed but the main goal is
Wimbledon.''
	   ``You never like losing, but if you take a step back and look at
how I've done at Wimbledon, I've always seemed to put what happened
here behind me.''
	   ``When Wimbledon comes around and I'm on Centre Court, I think
guys know I play pretty well there,'' Sampras added. ``It's nice to
have that on your side. I feel l'm going to be tough to beat, I
really do.''
	   Friday's defeat was the latest surprising loss for the four-time
and defending Wimbledon champion. He has struggled most of the year
and was ousted in the second round of the French Open by
little-known Ramon Delgado of Paraguay.
	   Sampras had beaten the 66th-ranked Woodforde in all of their
previous 10 matches.
	   But this time, Woodforde mixed up his shots, returned well and
often caught Sampras with lobs whenever the American ventured to
the net. But his most effective tactic was to hit a succession of
drop volleys which fell just over the net and left Sampras
stranded.
	   The Australian also served far better than Sampras, hitting
three aces in the opening game to set the tone of the match.
	   In contrast, Sampras produced four double-faults, the last of
which gave Woodforde a break for 3-2 in the second set. A netted
backhand volley then gave Woodforde a second break for 5-2.
	   ``Everyone is aware that, motivation-wise, he's (Sampras) not
there,'' Woodforde said.
	   ``I played a pretty good tight match against him, and he just
wasn't able to pick it up where in the past he was able to take it
up a notch or two,'' said Woodforde, known primarily as a doubles
specialist. ``That's where he is found wanting.''
	   In addition to its top seed, Queen's also lost No. 2 Greg
Rusedski of Britain, who suffered an ankle injury Friday during his
third-round match against Italian qualifier Laurence Tieleman.
	   A doctor and a trainer agreed that U.S. Open runner-up Rusedski
_ ranked No. 4 in the world _ was less than a 50-50 bet to be ready
for Wimbledon.
	   Tournament doctor Johnnie Gaynor said there was no fracture, but
said he had a severe sprain to one of three ligaments.
	   ``It is impossible to tell how long it will take to heal,''
Gaynor said. ``He'll rest for two or three days and then begin
therapy.''
	   ATP trainer Doug Spreen was doubtful.
	   ``There are definitely some question marks about Wimbledon for
Greg,'' he said.
	   With the score at 2-2 in the first set, Rusedski slipped while
stretching for a backhand volley and fell awkwardly with his left
leg buckling beneath him.
	   Rusedski screamed in pain and writhed on the grass before being
carried off the court and taken to a hospital for X-rays.
	   In order to clear up a backlog of matches caused by rain delays,
players Friday played two matches _ third round and quarterfinals _
to get the tournament back on track.
	   Woodforde later reached the Saturday semifinals with a 6-3, 1-6,
6-2 quarterfinal win over Thomas Enqvist of Sweden, seeded No. 8.
	   Also in the quarterfinals, 14th-seeded Byron Black of Zimbabwe
defeated Brian MacPhie of the United States, 7-5, 6-1, and
Australian Scott Draper defeated Doug Flach of the United States
7-6 (9-7), 7-6 (7-5).
	   Italy's Laurence Tieleman ended Britain's hopes in the
tournament with a three set win over No. 7 seed Tim Henman.
	   Tieleman defeated Henman 2-6, 7-6 (7-9), 6-4. Henman had his
winning chances, serving for the match at 5-3 and another match
point at 5-4 in the second set but missed both opportunities.
	   (scw)	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
