<SLUG> AFFIN-PRUDENT-MEASURES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Affin group to adopt prudent measures, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Affin group to adopt prudent measures, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Zety Fazilah BaharuddinASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   AFFIN Holdings Bhd will adopt prudent measures to cushion the
current economic slowdown and not simply focus on its traditional
core business.
	   Managing director Datuk Lodin Wok Kamaruddin says the group will
focus on the productive sectors such as export-oriented activities,
plantation, agriculture and industries of national importance, and
the production of food for future expansion.
	   ``This is in line with the Government's effort to place
financial institutions in the front line of steering the economy
towards a sustainable recovery,'' he says in his annual statement.
	   He adds that the group is also targeting to maintain a moderate
growth for its loan portfolio through the group finance company,
Affin Finance Bhd.
	   It will focus on small and medium-scale enterprises engaged in
manufacturing, and the development and end-financing of low- and
medium- cost houses.
	   He says this is part of its strategies and priorities to
strengthen the group and prepare it to meet the challenges in the
next millennium.
	   Affin posted a group pre-tax profit of RM209 million for the
financial year ended December 31 1997 from RM360 million the
previous year.
	   However, operating revenue increased from RM1.23 billion in 1996
to RM1.80 billion, while profit after tax and zakat was RM105
million compared with RM238.19 million previously.
	   Earnings per share surged substantially from 41.4 sen to 19.2
sen.
	   On the group's financial results, Lodin says major contributions
to the group earnings came from commercial and merchant banking
with 96.5 per cent.
	   This is followed by investment holdings with 9.1 per cent and
general insurance with 2.3 per cent.
	   Meanwhile, the group's banking arm Perwira Affin Bank Bhd (PAB)
registered a pre-tax profit of RM248.50 million, down 17 per cent
compared with RM301 million in 1996.
	   PAB shareholders' fund, however, increased to RM1.40 billion
compared with RM126 million in 1991.
	   The bank's interest-free banking operations completed another
year of growth with income rising from RM12.4 million in 1996 to
RM25.20 million, an increase of 103 per cent.
	   Assets under Islamic banking doubled to RM548 million during the
year under review, making PAB one of the top three banks in
Malaysia offering Islamic banking.
	   Commenting on the drop in PAB''s pre-tax profit despite being
the major contributor to the group earnings, Lodin says it was
attributed mainly to net increase in provisions for bad and
doubtful debts of RM189 million, in compliance with Bank Negara
guidelines.
	   The group's insurance company, Guardian Royal Exchange Assurance
(M) Bhd, posted a pre-tax profit of RM12.78 million, while profits
from investments including realised capital gain were RM3.52
million.
	   Net premium income increased 15.9 per cent to RM98.18 million
from RM84.73 million before.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
