<SLUG> HOTEL-SCORES-A-FIRST sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hotel scores a first with dessert buffet, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Hotel scores a first with dessert buffet, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THEY are not kind to one's waistline but who can resist the
delightful desserts that Etoile Bistro at the Equatorial Kuala
Lumpur is offering?
	   Imagine an unlimited supply of Haagen-Dazs ice-cream, crepes,
Mrs Fields cookies, cakes, savouries and pastries! While buffet
meals have become a standard feature of many restaurants in Kuala
Lumpur, none has yet to offer a dessert buffet.
	   Haagen-Dazs ice-cream flavours offered at the Etoile include
macadamia nut, chocolate chip, maple walnut brandied cherries,
strawberries vanilla and coffee.
	   With a little bit of creativity, one can mix and match the
ingredients at the pastry counter according to one's taste.
	   If one were to buy a pint of Haagen-Dazs outside, it will cost
close to RM20. At any Haagen-Daz outlet, a scoop will cost more
than RM5.50.
	   Basically, there is no way anyone can enjoy Haagen-Dazs
ice-cream as much as he or she likes without thinking about what
it'll do to the wallet! So with this dessert buffet, it is time for
ice-cream fans to rejoice.
	   The dessert buffet is an on-going feature of the bistro and the
hotel.
	   For only RM19.95++, diners can enjoy as many servings of premium
Haagen- Dazs ice-cream, rich Mrs Fields cookies and delicious
crepes, cakes and other pastries.
	   For an additional RM4.90++, one can have as many cups of Java
Coast gourmet coffee signature blend as one likes.
	   The Java Coast, popular among Westerners, especially Americans,
made its debut in the country at the hotel in February.
	   A fine selection of the coffee is available for patrons.
	   Equatorial general manager Donald Lim said: ``People will
realise what an outstanding value the bistro is offering.''
	   He added that the Etoile dessert buffet will appeal to fans of
Haagen- Dazs ice-cream, Mrs Fields cookies, and Java Coast gourmet
coffee.
	   Lim said customers can not only enjoy these brandname desserts,
but also a whole range of other fantastic desserts prepared by
executive chef Jean- Marc Veron and chef de partie Steven Tham.
	   The dessert buffet is available from 7.15pm to 11pm on weekdays
and until 1am on Fridays, Saturdays and Sundays.
	   To avoid disappointment, perhaps it is better to call the bistro
and ask what is available on the menu that evening.
	   Although the outlet can accommodate about 80 persons,
reservations are highly recommended.
	   Etoile Bistro can be reached at 03-2617777 ext 8030.
	   
</TEXT>
