<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Canada-Logging Boycott,0345 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Canadian activists call off seven-year boycott of Japanese firm
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Figures in U.S. dollars. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TORONTO (AP) _ Activists called off a seven-year boycott
campaign against a Japanese paper company Friday after the firm
pledged not to log on land claimed by an Indian tribe until the
disputed claim is settled.
	   Friends of the Lubicon, a Toronto-based group, initiated the
boycott against Daishowa Inc. in 1991 in support of the Lubicon
Indians of northern Alberta. The company said the boycott cost it
dlrs 10 million.
	   The case dates to 1988, when Daishowa reached an agreement with
federal and provincial officials to log about 4,000 square miles
(10,400 square kilometers) of land claimed by the Lubicons.
	   The isolated Indian community contended that no logging rights
should be awarded until its dispute with government authorities was
settled.
	   Diashowa never actually began logging on the disputed land. But
until last month it had antagonized the Indians and activists by
refusing to pledge it would never log there until the land-claims
struggle was resolved.
	   On May 20, a Daishowa executive wrote to the Lubicon chief
pledging to hold off on logging until a land settlement was
reached.
	   This week, company sent the Lubicons a map specifying that the
pledge covered all the disputed land. That was enough for Friends
of the Lubicon to announce that the boycott would end.
	   ``This has to be one of the most successful boycotts in Canadian
history,'' said Friends of the Lubicon spokesman Kevin Thomas.
``Now the Lubicons and their supporters can focus their full
attention on the Canadian govenment's failure to settle the ongoing
land rights dispute.''
	   The boycott was aimed at dissuading stores in Canada and
overseas from buying Daishowa's paper bags. More than 40 companies
changed their bag suppliers.
	   Daishowa won an injunction against the boycott in 1996. An
Ontario judge quashed the injunction in April, saying the boycott
was a legitimate form of political expression.
</TEXT>
