<BODY>
<SLUG> BRITISH-MALAYSIA-SCHEME sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STG300m British-Malaysia Scholarship scheme launched, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
STG300m British-Malaysia Scholarship scheme launched, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Adeline OngASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE British High Commission yesterday officially launched the
British- Malaysia Scholarship Scheme 1998.
	   Under the scheme, 1,583 successful Malaysian applicants will
receive a contribution of up to STG2,000 (approximately RM12,000)
towards their tuition fees to enable them to begin or continue
their studies at universities in the UK in the 1998/99 academic
year.
	   This means a total contribution of up to STG3 million (about
RM20 million) towards the education of Malaysian students in the
UK, British High Commissioner David Moss said yesterday.
	   ``With the fall in the value of the ringgit, there has been
growing concern over the financial hardships faced by Malaysian
students studying in the UK.
	   ``The response from the UK has been tremendous - practically all
British universities have already introduced special measures to
help Malaysian students studying in the UK or those who are about
to commence their studies,'' Moss said at the High Commission in
Kuala Lumpur.
	   He explained that the British Government has also been looking
for ways to help.
	   When the Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs
Derek Fatchett visited Malaysia in March this year, he announced
the British Government's intention to establish a special
scholarship scheme designed to support Malaysian students and other
students from the region.
	   Moss added that the new scholarships will be in addition to the
70 or so Chevening Scholarships already offered to Malaysian
students by the British High Commission each year.
	   Core funding for the scheme has been made available by the
Foreign and Commonwealth office. Additional funds have also been
contributed by the British Council, who will coordinate the scheme,
the Department of Trade and Industry and many British companies.
	   Matching funds are also being provided by participating British
universities, who will administer the scheme.
	   ``We attach a great deal of importance to Malaysian students
continuing to study in Britain. As the largest body of overseas
students in the UK, the contribution they make to the life of
British universities and indeed British life more generally, is
invaluable.
	   ``We hope this scheme will further enhance the valuable links
and friendship between our two countries and clearly demonstrates
Britain's continued interest in and support for Malaysia.
	   ``As Prime Minister Tony Blair said in his address to the Second
Asia- Europe Meeting in London in April - `We are not fair-weather
friends - but partners for the long term','' Moss said.
	   There are currently some 18,000 Malaysian students in British
schools, technical colleges and universities.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
