<BODY>
<SLUG> CONVENTION-TO-MONITOR sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Convention to monitor timber, plywood prices, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Convention to monitor timber, plywood prices, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Wendy LimASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE timber and plywood industry will be forming a national
marketing convention to monitor product prices and to improve
marketing strategies in the international market.
	   Primary Industry Minister Datuk Seri Dr Lim Keng Yaik said the
convention will look into making inroads into markets such as the
US, Europe and West Asia, apart from the traditional East Asian
market.
	   Japan, South Korea, China/Hong Kong, Singapore and Taiwan are
the main buyers of Malaysian plywood, but demand for the product in
these markets had softened since July last year.
	   Malaysia, he said, exported 200,000 cu m of plywood worth RM17
million to the US last year.
	   ``The parties involved should plan a proper market intelligence
survey with proper strategies to find new markets. They should also
work together in monitoring international prices,'' he told
reporters after a dialogue with Malaysian Panel Products
Manufacturers Association in Kuala Lumpur yesterday.
	   Representatives from The Sabah Timber Industries Association,
Sarawak Timber Association and Malaysian Timber Council also
attended the dialogue.
	   The export of plywood, he said, is expected to drop slightly
this year and total export earnings will be affected due to the
drop in international plywood prices and the weakening of the
ringgit.
	   ``We are forecasting about RM13.2 billion in total earnings from
timber and timber products from the first quarter sales. Last year,
the total earnings for timber and timber products was RM14.72
billion,'' Lim said.
	   Veneer and plywood make up about 34 per cent of total timber and
timber product earnings.
	   In 1996, 4.56 million cu m of veneer and plywood worth RM4.86
billion was exported.
	   Indonesia is the main exporter of plywood commanding 61 per
cent, Malaysia (28 per cent) and Brazil (7 per cent).
	   Lim said he will also seek cooperation from his counterpart in
Indonesia to ensure that international plywood prices are not
lowered due to competition.
	   Prices for 3mm plywood had dropped from US$420 per cu m before
July to the current price of US$240 per cu m. The price drop, he
said, had resulted in losses of up to RM1 million per month in
large sawmills.
	   Many of the plywood mills, he said, are considering relocating
to other countries such as Taiwan and China.
	   ``We have already brought the issue up with the Malaysian trade
commissioner in Indonesia. The meeting between Malaysia and
Indonesia last April had helped to stabilise the plywood prices but
at RM$220 per cu m, it is too low,'' he said.
	   At the dialogue, other issues such as difficulty in securing
credit financing from local banks and high interest rates of 16 per
cent were brought up. The association had requested banks to reduce
the interest rates to 14 per cent.
	   ``The association also said that export credit financing
interest rate at 10.8 per cent from the Export Import Bank is too
high. They assured me that if the interest rate is at 4.5 per cent,
they will be able to increase 30 per cent of the exports,'' he
said.
	   Lim said the Sabah Timber Industries Association, Malaysian
Panel Products Manufacturers' Association and Sarawak Timber
Association will submit a proposal to the Finance Ministry on this
matter.
	   Lim said he had also received reports on unethical practices of
plywood exporters auctioning the consignment overseas and also of
price undercutting.
	   The millers, he said, had also voiced their concern over the
increasing freight charges where a 20-ft container priced at US$950
in December had increased to US$1,100 in April this year.
	   The dialogue also raised the issue of government levy on foreign
workers which had increased from RM840 to RM1,500 per worker.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
