<BODY>
<SLUG> ROTHMANS-READY-TO-TAKE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rothmans ready to take on challenges, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Rothmans ready to take on challenges, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Shahriman JohariASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   AMID the steady drumbeat of bad news hogging the domestic
economic front in recent months, some companies still managed to
chalk up impressive profits.
	   One of them is Rothmans of Pall Mall (Malaysia) Bhd.
	   With the best foot forward, Rothmans Malaysia seems to be taking
on the challenges with a strong financial backing and aggressive
advertising strategy.
	   Dunhill has also appeared prominently amid the football fervour
as it is the official sponsor of the World Cup, bringing football
matches live to Malaysian televisions every day.
	   For the year just ended on March 31 1998, Rothmans Malaysia
registered a 16.8 per cent rise in group pre-tax profit to RM653.53
million on higher turnover of RM1.96 billion from RM1.76 billion
previously.
	   And if analysts' predictions are anything to go by, Rothmans,
producer of the country's leading cigarette brand Dunhill, will
record another satisfactory growth for the year ending March 31
1999.
	   According to an analyst, Rothmans Malaysia's overall market
share for the industry stands at 55 per cent, out of which Dunhill
makes up 40 per cent.
	   In addition, the analyst said the current economic downturn so
far has not affected the company, as its stocks which mainly
comprise tobacco leaves were bought well in advance last year and
typically last for a year.
	   Nevertheless, the analyst said there may be cause for worry if
the Malaysian economy fails to recover within next year, as
retrenchment is on the rise.
	   A crucial factor is that most smokers come from the middle- and
low- income categories which are badly hit by layoffs, the analyst
said. As their income is affected, their smoking habits would also
change.
	   ``Probably, smokers would change brands of cigarette from
premium to cheaper cigarettes,'' she added.
	   However, she said smoking is very much a psychological issue and
smoking patterns are difficult to study. The chances of smokers
changing their preferred brands can only be speculated.
	   There is also a lingering rumour that the Government may
increase taxes on tobacco and alcohol, she said. If this were to
happen, the tobacco industry would be affected, not just Rothmans
Malaysia alone.
	   However, the analyst expressed her confidence in the company as
the market leader in the industry.
	   ``Rothmans Malaysia has a very good advertising and marketing
strategy with Dunhill, and the industry is expected to grow between
2 and 4 per cent this year. The company will continue to be the
market leader,'' she said.
	   Another analyst said sales growth in terms of volume for the
industry is at 3 per cent. For the next two years, she said, the
industry will be exposed to slower growth but the numbers are not
expected to move into negative territory.
	   She said growth will persist due to the addictive nature of
cigarettes.
	   However, people may smoke less.
	   ``Rothmans for the last few years has gained some market share
but for the next two to three years, sales will decline,'' the
analyst said.
	   She said with the slowdown biting in, there will be a
``downtrend'' where smokers are expected to change to cheaper
brands.
	   However, she also pointed out that Dunhill smokers are mostly
hesitant to change cigarettes. Dunhill smokers will probably smoke
less rather than change brands.
	   The analyst is of the opinion that Rothmans Malaysia is still in
a good position due to economies of scale. Furthermore, the company
has zero borrowings and some RM400 million in net cash.
	   On the anticipated increase in sales tax and duty of imported
raw tobacco leaves, she said this is highly likely.
	   Currently, tobacco companies can only import a maximum of 30 per
cent of its required raw tobacco leaves. Import duty is RM50 for
every kg of imports. Sales tax is 15 per cent.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
