WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Petaling Jaya Municipal Council hopes to carry out an
operation soon to nab some 30,000 stray dogs.
	   Kampung Tunku State Assemblyman Khoo Ooi Seng said the operation
was necessary as there had been several reports of children being
attacked by stray dogs.
	   The operation would concentrate on housing estates, he added.
	   ``So far, we have identified only 30,000 strays in the
municipality, but there may be more,'' he said, adding that if the
dogs were not adopted by the public, the council would have to put
them to sleep.
	   Khoo said the council also intends to take cobblers off
five-foot ways and relocate them to dead ends.
	   He said the council wanted to centralise small businessess such
as cobblers and lottery ticket sellers at dead end roads so that
they would not block pedestrian traffic on the walkways.
	   
</TEXT>
