w1690 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  SecretaryrebukesRubinfor     06-12 0340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> Secretary rebukes Rubin for secrecy in sting operation </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Associated Press Writer
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By GEORGE GEDDA &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) - In a rare public display of high-level U.S.
disagreement, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has chastised
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin for failing to inform her of a
money-laundering sting operation that led to 150 arrests, including
many Mexican bankers.
	   ``I would appreciate being kept personally informed of
developing investigations in Mexico and other foreign countries
that could have a significant foreign policy fallout,'' Albright
said in a letter to Rubin, dated May 22.
	   ``I do not wish to interfere with your law enforcement work, but
I do believe we need to do a better job of coordination.''
	   The letter was inserted in the Congressional Record by Sen.
Charles Grassley, R-Iowa. It was not disclosed how Grassley
obtained the letter.
	   Albright wrote the letter following an uproar in Mexico touched
off by the disclosure that U.S. Customs agents working under
Rubin's jurisdiction had carried out part of the sting operation on
Mexican soil without Mexican authorization.
	   The bankers were arrested after being lured into the United
States under false pretenses. In addition, dlrs 10 million was
seized and three Mexican banks were indicted in the United States.
	   Mexico has indicated that laws were broken by the agents and
that it plans to prosecute them.
	   Albright expressed concern ``about the negative tone this
development introduces into the relationship and that Mexican
cooperation on several fronts, particularly counternarcotics, may
be affected.''
	   Efforts to obtain comment from the Treasury Department on the
letter were unsuccessful.
	   President Clinton also has expressed regret to Mexican President
Ernesto Zedillo about the secrecy of the operation, which was
carried out over three years and was made public last month.
Keeping Mexico uninformed about the operation was deemed necessary
to protect the agents. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:Secretary rebukes Rubin for secrecy in sting operation; CT:i; 
