<BODY>
<SLUG> TRAVEL-PACKAGES-GAMES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Travel packages for Games, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Travel packages for Games, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Kang Siew LiASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MALAYSIA Airlines is drawing up special travel packages for
those in Sabah and Sarawak to attract them to the upcoming 16th
Commonwealth Games in September.
	   Its chairman, Tan Sri Tajudin Ramli, said various types of
travel packages are being designed, which should see a maximum
discount of 55 per cent on air fares on its routes between Kuala
Lumpur and Sabah and Sarawak.
	   ``But some conditions will apply ... for example, passengers
must travel in a group,'' he told reporters in Petaling Jaya
yesterday after the launch of the ``Let the Games Begin'' album by
Youth and Sports Minister Tan Sri Muhyiddin Yassin.
	   Tajudin said the travel packages are in response to an earlier
request from Sukom Ninety Eight Bhd to review the carrier's high
air fares on routes between Kuala Lumpur and Sabah and Sarawak.
	   ``We have already started to notify our stations and offices
throughout the world with regard to these travel packages.
``However, we have yet to decide on the number of additional
flights to put into service during the Games because that will
depend on the response from people staying in Sabah and Sarawak,''
he said.
	   He expects the number of additional flights to be determined
next month.
	   On Malaysia Airlines' allocation for the promotions of the
Games, Tajudin said: ``We have a big budget for that.'' He,
however, declined to disclose the amount, saying that the air fares
for athletes from the participating countries alone amounted to
some RM15 million.
	   ``We feel that contributing to the Games is a worthwhile
investment because as the country becomes more well-known
internationally, more people will come to Malaysia.
	   ``Malaysia Airlines will benefit from it,'' he added.
	   Tajudin said many first-time travellers on Malaysia Airlines
have written to the airline saying that ``they had a good
experience and I think that sells the country.'' Sukom Ninety Eight
executive chairman Gen (R) Tan Sri Hashim Mohd Ali said it is still
short of 9 per cent of the overall budget needed to organise the
Games in September. It has estimated a total budget of RM310
million.
	   He also said it is likely that for the first time in the history
of the Games, all 69 countries of the Commonwealth will participate
in this year's event.
	   ``So far, all of the 69 countries of the Commonwealth have
decided to send teams, except Tuvalu, which is experiencing some
financial difficulties,'' he said.
	   However, Hashim said, the Pacific nation may reconsider its
earlier decision after Malaysia's offer of free three air tickets
and accommodation during the Games.
	   On the safety aspects during the Games, Hashim said a committee
chaired by Inspector-General of Police Tan Sri Rahim Noor has been
set up to look into this matter.
	   ``Sukom Ninety Eight and the Police have agreed to send three
police officers to Paris to study the country's safety measures
implemented during the current World Cup event.
	   ``In fact, some officers have already gone to Atlanta, Hiroshima
and Chiengmai. I am confident that all matters pertaining to safety
during the Games will be satisfactory,'' he said.
	   Muhyiddin said the Government has been making the necessary
arrangements to ensure that the public transport facilities are
sufficient during the Games.
	   ``Also, the Transport Committee, the Traffic and Safety
Committee, Sukom Ninety Eight and Kuala Lumpur City Council will be
coming out with a guidebook on the public transport systems.
	   ``Information on how to get to the games venues, the number of
buses available and their schedule will be included in the
guidebook,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
