<SLUG> SAMPLING-SHOWS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sampling shows chicken mostly free of antibiotic, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Sampling shows chicken mostly free of antibiotic, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Tina MelanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Thurs. - Ninety-seven per cent of chicken in the
market is free from the cancer-inducing antibiotic, nitrofuran,
once widely used by poultry farmers to promote growth of the bird.
	   Health Minister Datuk Chua Jui Meng said a recent nationwide
sampling of chicken and eggs showed less than four per cent (five
cases) contained residues of the antibiotic.
	   Nitrofuran was banned following a Cabinet decision on Aug 21,
1996, after it was found that long-term consumption of it causes
cancer of the lungs, breast and skin.
	   ``We are committed to fight the use of nitrofuran and hope we
find no residue of the antibiotic in our ongoing tests of chicken
by end of the year.''
	   He said out of the five nitrofuran violation cases, one chicken
seller was fined RM4,000 by the Teluk Intan magistrate's court on
May 26.
	   Four others - one in Perak and three in Kedah - are awaiting
prosecution.
	   Chua was speaking to reporters after opening the second day of
the third Health Ministry annual dialogue with non-governmental
organisations today.
	   The Food Act 1983 provides for a maximum penalty of five years'
jail or fine, or both, for those convicted of nitrofuran
violations.
	   He urged chicken sellers with information about poultry
suppliers and breeders using nitrofuran to co-operate with the
ministry and the Department of Veterinary Services in the interest
of the public.
	   Earlier in his speech, Chua said the ministry welcomed the
participation of NGOs in its public health programmes.
	   He said the involvement of NGOs was important as they, being a
less formal organisation, were an effective link between the
Government and the public.
	   He said NGOs participation in the ministry's community health
projects and other rehabilitation programmes would be useful as the
ministry needs complementary efforts to ensure its programmes are
successful.
	   Twenty-five NGOs presented their memorandums at today's session
including representatives of the Malaysian Council for Child
Welfare, All Women Action Society, National Stroke Association,
Cancerlink Foundation and the Society for the Deaf in Selangor and
Federal Territory.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:SAMPLING-SHOWS sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
