<SLUG> MILLERS-FIX-RICE-PRICE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Wholesalers, retailers, millers to fix rice price, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Wholesalers, retailers, millers to fix rice price, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Eirmalasare BaniASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   DOMESTIC Trade and Consumer Affairs Minister Datuk Seri Megat
Junid Megat Ayob is leaving it to rice wholesalers, retailers and
millers to decide on a suitable recommended retail price (RRP) for
home-grown rice.
	   ``The wholesalers, retailers and millers have given their word
that they will reduce the current price for local rice so that it
is equivalent to the price of rice sold by Padiberas Nasional Bhd
(Bernas) or at least lower than what is being sold now.
	   ``Let them sit down and discuss it,'' he told reporters in Kuala
Lumpur yesterday after chairing a three-hour meeting with 60 rice
millers, wholesalers and retailers including Bernas.
	   The meeting was held to find a solution to the spiralling
increase in the price of rice in recent weeks. The Federation of
Malaysian Consumer Associations (Fomca) had alleged that Bernas was
the cause of the price increase.
	   However, Bernas claims that it is a result of profiteering by
wholesalers and retailers.
	   Since May, prices of local rice had gone up by 21 per cent while
that of imported varieties are now 52 per cent more expensive.
	   Megat Junid said the wholesalers, retailers and millers have not
been given a timeframe to come up with a RRP list but he hopes it
will be ``as soon as possible''.
	   ``Datuk Mohd Nor Rahim (the ministry's secretary-general) will
jointly monitor the progress with the Agriculture Ministry,'' he
said.
	   The minister, however, declined to give the RRP proposed by the
ministry to the wholesalers and retailers.
	   ``Even if the millers sell the rice to the wholesalers and
retailers at RM1.50 per kg, they (the wholesalers and retailers)
should sell the rice to consumers at about RM1.70 per kg,'' he
said.
	   Megat Junid said the wholesalers and retailers had claimed
during the meeting that they had to sell their rice at a higher
price due to the rising costs of transportation, packaging and
cleaning of the rice.
	   He advised consumers to go to Bernas outlets such as B-Marts if
they are looking for rice at cheaper prices and ``we hope Bernas
has enough supply (to meet the demand)'', he added.
	   Asked if the ministry will act on errant wholesalers and
retailers who sell rice at a higher price despite sourcing it
cheaply from farmers, Megat Junid said that the Agriculture
Ministry's Padi and Rice Price Control and Monitoring Division will
look into ways to overcome the problem.
	   Effective September 1, however, the Division will be placed
under the Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs Ministry.
	   Megat Junid also said the wholesalers, retailers, millers and
Bernas have promised to meet regularly to ensure that the price of
rice remains stable.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
