<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Chiapas, 1st Ld-Writethru,0698 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Precede SAN CRISTOBAL DE LAS CASAS
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Mexican president says government commited to peace talks in
Chiapas &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with president visiting Chiapas, signing accord; ADDS
quotes from president, Chiapas governor, analyst; changes dateline,
byline. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos SCC102-103 &QL; 
 &UR; By NIKO PRICE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LAS MARGARITAS, Mexico (AP) _ With fears of renewed war between
Zapatista rebels and the government, Mexico's president flew to
Chiapas on Friday to defend his administration's stated desire for
dialogue and pledge money for towns where rebel support runs high.
	   Some analysts say a police and army raid on an Indian village
this week is the latest indication that the government has chosen
military might over the negotiating table.
	   But President Ernesto Zedillo told residents in Las Margaritas,
85 miles (135 kilometers) southeast of the state capital, Tuxtla
Gutierrez, that the government's goal is negotiation.
	   ``We want dialogue. We don't want to defeat anyone. The
government will not abandon this position,'' he said. Zedillo was
making his fourth visit to Chiapas in just over a month .
	   As he spoke, about a dozen people unfurled banners demanding a
halt to violence. ``Senor Zedillo, we do not want more war,'' one
said.
	   Guadalupe Gonzalez, 33, who held up a sign reading ``Senor
Zedillo, we want respect for our human rights,'' said she is not
sure the government still wants to negotiate.
	   On Wednesday, government forces clashed with apparent Zapatista
rebels in the municipality of El Bosque as they tried to evict a
town council that supported the Zapatistas, who took up arms in
1994 to demand greater democracy and Indian rights. The pro-rebel
council had been operating in parallel with the official town
council.
	   The clash, which killed nine people, was the first direct
skirmish between the government and the Zapatistas since peace
talks broke down nearly two years ago.
	   Some analysts said the government's tactics signaled that
officials have given up the idea of restarting talks and are
focusing instead on isolating the rebels from their civilian
supporters.
	   ``They have decided not to continue with negotiations, but they
can't say that because public opinion is in favor of resolving the
Chiapas problem through negotiations,'' said Lorenzo Meyer, a
political historian in Mexico City.
	   Meyer said the government over recent months has been
eliminating barriers to its plan _ expelling foreign human rights
observers from Chiapas, forcing the collapse of independent groups
mediating the peace talks and strengthening ruling party support
groups in Chiapas, including paramiltary groups.
	   In a speech Friday, Chiapas Gov. Roberto Albores Guillen took a
harder line than Zedillo, vowing to continue using force to achieve
what he called the rule of law.
	   ``The return to legality is not negotiable in Chiapas. We are
going to make the law prevail in Chiapas,'' he said.
	   Zedillo's trip to Chiapas had been planned in advance and did
not include stops near this week's clashes. All of his stops were
in towns dominated by supporters of his Institutional Revolutionary
Party.
	   In Las Margaritas, a lowland town where many government
supporters have fled after being driven from their villages by
Zapatista supporters, the president signed an accord for
``political stability, community reconciliation, social development
and economic growth.''
	   The accord is designed to provide special aid to 42
municipalities ``that need special attention,'' he said. The list
included all the pro-rebel towns the government has raided in
recent months _ including El Bosque, the site of Wednesday's raid.
	   The 42 municipalities will receive dlrs 290 million this year
for schools, health clinics, water purification plants and roads.
	   Zedillo said the towns were chosen for their extreme poverty,
lack of jobs and other problems.
	   But the accord was reminiscent of old-style Mexican politics, in
which the government threw money at ruling party supporters in
trouble spots in an attempt to buy off opposition supporters.
</TEXT>
