Apex financially sound, says chairman, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Ishun P. AhmadASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   APEX Equity Holdings Bhd said it is financially sound with about
RM90 million in cash reserves invested in fixed deposits and the
money market despite the slowdown in stockmarket.
	   Apex's executive chairman Chan Guan Seng told reporters after
the company's annual and extraordinary general meeting in Kajang
yesterday that Apex is fortunate because it has zero gearing.
	   The main activities of Apex's subsidiaries are acting as stock
and share brokers and dealers in securities, acting as futures
brokers, property holding, provision of portfolio management and
investment advisory services, provision of nominee services, unit
trust management, investment holding and money lending.
	   According to Chan, its core business of stockbroking which
contributes between 75 per cent and 80 per cent of its total
business will continue to contribute the bulk of its business.
	   Chan said that in the first three months of 1998, its
stockbroking business did fairly well.
	   On the performance of the stockmarket, Chan said that if it (the
KLSE Composite Index) deteriorates to the 480 level, investors
should look at the value of shares.
	   ``There are shares in the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE)
that are giving good value,'' Chan said.
	   On other developments, Chan said Apex expects its futures
broking business to break even by next year which has already churn
out positive results this year.
	   
</TEXT>
