<HEADLINE>
Pressmen protest ban by Sibu council, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Pressmen protest ban by Sibu council, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SIBU, Thurs. - The Sibu Journalists' Association and the
Institute of Rejang Journalists yesterday registered their protest
over a move by the Sibu Municipal Council to ban reporters from its
monthly full-council meetings.
	   ``We think the unprecedented step taken by the council has
infringed on Press freedom and denied the right of the public to
know what actually transpires at their meetings,'' they said in a
joint statement.
	   They said they could not agree with the council's suggestion
that reporters be briefed on the outcome of meetings the following
day by council chairman Kong Sien Han.
	   ``Such briefings may result in only sanitised reports, not
giving ratepayers an insight into the council's deficiencies.
	   ``Absence from the meeting also places reporters at a great
disadvantage because they would be unable to fully grasp issues
voiced out and will therefore be unable to ask relevant
questions,'' they said.
	   They said the ruling would prevent reporters from focusing on
matters they thought fit.
	   ``Moreover, reporters should not be made a tool of the
council,'' the statement added.
	   They also expressed regret at a statement by the council which
questioned the proficiency of reporters.
	   ``Over the years, the council has never asked reporters to
rectify any report on its full council meetings. We think there is
no ground for SMC to accuse reporters of filing inaccurate
reports.''
	   The council banned the Press from covering its meeting on June
5, citing inaccuracies in write-ups.
	   
</TEXT>
