<BODY>
<SLUG> RAM-LOWERS-HICOM-BONDS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAM lowers HICOM bonds to BBB2, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
RAM lowers HICOM bonds to BBB2, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   RATING Agency Malaysia (RAM) has downgraded the long-term rating
for HICOM Holdings Bhd's RM950 million redeemable secured bonds
(1996/2001) from A2(s) to BBB2.
	   In a statement, RAM said it has also downgraded the short-term
rating for HICOM's RM500 million Murabahah notes issuance facility
(1997/2002) from P2 to P3.
	   According to RAM, the rating downgrades reflect the negative
outlook for the automotive industry in the wake of the economic
slowdown and the depreciation of the ringgit.
	   The agency added that the downward pressure on future earnings
of HICOM's car-related subsidiaries and associate companies will
temper their ability to maintain dividend payments to HICOM.
	   RAM said this will in turn weaken HICOM's debt servicing ability
since its cash flow is mainly derived from dividend income from
subsidiaries and associates.
	   Furthermore, RAM said HICOM relies heavily on dividend and
investment income to service its debt and for investment.
	   However, RAM continues to see strong government support for
HICOM in view of its strategic importance as the vehicle for
developing Malaysia's automotive and heavy industries.
	   In addition, RAM said HICOM's holding of listed shares with a
market value of RM972 million as at June 5 this year will provide
it with some financial flexibility to refinance its debts upon
maturity of the bonds.
	   
</TEXT>
