<HEADLINE>
EON seeks ways to assist vendors, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
EON seeks ways to assist vendors, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   EDARAN Otomobil Nasional Bhd is looking at ways to assist its
vendors survive the economic slowdown, chairman Tan Sri Mohd Saleh
Sulong said yesterday.
	   ``We have already worked out some ways to ensure our vendors can
still keep their operations going but there may be other options we
have not looked at yet,'' he said after EON's annual meeting in
Shah Alam, Selangor.
	   One of the key strategies implemented so far has been to
repackage the Proton cars marketed by the company - which has seen
at least one model now having an enviable backlog of orders.
	   ``Demand for the Iswara 1.3 Aeroback model has been so good we
now have a temporary backlog of about 6,000 cars that need to be
delivered. This is now being looked into, but the delivery
schedules for other models are okay.''
	   Mohd Saleh said EON has already reached its limit of how it can
repackage accessories for Proton cars, but ``happily enough many
customers still opt for many accessories when making their
purchases''.
	   ``It came as a surprise to us just how big a demand there is for
accessories,'' he said, adding that it is a development which has
been very helpful in its effort to assist vendors.
	   ``The only real way we can help our vendors is by making sure
car sales remain steady, and our repackaging efforts to bring down
the cost of a car has proven to be quite successful in this
regard.''
	   ``If we cut back on our support of vendors now, it will be
difficult to rebuild the network later when demand for cars pick
up.''
	   Still, Mohd Saleh cautioned that expectations for total car
sales was as projected at the start of this year - a 60 per cent
reduction from over 210,000 units sold annually in the 1996/97
period.
	   This, in turn, is expected to see lower results for EON in the
current year ending Dec 31, 1998 - with contributions from
non-motor business projected to be almost equal to its earnings
mainstay.
	   
</TEXT>
