<HEADLINE>
Illegal software worth RM155,000 seized from firm, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Illegal software worth RM155,000 seized from firm, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Asiah BujangASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs Ministry has marked the
start of its nationwide crackdown on illegal software usage by
raiding an engineering company in Kuala Lumpur and seizing illegal
software valued at RM155,000.
	   The company had infringed copyright ofAutodesk's AutoCAD Rel.
12, Symantec's Norton Utilities 8.0 and Microsoft Windows 3.11
programmes.
	   The ministry's enforcement division's investigation and
prosecution unit head Encik Mohd Roslan Mahayudin said the
nationwide crackdown on illegal software usage follows the
ministry's 30-day awareness campaign on illegal software.
	   The June 9 raid was a a concerted effort by the division and the
Business Software Alliance (BSA), a non-profit software developers'
association which acts as an industry watchdog against piracy.
	   ``The 30-day grace period given during the campaign should have
been used by companies to legalise their software usage,'' he said,
adding that companies that continue to use illegal software for
their operations after the period will be penalised.
	   Those found guilty can be fined up to RM10,000 for each illegal
copy of software seized or five years' jail.
	   The awareness campaign, launched by Domestic Trade and Consumer
Affairs Minister Datuk Seri Megat Junid Megat Ayob on April 9,
ended on May 9.
	   BSA's vice-president Lee Tse Mei said there is now a greater
realisation among senior managers in the corporate sector against
illegal software usage.
	   Lee said companies located outside of the city should not think
that they are safe from any raids as there are 34 enforcement
branches throughout Malaysia.
	   Some 30 cases of illegal software usage are still under
investigation.
	   Even though, BSA and the division have given a 30-day grace
period for software legalisation, the Copyright Act 1987 outlawing
illegal usage of pirated software has been in effect for over 10
years.
	   In addition, BSA will be call on companies to check if they are
using original software.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
