<HEADLINE>
Parents chided for neglecting children, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Parents chided for neglecting children, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Zulkifli ShukorASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   TAIPING, Thurs. - Parents were today chided for not paying
adequate attention to their schoolgoing children, thus giving rise
to social problems involving youths.
	   National Unity and Social Development Minister Datin Paduka
Zaleha Ismail said various studies commissioned by the Ministry,
including those by the National Schoolchildren Welfare Council,
concluded that insufficient parental guidance gave rise to much
problems associated with youths today.
	   Zaleha said one of the studies was on Lifestyle of Youths Living
in High Rise Flats involving 180 families - of which an equal
number were drawn from the three major races.
	   ``Results of surveys showed that 10 per cent of them were not at
home between 7pm and 11pm. A significant percentage were still not
home at 2am.
	   ``It also showed that when parents monitored the activities and
whereabouts of their offsprings, they were less susceptible to
negative influences.
	   ``Similarly when parents play a meaningful role as members of
Parents Teachers Association and Rukun Tetangga, their children
(and those of their neighbours) were less likely to be involved in
social problems,'' she said.
	   Zaleha was speaking after witnessing and jointly signing a
Memorandum of Understanding in which the Kampung Dew Barat Rukun
Tetangga here adopted the nearby Sekolah Menengah Simpang.
	   According to the Minister, other studies showed many parents
still ignored letters from schools and that out of some 2,000
students per school, between 50 and 60 would be involved in social
problems.
	   Zaleha also disclosed feedback from a school PTA about a Form
Three student being tested positive for HIV, apparently contracted
from activities at a hotel where the student worked part-time.
	   Another case ended with counselling help for students who had
been extorting money from a fellow student, forcing the latter to
play truant.
	   ``These cases indicate how important and significant the roles
of parents, RT, PTA and other bodies are in safeguarding students'
welfare,''
	   she added.
	   At today's signing, the Kampung Dew Barat RT sector was
represented by its chairman C. Sarmugam while the school was
represented by its head Rosli Pin.
	   Perak Education Department deputy director Ahmad Shafie and
State Unity Department director Rohani Hussian Merican was also
present.
	   The MOU signing and adoption is the first of its kind in the
country where the participating RT also outlined monthly programmes
and activities for students at the school.
	   Among these were gotong royong to build study shelters and
hydrophonic farming at the school, student services project at RT
centre, tuition and counselling classes, recreational and
motivational courses as well as assistance to needy students.
	   Earlier, Zaleha also contributed books to 50 students and a
bicycle each to 10 students of the school.
	   She also presented cheques for RM4,000 - which were equally
contributed by the local Changkat Jering and Sepetang Assemblymen
Mat Isa Ismail and Siew Kok Kan respectively - to the school.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
