<HEADLINE>
Operations began at pilot plant in 1962, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Operations began at pilot plant in 1962, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Shahriman JohariASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE birth of Rothmans of Pall Mall (Malaysia) Bhd can be traced
as far back as 1962 when it first began operations in Singapore.
	   In fact, the company was the first Rothmans venture in Asia and
became the first overseas tobacco company to offer 50 per cent of
its holding to the Malaysian public.
	   Its operations started at a pilot plant in Singapore in May
1962. It then began activities in November of the same year in
Petaling Jaya.
	   On December 31 1981, a scheme was undertaken to separate
Rothmans' Malaysia and Singapore operations.
	   Rothmans sold its wholly-owned subsidiary, Rothmans of Pall Mall
(S'pore) Pte Ltd, to Rothmans Industries Ltd, also of Singapore.
	   On October 31 1985, Rothmans Malaysia announced proposals for a
restructuring of its equity in line with the National Economic
Plan.
	   The scheme increased the Bumiputera shareholding in the company
from 4 per cent to 30 per cent without departing from the equity
partnership, whereby the company was owned 50 per cent by the
parent company - Rothmans International Plc - and the rest by local
investors.
	   On January 15 1987, the existing shares in the company were
removed from the official list of the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange
and 61.97 million new shares arising from the restructuring were
listed.
	   In line with the scheme, 80.8 million new shares subscribed by
Rothmans International and approved Bumiputera investors were
listed on the same day.
	   On January 1 1988, Rothmans Malaysia put into effect a
re-organisation of its business whereby it transferred its tobacco
manufacturing and marketing operations to subsidiaries Tobacco
Importers and Manufacturers Sdn Bhd and Cigarette Importers and
Distributors Sdn Bhd, respectively.
	   Cigarette Importers and Distributors is now known as Commercial
Importers and Distributors Sdn Bhd.
	   The re-organisation transformed the company into an investment
holding concern. Rothmans Malaysia's main activities include
manufacturing, importation, distribution and sale of cigarettes and
other tobacco products.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
