<HEADLINE>
Transpacific carriers to adjust Canada rates, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Transpacific carriers to adjust Canada rates, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MAJOR ocean and intermodal shipping lines operating in the trade
lane from Asia to Canada will implement a second 1998 rate
adjustment in that market in order to help offset depressed rate
levels, address severe cargo and equipment imbalances and ensure
stable service.
	   A statement released yesterday in Kuala Lumpur said effective
July 1, rates for all cargo moving on the vessels of carriers in
the Canada Transpacific Stabilisation Agreement (CTSA) will be
increased by US$200 (US$1  &QC;  RM4.00) per 40ft container (FEU).
	   Proportionate increases will be implemented at the same time for
other equipment sizes and cargo otherwise rated.
	   CTSA noted that market conditions in the Asia-Canada trade have
changed dramatically since CTSA lines adopted and announced an
earlier increase in November 1997, to take effect last April.
	   In recent months, the surge in container traffic from Asia
through Canadian ports and the falloff in westbound shipments to
Asia have increased operational problems and costs relating to port
congestion, routing of cargo and balancing equipment.
	   CTSA is a discussion and policy setting group of 12 ocean and
intermodal carriers serving the trade from ports and inland points
in Asia and the Indian Subcontinent to destinations throughout
Canada.
	   Its members include American President Lines Ltd, Evergreen
Marine Corp (Taiwan) Ltd, Hanjin Shipping Co Ltd, Hapag-Lloyd
Container Line GmbH, Hyundai Merchant Marine Co Ltd, Kawasaki Kisen
Kaisha Ltd (K Line), Mitsui OSK Lines Ltd and A.P. Moller-Maersk
Line.
	   Others are P&AMP;O Nedlloyd Ltd, Nippon Yusen Kaisha (NYK Line),
Orient Overseas Container Lines Inc and Sea-Land Service Inc.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
