<HEADLINE>
INCORPORATES Egypt-Yassin
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Yassin: Israel will not stop my return to Gaza &QL; 
 &UR; By JACK KATZENELL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Sheik Ahmed Yassin, the spiritual leader of the
militant Palestinian Islamic group Hamas, said Friday he will
return next week to Gaza whether Israel agrees or not.
	   The 61-year-old quadriplegic, whose followers have killed scores
of Israeli civilians in suicide bomb attacks, was allowed to leave
the Gaza Strip for the purpose of receiving medical treatment, but
seized the opportunity to conduct a 3-month fund-raising trip in
the Arab world, reportedly raising over dlrs 20m.
	   Fears have been expressed in Israel that the money will be used
to finance a new wave of attacks. The Israeli army's outgoing chief
of military intelligence, Moshe Yaalon, said Friday Israel's
problem lay in deciding whether Yassin was more dangerous inside
the Gaza Strip or abroad.
	   Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu told Israeli television
Channel 1 Friday that he would decide in the next day or two
whether to allow Yassin to return or not.
	   Yassin is currently in the Sudanese capital Khartoum, because
the Egyptian government has not yet permitted him to fly to Cairo.
In a satellite interview with Channel 1, Yassin said he would
return to Gaza next week, ``God willing.''
	   ``I left Gaza by the front door. ... I left with official and
legal permission and therefore neither Israel nor any other entity
can prevent me from returning to my home and my family,'' he said
in a second interview with Israeli Channel 2 television.
	   He stressed that he would continue to fight Israel whether he is
at home or abroad. Hamas is opposed to peace with Israel and sees
the whole of Israel as occupied Palestinian land. ``I am fighting
the occupation and it is my right to fight it,'' he said.
	   Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat has said repeatedly he is doing
all he can to prevent attacks by Hamas and other militant groups
against Israel, but he insists that under the Oslo agreements
Israel has no right to prevent Yassin's return.
	   ``This would be a violation of what has been agreed and what has
been signed,'' he told reporters earlier this week.
	   Yassin planned to camp out at Egypt's border with the Gaza Strip
if Israel refuses to allow his return, the London-based Al-Hayat
newspaper reported Friday.
	   He would stay there until Israel's policy had been exposed to
the world, the paper quoted a Hamas official as saying.
	   Yassin would then leave Egypt for another Arab Muslim country.
	   Egyptian officials could not immediately be reached for comment.
	   Yassin was freed from an Israeli jail last fall in exchange for
the freedom of two Israeli Mossad agents captured in Jordan during
a bungled assassination attempt against another Hamas leader.
 &UR; jk 	   
</TEXT>
