	   SHARES fell 1.2 per cent yesterday amid concerns over rising
local interbank interest rates in the wake of renewed regional
currency weakness, dealers said.
	   The key Hang Seng index fell 93.30 points to close at 7,886.07 -
its third consecutive loss - after plunging 4.9 per cent on
Wednesday to a more than three-year low.
	   The value of turnover amounted to HK$6.751 billion, against the
previous day's HK$7.154 billion.
	   The market opened weakly on heavy selling by institutions and
retail investors with the key barometer falling 1.1 per cent by the
end of the morning session.
	   Dealers said the weakness of the yen was pushing up interbank
offered rates, drying up liquidity.
	   
