<SLUG> BC-NATO-Kosovo, 5th Ld-Writethru,0697 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO and Russia agree on danger, differ on method
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with possible exercise date, fresh details, new Cohen
quote. &QL; 
 &UR; With NATO-Albania
 &UR; By JEFFREY ULBRICH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) - Russia and the NATO allies agreed
Friday that the explosive situation in Kosovo represents a grave
danger to its neighbors, but differed on how to deal with defiant
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
	   U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen, who had a private meeting
with Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev and another as part of
the NATO-Russia Permanent Joint Council, stressed the urgency of
finding a solution to hostilities in the southern Yugoslavian
province.
	   ``We are looking at a very short time frame ... to solve this
peacefully,'' he told a news conference at the end of a two-day
North Atlantic Treaty Organization defense ministers' meeting.
	   On Thursday, NATO decided to demonstrate allied air power over
neighboring Albania and Macedonia in hopes of impressing Milosevic
and making him rethink his policy of escalating violence in Kosovo.
	   That demonstration, codenamed Determined Falcon, will probably
occur early next week, perhaps as soon as Sunday, and will involve
simulated air attacks and bombing raids.
	   One NATO official said the demonstration would involve a large
number of allies and types of aircraft.
	   The ministers also ordered military planners to study options
for further action ranging from accelerated planning for military
exercises in the region to direct air strikes inside Yugoslavia and
use of air-mobile ground troops.
	   Cohen said there was a great ``sense of urgency among NATO
members'' that something must be done quickly to stop Milosevic's
attacks on ethnic Albanians, who make up 90 percent of Kosovo's
population.
	   The rebel Kosovo Liberation Army is seeking independence, an
aspiration NATO does not support.
	   ``NATO, all the ministers, and Russia have a unanimous attitude
toward the events in Kosovo,'' said Sergeyev. ``Our differences are
in assessment, approach and methods.''
	   He said Russia ``is convinced we haven't exhausted all
non-military means ... to resolve this crisis.'' If ``other
methods'' must be adopted, he said, they ``should be the
prerogative of the U.N. Security Council.''
	   Cohen said Russia risked isolation if it blocked international
efforts.
	   ``Russia obviously would have to take into account its own
perception of events in Kosovo, and also take into account that it
might be isolated in the world community if it does not seek a way
to bring whatever leverage it can to bring Milosevic to the
table,'' Cohen said.
	   Macedonia has not yet given its authorization for the planned
military exercises over its territory, but Albania is delighted
with the decision to show force.
	   ``We are very pleased about the decision taken by the NATO
Council yesterday,'' Albanian Defense Minister Luan Hajdaraga said
in an interview.
	   ``The stand of Milosevic in the Kosovo crisis is very clear, it
is to dominate the situation by military means.'' The danger is, he
said, that ``those means can spread to Albania.''
	   Gen. Henry Shelton, chairman of the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff,
couldn't give details of exactly what form the exercises would
take, saying they were still being developed by NATO planners. Nor
could he say what might trigger a direct military intervention in
Kosovo.
	   The NATO-Russia Permanent Joint Council was formed a year ago as
part of the effort to ease Russia's fears about NATO enlargement.
It has become a forum for consultation on security issues as well
as planning future cooperation.
	   A joint statement at the end of the meeting said the ministers
discussed Kosovo and ``condemned Belgrade's massive and
disproportionate use of force as well as violent attacks by Kosovar
Albanian extremists.''
	   NATO must walk a fine line between trying to halt the Yugoslav
government's ``disproportionate use of force'' and offering aid and
comfort to the rebels seeking independence, which NATO opposes, and
has been careful to condemn the violence on both sides. 	   
</TEXT>
