<HEADLINE>
Shares retreat in thin trade, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Shares retreat in thin trade, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SHARES on the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE) closed lower
yesterday in thin trading due to persistent selling pressure.
	   At closing, the KLSE Composite Index (KLCI) lost 6.86 points to
483.00 while the Emas Index slipped 1.92 points to 124.35. The
Second Board index lost 0.93 points to 106.64.
	   On the scoreboard, losers led gainers 410 to 130 while 182
counters remained unchanged.
	   Yesterday's turnover was higher amounting to 130.017 million
shares valued at RM297.037 million compared with 111.432 million
sharse worth RM281.706 million traded on Wednesday.
	   ``Basically, the market is still blurred by the regional
currency weakness and the only way to go seems to be down,'' said
one analyst.
	   He said with the battered yen against the US dollar, investors
are worried that this will slow business recovery in the region.
	   Fears that the Chinese yuan will be devalued also arose and if
this happens, the region's exports will lose their competitiveness,
said another analyst.
	   ``Put these fears together with other uncertainties clouding the
region and the dump-the-stocks button is triggered,'' she said.
	   Blue-chip stocks led the market's slide yesterday with utilities
Tenaga and Telekom and Maybank losing between 5 and 20 sen. Telekom
lost 20 sen to RM6.80, said to be its lowest in more than six
years.
	   The broad-based BT Ordinaries eased 2.01 points to 117.24 while
the 30- share New Straits Industrial Index slipped 26.37 points to
end at 2,902.88.
	   Turnover on the Main Board amounted to 111.743 million shares
worth RM284.166 million while turnover on the Second Board was
7.536 million shares valued at RM10.344 million.
	   Magnum was the most active with 17.599 million shares followed
by Maybank with 16.745 million and AMMB with 7,649 lots done.
	   
</TEXT>
