<HEADER>
w1735 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  POLITICS-MATTERS-MOREske     06-12 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> POLITICS-MATTERS-MORE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Politics matters more, JAKARTA POST
</HEADLINE>
Politics matters more, JAKARTA POST &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   JAKARTA POST
   INDONESIA
   ENGLISH
   Gwynne DyerASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   LONDON (JP): On June 2, Californians voted by almost two-to-one
to end most teaching of immigrant school-children in their own
languages. On June 13, Queensland in Australia votes in an election
that could give the anti-immigrant One Nation party the whip hand
in the state legislature. These events are more closely linked than
they seem.
	   The United States and Australia are two of the more popular
immigrant destinations in the world, and Queensland is the 'Aussie
California': it's a 'sunshine state', it has led the other states
in population growth over the past few decades, and it is a fertile
growth medium for right-wing political movements. A couple of years
ago, it produced Pauline Hanson.
	   Hanson, a small businesswoman from the Queensland town of
Ipswich, soared to national attention by saying the rude, racist
things about immigrants -- and about Australia's own aboriginal
people -- that other rednecks had been dying to hear. She won a
seat in the last federal election, which made it impossible for the
media to ignore her, and set about building a national party.
	   This month's Queensland election is the first serious outing for
her 'One Nation' party, and the vote is so finely balanced between
the governing conservative coalition and the opposition Labor Party
that even a couple of seats would give her the balance of power in
state politics. So she has pulled all the stops out -- and with the
opinion polls equally knife-edged for the federal election due in
the next year, so have her opponents.
	   Hanson was in classic form early this month, warning voters that
a draft United Nations treaty would help aborigines, who are 2
percent of Australia's population, to set up a separate black
homeland. She named Queensland University professor Peter Jull as
the architect of the planned Nunavut homeland for the Canadian
Inuit (Eskimo) people, and alleged that he was advising the
Northern Land Council on setting up race-based states in Australia.
	   None of it was true, as she was subsequently forced to admit,
but the accusations nevertheless have an impact on those who are
predisposed to believe them. It's the same with her anti-immigrant
diatribes, and the net impact has been to double her expected vote
in Queensland from 5 to 10 percent since the campaign began.
	   That even scared Prime Minister John Howard into responding at
last. For the past two years Howard has affected to ignore Hanson,
but now he waded in: ``It is not only an inaccurate, dishonest
speech, but it verges on the deranged. This speech is appealing to
irresponsible racist sentiment in the Australian community.''
	   This condemnation came a bit late for Kim Beazley, leader of the
federal Labor party, who accuses Howard's Liberal Party of tacitly
nurturing One Nation in order to steal Labor votes: ``We say this
One Nation is simply the unacceptable face of the Liberal party.''
Unprovable, of course, but he has logic on his side, since Labor's
less-educated working-class backers (together with rural whites)
are the likeliest to be seduced by Hanson's racist song.
	   How does all this connect with California, where voters have
just approved Proposition 227 ending most 'bilingual' education in
the schools? Even though President Bill Clinton and all four
candidates for state governor opposed the proposal, it is not an
unambiguously anti-immigrant policy: many Hispanic and Asian
community leaders backed it, and so did majorities of Hispanic and
Asian voters.
	   'Bilingual' education in California was not really bilingual,
but just education in Spanish and other immigrant languages. Ron
Unz, the millionaire who sponsored Proposition 227, contended that
this consigned immigrant children to a linguistic limbo and
blighted their chances of success in American society. Many
immigrant parents clearly agreed.
	   But the broader thrust of California's referendum-driven
politics over the past 20 years is clearly anti-immigrant, and as
the proportion of white anglos has declined (from 78 percent in
1970 to 52 percent today) their resistance has grown ever fiercer.
	   The vote against 'affirmative action' two years ago has
drastically cut the number of 'minority' students admitted to
California's state university system. In the past 20 years the
school system, seen to be catering mainly to immigrant children,
has gone from 10 percent above the national average in spending per
student to 20 percent below it, with calamitous results on success
rates. And California has not built one new university campus since
1978, but it has opened twenty new prisons.
	   ``It's not explicitly racist,'' says Peter Schrag, author of the
recent 'Paradise Lost' that chonicles California's decline, ``but
it has a racist theme.'' And now the Australians (and of course the
French, with the rise of the National Front) seem to be going the
same way. Is this the fate that awaits every society that is too
open to immigrants from different cultures?
	   No. It's what happens when the political system delivers power
into the hands of a determined minority (like California's system
of referendums). It hasn't even happened in Australia yet, though
the excessively complicated electoral system makes it more possible
there. And it has certainly not happened in Canada and Britain,
though cities like Toronto and London are just as ethnically mixed
as Los Angeles and a lot more so than Sydney or Brisbane.
	   For whatever reason, English-speaking countries seem better able
to integrate and benefit from large immigration flows than most
other developed countries, but there are huge differences between
them. Canada takes in proportionally twice as many immigrants as
Australia or the U.S., with no comparable political backlash. The
United States as a whole is far to the right of other developed
countries, but few other states have traveled the same road as
California.
	   Or to put it more generally: culture matters, but politics
matters more.
	   Gwynne Dyer is a London-based independent journalist and
historian whose articles are published in 45 countries.
	   
</TEXT>
