Foo tries his luck in US Open, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Foo tries his luck in US Open, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MALAYSIA will be represented by one shuttler at the United
States Open badminton championships which started in Atlanta
yesterday.
	   And that is BAM dropout Foo Yong Kean, who will be paying his
own way to the tournament.
	   The BA of Malaysia (BAM) and Nusa Mahsuri have decided not to
send their shuttlers to tournament which carries a two-star rating
this year because of the small prize money offered.
	   Many regular sponsors of the tournament, who are mostly from
Asia, have pulled out because of the present economi slowdown.
	   When it offered US$170,000 (RM680,000) the last three years and
was rated a four-star tournament, the US open is now offering only
US$40,000 (RM160,000) in prize money.
	   The weakened ringgit is also another reason why BAM felt it was
better for their shuttlers to prepare for the Malaysian Open on
July 1-5.
	   BAM general-manager Phua Tai Neng said they helped with Foo's
registration for the tournament.
	   ``He informed us that he has some business to attend to in the
United States and he will use the opportunity to take part in the
tournament,''
	   said Phua.
	   Foo, who was in the BAM academy for five years, was dropped from
the national training squad because he had not improved in the last
two years.
	   The US Open not only failed to attract the country's top players
but also from Indonesia, China and Europe.
	   
</TEXT>
