<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 4th Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Albanian militants kill Serb policemen near Kosovo capital
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS context. &QL; 
 &UR; By ISMET HAJDARI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Ethnic Albanian militants, boldly
stepping up their attacks, killed two Serb policemen just a few
miles from Kosovo's capital and on Friday said they command 15,000
fighters across the secessionist province.
	   Fighting between Serbian forces and the militants erupted again
in the Decani region in western Kosovo, close to the border with
Albania. It was a Serbian offensive there last week that prompted
NATO Thursday to announce a show of air power to persuade Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic to halt such assault.
	   Ethnic Albanian sources claimed that seven villages in the
Decani area were under attack Friday, including from grenade
launchers normally issued to the Yugoslav army. They said one
Albanian, named as Rexhep Mazrekaj, 38, was killed.
	   There was no independent confirmation of their report, but the
state-run Tanjug news agency in Belgrade reported that a Serb
policeman was seriously hurt in what it called an attack by ``armed
Albanian terrorists'' near one of the villages, Prilep.
	   Ethnic Albanians outnumber Serbs nine-to-one in Kosovo. Most
seek independence from Serbia, which in 1989 stripped the province
of broad autonomy and has ruled repressively since. More than 250
people have been killed since Serbian police started a crackdown
against Albanian militants in March.
	   Serb sources in the province said two policemen where killed and
one was seriously wounded in an overnight ambush by separatists
near Obilic, just 7 kilometers (4.3 miles) northwest of the
provincial capital Pristina. Ethnic Albanian sources claimed one
Albanian was wounded in the same incident.
	   Fighting has come much closer to Pristina in recent weeks,
causing the occasional shutdown of the city's airport, some 12
kilometers (eight miles) west of Pristina.
	   Militants have gained much more popular support since March, and
young Kosovo Albanians who live in western Europe have gone to
Albania to organize or fight.
 &UR; According to, 7th graf, BC-Yugooslavia-Kosovo, 3rd Ld-Writethru
	   (as)
