<HEADLINE>
Malaysians drawn to meet Indons in the last four, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Malaysians drawn to meet Indons in the last four, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   S. NavalanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MALAYSIA, seeded third in the Asian Badminton Junior
championships, have been drawn to meet powerhouse Indonesia in the
semifinals of the tournament which begins on Monday.
	   Defending champions China, Malaysia, Indonesia and South Korea
all received byes from the first round at the draw made yesterday.
	   Malaysia, placed in the lower group, begin their campaign with
an easy match against minnows Macau and after that are expected to
meet Thailand in the quarterfinals, a team they should easily get
past.
	   Indonesia, the runnersup last year, meet Cambodia in the second
round and should not have any problem in beating Japan, their most
possible opponents in the quarterfinals.
	   China open their campaign against Maldives and probably play
India in the quarterfinals.
	   South Korea also should not have any problem beating Brunei in
the second round and Taiwan likely to be their quarterfinal
opponents.
	   In the girls' section, Malaysia will have a very tough time
getting past even the first round.
	   Failing to get a bye, the lowly placed Malaysian girls have an
uneasy task against Thailand in the first round. Thailand have
proven to be tough customers in senior and junior competitions
recently.
	   If Malaysia get past Thailand, they will meet fourth seeded
South Korea in the next round.
	   Defending champions China, who have a bye to the quarterfinals,
open their campaign against Sri Lanka and their likely opponents in
the semifinals are Japan.
	   Indonesia also start their campaign in the quarterfinals and
they are likely to play India. South Korea look their opponents in
the semifinals.
	   Twenty teams are competing in the boys' section and 11 in the
girls' section.
	   The individual tournaments begin on June 18 with 109 entries for
the boys' section, 55 entries for boys' doubles, 72 (girls'
singles), 36 (girls' doubles) and 68 (mixed doubles).
	   The Malaysians have set a target of winning at least one gold
medal.
	   
</TEXT>
