</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> SIDE-OF-GLOBALISATION sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
The dark side of globalisation, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
The dark side of globalisation, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE widespread economic problems in Asia could well be an
indicator that economic globalisation has a dark side. For now, at
least, it is clear that Asia is facing an economic crisis while a
large part of the world sits back and watches. Unaffected economies
and western-based institutions seem to be satisfied that their long
standing belief that governance in Asia is riddled with bad
practices has been proven true. However, the joy of being detached
from Asia's economic problems cannot possibly last and it would be
naive for unaffected economies to assume that they will remain
immune to the economic malaise forever. In actual fact, there
exists an increasingly real threat that the economic turmoil in
Asia will spread to the rest of the world, plunging the entire
globe into a reccession.
	   It is therefore surprising that major economic powers and
powerful world institutions such as the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) have largely preferred to engage in endless negotiations
before making any move to aid the region. The recent plunge in
Asian stock markets and the value of currencies, comes at a time
when countries like the US are basking in what could be their
strongest period of economic growth to date. However, if Washington
fails to recognise the need to support Asia's swift economic
recovery, its bright days in the sun may come to a screeching halt.
In the case of the IMF, the more difficult it makes accessibility
to aid for Asian economies and the more it refuses to acknowledge
certain shortcomings in the world's financial system, the greater
the likelihood of the economic crisis sweeping across the world.
	   In less than a year, what started as a de-facto devaluation of
the Thai bhat, has developed into a massive problem that is even
threatening to drag the once mighty Japanese economy down to its
knees. The yen has slumped to its lowest level against the US
dollar and because of its close economic relations with the rest of
Asia, the regional currencies which had been grossly weakened since
last July suffered another blow. The yen's weakness also struck
Japan's faltering real economy, which according to western
observers, was due to poor financial governance on Tokyo's part.
	   If the economic problems faced by South-East Asian economies do
not attract a response from the West and institutions like the IMF,
Japan's case deserves special attention because of its position as
a net investor with huge investments the world over, including in
the US. It is perhaps the one country that has truly benefitted
from globalisation and it is practically impossible to find a spot
on the world map where Japanese goods are not present. Japan has
large investments in the US and holds a significant amount of US
bonds, which makes the reports that Japanee authorities are
scrambling for loans to help its battered financial system,
extremely worrying.
	   It is not impossible for Japan to do what many other South-East
Asian countries are adopting in their present situation - bringing
back their financial wealth from overseas. This means that Japan
could liquidate its foreign investments, including its huge
bondholdings in US and European corporations. When that happens,
the already damaged South-East Asian economy will suffer further.
The US and much of Europe would be hurt too, both in terms of
Japan's direct investments and securities as well through the
weakened imports by Asia. In addition, as Japanese direct
investments have become an important source of employment, their
return to Japan, may well be the starting point for the Asian
economic problem's transitition into a global social issue.
	   Thus, if the world fails to recognise the significance of Japan
and of assisting Asia in getting out the economic quagmire quickly,
the outlook is a grim one where only rebuilding offers a solution.
But what would there be to rebuild, when the fault lies not in the
physical aspects of the affected countries but rather in the
globalised economic system? Would it be necessary to destroy
everything first before the world has something to rebuild. We must
remember that at least two major wars fought this century were
preceded by a global recession. If that is to be the only option
now, then God help us all.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:SIDE-OF-GLOBALISATION sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
