<HEADLINE>
Collett failed to get clearance, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Collett failed to get clearance, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   NEW Zealand jockey Jim Collett, who was granted a visiting
permit to ride at the current meeting in Ipoh, failed to get
immigration clearance.
	   The 38-year-old rider, who arrived in Singapore two weeks ago,
only handed in his application for work permit late last Thursday,
giving too little time for the immigration department to look into
his application.
	   The authorities had less than 24 hours to go through his papers
and on top of that, Saturday was a National holiday being the
birthday of the Agong.
	   Collett, who was booked on two rides on Saturday and five rides
on Sunday, had to be replaced. However, two of his mounts were
scratched.
	   Aussies Paul Saunders and Glenn Smith were given clearance as
their application were handed in on Monday, the day they arrived
from Australia.
	   
</TEXT>
