w1763 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  GOVT-TO-AWARD-SMALL-JOBS     06-12 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> GOVT-TO-AWARD-SMALL-JOBS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Govt to award small jobs directly to firms (HL), BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Govt to award small jobs directly to firms (HL), BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ALL small government contracts will now be awarded directly to
companies selected by the Government, and no longer through a main
contractor.
	   Announcing the move to end the so-called ``umbrella concept''
practice in awarding small government contracts, Deputy Prime
Minister and Finance Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim said
yesterday the Government is ensuring that these small contracts go
to genuine and deserving small-time contractors.
	   Under the umbrella concept, state governments would award a
project worth not more than RM15 million to a main contractor, who
is entrusted with the task of farming out portions of the project
to small contractors.
	   Minor contracts are defined as jobs normally handled by class F
contractors, such as upgrading rural roads and infrastructure. The
Rural Development and the Entrepreneur Development ministries
oversee the award of these projects.
	   Anwar said there have been numerous complaints from small
contractors about the award of jobs to them by the main contractor
under the umbrella concept.
	   ``We have heard many grouses from small-time contractors in
several districts who feel that, while there are merits to allocate
contracts under the umbrella concept, most of them are being left
out,'' he said at the Finance Ministry's excellence service awards
presentation in Kuala Lumpur yesterday.
	   As such, he said, all new contracts will be awarded directly to
small contractors identified by the Government. Small-time
contractors can now deal direct with district offices to bid for
jobs.
	   Existing contracts under the umbrella concept, however, will not
be affected by the new ruling.
	   Anwar said the Government needs to ensure that the interests of
the small-time contractors are safeguarded.
	   ``At a time when the country is facing difficult times
economically, we do not want to appear to be attending only to the
problems of the bigger contractors and ignoring those of the
small-time contractors.'' ``I have met the menteris besar and
officials of the state governments and the ministries of Rural
Development and Entrepreneur Development. They have been told that
the award of contracts under the umbrella concept will be done away
with.
	   ``Instead, we have reverted to the old system,'' he said.
	   Deputy Finance Minister Datuk Dr Affifuddin Omar said the
current economic slowdown caused projects to be shelved and this
had contributed to lesser jobs being allocated to minor
contractors.
	   He said established contractors involved in the umbrella concept
have been known to farm out jobs to minor contractors ``as and when
they please''.
	   ``For example, in the Padang Terap parliamentary constituency,
most minor contractors did not secure contracts ... the established
contractor would only allocate jobs to only 15 contractors whereas
50 more of them did not get any,'' he said.
	   Affifuddin said only contracts worth more than RM15 million
would have to go through the minister's tender committee.
	   Bernama reports: Umno Youth has welcomed the government's move
to stop issuing minor contracts under the umbrella concept to
ensure survival of small-scale contractors.
	   Its chief, Datuk Ahmad Zahid Hamidi, said government agencies
should act immediately on the new ruling.
	   Zahid said established companies awarded projects under the
umbrella concept had not transparently distributed them to the
small-scale contractors.
	   He told reporters this after the launching of a state-level
workers' savings programme through Bank Simpanan Nasional by
Menteri Besar Tan Sri Ramli Ngah Talib in Ipoh, Perak.
	   Zahid, who is also BSN chairman, said most of the main
contractors would award the projects to companies linked to them
and this practice was killing other small-scale contractors.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
