<HEADLINE>
Shares across region end mostly lower, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Shares across region end mostly lower, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Roziana HamsawiASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SHARE prices across the region were mostly down yesterday, as
the sluggish Japan economy and depreciation of the yen against the
greenback continued to inflict pain in the region's stock markets.
	   The yen breached the 142 barrier to the US dollar yesterday,
causing worries that business recovery in the region would be
slowed down.
	   Another concern was the possibility that the yuan would be
devalued, which would see a decline in the competitiveness of Asian
exports.
	   Analysts said the yen's depreciation yesterday was triggered by
falls in Japanese stocks and bonds.
	   Tokyo's share price closed 2.12 per cent lower yesterday, with
the key Nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues on the Tokyo
Stock Exchange falling 325.219 points to end at 15,014.04.
	   In Kuala Lumpur, the KLSE Composite Index lost 6.86 points, or
1.14 per cent, to 483.00 while the Emas Index slipped 1.92 points
to 124.35. The second board index lost 0.93 points to 106.64.
	   Total turnover was thin at 130.017 million shares valued at
RM297.037 million, compared with 111.432 million shares worth
RM281.706 million on Wednesday.
	   ``Basically, the market is still blurred by the regional
currency weakness and the only way to go seems to be down,'' said
an analyst.
	   Another big loser was the Hong Kong market, which was down 1.17
per cent on concerns about the impact of a yuan devaluation and the
Hong Kong dollar's peg to the US dollar.
	   At closing, the Hang Seng index was down 93.29 points to
7,886.07.
	   Also down were the Taiwan weighted index, closing 12.389 points
lower to 7,210.74, and the Stock Exchange of Thailand index, down
8.18 points at 283.92.
	   In Manila, shares were down 88.85 points to 1,829.02. Likewise
in Sydney, share prices fell 1.3 per cent amid concern about the
lower Asian equity markets.
	   There was a different scenario across the Causeway when its
shares closed 1.8 per cent higher on bargain hunting. Singapore's
benchmark stock index, the Straits Times Industrials index, rose
19.02 points to 1,086.83.
	   Also up were Indonesian stocks, with the Jakarta Stock Exchange
Composite Index closing 3.46 points higher at 411.544.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
