<HEADLINE>
`Light Bulbs' for the city that never sleeps, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
`Light Bulbs' for the city that never sleeps, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   WELL, what do you know! A Malaysian play is making inroads
elsewhere. Very soon Light Bulbs, which was staged here in 1996 and
received rave reviews, will be seen in ``the city that never
sleeps''. Yes, New York, New York.
	   Said Light Bulbs writer-director Karen Quah in a Press release,
the play will be staged at the New York International Fringe
Festival (FringeNYC) from Aug 19 to 30. Now, how about that?!
Originally a production of The Actors Studio, Light Bulbs starred
Johanna Varghese, Sandra Sodhy and Huzir Sulaiman.
	   This slick blend of theatre, live music, video and slide
projection focuses on a rock band called Light Bulbs. It examines
the intricacies of local pop culture and the influence of the
Western media on Malaysian society.
	   Varghese will once again star. She will be joined at the
FringeNYC by actors Afdlin Shauki, Jit Woei, Vishal Doshi and Lina
Teoh.
	   So, you can start spreading the news...
	   ERMA Fatima may feel slightly down these days. Although her BNE
Studio has been cooking up some very entertaining made-for-TV
dramas like Pengantin Popular, Ratu Jamu and Orang Gaji, she has
been forced to give up her office and operate from the comfort of
her home.
	   The latest we heard is that her products have not been moving.
For instance, Jangan, which was judged Best Drama at last year's
Malaysian Film Festival, has yet to be bought by any TV station.
	   The fact is, there are no takers because TV stations have cut
down on new purchases due to budget constraints. Which is a shame,
really, because the drama is said to be marvellous.
	   Apparently, Erma was also unprepared to take out several scenes
as requested by a buyer.
	   You sure can hit rough waters in show business...
	   THE Corrs' Talk On Corners, which knocked Celine Dion's titanic
My Heart Will Go On off the top of the RIM charts eight weeks ago,
is still firmly perched there.
	   Sales of the group's album of the same name has hit platinum
with over 25,000 units sold here. Besides striking success in
Malaysia, Talk On Corners has been certified gold in France,
Canada, Norway and Japan; double platinum in Spain, Denmark and New
Zealand; and an unprecedented eight times-over platinum in
Australia and Ireland.
	   Comprising Andrea on lead vocals, Caroline on
drums/bodhran/vocals, Sharon on violin/vocals and Jim on
keyboards/guitar/vocals, they came to our shores this year to grace
the AIM '97 awards.
	   The Corrs, whose other hits include I Never Loved You Anyway and
Don't Say You Love Me, looks set to ride the waves for a few more
weeks or at least, until another ship arrives on the horizon.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
