w1776 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  IT-CAN-HELP-FIRMS-MIMOSs     06-12 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> IT-CAN-HELP-FIRMS-MIMOS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT can help firms to be more competitive: Mimos, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
IT can help firms to be more competitive: Mimos, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Vasantha GanesanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   INFORMATION Technology (IT) can play a dual role for companies -
it can enhance their efficiency while increasing automation for
production.
	   ``There are basically two parts to the use of IT in industries:
its function in increasing the efficiency of the company, and where
IT helps to increase automation and thereby production,'' said
Mimos Bhd vice president of the commercial sector Rafee Yusoff.
	   Rafee said IT can help a company to become more efficient,
competitive and to survive and compete in a global environment.
	   He added that e-commerce programmers can now sell more products
and services and should thus invest in the sort of solutions that
can expand their business.
	   ``If they are only thinking of current business, they will
shrink. We are saying, use this opportunity to invest and therefore
get new business opportunities.'' Rafee also said that
opportunities for e-commerce have not been fully exploited. ``One
should invest in IT opportunities that will create more business.''
On how costs can be reduced, he said that instead of resorting to
layoffs, a company should strive to survive. ``If they survive and
create more business opportunities, only then can we talk about
creating more jobs,'' he said, adding that this whole process is a
cycle.
	   ``Many people neglect to ensure that their system is integrated
and their productivity system expandable through the use of
e-commerce.
	   ``Since many fail to see this, they have two separate systems.
When they are looking into expansion, they realise that their
current investment for automation is not tailored for Internet and
therefore they have double investments.'' He noted that today the
trend is to invest in technology which can do both functions.
	   Rafee also said that IT should be looked at as a future
investment and business opportunity, rather than a short-term cost
problem.
	   ``People are looking at IT as a cost problem and as such, they
are losing money by investing in it. I say, look at IT as a
business opportunity and as a strategic investment to expand your
business.'' He added that initially, many companies think about
reducing cost but what they fail to recognise is the tremendous
opportunities available as a result of investing in IT.
	   He said because many are focusing on IT as only a tool that
improves their efficiency and productivity, it appears to them as a
cost item.
	   ``I am not saying that this is wrong. That must be done but at
the same time, to increase your revenue you must do both,'' he
urged.
	   Asked how far the current economic climate has affected the IT
sector, Rafee said it is too early to judge although some IT
companies have been hit by the situation.
	   Nevertheless, he said a Website has been created for those who
are looking for opportunities in MSC companies.
	   ``The Multimedia Super Corridor is the indicator of our IT
industry and at the end of 1997 and early 1998, it was moving in
the same direction, that is, growing as fast. We are assuming
therefore that the opportunities are there.
	   ``We are taking these opportunities to create or re-engineer a
change by encouraging those who are in other industries to take the
opportunities in the MSC.'' Looking at the positive aspect of
layoffs of IT professionals, he said: ``Where we earlier had
difficulties getting knowledgeable workers in the MSC, today
because of the economic downturn, professionals who were in other
industries can focus more on the MSC.
	   ``Therefore, the MSC is growing. On the other hand, the IT
industry in Malaysia is affected as they are dependant on the local
companies for their businesses and they are affected.
	   ``We hope this idea of IT to increase productivity and
efficiency is there, and this is a time to invest in IT. Where one
can no longer sustain labour intensive activities, IT can
definitely help.'' Rafee said generally, e-commerce is thought of
as an ability to use IT in telecommunications and computer
technology to enable us to do better business and to expand
business.
	   E-business is viewed as anything to do with electronic and
computer business that helps trading or helps people to do business
- everything that has to do with facilitating trade.
	   ``Today we have to rethink the use of technology to facilitate
trade and business,'' he noted.
	   To improve the software development industry in the region, an
exhibition called Software Development Asia '98 will be held from
July 7 to 9 at the Putra World Trade Centre in Kuala Lumpur.
	   
</TEXT>
