<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Dugarry header gives French 1-0 lead
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: NOTE change of John Moshoeu for Themba Mnguni in starting
lineups. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MARSEILLE, France (AP) _ Substitute Christophe Dugarry
back-headed a corner from Zinedine Zidane in the 34th minute,
giving France a 1-0 lead over South Africa in the World Cup opener
for both teams Friday night.
	   Dugarry, who came on as a substitute for Stephane Guivarc'h only
seven minutes before, beat South African keeper Hans Vonk to the
corner and flicked it with the back of his head inside the far
post.
	   It was the finale in a series of chances the French created in
quick succession. Only a minute after coming on, Dugarry broke in
on Vonk unmarked, only to have the South African keeper come
quickly off his line to snuff out the threat.
	   The game started slowly with South Africa limited to one
legitimate chance in the entire half. Brandan Augustine's free kick
from 25 meter was blocked by Emmanuel Petit.
	   But Zidane, a best friend of Dugarry and whom many think is
responsible for the reserve's place on the team, created two
chances in the first 17 minutes on free kicks.
	   His first from 25 meters in the second minute skidded wide of
the right post and his second went over the bar.
	   A strong wind that blew toward the South African goal seemed to
hurt the World Cup debutante's clearances and long pases from the
back. But the French were clearly dominant, gaining control of the
game after the first 15 minutes.
	   One of South Africa's few dangerous moments came in the 20th
minute when French keeper Fabien Barthez had to come out to the top
of the box to chest away a bounding through ball. After getting to
the ball, he collided with Benedict McCarthy and was knocked off
his feet before the ball was cleared from danger.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; Lineups &QC; 
	   France: Fabien Barthez; Lilian Thuram, Laurent Blanc, Marcel
Desailly, Bixente Lizarazu; Didier Deschamps, Zinedine Zidane,
Emmanuel Petit; Youri Djorkaeff, Stephane Guivarc'h (Christophe
Dugarry, 27th minute), Thierry Henry.
	   South Africa: Hans Vonk; Willem Jackson, Pierre Issa, Lucas
Radebe, Mark Fish; David Nyathi, John Moshoeu, Quinton Fortune,
Brendan Augustine; Benni McCarthy, Philemon Masinga.
	   Referee: Maurizio Rezende, Brazil.
</TEXT>
