<HEADLINE>
Metacorp submits plan to upgrade roads, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Metacorp submits plan to upgrade roads, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Jimmy YeowASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   METACORP Bhd, a toll road operator and property developer, said
it has submitted a proposal to the Government to upgrade several
congested roads in the Klang Valley leading into Kuala Lumpur city.
	   The company is proposing to upgrade the road from the Loke Yew
roundabout to Bank Negara, from Taman Melawati to Jalan Pahang and
from the Jalan Pahang-Jalan Tun Razak roundabout to the city,
Metacorp chief executive officer Yusli Mohamed Yusoff said.
	   Speaking to reporters after Metacorp`s annual general meeting
yesterday, he said the company made its presentation to the Works
Ministry about a year ago, but declined to disclose the project
cost.
	   Yusli said many motorists had complained that it was unfair for
them to pay toll to use the upgraded stretches which only led to
traffic-congested roads.
	   ``However, the road users are not aware that these bottlenecks
are beyond our concession areas and there is nothing the company
can do,'' he pointed out.
	   ``As such, Metacorp is proposing to upgrade these congested
stretches to ease the traffic flow into the city,'' Yusli said.
	   If the Government gives the green light for the project, the
alternative for the company to recoup its huge investment is to
seek the extension of the toll collection period on its four
concessions, which ends between 2003 and 2018, and some toll
increase.
	   ``This is because no more toll booths can be build along the
concession stretches as that will slow down the traffic flow,''
Yusli said.
	   He said the company collects about RM60 million in tolls a year
from its four concessions at Jalan Cheras, Jalan Pahang, East-West
Link Expressway and Sungei Besi Expressway.
	   The company exprienced a 1 per cent drop in traffic using its
toll roads. Yusli said this was partly due to people travelling by
other transport modes and the traffic diversion with the opening of
more roads.
	   On property development, he said Metacorp's UK subsidiary Precis
(1474) Ltd has a one-third interest in Spitalfields Holdings Ltd
and Spitalfields Development Group.
	   A large part of the Spitalfields site was sold to London
International Financial Futures &AMP; Options Exchange (Liffe) in
April. Part of the proceeds from the transaction was used to reduce
the group`s borrowings by STG10 million (STG1  &QC;  RM6.51).
	   Meanwhile, Datuk Mohamed Ishak Mohamed Ariff, Mr David Willian
Berry  &LR;  Dayan Wazir Berry and Encik Marzuki Rafie were re-elected
as directors of the company.
	   The results of their re-election were delayed by the counting of
votes, as the shareholders requested the voting to be carried out
by ballots rather than a show of hands.
	   In his statement to shareholders, Mohamed Ishak said that
barring any further deterioration of the economy, the directors
expect the financial performance of the group for 1998 to exceed
that of 1997 with the anticipated increase from its overseas
investment.
	   
</TEXT>
