<HEADLINE>
Two ex-aides of former MB arrested (HL), NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Two ex-aides of former MB arrested (HL), NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   R.V. VeeraASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Thurs. - Two ex-aides of a former Selangor Menteri
Besar were arrested today by the Anti-Corruption Agency for
allegedly using their position in connection with a land deal.
	   One of them is alleged to have accepted a RM1.2 million bribe
from a person with whom he had official business dealings.
	   Both were alleged to have misused their positions in connection
with a land application from a company in which they had a vested
interest.
	   An ACA statement issued today confirmed that the ex-aides, aged
46 and 54, from a former Selangor Menteri Besar's office in Shah
Alam, were arrested by ACA superintendents Hishamuddin Hashim and
Alias Salim about 10.20am when they turned up at the ACA
headquarters in Persiaran Duta.
	   They had been earlier asked to report to the agency's Economic
Investigation Department.
	   The two will be charged under section 2(1) of the Emergency
(Essential Powers) Ordinance 22/1970 in the Shah Alam Sessions
Court tomorrow morning.
	   The section states that any public officer who has used his
public position or office for his pecuniary or other advantage
shall be guilty of an offence and shall be liable to a maximum fine
of RM20,000 or 14 years' jail or both upon conviction.
	   The ACA said one of them, currently attached to the Ministry of
Rural Development, would, in addition, face four charges under
section 165 of the Penal Code, for allegedly accepting a RM1.2
million bribe.
	   He will be charged under section 165 of the Penal Code at the
Sessions Court in Kuala Lumpur tomorrow afternoon.
	   Anyone convicted under section 165 is liable to be imprisoned up
to two years or fined or both.
	   The ACA investigation followed a report lodged by Pas Youth
secretary Mahfuz Omar with its Selangor headquarters in Shah Alam
on Dec 29.
	   The investigation focused on alleged corrupt practices and
misuse of powers in connection with the conversion of a 40ha forest
area in Bukit Sungai Putih, Hulu Langat, involving the ex-aides of
the former Menteri Besar.
	   It was reported that the land was gazetted as a forest reserve
in 1972, but the State Executive Council decided in 1990 to
degazette it.
	   The land was originally part of the Bukit Sungai Putih forest
reserve and had been earmarked for mixed development after a
logging licence was given to a company.
	   ACA officers interviewed and took statements from all parties
involved in the decision-making including State Forestry Department
officers and State executive councillors, past and present.
	   During a follow-up action in December 1996, ACA officers said
they found one of the two ex-aides with about RM1.5 million in his
car, parked at his house in Shah Alam.
	   The two former aides spent over an hour at the ACA headquarters
today before posting bail.
	   One of them was released on RM400,000 bail while the other was
released on RM200,000 bail.
	   
</TEXT>
