<BODY>
<SLUG> CHICKEN-SAFEST-MEAT-CHUA sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chicken safest meat in the country: Chua, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Chicken safest meat in the country: Chua, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Hamisah HamidASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   CHICKEN is probably the country's safest meat as it is mostly
free from the cancer-causing nitrofuran antibiotic, Health Minister
Datuk Chua Jui Meng announced yesterday.
	   From the 135 random samples of chicken meat and eggs collected
throughout the country between the first four months this year,
only 3.7 per cent or five samples of the meat have been found to
have residues of nitrofuran. The eggs were also nitrofuran-free.
	   The tests were conducted by the ministry at its nine food
laboratories nationwide, he told a press conference in Kuala Lumpur
after chairing a meeting with Non-Governmental Organisations
(NGOs).
	   ``Today, some 96.3 per cent of chicken breeders and sellers
abide the regulations in banning the use of nitrofuran.
	   ``As such, it can be said that chicken meat and eggs are safe
for eating,'' he said.
	   The Cabinet, realising the danger of the use of nitrofuran by
chicken breeders as a growth-promoter, decided to ban its use on
August 21 1996.
	   Those who flout the regulations are liable to five years'
imprisonment and/or fine (unlimited) under the Food and Drugs Act
1952. Five chicken sellers have been brought to Court and one has
been fined RM4,000 or three months' jail.
	   Before the ban was imposed, the use of nitrofuran was widespread
in the country.
	   Immediately after the ban, the ministry found that 51 per cent
of the 142 samples of chicken meats nationwide showed residues of
the chemical.
	   At at the end of last year, some 53,000kg of nitrofuran were
surrendered to the ministry. Of the total, 48,000kg were exported
to countries which allow the use of nitrofuran while the rest were
destroyed.
	   Chua expressed confidence that the ministry's target to have 0
per cent use of nitrofuran in chickens by the end of this year can
be achieved.
	   The ministry will continue to take samples of chicken meat and
eggs from the farms and markets for tests at its laboratories.
	   The minister also said that the ministry is also monitoring the
use of beta-agonist to feed pigs and some cattle as it is against
the Food and Drugs Act.
	   The chemical has side-effects on humans, especially those with
cardiovascular problems and diabetics.
	   Earlier in his speech, Chua stressed the importance of
accountability and integrity in the administration of NGOs.
	   The Finance Ministry has set a condition that NGOs, which
receive financial assistance from the Government, are bound by
certain guidelines.
	   One such guideline is that the NGOs have to keep the money they
get from Government separate from other financial assistance
received from other agencies.
	   ``The NGOs also have to submit a progress report of a project
and financial report within 30 days after the project begins as
well as the final report on the project.
	   ``They should not go against the Government's or the ministry's
policies and must allow the ministry to conduct checks and audit
any project or sit on any committee,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:CHICKEN-SAFEST-MEAT-CHUA sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
