<HEADLINE>
Another rough night for Chempaka, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Another rough night for Chempaka, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Timothy LeonardASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   NS CHEMPAKA will have a tough battle on their hands when they
take on Malacca in the opening Premier Two second round match at
the Kubu Stadium tonight.
	   Regaining their confidence will be their first battle especially
after their 3-0 defeat to Perak in the FA Cup second round second
leg match at the Paroi Stadium on Tuesday.
	   Chempaka, currently second in the table behind league leaders
Terengganu with 12 points after seven matches, are in no position
to expect an easy win even though they have beaten Malacca 3-0
before at the Paroi Stadium.
	   This is because Chempaka will be without several key players who
are out due to injury and suspensions whereas Malacca look to be in
great form after having thrashed the more experienced Premier One
side Negri Sembilan 4-1 (5-2 on aggregate) in the FA Cup second
round.
	   Yusafizan Johar, the top scorer of the team with five goals,
would most probably be out as he is still suffering from the ankle
injury he sustained against Police two weeks ago.
	   Meanwhile defenders R. Michael and Fatawu Ibrahim will miss
tonight's game after collecting two yellow cards each.
	   However, midfielder V. Arumugan, who was out in the recent FA
Cup match due to a hamstring injury is back and will support
Stephen Abarowei and Roshan Pereira on the forwardline.
	   ``The players have to work very hard and must have the
concentration and self-confidence to win the match,'' said team
coordinator K.
	   Dharmarajasingham.
	   ``With the FA Cup out of our reach, we have to concentrate on
the Malaysia Cup,'' he added.
	   
</TEXT>
