<HEADLINE>
FAS Council want Aini out, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
FAS Council want Aini out, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   S. NavalanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE FA of Selangor (FAS) council convened an emergency meeting
yesterday and agreed that their president, Datuk Aini Taib, has to
go.
	   Aini did not attend the meeting held at a hotel in Kuala Lumpur
but 21 of the 27 elected council members turned up.
	   Nineteen of the members called on Aini to step down gracefully
or the council would convene an extraordinary general meeting and
do the needful.
	   According to vice-president Datuk Mokhtar Ahmad, the reason for
the meeting last night was because they have lost faith in Aini as
he had failed to bring in funds and to settle debts incurred last
year.
	   The council said that when Aini took over as team manager of the
Selangor side in 1993, they were no debts. And when Aini became
president two year later, they had ample funds including RM100,000
in fixed deposits.
	   However, Selangor now have a debt of RM1.6 million.
	   And they have also yet to settle the income tax for former
striker Tony Cottee who played for them about six months.
	   ``We have done all we could do to get Aini to find ways to ease
our financial problems,'' said Mokhtar.
	   ``But there has been nothing from his side to this day. So it is
best we find a new president who can get the funds to run our
team.''
	   It is understood that Menteri Besar Datuk Abu Hassan Omar has
been approached to take over as president.
	   Apparently Abu Hassan has promised the FAS council members that
should he not want the job, he will nominate a candidate who will
be able to bring in funds.
	   Already faced with a RM1.6 milllion debt, the gate takings this
season has dropped drastically.
	   Selangor who used to get an average attendance of 45,000 per
match in past seasons now average 5,000.
	   According to Mokhtar, Aini was informed on Sunday about last
night's emergency council meeting.
	   ``However, he informed us that he will not attend the meeting,''
said Mokhtar.
	   ``But we decided to go ahead with the meeting. The FAS legal
officers advised that that we were within our right to continue
with this meeting.''
	   Mokhtar added they will now write to Aini explaining why they
want him to step down and will wait for his answer before taking
the next course of action.
	   
</TEXT>
