<HEADLINE>
Now Sarawak look at the Malaysia Cup, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Now Sarawak look at the Malaysia Cup, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Martin YeeASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   FOR Sarawak manager coach Alan Vest there is still hope this
season even though their FA Cup campaign came to an end when
Selangor edged them 3-2 on aggregate.
	   According to Vest, his team bowed out of the FA Cup with their
heads high knowing fully well that injury problems that ravaged the
team ruled out any realistic challenge.
	   Even then, they had displayed sheer guts despite their odds in
the FA Cup.
	   Now with the near return to fitness of a few key players, they
are focussing on the Malaysia Cup, with Premier One title almost
out of their hands.
	   Troubled by injuries to nine players throughout the season in
what is his worst season, Vest's hopes is raised with the return of
Billy Bone and Shamsurin Abdul Rahman - two players who had been
out for months and had not been physically nor match fit when they
played in the last match against Selangor.
	   The progress of key players on the injured list who had at least
started to train in the past few days like Alistair Edwards,
playmaker Nazri Yunos and defender Ahmad Fairuz Yunus put the smile
back on Vest.
	   Shamsurin Abdul Rahman did not impress in the last match and
Vest is keeping his fingers crossed that of all players, Edwards
can turn out to be the out-and-out striker that his team did not
have all these matches.
	   ``There is light at the end of the tunnel with several players
like Alistair (Edwards), Nazri (Yunus), Dave (Evans) starting to
train. They should be ready in the next few weeks,'' said Vest.
	   ``Even with so many players down with injuries throughout the
season, nobody had hammered us by more than three goals. Can you
imagine even for a team like Pahang with nine of their regulars
out?
	   ``We hang in there and even though we lost to several top teams
by the odd goals.
	   ``We had a `patched-up' team playing on sheer guts to carry them
through the whole season.
	   ``Even against Selangor in the FA Cup, what do you expect from
us with two players like Shamsurin (Abdul Rahman) and Billy (Bone)
who had not seen action for months,'' said Vest.
	   Now that their FA Cup campaign is ended and with the Premier One
title looking a distant dream, Vest will be concentrating on
getting his men prepared for the tilt at the Malaysia Cup, a
realistic target.
	   
</TEXT>
