<SLUG> BC-Lebanon-Child Custody </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Husband of Brazilian woman accused of breaking custody, forgery
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) _ A Lebanese man who took his children from
his estranged wife in Brazil was accused by a prosecutor Friday of
breaking child custody and forgery.
	   Prosecutor Joseph Khalil ordered that Atef Abbas, 38, be kept in
detention for ``the crime of breaking child custody and forging a
permit allowing their travel.''
	   Abbas, who was detained early this month while under
investigation, could be jailed for up to three years if convicted.
	   He has been locked in a bitter custody battle with his estranged
Brazilian wife, Vagna Bandeira, who came to Lebanon on May 9 and
went on a hunger strike in the Brazilian Embassy after failing to
persuade the authorities to return her two sons, who are living
with their father in eastern Lebanon.
	   Bandeira, 35, broke the strike after two weeks and filed a suit
against her husband in the courts. She has returned to Brazil.
	   Abbas is wanted in Brazil for taking his sons while they were in
Bandeira's legal custody and bringing them to Lebanon. He is
alleged to have forged his wife's signature on a travel permit for
the boys, Hamze, 4, and Bilal, 2.
	   Abbas has denied the Brazilian accusations.
	   The couple separated in April 1997 in Brazil and the children
lived with their mother until Abbas brought them to Lebanon.
	   Friday's decision turned the case over to an investigating
magistrate, who will either formally charge Abbas or dismiss the
accusations.
	   The prosecutor's order placed him under arrest until trial, bond
or dismissal of the case.
 &UR; sfg-jbm
</TEXT>
