<HEADLINE>
Not all look to be right for the MHF job, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Not all look to be right for the MHF job, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   M.K. MeganASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   FORMING a committee to analyse the national hockey team's dismal
performance at the World Cup in Utrecht, Holland, which ended early
this month, was indeed a wise move by the Malaysian Hockey
Federation (MHF).
	   However, not all the individuals selected to serve in this
committee may be the right choice.
	   No doubt all of them come with impressive credentials but how
many have been directly involved in hockey in recent times and,
more importantly, how many of them really have the time.
	   The committee members are R. Yogeswaran, Ho Koh Chye, M.P.
Haridass, Poon Fook Loke and National Sports Council director
general Datuk Mazlan Ahmad.
	   Ho was a talented player and capable coach. But that was all
before 1978 while Yogeswaran's last assignment as the national
coach was 16 years ago.
	   Haridass coached the national women's team a long time ago and
has not been actively involved in hockey since then.
	   All these people are now busy with their own career and it has
nothing to do with hockey.
	   So, will they have the time to analyse the national team's
performance, an exercise which obviously cannot be done within a
day or two if a realistic conclusion is to be reached.
	   Furthermore the game itself has changed drastically since their
days.
	   Can they use their experience of playing or coaching on grass to
analyse a match currently being played on synthetic pitch, and that
too with so many changes to the rules.
	   And they are supposed to present their recommendation to Paul
Lissek, one of the world's best coaches. Lissek will be in charge
of the national team for the next three months for the Commonwealth
Games.
	   Lissek arrives in Kuala Lumpur today.
	   Ho is the sports advisor to the Johor State Govenment, Haridass
is with the Olympic Council of Malaysia, and Yogeswaran works for a
bank.
	   Poon still plays hockey and looks a suitable choice.
	   Another question is the appointment of Yogeswaran as the team
manager to replace S. Kali Kavandan.
	   Yogeswaran is already the 2001 Junior World Cup team manager and
he also has a health problem.
	   Managing the national team is no easy task and whether
Yogeswaran can take the strenuous task is left to be seen.
	   We have to bear in mind that the team are already preparing for
the Commonwealth Games in September and Asian Games in December.
	   It was learnt that competitions committee chairman Thasleem
Ibrahim was earlier proposed for the job but the coaching committee
decided against him.
	   They apparently wanted a man with some coaching knowledge to
manage the national team and counter proposed Yogeswaran.
	   They have not learnt that a manager who has coaching experience
may unwittingly interfere with the coach's job like what happened
during the 1996 Asian Junior championship in Singapore.
	   There was some misunderstanding between team manager V.
Sivapathasundram and coach Stephen van Huizen. Sivapathasundram
was, at that time, coaching in Negri Sembilan.
	   Finally Sivapathasundram had to resign to give van Huizen a free
hand with the team.
	   
</TEXT>
