<HEADLINE>
Zahid calls for quick action, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Zahid calls for quick action, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   IPOH, Thurs. - Authorities at the district level have been urged
to take immediate action to be in line with the Government's
decision to do away with the ``umbrella concept'' in awarding minor
contracts.
	   Umno Youth leader Datuk Ahmad Zahid Hamidi said today the
movement had proof of abuse of the concept by selected credible and
established contractors and it was timely that the concept be
abolished.
	   He said most big-time contractors who were supposed to
distribute work to smaller contractors awarded projects only to
Class F contractors linked to them.
	   As a result, many contractors faced hardship and would wind up
if the concept continued to be practised.
	   Ahmad Zahid was speaking after the launching of the State-level
Bank Simpanan Nasional Employees Savings Scheme by Menteri Besar
Tan Sri Ramli Ngah Talib.
	   He said the credible and established contractors were also not
transparent in awarding jobs.
	   Deputy Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim today announced
the Government's decision to stop allocating new minor contracts
under the umbrella concept and would instead revert to the old
system of awarding work directly.
	   The decision followed numerous complaints from small-time
contractors who were unhappy over the distribution of contract
jobs, particularly for rural projects.
	   Under the concept, each State has a credible and established
contractor handling Government contracts worth up to RM15 million
and it is supposed to distribute jobs to the smaller contractors.
	   
</TEXT>
