<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-NATO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yugoslavia talks tough to NATO; Montenegro takes different stand
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo BEL101 &QL; 
 &UR; By MISHA SAVIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ If NATO intervenes in secessionist
Kosovo, the Yugoslav army would treat the alliance as an intruder
and ``defend the territory ... with all means available,'' a top
aide to President Slobodan Milosevic said Friday.
	   Zoran Lilic, a close Milosevic aide who was Yugoslavia's
president until last year and is now a deputy premier, told The
Associated Press he hoped there would never be a clash between NATO
and Yugoslavia.
	   He made clear that Serbia, which with Montenegro makes up
Yugoslavia, does not regard Kosovo's violence as an all-out war
with dangerous regional consequences.
	   Washington, he said, should get Albanian militants to cease
fire, adding that action by government forces would then
automatically cease.
	   ``We know that in a clash with NATO _ it's stupid even to think
about that _ we don't stand a chance,'' Lilic said. ``But it is its
(Yugoslav army's) duty to defend the territory against anybody who
tries to enter by force.''
	   ``We would have to defend the territory ... with all means
available for as long as we could,'' he said.
	   Serbia's southern province of Kosovo has been on the verge of
all-out war that could spread to neighboring countries. Ethnic
Albanians, who outnumber Serbs about nine to one in Kosovo, want
independence and are increasingly prepared to fight for it.
	   More than 250 people have died in clashes since government
forces in March began a crackdown on Albanian militants, known as
the Kosovo Liberation Army.
	   Lilic said fighting occurred only in some parts of Kosovo and
it's not an all-out Serb-Albanian war, just a clash ``between
security forces and the terrorists.''
	   ``The United States can play a key role if they exert pressure
on Albanians to cease terrorist actions _ which would mean an
automatic halt of actions by the police,'' Lilic said.
	   In 1989, trying to quash Albanians' push for independence and
claiming to protect the Kosovo Serb cause he had espoused to gain
power, Milosevic revoked the province's broad autonomy.
	   But nine years of heavy-handed Serbian rule, enforced with a
strong police and army presence, have only fanned demands for
independence. The peaceful course pursued by ethnic Albanian
political leaders is losing ground to KLA militancy.
	   Kosovo's Albanians, protesting Serbia's rule, have boycotted all
Serbian elections since 1990, and founded alternative schools and
hospitals since being sacked or quitting most state jobs that year.
	   Lilic called on ethnic Albanians to use the rights they still
have and thus win local elections and return to Serbia's
parliament, where they can easily win at least 30 of the 250 seats.
	   Lilic denied government forces use brutality against Albanian
civilians. Foreign diplomats allowed into the region of the most
recent severe fighting in western Kosovo saw scenes of devastation
reminiscent of Bosnia, with houses burned and shelled.
	   Claiming the KLA are ``actually Muslim fundamentalists'', Lilic
reiterated Yugoslav accusations against neighboring Albania,
accusing it of training and arming the rebels.
	   ``The issue is not independent Kosovo. It's about expansion of
Albania,'' he said.
	   Also Friday, the president of Montenegro, Serbia's only
remaining partner in the Yugoslav federation, indicated he might
withdraw recruits from his republic from the army if it became
implicated in atrocities.
	   Montenegrin President Milo Djukanovic, who is at odds with
Milosevic, told reporters in his capital, Podgorica that the
Yugoslav army ``must carry out its constitutional function, to
protect ... Yugoslavia's border.''
	   But if the army gets drawn into conflicts between the KLA and
the Serbian police, ``that would be a warning sign for me'' to hold
urgent meetings ``in order for us to reach decisions, on the basis
of knowledge, regarding the participation of recruits from
Montenegro in the Yugoslav Army,'' Djukanovic added.
	   A letter from a Yugoslav army soldier published in the Belgrade
independent daily Glas last week said the army was giving police
logistic support such as heavy guns, and had plans to help raze
suspected KLA hideouts and villages.
	   Striking a different note than Lilic, Djukanovic said that if
NATO intervened in Kosovo, and bombs fall ``on the innocent
population, on our innocent brethren in Yugoslav army uniforms,
then it would not be bombs dropped by NATO but by those _ on both
sides _ who have decided, instead of negotiations, to again lead
peoples against one another.''
	   (ms/as)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Yugoslavia-NATO; CT:i; 
