<HEADLINE>
Sabah Umno told to get ready for elections, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Sabah Umno told to get ready for elections, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Joniston BangkuaiASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KOTA KINABALU, Thurs. - The 20 Umno divisions in Sabah have been
directed to streamline and reactivate their election machinery,
including determining the status of party members.
	   State Umno leaders will be visiting the respective divisions to
ensure that the party machinery, especially election operation
centres, are in place.
	   ``We must make sure that the party is fully prepared to face the
State election,'' Datuk Osu Sukam told a Press conference after
chairing the State Umno liaison committee meeting last night.
	   Except for Tawau Umno division chief, Datuk Abdul Ghapur Salleh,
who had recently declined to be re-appointed Deputy Chief Minister
and Finance Minister, all party divisional heads were present.
	   Sabah Umno Youth chief, Jema Khan Datuk Majid, and State Umno
Wanita head, Senator Datuk Norjan Khan Bahadar, also attended the
meeting.
	   ``Discussion at the meeting was mainly focused on preparations
for the State election which is expected to be held soon,'' Osu
said.
	   He added that the respective Umno bureaus had been asked to
conduct relevant courses for leaders and members at branch levels.
	   Osu, who replaced Ghapur as Deputy Chief Minister and Finance
Minister, said Umno division leaders had been directed to work
closely with leaders of Barisan Nasional component parties in their
respective divisions.
	   He said a close working relationship among BN component parties
at all levels was vital to ensure the BN's victory in the State
election.
	   Also discussed at the meeting was the squatter problem.
	   Osu said Sabah Umno viewed the problem seriously and hoped that
a solution could be found.
	   ``All Umno divisions in the State have been directed to gather
information on the problem to compile a report to be submitted to
the State Government for action,'' he said.
	   The number of squatters and the total area occupied by them were
among the data needed to ensure speedy solution to the problem.
	   He said the customary rights of locals who had settled in
Government land for the last 12 years needed to be considered in
solving the matter.
	   
</TEXT>
