<HEADLINE>
US$500m fund waiting for the right time, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
US$500m fund waiting for the right time, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   pratap ParameswaranASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUMPULAN Guthrie Bhd has raised US$500 million (US$1  &QC;  RM4.00)
for its Guthrie-Koll Fund and is now waiting for the right time to
enter the Malaysian property market.
	   The money was raised from various investment groups in the US,
chairman Tan Sri Abdul Khalid Ibrahim said yesterday.
	   ``We are waiting for the property and the currency markets to
stabilise,'' he said.
	   The US$500 million property investment fund, a result of the
collaboration with US-based Koll Real Estate Group Inc, will be
jointly managed by both parties.
	   The group had been on a roadshow in the US to woo major
insurance companies and pension funds to put their money in the
fund to buy properties in the country which would be leased to US
companies operating here.
	   The properties that the fund would most likely focus on would be
properties or real estate which are in need of financial
assistance.
	   Khalid told reporters this after Guthrie Ropel Bhd's annual
general meeting in Kuala Lumpur yesterday. Kumpulan Guthrie has a
58.35 per cent share in Guthrie Ropel.
	   The company, an oil palm and rubber producer, he said, would see
an improved performance this year as the company had seen higher
oil palm production and also better prices.
	   He also said the exchange rate fluctuations have had no impact
on rubber prices as opposed to palm oil prices which improve in
relation to the depreciation of the ringgit.
	   According to Khalid, due to the current depressed property
market, the company ``will be unlikely to invest in the property
sector in 1998,'' he said, adding that the company will concentrate
on oil palm and rubber production.
	   At the end of 1997, a total of 626.53ha has been earmarked for
property development.
	   Meanwhile, Khalid also said that Malaysia should opt out of the
International Natural Rubber Organisation (Inro) as the
organisation is only benefitting the consumer countries.
	   Independent of an organisation that is trying to control rubber
prices that will only be to the advantage of the non-producing
countries, he said.
	   Since Malaysia is both a producer and user of rubber, it is not
necessary to protect only the users or rubber consuming countries,
he said. ``It is in the best interest to allow rubber prices to
find its own level,'' said Khalid.
	   This, he said, would be a good thing as ``rubber producers can
find the genuine level of rubber prices and determine whether they
want to continue producing rubber''.
	   Primary Industries Minister Datuk Seri Dr Lim Keng Yaik had said
that Malaysia will immediately pull out of Inro if Thailand
withdraws from the organisation.
	   Malaysia, he said, shared Thailand's frustration over Inro's
inability to support natural rubber prices at a fair and equitable
level.
	   Khalid also said that, ``... if the prices of rubber are
dependent on supply and demand, chances are that they can get to a
level when prices reflect the currency situation''.
	   Current rubber prices did not reflect the depreciation of the
ringgit, he said.
	   Although the three major natural rubber producing countries -
Indonesia, Thailand and Malaysia - had faced significant currency
depreciation, natural rubber prices were in fact cheaper in terms
of the US dollar and European currencies now than a year ago.
	   
</TEXT>
