<HEADLINE>
Muhyiddin: Only the best will do, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Muhyiddin: Only the best will do, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Zakri BaharudinASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SPORTS associations are required to name their athletes for the
Kuala Lumpur Commonwealth Games by the end of this month.
	   Sports Minister Tan Sri Muhyiddin Yassin said yesterday in Kuala
Lumpur he expects the respective selection committees to impose
objective minimum qualification requirements in their selection
process.
	   ``We want only the best of the best. The selectors should base
their decision on the athletes' performance, consistency and past
achievements, keeping in mind the country's interest,'' said
Muhyiddin after handing out the National Sports Council cash awards
to national shooters, taekwondo exponents and shuttlers.
	   ``However, Malaysia will not be represented in all 213 events
especially in events such as weighlifting, boxing and athletics.
	   ``And we may not be competing on the same level as some of the
other countries in some of these events, but are only participating
for the exposure.''
	   Muhyidin also said he hopes that the national sports development
project will continue after 1998.
	   ``There will be about 300 Games athletes at the final stage of
preparation. And it would be a waste if the programme does not
survive after the Games.
	   ``I am confident the associations will utilise their allocated
budgets wisely despite the current economic slowdown.
	   ``We managed to cut our budget, spending RM129 million for the
past four years (under the Jaya'98 project) to prepare the athletes
although the budget was RM160 million.
	   ``The Jaya'98 project has indeed given some very positive
results as was seen in sports like bowling, shooting and
gymnastics.
	   ``This effort must continue for at least another eight years to
reap the benefits as it would be a waste to set it aside after the
Games.''
	   According to Muhyiddin, the Cabinet had agreed to continue with
the sports development fund which is supported by contributions
from the private sector.
	   ``I understand that the Finance Ministry are looking into this
matter.''
	   The members of the Thomas Cup team, who finished second to
Indonesia at the recent Finals in Hong Kong, received RM8,000 each
while the BA of Malaysia were given RM12,000.
	   The Thomas Cup shuttlers are Cheah Soon Kit, Ong Ewe Hock,
Roslin Hashim, Yong Hock Kin, Yap Kim Hock, Wong Choong Hann, Lee
Wan Wah, Choong Tan Fook and Tan Kim Her.
	   The shooters who did well at the 22nd Seasa Championships in
Manila in February received a total of RM3,900.
	   Double gold medallist Jasni Shaari got RM2,000 while Mutalib
Razak and Sabki Mohamed Din received RM500 each.
	   Taekwondo exponents Lee Wan Yuen and S. Saravanan got RM3,000
each for the bronze medal they won at the Asian Taekwondo
Championships in Vietnam last month. Their association received
RM1,800.
	   
</TEXT>
