<HEADLINE>
Red Box considers suit against Maybank, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Red Box considers suit against Maybank, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   RED Box (Malaysia) Bhd is considering taking legal action
against Malayan Banking Bhd (Maybank), which it claims has violated
a court order restraining the bank from taking any winding up
proceedings against the company.
	   In a statement to the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange, Red Box said
Maybank had advertised a winding up petition against the company on
June 10, despite an ex-parte court order restraining the bank from
taking any such proceedings on June 8, pending hearing of the inter
parte application on the same matter scheduled for next Friday.
	   The court order was served on Messrs David Chong and Co in Johor
Baru, the solicitors acting for Maybank, on June 8.
	   ``Due to the adverse effect of the advertisement, the company is
considering pursuing legally the matter of violation of the court
order by Maybank,'' said Red Box.
	   On April 13, a winding up petition was filed by Maybank in the
Johor Baru High Court, claiming that Red Box was unable to repay
borrowings of some RM8.4 million.
	   As a result, Maybank had decided to terminate all its credit
facilities to the company.
	   However, Red Box said it had not defaulted on any payment and
had been prompt in repaying bank borrowings and interest until the
bank recalled all its credit facilities.
	   The company also said it had proposed various debt restructuring
and securitisation plans to Maybank, and was able to meet most of
the bank's terms and conditions.
	   Meanwhile, the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange announced in a
separate statement that Red Box shares have been suspended with
effect from June 10.
	   It was last traded at 40.5 sen, up 0.5 sen.
	   
</TEXT>
