<SLUG> BRITAIN'S-RM19.5M sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Britain's RM19.5m scholarship scheme for Malaysian students, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Britain's RM19.5m scholarship scheme for Malaysian students, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Carolyn HongASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Thurs. - Adding to the assistance offered earlier
by individual British universities, the British Government has
initiated a STG3 million (RM19.5 million) scholarship scheme for
Malaysian students.
	   This is part of a STG6.6 million fund set up to help Asian
students affected by the economic downturn, namely from Malaysia,
Thailand, Indonesia and South Korea.
	   British High Commissioner to Malaysia David Moss said today the
core funding came from the Foreign and Commonwealth Office, with
additional funds from the British Council which will co-ordinate
the scheme, Department of Trade and Industry in London, and British
companies.
	   Matching funds were also provided by participating British
universities.
	   The companies include Standard Chartered, Hong Kong and Shanghai
Banking Corporation, ICI, British Gas International, Unilever,
Rolls-Royce, British Airways, Reuter Foundation, BP, Coopers &AMP;
Lybrand and Price Waterhouse.
	   Moss said 1,583 Malaysian students will benefit from this
one-off assistance of STG1,600 for undergraduates and up to
STG2,000 for postgraduate students.
	   The scholarships will go towards tuition fees to enable students
to begin or continue their studies in the 1998/99 academic year
which begins in September.
	   ``With the fall in the value of the ringgit, there has been
growing concern about the financial hardships faced by Malaysian
students in the United Kingdom,'' he said at a Press conference to
announce the details of the British-Malaysia Scholarship Scheme
1998.
	   Moss said this scheme was in addition to the 72 Chevening
scholarships offered to Malaysian students by the British High
Commission each year.
	   There are about 18,000 Malaysian students in Britain. British
universities which earn about STG300 million a year from Southeast
Asian students, are expecting a substantial drop in their enrolment
this year.
	   It was reported earlier that applications from Malaysian
students this year had dropped by 36 per cent.
	   Moss said Britain attached a great deal of importance to
Malaysian students continuing to study in Britain.
	   As there are no official application forms, students should
write to their respective universities which will then select the
names to be put forward, based on merit.
	   Malaysian students holding British Government scholarships will
be not eligible.
	   However, while it was not specifically stated that Malaysians
holding scholarships which are not from the British Government were
also excluded, this factor will be considered in the selection
process.
	   Moss said ``practically all British universities'' have
introduced measures to help Malaysian students, taking the form of
scholarships, ``fees only'' awards, fee grants or discounts,
deferred payment schemes and fees set at a fixed rate in ringgit.
	   
</TEXT>
