w1814 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ForeignMinisters 6thLd-Writethru   06-12 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Foreign Ministers, 6th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World powers take action against India, Pakistan and Yugoslavia
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs; RECASTS and UPDATES throughout with new material; changes
byline &QL; 
 &UR; With BC-Kosovo-Allies &QL; 
 &UR; By EDITH M. LEDERER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Tackling two global hotspots, the world's leading
industrial nations on Friday blocked new loans to India and
Pakistan in retaliation for their nuclear tests and imposed fresh
sanctions on Yugoslavia to protest a wave of ethnic cleansing in
Kosovo.
	   Acting on a U.S. proposal, foreign ministers from eight key
nations agreed to postpone all loans to India and Pakistan except
those to meet ``basic human needs.'' India has already seen more
than dlrs 1 billion in loans delayed since its nuclear tests last
month.
	   A communique approved by the eight countries _ the United
States, Britain, France, Germany, Japan, Canada, Italy and Russia _
urged India and Pakistan to halt further tests, refrain from
building nuclear weapons, and resume a dialogue ``without delay''
to address the root causes of tensions in the region.
	   With a view to reducing tensions, it urged both countries to
avoid threatening military movements, discourage terrorist activity
and develop new confidence-building measures.
	   ``Our meeting sends the message that the world community is
united not just in outrage and dismay but in action,'' U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said. ``Today, the eight
spoke with one voice.''
	   To add moral pressure, foreign ministers from Argentina, Brazil,
South Africa and Ukraine, all of whom have given up the nuclear
option, joined the others at a lunch. So did the ambassadors of
China and the Philippines, representing the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations.
	   The ministers agreed to set up a task force with the four
nations that have eschewed nuclear weapons to help get India and
Pakistan on the same path.
	   While the Group of Eight called the London meeting to discuss
the South Asian nuclear crisis, the ministers also discussed the
Yugoslav offensive against ethnic Albanians, who account for nearly
90 percent of the population in Kosovo.
	   Calling the crackdown ``the worst violence'' in the Balkans
since Bosnia, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook announced that
the U.N. war crimes tribunal would be extended to cover war crimes
in Kosovo.
	   The United States, Britain, Germany, France, Italy and Canada
have already banned new investment in Serbia and ordered a freeze
on funds held abroad by the Yugoslav and Serbian governments.
	   They announced Friday that they would move to ban flights of
commercial Yugoslav airlines to and from their countries, a new
sanction strongly welcomed by Albright. This will require action by
the European Union in the case of the four European countries.
	   Japan agreed to consider a flight ban. But Russia, which has
close ties with Yugoslavia, did not support any of the sanctions.
	   All eight nations demanded that Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic call an immediate cease-fire, allow effective
international monitoring, facilitate the return of over 50,000
refugees who have been made homeless, and ``make rapid progress''
in talks with Albanian leaders.
	   ``President Milosevic will be making a grave mistake if he
imagines that the international community will be as slow to
respond in Kosovo as it was in Bosnia,'' Cook said.
	   ``The time available for President Milosevic to respond is
limited,'' Albright warned. ``The escalation of violence in Kosovo
is real and it is unacceptable.''
	   Russian President Boris Yeltsin in Moscow is to meet Milosevic
in Moscow next week and will push for his agreement to the demands,
Cook said.
	   If Milosevic does not respond quickly, the ministers warned of
further measures, ``including those that may require the
authorization of a United Nations Security Council resolution.''
	   Washington does not believe a Security Council resolution is
necessary to autorize NATO military action in Kosovo.
	   ``We believe we have inherent authorization to do what needs to
be done,'' said Albright, echoing Defense Secretary William Cohen's
remarks that ``a resolution may be desirable but is not required.''
	   (eml-acw)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Foreign Ministers, 6th Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
(REG:ASIA;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:INDI;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
