<BODY>
<SLUG> AWARD-OF-CONTRACTS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Award of contracts to build rural roads under umbrella concept stopped, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Award of contracts to build rural roads under umbrella concept stopped, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Ramlan SaidASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Thurs. - Deputy Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar
Ibrahim said today the awarding of government contracts to build
village roads under the umbrella concept has been stopped due to
complaints of unfair distribution.
	   He said the selection of successful contractors would now be
handled by district offices as was the practice before the concept
was introduced by the Treasury last year.
	   ``But contracts already awarded will not be affected. The
directive only involves new ones,'' he said at the presentation of
the Treasury's excellent service awards at the Finance Ministry.
	   Under the umbrella concept, each State has a reputable and
established contractor (normally Class A) handling government
contracts worth up to RM15 million under the Projek Jalan Kampung
of the Rural Development Ministry.
	   The contractor is expected to sub-contract jobs - to build
roads, bridges and related works - to small-time contractors or
Class F contractors under their ``patronage'' who are qualified to
undertake projects worth up to RM100,000.
	   Anwar, who is also Finance Minister, said feedback from State
Governments, district offices and Members of Parliament indicated
that there were problems in the awarding of minor projects under
the concept.
	   ``The programme has its merits but the implementation has drawn
many complaints, especially from small contractors in the
districts, who say they have been left out.''
	   In view of the difficult times now, Anwar said the Government
did not want to appear to be attending only to problems of big
contractors while neglecting the welfare of small-time contractors.
	   Meanwhile, Rural Development Minister Datuk Annuar Musa and
Entrepreneur Development Minister Datuk Mustapa Mohamed said they
believed the complaints of unfair distribution were due to a lack
of understanding of the concept.
	   They were speaking after a visit by Kelantan Umno leaders to the
New Straits Times office Balai Berita.
	   Annuar said the concept was introduced following comments by the
Public Accounts Committee of various weaknesses related to the
awarding of contracts to build rural roads under the open tender
system.
	   ``It is not true that the main contractors can give the job to
any Class F contractors. The selection of contractors is determined
by the Treasury.''
	   Contrary to the claims that the concept benefitted only a small
number of Class F contractors, he said some 700 of them were
expected to secure contracts this year compared to only 400 under
the open tender system.
	   He said the ministry had allocated RM50 million last year and
RM185 million this year under the PJK programme.
	   
</TEXT>
