<SLUG> BC-Guinea-Bissau-Foreigners </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. and other evacuees arrive from battle-torn Guinea-Bissau
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Guinea-Bissau &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By DAVID GUTTENFELDER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   DAKAR, Senegal (AP) _ More than 1,000 foreigners evacuated from
violence-wracked Guinea-Bissau docked in Senegal's capital Friday
after a miserable 24-hour journey on the deck of a Portuguese
merchant ship with little food or water.
	   Two other Senegalese boats carrying more of the 2,200 evacuees
who fled the troubled West African nation were expected to arrive
later Friday or early Saturday.
	   Guinea-Bissau has been wracked with scattered fighting between
government troops and renegade soldiers who launched a coup attempt
on Sunday, prompting an exodus by water and land.
	   The initial evacuees, who numbered more than 1,000, were mainly
Senegalese, but also included a number of American, Canadian,
Portuguese, German, Japanese, French, Brazilian and Cape Verdian
nationals.
	   Emotional reunions occured between some of the boat passengers
and family members and embassy staff who had waited several hours
at the main port.
	   The first person off the ship _ an American woman employed by
the U.S. embassy in the capital, Bissau _ raised her fist in
triumph as she strode down the ramp onto the crowded dock.
	   ``We are hoping that between the Portuguese vessel and later the
Senegalese boat today that we will have the vast majority of
Americans in Guinea-Bissau out,'' said David Wagner, a diplomat
with the U.S. Embassy in Dakar. It was not immediately clear how
many Americans were in Guinea-Bissau.
	   Portuguese and Senegalese soldiers helped entire families off
the boat, including a U.S. missionary, Fred Wieger, and his wife
and two small children.
	   Wieger, of York, Pennsylvania, told a harrowing tale of how his
family had driven fearfully through the streets of Bissau filled
with troops and wounded people _ both soldiers and civilians.
	   ``It was very intense and at times there were mortars that
landed 200 meters from our boat, so we had to hit the deck while we
were waiting for the ship,'' Wieger said. He said he saw wounded on
streets patrolled by soldiers.
	   ``We had to leave when the heavy artillery began and kept going.
Everything intensified,'' he said.
	   In Britain, the Foreign Office urged the 15 Britons believed to
be in Guinea-Bissau to leave. It said its warning was
``cautionary'' and that they were in no immediate danger.
	   (dg-gam-bk)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Guinea-Bissau-Foreigners; CT:i; 
