<HEADLINE>
30pc drop in industrial accidents in Penang, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
30pc drop in industrial accidents in Penang, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PENANG, Thurs. - Penang has recorded a 30 per cent decrease in
the number of industrial accidents over the past four years.
	   A total of 13,337 industrial accidents occurred in 1994, while
last year there were only 9,400 such cases.
	   Chief Minister Tan Sri Dr Koh Tsu Koon today said while the dip
reflected the high level of awareness and commitment among
employers, there was a need for greater commitment, especially from
factories in the State.
	   ``Despite there being 743 factories located in Penang
Development Corporation industrial parks, only 113 have set up
emergency response teams,'' he said when launching the State-level
Health and Industrial Safety Week at the polo ground.
	   ``This figure constitutes not even a quarter of ERTs in Penang's
factories and employers should rectify this situation.''
	   Also present at the event, themed A Safe and Healthy Work
Culture, were Fire and Rescue Services Department director-general
Datuk Dr Soh Chai Hock and State Human Resources Committee chairman
Datuk Dr Kang Chin Seng.
	   In urging more factories to set up ERTs, Koh said the State Fire
and Rescue Services Department was ready to assist factories with
such efforts.
	   ``The challenges being faced by employers as a result of the
economic problems should not be an excuse to compromise the health
and safety of workers.
	   ``Workers are assets whose sacrifices had enabled everyone to
enjoy the good times,'' he said.
	   ``Since they are the ones whose efforts are needed to promote
the nation's economic recovery, we must ensure that their working
conditions are conducive to producing proactive and hardworking
workers,'' he added.
	   
</TEXT>
