	   ALOR STAR, Thurs. - Yang di-Pertuan Agong Tuanku Ja'afar today
presented diplomas to 48 graduates in aeronautical engineering at
the Royal Malaysian Air Force flight training college in Kepala
Batas.
	   The cadets, including two Bangladeshis, were the first batch to
graduate from the three-year course.
	   They were the only graduates out of 128 who had originally
enrolled for the course in May 1995.
	   It was jointly conducted by the RMAF and Universiti Teknologi
Malaysia.
	   Some of the dropouts opted out of the course while others were
dropped after they failed academically or because of poor
disciplinary records.
	   Among the subjects included in the course were nuclear, chemical
and biological warfare, first aid and military ethics.
	   In his speech, the King called on the RMAF to strive for greater
advancement in the information technology era.
	   He also said there should be no lax in defence related
activities although the country was facing economic problems.
	   Best overall student cadet officer Baharin Mohamad, 21, was
awarded the Sultan Ahmad Shah trophy while cadet officer Khoo Heng
Giap, 26, was adjudged the best academic achiever.
	   The two Bangladeshis who received their diplomas were pilot
officer Mustafa Nazmul Alam and pilot officer Mohammad Manjoor
Elahee.
	   
</TEXT>
