	   KUALA LUMPUR, Thurs. - The High Court today dismissed an
application by MCA president Datuk Seri Dr Ling Liong Sik to review
the costs awarded to him arising from an unsuccessful libel suit by
DAP secretary-general Lim Kit Siang.
	   With the dismissal of the application, the original amount of
costs, RM29,960, to be paid by Lim remains.
	   On May 12 last year, Senior Assistant Registrar Rozielawaty Abd
Ghani had ordered Lim to pay RM29,960 as costs to Dr Ling after
Lim's defamation suit was dismissed by Judicial Commissioner Zainun
Ali on Nov 7, 1996.
	   Dr Ling, who is also the Transport Minister, had asked for costs
totalling RM104,612.50 to be taxed in his favour following the
dismissal of the suit.
	   Lim was represented by Karpal Singh while Joseph Yeo appeared
for Dr Ling.
	   Lim had sued Dr Ling and three others over an alleged statement
concerning the ``Save Bukit China'' fund published in The Star on
Aug 26, 1993.
	   In his statement of claim, Lim had contended that Dr Ling had
falsely and maliciously spoken and caused the newspaper to print
and publish the said article under the heading ``Ling: Guard
against DAP's armchair politics''.
	   Lim had named Dr Ling, The Star's editor, Star Publication (M)
Sdn Bhd and its printer Papyrus Printing Sdn Bhd as defendants.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
