<HEADLINE>
PM gets list of candidates to replace Osu Sukam, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
PM gets list of candidates to replace Osu Sukam, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KOTA KINABALU, Thurs. - Sabah Umno has forwarded to the Prime
Minister its recommendation on the potential candidates to replace
Datuk Osu Sukam as Land and Co-operative Development Minister.
	   Osu, who is Sabah Umno liaison committee chief, vacated the post
on June 8 to pave the way for his appointment as Sabah Deputy Chief
Minister and Finance Minister.
	   Speaking to reporters after chairing the State Umno liaison
meeting here last night, Osu said appointment to the Federal
Cabinet was the prerogative of Prime Minister Datuk Seri Dr
Mahathir Mohamad.
	   It was reported that the likely candidates for the post were
former Chief Minister Datuk Salleh Tun Said, Deputy Works Minister
Datuk Railey Jeffrey and Information Ministry Parliamentary
Secretary Datuk Shafie Apdal.
	   Dr Mahathir had said on June 5 that the post vacated by Osu
would be filled by a Sabah Umno leader.
	   On the position of Datuk Abdul Ghapur Salleh, who declined to be
re- appointed to the Cabinet of new Chief Minister Tan Sri Bernard
Giluk Dompok, Osu said he was still Sabah Umno deputy chief.
	   Ghapur, who is Tawau Umno division chief and Merotai
Assemblyman, did not attend the State Umno liaison meeting last
night.
	   On the sacking of 11 Umno members from Sabah for joining the
Parti Barisan Rakyat Sabah Bersekutu (Bersekutu), Osu said the
decision was made by the Supreme Council following a report from
Sabah Umno.
	   Those sacked were Datuk Askalani Abdul Rahim, Datuk Dr Zulkipli
Abdul Hamid, Lassim Abdul Rahman, Mohd Dini Khan, Mohd Topik Awang
Ajak, Naim Ahmad, Ahmas Nunsi OKK Mahadi, Uda Sulai, Isnain Amat,
Pengiran Othman Rauf and Datuk Monggoh Orow.
	   
</TEXT>
