<SLUG> BC-Read All About It,0680 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
For release Monday, June 15, and thereafter
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: The ``Read All About It'' column is a reading comprehension
exercise for children. It is written by Susan Fineman, a reading
specialist in the New Haven, Connecticut, school district. The
column is sponsored by The Associated Press and the Newspaper
Association of America Foundation.

<TEXT>
	   This column is based on an AP story that was for use on May 13.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; Conductor saves girl with kick
	   LAFAYETTE, Indiana (AP) _ The conductor on a slow-moving freight
train spotted a toddler lying on the tracks just ahead, so he
dashed to the grille at the front of the locomotive and kicked her
out of harm's way.
	   ``I just had to try something. It had to be just all
adrenaline,'' conductor Robert Mohr said Wednesday.
	   Nineteen-month-old Emily Marshall was bumped Tuesday by part of
the locomotive, and was hospitalized with just a cut on her head
and a swollen lip. She was released Wednesday.
	   Mohr spotted Emily when she was still about a city block ahead
of the Norfolk Southern train, which was moving at 24 mph (39 kph).
The girl had wandered away from home while her mother planted
flowers in her yard.
	   Engineer Rod Lindley thought it was a dog on the tracks, until
Emily raised her head at the sound of the train's whistle.
	   ``That's a baby!'' Mohr hollered.
	   Lindley hit the brakes and Mohr bolted out the door of the cab,
racing along a ledge to the front of the engine.
	   He said he realized there was no time to jump ahead of the train
and grab the baby, so he went down a set of steps, squatting at the
very bottom and hanging on.
	   As the train neared Emily, slowing to 10 mph, the little girl
rolled off the rail onto the outside of the roadbed but was still
in danger of being hit by the engine.
	   So Mohr stretched one leg out to kick her away.
	   ``I don't even remember going out the door and down the steps,''
Mohr said from his home in Denver, Indiana. ``I don't even remember
the engineer blowing the whistle. Everything was on that baby.''
	   Mohr jumped off the train and ran to the girl.
	   He picked Emily up and cradled her in his arms, and when
paramedics arrived and tried to take her, she clung to Mohr.
	   ``She didn't want me to let loose of her,'' he said.
	   Mohr, 48, who has four children of his own, said he didn't feel
like a hero.
	   ``I did what anybody would have done,'' he said.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; Fast thinking saves baby
	   Using the newspaper story, find the 10 vocabulary words and
circle them in the article. Use the context of the story to help
you figure out the meaning of each vocabulary word. Then write the
number of each word next to its correct meaning. Use a dictionary
to check your answers.
	   1) conductor. 2) squatting. 3) rail. 4) cab. 5) toddler. 6)
stretched. 7) grille. 8) paramedics. 9) bolted. 10) clung.
	   ---a) crouching; sitting on one's heels.
	   ---b) place in a locomotive where the engineer sits.
	   ---c) young child.
	   ---d) held tightly.
	   ---e) suddenly dashed; darted.
	   ---f) person in charge of a railroad train.
	   ---g) steel bar used as a track.
	   ---h) reached; extended.
	   ---i) people who are trained to give first aid.
	   ---j) covering made of pieces of metal.
	   Answer Key: a)2. b)4. c)5. d)10. e)9. f)1. g)3. h)6. i)8. j)7.
 &UR; PART TWO
 &UR; QUICK-WITTED
	   How good are you at making quick decisions? Pick one of the
three ``emergency'' story starters listed below. Tell what you
would do if you found yourself in the situation described. You'll
have to act quickly to complete this assignment.
	   1. Walking past a sewer grate on your way to school, you hear
the sounds of splashing water and a whimpering puppy.
	   2. While you and a friend are roller blading down a busy street,
your companion hits a pothole and tumbles to the ground.
	   3. As you watch a group of people play games in a lake near your
home, one of the swimmers suddenly begins yelling for help.
