<SLUG> DROUGHT-DESTROYED sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Drought destroyed 20pc of timber saplings last year, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Drought destroyed 20pc of timber saplings last year, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KANGAR, Thurs. - The seven-month-long drought starting last
November had destroyed an estimated 20 per cent of one million
timber saplings planted last year under the State reafforestation
programme.
	   Menteri Besar Datuk Seri Shahidan Kassim said persistent
outbreaks of fire in forest reserves due to prolonged dry
conditions had killed these saplings.
	   The drought had also forced the Government to defer this year's
reafforestation programme to the second half of the year.
	   ``We've set a target of planting one million saplings yearly
since the programme took off three years ago,'' he said after
chairing the State Development Committee meeting today.
	   ``Planting one million of them within six months is not beyond
reach when we're aided by the arrival of the rainy season.''
	   He said saplings to be planted comprised high-grade timber
species of teak, sentang, teja, meranti and merawan.
	   Shahidan also said some 900 farmers would be issued with an
annual permit to enable them to enter forest reserves to collect
durian and other seasonal fruits from orchards planted decades ago.
	   The orchards were opened in jungle clearings on the
Malaysia-Thai border before the Government decided to gazette the
areas as forest reserves.
	   However, Shahidan said the authorities would not compromise with
an identified 100-odd `latecomers' who began encroaching on the
reserves a decade ago.
	   
</TEXT>
