<SLUG> POLICE-TAKE-SERIOUS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police take serious view of DAP public gatherings, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Police take serious view of DAP public gatherings, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Thurs. - Police have taken a serious view of
public gatherings organised by the DAP as a show of support towards
Kota Melaka Member of Parliament Lim Guan Eng.
	   In a Press statement today, Federal police Criminal
Investigation Department director Datuk Yaacob Md Amin said police
viewed the gatherings as unlawful under the Sedition Act, 1948.
	   He said this was because the gatherings were to discuss a
sentence served on Guan Eng which he had since appealed.
	   ``As the case is still pending, the issues discussed at such
gatherings are sub judice.
	   ``The issues also insult the integrity of judges and the justice
system.
	   As such, these issues have seditious tendencies as defined under
section 3(1)(c) of the Seditions Act,'' he said, adding that
discussing the issues was an offence under section 4(1) of the same
Act.
	   Yesterday, Guan Eng and three others - party secretary-general
Lim Kit Siang's political secretary Hew Kuan Yow, Selangor DAP
committee member Wong Kok Yew and party member Lee Pin Soo - were
detained when police broke up a dinner at the Yat Yeh Hing
restaurant in SS4D/2 about 10.30pm.
	   While Guan Eng was detained for questioning for speaking at the
dinner, Hew, Wong and Lee were detained for preventing police from
carrying out their duties.
	   The dinner was held as a show of solidarity towards Guan Eng who
was handed an 18-month jail sentence by the Court of Appeals on
April 1 on two counts of publishing false news.
	   Guan Eng has since filed an appeal against the sentence.
	   Yaacob said such gatherings were deemed to be public gatherings
and as such, the organisers were required to apply for a police
licence to hold them under section 27(5) of the Police Act, 1967.
	   He added that the district police chief reserved the right to
deny such a licence to the organisers if the gathering was deemed
to be a threat to national security or would cause public disorder.
	   
</TEXT>
