<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-South Korea-Mexico, 1st Ld-Writethru,0552 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Mexico and South Korea hopes hinge on head-to-head
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: UPDATES with changes in Korean and Mexican lineups; RECASTS
throughout &QL; 
 &UR; By ERICA BULMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LYON, France (AP) _ Any hopes Mexico and South Korea entertain
of advancing past the first round of the World Cup hinge on the
outcome of their opening match on Saturday. It promises to be a
hard-fought game with so much at stake.
	   The two less-fancied teams of Group E that includes soccer-power
Netherlands and tough Belgium know that anything less than a
victory in Lyon could bring their stay in France to an early end.
	   Lineup changes on the eve of the encounter at Lyon's Gerland
stadium hinted at the strategy the coaches will use.
	   Mexico's Manuel Lapuente moved Baulio Luna, an attacking
midfielder, to left back in place of Salvador Carmona, in an effort
to bolster the defense against the fleet-footed Koreans.
	   South Korea's Cha Bum-kun decided to start 19-year-old Ko
Jong-soo at midfield in place of Seo Jung-won, the first South
Korean ever to sign with a French club when he joined Strasburg for
dlrs 1.5 million early this year.
	   Mexico has made clear that its objective is to advance to the
second round.
	   ``The match against South Korea is the most important,'' said
Lapuente. ``It's our biggest chance of earning three points, then
maybe we can get another with a tie against Belgium.
	   ``If we don't beat South Korea we'll face a severe problem
against Netherlands and Belgium.''
	   South Korea would be satisfied just to win its first match in
five World Cup finals, and they've focused on the match against
Mexico as their best chance for a landmark victory.
	   ``The team has prepared intensely for this match,'' said Cha,
who played for South Korea in the 1986 World Cup finals in Mexico.
``The players are at their peak. They are ready to play Mexico, and
win.''
	   Mexico is also anxious to show that a string of poor
performances in warm-up matches ahead of the World Cup are not an
indicator of the team's potential. The team is known as ``El
Tricolor'' for its green, red and white national colors.
	   ``Korea is a hard team, with very fast players,'' said defender
Claudio Suarez. ``They'll be difficult to beat. We'll need to play
well, stay concentrated and beware of breakaways, which they excel
at.''
	   Following Friday's training, Cha also announced two other
changes in his lineup.
	   Top-scorer Choi Yong-soo was left off the roster because of an
injury, replaced by 29-year-old Kim Do-hoon. The 24-year-old
striker, who scored seven times in as many games during the second
round of Asia's World Cup qualifying, had been considered the
team's key attacker going into the World Cup finals.
	   Veteran defender Choi Young-il, the 1994 World Cup team captain,
was also benched in favor of Kim Tae-young.
	   ``The players were chosen based on their physical condition,''
explained Cha.
	   In soccer-mad Mexico, where the match will be televised live at
10 a.m. local time, over 55 million people are expected to be
watching.
	   The South Koreans, meanwhile, are counting on the team to boost
the nation's morale in a time of economic troubles.
</TEXT>
