<SLUG> KIT-SIANG-KEEPS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kit Siang keeps mum on issue of suspension, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Kit Siang keeps mum on issue of suspension, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Ashraf AbdullahASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PETALING JAYA, Thurs. - DAP secretary-general Lim Kit Siang kept
mum today as more party members came out in support of the two
suspended DAP officials and another who was removed from his party
post.
	   At a Press conference today, he said: ``This is a Barisan
Nasional media agenda. I am not saying a single word.''
	   The Press conference was called to protest against the arrest of
his son Lim Guan Eng and three other DAP members during a gathering
in Kelana Jaya last night.
	   The four were released at 2.30am.
	   The Jalan Sungai Besi DAP branch in a resolution unanimously
passed at its annual meeting last night demanded that the party's
central executive committee withdraw the action against the three -
national vice-chairman Liew Ah Kim and treasurer Fung Ket Wing who
have been suspended from their party posts, and Wee Choo Keong who
was removed as national publicity secretary.
	   Branch secretary See Keng Hock said in a statement the three did
not break any party rules, and therefore an independent committee
should be set up to investigate allegations levelled at them by the
CEC.
	   Asked whether the disciplinary committee headed by vice-chairman
Ahmad Nor will meet on June 17 to hear charges against the three,
Kit Siang said: ``You have to ask Ahmad Nor.''
	   Kit Siang refused to comment when asked whether the party was in
a crisis but said it was an attempt by the BN Government to
distract public attention from the current economic problems and
issues of cronyism and nepotism.
	   Kit Siang also criticised police for the way they broke up the
gathering of DAP members last night, resulting in the arrest of
Guan Eng, who is deputy secretary-general.
	   ``It was a very orderly, peaceful and happy gathering of
Malaysians coming together because of their concern for justice,
freedom, democracy and good governance,'' he said.
	   He said the DAP had been organising meetings and dinners over
the past 30 years without breaking any law.
	   Kit Siang said he had faxed a letter to Prime Minister Datuk
Seri Dr Mahathir Mohamad asking him for a meeting to discuss the
police action and to get an explanation over the incident.
	   Guan Eng and three other party members were arrested for holding
an illegal assembly and obstructing police in the discharge of
their duties.
	   Policemen went on stage and detained Guan Eng as he was
addressing a crowd at a restaurant near Kelana Jaya.
	   At a Press conference in Penang, Liew, Fung and Wee said they
regretted that Kit Siang had not responded to their request for an
independent and impartial committee to investigate the allegations
against them.
	   ``Going round the country to justify what they had done will not
help the party in any way but will put the party in bad light with
regard to justice and fair play.
	   ``It's like a deputy public prosecutor going around justifying
why he had sent a person to jail without a trial. This is what has
happened to us.''
	   Meanhile, Penang DAP chairman Teoh Teik Huat said the State DAP
leaders and members had last night listened to the explanation and
grievances of the three.
	   He said: ``In keeping with the principles of justice, fairness
and impartiality as well as in order not to pre-empt or undermine
any future decisions of the party's disciplinary committee, the
Penang DAP leaders will not comment or express any views on what
they have heard from the suspended trio.''
	   However, he said they were in full agreement that the
disciplinary committee should be fair and impartial.
	   ``The grievances of the trio against the existing composition of
the disciplinary committee are indeed well founded and the party
leadership should immediately address this.''
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
