<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-US Open-Dry Course,0791 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Despite El Nino's battering, Olympic Course is ready
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos NY165-168 &QL; 
 &UR; By ROB GLOSTER &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) _ It's just a quarter-mile (0.4 kilometers)
from the ocean and months of pounding by El Nino left it soggy.
	   But The Olympic Club course on which the U.S. Open will be
played next week survived intact, unlike a neighboring course that
had four holes destroyed by the wicked weather.
	   Though some grassy spots on the course still are slippery,
workers have been able to concentrate on mostly cosmetic touchups
in recent days. Trees were trimmed, greens were mowed and _ in
almost a slap at El Nino _ sprinklers watered the course.
	   The Lake Course that will play host to the U.S. Open was a lot
luckier than the adjacent Ocean Course, where the soil beneath four
holes was eaten away by erosion and oversaturation _ leaving those
holes unplayable this spring.
	   ``It's had minimal impact on the Lake Course,'' course
superintendent John Fleming said. ``It had dramatic effects on the
other properties.''
	   The biggest challenge for Fleming and his crew has been
adjusting to the 5-inch (13-cm) rough the United States Golf
Association requires for the Open. The last time the Open was
played at The Olympic Club, in 1987, the rough was 4 inches (10
cms) tall.
	   ``The U.S. Open is rough. Rough is what defines the
championship,'' he said.
	   In fact, Fleming said, the unusually heavy rains of the last few
months have actually helped him prepare the rough _ and the rest of
the course _ for the Open, even though the wetness has made it
difficult at times to mow the grass.
	   ``I actually think El Nino has been a blessing in disguise. The
warm spring rains allowed us to germinate the rough grass, the rye
grasses that we've seeded into the rough areas to get the density
that the USGA requires for this tournament,'' he said.
	   ``It's also kept a lot of play off the golf course, which is
important to a superintendent getting a course ready for a major
championship.''
	   The U.S. Open is famous for its narrow fairways and deep, thick
rough. The rains virtually assured that the USGA will get the
conditions it wants. The soft fairways will also take much of the
roll off of tee shots and make the course play a lot longer.
	   The Olympic Club course, which also played host to the Open in
1955 and 1966, always has presented a variety of natural challenges
for golfers and fans. A chilly fog often rolls off the Pacific and
the course's 40,000 trees have played a part in determining
champions.
	   In contrast to this year, too much June sunshine was the big
fear for golfers during the last Open here in 1987. The sun firmed
up fairways and greens, usually kept relatively soft by the fog,
and made conditions fast and tricky.
	   The towering cypress and pine trees that line the narrow,
twisting fairways and surround the unusually small greens have
played a part in U.S. Open history.
	   At the 1955 tournament, amateur Harvie Ward was close to the
lead in the third round when he hit into a tree on the eighth hole
and the ball didn't come down. He took a penalty stroke on the way
to a double bogey, and never threatened again.
	   The ball fell out of the tree a week later.
	   The Pacific Ocean and the Golden Gate Bridge provide part of the
spectacular backdrop at The Olympic Club, which was dubbed ``the
longest short course in the world'' by Ben Hogan. It's 83 yards (75
meters) longer than the last time it welcomed the Open, but still
is just 6,797 yards (6,185 meters) overall.
	   The 16th hole, a par 5, is 609 yards (554 meters) and the 17th
is an uphill challenge of 468 yards (426 meters). But there are
several extremely short holes, including the 137-yard (125-meter)
eighth hole and the 157-yard (143-meter) 15th.
	   The lack of length is appropriate because of the course's
location.
	   ``Because of the proximity to the ocean and the density of the
air, the ball doesn't travel as far,'' Fleming said.
	   There are no water hazards, no out of bounds and just one
fairway bunker, yet the Lake Course has always tormented players
with its fickle winds and difficult angles. In the three Opens at
The Olympic Club, only four golfers have broken par for 72 holes.
	   Birds hopped around the fairways and flowers basked in a
late-spring dew as Fleming and his 45-person crew put the finishing
touches on a course that has been turned a lush green by the winter
and spring rains.
	   ``Architecturally, this is the simplest golf course in the
world,'' said Fleming, who has been tending to it since 1972.
``It's just pure golf.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Golf-US Open-Dry Course; CT:s; 
