AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SEPANG, Thurs. - The Special Malaysia Disaster Assistance and
Rescue Team (Smart) is in the process of determining the fastest
route to the Kuala Lumpur International Airport to establish a
response time of no more than 30 minutes.
	   National Security Division director-general Datuk Ja'afar
Ismail, who was at the airport today with some 20 members of the
team for the first official briefing, said the response time
registered in the team's two test runs stood at a little under an
hour.
	   ``I'm not very happy with the time yet. So we are trying to find
the best possible route with the least traffic to reduce it
further,'' he said.
	   The Smart team, which was established after the Highland Tower
disaster of 1993, will be contacted in the event of an emergency or
disaster at KLIA.
	   The team, based at the police depot in Jalan Semarak, comprises
of 85 personnel specially selected from the armed forces, the Fire
and Rescue Department and the police.
	   ``Based on what we heard during the briefing today, we believe
KLIA's security authorities have got very good systems and
contingency plans.
	   ``Now we want to work on how the team can be fully integrated
into the airport's own emergency teams.''
	   KLIA is scheduled to be opened by the Yang di-Pertuan Agong
Tuanku Ja'afar on June 27.
	   
</TEXT>
