<HEADLINE>
Terengganu island resorts record high occupancy, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Terengganu island resorts record high occupancy, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA TERENGGANU, Thurs. - The majority of hotels and resorts in
the State recorded a marked increase in room occupancy rates in the
first quarter of the year.
	   State Tourism, Culture and Arts Development Committee chairman
Datuk Aziz Awang said most resorts, especially those of islands,
had shown between 75 and 80 per cent occupancy compared to less
than 50 per cent last year.
	   ``Most resorts on the islands, such as Pulau Perhentian, Pulau
Redang and Pulau Lang, gave satisfactory reports on their room
occupancy rates since early this year,'' he told the reporters
after chairing a meeting on the International Marang-Kapas
Swimathon 1998 yesterday.
	   He said resorts and chalets at Perhentian Island Resort recorded
full occupancy with visitors from Germany, France, Australia, Italy
and Belgium.
	   ``In our interviews with some tourists, they said they chose the
islands because the beaches are clean and unpolluted, besides being
an ideal place to relax,'' he said.
	   However, he said there were also other hotels, especially those
on the mainland, which needed to improve their services.
	   He said some of these hotels recorded less than 35 per cent in
room occupancy rates.
	   In view of this, he said the State Government had set up a
committee to assist the hotels in overcoming their problems.
	   
</TEXT>
