<HEADLINE>
Manager denies giving car to former aide of ex-CM, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Manager denies giving car to former aide of ex-CM, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SEREMBAN, Thurs. - A company manager told the Sessions Court
today that he did not give a RM274,453.82 Mercedes Benz to an
ex-aide of former Malacca Chief Minister, the late Datuk Seri Mohd
Zin Abdul Ghani.
	   Chang Kok Chuang, 40, from Atlantic Potential Sdn Bhd said he
did not have any dealings with Azman Ghani, 38, who was also at the
time assistant director of valuation and property management of the
Malacca Municipal Council.
	   Azman is charged with accepting the car, bearing registration
number MAB 747 as gratification to expedite the approval of a
project in Malacca.
	   He is accused of committing the offence at Minsoon Credit Corp
(M) Sdn Bhd at 73, Jalan Tuanku Antah, Seremban at 2.30pm on Feb
25, 1995.
	   The charge under Section 165 of the Penal Code which carries a
maximum sentence of two years' jail, a fine or both.
	   Azman was represented by Christopher Fernando, Haresh Mahadevan,
Ramzani Idris and K.K.Low while Ahamad Bache from the
Anti-Corruption Agency prosecuted before judge Supiah Meon.
	   Chang said all dealings between his company and the Malacca
State Government for the development of a bus and taxi terminal in
Semabok were between the company and the Malacca Municipal Council
and never involved Azman.
	   Md Zuhaidi Ramji, a clerk with Mayban Finance in Rahang,
Seremban, said he was responsible for the accounts of two cars, MAB
747 and WDV 9.
	   The second car, WDV 9 was purchased by Atlantic Potential for
one of its directors while the other car (MAB 747) was registered
in the name of Malaysia Airlines pilot, Najme Khir Mohamad, 46.
	   He said Atlantic Potential had only been involved in the
transaction for the second car (WDV 9). June 16 was fixed for
submissions.
	   
</TEXT>
