<SLUG> FEWER-FIREMEN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fewer firemen at stations in effort to reduce costs, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Fewer firemen at stations in effort to reduce costs, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   BUTTERWORTH, Thurs. - The Fire and Rescue Department is
considering posting fewer firemen at most of its stations in a bid
to reduce its operating costs by 60 per cent.
	   Its director-general Datuk Soh Chai Hock said today, positions
vacated by the firemen would instead be replaced by volunteers.
	   ``We are conducting a study on the matter. The proposed
reduction on the number of firemen is based on the system carried
out in the United Kingdom,'' he told reporters when met at the
department's State headquarters in Prai.
	   He was asked to comment on Housing and Local Government Minister
Datuk Dr Ting Chew Peh's announcement on the Government's move to
revamp all volunteer fire fighting squads in the country.
	   Soh said the proposal, when carried out, would involve staff
from all levels at all 193 fire stations and the respective 14
State headquarters.
	   ``For instance, in smaller stations, we would have three
volunteers to perform the task of a single fireman and the number
of firemen in such stations would be limited to 12.''
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
