<BODY>
<SLUG> FOUR-IN-FAMILY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Four in family found murdered in farm house, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Four in family found murdered in farm house, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 12, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Thanam VisvanathanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PONTIAN, Thurs. - A smallholder, his wife, their eight-year-old
son and soon-to-be-married daughter were found brutally murdered at
their farm home in Kampung Parit Hj Arif, near Parit Madirono,
Benut, yesterday.
	   The victims were identified as smallholder Redzuan Mansur, 55,
housewife Rosnah Busari, 44, their daughter Hamsah, 20 and son Mohd
Azizul, 8.
	   Their partially decomposed bodies were discovered by the fiance
and Hamsah's sister.
	   Police have yet to establish the motive for the killings, which
was described by district police chief Superintendant Gingkoi Seman
Pancras as ``the most vicious, cold-blooded and brutal murders'' in
Pontian in recent years.
	   Hamsah, a factory worker, was to have been married on July 15.
Mohd Azizul was a Standard Two pupil of Sekolah Rendah Kebangsaan
Lubok Sipat.
	   Redzuan, Rosnah and Mohd Azizul's bodies were found piled on a
bed in a rear bedroom of the house.
	   Rosnah's body was lying next to her son, both face-up, while
Redzuan's body was stacked on top of them face-down. The three had
been hacked on the back of their necks, and Redzuan's and Mohd
Azizul's heads were almost severed.
	   They also had several other deep slash wounds all over their
bodies.
	   Mohd Azizul's throat had also been slit, and he had been cut
across his face along his mouth.
	   Hamsah's semi-nude body was found lying face-up on a bed in
another bedroom. A towel was found stuffed in her mouth, and a
pillow was on her face.
	   Gingkoi did not rule out the possibility that she may have been
sexually assaulted.
	   There were no outward injury marks on her body, and she is
believed to have died of suffocation and shock.
	   The room next to the one she was found, had been decorated with
new furniture, golden yellow bridal bedlinen and vases of
artificial flowers, in preparation of her wedding.
	   Gingkoi said the four victims were last seen alive at a wedding
function in the village on Sunday evening.
	   The bodies were found after Hamsah's fiance, rubber tapper Md
Zali Tarhib, 26, who had gone to the house to visit the family and
discuss the wedding arrangements.
	   He suspected something amiss when no one answered his calls and
immediately contacted Hamsah's sister, Misiah in Batu Pahat.
	   Md Zali and Misiah later forced open the rear door yesterday
afternoon and found the dead.
	   Police sent tracker dogs to comb the area, and forensic experts
were also at the scene to facilitate investigations.
	   ``From our initial investigations, we believe more than one
killer was involved, and that the killers were persons known to the
family,'' he said.
	   Gingkoi said that there were no signs of forced entry and that
the house was still locked from the inside at the time the bodies
were discovered.
	   ``The killers appear to have gained entry through an access
opening at the back of the house.''
	   The house was in an isolated location, and the nearest house was
nearly a kilometre away.
	   The house had been partly ransacked but nothing valuable was
found missing.
	   Gingkoi said the approximate time of the murders was probably
between Sunday evening and Monday morning.
	   Rosnah's brother Kassim Busari that Mohd Azizul had not attended
school since Monday. Hamsah too had not reported for work since
Monday.
	   Anyone with information on the case can contact Pontian CID
chief ASP V.
	   Pushpanathan at tel: 07-6871222, or the Benut Police Station
tel: 07- 6903222.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
