<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0645 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Albanian militants kill Serb policemen near Kosovo capital
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with one ethnic Albanian reported killed, seven
villages said under attack; changes sourcing on 15,000 fighters;
ADDS details; TRIMS. &QL; 
 &UR; By ISMET HAJDARI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Ethnic Albanian militants, boldly
stepping up their attacks, have killed two Serb policemen just a
few miles (kilometers) from Kosovo's capital.
	   Fighting between Serbian forces and the militants erupted again
Friday in the Decani region in western Kosovo, close to the border
with Albania. It was a Serbian offensive there last week that
prompted NATO on Thursday to announce a show of air power aimed at
persuading Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to halt the
assault.
	   Ethnic Albanians outnumber Serbs nine-to-one in the southern
province of Kosovo. Most seek independence from Serbia, the
dominant republic in Yugoslavia, which in 1989 stripped the
province of broad autonomy and has ruled with a heavy hand ever
since. More than 250 people have been killed since Serbian police
started cracking down on Albanian militants in March.
	   Ethnic Albanian militants have gained popular support since the
crackdown, and young Kosovo Albanians who live in western Europe
have gone to Albania to help organize resistance or fight.
Militants said Friday that they now command 15,000 fighters in
Kosovo, according to the Albanian state news agency ATA.
	   Ethnic Albanian sources claimed that seven villages in the
Decani area were under attack Friday from forces using grenade
launchers normally issued to the Yugoslav army. One Albanian,
Rexhep Mazrekaj, 38, was killed, they said.
	   There was no independent confirmation of their report, but the
state-run Tanjug news agency in Belgrade reported that a Serb
policeman was seriously hurt in what it called an attack by ``armed
Albanian terrorists'' near one of the villages, Prilep.
	   Serb sources in the province said two policemen where killed and
one was seriously wounded in an overnight ambush by separatists
near Obilic, seven kilometers (four miles) northwest of the
provincial capital, Pristina.
	   Albanian sources reported other Serb attacks on villages near
Obilic and adjacent Vucitrn.
	   The ethnic Albanian daily Bujku reported Friday that five ethnic
Albanians and seven Serbs were killed in clashes Thursday in Suvo
Grlo in the Drenica area, 30 kilometers (20 miles) west of
Pristina. Bujku said the fighting was fierce, with villagers
determined to ``resist to the end with the help of the KLA.''
	   NATO is planning simulated air attacks in neighboring Albania
and Macedonia in an effort to persuade Milosevic to end the
military action.
	   On Friday, Western foreign ministers met in London with their
Russian counterpart to step up pressure. Britain, which is weighing
a United Nations' move to back use of NATO force in Kosovo, called
on Milosevic to withdraw his troops immediately.
	   The United States, Canada, Britain, France, Italy and Germany
said they would ``take steps to ban'' flights by Yugoslav Airlines,
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said.
	   Kosovo's Albanians welcomed the NATO activity. Eroll Haxhiu, 46,
a jewelry merchant in Pristina market, said the United States ``can
and should'' strike at Milosevic.
	   Members of Kosovo's Serb minority _ whom Milosevic promised to
protect when taking power in Serbia in 1987 _ were alternately
gloomy and defiant.
	   ``We are to blame for everything that is happening. We deserve
it,'' said Vasilje Stefanovic, a pensioner from Prizren.
	   ``If they attack us, they'll be attacking a sovereign country,''
said Jovan Banjanin, 40, who refused to state his occupation. ``We
will have to defend ourselves, and this has nothing to do with the
Albanian issue.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 3rd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
