</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-NATO,0505 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yugoslavia talks tough to NATO
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo BEL101 &QL; 
 &UR; By MISHA SAVIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ If NATO intervenes in secessionist
Kosovo province, the Yugoslav army will treat the alliance as an
intruder and ``defend the territory ... with all means available,''
a top aide to President Slobodan Milosevic said Friday.
	   Zoran Lilic, a close Milosevic aide who was Yugoslavia's
president until last year and is now a deputy premier, told The
Associated Press he hoped there would never be a clash between NATO
and Yugoslavia.
	   He made clear that Serbia, which along with Montenegro comprises
Yugoslavia, does not regard violence in Kosovo as an all-out war
with dangerous regional consequences.
	   ``We know that in a clash with NATO _ it's stupid even to think
about that _ we don't stand a chance,'' Lilic said. ``But it is its
(Yugoslav army's) duty to defend the territory against anybody who
tries to enter by force.''
	   Hostilities in Serbia's southern province of Kosovo threaten to
ignite a war that could spread to neighboring countries. Ethnic
Albanians, who outnumber Serbs by nine to one in Kosovo, want
independence and are prepared to fight for it.
	   More than 250 people have died in clashes since government
forces in March began a crackdown on Albanian militants, known as
the Kosovo Liberation Army.
	   Lilic said fighting occurred only in some parts of Kosovo and
called the clashes a conflict ``between security forces and the
terrorists.''
	   ``The United States can play a key role if they exert pressure
on Albanians to cease terrorist actions _ which would mean an
automatic halt of actions by the police,'' Lilic said.
	   Milosevic revoked the province's broad autonomy in 1989, trying
to quash Albanians' push for independence and claiming to protect
the Kosovo Serb cause he had espoused to gain power.
	   But nine years of heavy-handed Serbian rule, enforced with a
strong police and army presence, have only fanned demands for
independence. The peaceful course pursued by ethnic Albanian
political leaders is losing ground to KLA militancy.
	   Kosovo's Albanians, protesting Serbia's rule, have boycotted all
Serbian elections since 1990, and founded alternative schools and
hospitals since being sacked or quitting most state jobs that year.
	   Lilic denied that government forces have acted brutally against
Albanian civilians. Foreign diplomats allowed into the region of
the most recent severe fighting in western Kosovo saw scenes of
devastation reminiscent of Bosnia, with houses burned and shelled.
	   Claiming the KLA are ``actually Muslim fundamentalists'', Lilic
reiterated Yugoslav accusations against neighboring Albania,
accusing it of training and arming the rebels.
	   Also Friday, President Milo Djukanovic of Montenegro, Serbia's
only remaining partner in the Yugoslav federation, indicated he
might withdraw recruits from his republic from the army if it
became implicated in atrocities.
</TEXT>
