<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Spain-Chess Computers </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kasparov beats Topalov in tie-break after drawing computer-aided
</HEADLINE>
chess competition &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LEON, Spain (AP) _ World chess champion Garry Kasparov of Russia
beat Bulgarian Grand Master Veselin Topalov Friday in an all-human
tie-break after their computer-assisted chess challenge ended in
stalemate.
	   Kasparov's tie-break victory came on the fourth game, after
winning the first, losing the second and drawing the third.
	   Both players had won two, lost two and drawn two of the six
prior games in which they had been permitted to consult moves with
the Chessmaster 5500 program, designed by the U.S. company
Mindscape.
	   Two games were played each day in the three-day experimental
competition that sought to eliminate human error while retaining
human imagination and flare.
	   Topalov had gone into Friday's matches one point down, but the
Bulgarian, playing the black pieces, came back with a win in a
tense match in which being two pawns up proved worth exposing his
king at the center of the board.
	   In the final game Kasparov, playing black, held his young
challenger to a draw and both players were level playing with three
points each.
	   No title was at stake in the challenge dubbed ``chess of the
future'' and held in this northern Spanish city.
	   Kasparov's tie-break victory earned him dlrs 6,600 and Topalov
got a compensation dlrs 3,000.
	   Without computers, Topalov, 23, the world's No. 4, has now
defeated Kasparov three times and lost eight of the 19 games they
have played. The remainder were draws.
	   Despite being barred from professional competitions, computers
have come to dominate the chess world over the last quarter
century.
	   Modern programs, many of them designed under Kasparov's
guidance, have become capable of beating most humans, including
Kasparov himself.
	   Kasparov is considered the world's top chess player, although
fellow Russian Anatoly Karpov is the reigning champion of the World
Chess Federation.
	   (jt)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
