w1918 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-USAirlineInvestigatio     06-12 0388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US Airline Investigation,500 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Government probing Northwest Airlines maintenance
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By GLEN JOHNSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ The U.S. Federal Aviation Administration is
investigating whether Northwest Airlines has properly cared for its
aging fleet, as well as concerns that a local FAA inspector may not
have properly supervised the carrier and its maintenance regimen.
	   Northwest has saved billions in recent years by skipping a round
of new airplane purchases in favor of refurbishing its aged
workhorse, the McDonnell Douglas DC-9, but the airline says the
FAA's allegations are only the most bitter pill in its contentious
contract negotiations with unions.
	   ``These are stories that resulted from allegations from a
disgruntled former employee and have been looked at and found
meritless by the FAA twice,'' company spokesman Jon Austin said
Friday. ``If the FAA has any lingering questions, we would welcome
a third look.''
	   Northwest, which flies the oldest fleet of airplanes among the
nation's major carriers, decided in 1994 to delay buying new planes
and instead extend the life of some 25-year-old DC-9s up to 40
years. The airline has extensive operations in Asia and Europe.
	   Airplanes are designed to fly safely for 30 years or more, and
the FAA has a program to monitor aging aircraft to keep them in the
sky even longer. But the decision to extend the life of the DC-9s
and the program to do so would have to have been approved by the
FAA office in Minneapolis, where Northwest is based.
	   A ``fact-finding review'' was launched in February after an FAA
employee from another region raised concerns about the supervision
provided by the Minneapolis office. Afterward, two other
allegations were received, one from a current Northwest employee
and one from a former worker.
	   The airline had to cancel or delay an unusually high number of
flights recently and it ranked ninth among the nation's 10 major
carriers in on-time performance last year.
	   Other airline officials noted that Northwest has not had an
accident caused by mechanical failure in the nine years under the
current management team. The airline, the nation's fourth largest
carrier, had its last accident in December 1990, when two planes
collided on the ground. Eight people were killed.
</TEXT>
