<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-Buick Classic,0436 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rain washes out most of Buick Classic play Friday
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JOEL STASHENKO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HARRISON, New York (AP) _ A drenching, wind-whipped rain washed
out most of Friday's second round of the Buick Classic.
	   The round will be completed early Saturday, followed by the
start of the third round.
	   Only 18 golfers finished Friday's round before the rain and
casual water at the Westchester Country Club forced the suspension
of play. Forty-eight players were on the course and 73 others,
including first-round leader Kevin Sutherland and most of the rest
of Thursday's top finishers, hadn't started their rounds.
	   Not having to play Friday could be a ``huge break,'' said
Sutherland, a non-winner in five years on the PGA tour.
	   ``These conditions are terrible,'' he said.
	   The best round among those who finished was Brad Faxon's
2-under-par 69, which put him at 1-under 141 after two rounds. Joe
Ozaki shot a 70 for 140.
	   Players who hit the ball in the fairway Friday were allowed to
lift, clean and place their ball within one club length of where it
came to rest because of the soggy ground. But that hardly made up
for the saturated conditions.
	   Faxon said he was unluckly having to play Thursday afternoon,
when winds began to swirl following a calm morning, and again in
Friday morning's rain. Sutherland, who shot a 7-under 64 Thursday,
and the other leaders have avoided the worst of the weather both
days.
	   ``I think these guys should play in this garbage a little,''
Faxon said. ``The greens didn't seem that saturated. They were
rolling nice. ... It wasn't like it was unplayable.''
	   In addition to cutting driving distance by 30 yards (9 meters)
or more a hole, the rain also made it impossible to get a dry grip
on the club, Faxon said.
	   ``The bottom of the bag gets wet, so every time you pull a club
out it's wet and the shafts go in and they're wet,'' he said.
``Gloves get wet. Your hands get wet.''
	   Faxon used four towels trying to keep his hands and grips dry
and two pairs of golf shoes.
	   Among golfers on the course when play was stopped, Stewart Cink
was 3 under for the round and even par overall through 15 holes.
Nick Faldo was on the 15th at 3-under for the day when play was
suspended. He also was at par.
	   Vijay Singh, Buick Classic winner in 1993 and 1995, was 2-under
on the day and 2-under for the tournament through 16 holes Friday.
	   Paul Goydos started the day tied for second at 5-under but was
3-over through 15 holes for the round.
</TEXT>
