<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-South Africa,0566 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: For South Africa, emotional first appearance overshadows
</HEADLINE>
defeat &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos available &QL; 
 &UR; By TOM COHEN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MARSEILLES, France (AP) _ For South Africa, just being there
Friday night was what mattered most.
	   Never mind that host France easily won 3-0 against the
defense-minded South Africans, who were playing their nation's
first World Cup game.
	   There are two more first-round matches for South Africa and
other World Cups to come, more chances to shine across the planet
and create dreams for those back home. The inaugural appearance in
soccer's biggest tournament was a coming of age for players, fans
and a nation that has long-thirsted for recognition, and even more,
acceptance.
	   A lifetime of waiting meant the hundreds of flag-waving, singing
South African fans didn't really care if ``Bafana Bafana'' _ Zulu
for ``the boys'' _ won or lost.
	   ``I think the significance is being able to compete in a world
event like the World Cup for the first time,'' said Andre Luck, 35,
of Cape Town. ``It would be good if we could win, but I'm glad
we're just competing.''
	   Shipping company official Phillip Malebe, 44, of Johannesburg
said he was amazed at how the event brought South Africans of all
colors and backgrounds together.
	   ``The fact is we are here. They brought us all here,'' said
Malebe, who wore a South African jersey. ``I've seen the beautiful
rainbow nation, all colors, singing our song. We were singing
together, we were passing drinks mouth-to-mouth. ... Just to be
here, we don't need the Cup.''
	   Deputy President Thabo Mbeki, the heir apparent to Nelson
Mandela, was among the 60,000 spectators packed into Stade
Velodrome, sitting with French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin and
World Cup organizing committee chairman Michel Platini.
	   French fans belted out a stirring ``La Marseillaise'' and the
French players responded, attacking the South Africans for most of
the first half and going ahead on a 34th minute header by
Christophe Dugarry off a corner kick. An own-goal by South Africa's
Pierre Issa in the 78th and Thierry Henry's shot in the second
minute of penalty time completed the rout.
	   South Africa lacked the speed and strength to win battles for
the ball, and its defensive shell allowed France to control play
and set up numerous chances around goalkeeper Hans Vonk.
	   Since arriving in France on Sunday, the players have been
reminded again and again that the bad years of apartheid and
international isolation are gone. In Vichy, the central town where
they train, residents have welcomed them warmly, seeking autographs
at every chance.
	   Back home, the significance is even greater. South Africa has
enjoyed lots of sports success since its return to the
international arena in the early 1990s. Ernie Els has won two U.S.
Opens in golf, while Josia Thugwane was the Olympic marathon
champion and Penny Heyns won two swimming gold medals in Atlanta
two years ago. The rugby Springboks won their World Cup at home in
1995.
	   But soccer is the national sport, followed and played zealously
by most of the black majority. For 28 years, until 1992, South
Africa was banned from international soccer because of apartheid
and its players and fans could only wonder what a World Cup was
like.
	   Now they know.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
