<SLUG> BC-Guyana-Opposition Ousted,0386 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Opposition party representatives ousted from Guyana Parliament
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By BERT WILKINSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   GEORGETOWN, Guyana (AP) _ The representatives of the main
opposition party were kicked out of Parliament after they failed to
attend the minimum number of consecutive sessions, party officials
confirmed Friday.
	   The People's National Congress, which won 25 of the 65 seats in
Parliment in the December general election, had refused to take its
seats. The party has claimed the elections were unfair although two
international groups have said election irregularities were minor.
	   On Thursday, the government told the party to provide the names
of 25 new representatives or the ban on its attendance in
Parliament would continue indefinitely.
	   ``We were sort of expecting it,'' said Malcolm Parris, a member
of the party's central executive committee. ``I don't think it will
bring a crisis. We are going to submit the same 25 names because
they were the ones elected.''
	   Party President Desmond Hoyte, the losing presidential candidate
in the election, said the party has yet to decide if or when it
will take its seats.
	   The party contends the elections were marred by fraud although a
panel of regional elections experts, funded by the United Nations,
audited the results and found only minor problems. A team of
elections observers from the Organization of American States issued
a similar finding.
	   The party's representatives were ousted under parliamentary
regulations that prohibit members from missing six consecutive
meetings of the House in an eight-week period.
	   The majority needs the cooperation of the minority members of
Parliament to undertake a planned revision of the Constitution in
this former British colony in South America.
	   Parris said he did not think the ouster of his party's
representatives would derail current talks between the People's
National Congress and the ruling People's Progressive Party on race
relations and constitutional reform.
	   Supporters of the People's National Congress are mostly of
African descent while People's Progressive Party members are
primarily East Indian, with the population of the country roughly
split between the two groups.
</TEXT>
