<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup Roundup, 1st Ld-Writethru,0892 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bomb threats, investigations, but only one goal
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: UPDATES with France-South Africa match. &QL; 
 &UR; By BRIAN TRUSDELL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Paraguayan keeper Jose Luis Chilavert nearly
scored; the French did it three times.
	   Chilavert's would have been historic, but wouldn't have equalled
the pleasure for the French, who saw ``Les Bleus'' open their World
Cup campaign Friday night with a dominating 3-0 victory over South
Africa.
	   Chistophe Dugarry came off the bench for injured forward
Stephane Guivarc'h in the 27th minute and scored seven minutes
later to lead the hosts' rout of the world championship debutantes
on a day that showed little excitement and several problems until
the match in Marseille.
	   It started with the evacuation of the Stade de le Mosson press
tribune in Montpellier before the Paraguay-Bulgaria match because
of a bomb scare. The media center next to the stadium had to be
evacuated after the match due to another threat.
	   Those distractions came amidst a 0-0 draw between Paraguay and
Bulgaria, and a 1-0 victory by Denmark over Saudi Arabia in Lens.
	   Dugarry's goal electrified a crowd in Marseilles that included
French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin and French organizing committee
co-president Michel Platini. It also silenced his critics, who
complained his inclusion in the squad was only due to his close
friendship with team star Zinedine Zidane.
	   The Olympique Marseille forward backheaded in a corner from
Zidane and seemed to minimize his troubled half season with the
French club after transferring from FC Barcelona.
	   His Marseille teammate Pierre Issa was responsible for the
second goal, deflecting a slow Youri Djorkaeff shot over his own
goalkeeper, Hans Vonk, in the 78th.
	   Thierry Henry then closed out the French celebration, stealing a
ball and driving in before chipping a shot over the defenseless
Vonk.
	   One of the few highlights early in the day came when Chilavert
forced his Bulgarian counterpart, Zdravko Zdravkov, into a leaping
save on a 25-meter free kick in the 78th minute.
	   The flamboyant Chilavert curled his left-footed free kick over
the wall that Zdravkov parried away as it headed for just under the
crossbar.
	   ``I already saw the ball in the net,'' said Chilavert, who has
35 goals in his professional career and was within an outstretched
hand of becoming the first goalkeeper score a goal in the World
Cup. ``Too bad, I could have made history.''
	   Otherwise the match was a series of missed opportunities.
	   Hristo Stoichkov put Bulgaria's best chance off the right post
with a left-footed shot in the 35th minute.
	   Bulgaria felt it was cheated in the fifth minute when Stoichkov
was upended in the Paraguayan box but Saudi referee Abdul Rahman
Al-Zeid failed to whistle a foul.
	   ``It was a 100 percent penalty,'' Bulgarian coach Hristo Bonev
said. ``We played well in the first half, but our game collapsed in
the second.''
	   Denmark and Saudi Arabia did the Paraguayans and Bulgarians only
one better, a lone tally from Marc Rieper in the 68th minute to
give the Europeans the victory.
	   In Lens, Rieper came from his backline position to head in a
cross Brian Laudrup from eight meters and give the Danes victory in
a match the Scandinavians could have won by a larger margin.
	   Michael Schjonberg forced Saudi keeper Mohammed Al Deayea to
make a scrambling, diving save and then substitute Per Frandsen
fired across the face of the goal as the Danes pressed for a second
goal.
	   The Saudis created few opportunities in the opening 40 minutes,
but forced Schmeichel into a fingertip save from a free kick by
Saeed Owairan just before the break.
	   In the meantime, FIFA spent the day trying to ward off an own
goal.
	   In a growing scandal that started with Japanese fans a day
before, the world body was investigating two national federations
and a subsidiary of its own marketing arm regarding game ticket
fraud at the World Cup.
	   FIFA said it has warned fans not to deal with anyone but
licensed ticket operators.
	   ``There's some confusion here, and that is creating excuses for
the operators,'' said Isabelle Delaye, the French organizing
committee's ticket chief. ``We should criticize them. They found
the ideal way of making money, by deceiving people.''
	   Acting FIFA general secretary Michel Zen-Ruffinen said the
organization was probing the improper sale of tickets by soccer
officials in Cameroon and an unnamed South American country. French
news reports said it was Colombia, but Colombian federation has
denied it is involved.
	   FIFA also was looking inside its own house. A representative of
ISL France ``apparently sold tickets he did not have to
individuals.'' The company is the French arm of Swiss giant ISL,
which handles FIFA's negotiations on sponsors and television.
	   ``It's a rather serious issue'' involving several thousand
tickets, Zen-Ruffinen said.
	   It seemed like an expansion of an issue which erupted Thursday,
when reports had about 12,000 Japanese fans without tickets from
tour operators.
	   FIFA said it had complaints from fans missing tickets in the
Netherlands, Belgium, Germany, England and Brazil, as well as
Japan.
</TEXT>
