<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Albania-Macedonia-NATO-Kosovo, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Albania will offer space for NATO drills, Macedonia not yet
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; RETRANSMITTING TO FIX SEQUENCE NUMBER &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS and UPDATES with Macedonian government approving NATO
exercise. &QL; 
 &UR; By MERITA DHIMGJOKA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TIRANA, Albania (AP) _ Albania and Macedonia on Friday hastily
approved NATO exercises that will allow Alliance planes to fly
simulated bombing raids over the two Balkan countries in an effort
to halt violence in neighboring Kosovo.
	   Albania, which has for weeks sought NATO action to stem
bloodshed in Serbia's secessionist province, swiftly agreed to make
air space and airfields available.
	   Macedonia's government met late into the night. But a statement
issued around 11 p.m. (2100 GMT) said it had received a NATO
request for one exercise consisting of ``a flyover through
Macedonia's airspace.''
	   ``Any new request in the future will be considered separately,''
it added.
	   Macedonia's Defense Minister Blagoj Handziski had earlier
stressed to reporters that his country would not allow itself to be
used for any military intervention against a neighbor.
	   Macedonia's Slav majority has closer ties to the Yugoslavs than
to Kosovo's Albanians. But Macedonia's sizeable ethnic Albanian
minority is naturally bound to kin in Kosovo and Albania.
	   Every Macedonian is deeply aware that ethnic conflict there can
lead to a break-up of their small, young country of just under 2
million, possibly sparking a wider Balkan conflict.
	   The government statement made no mention of a special session of
parliament to approve the NATO maneuvers.
	   Macedonia is a member of Partnership for Peace, the waiting room
for east European countries seeking Alliance membership, and its
approval had been expected.
	   Macedonia's prime minister visits Tirana this weekend to discuss
the Kosovo conflict with Albanian counterpart Fatos Nano, who
announced his Cabinet approved the NATO maneuvers Friday.
	   ``We are convinced that the crisis in Kosovo is not only a
problem for Albania,'' Nano said. Macedonia ``is also interested in
regional stability ... and I hope that they will not try to keep
their country artificially out of the crisis when the crisis is at
its door.''
	   (pvs/ms/kt/as)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
