w1947 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Mexico-Chiapas-Reacti     06-12 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Chiapas-Reaction,0470 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
International groups, parties, urge Mexico to restart peace talks
</HEADLINE>
in Chiapas &QL; 
 &UR; With Mexico-Chiapas &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ International observers and Mexican
opposition groups demanded Friday that the government show it truly
wants to resolve rebel conflicts through talks rather than violence
in the wake of a deadly raid this week in Chiapas.
	   The calls came as President Ernesto Zedillo toured Chiapas,
Mexico's southernmost state, where he insisted that his
administration would like the leftist Zapatista rebels to restart
negotiations that broke down in 1996.
	   On Wednesday, soldiers and police raided an Indian village in
the Chiapas municipality of El Bosque to break up a symbolic town
council supportive of the Zapatistas. Nine people were killed,
including a police officer, in what was one of the most serious
skirmishes of the 4-year-old conflict.
	   The United Nations high commissioner for human rights, Mary
Robinson, said Wednesday's raid and other recent violence in
Chiapas ``are serious violations of the rights of indigenous
people'' and urged the government to resume a dialogue.
	   ``A reduction in the military presence in the region could be an
important first step in restoring confidence that a peaceful
solution might be found,'' she said in a statement from Geneva.
	   Mexico has sent thousands of soldiers to Chiapas since Zapatista
rebels took up arms on Jan. 1, 1994, to demand greater rights and
democracy for Mexico's impoverished Indians.
	   Last week, an army patrol clashed with a separate rebel group in
the southwestern state of Guerrero. The shootout killed 11 people,
all apparently members of the leftist Popular Revolutionary Army,
which rose up briefly in 1996 demanding political and social
reform.
	   Amnesty International denounced the recent clashes, saying the
escalating violence threatened to degenerate into a ``human rights
catastrophe.''
	   ``While some of the dead may have been armed insurgents, we
suspect that others are civilians who have been killed by
government soldiers,'' the London-based human rights group said in
a statement. It called for independent autopsies to determine the
circumstances of the killings.
	   Amnesty said government actions to break up symbolic pro-rebel
town councils in Chiapas have been used as a ``pretext for
widespread arbitrary detentions'' that have fueled insecurity in
opposition areas.
	   The leftist Democratic Revolution Party threatened to abandon
talks on federal political reform unless the government returned to
peaceful negotiations with the rebels. The party was organizing a
protest Friday night in Mexico City.
	   After Wednesday's raid, the conservative National Action Party
also urged Zedillo's government to reestablish negotiations in
Chiapas.
</TEXT>
