w1958 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Israel-Palestinians 2ndLd-Writethru   06-12 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Palestinians, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0505 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIMS, CHANGES byline
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; RETRANSMITTING to restore cycle designator &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: LEADS to UPDATE with new statements by Netanyahu, RECASTS,
 &UR; By JACK KATZENELL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on Friday
challenged the American and Palestinian position that the
Palestinians have accepted a U.S. proposal that they fulfill their
commitments under the Oslo accords in return for an Israeli
withdrawal from 13 percent of the West Bank.
	   Interviewed on Israeli Channel 1 television, Netanyahu said
agreement could be reached but that it depended on the
Palestinians.
	   The reporter pointed out that the Palestinians have agreed to
the American proposal, and Netanyahu retorted: ``That's what you
say.''
	   Netanyahu implied that the Palestinians' assurances _ that they
will abrogate clauses in the Palestinian Covenant calling for the
destruction of Israel and do more to crack down on terrorist groups
_ are too vague.
	   ``I want to see the fulfillment of these promises in practice,
with dates, and the knowledge that the commitments are really being
implemented in a concrete manner,'' Netanyahu said.
	   The U.S. plan, which has not been officially announced although
many of its details have been disclosed, is an attempt by the
Americans to re-start the peace process that broke down 15 months
ago.
	   In his public statements until now, Netanyahu has rejected the
U.S. proposal for a 13 percent withdrawal from the West Bank, which
Israel captured and occupied in the 1967 Mideast war. He has
reportedly been holding out for nine percent.
	   He has demanded that an agreement also specify the size of the
next withdrawal, which would be the third and last redeployment of
the Oslo interim accord.
	   ``I think ... it will be the last agreement we will make, which
the State of Israel will make, until the completion of the
permanent settlement,'' he said.
	   Netanyahu rejected speculation that he discussed the possibility
of a national unity government Friday when he met Ehud Barak,
leader of the opposition Labor party.
	   Right wing parties in Netanyahu's coalition have threatened to
bring down his government if he carries out any withdrawal in the
West Bank.
	   There was speculation that he met Barak as a hint to the right
wing parties that he has the option of forming an alliance with
Labor, in order to win parliamentary approval for the withdrawal.
	   However Netanyahu insisted he just briefed Barak on the
negotiations with the Palestinians ``I didn't talk to him about a
unity government,'' Netanyahu said.
	   In another U.S. effort to move the process forward, CIA Director
George Tenet met separately this week with Netanyahu and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and reportedly passed messages
about security coordination between the two leaders.
	   Meanwhile, the prospect of holding a national referendum on the
West Bank withdrawal has been gaining momentum in government
circles.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
