<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-France-South Africa, 1st Ld-Writethru,0831 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Dugarry leads dominating 3-0 French victory
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: Optional; UPDATES with quotes. &QL; 
 &UR; By RAF CASERT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MARSEILLE, France (AP) _ With three goals and repeated attacks,
France produced the result and the whole host nation had been
hoping for and crushed South Africa 3-0 to stake its claim as a
World Cup favorite.
	   Olympique Marseille's hero Christophe Dugarry scored one goal
and assisted on another and prodigy Thierry Henry weaved through
the South African defense in injury time with a darting run and a
gentle, cunning finish, to top off a dominating performance Friday
night.
	   Marseille's native son Zinedine Zidane led the French forward
throughout the match, and together with his best friend Dugarry,
paced France past an all-important first test.
	   ``The door is wide open now,'' French coach Aime Jacquet said.
``We are really confident.''
	   France moved atop Group C after one round, moving past Denmark,
which beat Saudi Arabia 1-0, on goal difference.
	   Wave after wave of attacks finally paid off in the 34th minute
when a corner from Zidane found Dugarry unmarked in the goalmouth
and the substitute for injured striker Stephane Guivarc'h headed
home off the post to set the crowd of 60,000 alight.
	   In the 78th minute, continuous pressure paid off again, with
Dugarry finding Youri Djorkaeff free in the penalty area and the
forward's shot on goal was deflected by South Africa's Pierre Issa
into his own net.
	   Henry, just 20, then made it a perfect night for France, lifting
the ball over goalkeeper Hans Vonk for his first goal for France.
	   The goals weren't the occasions that caused celebration for the
French, which silenced the critics and sent the crowds into
continuous roars despite the howling winds that beat on this
Mediterranean port throughout the evening.
	   ``We knew we could count on the Marseille crowd,'' Jacquet said.
``It was good soccer in very tough conditions.''
	   South Africa's latest chapter in its sporting history, following
almost three decades on the sidelines of international soccer
because of apartheid, never had any shine.
	   ``We were missing experience and chances to play together. We
played against a great team,'' said South African coach Philippe
Troussier. ``But we did not deserve this kind of result.''
	   The 3-0 was by far the most decisive match in the World Cup so
far.
	   South Africa got its only chance in first half injury time when
Issa, an Olympique Marseille teammate of Dugarry, rose above
Laurent Blanc to meet a free kick from David Nyathi, but his
glancing header went just wide of the post.
	   The only French worry was that for 78 minutes only a single goal
separated the two.
	   South Africa started as promised, with a slew of defenders
refusing to come out of that wall in front of Vonk.
	   France appeared tentative for the first 20 minutes, but slowly
started producing chances in the next 15 minutes with a half dozen
opportunities.
	   Guivarc'h was denied on a break and headed a cross just wide
before he injured his leg and was replaced in the 27th minute by
Dugarry.
	   The 26-year-old Dugarry, who some had said only received his
spot on the French team through his close friendship with Zidane
and was criticized for a string of weak performances, produced
quickly.
	   Seven minutes after entering, Vonk had to come quickly off his
line to block a shot from a charging unmarked Dugarry.
	   Dugarry appeared to get a second goal in the second half, using
the outside of his right foot from 15 meters to put a pass from
Zidane past Vonk, but Brazilian referee Maurizio Rezende earlier
had blown the play dead for a foul.
	   Throughout, South Africa was invisible up front. Even with the
Mistral winds off the Mediterranean in their favor, Marcel Desailly
and Laurent Blanc controlled the central defense and kept the
``Bafana Bafana'' from threatening French keeper Fabien Barthez.
Starting with a defensive mindset, they were unable to adjust after
Dugarry's goal and had no one to inspire them.
	   All through the evening, a strong, blustery wind whipped in from
the Mediterranean, keeping temperatures at a cool 16 degrees
Celsious (61 Fahrenheit) while gusts of up to 80 kph (50 mph)
swirled around the Velodrome stadium.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; Lineups &QC; 
	   France: Fabien Barthez; Lilian Thuram, Laurent Blanc, Marcel
Desailly, Bixente Lizarazu; Didier Deschamps, Zinedine Zidane,
Emmanuel Petit (Alain Boghossian, 74th minute); Youri Djorkaeff
(David Trezeguet, 83rd), Stephane Guivarc'h (Christophe Dugarry,
27th), Thierry Henry.
	   South Africa: Hans Vonk; Willem Jackson, Pierre Issa, Lucas
Radebe, Mark Fish; David Nyathi, John Moshoeu, Quinton Fortune,
Brendan Augustine (Helman Mkhalele, 57th), Benni McCarthy (Shaun
Bartlett, 88th), Philemon Masinga.
	   Referee: Maurizio Rezende, Brazil.
</TEXT>
