<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Pigs-NATO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Britain reconsiders medic practice on pigs in NATO exercise
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Britain has suspended its participation in a NATO
exercise in which pigs are shot to provide field practice for
medics, the Defense Ministry said Friday.
	   Armed Forces Minister John Reid has ordered a review of the
annual exercise that takes place in Denmark, after it was brought
to his attention that live pigs were being shot, a department
spokeswoman said on customary condition of anomynity.
	   She said a small team of British medics _ '' about four'' _ had
participated previously in the exercise, which is designed to allow
them to practice medical techniques.
	   Now, she said, British participation is being suspended while
the department determines if the exercise is really necessary.
	   A Scottish newspaper reported Wednesday that animal welfare
groups condemned lthe exercises in which live pigs were strung up
and shot with a variety of weapons to allow military doctors to
simulate the treatment of gunshot wounds.
	   The animals are sedated and anesthetised, then tied with ropes
to a wooden frame and fired at from short and long range, The
Scotsman newspaper said. After treatment, they are killed. Pigs
reportedly are used becausse their organs are similar to those of
humans.
	   The British Union for the Abolition of Vivisection was quoted as
calling the exercise ``morally abhorrent.''
	   ``We would be very disappointed if this is happening,'' Julie
Briggs, spokeswoman for the Royal Society for the Prevention of
Cruelty to Animals, was quoted as saying. ``It is very difficult to
ensure that the animals are not suffering any pain.''
	   The Scotsman quoted Jens Mossing, manager of the Danish animal
welfare agency Vrn For Vrrgeloese, as saying he thought the tests
had stopped in the 1980s after protests from Danish animal groups,
and that it had been very difficult to prove the exercises were
cruel.
	   The newspaper quoted an unidentified British Defense Ministry
spokesman as saying service personnel had taken part for several
years in the NATO-run course and that all procedures were conducted
under veterinary and animal welfare supervision.
	   It also quoted Capt. Paul Grooss, military attache at the Danish
Embassy in London, as saying the exercises had been taking place
for more than 20 years: ``We know this is a very sensitive field,
and people could argue that it is cruel for the animals, but it is
not something that is done for fun.''
	   (acw) 	   
</TEXT>
