<SLUG> BC-Nigeria, 8th Ld,0323 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With show of force, Nigeria's new regime dispels demonstrators
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with quote from Fawehinmi, human rights lawyer seeing
hope in Friday's actions. &QL; 
 &UR; By TIM SULLIVAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ With his forces shooting into the air,
firing tear gas and briefly detaining a leading dissident,
Nigeria's new military boss sent a clear signal Friday to his
myriad opponents: Muscle still rules this junta-weary country.
	   Opposition activists demanding an end to military rule took to
the streets in a planned mass protest, but they were quickly
confronted by a wall of police and soldiers in Lagos, Nigeria's
commercial hub.
	   Faced with his first major test _ the prospect of defiant
opposition _ Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar responded with enough force
to quell any hopes of a meaningful anti-government demonstration.
	   Police arrested Gani Fawehinmi, a lawyer and leading dissident
who organized the protests, and held him for several hours before
he was released on bail. They also arrested Dupe Abiola, one of the
wives of imprisoned businessman Moshood Abiola, the presumed winner
of canceled 1993 elections. She too was later released, along with
five other people also arrested.
	   ``This new government shows signs of repression reminiscent of
Gen. Sani Abacha's diabolical regime,'' Fawehinmi said in an
interview after his release. ``It appears nothing has changed.''
	   However, some democracy supporters saw hope in what had happened
_ notably that the arrested people were eventually freed. During
the Abacha years, people arrested would often disappear for months,
languishing in Nigerian prisons.
	   ``I think it's a good sign,'' said Clement Nwankwo, a prominent
human rights lawyer, adding that the prisoners may have been freed
as a signal to pro-democracy activists that things have changed
under Abubakar.
	    &UR; ``Soldiers are, 6th graf pvs
</TEXT>
