<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Caribbean-Briefs,0769 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A Package of Caribbean News Briefs
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 
 &UR; GUYANA: Opposition ousted from Parliament for not attending
sessions &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   GEORGETOWN, Guyana (AP) _ The representatives of the main
opposition party were kicked out of Parliament after they failed to
attend the minimum number of consecutive sessions, party officials
confirmed Friday.
	   The People's National Congress, which won 25 of the 65 seats in
Parliment in the December general election, had refused to take its
seats. The party has claimed the elections were unfair although two
international groups have said election irregularities were minor.
	   On Thursday, the government told the party to provide the names
of 25 new representatives or the ban on its attendance in
Parliament would continue indefinitely.
 &UR; TURKS AND CAICOS: Police say Haitian refugees who died were not
shot
	   COCKBURN TOWN, Turks and Caicos (AP) _ Examinations of the
bodies of six Haitian refugees who drowned Monday when their sloop
capsized off the Turks and Caicos islands showed they did not have
gunshot wounds, police said.
	   Some of the survivors of the shipwreck said marine police had
fired at the boat. But police said warning shots were fired in the
air, but not at the overcrowded boat, Deputy Police Commissioner
Bryan Davies said Friday.
	   Emma Lou, a pathologist with the Dade County Coroners Office in
Florida, was brought in to examine the bodies of the victims.
	   The sunken boat has been raised and will also be examined by
police, Davies said.
	   The ship sank Monday just 15 miles off Providenciales, the
largest island in the British archipelago 600 miles southeast of
Florida.
 &UR; MARTINIQUE: Banana growers protest crop losses due to strike
	   FORT-DE-FRANCE, Martinique (AP) _ The citizens of this Caribbean
capital awoke Friday to the surprising sight of tons of green
bananas dumped in front of the entrances of some official
buildings.
	   The bananas were left by angry producers during the night as a
protest. Berard Capgras told the Caraibes International radio
station that the bananas were part of the 4,000 tons that producers
have lost since some employees went on strike at the Fort-de-France
harbor recently.
	   Capgras said the banana producers are desperate.
	   ``We want a minimum service at the harbor,'' said Capgras. ``We
are going to lead actions until the authorities find a solution.''
	   Dock workers went on strike recently in support of workers at a
banana farm in the southern town of Francois on this Caribbean
island.
 &UR; JAMAICA: Angry depositors storm meeting
	   KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) _ Angry depositors stormed a meeting and
forced the retreat of the chief executive officer of one of
Jamaica's failed financial institutions, with some climbing on top
of his car as he sped off.
	   Henry Fullerton, CEO of Caldon Financial Group, came
face-to-face with angry investors Thursday night at a meeting
scheduled to liquidate another company. The hotel management called
police as the protesters forced their way into the meeting and
confronted Fullerton, waving placards and shouting ``We want our
money!''
	   ``You're a damned thief. You're a disgrace to society. If you go
to Timbuktu we are coming there for you,'' one person shouted at
Fullerton.
	   Fullerton agreed in February to voluntarily liquidate the Caldon
Financial Group after months of financial difficulties. The
government spent dlrs 700 million last year to take over numerous
banks and financial institutions in Jamaica to try to avoid a
financial crisis.
 &UR; UNITED STATES: Infamous smuggler may be back on the job
	   WEST PALM BEACH, Florida (AP) _ The man dubbed ``Captain Jump
Off'' for prodding smuggled illegal immigrants to jump from his
boat into choppy surf is a fugitive and could be back in business,
federal officials said.
	   Richard B. Barker, 46, of West Palm Beach, is being sought for
violation of probation after spending less than four years in
prison for the drownings of four Haitians he dropped near the
Martin County coast in 1994.
	   The U.S. Marshal's office said Barker failed to report to his
probation officer and take part in substance-abuse counseling after
his release from prison. An arrest warrant was issued Feb. 20.
	   Barker was convicted Aug. 25, 1994, on four counts of negligent
homicide. Some of the 27 Haitians aboard the 28-foot boat piloted
by Barker said they were ordered to jump off the boat into
neck-high water. 	   
