<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Angola, 1st Ld-Writethru,0187 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Security Council moves toward new, tough sanctions against UNITA,
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; URGENT &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with resolution approved; changes
throughout to conform with finalized text &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT H. REID &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ The Security Council agreed unanimously
Friday to freeze foreign-based funds of Angola's UNITA movement and
ban the sale of diamonds by the former rebels effective June 25
unless they meet terms of a peace agreement.
	   The new sanctions take effect automatically unless
Secretary-General Kofi Annan advises the Security Council by June
23 that UNITA has ``full complied ... with all relevant
obligations'' of the 1994 agreement that ended the civil war.
	   That includes allowing the Angolan government to extend its
control to UNITA-held areas _ including the movement's central
highland strongholds at Andulo and Bailundo _ complete the
demilitarization of its fighters, allow U.N. monitors to verify
compliance and cease attacks on U.N. and government personnel.
	    &UR; MORE
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-UN-Angola, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
