w2093 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APTopFinancialNews     06-12 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP Top Financial News,0756 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   A summary of financial and business news from The Associated
Press at 0000 GMT. Stories carry ``f'' or ``i'' category codes and
move on this circuit in expanded form:
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ The Dow industrials pitched a final-hour rally,
ending three days of losses as investors searched for bargain
stocks whose prices sank amid renewed fears of lower corporate
profits and Asian economic troubles. At the close of trading on
Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was up 23 points at
8,834 after sliding every day this week except Monday. The blue
chip indicator made a dramatic turnaround amid late-day
bargain-hunting after sinking nearly 128 points earlier in the day.
Broad stock market indicators were mixed. The selling occurred
after Japanese officials on Friday announced the first year of
economic contraction in two decades, which confirmed Japan is in a
severe recession and deepened fears that its financial troubles
will worsen Asia's economic crisis. (US-CLOSING STOCKS)
	   TORONTO (AP) _ Activists called off a seven-year boycott
campaign against a Japanese paper company Friday after the firm
pledged not to log on land claimed by an Indian tribe until the
disputed claim is settled. Friends of the Lubicon, a Toronto-based
group, initiated the boycott against Daishowa Inc. in 1991 in
support of the Lubicon Indians of northern Alberta. The company
said the boycott cost it dlrs 10 million. The case dates to 1988,
when Daishowa reached an agreement with federal and provincial
officials to log about 4,000 square miles (10,400 square
kilometers) of land claimed by the Lubicons. The isolated Indian
community contended that no logging rights should be awarded until
its dispute with government authorities was settled.
(CANADA-LOGGING BOYCOTT)
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ Hong Kong hopes to ride out the slide into
recession caused by the Asian financial crisis and may be among the
first to rebound, the territory's No. 2 official said Friday. Anson
Chan also said that if Congress does not renew so-called most
favored nation trading status for mainland China it would have a
severe impact on Hong Kong, which reverted from British colonial
rule last July 1. Chan said even though Hong Kong had the world's
third largest currency reserves and a well regulated banking and
financial sector, it was not spared from the financial crisis that
hit Asia last year. Analysts estimate that economic output could
fall by five percent this year if the credit crunch gripping Hong
Kong continues. The territory is experiencing its first recession
since 1985. (US-HONG KONG-ECONOMY)
	   MIAMI (AP) _ A young, telegenic state senator and rising star in
the Legislature was charged Friday with Medicare fraud, becoming
the highest-ranking figure caught up in the corruption
investigations that have engulfed Miami politics. Sen. Alberto
Gutman was accused with his wife of bilking the federal health
insurer Medicare in the early 1990s by submitting fraudulent
requests for reimbursement through two phony home health care
agencies he co-owned. He and his wife, Marcie, were released on
dlrs 150,000 bail each on federal charges of fraud, filing false
Medicare claims, witness tampering, money laundering and
conspiracy. A third defendant, businesswoman, Maricela Maury, was
also released on bail. Gutman, a 39-year-old Cuban-born Republican
who represents Miami's Little Havana section, called the case
politically motivated. (US-MIAMI-CORRUPTION)
	   DETROIT (AP) _ Worried that the progress in streamlining its
operations hasn't been enough, General Motors Corp. is in an
all-out war with its workers to make itself a leaner, more
competitive global automaker. Though GM profits total billions of
dollars thanks to a healthy U.S. economy, it still lags behind Ford
Motor Co., Chrysler Corp. and the foreign ``transplant'' automakers
in factory productivity. GM has reduced its U.S. work force by
65,000 hourly jobs in the past five years, but still needs to cut
an additional 50,000 jobs to become competitive, analysts say. To
the United Auto Workers that's unacceptable. GM's North American
production, already crippled by a UAW strike that began June 5 at a
Flint stamping plant where sheet-metal parts are made, could come
to a virtual standstill by the end of next week because of a strike
that began Thursday at the Delphi Flint East parts plant. Talks
resumed at both plants Friday. There was no word on any progress.
(US-GM-STRIKE)
</TEXT>
