<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0678 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   A summary of late news from The Associated Press. Some items
have moved on this circuit in expanded form with ``i'' or ``f''
category codes:
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ Russia and the NATO allies agreed
Friday that the explosive situation in Kosovo represents a grave
danger to its neighbors but differed on how to deal with defiant
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen, who had a private meeting with Russian Defense
Minister Igor Sergeyev, stressed the urgency of finding a solution
to hostilities in the southern Yugoslavian province. However,
Sergeyev said Russia ``is convinced we haven't exhausted all
non-military means ... to resolve this crisis.'' Cohen said Russia
risked isolation if it blocked international efforts. NATO plans as
early as next week to demonstrate allied air power over neighboring
Albania and Macedonia in hopes of impressing Milosevic and making
him rethink his policy of escalating violence in Kosovo.
(NATO-KOSOVO)
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ With his forces shooting into the air,
firing tear gas and briefly detaining a leading dissident,
Nigeria's new military boss sent a clear signal Friday to his
myriad opponents: Muscle still rules this junta-weary country.
Opposition activists demanding an end to military rule took to the
streets in a planned mass protest, but they were quickly confronted
by a wall of police and soldiers in Lagos, Nigeria's commercial
hub. Police arrested Gani Fawehinmi, a lawyer and leading dissident
who organized the protests, and held him for several hours before
he was released on bail. They also arrested Dupe Abiola, one of the
wives of imprisoned businessman Moshood Abiola, the presumed winner
of canceled 1993 elections. She too was later released, along with
five other detainees. (NIGERIA)
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) _ Tens of thousands of people fled the
former Portuguese colony of Guinea-Bissau on Friday as government
troops fought renegade soldiers who launched a coup attempt,
according to reports. As many as 40,000 people in the West African
nation were heading on foot along the road to the northern border
with Senegal, a Portuguese journalist in the area said, citing
local reports. More than 2,200 people, mostly foreigners, arrived
in Dakar, Senegal, on Friday after being evacuated from the
capital, Bissau, on a Portuguese merchant ship. In Bissau, the
French embassy was hit by a bazooka shell but no one was injured,
the Portuguese news agency Lusa reported. (GUINEA-BISSAU)
	   LAS MARGARITAS, Mexico (AP) _ Amid fears of renewed war between
Zapatista rebels and the government, Mexico's president flew to
Chiapas on Friday to defend his administration's stated desire for
dialogue and pledge money for towns where rebel support runs high.
Some analysts say a police and army raid on an Indian village this
week is the latest indication that the government has chosen
military might over talks. Nine people were killed when government
forces clashed Wednesday with apparent Zapatista rebels while
trying to evict a symbolic pro-rebel town council. As the president
spoke in Chiapas, a dozen people unfurled banners demanding a halt
to violence. In Las Margaritas, Zedillo signed an accord granting
aid to 42 municipalities ``that need special attention,'' he said.
(MEXICO-CHIAPAS)
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ The Chinese ambassador suggested Friday that
the United States needs China as an ally in a region troubled by
fresh nuclear threats and financial crisis. Just two weeks before
President Clinton was to visit China, Ambassador Li Zhaoxing
offered assurances that his nation has only peaceful and prosperous
ambitions. ``China presents no threat to any country, at all,'' Li
said, denying U.S. intelligence information that Beijing's nuclear
missiles are targeting American cities. Clinton's five-city
journey, from June 25 to July 3, will be the first visit to China
by an American president since the 1989 crackdown on pro-democracy
students at Tiananmen Square. (US-CHINA)
</TEXT>
