<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ecuador-Galapagos Sinking,0302 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tourist ship sinks off Galapagos Islands; one dead and three
</HEADLINE>
missing &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   QUITO, Ecuador (AP) _ A 70-year-old woman died and three people
were missing after a boat carrying 15 elderly American tourists
sank off the coast of one of the Galapagos islands, port
authorities said Friday.
	   The U.S. Embassy identified the dead woman as Diane Sayre but
had no information on her home town.
	   The missing passengers were identified as Richard Sayre, 80,
Robert Donna, 75, and Lyon Zeiler, 75, by Lt. Jacinto Trivino, the
captain of the port of Puerto Ayora in the Galapagos Islands. But
U.S. Embassy officials could not confirm the names.
	   One of the 11 passengers who were rescued from Wednesday night's
shipwreck suffered serious injury, Trivino said. Eight crewmen also
survived.
	   The boat, called the ``Moby Dick,'' sank after sea conditions
changed suddenly and two large waves swamped the boat near the
island of Santa Fe, which forms part of the Galapagos archipelago,
Trivino said. Passengers did not have time to put on their life
jackets, he said.
	   A navy and private boats were searching for the missing
tourists, but hopes for finding them alive are dim, he said.
	   ``The people who are missing were lost because they were elderly
_ 70 to 80 years old _ and did not know how to swim,'' said Antonio
Saman, manager of the Galasam travel agency, which organized the
chartered boat tour.
	   The boat stayed afloat for 20 to 30 minutes before sinking. A
nearby yacht arrived within 10 minutes after the boat sank and
began rescuing the survivors from the water.
	   The Galapagos Islands, home to unique forms of animal and plant
life, are located 600 miles (1,000 kms) west of the Ecuadorean
mainland. They are Ecuador's major tourist attraction.
</TEXT>
