<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turks and Caicos-Haitian Refugees,0269 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Examinations find Haitians who died in capsized boat were not shot
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   COCKBURN TOWN, Turks and Caicos (AP) _ The bodies of six Haitian
refugees who drowned when their sloop capsized off the Turks and
Caicos islands had no bullet wounds, police said.
	   Some survivors of the shipwreck claimed that marine police fired
at the overcrowded boat. But police have said they only fired
warning shots in the air.
	   A pathologist with the Dade County Coroner's Office in Florida
was brought in to examine the bodies. No gunshot wounds were found,
police said Friday.
	   The ship sank Monday, just 25 kilometers (15 miles) off
Providenciales, the largest island in the British archipelago,
which is 1,000 kilometers (600 miles) southeast of Florida.
	   The boat has been raised and will be examined, Deputy Police
Commissioner Bryan Davies said.
	   The 70 Haitians who survived are being interviewed with the help
of interpreters. The Haitians, who largely speak Creole, also spent
more than an hour Thursday talking with a representative from the
Haitian consulate in the Bahamas.
	   Survivors said as many as 113 people were on the boat. Police
said there were about 70 survivors and only six bodies were
recovered.
	   Davies said police also want to interview the occupants of two
yachts that may have been nearby when the ship sank. The names of
the vessels are unknown, but some survivors said they were flying
U.S. flags.
	   Thousands of Haitian refugees fleeing their impoverished country
have ended up in the Turks and Caicos islands in recent years.
</TEXT>
