w2111 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Soccer-WorldCu     06-12 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup Roundup,0616 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Host hits three, helped by another own goal
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS previous &QL; 
 &UR; BY ROBERT MILLWARD &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ The first red card, the first scoreless tie, the
first team to score three times.
	   Almost the first World Cup strike by a goalkeeper.
	   Oh, and another own goal.
	   While furious Japanese fans continued their search for tickets
they had been promised and had paid for, day three of the World Cup
produced a curious mixture on the field.
	   Veteran striker Hristo Stoichkov fired against the post and
Paraguay's attack-minded goalkeeper, Jose Luis Chilavert produced
the best free kick so far.
	   It was curling just under the crossbar from 30 meters but
Bulgarian 'keeper Zdravko Zdravkov produced an acrobatic save to
make sure the game ended 0-0.
	   ``I already saw the ball in the net,'' said Chilavert, who has
35 goals in his professional career. ``Too bad, I could have made
history.''
	   Bulgaria's Anatoli Nankov became the first player of the
championship to be expelled. But at least it was for two yellow
cards. We're still awaiting the first red card for a tackle from
behind.
	   Bulgaria-Paraguay was game five and the first to be scoreless.
It was followed by Denmark's 1-0 victory over Saudi Arabia in which
defender Marc Rieper headed the winner and Michael Laudrup made his
100th appearance with a win.
	   Having held its breath for the opening two days, the host nation
went into action against South Africa and came up with the biggest
win so far.
	   In a one-sided 3-0 victory in Marseille, it was uncanny that
Olympique striker Christophe Dugarry netted the first and teammate
Pierre Issa added the second.
	   Trouble was, Issa was playing for South Africa.
	   The defender lunged at a goalbound Youri Djorkaeff strike, which
'keeper Hans Vonk appeared to have covered, and deflected it the
other way into the net.
	   Issa became the third player in three days to score in his own
net after Scotland's Tommy Boyd against Brazil and Morocco's
Youssef Chippo against Norway.
	   To make things worse for Issa, FIFA announced later his
deflection past his own 'keeper was the 1,600th goal in the history
of World Cup final tournaments.
	   Monaco's Thierry Henry saved his embarrassment by scoring a
third for the French in injury time as the host nation went to the
top of Group C, ahead of the Danes.
	   ``The door is wide open now,'' said French coach Aime Jacquet.
``We are really confident.''
	   It was cruel World Cup debut for South Africa, the former
African Nations Cup holder.
	   ``We were missing experience and chances to play together. We
played against a great team,'' said South Africa's coach Philippe
Troussier. ``But we did not deserve this kind of result.''
	   In Saturday's games, Olympic champion Nigeria faced Spain in
Nantes, neighbors Belgium and the Netherlands confronted each other
in Paris and South Korea met Mexico at Lyon.
	   Meanwhile, the ticket problems that have plagued the organizing
committee for more than a year, were biting hard as the tournament
went into a fourth day.
	   Fans from as far afield as Japan have arrived in France to find
the tickets aren't here to meet them and FIFA, soccer's governing
body, is investigating two national federations and a subsidiary of
its own marketing arm regarding game ticket fraud at the World Cup.
	   FIFA, which said it had complaints from fans missing tickets in
the Netherlands, Belgium, Germany, England and Brazil, as well as
Japan, said it has warned fans not to deal with anyone but licensed
ticket operators.
</TEXT>
