r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UN-BurundiTalks     06-12 0388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Burundi Talks,0394 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Annan urges success in Burundi talks, offers readiness to help
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ROBERT H. REID &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Secretary-General Kofi Annan urged all
parties in Burundi to show a ``spirit of cooperation'' in next
week's peace talks and offered U.N. help ``at all stages of this
process.''
	   Talks open Monday in Arusha, Tanzania, between Burundi's
Tutsi-led government and its Hutu opponents. Burundi's President
Pierre Buyoya will take part in the talks, arranged by former
Tanzanian President Julius Nyerere.
	   ``The secretary-general urges all parties, both within and
outside the country, to act in a spirit of cooperation, tolerance
and reconciliation and refrain from any action that could undermine
the chances of reaching the sort of peaceful and stable settlement
that is so necessary for the people of Burundi and for the region
as a whole,'' the United Nations said in a statement.
	   The statement added that Annan ``reaffirms the readiness of the
United Nations to continue to assist (Nyerere) and the parties at
all stages of the process.''
	   At least 200,000 people have died in politically motivated
ethnic violence in the tiny African country since October 1993,
when Tutsi paratroopers assassinated the country's first
democratically elected president, a Hutu.
	   Buyoya, a retired Tutsi army major who ousted Hutu coalition
President Sylvestre Ntibantunganya in July 1996, has proposed a
transitional government that comprises all political parties.
	   Hutu rebels are trying to oust Buyoya's Tutsi-led government and
army and reinstate a Hutu as president.
	   Buyoya boycotted talks last year brokered by Nyerere because he
claimed the former Tanzanian president was pro-Hutu. Five days
after Buyoya's 1996 coup, Burundi's neighbors imposed economic
sanctions in order to force Buyoya to return to the partial
democracy he overthrew.
	   Tutsis make up just 14 percent of Burundi's population of 6
million.
	   But they have controlled the country for all but four months
since independence in 1962. Hutus make up 85 percent of the
population.
	   On June 6, a transitional constitution took effect under which a
government of transition and an expanded national assembly of 121
seats will be established.
</TEXT>
