r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Hungary-Chess     06-12 0319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hungary-Chess,0318 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Polgar defeats Karpov 5-3 in battle of sexes
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) _ Judit Polgar, the 21-year-old Hungarian
chess prodigy, dealt a humiliating blow to defending world chess
champion Anatoly Karpov, winning a speed match challenge 5-3
Friday.
	   On the last day of a four-day, eight-match contest that was the
first to pit the world's top male and female players, both games
ended in ties.
	   ``I think this is the greatest failure of Karpov's life, and it
must be hard for him to suffer this defeat,'' said Laszlo Polgar,
father and coach of Judit and her two sisters, both chess masters.
	   ``It's a great feeling to defeat the world champion,'' a visibly
tired Judit Polgar said after her win.
	   Karpov was unavailable for comment, leaving the venue
immediately.
	   In Friday's first game, Karpov started with an English opening,
was in a winning position in most of the game but blundered in the
endgame. The two agreed a tie on the 71st move.
	   That meant that _ irrespective of the last match _ Judit had won
their contest.
	   The last game went without much excitement. Karpov, playing
black, started with a Caro-Kann defense, then played a Panov
variation.
	   Polgar failed to capitalize on a potentially winning advantage,
and a tie was agreed on the 68th move.
	   This was the first time in chess history that the top male and
female players played each other.
	   Although Karpov is world champion of the World Chess Federation,
FIDE, fellow Russian Garry Kasparov is regarded the true world
champion.
	   Laszlo Polgar said after the match that Kasparov's
representative watched the Budapest match and that a match between
Judit Polgar and Kasparov in already being negotiated.
	   ``There is already dlrs 1 million prize money offered for that
match,'' he said, but declined to answer who the sponsor would be
or where it would be played. 	   
</TEXT>
