<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-France-Henry,0424 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Henry comes from nowhere to steal limelight
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Sports-Soccer-France-South Africa &QL; 
 &UR; By RAF CASERT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MARSEILLE, France (AP) _ The World Cup has a knack of springing
surprises. Any armchair pundit who would have predicted two months
ago Thierry Henry would have been on France's lineup would have
been laughed into embarrassment.
	   To have predicted he would have scored a great World Cup goal
with a darting run and sweet finish would have been beyond words.
	   Yet Monaco's Henry made a startling recovery from a midseason
slump, squeezed into the World Cup squad of 22 against expectations
last month and rode that piece of luck right into Friday's opener
against South Africa.
	   And with a darting run down the right and a subtle finish over
the outstretched hands of 'keeper Hans Vonk, the 20-year-old drove
home the last goal in a 3-0 thrashing of South Africa.
	   ``We will savor this win but we mustn't rest on our laurels,''
Henry said afterwards. He knows about resting on his laurels,
	   Henry started the season in startling form bobbing and weaving
through the defense of some of the best continental clubs during
the European Champions League, scoring a half dozen goals as Monaco
reached the semifinals.
	   But suddenly, as quickly as his form dropped, reports of his
personal problems rose, and Henry was a young spirit finding it
tough to adapt to an adult life. ``There were moments when it was
really tough,'' he said.
	   As his fortunes sank, one of the people who continued to believe
in him was goalkeeper Fabien Barthez, also of Monaco and the French
team.
	   During the spring, the intense goalkeeper took the wayward
youngster aside and gave him the grilling of his life. ``It's true,
it was heated,'' said Henry. Barthez basically told that even if
things looked bad, the World Cup still was within reach.
	   ``It really dawned on me. If somebody like that backs you, it
means something,'' he said.
	   Suddenly he was back in the hunt.
	   In the European Champions Cup semifinal, he found his old touch
again, and despite Monaco's loss to Juventus Turin, Jacquet had
noticed the prodigal son was back.
	   Good outings during the preparation campaign and he was selected
for the squad of 22 and against all expectations. Friday's opener.
	   ``You have to work. Work brings about everything,'' he said.
``Work and a sense that you should never be satisfied.''
</TEXT>
