<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Tickets,0346 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Ticket problems rumble into day four
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ The World Cup ticket flap just goes on and on.
	   After month after month of taking hassle from English, Dutch,
German and Italian fans for their ticket distribution policy, World
Cup organizers now have to face supporters who have arrived in
France to find there is no ticket at all.
	   Among them are 76 Japanese fans who have flown thousands of
miles to see their country play in the World Cup for the first
time. They have just 40 tickets between them.
	   Bruno Travade, a spokesman for the World Cup organizing
committee, said he could not explain reports that 12,000 Japanese
tickets had gone missing and that five Japanese travel agencies
reportedly were deciding to cancel World Cup tours.
	   He said that representatives of the only three licensed ticket
agencies for Asia _ JT Travel, Ken R Tours and Prime Sports
International _ picked up their tickets at the organizers' Paris
headquarters between April 27-29.
	   ``We have the receipts, signed by representatives of the tour
operators, that they collected the number and classification of
tickets they had contracted for,'' Travade said.
	   The Japanese aren't the only fans to say they have arrived in
France to find the tickets aren't here.
	   Brazilians and English followers also were caught up, many of
them after travel companies failed to come up with the tickets.
	   Worldwide, Travade said, 138,000 tickets had been distributed to
17 licensed agencies. Other brokers who peddled World Cup tickets
face legal action, the spokesman said.
	   ``We will sue anyone or any organization who undertakes to
damage our image or intentions,'' Travade said. ``And we encourage
individuals to sue the persons who cheated them.''
	   Masami Tachi, a 34-year-old housewife from Tokyo, is one of the
Japanese fans caught in the ticket trap.
	   ``We came here to see the World Cup,'' she said. ``It's not good
enough to get the money back for the tickets.''
</TEXT>
