<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo,0733 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Militants move closer to Kosovo's capital, kill two Serb policemen
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS previous &QL; 
 &UR; With Yugoslavia-NATO, Albania-Rudderless Rebels &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos BAJ101-103 &QL; 
 &UR; By ISMET HAJDARI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Boldly striking just outside the
capital, Kosovo's ethnic Albanian militants said they killed two
Serb policemen in one of a series of attacks around the
secessionist province.
	   Rebels also Friday claimed to have mustered a 15,000-strong
fighting force for the escalating battle against Serb rule. The
Kosovo Liberation Army, a shadowy group that first emerged in 1996,
said it intended to prove it has a large force uniting the
province's majority ethnic Albanians.
	   The level of fighting has escalated in recent weeks. KLA attacks
such as the killing of the policemen have come to the edge of
Pristina, Kosovo's capital, severed main roads and occasionally
shut the city airport.
	   Popular support for the KLA's militancy has grown, making it
more difficult to envisage the negotiated settlement the United
States and other Western nations seek.
	   On Friday, fighting between Serbian forces and the militants
erupted again in the Decani region in western Kosovo, close to the
border with Albania.
	   Ethnic Albanian sources said seven villages were under Serb
attack, pummeled by artillery and grenade launchers.
	   One ethnic Albanian was killed, they said; their report could
not be independently confirmed.
	   Last week's latest Serb offensive in western Kosovo prompted
NATO to announce Thursday it would stage a show of air power to
persuade Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to halt the
assaults.
	   Ethnic Albanians outnumber Serbs by 9-to-1 in Kosovo. Most want
independence from Serbia, which in 1989 stripped the southern
province of broad autonomy and has governed through military and
police rule ever since. More than 250 people have died since March,
when Serb forces started a crackdown aimed at Albanian militants.
	   An estimated 60,000 villagers fled their homes in Kosovo during
the latest Serb offensive, the U.N. refugee agency said. Thousands
have crossed rugged mountains into Albania and Macedonia. The
nations border Serbia, the dominant of two republics remaining in
the former Yugoslavia.
	   A U.N. war crimes tribunal said Friday it was sending
investigators on a U.S.-backed mission to Kosovo to check out
allegations of atrocities in the Serb offensive.
	   Militants have gained much more popular support since March, and
young Kosovo Albanians who live in western Europe have flocked to
Albania to organize or fight.
	   The KLA said it now commanded 15,000 fighters and named Jakup
Krasniqi, a teacher from the Drenica region, as its spokesman.
	   Fighting between the militants and Serb forces has come much
closer to Pristina in recent weeks, causing the occasional shutdown
of the city's airport, 13 kilometers (8 miles) west of Pristina.
	   Serb sources in the province said two policemen where killed and
one was seriously wounded in an overnight ambush by separatists
near Obilic, just 7 kilometers (4 miles) northwest of Pristina.
	   The ethnic Albanian daily Bujku reported Friday that five ethnic
Albanians and seven Serbs were killed in fierce clashes Thursday in
Suvo Grlo in the Drenica area, 32 kilometers (20 miles) west of
Pristina.
	   In other fighting, the state-run Tanjug news agency in Belgrade
reported that a Serb policeman was seriously hurt in what it called
an attack by ``armed Albanian terrorists'' near one of the seven
Kosovo villages, Prilep.
	   Albanian sources also reported Serb attacks on villages in the
Obilic and adjacent Vucitrn regions, saying residents who fled the
fighting spent the night under open skies.
	   NATO is planning simulated air attacks in Albania and Macedonia
to try to persuade Milosevic to halt military action in Kosovo.
	   On Friday, Western foreign ministers met in London with their
Russian counterpart to step up pressure on Milosevic. Britain,
which is weighing a U.N. move to back use of NATO force in Kosovo,
urged Milosevic to pull back his troops immediately.
	   The United States, Canada, Britain, France, Italy and Germany
also said they would move to ban flights by Yugoslav Airlines to
underline their concern about the violence in Kosovo, British
Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said.
</TEXT>
