<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Brazil,0364 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Leonardo could be new starter on Brazilian team
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By PETER MUELLO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   OZOIR-LA-FERRIERE, France (AP) _ Hush. Zagallo's thinking.
	   While the Brazilian training camp is abuzz that the veteran
coach plans changes to the lineup after an indifferent performance
against Scotland, Mario Zagallo won't say what's on his mind.
	   Followers of the four-time titlist are suggesting that Zagallo
will drop the disappointing Giovanni from the lineup and start AC
Milan midfielder Leonardo.
	   ``Everybody's saying Leonardo is the starter,'' Zagallo said
after Friday's practice. ``I don't want to talk right now. I want
to take a few days and think about it.''
	   But Zagallo made no secret that he felt the team played better
with Leonardo, who replaced Giovanni at the start of the second
half. The defense became stronger, the offense sharper, and Brazil
gradually dominated the stalwart but limited Scots in a 2-1 victory
in the opening game of the championship.
	   Giovanni ignored requests for interviews and raced into the
dressing room after Friday's practice.
	   ``I thought he was very apathetic. He didn't show up on the
field,'' Zagallo said. ``I don't know what the matter is. I'm a
soccer coach, not a psychologist.''
	   But Zagallo's substitution of Giovanni was a clear sign of his
displeasure. Normally, the coach discusses what he feels were a
player's errors during halftime, and gives him a second chance in
the final 45 minutes. With Giovanni, he ran out of patience.
	   ``A player with Giovanni's talent and strength can't be so out
of tune,'' team coordinator Zico said. ``He was very dispersive.
	   ``Leonardo trains as if it were a real game, and when he plays,
he shows motivation and joy.''
	   Leonardo started his career in the back before switching to
midfield and that could give him an edge because Morocco has a
talented offensive team that is expected to press the Brazilians
more than Scotland.
	   ``I've been prepared for a long time,'' Leonardo said. ``The
coach has to be illuminated to decide and choose the best.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Soccer-Brazil; CT:s; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
