<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Italy-Baggio,0391 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Baggio may have earned himself a permanent position in
</HEADLINE>
Italy's lineup &QL; 
 &UR; By PIERO VALSECCHI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SENLIS, France (AP) _ Roberto Baggio, a veteran brought to
France as a substitute for the injured Alessandro Del Piero, played
so well in Italy's opener against Chile that coach Cesare Maldini
is considering pairing him with the star striker in future matches.
	   The combination, considered outlandish a few days ago, is now a
distinct possibility. Baggio is in top form and Del Piero is ready
to return to the team from a painful right thigh strain.
	   ``I must understand if they can play together, and in which way.
I have several days for deciding, before the next match,'' Maldini
said at Italy's training camp in Senlis following a dramatic 2-2
draw against Chile at Bordeaux.
	   Baggio was the best player on the Italian side and salvaged
Italy from a sensational upset by earning and converting a late
penalty.
	   ``I don't know if they are compatible. I'll think of it,''
Maldini said.
	   Italy may need to field a third forward in their game against
Cameroon Wednesday as Baggio and Christian Vieri looked quite
isolated in front against Chile.
	   ``That was a tactical problem (against the Chileans). We must
improve cohesion between midfield and the attack,'' the Italian
coach explained.
	   He rejected criticism of young defenders Alessandro Nesta and
Fabio Cannavaro, who had a difficult match against Ivan Zamorano
and Marcelo Salas in Thursday's match of Group B.
	   Salas scored both Chile's goals while Zamorano was a steady
threat with his headers.
	   ``Zamorano is one of the best world players in aerial play and
is difficult to stop. I can say both Nesta and Cannavaro will start
against Cameroon,'' Maldini said.
	   ``We are aware that Cameroon is very strong athletically. We
will study the tape of its last match against Austria tonight,'' he
said.
	   Del Piero, 23, practiced full time Friday and said he felt ready
to play against Cameroon.
	   ``It's up to Maldini to decide if I can be started. I am ready.
I see no problem in playing with three forwards, along with Roberto
(Baggio),'' Del Piero said.
	   Maldini said Italy will have to play for victory against
Cameroon.
</TEXT>
