<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Recession,0671 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japan's recession deepens fears of regional crisis
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos TOK101-103,105-107 &QL; 
 &UR; By JOJI SAKURAI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ News that Japan is mired in recession has sparked
fears of another round of regional currency devaluations.
	   In a much-awaited announcement, the Economic Planning Agency
said Friday that the gross domestic product in the world's
second-largest economy shrank for two consecutive quarters, and
that it suffered the first full year of negative growth in 20
years.
	   That bodes badly for the rest of Asia, which has been nursing
the wounds of last year's regionwide currency crisis. Asian
countries have been heavily reliant on Japanese investment and
Japanese loans, and they consider Japan a vital import market.
	   But with its own economy in tatters and consumer confidence at
all-time lows, Japan will be more tempted than ever to embark on a
path of export-led growth _ and if it does, the government will be
very reluctant to stem the yen's slide against the dollar. A cheap
yen makes Japanese exports cheaper, and thus more popular,
overseas.
	   A continued plunge in the yen _ it fell again Friday, to as low
as 144.75 to the dollar _ could set off another round of regional
currency devaluations as Asian countries fight to keep their
products competitive in key foreign markets.
	   The yen's weakness, which makes it less profitable for U.S.
companies to sell goods throughout Asia, has weighed on the stock
market and pushed the Dow Jones industrial average down by as much
as 250 points this week. Hard times in Japan mean consumers there
are more reluctant to spend money on goods made elsewhere.
	   The weak Asian currencies have helped keep U.S. inflation in
check. The lower prices of imported goods has held back price
increases and largely done the work of the Federal Reserve, which
otherwise may have increased interest rates by now to cool the
economy.
	   U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, speaking in Alabama on
Friday, stressed his concern about Japan's ailing economy. Rubin
has been pushing Japan for months to take measures to stimulate its
economy.
	   The fate of the rest of Asia's struggling economies depends on
Japan, Rubin said. ``It is a very serious problem for the world.''
	   Friday's numbers out of Tokyo depicted an economy in need of
serious first aid.
	   The government said gross domestic product, the sum of all goods
and services produced in Japan, fell by a steeper-than-expected 1.3
percent in the January-March quarter, following a drop of 0.4
percent in the previous quarter.
	   Two straight quarters of economic contraction is the generally
accepted definition of a recession.
	   Worse yet, the agency said Japan's GDP for fiscal year 1997,
which ended in March 1998, shrank by 0.7 percent, the first full
year of economic contraction since 1974, when the economy was
suffering from the oil shock.
	   The news in other Asian countries Friday was not much better.
	   Asian stock markets ended the week mixed, but the key index in
Seoul tumbled 8.1 percent _ its biggest ever one-day fall _ on
fears that the falling yen could wreck South Korea's own plans for
an export-led recovery.
	   While Japan hardly seems in a position to rescue Asia's other
ailing economies, the reverse is also true. The government said
falling demand for Japanese goods in Asia, Japan's largest market,
was a prime reason for Friday's negative numbers. Exports dropped
by 3.8 percent in the January-March quarter.
	   Japan's prospects for the current year are bleak. Economists say
a dlrs 116 billion stimulus package _ which represents 1 percent of
Japan's GDP _ will help growth, but won't be enough to sustain a
recovery.
	   While Japanese officials avoided the word ``recession'' in
addressing Friday's developments, they acknowledged the news was
bad.
	   ``The data illustrated the severity of the economy,'' said
Shimpei Nukaya, the top-ranking bureaucrat at the Economic Planning
Agency.
</TEXT>
