<SLUG> BC-Indonesia,0409 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Twelve East Timorese political prisoners released
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos JAK101-106 &QL; 
 &UR; By CHRISTOPHER TORCHIA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   DILI, Indonesia (AP) _ Raising their fists in the air as they
walked from jail, a dozen political prisoners pardoned by
Indonesia's new president pledged to renew their pro-independence
campaign for East Timor.
	   The prisoners, many of them students, were freed Friday by
President B.J. Habibie, who is seeking an end to a conflict that
has plagued East Timor since Indonesia invaded the former
Portuguese colony in 1975 and annexed the territory a year later.
	   More than 1,000 protesters rallied Friday at the Foreign
Ministry in the Indonesian capital of Jakarta, pressing for a vote
on East Timor independence.
	   Police and troops broke up the rally by beating and kicking
protesters, confiscating rebel flags and anti-Indonesian banners
and herding people onto buses that were driven away under police
escort.
	   The Foreign Ministry said two East Timorese women were
hospitalized. A security guard also was treated after being hit by
a rock.
	   In Dili, the East Timorese capital, the 12 prisoners filed out
of Becora prison shouting separatist slogans and carrying plastic
bags full of clothes and other belongings. One man clutched a
chicken.
	   ``This freedom is good for our struggle. It's a victory for
us,'' said Tomas Augusto Correia, a 33-year-old municipal worker
who was among the detainees.
	   On Thursday, the prisoners in Dili refused to leave the jail,
saying they wanted freedom for rebel chief Xanana Gusmao. They
agreed to go Friday after giving wardens a litany of complaints,
ranging from the poor quality of prison food to military
repression.
	   Gusmao, 52, was arrested in 1992 and is serving a 20-year
sentence in a Jakarta prison. He is a hero to many East Timorese
who see him as a symbol of their struggle against Indonesian rule.
	   Habibie is reluctant to yield to demands for a referendum on
independence in East Timor. Instead, he has offered the area a
special status that might include some autonomy.
	   And the government has yet to make clear what it plans to do
with Gusmao, whose case has attracted international attention,
including a plea from South African President Nelson Mandela for
his release.
	   Tens of thousands of East Timorese died during Indonesia's
efforts in the 1970s to wipe out the area's independence movement.
</TEXT>
