<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Denmark-Saudi Arabia,0459 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Rieper heads Denmark to 1-0 victory over Saudi Arabia
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS previous &QL; 
 &UR; By ADNAN MALIK &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LENS, France (AP) _ Delighted coach Bo Johansson is confident
Denmark team can beat South Africa in its second Group C World Cup
encounter and make it to the next round.
	   ``We know they are a difficult team to beat but we know that we
can win so we will try to do the best,'' Johansson, a Swede, said
after the Danes' 1-0 victory over Saudi Arabia at Felix Bollaert
Stadium.
	   Danish supporters went into a frenzy as defender Marc Rieper
neatly headed a cross into the net to give Denmark its victory.
	   The Danes next face South Africa in Toulouse June 18 while Saudi
Arabia faces a daunting match against France in Saint-Denis on the
same day.
	   Rieper rose unmarked in the box in the 68th minute to secure the
points for the Danes after a poor show by Saudi Arabia.
	   ``We created a lot of chances so we should have won by a bigger
margin,'' Rieper said.
	   Denmark dominated through out the match but could not convert
its superiority into a goal until the second half before 38,140
fans at the 41,275-seater stadium.
	   Brian Laudrup and his older brother Michael, playing in his
100th international, caused problems for the Saudi defense, but
Denmark lacked a knockout punch.
	   Early in the match the Saudis continually squandered possession
with inaccurate passing, seemingly taking time to warm up on a cold
day in this northern French coal mining town.
	   The Saudi's coach, Carlos Alberto Parreira, who led Brazil to a
record fourth World Cup triumph four years ago, praised the Danes,
but also said his team had acquitted itself well.
	   ``We played against a good team with nice players and they did
well,'' he said.
	   Saudi Arabia played with style, especially in the second half,
Parreira said, but added that misplaced passes let them down. ``We
gave away so many balls,'' he said, ``so we lost a little
control.''
	   Denmark created ample chances _ Ebbe Sand and Martin Jorgensen
both missed good opportunities before the break.
	   But the Danes finally found a way to the net in the 68th minute
when Brian Laudrup crossed from the right to Rieper in the center
who headed past al-Deayea.
	   Saudi Arabia nearly pulled back a quick equalizer but Ibrahim
al-Shahrani's flicked header drifted wide after a good cross from
the right by Mohammed al-Jahani.
	   Denmark and Saudi Arabia both were making their second
appearances in the World Cup finals. The countries reached the last
16 in their previous visits to the finals, Denmark in 1986 and
Saudi Arabia in 1994.
</TEXT>
