<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-LPGA-Oldsmobile,0370 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Andrews holds lead after second round
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   EAST LANSING, Michigan (AP) _ Donna Andrews survived a
double-bogey, a double hit and a 2 1/2-hour rain delay to shoot a
4-under-par 68 Friday and remain in the lead after the second round
of the LPGA Oldsmobile Classic.
	   Andrews, who is the tour's leading money-winner this season, is
at 12-under 132 midway through the dlrs 650,000 tournament, leading
Canadian Lisa Walters by two strokes with Meg Mallon another stroke
back.
	   Andrews, who has won more than dlrs 465,000 this season,
double-bogeyed No. 9, a 385-yard (350-meter) par-4 after hitting
her second shot into a bunker.
	   She double hit a chip shot on 15, a 397-yard par-4 and had to
make a short putt to save bogey.
	   ``I have hit a lot of good shots this week but I've made some
mistakes too,'' said Andrews, who opened with a 64 that gave her a
two-stroke lead. ``I've been able to get away with it. I've had my
share of good breaks and you just have to take what you get.''
	   Andrews, who won the Longs Drugs Challenge in April and who has
finished second each of the past three weeks, had not practiced a
bunker shot at Walnut Hills Country Club when she stepped into that
trap on No. 9.
	   ``It's my own fault,'' she said. ``I hadn't worked on it and I
hit a fat bunker shot. A lack of practice is what that was.''
	   A second round with seven birdies kept Andrews atop the
leaderboard.
	   ``I make mistakes but I try not to make a big deal out of it,''
Andrews said. ``I'm good about focusing in the present and not
worrying about what's in the past. There are a lot of birdies out
here and they are there for me if I hit the ball well.''
	   Walters is 10 under after two 67s. She birdied four of her first
six holes Friday morning then added a birdie on No. 12.
	   ``I drove and putted well but I missed greens due to the wind,''
Walters said. ``It was hard to judge because it was swirling.
(Thursday) I missed putts but today I made everything.''
	   Mallon had a second-round 66 to hold third place. Four players,
Mardi Lunn, Karrie Webb, Karen Weiss and Julie Piers are four
strokes back at eight under.
</TEXT>
