<HEADLINE>
APTV 0100 GMT Outlook
</HEADLINE>

 &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  APTV 0100 OUTLOOK SATURDAY 13 JUNE 1998  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC; 

 &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  For Planner / Newsdesk use - stories expected to move in the
next 12 hours.  All times are GMT  &QC;  &QC;  &QC; 
----
EXPECTED:  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC; 
----
WORLD CUP: FANS 2 - French supporters took to the streets of
Marseille and the capital, Paris, after their team defeated South
Africa 3-0 in the World Cup. APTV has coverage of the celebrations.
(FIRST RUN 0300 EUROPE EARLY)
----
US: HOLBROOKE - APTV has an interview with Richard Holbrooke -
architect of the Dayton peace accord and special envoy to Cyprus. He
talks about his Bosnian experience and the current crisis in Kosovo.
(FIRST RUN 0300 EUROPE EARLY)
----
UN: ANGOLA - The Security Council agreed unanimously to freeze
foreign-based funds of Angola's UNITA movement and ban the sale of
diamonds by the former rebels effective June 25 unless they meet
terms of a peace agreement. APTV has comments from various U-N
ambassadors. (FIRST RUN 0300 EUROPE EARLY)
----
US: CLINTON - President Bill Clinton moved to better protect the seas by
announcing a series of measures, including an extension of a ban on
most offshore oil drilling. APTV's package includes soundbites from
Clinton. (FIRST RUN 0300 EUROPE EARLY)
----
IRAN: FOOTBALL - With the start of the World Cup, nations around the
globe are going football crazy. But none more than Iran which is
making its first World Cup finals appearance in 20 years. Iran's
involvement symbolises the country's emergence from both
international sporting and political isolation. (FIRST RUN 0300
EUROPE EARLY)
----
POLAND: SURGERY - Looking for an out-of-the-ordinary holiday? Tired
of the usual
sunspots? Try the industrial region of Wroclaw in Poland, which is
offering plastic surgery holidays. APTV's feature joins one
holidaymaker on the trip of a lifetime. (FIRST RUN 0715 ASIA PACIFIC
LATE)
----
RUNNING:  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC; 
----
US: INTERNMENT - The U-S has agreed to pay five-thousand U-S dollars
to each Japanese person taken from Latin America and held in U-S
internment camps during the war. APTV has comments from U-S
officials and former internees and file of the former migrant labour
camp in Crystal City. (FIRST RUN 2130 LATAM)
----
UK: MANDELA - APTV has coverage of South African President Nelson Mandela's visit
to the South African High Commission in London and a London theatre for the
charity gala performance of ``Kat and the Kings'', which is set in
1950s South Africa. The package includes comments from Mandela and
the president meeting the parents of Stephen Lawrence, a young black
man killed in an apparent racist attack. (FIRST RUN F-L-A-S-H)
----
US: SHUTTLE - The space shuttle Discovery has returned to Earth,
bringing home the last American astronaut on the space station Mir.
Andrew Thomas spent 141 days in orbit. (FIRST RUN NORTH AMERICA LATE
1930)
----
US: CHINA - China's Ambassador to the U-S has played down any
differences between his country and the U-S, just weeks before
President Bill Clinton's official visit to Beijing. APTV has highlights
of his news conference. (FIRST RUN NORTH AMERICA LATE 1930)
----
EL SALVADOR: WORLD CUP - APTV reports on World Cup fever in El
Salvador, where television sales have increased dramatically - and
even those who cannot afford to buy their own set have found a way
to see the football. (FIRST RUN 1900 LATIN AMERICA)
----
ARGENTINA: VIDELA 3 - Former president Jorge Rafael Videla -
detained on accusations of kidnapping children whose parents
disappeared during Argentina's military dictatorship - refused to
testify at a court hearing.
----
ETHIOPIA: BOMBS 2 - APTV has exclusive footage from Adigrat in
Ethiopia, showing an Eritrean air attack. The dramatic pictures show
bombs landing and women and children running scared. (FIRST RUN 1645
F-L-A-S-H)
----
ERITREA: FIGHTING - APTV also has exclusive shots from the Eritrean
side of the conflict showing women praying and marching for peace in
Asmara, tanks on the front line at Zalambesa and people queuing
outside the offices of Eritrean Airlines trying to buy tickets to
get out. (FIRST RUN 1645 F-L-A-S-H)
----
BRUSSELS: NATO 3 - NATO ministers have agreed to stage a display of
air power around Kosovo's borders next week and have ordered
military planners to prepare strategies for possible air strikes and
even the use of ground troops. (FIRST RUN 1830 NORTH AMERICA)
----
UK: MINISTERS 6 - The world's leading industrial nations have warned
the Serbs to meet tough demands to end violence in the province of
Kosovo or face the might of the international community. APTV has
comments from British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook and U-S Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright. (FIRST RUN 1645 F-L-A-S-H)
----
WCUP: PROTEST 3 - French police fired teargas to try to disperse
union activists who blocked the main Lyon to Marseille motorway. The
protest was designed to cause maximum disruption ahead of World Cup
matches in Marseille and Lyon. (FIRST RUN 1830 NORTH AMERICA UPDATE)
----
