<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Chiapas,0725 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mexican president says government committed to peace talks in
</HEADLINE>
Chiapas &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS to UPDATE with government response to U.N. High
Commissioner for Human Rights. &QL; 
 &UR; With BC-Mexico-Chiapas-Reaction &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos XSCC101 &QL; 
 &UR; By NIKO PRICE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LAS MARGARITAS, Mexico (AP) _ Amid fears of renewed war between
Zapatista rebels and the government, Mexico's president flew to
Chiapas on Friday to defend his administration's stated desire for
dialogue and pledge money for towns where rebel support runs high.
	   Some analysts say a police and army raid on an Indian village
this week is the latest indication that the government has chosen
military might over talks.
	   But President Ernesto Zedillo told residents in Las Margaritas,
85 miles southeast of the state capital, Tuxtla Gutierrez, that the
government's goal is negotiation.
	   ``We want dialogue. We don't want to defeat anyone. The
government will not abandon this position,'' he said. Zedillo was
making his fourth visit to Chiapas in just over a month.
	   In Mexico City, the government's chief negotiator Emilio Rabasa
Gamboa asked a mediation group of legislators to help the
government set up a direct dialogue with the Zapatistas, the
government news agency Notimex reported.
	   As Zedillo spoke in Chiapas, about a dozen people unfurled
banners demanding a halt to violence. ``Senor Zedillo, we do not
want more war,'' one said.
	   Guadalupe Gonzalez, 33, held up a sign reading ``Senor Zedillo,
we want respect for our human rights,'' and said she is not sure
the government still wants to negotiate.
	   ``There is much repression. There is not much freedom of
expression,'' she said.
	   On Wednesday, government forces clashed with apparent Zapatista
rebels in the municipality of El Bosque as they tried to evict a
symbolic pro-rebel town council.
	   The clash, which killed nine people, was the first direct
skirmish between the two sides since peace talks broke down nearly
two years ago. The Zapatistas took up arms in 1994 to demand
greater democracy and Indian rights.
	   The dead included a 1-year-old child and a woman who supported
Zedillo's ruling party, according to a statement that the symbolic
town council issued Friday.
	   Some analysts said the government's tactics signaled that
officials have given up the idea of restarting talks and are
focusing instead on isolating the rebels from their civilian
supporters.
	   ``They have decided not to continue with negotiations, but they
can't say that because public opinion is in favor of resolving the
Chiapas problem through negotiations,'' said Lorenzo Meyer, a
political historian in Mexico City.
	   The U.N. high commissioner for human rights, Mary Robinson,
urged the government Friday to resume dialogue, calling Wednesday's
raid and other recent violence in Chiapas ``serious violations of
the rights of indigenous people.''
	   In a statement late Friday, the Mexican foreign secretariat
acknowledged Robinson's letter and said the government has stressed
the need to resolve the conflict through dialogue. He said Mexico
would send its representative to the United Nations, Antonio de
Icaza, to meet with Robinson to discuss its efforts to restore
order and fight poverty in Chiapas.
	   Amnesty International also denounced the raid and a clash
between soldiers and apparent rebels in Guerrero state which left
11 people dead last week.
	   Mexico's leading opposition parties, the pro-business National
Action Party and the leftist Democratic Revolution Party, called on
Zedillo's administration to reestablish talks.
	   In a speech Friday, Chiapas Gov. Roberto Albores Guillen took a
harder line than Zedillo, vowing to continue using force to achieve
what he called the rule of law.
	   ``The return to legality is not negotiable in Chiapas. We are
going to make the law prevail in Chiapas,'' he said.
	   In Las Margaritas, a lowland town where many government
supporters have sought refuge, Zedillo signed an accord granting
aid to 42 municipalities ``that need special attention,'' he said.
The list included all the rebel supporting towns the government has
raided in recent months _ including El Bosque.
	   The towns will receive dlrs 290 million this year for schools,
health clinics, water purification plants and roads.
</TEXT>
