<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-South Africa,0521 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: For South Africa, being there is what mattered
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS previous &QL; 
 &UR; By TOM COHEN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MARSEILLES, France (AP) _ Their heroes lost 3-0 to France in the
most lopsided match so far of the World Cup, but South African fans
said just being at the global soccer showcase was more important
than winning or losing.
	   It was South Africa's first World Cup appearance and several
hundred singing, flag-waving fans cheered their loudest despite the
one-sided score.
	   Shipping company official Phillip Malebe, 44, of Johannesburg
said he was amazed at how the event brought South Africans of all
colors and backgrounds together.
	   ``The fact is we are here. They brought us all here,'' said
Malebe, who wore a South African jersey. ``I've seen the beautiful
rainbow nation, all colors, singing our song. We were singing
together, we were passing drinks mouth-to-mouth. ... Just to be
here, we don't need the Cup.''
	   There will be other World Cups, more chances to shine across the
planet and create dreams for those back home. Friday's inaugural
appearance in soccer's biggest tournament was a coming of age for
players, fans and a nation that has long sought recognition, and
even more, acceptance.
	   Deputy President Thabo Mbeki, the heir apparent to Nelson
Mandela, was there, sitting with French Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin and World Cup organizing committee chairman Michel Platini.
	   Since arriving in France on Sunday, the players have been
reminded over and over that the bad old days of apartheid and
international isolation were gone. In Vichy, the central town where
they train, residents have welcomed them warmly, seeking autographs
at every chance.
	   Back home, the significance is even greater. South Africa has
enjoyed lots of sports success since its return to the
international arena in the early 1990s. Ernie Els has won two U.S.
Opens in golf, while Josia Thugwane was the Olympic marathon
champion and Penny Heyns won two swimming gold medals in Atlanta
two years ago. The rugby Springboks won their World Cup at home in
1995.
	   But soccer is the national sport, followed and played zealously
by most of the black majority. For 28 years, until 1992, South
Africa was banned from international soccer because of apartheid
and its players and fans could only wonder what a World Cup was
like.
	   Now they know.
	   French fans belted out a stirring ``La Marseillaise'' and the
French players responded, attacking the South Africans for most of
the first half and going ahead on a 35th minute header by
Christophe Dugarry.
	   South Africa lacked the speed and strength to win battles for
the ball, and its defensive shell allowed France to control play
and score twice more in the second half for a 3-0 victory.
	   ``I'm obviously disappointed but its not the end of the world,''
defender Mark Fish said.
	   He could have been speaking for the hundreds of flag-waving,
singing South African fans, who had waited a lifetime for Friday
night.
</TEXT>
