<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Albania-Rudderless Rebels,0794 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kosovo separatists try to regroup after Serb offensive
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By BRIAN MURPHY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TROPOJA, Albania (AP) _ The men who aspire to defeat the
battle-hardened Yugoslav military could barely keep from tearing
into each other.
	   In the village mosque Friday, about 30 ethnic Albanian refugees
from Kosovo argued wildly about a strategy for rejoining the
independence fight in the Serbian province. ``Now! We must go
now!'' shouted one man. ``I will lead you.''
	   ``No,'' countered another. ``We must wait and get real uniforms
and boots. And why should you lead? We need someone with military
experience.''
	   The meeting broke up, and the men _ still bickering _ streamed
out of the mosque, leaving a trail of orange-brown mud from their
shoes. No one bothered to take off footwear as Islamic custom
dictates.
	   But different rules often apply in this corner of the Balkans.
	   The Kosovo Liberation Army appears to have mushroomed into a
sizable militia without the usual consolidating influences: a clear
leadership and direction. Along the rebels' important supply
pipeline from Albania, a picture emerges of a group growing in
numbers but short on an overall plan for using its muscle.
	   In Albania _ where the rebels have attempted to regroup after
the latest Serb offensive _ there appears to be no established
procedure to recruit, train and equip. It's not clear the KLA can
mount a sustained guerrilla campaign against an army tested by
years of conflict within Yugoslavia.
	   A small force was capable of harassing Serb forces. But a much
larger militia is needed to back up the call for independence for
Kosovo, where almost 90 percent of the population is ethnic
Albanian.
	   Even some rebels admit they must try to unify as a fighting
force or risk splintering. ``Every army needs a general. At the
moment, we just have lots of lieutenants going in different
directions,'' said Miliam Coruca, who claimed he fought with the
KLA before retreating to Albania.
	   The rebels seem driven by a mentality of blood feuds and
vendettas that has ruled Albanian culture for centuries.
	   ``The Serbs kill us, we kill them,'' said Ilir Maliq, 24, a
refugee from the Kosovo village of Junik who vowed to return and
fight. But he looked bewildered when asked whether he could command
a group of guerrillas.
	   Many young ethnic Albanians in Kosovo lack the formal military
training other Yugoslavs get from compulsory army service _ most
tend to evade conscription into the Yugoslav army.
	   The ethnic Albanian political leader, Ibrahim Rugova, appears to
have little sway over the separatists. This opens the possibility
for ``spontaneous guerrilla actions'' that could flare into wider
conflict, said a Western military observer, insisting on anonymity.
	   The KLA has taken some steps to dispel the idea of disarray.
	   It announced through Albanian language newspapers in Kosovo on
Friday that it is organizing a fund, ``Homeland Calls,'' for
donations. It also identified an unknown teacher, Jakup Krasniqi,
as KLA spokesman. But there was no clarification of KLA objectives
or command structure.
	   Along the border in Albania, rebel activity is openly on
display. Regular convoys of mules loaded with arms and supplies
move toward mountain outposts in Kosovo. The family home of former
President Sali Berisha _ a champion of the separatist cause _ has
become a hub for stockpiling weapons and a kind of KLA nerve
center.
	   A large cache of guns and explosives outside the crumbling stone
farm house earlier this week was no longer visible by Friday. A man
who identified himself as Berisha's cousin told journalists they
were not welcome.
	   Rebel ranks appear to have swelled in a sign that there is at
least the raw manpower to challenge the Serbs if the conflict is
not defused.
	   Fighters _ some still boys wearing rock band t-shirts _ watch
the dirt roads coming from the border and escort new refugees down
toward Tropoja and other Albanian towns.
	   Almost every male refugee near the border is immediately
recruited. Some refugees say they were outfitted for free with
AK-47 rifles and ammunition. Others complain they must purchase
their weapon _ up to dlrs 300 for an AK-47 in good condition.
	   For now, money appears to buy leadership. Ethnic Albanian
emigres who have funneled money and materiel from Germany and
elsewhere in western Europe appear to be in charge of the Albanian
staging areas.
	   Hundreds of German military uniforms _ possibly purchased on the
black market _ have been distributed among the rebels.
	   But most newcomers in the rebel ranks still march back into the
hills with the same clothes they wore when they fled Kosovo.
</TEXT>
