r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Guinea-Bissau     06-12 0405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Guinea-Bissau,0405 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Some 40,000 flee Guinea-Bissau as government, rebels exchange fire
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS previous &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) _ Government troops from the former
Portuguese colony of Guinea-Bissau kept up their siege of a group
of renegade soldiers as tens of thousands of people fled the
fighting, according to media reports.
	   As many as 40,000 people in the West African nation on foot
along clogged roads to the northern border with Senegal, a
Portuguese journalist reported on Friday.
	   Senegal closed the border on Thursday, and medical teams were
dispatched to vaccinate the refugees against yellow fever and
meningitis, Pedro Rosa Mendes told Portuguese state radio Antena 1.
	   Government troops, supported by soldiers from neighboring
Senegal and the Republic of Guinea, kept up their siege of a
military garrison in a northern suburb of the capital, Bissau,
where the rebels have been holed up since their coup attempt
Sunday.
	   The Portuguese Embassy in Bissau reported sporadic shelling and
automatic weapon fire in the capital throughout the day.
	   ``It's a very unstable situation. We're not sure who's
winning,'' the spokesman said on customary condition of anonymity,
adding that the embassy had been hit by several stray shells.
	   The French Embassy was hit by a bazooka shell, but no one was
injured, the Portuguese news agency Lusa reported.
	   The rebels are led by former armed forces chief Brig. Ansumane
Mane, who was fired in January amid allegations he was involved in
smuggling arms to rebels in Senegal. He has accused President Joao
Bernardo Vieira of corruption and called on him to step down so
that early elections can be held.
	   Vieira himself came to power in a 1980 coup. He was then elected
in the country's first democratic elections four years ago.
	   More than 2,200 people, mostly foreigners, were evacuated from
Bissau to Dakar, Senegal, on a packed Portuguese merchant ship
Thursday, with children and elderly people squeezed onto the deck.
	   A Portuguese frigate was expected to arrive in Guinea-Bissau on
Sunday to oversee the evacuation of more foreigners, diplomats
said.
	   The Portuguese phone company Marconi said international phone
lines apparently had been cut in Bissau.
	   Portuguese residents in Bafata, the country's second-largest
city 90 miles to the east, told Lusa there was no military activity
in the area.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Guinea-Bissau; CT:i; 
