<SLUG> BC-TRAV-Travel Briefs,0967 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
European Union says safest roads are in Britain and Sweden
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ If you're planning to drive in Europe,
getting behind the wheel is considerably safer in Britain and
Sweden, statistics show. Portugal and Greece are the most
hazardous.
	   The European Union, which is working hard to form market
standards through a common currency for 15 European countries, last
week released a comparative auto fatality report based on 1995
figures.
	   The EU statistics agency Eurostat said for each one million
inhabitants, 64 people died on British roads in 1995 and 65 in
Sweden.
	   The figures for Portugal and Greece were 217 and 195,
respectively
	   Almost 44,200 people lost their lives on roads in the EU in
1995, 14 percent less than in 1989, the report said.
	   The situation improved in nearly all 15 EU countries in the
1989-1995 period, except in Italy, Luxembourg, and Greece.
	    &UR; ___ &QC; 
 &UR; Magazine ranks the world's hotels providing the best service
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Really topnotch hotel service isn't easy to come
by. First, you need the money. In most cases, you also need to
travel overseas.
	   Of the world's top 10 hotels providing the best service, as
ranked by Travel and Leisure magazine in its June issue, only two
are in the United States: the St. Regis (formerly the Ritz-Carlton)
in Aspen, Colorado, and the Ritz-Carlton in Naples, Florida. The
Aspen hotel ranked No. 5 and the Naples hotel was No.7.
	   The Oriental in Bangkok offers the best service in the world,
the magazine said. Its staff to guest ratio is 2.5 to 1.
	   Close on its heels were The Peninsula in Hong Kong and the Ritz
in Paris. The Ritz-Carlton in Cancun was ranked No. 4.
	   The bottom half of the creme de la creme were: No. 6, Four
Seasons Resort in Hualalai, Hawaii; No. 8, Amanpuri, Phuket,
Thailand; No. 9, Halekulani, Oahu, and No. 10, Lodge at Koele,
Lanai, Hawaii.
	   The magazine didn't say how it conducted its poll, or how many
people responded.
	    &UR; ___ &QC; 
 &UR; Butterflies return to Memphis zoo for popular show
	   MEMPHIS, Tennessee (AP) _ Picture about 1,200 butterflies in 43
species _ all in one horseshoe-shaped, net-covered garden at one
time.
	   Add the sounds of New Age music in the background and water
trickling over rocks into fish-filled ponds.
	   The stage is set for the Memphis Zoo's encore of the world's
largest exhibit of U.S. butterflies, credited with boosting last
year's June-to-September zoo attendance by 16 percent over the
previous summer.
	   Since butterflies live up to only two weeks, maintaining the
colorful collection presents special challenges. It requires
obtaining weekly supplies of butterfly larvae and moth cocoons from
Florida and Texas.
	   The zoo logged more than 100,000 visits to the display last
year, says zoo spokeswoman Jennifer Coleman.
	   ``Butterflies: In Living Color'' runs through Oct. 4. Cost is
dlrs 1, in addition to the cost of zoo admission.
	    &UR; ___ &QC; 
 &UR; West Virginia trying to lure white water enthusiasts
	   CHARLESTON, West Virginia (AP) _ Hoping to one-up fly-and-drive
vacation packages, West Virginia tourism companies are pushing
white water rafting deals.
	   A fly-and-raft vacation plan is available to Charleston from
airports in Atlanta and Washington, D.C., and will be available
late this summer from Chicago, Yeager Airport officials announced
last week.
	   The package will include round-trip air fare, a rental car,
two-night's accommodations and a full day of white water rafting on
the New or Gauley rivers for dlrs 446 per person, based on double
occupancy.
	   Both the rugged Gauley and the tamer New rivers take white water
enthusiasts through steep, pristine canyons. Both are about an
hour's drive from Charleston.
	   Tourism officials are hoping the flights will lure more white
water enthusiasts, since few carriers serve West Virginia.
	   Other partners in the promotional venture are the Charleston
Convention and Visitors Bureau, the Charleston Marriott hotel,
Budget Rent-a-Car, white water Class VI and Appalachian Wildwaters.
The Division of Tourism provided a matching grant.
	   Air service is provided by Atlantic Southeast Airline from
Atlanta and Atlantic Coast Airline from Washington, D.C.
	    &UR; ___ &QC; 
	   COPPER CANYON, Mexico (AP) _ If you're in the mood to pay dlrs
500 to sleep in a cave for a night, a mountain lodge here can put
you up in an ancient Tarahumara Indian dwelling.
	   Room 18A is hidden among huge boulders and near a small stream,
but it's just 1,000 feet (300 meters) from the Sierra Lodge's log
porch.
	   The room has a dirt floor and rock ceiling that is charred from
centuries of cooking fires. It's equipped with a log bed, night
stand and lantern. Guests are encouraged to build a fire to keep
off the night chill.
	   Tarahumara Indians have lived in rock caves for nearly 400
years, and many still inhabit the more remotely situated caves in
the deep copper canyons near Creel in the state of Chihuahua.
	   Information about the area can be found at the Web site:
www.coppercanyonlodges.com. The agent for Sierra Lodge can be
reached at 1-800-776-3942.
	    &UR; ___ &QC; 
	   BRANSON, Missouri (AP) _ Music fans headed for Branson can now
fly by commercial airline to the Ozark playground, provided they
don't mind going through Texas.
	   Aspen Mountain Air has begun two daily nonstop flights from the
Dallas-Fort Worth to the M. Graham Clark airport in Branson.
	   The hour-long flights depart from Texas at 11 a.m. and 4:55
p.m., with return flights at 1:15 p.m. and 6:35 p.m.
	   Flight reservations and information on tour packages are
available through Country Tours at (888) 458-9696. Reservations can
also be made through Aspen Mountain Air, (800) 877-3932, or through
any travel agent.
