</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-East Timor </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dancing and chanting, East Timorese students stage protest
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos planned &QL; 
 &UR; By CHRISTOPHER TORCHIA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   DILI, Indonesia (AP) _ Stepping up their demands for
independence from Indonesia, more than 1,000 students protested
Saturday in East Timor, dancing, raising their fists and chanting
the name of the jailed rebel chief they adore.
	   It was the second large protest this week in the former
Portuguese colony, with demonstrators reiterating demands for a
vote on independence as well as the release of rebel Xanana Gusmao,
who is serving a 20-year sentence in a Jakarta jail.
	   ``Free Xanana. You sent him to prison because he fought for our
freedom,'' read a banner at the rally in a palm-tree-dotted yard at
East Timor University. Other crude poster sketches depicted
Indonesian soldiers stabbing civilians and giving them electric
shocks with wires.
	   Smiling protesters, many wearing headbands declaring
``Referendum,'' held hands and shuffled in a traditional dance.
``The struggle continues,'' they shouted in Portuguese.
	   Animosity among East Timorese runs deep toward Indonesia, which
invaded in 1975 and wiped out most armed resistance in a military
campaign that lasted several years. Human rights workers say tens
of thousands of people died.
	   Indonesia defends its record, pointing to the large amount of
aid it has funneled into East Timor after centuries of Portuguese
neglect. A large minority of the population now consists of
entrepreneurial newcomers from other Indonesian islands.
	   President B.J. Habibie, who is promising a new era of reform
after the downfall of his authoritarian mentor, Suharto, has
suggested special status for troubled East Timor. On Friday, a
dozen political prisoners were freed from a jail in Dili, the
seaside capital of the half-island territory of 800,000 people.
	   However, East Timorese activists reject the measures as
inadequate, saying they will settle for nothing less than total
independence.
	   On Friday, security forces broke up a rally by East Timorese
separatists at the Indonesian foreign ministry in Jakarta,
pummeling some protesters with clubs. And memories are fresh of a
1991 demonstration in Dili in which soldiers opened fire, killing
dozens of pro-independence activists.
	   Anxious to avoid a confrontation, protest organizers in Dili
notified the military and the governor's office of their plans and
roped off sections of the rally site to keep order. Many students
arrived on packed buses, with some sitting on the roofs.
	   ``We won't stop the demonstrations until Xanana is released and
we get a referendum,'' said Vera Lucia, a student protester. 	   
</TEXT>
