w2280 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OAS-US-HumanRights     06-12 0277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OAS-US-Human Rights,0276 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. asks international court to reject Mexico's claim on
</HEADLINE>
prisoner's rights &QL; 
 &UR; By MARIANELA JIMENEZ &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) _ Foreigners arrested in the United
States do not necessarily have the right to meet with consular
officials under international law, U.S. officials told the
Inter-American Court of Human Rights.
	   The United States is asking the court to reject a request by
Mexico to clarify the rights of suspects arrested in foreign
countries _ especially in cases that could involve the death
penalty. The court, based in the Costa Rican capital, San Jose, is
holding hearings Friday and Saturday.
	   Mexico, Honduras and Paraguay have protested the executions of
their citizens in the United States, arguing the prisoners were not
given the right to contact consular officials. Mexico claims that
under the Vienna Convention on Consular Relations, a country should
notify the appropriate consulate when a foreigners are arrested to
help guarantee the rights of the suspects.
	   The United States says the convention establishes no such
requirement and that consulates can seldom provide effective legal
assistance.
	   ``Consulate notification is not indispensable'' to assure a fair
trial, the U.S. delegate, Catherine Brown, told the court Friday.
	   She asked the court to rule that it lacks the authority to act
on Mexico's request.
	   A ruling against the United States would be largely symbolic.
The United States never signed the American Convention on Human
Rights and is not bound by rulings of the court, which is under the
Organization of American States.
</TEXT>
